<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-U.S.-CUSTODY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, A LESS-PUBLICIZED CUSTODY CASE INVOLVING INTERNATIONAL
RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl) 
By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the angry tug of war over a young Cuban boy ended
Wednesday with a decision to send him back to his father in Cuba,
another international custody battle was being waged in U.S.
District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But while the case of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez inflamed
tensions between the United States and Cuba and attracted attention
from around the globe, the New York case _ a mother who abducted
her two children from Paris, contending that their father regularly
beat her _ shows another, more prosaic side of how international
politics usually works in such custody disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Marthe Dubois, finds herself fighting both the United
States and French governments, which have urged a federal judge in
Manhattan to send her 8-year-old daughter and 4-year-old son back
so France can decide the case. Their pleas come despite a finding
last year by the judge that the abuse accusations were true.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, the mother had told the judge, the father tied
an electrical cord around the neck of their daughter, Marie-Eline
Blondin, then 13 months old, twisted it and said he would kill her
and the rest of the family. Ms. Dubois twice moved into battered
women's shelters in France. In the two and a half years since they
fled to New York, eventually moving in with relatives in
Woodbridge, N.J., Marie-Eline and her brother, Francois, have
thrived, Ms. Dubois said. Marie-Eline has testified that she is
afraid to return to France because of her father.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the U.S. and French governments maintain that the
judge should send the children back because of an international
treaty, the Hague Convention, which guarantees the prompt return of
abducted children in international custody disputes in almost all
cases. The Hague Convention was not an issue in Elian's case
because Cuba never signed the 1980 treaty, and the uproar seemed
mostly the result of the poisoned relationship between Washington
and Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But the case of the French children underscores how hundreds of
custody battles that do not play out on a public stage are just as
fraught with emotional turmoil and ambiguity when global politics
intrudes. It also shows how difficult it can be for American judges
to decide what to do with children in cases governed by
international treaties and influenced by differences in cultural,
ethnic or religious heritages.
</P>
<P>
   ``No system, including the United States', is as error free, as
perfect, as we'd like it to be for children,'' Dr. Albert Solnit, a
child psychiatrist and former director of the Child Study Center at
Yale University, who recently evaluated the French children, said
in an interview. ``So if you can find grounds to judge what is best
for children that do not compare national systems, you avoid a lot
of unnecessary political or policy or chauvinistic issues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case of the French children has wended its way through the
federal courts in Manhattan for a year and a half. Judge Denny Chin
initially ruled that the children should remain in the United
States, but the case was sent back to him by a federal appeals
panel that called for further review. He has promised a final
ruling this month.
</P>
<P>
   The case began when Ms. Dubois, 45, moved with her children to
the United States in August 1997, admitting that she had forged
travel documents to make it appear that her boyfriend, Felix
Blondin, had given permission for their children to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Blondin flew to New York in June 1998, and citing the Hague
Convention, requested his children's return to him. In a hearing
that month, Ms. Dubois admitted faking the travel documents, but
said she had been desperate to escape from Blondin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix was worse and worse and worse,'' she testified. ``He
would beat me very often, be angry all the time, always yelling,
screaming. The children could not sleep. They were getting
nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   The beatings had begun shortly after they moved in together in
1991, she said. He often hit her when he was drinking, she went on,
and sometimes while she was holding their baby daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Blondin, a nurse-anesthesiologist in Paris,
denied the accusations of abuse. ``That's a lie,'' he told Chin.
``Everybody knows that I love my children.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Valerie Wolfman, said, ``I have dealt with the man
for two years and I believe him.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parents, through their lawyers, would not comment for this
article.
</P>
<P>
   France has told U.S. officials and Chin that it supports the
request of Blondin, 52, for the return of his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must tell you,'' an official with the French Ministry of
Justice wrote to the State Department last July, ``that this office
attaches great importance to the distressing situation of this
father who over the past months has nonetheless never lost his
determination to recover his two children.''
</P>
<P>
   Another French official asked that Chin should ``please have
confidence in our administrative and judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of the French children is one of about 1,224 since 1995
in which children have been abducted to the United States by
parents in other countries, and whose return has been sought under
the Hague Convention, said Jennifer Penta, an official with the
National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, which
coordinates the handling of such cases for the State Department.
The State Department says that it is separately seeking the return
of hundreds of other children wrongfully removed from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States consistently argues that the treaty should be
honored, in part so that children abducted from this country will
be returned, as well. In urging Judge Chin to return the French
children, it said the French courts could protect them and
ultimately resolve the abuse and custody questions. ``The Hague
Convention cannot function,'' the State Department wrote, ``without
a substantial amount of cooperation and mutual respect among the
different legal systems represented by the nearly 60 states party
to the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   But Leonard Joy, the federal defender for New York who was
appointed to represent Ms. Dubois, told Chin in a hearing in
December that the children's best interests were being forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we are talking about is the pride of France and
getting the children back to France so they can decide,'' he said.
``The last thing in the world that any communication from France
has said is that they are concerned about the welfare of the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his initial ruling in 1998 that the children should
stay in the United States, Chin found that the father had been
abusive. He wrote in an opinion that he found some of Blondin's
testimony ``nonsensical'' and that he was ``firmly convinced''
Blondin was lying. He ruled that the case fit the narrow exception
in the Hague Convention, in which children do not have to be
returned if that would place them at ``grave risk'' of physical or
psychological harm.
</P>
<P>
   Blondin successfully appealed. The case was sent back to Chin,
who was told to investigate further whether he could somehow return
the children safely while the custody and abuse issues were decided
in France.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing Dec. 20, Solnit testified on behalf of Ms. Dubois
and agreed that the children would suffer grave psychological harm
if uprooted from New Jersey and sent back. Marie-Eline, in
particular, had repeatedly described her fears and nightmares while
living in France, and of being unable to eat there, said Solnit,
now Connecticut's commissioner of mental health and addiction
services.
</P>
<P>
   Solnit also said that during their session, Marie-Eline used
crayons to draw her family, sketching her mother, brother and three
relatives but not her father.
</P>
<P>
   Chin also met with the children in his chambers, and gently
questioned Marie-Eline about what she remembered from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not nice things,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever see your daddy hit your mommy?'' he asked later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said. ``It was not nice. It hurts. It hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Chin told the lawyers that he was concerned about
suggestions by a French official. In a letter, the official said
that France might seek to force Ms. Dubois' return through
extradition if the judge did not issue a favorable ruling. It was
``almost a threat,'' Chin said.
</P>
<P>
   When a U.S. government lawyer contended that the issue was not
the pride of either country, Chin did not appear convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be true from your point of view,'' he said. ``But
from France's point of view it is clear that their pride has been
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think in general parents should not be permitted
to abduct children and take them to another country. I agree
wholeheartedly with the purpose. On the other hand, there is an
exception, and the question is, does the exception apply in this
case?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
