<HEADLINE>
THOSE DOMINANT YANKEES FIGHT FOR A DOMAIN NAME
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fight over an Internet address for the New York
Yankees, depending on whom you talk to, is either the story of a
giant sports franchise seeking to crush a hapless fan or one of an
unprincipled ``cybersquatter'' hoping to cash in on the team's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the team and for Brian McKiernan, a 41-year-old
Queens man involved in the dispute, agree on a few basic facts.
Sometime in June 1997, while fishing around with his three children
on the Internet, McKiernan discovered that the name
newyorkyankees.com had not been registered. So he paid a small
registration fee and got the rights to the name.
</P>
<P>
   But from here the accounts begin to diverge. McKiernan's lawyer
says the Yankees ultimately offered his client $450 plus tickets to
two games in exchange for relinquishing the Internet domain name.
The team contends in court papers that McKiernan demanded $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The acrimony reached the point where on Dec. 24 lawyers for the
Yankees filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn seeking
to wrest the domain name from McKiernan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McKiernan insists on selling back to the Yankees that
which is rightfully theirs, which is their name,'' said Ethan G.
Orlinsky, the lawyer speaking for the Yankees and the other
plaintiff in the suit, Major League Baseball Properties, which owns
the rights to market the names of the 30 Major League Baseball
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not feel it was appropriate to buy it back for, among
other reasons, it is outrageous behavior,'' Orlinsky said. The
Yankees already own most combinations of their name, and operate
their official site at yankees.com.
</P>
<P>
   But McKiernan's lawyer, John S. Selinger, paints the lawsuit as
a David vs. Goliath fight, with his client hoping one day to use
the now inactive address to establish a fan site and instead
finding himself facing a battery of high-priced lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Selinger denies that McKiernan asked for $25,000, but he admits
that McKiernan did use the address initially to advertise various
businesses he runs, including a paging service for nurses. Selinger
said McKiernan planned to build the fan site himself and was just
using the advertisements for his business as test runs, which he
stopped about 18 months ago. ``He has been a Yankee fan for 25
years,'' Selinger said. ``He was excited when he originally got the
name. He thought it was neat.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the buying and selling of domain names
has become a lucrative business. In what is thought to be the
highest price ever paid for an Internet address, a Los Angeles
company paid $7.5 million last fall for the domain name
business.com.
</P>
<P>
   But a law passed by Congress in November was intended to stamp
out cybersquatting, in which individuals register Internet
addresses _ usually for as little as $70 for two years _ in hopes
of reselling them. Some companies have paid to get their names, but
others have gone to court to obtain addresses that they believe
they own by right.
</P>
<P>
   The newly enacted law strengthened the rights of the trademark
holders to claim the addresses and to seek up to $100,000 in
damages against the squatters. In the last month, it has fueled
suits like the Yankees case around the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
