<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS ASSISTANT SAYS DEFENSE SET FOR EMMITT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Vikings defensive coordinator Foge Fazio has
jumped aboard Emmitt Smith's crowded bandwagon, the same one that
was almost barren two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's every bit as good as he's ever been,'' Fazio said. ``I
thought he might have lost a little bit, but that's not the case.
He's as good as he's ever been. He's running as well as anybody in
this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith shredded the middle of Minnesota's defense for 140 yards
Nov. 8 before leaving at halftime with a broken bone in his hand.
Smith had more yards in the first half than any runner managed in
an entire game against the Vikings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we've got to be ready for him to be there the whole
game, pounding at us,'' Fazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have an undersized front seven that is built on
speed, but is susceptible to power runners between the tackles.
Kansas City rushed for 173 yards in a December win and Oakland for
162 yards in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they're going to come in here and try to run the ball
like they did last time,'' middle linebacker Ed McDaniel said. ``If
we stop that, we're pretty much done. That's how they'll try to
hurt us.'' No ``showdown'' likely On a conference call with the
Minnesota media yesterday afternoon, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey shot
down the hype surrounding a showdown between Deion Sanders and
Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably on everyone's wish list, but it's also probably
not going to happen,'' Gailey said. ``They'll be matched up a
couple of times. But after the game I'm sure we'll all wish we
could've seen them do battle a little more.'' Talk is ... talk
Despite Sunday's victory that propelled his team into the playoffs,
Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman downplayed last week's meeting with
owner Jerry Jones as a major motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably benefited Jerry more than anyone,'' Aikman said in
a conference call with Minnesota media. ``I'm not one to give a lot
of credence to meetings or speeches this late in the season. If you
need that to be motivated in week 16 then you've got big
problems.'' Briefly The Vikings are 2-6 in the playoffs under coach
Dennis Green. ``I'd say it's more like 6-6,'' quarterback Jeff
George said. ``We've played the past four weeks just like they were
playoff games. Having done that, we've got a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings practiced in sweats at their Winter Park facility
south of downtown. Technically, they practiced inside, but players
demanded all doors be opened so they could enjoy the 2 inches of
falling snow and 15-degree temperatures.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
