u k BC-EDIT-NY-PATAKI-NYT &LR;      01-06 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE STATE OF NEW YORK STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 6:
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki, offering an intriguing wish list in
his State of the State address Wednesday, focused on public
education, the environment and boosting the lagging upstate
economy. The Republican governor's opening proposal on education
shifts attention to a hot political topic that has seldom appeared
high on his priority list. While the tendency is to see this speech
as a semaphore signal to Texas Gov. George W. Bush to consider
Pataki as a vice presidential running mate, the worth of some of
these proposals makes such assessments secondary, especially if
Pataki follows through.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki offered a promising plan to relieve an acute shortage of
qualified teachers expected in New York over the next few years. He
proposed such environmental advances as a research institute to
study rivers and estuaries, which he characterized as a ``Woods
Hole on the Hudson.'' And he laid out a questionable $700 million
package of tax cuts and economic incentives to spread the nation's
economic boom to upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although this annual speech is traditionally designed to sell
concepts with little supporting detail, Pataki's five-point
education plan outlines ways to attract new teachers to
disadvantaged schools. The idea of providing free tuition for CUNY
or SUNY students who commit to teaching in these high-risk areas
sounds especially encouraging. So does a summer school tutoring
program using college juniors, and his proposal to allow retired
public employees to teach without losing their retirement benefits.
A plan to help uncertified teachers and to allow talented people to
teach without going through the normal vetting system deserves a
fair hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's tax and incentive proposals _ especially his
effort to phase out a $500 million energy tax primarily on large
businesses _ are aimed at his constituency in upstate New York. But
the resulting revenue cuts would strain a state budget already
facing multibillion-dollar gaps in the next two fiscal years. Even
more troubling is his proposal to cap local school budgets and
require two-thirds of the voters to approve going above those
state-imposed limits. Such a plan would make it difficult for
school boards trying to meet new academic standards in less
affluent districts.
</P>
<P>
   The governor failed to mention his proposal for campaign finance
reform last year or the need to open the state's primary ballot to
a broader array of candidates March 7. Still, the teacher plan was
worth the effort. Now Pataki must add the detailed legislation and
necessary funds to go along with Wednesday's pronouncements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0005EST &QL; 
