<HEADLINE>
LSU REAPPEARS ON NATIONAL RADAR SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LSU basketball. You remember it, don't you? Had a guy named
Maravich in the '60s. Reached the Final Four in 1981, snuck into
the Final Four in Dallas in 1986. Had that wacky coach, Dale Brown.
He had teams featuring Chris Jackson and Shaquille O'Neal that went
nowhere in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers have dropped off the national radar screen of late.
Brown got canned. The NCAA sheriffs rode into town and took away
scholarships. John Brady was hired from Samford in 1997. The past
five years, LSU has won 12, 12, 10, 9 and 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last night's Southeastern Conference opener with
Alabama, Louisiana State was 12-0 and ranked 20th. Judging from
LSU's defeat of previously undefeated Oklahoma State last week, the
Tigers are going to make the Deaf Dome in Baton Rouge a tough place
to visit again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show people we're good enough to be ranked,'' LSU
guard Lamont Roland said. ``We saw something in the paper that we
were the worst undefeated team in the country. It meant a lot for
us to beat Oklahoma State.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Tigers danced on the New Orleans Arena court a week
ago as if they had just punched their ticket to the Final Four.
Perhaps it was a bit much, celebrating a regular-season victory
like that. But after victories against a bunch of average-to-worse
teams, a victory against a solid team like Oklahoma State was a
much-needed boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what we've gone through and what we've faced the last two
years ... We've been close to beating some nice teams,'' said
Brady, whose top assistant is former Texas A&AMP;M coach Kermit Davis.
``Beating Oklahoma State answers a lot of questions, really puts us
back into a position to earn respect. I think our players deserve
respect for the way they try to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is pretty good. If we have enough offense, guard,
rebound and keep playing with pretty good effort, we can be pretty
good. We responded pretty well when the game was on the line
\Ragainst Oklahoma State\S. We showed more poise than I thought we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady has only nine players (four below NCAA limits) on
scholarship. However, one of those players is 6-foot-9 sophomore
Stromile Swift. Last season, Swift missed the first third of the
season trying to become academically eligible. Once he did start
playing, he recorded 11 blocks in one game at Alabama, then had 24
points and nine rebounds against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Swift is averaging 19.5 points and 8.6 rebounds a
game. He also has 36 dunks and 34 blocked shots. Along with 6-11
senior Jabari Smith (13.3 points, 7.5 rebounds a game) and 6-8
Brian Beshara (a Dallas Highland Park product who started his
career at Rice), Swift gives the Tigers a mobile, menacing front
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might not have a lot of depth, but they've got some
really talented big people up front,'' Oklahoma State coach Eddie
Sutton said. ``They can put a lot of pressure on you. They've got a
good inside game, a good perimeter game.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into last night's game, LSU was one of three undefeated
teams in NCAA Division I. That and their ranking has put the Tigers
back on the basketball map.
Spotlight Ball in political arena to create Ohio rivalry It would
appear to be a natural. Why shouldn't two schools from the same
state, with great basketball traditions, play an annual
nonconference game ... even if it has to be at a neutral site?
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the way it is in Ohio, where Cincinnati and Ohio
State haven't played each other in 38 years. And that one meeting
happened only because the Bearcats and the Buckeyes played in the
1962 national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Ohio governor Bob Taft wants to see if he can exert
political pressure to force the schools to play each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is going to be in contact with the schools to see
if we can get a game like this going,'' Scott Milburn, Taft's press
secretary, said. ``He believes it would be a great rivalry to
establish and wants to see if we can set it up. He will be
contacting the schools shortly to pitch the idea. The governor is
very enthusiastic about it. He's a basketball fan, and it's
something he thinks would be very exciting for basketball fans in
Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft happens to be a graduate of Cincinnati's law school. And
Cincinnati is in the position of having nothing to lose. Despite
their basketball success, the Bearcats do not represent the
``state'' school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play anybody,'' Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins said. ``But
we're not a stepchild down here begging teams to play us. I think
playing Ohio State would be a great game for the fans and for
basketball in the state of Ohio, but I'm not going to sit around
and worry about Cincinnati playing Ohio State.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we talking about Cincinnati? That's what you want to
talk about and I don't want to talk about Cincinnati ... I don't
want to play Cincinnati. We're not playing Cincinnati,'' Ohio State
coach Jim O'Brien said. ``You can talk all you want, we're not
going to play Cincinnati. You can find whatever angle. You can say
whatever you want about why or why not, this and that. We have no
interest in scheduling Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State athletic director Andy Geiger supports his coach,
saying a Cincinnati-Ohio State game wouldn't help develop the
basketball program O'Brien wants.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, old-time Buckeyes aren't letting the bitter
memories of national championship-game losses to Cincinnati in 1961
and 1962 color their thinking.
Fast breaks] Hot, hotter, hottest Before we get too deep into the
new year, time to acknowledge one of 1999's more incredible feats.
On Dec. 22, in a 127-57 rout of Division II Cal State Monterey Bay,
Long Beach State opened the second half by making 31 consecutive
shots. Counting their last field goal of the first half, the 49ers
made 32 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   D'Cean Bryant was the only Long Beach State player to miss a
second-half shot. The 49ers' 32-of-33 second-half shooting set an
NCAA record for shooting percentage (97 percent) in a half. It
broke the record of 94.1 percent, set by North Carolina against
Virginia in 1978. The Tar Heels made 16 of 17 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's miss was a 3-pointer. Of the 32 baskets, 20 were dunks
or layups. Just so you know, for the season, Long Beach State is
shooting 49.3 percent from the field. Yeah, coach, we know Indiana
appears to be back where its fans expect it to be. Indiana won the
national championship in 1987, made the Final Four in 1992 and won
the Big Ten Conference title in 1993. But that's the last time any
of those things have been accomplished in Bloomington. In recent
years, player defections and a lack of talent have left Indiana in
the also-ran category.
</P>
<P>
   But heading into Big Ten Conference play, coach Bob Knight's
team is 10-1, with impressive victories against North Carolina and
Kentucky. It appears these Hoosiers should be solid contenders for
the Big Ten and able to make some noise in the NCAA Tournament.
Right, coach?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never look at that,'' Knight said. ``We just try to get
better every day we play. We went 32-0 in 1976, and I'm not sure I
was ever comfortable. Comfortable is not a word that you'd really
associate with me as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Knight knows that three years ago, Indiana started 13-1,
but finished 9-9 in the Big Ten. Two years ago, the Hoosiers
started 9-3 and went 10-8 in the league. Last season, they started
13-2 and finished 9-7. Trash talk Iowa coach and former Indiana
All-American Steve Alford, on how he tries to influence Big Ten
Conference referees:
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys were in the league when I was a player. I've
tried to tell them, `Hey, when I was a player, I thought you were
the best official I ever had.' But I'm sure they're smart enough to
read into that and not believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina senior point guard Ed Cota, on the Tar Heels'
first-round upset loss to Weber State in the NCAA Tournament in
March:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that game. Even if we win the national
championship this year, it still won't make up for losing to Weber
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa coach Bill Self on his 13-1, No. 22-ranked team, which
plays at TCU tonight:
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we are playing amazes me, because we're just loose
enough that you worry about if they are ready. But in a lot of ways
being loose is better than being uptight and focused. We've got a
collective group of guys that are focused but still] just want to
have fun. And we'll have fun, so it's a nice mix.'' By the numbers
1: Number of victories California coach Ben Braun needs to reach
400.
</P>
<P>
   2: Number of victories Arizona coach Lute Olson needs to reach
600. The Wildcats play at California tonight and at top-ranked
Stanford on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   3: Number of players from Minnesota leading Big East Conference
teams in scoring (Boston College's Troy Bell of Minneapolis,
Connecticut's Khalid El-Amin of Minneapolis, and Seton Hall's
Darius Lane of Findley, Minn.)
</P>
<P>
   20: Consecutive Wisconsin losses at Indiana going into last
night's Big Ten Conference opener in Bloomington. Wisconsin's most
recent victory at Indiana came in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   64-1: Penn State's record at home in the 1990s against
nonconference opponents. The Nittany Lions are 24-0 the past five
years at the Bryce Jordan Center.
</P>
<P>
   1977: The last time a team had its basketball team ranked No. 1
and its football team playing in the Rose Bowl. Stanford pulled
that off this New Year's Day.
\Nsubheds:Layups Stanford junior forward Ryan Mendez of Burleson
was selected MVP of the Stanford Invitational after averaging 16.5
points and 7.0 rebounds. Before the two-game tournament, Mendez was
shooting 8-for-32 (.250 percent) from 3-point range, but went
6-for-10 (.600) from beyond the arc in the two games.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Lute Olson donates the tie he wears in each
Wildcats victory. Last season, the Tucson YMCA wound up with about
$10,000 after auctioning off the neck wear. This season, the YMCA
has turned over the donated-tie auctioning to the Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Elon College, which is competing in Division I for the first
season, wants to change its image. So, the school is looking for a
new nickname. Since 1921, the school has been known as the
``Fightin' Christians.'' Its mascot is ``Mr. E,'' a bearded,
barrel-chested mascot with balled fists and a deacon's hat. Elon, a
school of approximately 4,000 students, has students from 42 states
and 35 foreign countries, representing many religions.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern, 4-7 going into Big Ten Conference play, figures to
be in for a long season. Sunday, the Wildcats lost at home to
Oakland University, 60-41. Oakland has lost this season to Michigan
State by 35, Ohio State by 26, Akron by 25, Michigan by 20,
Cleveland State and Toledo by 14 and Bowling Green by 12.
