<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SIGN OLSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's too much and too tiresome to recount all the
problems the Dodgers had last season, but a worn-down bullpen fit
markedly into the rickety puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the bullpen is revamped with a trio of set-up men for
closer Jeff Shaw. The Dodgers signed veteran right-handed reliever
Gregg Olson to a two-year, $3 million free-agent contract
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Olson joins Terry Adams, acquired in the Ismael Valdes and Eric
Young trade to Chicago, and Alan Mills as set-up men to Shaw. That
should allow manager Davey Johnson to divide the innings from the
bullpen better, and gives the Dodgers a trio of options between the
starter and Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a much better ball club right now,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``The way I run my bullpen, I don't like to
overburden anybody. Alan Mills did a good job for us last year but
got a little overburdened. We have Adams, Olson, Mills, and I can
give them some time off so they're fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Dodgers starters averaged six innings. The club
allowed more runs in the seventh inning than any other inning,
followed by the sixth inning and the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers say Olson, if need be, could be used as a closer to
give Shaw a rest. Of course, they've said the same things about
Mills and Adams.
</P>
<P>
   But that's clearly not where the help is needed. Olson was
deplorable as a closer with Arizona last season. He blew his first
three save opportunities, including the memorable opening day game
against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But Olson, 33, flourished in a set-up role once the Diamondbacks
acquired Matt Mantei in a trade. He went 9-4 with a 3.71 ERA and 14
saves in 61 games. He had a 2.61 ERA in his final 29 appearances,
which spanned 31 innings. Olson will be paid $1.25 million in 2000
and $1.75 million in 2001. The club holds an option for the 2002
season. He made $850,000 with the Diamondbacks last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have three people setting up Jeff Shaw, and the more
people you have in that area that can out and do that job, the less
pressure there's going to be on everybody else,'' Olson said. ``You
take some of the burden off, so when it comes to August, September,
every off day you had is welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   By the midpoint of last season, Johnson lost confidence in his
young bullpen. Rookies Onan Masaoka and Jamie Arnold were used
almost exclusively in low-pressure situations. Mills and Pedro
Borbon (now in Toronto) pitched every time a starter left with a
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen, we didn't have a lot of people that could miss
some bats,'' Johnson said. ``Our bullpen did a decent job. We were
like eighth or ninth (in the NL), but you don't win championships
being eighth or ninth in the league in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said lefty Jeff Williams and Masaoka would compete for a
spot in the bullpen, and the Dodgers also have former Yankee Dan
Naulty and veteran Mike Fetters and Matt Herges and Mike Judd in
the mix. In addition, Orel Hershiser will get a chance to win a
spot in the starting rotation but also could fill out the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this addition really solidifies (our bullpen) and
gives Davey a lot of weapons out there,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``We're not completely finished. We still have
some modifications. We're still looking to diversify the bench a
little bit, balance the lineup a little bit more and improve the
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson rejuvenated his career with the Diamondbacks in 1998 after
a four-year journey took him to six teams. He saved 130 games in
five years with Baltimore before elbow problems sent him on a
four-year odyssey to regain his form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
