<HEADLINE>
STARS WIN WITH RESERVE DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ What do you do when you're facing the hottest team in
the NHL and you have more of your top defensemen in the training
room than on the ice? ``I just think right now it's just find a
way,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We're just absolutely
finding a way. It's not pretty. It's not filled with a lot of
fanciness. The attitude of our group is to find a way.'' The way
last night was to play grind-it-out hockey, score just enough goals
and get strong goaltending and some big minutes from some
not-usually-big-minute defensemen. The way proved to be enough for
a 3-1 victory against the Nashville. The Predators rode into
Reunion Arena last night as the hottest team in the league, a
four-game winning streak, eight unbeaten, in tow. The Stars might
have ridden out with the hottest team after extending their winning
streak to a season high-tying four games. They've won four of five
on their homestand, which wraps up tomorrow against Vancouver. Not
bad for a team with an injury report that reads like a who's who in
the NHL. Defensemen Derian Hatcher and Shawn Chambers were already
missing, sidelined by long-term injuries. Add defenseman Richard
Matvichuk on a lesser scale to that list, sidelined after a period
by that nasty flu going around. Oh yeah, Joe Nieuwendyk, Roman
Lyashenko and Grant Marshall were missing with injuries, too.
``Everybody knows our injury situation,'' Hitchcock said. ``There
is a lot of impact players.'' Plenty of impact players remained,
though. Captain Mike Modano absorbed a lot of minutes, playing on
his line and another. Defenseman Brad Lukowich went from being
benched for Monday's game to earning a game star against Nashville.
Backup goalie Manny Fernandez stopped 18 of 19 Predators shots.
Stars winger Mike Keane, well, he just did what he likes to say he
isn't good at doing _ score. His shot from inside the circle, hit
on Predators goalie Tomas Vokoun's glove and went in 43 seconds
into the third period. The Stars never trailed again. ``I saw it at
the last second,'' Vokoun said. ``It went through one of our
player's legs. It hit on the top part of my catching glove. I
turned around and saw it in the net.'' Two of the Stars' goals were
generated by the grinding line of Keane, Guy Carbonneau and Blake
Sloan. Carbonneau's empty-net goal with 4.9 seconds remaining
sealed another Stars victory. ``We played the way Dallas has got to
play and we won the way Dallas usually wins,'' Stars defenseman
Darryl Sydor said. ``I guess chemistry is really coming with our
team knowing we have key players out and we're still doing the
job.'' After a lackluster first period, things heated up in the
second. The Stars finally sneaked a puck past what had been a
red-hot Vokoun, at 10:25 of the second period. Actually, Predators
defenseman Karlis Skrastins did. Stars defenseman Richard Jackman
made the centering pass from along the boards. Stars winger Juha
Lind tipped the puck in front, but it was off of Skrastins' skate
and in. Nashville had that kind of luck on their first goal. The
puck seemed to be on a string with the other side attached to the
net. Not one, but two, Stars clearing attempts hit Stars players
before ending up on Scott Walker's stick in the slot. His shot hit
a post, bounced out and hit Fernandez in the back of the leg and
bounced back in at 16:56 of the first period. After the Stars and
forged a tie, Lukowich really revved them up with a draw in a fight
against Walker later in the second. The Stars had their sticks
banging against the side of the bench in appreciation. ``There are
four defensemen back there that weren't scheduled to play for us
this year,'' Hitchcock said. ``There was \RSergei\S Zubov and Sydor
and nothing else. We've held together pretty well.'' Just finding a
way to win until the ice is more full than the training room.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
