<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL IT BE EASY START FOR UCLA?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UCLA opens Pac-10 play this weekend with the easiest road trip
of the season. Washington and Washington State were preseason picks
to finish ninth and 10th, respectively, and they've done nothing to
alter that perception. Compared to upcoming showdowns at USC,
Oregon, Arizona and Stanford, this trip is inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly why it's so important. Pac-10 road wins are
rare. The Bruins had four last year and need at least that many to
compete for the title this season. They can't afford to lose the
two easiest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go up there and struggle, then people are going to say,
`If they can't get two wins in Washington, how are they going to go
to the desert and win, or go to Maples Pavilion and win?''' UCLA
junior forward Rico Hines said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prove we're a mature team and not just win, but win
convincingly. Somebody's going to lose between Stanford and Arizona
(Saturday), so we can get a head start.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more at stake this weekend than a small step towards the
Pac-10 title. The Bruins, 8-2 overall, need 18 victories to secure
an NCAA Tournament at-large bid. Considering their poor showings
against Gonzaga and Colorado State and their last-second escapes
from Pepperdine and Purdue, that won't be easy. The toughest
portion of the schedule, by far, awaits.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the 18-victory plateau, UCLA must win 10 of its last
20. That's not as easy as it sounds. Not with six games against
Arizona (twice), Stanford (twice), North Carolina and Syracuse. Not
with tough road games at Oregon, Oregon State, Cal and USC. And not
with the upset factor. Each year, the Bruins lose a game or two
they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see UCLA losing at USC and North Carolina next
week. Then the Arizona schools come to town. Then the Bruins visit
Oregon and Oregon State, a trip they haven't swept in four years.
Then Stanford and Cal invade Pauley Pavilion. That's a brutal
eight-game stretch _ one that could deal the Bruins four or five
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend is the last stop before crossing the Mojave. They
can't waste the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very serious about this trip,'' UCLA junior guard Earl
Watson said. ``We can get a jump on the race, but we know the
Washington schools will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   They always are. The Bruins have lost two straight in Seattle,
and their last four games at Washington State _ all UCLA victories
_ have been decided by 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Tonight's game won't be televised. It's being played at
KeyArena because Washington's on-campus facility, Edmundson
Pavilion, is undergoing a season-long renovation. A crowd of 8,000
is expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
