r s BC-BKC-USC-LADN     01-06 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HAS A FEW GOOD MEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC doesn't usually lead the Pacific-10 Conference in anything,
but the Trojans are undeniably atop one category this season.
</P>
<P>
   They have the happiest starting five in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans may have been inconsistent through a 7-5
nonconference season, but none of their starters are complaining.
Why should they? They are averaging 33 minutes per game and about
to try something many would consider foolish.
</P>
<P>
   USC is going to attempt to survive its 18-game conference
schedule with five players, and perhaps two reserves getting
throw-in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The players love it, naturally, because no one is looking over
his shoulder to see if he will be yanked for taking a bad shot or
making a bad pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were pretty deep and we had a lot of rotations
in the lineup,'' junior guard Jeff Trepagnier said. ``We didn't
have good chemistry. This year, no one is worrying about playing
time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that the Trojans are probably fielding their best
first five in years with forwards Brian Scalabrine, Sam Clancy and
David Bluthenthal, and guards Brandon Granville and Trepagnier.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the bench appears to be one of the worst in
recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest sign that coach Henry Bibby is not willing to try
out his new players came last week against Northwestern. The
Trojans won by 41 points, but other than freshman guard Nate Hair
(18 minutes), no reserve played more than eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of how desperate USC is for bench help: Senior
Jarvis Turner, who averaged 1.3 points his first three games, is
returning with great anticipation from a stress fracture in his
foot.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem a little negative, but it's hard to imagine that
the Trojans will experience a Pac-10 season free of injury or foul
problems.
</P>
<P>
   What then? No one really knows.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that Granville continues his recent hot streak from
the perimeter, that Clancy and Scalabrine remain effective inside
and Trepagnier shuts down the opponent's best player while getting
his share of crowd-pleasing dunks.
</P>
<P>
   That might be enough to beat the Washington States and Arizona
States. But it gets a lot stickier when USC faces Oregon, Cal or
even Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   USC hopes it can more than hold its own against those teams,
then it won't have to worry so much about beating Stanford, Arizona
or UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Already, USC ran out of energy in losses to North Carolina and
Duke. So it's likely that last year's upset over sixth-ranked
Stanford will be difficult to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when this year's losses to Utah State, St.
Bonaventure and Long Beach State are taken into consideration. The
Trojans lost to St. Bonaventure without Trepagnier, so that shows
how well things go when you remove one starter.
</P>
<P>
   There's always a chance someone will come off the bench and
surprise observers, but it's clear why no one rated this recruiting
class very high. Consider that as desperate as the Trojans are for
bench support, 7-foot-3 center Luke Minor is being redshirted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you're going to see a big, big improvement
(in conference play),'' Bibby said. ``We're building this program
and laying the foundation. We're a young, young team. Our guys are
decent enough to play 32-35 minutes a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will we win the Pac-10? Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a bench makes it difficult to assess where USC fits
into the Pac-10. The Trojans should be able to jockey for a
fourth-though-sixth spot, if they can physically withstand the
grind.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is a best-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a little easier to project them higher if forward
Greg Lakey (Loyola Marymount) or guards Kevin Augustine (Fullerton
Junior College) and Quincy Wilder (Boise State) had stuck around
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Even forward Shannon Swillis (Fresno State) might have added
something.
</P>
<P>
   But playing time was a factor in all four departing. If there is
a bright side for Bibby, he won't hear similar arguments from any
of this year's players. And if one of the current reserves decides
to leave, no one will care anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Trojans should be interesting to watch, an
odd experiment in physical endurance. But here's the bottom line:
The players know Bibby's system and are operating it quite
comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   There just aren't enough of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
