<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     01-06 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USUAL SUSPECTS IN PAC-10 RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's opening night in the Pac-10, so let's get to it. Around the
league in 1,200 words:
</P>
<P>
   10. Washington State (5-4): New coach Paul Graham, fresh from
Eddie Sutton's staff at Oklahoma State, began his tenure by running
off the starting point guard (Blake Pengelly) and losing to Nevada
by 25 points. Life in the Palouse might make Graham long for
Stillwater. Guard Jan-Michael Thomas figures to shoot the Cougs to
a few home wins. But they have no chance on the road and no chance
to finish higher than ninth.
</P>
<P>
   9. Washington (5-7): Only Pac-10 team with a losing
nonconference record. Huskies don't have center Todd MacCulloch for
first time in five years, and they've suffered a slew of injuries
to their makeshift frontline. Success depends on inconsistent
shooting guard Deon Luton and sophomore point Senque Carey. Huskies
won't get to set a school record with their third consecutive NCAA
Tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   8. Arizona State (8-3): Remember Ed Gray's unstoppable senior
season at Cal a few years ago? Well, Sun Devils guard Eddie House
is Gray II. Averaging 35 points in his last four games, House is
good enough to make the Sun Devils competitive against the league's
top teams. Whether ASU finishes eighth or sixth depends on everyone
else, especially forward Awvee Storey, a transfer from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   7. Cal (9-3): A good bet to be the league's big surprise. Bears
have one elite player, forward Sean Lampley, and a slew of talented
freshmen. More importantly, rookies Donte Smith, Shantay Legans,
Joe Shipp and Brian Wethers have accepted Ben Braun's superb
coaching _ unlike last year's reckless seniors, Geno Carlisle and
Thomas Kilgore. Bears beat Gonzaga two weeks ago; stay tuned for
more upsets.
</P>
<P>
   6. Oregon State (7-3): Beavers beat Stanford, UCLA and Arizona
at home last year, but no one's overlooking them this season. An
NIT bid is not only possible, it's probable. But to reach NCAAs,
OSU needs a few road wins, and that means point guard Dino Tanner
must make big shots and sound decisions. Center Brian Jackson is
one of the league's best rookies. Big blow: Center Jason Heide is
out indefinitely with a broken thumb.
</P>
<P>
   5. USC (7-5): It's a numbers game for USC. Losses to Utah State,
St. Bonaventure and Long Beach State mean the Trojans must win 10
conference games (and probably 11) for a shot at NCAAs. It's tough
to get 11 without at least one victory over UCLA, Arizona or
Stanford, so the pressure's on next week when Bruins visit the
Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Starters have scored 92 percent of the points, but forward
Jarvis Turner's return this week will help immensely. Four-man
frontline is solid, but success depends on guards Brandon Granville
and Jeff Trepagnier. They must score from perimeter to give
forwards room to work.
</P>
<P>
   4. UCLA (8-2): By far, the league's most unpredictable team. If
coaching, effort and talent coalesce, Bruins could win 22-24 games
and compete for the title. If injuries, sloppiness and lethargy
prevail, they could finish as low as fifth or sixth. Most likely,
Bruins will beat the bad teams, struggle against the mediocre teams
and flail against Stanford and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy when your point guard (Earl Watson) is a natural
wing guard, when your best player's a freshman (Jason Kapono), when
your potentially dominant center (Dan Gadzuric) has the knees of a
40-year-old and when your coaching staff has designed an offense
(the 1-4 high) that might not fit personnel. NCAA Tournament is no
guarantee; if Bruins don't qualify, coach Steve Lavin will need the
witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   3. Oregon (8-2): Ducks needed weeks to recover from the buzzer
loss to USC last year and staggered to the NIT. They won't lose
five games at McArthur Court this season, not with wing man Alex
Scales and guards Darius Wright and Freddie Jones. Although they've
struggled so far, Scales and Co. are one of the Pac-10's best
perimeter units. Forward A.D. Smith is a solid player, but Oregon's
fate hinges on the play of its other big men (Flo Hartenstein,
Chris Christoffersen and Julius Hicks). They only need to be decent
for Ducks to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   2. Arizona (11-2): Wildcats have the Pac-10's best starting five
and one of the nation's top forward tandems in Michael Wright and
Richard Jefferson. They're big and quick and immaculately prepared
by Lute Olson and assistant Jim Rosborough.
</P>
<P>
   But there are three potential problems. First, center Loren
Woods, for all his talent, is passive and inconsistent. Second, the
Pac-10 road is an unforgiving place for freshman guards, and Jason
Gardner and Gilbert Arenas are not immune. Third, there isn't much
depth. A series of transfers has left Arizona with eight
scholarship players and no backup point guard. (Bell-Jeff's Ruben
Douglas would be playing major minutes if he had stayed.)
</P>
<P>
   1. Stanford (11-0): Good enough to beat Duke and Auburn without
Mark Madsen. Good enough to beat Georgia Tech despite horrendous
shooting and a 9 a.m. (body time) tipoff. Good enough to redshirt
mega-recruit Justin Davis. Good enough to go 18-0?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. With the Collins twins, Madsen and fabulous
freshman Curtis Borchardt, the frontline is devastating. But point
guard Mike McDonald and the wings, David Moseley, Ryan Mendez and
Casey Jacobsen, haven't proven they can make big plays in the final
minutes on the road. No matter how impressive the nonleague
results, there's something about league play that exposes the
smallest deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   All-conference team: Arizona's Wright and Jefferson, UCLA
forward Jerome Moiso, USC forward Brian Scalabrine, Stanford's
Madsen and Jason Collins, Cal forward Lampley, Oregon's Scales,
Oregon State's Tanner and Arizona State's House. UCLA's Watson and
Arizona's Woods were the last cuts.
</P>
<P>
   All-freshman team: Stanford's Jacobsen, UCLA's Kapono, Arizona's
Gardner and Arenas, and Oregon State's Jackson form a sterling
quintet of rookies _ the best in years. (Playing time, not talent,
will keep Stanford's Borchardt off the team.)
</P>
<P>
   Best NBA prospect: Forget what you've read about Wright. He's a
superb college player, but when was the last time a 6-7 power
forward excelled in the NBA? He's not even the best prospect on his
team: Jefferson and Woods have more potential. But the player
scouts are drooling over is... Borchardt. He's big, mobile and
skilled, and he'll own the league in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Games of the year: The first showdown comes Saturday, when
Arizona visits Stanford. The winner takes a huge step towards the
league title, especially if it's Arizona, since victories in Maples
Pavilion are rarer than Pac-10 bowl victories.
</P>
<P>
   Five others to watch:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona at UCLA, Jan. 20: Bruins must win to compete for the
title. Last eight in Pauley Pavilion have been decided by 38
points.
</P>
<P>
   USC at Oregon State, Jan. 29: Chance for the Trojans to beat a
team with which they're competing for NCAA bid.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford at UCLA, Feb. 3: Cardinal has won five of the last six
overall and two straight in Pauley. Another chance for Bruins to
prove they belong with the elite.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford at Arizona, March 9: Pac-10 title and No. 1 seed in
West might be at stake. Cardinal has won two of the last four at
McKale Center.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State at Oregon, March 11: Tournament bid could be on the
line in the season finale. Mac Court promises to be bedlam. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0103EST &QL; 
