<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL CLIPS OTHER CENTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He would hardly be the first player accused of
appearing slightly intimidated by Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   As if Clippers center Michael Olowokandi wasn't having a bad
enough week, he had to to play consecutive nights against the most
dominating post player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal plays against Olowokandi and backup center Keith Closs
like a man who privately believes he can't be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay any attention,'' O'Neal said. ``I know
psychology-wise, when you first meet a guy and go at him, then he
has to think about you. You don't really have to think about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish one team would come in here and not double me so I
could give you all an exhibition of the 2,000 moves that I have in
each block (post).''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is off to an MVP start and has taken over the NBA lead in
rebounding from Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo at 14.5 per game.
Olowokandi and Closs are clearly overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal enjoys playing against the league's other premier
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up for the big guys,'' he said. ``Those are the guys
with the same talent I have, and if I don't get up for them,
they're going to embarrass me. And I don't like being embarrassed.
That's why I take it to everybody and try to demolish them.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland hovers: As well as the Lakers have been playing,
they've been unable to put much distance between themselves and the
Portland Trail Blazers, who remained two games out entering
Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers first played the Blazers this year, coach Phil
Jackson called them the ``best team money can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson isn't backing off, nor is he expecting Portland to start
falling off. The two teams next meet here on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be a time when you find out again where we're
out with the leaders of this conference,'' he said. ``I think
they'll be right where they're at now. We have a few tough games to
go through on a road trip, and I wouldn't be surprised if that game
might mean the division lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Tidbits: Jackson was named the NBA coach of the month, after the
Lakers completed a 14-1 December. Jackson said it really is a team
award: ``Our team was obviously the hot team for the month. I'm
happy to accept it on behalf of the team.''... Ex-Laker Derek
Harper, in limbo since his trade to Detroit, told ESPN.com that
Kobe Bryant is worthy of all the Michael Jordan hype: ``Kobe could
turn out to be that player, I'm serious. Being around Kobe last
year and seeing how he works on his game, he has a great chance.
Besides having all that talent, he's always picking your brain and
looking for an edge. All he needs is to learn how to help his team
win. I'll go out on a limb and say that when it's over, he'll be
one of the greatest players to ever play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
