<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTH SONICS SLIP PAST SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When the Sonics embarked on this two-game trek
through Texas, parts of their game were rough and ragged.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Sonics return home rolling quite smoothly after
finishing off the San Antonio Spurs 99-96 at the Alamodome
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was arguably the Sonic's most impressive victory of the
season for a few reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One, they won their second straight game on the road. Secondly,
they controlled a quality team in the defending NBA champion Spurs
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: The Sonics are now clicking with good offensive
execution and thorough defense when neither factors were strong
during their recent five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good a win as you're going to see,'' Sonics coach
Paul Westphal said. ``It came at a good time after losing five in a
row and then going on the road. But we were not playing poorly
during the losing streak. We could have had that game in Portland
(Dec. 28) and in Indiana (Dec. 21) it came down to the wire, and
Minnesota has just been beating everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're losing, it's not like everything stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Sonics had not been good enough in areas that
helped them chop down a taller, more physical Spurs team.
</P>
<P>
   But turning the ball over just eight times and scoring clutch
baskets down the stretch were keys to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' offensive execution created good, sometimes easy
shots. They moved the ball, and looked for two or three options
before attempting a shot. The team was particularly sharp with the
ball in the fourth quarter after having a 15-point first-half lead
dwindled to 91-89 with 2:40 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Brent Barry found Chuck Person wide open for a baseline
3-pointer. After Vin Baker split two free throws, Gary Payton put
the Sonics ahead 97-91 when his 6-foot floater fell with 18.6
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that the Sonics contained San Antonio's perimeter
players while making Tim Duncan and David Robinson work hard in the
paint.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, Greg Foster and Horace Grant took turns on the duo. They
gave Duncan and Robinson different defensive looks with arbitrary
double teams.
</P>
<P>
   He came up with a blocked shot and took a charge on David
Robinson in the final minute of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you beat a quality team like San Antonio on the road, it
feels like a roll,'' Baker said. ``It's kind of like it counts for
three wins even though it won't in the standings. But
confidence-wise, it helps us tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one drawback, it was the Sonics' free throw
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   They converted just 7-of-17 from the foul line. Otherwise, the
Sonics may have blown the game open. They led 46-31 with 4:49 left
in the second period. That lead was built mainly on forcing the
Spurs to settle for outside shots and the Sonics making their
jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Baker struggled through 4-of-16 shooting. But just about
everyone who played significant minutes shot well, including Foster
(5-of-5) and Person (3-of-7) off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary was just penetrating and finding us,'' Foster said.
``Early on in the season, we had a wild, run-and-gun attitude. Now,
we understand when we take bad shots, its makes it easier for the
other team to score.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio shot 48 percent, but most of its offensive
production came in the second half. The Sonics essentially kept the
Spurs at bay, and trailed only briefly in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But after San Antonio used a 9-2 run to go ahead 67-66, the
Sonics responded with a 3-pointer from Emanual Davis and took a
73-71 lead in to the fourth. They led 91-83 with six minutes left
in the game, and fought off a pair of San Antonio attempts to tie
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't look tired,'' Payton said. ``We just have to always
show this intensity, especially on the road. We were taking good
shots and running our offense. When you execute, you get easy
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Sonics game plan was to take advantage of their good
outside shooters. They conceded Duncan and Robinson would dominate
the paint. So Grant (8-for-12, 16 points) and Foster mostly sank
mid-range jumpers whenever Payton drew a double team or a crowd on
his drives to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Sonics activated forward Jelani McCoy and
place Lazaro Borell on the injured list. But McCoy did not play
because the offensive scheme was working so well.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Westphal played Person 19 minutes and he provided more
outside shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talked about how bad our defense was, but we had bad
offense during the losing streak,'' Person said. ``This (win) can
get us back to doing what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
