r s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      01-06 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS, DOLPHINS ENTER RUBBER MATCH IN POSTSEASON RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sixteen years later, after the advent of the Internet,
instant replay and cinnamon roll ice cream, we have the rubber
match.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins vs. Seahawks, postseason III.
</P>
<P>
   With the first-round AFC playoff game Sunday in the Kingdome,
distant memories have been stirred. There are even people pacing
the sideline, trying to shake off cobwebs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could put a uniform on, I'd go out there,'' former
Seahawks quarterback Dave Krieg said. ``I'd like a third chance to
see what could happen. I like the weapons. I'd like to make Sean
Dawkins catch the ball more. I'd throw it to Joey Galloway. I
wouldn't mind that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1983, the Seahawks traveled to Miami, and in 1984
made a return visit. The first trip brought what many consider the
most satisfying victory in Seattle's NFL franchise history, a 27-20
decision determined in the game's final two minutes. The other
resulted in comeuppance, a 31-10 drubbing in a return visit to the
Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino, 38, is the only player from
either game still in the league, though he feels the constant push
from those who firmly believe he belongs in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was a rookie the first time the Seahawks came to town.
Asked Wednesday to contrast the situations then and now, he let out
a weary sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 17 years ago,'' he said. ``That's two different things.
Then, I think you have the mindset where you're just kind of happy
to be in the league and be in the position. Now, your mindset is
you want this opportunity and to take advantage of it because you
never know when it might be your last.''
</P>
<P>
   On a rainy Saturday in South Florida, the Seahawks entered the
first Miami matchup as an eight-point underdog. They had struggled
to reach the playoffs for the first time with a 9-7 record,
advancing as a wild card team; the Dolphins were 12-4, AFC East
champs and a postseason team for the fifth time in six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we had was a lot of hope and (coach) Chuck Knox making us
believe in ourselves,'' Krieg said.
</P>
<P>
   Knox also brought veteran football smarts, putting the Seahawks
in a new two-back, two-tight end formation he had drawn up on the
plane ride to Florida. The Dolphins weren't ready for it, and were
unable to stop rookie running back Curt Warner, who rushed 29 times
for 113 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Seahawks would need some magic to pull this one out.
Leading 17-13 with 4:34 to play, Krieg nearly gave it all away when
he hurried a pass on a blitz, throwing outside while Hall of Famer
Steve Largent turned in. Defensive back Gerald Small intercepted
the ball and returned it 18 yards to the Seattle 16. Miami's Woody
Bennett scored three plays later to put his club on top.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seahawks and Krieg bounced back. The young quarterback
from Milton College hit Largent with a 40-yard pass to put his club
on the Miami 2. On the next play, Krieg handed off to Warner on a
sweep for the go-ahead score with 1:48 remaining. The Seahawks
recovered a Fulton Walker fumble on the ensuing kickoff and added a
37-yard Norm Johnson field goal with 24 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks had beaten the New York Giants and New England
Patriots in must-win games to make the playoffs, and ousted Denver
and Miami from the postseason. They were one game from the Super
Bowl. They could hardly believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Center Blair Bush had been to the Super Bowl with Cincinnati two
years before, the Rose Bowl with the Huskies six years earlier. The
Seahawks' first playoff run left undeniable memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole three- or four-week period might be the most fun I
had in my football career,'' said Bush, a 17-year NFL veteran who
retired in 1994 and now sells carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, it was a huge win,'' Krieg said. ``I watched the
interviews later, and I was talking really fast and really loud.
The emotions took you away. I just got swept up in it. We carried
Chuck off the field. We hadn't got to the big game yet and we
carried Chuck Knox off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, it was the Seahawks who needed stretchers.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Miami, the Seahawks had avenged a playoff
defeat to the Raiders. The Dolphins would do the same to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks showed up without Warner, who had torn up his knee
in the season opener. Dan Doornink, David Hughes, Eric Lane and
even fading Steelers standout Franco Harris had tried to replace
Warner. Their patchwork attempt was successful, as evidenced by the
club's 12-4 record and second playoff appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But Marino was no longer a rookie, and he wasn't bad as a
first-year player either. In his second trip 'round the NFL, he
threw an NFL-record 48 touchdown passes and 5,048 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, 6{-point underdogs this time, gamely lasted a
half, trailing 14-10 at intermission. Marino put them away with a
21-for-34, 262-yard, three-touchdown passing effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the week we were throwing it pretty well,'' Marino
recalled, probably confusing the game with every other that season,
``and we went to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Held to 51 yards rushing, the Seahawks went nowhere. They
obviously missed Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curt was our equalizer,'' defensive end Jacob Green said. ``He
could take some time off the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Warner might not have been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely wanted revenge,'' Krieg said. ``They weren't
that much better than the year before. We kept it close as long as
we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Now as the two teams prepare for their third playoff encounter,
the guys who squared off twice in 1984 are nursing their wounds,
working real jobs, counting their money. With the exception of
Marino, their time has passed.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell a certain former Seahawks quarterback that.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 seasons in the NFL, Krieg, 41, just spent his first
year out of football _ unvoluntarily. He stayed in shape, hoping
for a midseason call that never came. He's still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one curse about being a competitive person _ it doesn't
allow you to look at things rationally,'' Krieg said. ``I'm
watching the quarterbacks who are playing and that's why I still
want to play. I still believe I can do it, like Dan does.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
