u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE-2NDLD-WRI     01-06 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH BRADLEY AND GORE ENDORSE GAYS SERVING IN THE MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore and his Democratic
opponent, Bill Bradley, said on Wednesday night that if they were
elected president they would require their appointees to the Joint
Chiefs of Staff to fully support allowing homosexuals to serve
openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Although both candidates had previously opposed the Clinton
administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, their comments
in the fourth Democratic debate of the primary season, here at the
University of New Hampshire, were a strikingly forceful embrace of
gay rights and were bound to come under attack by the Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Their remarks came in response to a question of whether they
would support a ``litmus test'' on gays in the military in
nominating members of the Joint Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, Gore was the more expansive, saying he wanted to
make the same sweeping changes toward allowing homosexuals to serve
openly in the military that President Harry S. Truman made toward
racially integrating the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would require those who wanted to serve on the
Joint Chiefs to be in agreement with that policy,'' Gore said. ``I
would insist before appointing anybody to the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, that that individual support my policy, and yes, I would
make that a requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president drew a distinction between applying a litmus
test to Supreme Court justices and military officials, saying this
was ``not interfering with an independent judicial decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said simply that the commander in chief issued orders
and soldiers followed them. He said that while many in the armed
forces probably did not agree with President Clinton on some
military matters, ``My sense is that when you're president of the
United States, military people are loyal to their commander in
chief whatever the policy of the commander in chief calls for the
country, and that's what I'd expect them to do if I'm president of
the United States and we move toward gays in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said later that while he objected to the concept
of litmus tests, they could not imagine that he would appoint
anyone to the Joint Chiefs who did not back his policy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the candidates' agreement on homosexuals in the
military, the debate on Wednesday night was punctuated by edgy
exchanges as Gore and Bradley picked at details of each other's
past votes and present proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley portrayed the vice president as having been so trapped
in a ``Washington bunker'' that he had lost the ambition to fight
for proposals on health care and gun control. Gore suggested that
his rival was living in an ivory tower and lacked the know-how to
get things done.
</P>
<P>
   But the exchange over a gay-rights litmus test for top
commanders is almost certain to renew controversy in the military,
where many high-ranking officers strongly oppose allowing gays to
serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had originally pledged to allow homosexuals to
serve openly, but backed away from the plan after a near revolt by
Gen. Colin L. Powell and other members of the Joint Chiefs early in
his presidency. A result was ``the don't ask, don't tell'' policy,
which Bradley and Gore say is a failure.
</P>
<P>
   Retired members of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and other military
experts warned on Wednesday night that subjecting future members to
a litmus test would hurt the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military officers certainly execute the orders of the
president, but a litmus test beforehand would place an officer in
an untenable position saying, `Do you believe what I believe?'''
said Gen. Carl E. Mundy, a retired commandant of the Marine Corps.
``I think it would be unworkable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An officer's judgment has to be tempered by his judgment of
what's best for the armed forces, not for a political agenda,''
said Mundy, who opposes allowing homosexuals to serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' comments on Wednesday night about homosexuals in
the military underscored the degree to which Gore and Bradley are
intent on courting the liberal base of their party. In fact,
earlier in the debate, neither candidate objected to being
described as a liberal _ a label that Democrats, including Bill
Clinton, have eschewed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberal, progressive, whatever,'' Bradley said. ``I'll accept
whatever label you want because that's who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who earlier in the day was endorsed by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy of Massachusetts, said, ``I really don't care what kind of
label people apply to those positions and views.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the harshest remark during the hourlong debate came from
Bradley after he was asked when Gore had ever taken one of his
quotes or votes out of context. ``The one that was most
particularly offensive to me was when he said in this campaign that
I was going to hurt African-Americans, Latinos with the health care
program I have offered,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say to me, who's had the deep commitment to the issue of
racial unity in this country since I started in politics, that I
would go out and hurt African-Americans and Latinos, consciously,
as part of a policy, I think really offended me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore defended his comments, saying, ``Well, you know, Harry
Truman said in 1948, `I'm not giving him hell. I'm just telling the
truth and he thinks it's hell.''' He said he had simply explained
that ``poor people are disproportionately likely to be minorities''
and would be affected the most by Bradley's replacement of Medicaid
with an alternative program.
</P>
<P>
   Both contenders were trying to score points with a precious few
weeks before the Feb. 1 primary here. Polls in this state show that
Gore and Bradley are within shouting distance of each other.
</P>
<P>
   The face-off here, the first in 2000, opened a flurry of debates
among the White House hopefuls. Republicans will debate here on
Thursday and in South Carolina on Friday. On Saturday, Gore and
Bradley will debate in Iowa. And the Republican candidates will
appear at a forum here on Sunday and then at a debate in Michigan
on Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday night's debate, Bradley appeared particularly
aggressive and was more willing to take issue with Gore than he had
been in the past. But he also had a relaxed air and displayed an
easy humor.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, for instance, Gore insisted that he respected his
rival. ``I respect Bill, I really do,'' he said. ``I'm not just
saying that as a ploy. I think he's a genuinely good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Peter Jennings, the moderator and ABC News anchor, if
he agreed with Gore, Bradley drew laughs when he replied, ``I agree
with what he said, yeah. I think I'm a genuinely good person.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Bradley verged on condescension, as when he said,
``Let me explain to you, Al, how the private sector works, O.K.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore seemed calmer than in his earlier performances as he
fielded questions, but still did not shrink from criticizing
Bradley's record. He was particularly persistent in upbraiding the
former senator from New Jersey for what he depicted as mistaken
votes, such as supporting President Ronald Reagan's budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We passed tough welfare reform, which I think has worked; you
voted against it,'' Gore said. ``I voted against those budget cuts;
you voted for them. I voted, as I said a moment ago, for the
resolution to use military force to push Saddam Hussein out of
Kuwait; you voted against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he did not regret any of those votes. ``In '81, if
everybody in the Congress had voted as I had voted,'' he said, ``we
would not have had the deficit of the 1990s. As a result of that we
would have had more economic growth.'' And Bradley said he was
still not convinced that the welfare reform effort was working or
that it would have been wrong to try sanctions before using force
against Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sought to depict the vice president as thinking like a
Washington insider and afraid to try ambitious proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear you talk, Al, it reminds me of a Washington
bunker,'' Bradley said. ``I can understand why you're in the bunker
because of Gingrich, there was the fund-raising scandal, the
impeachment problem. And I think that the major objective in the
last several years in the White House has been political
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that,'' Bradley continued. ``But the reality is
the Democratic Party should be thinking big things, with big
ambitions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore portrayed Bradley as out of touch with the realities of
Washington. ``I believe that the presidency is not an academic
exercise,'' Gore said. ``It's not an extended seminar on theory. It
has to be a daily fight for the best interests of the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The country can ill afford big mistakes by a
president who stumbles into something that could be avoided with
the kind of judgment and experience that our people ought to have
the right to expect in any president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
