<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ SCORES 40 AS LAKERS SWEEP CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As an historic event, it may not hold up as the
highlight of the century, but it's a new millennium and the Lakers
will take what they can these days.
</P>
<P>
   What they are mostly taking is victory after victory, their
118-101 dismantling of the Clippers on Wednesday night leaving them
with 12 consecutive overall and an equal amount in a row over their
Staples Center B team.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first known time in NBA history that two teams
played each on consecutive nights in the same arena during a
regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen this one before,'' said Lakers coach Phil
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels,'' said Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal, ``strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately it had to feel like something else to the Clippers _
very familiar. O'Neal led the Lakers with 40 points and 19
rebounds, again pulling his man-against-boys routine against the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, starting his first game of the season without the
supporting glove for the hand he broke in the preseason, added 26
points, 10 rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom did what he could with 26 points and 12 rebounds for
the Clippers, while Tyrone Nesby added 23 and Maurice Taylor 22
points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Clippers, there could be much better starts to a new
century.
</P>
<P>
   They did manage to tease their faithful early. The first half
looked nothing if not familiar.
</P>
<P>
   It felt like a virtual replay of the previous night, the
Clippers playing well, hitting their shots, playing some defense,
holding their own.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Troy Hudson gave them a particular early lift, hitting
five of eight shots to lead the Clippers with 13 first-half points
and passing out five assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, too, looked much like the team that had started
slowly in the first half Tuesday, needing only to suddenly get
serious in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   It was tied 52-52 at the half, but there was hardly any sense of
urgency. The Lakers had been through all this before, and only 24
hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, the Clippers wouldn't go for the quick
second-half fade.
</P>
<P>
   This time they lasted almost another whole quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With Odom giving them a boost, the Clippers remained tied with
the Lakers at 73-73 with 2:44 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers finally decided to flex their muscle, or at
least O'Neal did.
</P>
<P>
   With both Clippers centers Michael Olowokandi and Keith Closs
again ineffective against O'Neal and battling foul trouble,
Clippers coach Chris Ford tried 6-foot-9 forward Maurice Taylor on
the 7-2 O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored four of the six points the Lakers closed the
quarter with and the first five of the final quarter. Suddenly the
Lakers had an 84-73 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was never a game again.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers wilted under the Lakers' first real charge and it
was quickly scrub time.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Lakers improved their NBA-best record to
27-5. The 12 consecutive victories is their most since the 1990-91
team won 16 straight.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi fouled out with four points, giving him five total in
the two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
