A8000 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PNEUMONIA-WAVE-LADN     01-06 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PNEUMONIA-WAVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLU, COLD SEASON TOLL IS CHILLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Robert Monroe 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hospitals across the Los Angeles region and state reported
Wednesday that the numbers of patients with pneumonia have soared
as a result of a wave of cold and flu cases.
</P>
<P>
   The influenza virus can cause pneumonia or act as a catalyst for
the potentially fatal illness by weakening the body's defenses,
doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Presbyterian Hospital in Van Nuys said 10 percent of its
230 patients have pneumonia-related illnesses compared with 1
percent or 2 percent normally.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the hospitals are getting bombarded,'' said Valley
Presbyterian spokeswoman Kellye Tarelka, who also noted a 30
percent increase in emergency room visits due to the flu and
similar illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Other hospitals also reported a spike in pneumonia cases.
</P>
<P>
   At Granada Hills Community Hospital, 37 out of the 104 admitted
patients have pneumonia or respiratory illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been this impacted probably in 10 years,'' said
hospital spokeswoman Sara Buchbinder.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials said pneumonia accounted for 10 percent
of hospital admissions at the height of last year's cold and flu
season but now is upward of 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think flu is driving most of that,'' said Carol Glaser, a
medical officer with the state Department of Health. ``It's a
heavier flu season. Last year was a light year.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of flu season, pneumonia typically accounts for about 3
percent of hospital admissions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Providence Holy Cross Medical Center in Mission Hills, 29 of
222 patients have pneumonia, an unusually large number, said
spokeswoman Tiffany Devall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospital's full,'' said Dr. Jay Brown, an emergency room
physician at Providence Holy Cross, who said a flu epidemic from
two years ago pales in comparison with this year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is worse than that one. It's lasting longer and more
sustained,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County numbers for pneumonia cases were not
immediately available, but hospital association representatives
said they have noticed a surge in pneumonia cases, some caused by
the flu and others prompted by other respiratory viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an unrelated virus that was aggravated by dry and arid
conditions in Southern Californa that contributes to pneumonia
cases,'' said Jim Lott, spokesman for the Health Care Association
of Southern California, which represents 220 hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis Dassey, deputy medical director of acute communicable
disease control of the county Department of Health Services, said
his agency is monitoring the situation but that a comprehensive
picture of pneumonia's spread might not be available for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say whether pneumonia is up, down or whatever,'' said
Dassey.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, most of the pneumonia patients filling local
hospital beds come from the populations most vulnerable to it: the
very young and the very old. Brown advised that the elderly should
visit their physicians at the first sign of illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If older folks start to get a cough, they should come in
rather than waiting until they have fever or chest pains or are
really debilitated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mike Neskovic, medical director for preventive services at
Glendale Memorial Hospital and Health Center, said the consensus
among his colleagues is that the viruses now circulating are much
more aggressive than types seen in recent years. He said young,
otherwise healthy people can ride out the viruses by drinking
plenty of water, taking vitamins and anti-inflammatory drugs to
combat fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say if you are young and healthy, you don't have to
call the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   And Neskovic also advises people to get flu shots if they
haven't done so, all the way up to April. There is little
assurance, say other officials, that the cold and flu season will
be over any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably won't crest until the middle of January,'' said
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   -- Staff Writer David Baker contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
