 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THRUSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LAWYERS (Nanjing, China) _ Though China has tried to
change its legal system, growing numbers of young lawyers find
themselves on the wrong end of the law. Defense lawyers are often
harassed, beaten and occasionally thrown in jail. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHURCHILL-DEGAULLE (London) _ Winston Churchill plotted to oust
Gen. Charles de Gaulle as leader of the Free French forces during
World War II, according to British government papers released to
the public. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEATH-PENALTY (Tallahassee, Fla.) _ As state lawmakers begin
meeting in a special session to consider doing away with the
electric chair, one thing is clear: The real debate lies not in
that issue but in an accompanying proposal to speed up the appeals
process, with its intended result to allow the state to execute
death row inmates more quickly. The proposal, put forward by Gov.
Jeb Bush, would pattern Florida's death penalty appeal process
after the one in Texas, which has executed more people than any
other state in history. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-TAX (Washington) _ Assessing the Bill Bradley tax
loophole closing plan. A political memo by Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSHING-RUSH-LIMBAUGH (Undated) _ Rush Limbaugh noticed it about
two months ago. Listeners were asking why there were more
commercials on his daily three-hour radio program. ``At first I
didn't know what they were talking about,'' Limbaugh said. ``I was
talking for the same amount of time every day.'' But without his
knowledge, his words were being sucked into a temporal never-never
land. A new kind of digital technology was literally snipping out
the silent pockets in between words, shortening the pauses and
generally speeding up the pace of his speechifying. With no
fanfare, the digital program has established a foothold in the
radio industry in the last six months. General managers at about 50
radio stations across the country are eagerly using it, unbeknownst
to consumers, for one purpose: squeezing talk and music so that
they can wedge in more commercials and make more money. By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MERRILL-LYNCH (Takamatsu, Japan) _ The ``ginza,'' or
shopping street, of this Japanese town looks much like the ginza of
any other moderately sized city in Japan. It is also home to one of
the most successful Japanese branches of Merrill Lynch, which has
placed the biggest, riskiest bet so far in the continuing effort by
foreigners to sell ever-so-wary Japanese on American-style asset
management. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Amazon.com says fourth-quarter
sales more than doubled to $650 million, higher than analysts
estimates of $450 million to $600 million. But it also announces
plans to take bigger-than-expected fourth-quarter charges to write
down inventory. It's stock takes a tumble. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WILD-PARTIES (New York) _ So is that the ``Wild Party''
featuring Mandy Patinkin or the ``Wild Party'' featuring Taye
Diggs? The ``Wild Party'' written by Andrew Lippa or the one by
Michael John LaChiusa and George C. Wolfe? The ``Wild Party''
produced by Manhattan Theater Club which opens Feb. 24 Off Broadway
or the ``Wild Party'' presented by the New York Shakespeare
Festival/Joseph Papp Public Theater and several commercial
producers that opens April 6 on Broadway? This is exactly the
confusion that producers of both ``Wild Party'' productions are
concerned about creating in the months ahead. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly books column. By Martin Arnold.
</P>
