 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-HOUSE (Undated) _ During our fourth year of spending time
in the Mexican mountain town of San Miguel de Allende, I and my
wife, the artist and photographer Masako Takahashi, were taken to
see a derelict house with an interior courtyard, a stable and a
small attached house. Ravished by the possibilities, but daunted by
the house's condition and its price ($65,000), we nonetheless took
the plunge. With time, we came to understand that this house in
fact completed us as much as we completed it. By Tony Cohan.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LANDFILL (New York) _ Dr. Steven Handel stood on top of a
mountain of garbage, 150 feet above Richmond Creek, and imagined
woodlands and meadows rambling over the Fresh Kills landfill in
Staten Island. ``This is the biggest landfill in the world,'' said
Handel, a plant ecologist based at Rutgers University in New
Brunswick, N.J. ``But you have to have vision. Imagine this as a
developing oak forest. Or a stand of red cedars, or a wildflower
meadow. With 3,000 acres, we could bring back some plants which are
locally uncommon.'' By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-FERRIS-WHEEL (London) _ They had promised their children
a New Year's Eve ride on the British Airways London Eye, the
455-foot Ferris wheel that stands over the Thames across from Big
Ben. Instead, David Marks and Julia Barfield, the husband-and-wife
architects who designed the structure, had to entertain their
family on the ground. The children _ plus several hundred guests of
British Airways _ were unable to ride after the attraction failed
an 11th-hour inspection. For Ms. Barfield and Marks, who went into
debt to get the $40 million dollar wheel built, the failure of a
clutch mechanism in one of its 32 passenger compartments was only
the latest indignity. By Fred A. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-HOARD (Undated) _ Two times during the 19th Century, the
Millerites predicted that the world would end. The first error was
attributed to a little miscalculation. Before the second date _
Oct. 22, 1844 _ followers eagerly packed up their homes, sold all
their possessions, and prayed. Once again, the Apocalypse failed to
arrive and this time the (penniless) followers insisted that their
prayers had kept it at bay. More modest versions of this scenario
appear to be taking place now in homes across the country: while
the Y2K crisis never materialized, the most dedicated hoarders are
holding on to their 200 cans of tuna fish, 100 freeze dried MREs,
and 55-gallon water tanks as tightly as their convictions. By Lynn
Ermann.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
