<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8039 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-     01-06 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ SCORES 40 AS LAKERS SWEEP CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As an historic event, it may not hold up as the
highlight of the century, but it's a new millennium and the Lakers
will take what they can.
</P>
<P>
   What they are mostly taking is victory after victory, their
118-101 dismantling of the Clippers on Wednesday night leaving them
with 12 consecutive overall and an equal amount in a row over their
Staples Center B team.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first known time in NBA history that two teams
played each other on consecutive nights in the same arena in
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   That will prove of little solace to the Clippers, who have no
answers for the Lakers in general and Shaquille O'Neal in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal again did his man-against-boys routine, scoring 40 points
and pulling down 19 rebounds. He felt so good afterwards, he
offered up a new nickname for himself: the Big Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers, baby, numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Very big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have now won 19 of their last 21, and matched against
a talented but typically inexperienced Clippers team, suspense
wasn't going to make a long stay Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the Clippers made it a virtual replay of the previous
night's effort, by keeping close early. The game was tied 52-52 at
the half, yet with O'Neal in the middle there never seemed any
sense of urgency, just a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the toughest thing about Shaq?'' asked Clippers
forward Lamar Odom. ``He makes you feel like you're in junior
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Clippers _ battling, playing some solid defense,
spreading the ball around _ made a game of it.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, the Clippers wouldn't go for the quick
second-half fade.
</P>
<P>
   This time they lasted almost another whole quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With Odom (26 points, 12 rebounds, five assists) giving them a
boost, the Clippers were still tied with the Lakers at 73-73 with
2:44 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers finally decided to flex their muscle, or at
least O'Neal did.
</P>
<P>
   With both Clippers centers _ Michael Olowokandi and Keith Closs
_ again ineffective against O'Neal and battling foul trouble,
Clippers coach Chris Ford tried 6-foot-9 forward Maurice Taylor on
the 7-2 O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored four of the six points the Lakers closed the
quarter with and the Lakers' first five of the final quarter.
Suddenly the Lakers had an 84-75 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And it was never a game again.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers wilted under the Lakers' first real charge and it
was quickly scrub time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have an answer for (O'Neal),'' Ford said. ``In the
triangle offense, it's very difficult to double him _ they have
great spacing and great cutting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, cleared to play without the supporting glove he had
worn since fracturing his right hand, added 26 points and 10
rebounds for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lakers coach Phil Jackson was less than thrilled overall
by the odd two-game stretch against an undermanned opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that's over with,'' Jackson said. ``Good games for us
to win, not a whole lot of fun to play, or watch or coach.''
Expected to win, Bryant said there isn't a lot the Lakers can gain
from such games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate games like this,'' Bryant said. ``The only positive
thing that comes out of a game like this is a `W.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson wasn't thrilled with the Lakers' defensive effort and
complained ``there was a sense of complacency I didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's difficult to get too upset when you're pounding
everyone in sight, even if it is the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Lakers improved their NBA-best record to
27-5. The 12 consecutive victories is their most since the 1990-91
team won 16 straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, meanwhile, tried to help Odom's cause with 23
points from Tyrone Nesby and 22 and 11 rebounds from Taylor, but
they were almost playing four against five when O'Neal was around.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi fouled out with four points, giving him five total in
the two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0241EST &QL; 
