<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR WOULD WELCOME A TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The ship has been sinking for more than a week,
but Maurice Taylor doesn't feel like the king of world.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the Clippers' free-agent-to-be power forward
is ready to roll overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Taylor said Wednesday, responding to an
inquiry about his interest in being shopped before next month's NBA
trading deadline. ``The best thing for them (Clippers) would be to
trade me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Taylor's not-so-free agent, David Falk, encouraged
such a maneuver before training camp. That posture was inspired by
Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling's thumbs-down response to their
request for a big-loot contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Team sources said no deadline-beating deal is imminent. The
Clippers might recoup more value in a sign-and-trade this summer,
although they'd run the risk of having a team with cap room hire
Taylor outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to do what's best for the team now,'' Taylor, who's
averaging 17.8 points and 6 rebounds, said as a sooner-than-later
trade endorsement. ``But while I'm here, I'm just going to play as
hard as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Closs-trophobia
</P>
<P>
   During the lingering foul play of center Michael Olowokandi,
Keith Closs - the 7-foot-3 caddy - has provided some bite when
summoned from Coach Chris Ford's doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   While averaging an utterly modest 4.3 points and 2.8 rebounds
per game, a Closs sighting often generates unmatched Clipper fan
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because I take time to interact with the fans,'' Closs
explained. ``I talk to them before the game, during the game - even
though that's discouraged - and spit out a couple of jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   His popularity also is enhanced by his involvement in the team's
many community relations events.
</P>
<P>
   To Closs, being a towering professional athlete still doesn't
put him above the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just have a different job than someone else,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He had Olowokandi's job for 14 minutes Wednesday, coming through
with a modest 4 points and 2 rebounds. He also was the third victim
in Shaquille O'Neal's tag-team demolition of Olowokandi and Taylor.
O'Neal, who had 38 points and 15 rebounds Tuesday, produced 40 and
19 Wednesday. The Clippers hadn't surrendered 40 or more points
since Utah's Karl Malone to 42 on 'em Nov. 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fast breaks
</P>
<P>
   Reserve forward/center Brian Skinner had the protective boot
removed from his left foot, and is moving around on the left ankle
he sprained in the Dec. 14 loss to the Lakers. But don't expect to
see the 6-9, 250-pound strongman anytime soon. ``It could be
anywhere from two weeks to a month before I'm back,'' Skinner said.
... The Clippers waived frontcourt temp Marty Conlon, who averaged
.7 points and .7 rebounds in three cameos. ... Tyrone Nesby dropped
3 of 7 3-point shots vs. the Lakers, and has connecte d on 23 of
his last 52 (45 percent). ... Fans planning to attend Saturday
night's game with the Indiana Pacers at Staples Center are warned
that traffic flow could be compromised by the auto show at the L.A.
Convention Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
