<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-INDEPENDENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT ANDERSON TO MEET WITH HIS CALIFORNIA BACKERS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ John Anderson, the 1980 independent
presidential hopeful, said he's coming to California to meet with
supporters and ``give serious thought'' to a movement by Reform
Party loyalists to draft him for a 2000 presidential run.
<P>
   The former GOP congressman from Illinois, who earned 8.6 percent
of the California vote during his maverick campaign for the
presidency, said an Anderson candidacy would offer voters a serious
debate on issues that ``I don't hear coming from either Republicans
or Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Anderson, 77, president and CEO of the World Federalist
Association, a nonprofit political advocacy group, hasn't decided
whether to run, his name has been officially placed on the March 7
primary ballot in California at the request of Reform Party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a lot of friends in California, and I have spoken
extensively in the state,'' Anderson said in an interview. Saying
he will make his decision in the next few weeks, he added, ``I'm
planning a visit in March ... to touch bases with them. Then we'll
have to see what the next step is.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of Anderson's possible jump into the Reform Party fray
comes as millionaire developer Donald Trump prepares to meet this
week with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura. It also comes as Pat
Buchanan _ the former GOP commentator whose state campaign has been
decidedly low-key to date _ comes to California for a private
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes as bitter infighting has split the party, with
factions loyal to Ventura and to Reform Party founder Ross Perot
squabbling over the location of the national Reform Party
convention.
</P>
<P>
   With that backdrop, Anderson said he knows any fight for the
Reform Party nomination could be a knock-down, drag-out affair _
and it doesn't worry him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never shied away from a battle or fight,'' he said. ``I
wouldn't engage in a political contest solely for the purpose of
blackening the name of anyone, even though I hold views that are
profoundly different'' from those of Trump, Buchanan and Perot.
</P>
<P>
   But the possibility of another run by Anderson sent a buzz
through the Reform Party rank and file this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although some critics have suggested that, two decades after his
last presidential bid, Anderson may be past his prime, a Web-based
Draft Anderson movement
 &UR; (www.prairienet.org/icpr/anderson)  &LR; has sprung up, with supporters
saying the veteran politician could be a unifier and a credible
third-party alternative to Republican and Democratic choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the father of the independent political movement,'' said
Dan Johnson-Weinberger, a Reform Party activist and a driving force
behind the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that for the silent majority of the Reform
Party ... this is the candidate they've been waiting for _
unmatched integrity, a record of public service and an innovative
progressive candidate. He's talking about real political reform.''
</P>
<P>
   With California's March 7 primary barely 60 days away, Anderson
said he's flattered by such support.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has something to offer voters on such issues as
campaign finance reform, trade and foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a much more advanced position on campaign finance
reform than either Mr. (Bill) Bradley or Mr. (John) McCain,'' said
Anderson, who calls the McCain-Feingold campaign finance reform
measure ``a weak, weak compromise that doesn't begin to address the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in total public financing,'' Anderson said. ``I
don't believe you're ever going to cure the mess we have in
American politics unless you accept the idea that an election is a
public function and ought to be publicly financed.''
</P>
<P>
   Without it, ``the linkage between special interests and
contributions can never be removed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, whose work at the World Federalist Association
involves lobbying for ``universal human rights and the global rule
of law,'' also provides a dramatic contrast to other candidates _
particularly Buchanan, in the area of international relations and
free trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the (United Nations) not only must be supported by
the payment of our dues _ but we have to work to empower it, to
strengthen it, to make it the basis of a world organization that
would give it strength to deal with the bloody crisis we've seen in
the past decade,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
