<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-DRUG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLU DRUG IN STRONG DEMAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A wave of flu and respiratory illness has nearly
exhausted supplies in the suburban Los Angeles of two of the newest
flu-fighting drugs, pharmacists said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Pascal, pharmacist at Northridge Pharmacy in a suburban
area of Los Angeles, said that just before New Year's Day, he
ordered nearly 36 units of the prescription anti-flu drug Relenza,
three times his normal stock, after being told earlier that
wholesalers were out of stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually never ran out of it, but we got really close,''
Pascal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere around the Valley, doctors said their patients have
had trouble as recently as last week finding Relenza, one of
several antiviral drugs that can be effective if used within 24
hours of symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Drug wholesalers including the Orange, Calif.-based Bergen and
Brunswig, which supplies Pascal's pharmacy among others, said there
have only been brief shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not experiencing any shortages we can't meet,'' said a
company spokeswoman who did not wish to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome, maker of Relenza, said that in the middle two
weeks of December, prescriptions of the drug more than doubled from
70,000 to 168,000. Company spokeswoman Lisa Behrens said there was
no indication the drug maker had any trouble keeping up with
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The product is moving very briskly and working beyond our
expectations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said they are writing more prescriptions for standard
antibiotics that are more effective once flu and cold viruses take
hold and leave people vulnerable to bacterial infections.
</P>
<P>
   After a week or more of symptoms, physicians usually try to
treat secondary bacterial infections of the lungs or sinuses, said
Dr. Robert W. Rigg Jr. of West Oaks Family Practice Urgent Care
Center in Canoga Park.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Golden, pharmacist at the Medicine Shoppe in Encino, said
he has handled only a handful of Relenza prescriptions and none of
Tamiflu. He said he is filling more prescriptions of conventional
antibiotics and that over-the-counter drugs remain as popular as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequently it's a matter of treating the symptoms to make
people comfortable and let it run its course,'' Golden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8049 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     01-06 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TRYING TO HELP JUST DOESN'T PAY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The beat cop wasn't trying to be the Lone
Ranger, he swears. Just trying to do his job, maybe do a little
extra to help people out, but it didn't really work.
</P>
<P>
   His good intentions, as the old expression goes, came back and
bit him on the ass.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gratz pounds the beat at Washington Square Park in North
Beach, and at Union Square, Justin Herman Plaza and several other
smaller parks in the Central Station jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   He's a 20-year veteran of the force, and five years ago, he and
some other officers were assigned to the parks, with instructions
to take them back, make them usable for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   What Gratz found at Washington Square was a group of about 15
regulars, homeless and semi-homeless. They slept in the park, and
they peed and pooped and barfed and drank and smoked and shot up
and fell down and once in a while died in the park, too.
</P>
<P>
   To each his own, but Washington Square isn't that big, and when
people are fighting with 2-by-4s and having group sex, where do you
put the kiddies and the moms and the old-timers and the tai chi-ers
and the Frisbee flingers?
</P>
<P>
   How do you deal fairly and humanely with the unruly element?
</P>
<P>
   ``We made friends with 'em from the start,'' says Gratz, a
lanky, amiable guy who plays guitar and writes songs for a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   If the folks in the park seemed to need shelter, or food, or a
place to sober up, the cops would load 'em in the police van and
take 'em to 39 Fell Street, a shelter where they could get a
shower, a meal, a cot and some counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd walk 'em in like we were their dads,'' Gratz says.
``They'd be back in the park in an hour, drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   The cops wrote hundreds of citations for drinking in public and
other offenses, but Gratz says all the citations were dismissed by
the court commissioner. One woman has been written up and/or
arrested well over 100 times, Gratz says.
</P>
<P>
   One day Gratz read a column in The Chronicle about some Bay Area
police forces that were distributing flyers to liquor stores, with
snapshots of habitual public drunks and a warning not to sell 'em
booze.
</P>
<P>
   Gratz figured he'd give it a try. He did a little legal research
of his own, got permission from his lieutenant, took a camera into
the park, asked some of the hardest-core drinkers if he could snap
their picture. One of the men joked, ``What's this for, a
yearbook?'' But Gratz swears  &UR; he  &LR; never said that.
</P>
<P>
   He had flyers made up, and he handed them out to a half dozen
liquor stores near the Square with instructions not to sell liquor
to these people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had to do something to try and save their lives,''
Gratz says. ``That's exactly what I get paid to do. I knew if I
could help them with the alcohol problem, it might be the first
step in getting them indoors. I have nothing against booze, but
plainly it was killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gratz says the flyers got a 100 percent positive reaction from
the liquor store owners. But the Coalition on Homelessness heard
about the flyers and made a claim against the city that the flyers
were a violation of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gratz says he's sure the city would have won a legal fight, but
it chose to avoid a costly court battle, and he doesn't blame his
bosses. As a settlement, each of the 10 people was given about
$960.
</P>
<P>
   None, as far as Gratz knows, used a dime for shelter. All 10 are
still on the street or worse, he says. One is in a near-continual
drunken stupor. Another was admitted to Laguna Honda nearly
paralyzed with alcohol poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is gone and the Coalition will tell you some of them
are better off, but I know better,'' Gratz says. ``I see them every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing you should know about the ongoing battle to help the
homeless is that the Helping Army is split into many squabbling
factions. To over-generalize, homeless advocates distrust the cops,
cops are cynical of the advocates, and each group has its own
philosophy and turf and agenda and horror stories about the other
guys. Any time I write something positive about a shelter or soup
kitchen, someone from another homeless-helper outfit calls
anonymously to tell me what a crooked sham operation it is I'm
praising.
</P>
<P>
   The war within a war will continue. Gratz would like to see
public assistance money given in the form of vouchers for food and
shelter, but many homeless advocates say that would deprive the
homeless of their rights and their dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Gratz watches the park folks beat one another up on a regular
basis and pass out on the grass during a rainstorm, and he wonders
where the dignity is in that.
</P>
<P>
   When his flyers were shot down, when his plan went awry, Gratz
says a lot of other cops laughed or said, ``We told you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So now we'll just do our jobs,'' Gratz says, strolling the
walkway around Washington Square on a beautiful winter morning.
``We'll collect our paychecks, try to make it to retirement without
getting into trouble. But it would be nice if someone could come up
with a solution. I tried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
