<SLUG> BC-STATE-OFTHESTATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS VOWS AID TO RAISE POOR SCHOOLS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Declaring ``war on mediocrity in our public
schools,'' Gov. Gray Davis called Wednesday night for greater
incentives to increase the number of skilled teachers, particularly
in low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   In his second State of the State address, the Democratic
governor also called for improving care for the elderly, speeding
construction of transportation projects and beefing up local police
and sheriff's departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of our state is strong,'' Davis told the Legislature
and other California elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy is booming, unemployment is at an historic low,
the technological revolution begun in our Silicon Valley is
transforming the globe, our universities are world class, crime
rates are heading downward and our budget is balanced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate themes of Davis' speech were the same as those he
campaigned on in 1998: more money for schools, more money to fight
crime and more money for projects to repair, replace or expand
California's aging public works.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's short-on-specifics speech was broadly praised,
even by Republicans who backed many of his reward-for-performance
themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a speech that could have been given by Pete Wilson. In
fact, I think it was,'' said Senator Jim Brulte, R-Rancho
Cucamonga, referring to Davis' GOP predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats worried that their governor offered little
assistance to lower-income Californians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Class divisions in this state have never been sharper,'' said
Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco. ``If we have this
one-time bonanza of cash, we should do something significant to
alter that imbalance.''
</P>
<P>
   Migden said she hopes that when Davis outlines the specifics of
his spending plans in the state's $80 billion-plus budget Monday, a
hefty chunk of an expected $2.5billion surplus will be devoted to
poorer Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Often using military imagery, Davis spent most of his 44-minute
speech outlining a variety of proposals directed at improving the
state's sprawling public school system _ particularly a shortage of
qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next eight years, we must recruit and train more
teachers than were troops in the Allied forces that stormed
Normandy on D-Day,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Several ideas appeared to be responses to critics who have said
Davis' education spending does not emphasize assistance for
students in schools in low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   To lure qualified teachers to such schools, Davis offered a grab
bag of financial incentives to teachers who agree to work in
schools whose academic performance ranks in the lower 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He offered college loans of as much as $11,000 and a $20,000
bonus for top college graduates who get teaching credentials.
Credentialed teachers could also receive $10,000 loans to help buy
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Retired teachers who chose to return to work at any school would
be allowed to keep their full pensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To borrow a phrase from Uncle Sam, I intend to say to our
young people: `I want you to be a teacher,' '' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats opposed Davis' proposed $1,000 college
scholarships for students who score in the top 10 percent on
statewide academic assessment tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is important. We should do all the things the
governor said except that stupid scholarship. One thousand dollars
to take a stupid test. That's inane,'' said Sen. John Vasconcellos,
D-Santa Clara. ``You should put the money where people in need can
use it.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also called for increased aid for the elderly,
including higher pay for in-home caregivers, better pay for
nursing-home staff and more money for adult day-care facilities and
residential centers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Highway, Transit Projects
</P>
<P>
   Citing congestion in Silicon Valley and the clogged commute from
the San Joaquin Valley to the Bay Area, Davis proposed spending
$7.5 billion on highway, transit and inter-city rail projects.
</P>
<P>
   He said that $3 billion of the $7.5 billion would be new funds,
but he did not say where the money would come from.
</P>
<P>
   After noting that the state's crime rate is at its lowest point
in 25 years, Davis said he wants to provide more grants to police
and sheriff's departments for ``crime-fighting technology to
improve response times.''
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed hiring 100 new parole agents to supervise
paroled felons who have committed two violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   With the new agents, the average caseload would decline from 70
parolees per agent to 40 parolees per agent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other items Davis proposed were:
</P>
<P>
   -- $200 million to link schools to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   -- $75 million to create ``Institutes for Science and
Innovation'' at three University of California campuses to
encourage more research and development.
</P>
<P>
   -- $500 tax credits for caregivers to the elderly to defray the
costs of in-home care.
</P>
<P>
   -- 200 new investigators to monitor the quality of care in
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   -- $26.2 million to increase efforts to uncover fraud in
Medi-Cal, the state's health care program for the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
