<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8051 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GOV-SPEECH-2Takes-LAD     01-06 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-SPEECH-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS TOUTS EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRI HARDY  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis offered up an
unsurprisingly moderate plan for the year in his State of the State
address, focusing largely on solving commuters' traffic woes,
recruiting new teachers and offering incentives to high-achieving
students.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-minute speech before a joint session of the Legislature
on Wednesday night ruffled few feathers and brought no standing
ovations. At one point, the governor even had to tell the crowd to
applaud. But in true Davis style, he won mild praise afterward from
Democrats and Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where I sat, I'd say he hit one right up the middle into
center field,'' said Assemblyman Bob Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, the
speaker in waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles lawmakers were most enthusiastic about the
governor's proposal to pour an additional $3 billion into
transportation for a total of $7.5 billion for roads, highways,
mass transit and inter-city rail.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis said he is ``very intrigued'' by the idea of
high-speed rail that would travel the length of the state and
possibly put the fast-growing Antelope Valley on the map, he said
the state's priority must be eliminating traffic congestion in the
Los Angeles Basin and other congested areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, motorists on California's freeways spent more than
800,000 hours each day in traffic jams at a daily cost of nearly $8
million,'' Davis said. ``Our freeways are anything but free.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis criticized local transit agencies for much of those
traffic woes, saying ``billions of highway dollars are languishing
unspent'' in their coffers. The governor said his message to those
agencies was a simple ``use it or lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   If funds are not targeted by July 31, the state will take over
and ``reprogram'' $1.7 billion by the end of the year, Davis
warned.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, said Davis' laser-like
attention to solving traffic congestion was ``great news for Los
Angeles.'' He said he believes that progress will speed along on
the notorious 405-101 interchange, and that other traffic fixes
throughout the region would break ground and be completed this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg said he had been told that ``a lot of money'' remained
unspent in the Los Angeles region's coffers, and while he would not
give details, said he believed there would be legislative proposals
introduced on how to deal with the unspent funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for not spending the money the challenge is
to spend it in an intelligent way,'' Hertzberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing his emphasis on education, Davis spent most of his time
detailing his plans to funnel resources into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was issuing a call to arms for a ``war on mediocrity''
in public schools, Davis proposed a tantalizing package to recruit
new teachers. Among its features:
</P>
<P>
   _ New teachers who become credentialed would be eligible for a
$10,000 forgivable loan for a down payment on a new home and a
$2,000 cash bonus for the teacher and his or her school.
</P>
<P>
   _ A bonus of $30,000 for teachers who receive national board
certification.
</P>
<P>
   _ The establishment of five recruitment centers to hire the
300,000 teachers needed over the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Davis called his plan ``the largest and most rigorous
state-sponsored drive to train teachers ever initiated by any
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, said they
were ``great incentives to recruit the best and brightest to teach
in our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also wants to reward students who are high
achievers, and proposed offering merit scholarships of $1,000 to as
many as 100,000 students in grades nine, 10 and 11 each year. In
addition, those students who receive the highest possible score on
the Advanced Placement calculus examination and in an AP science
exam could earn $2,500 toward the college of their choice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &QL;
<P>
   Calling for more access to the more academically rigorous AP
courses, Davis said he would provide $20.5 million over two years
to ensure that at least four of those courses will be offered in
every high school in California.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's push in other policy areas was limited. His
health care proposals focused solely on the elderly and included a
$500 tax credit for families that provide care for elderly
citizens. He called for increasing the number of police and
sheriff's deputies on the street, but failed to say by how many,
while he proposed adding 100 more parole agents to deal with
high-risk parolees.
</P>
<P>
   The limited health care plan disappointed Assemblyman Martin
Gallegos, D-Industry, who has long pushed for HMO reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the 7 million uninsured Californians?'' Gallegos
said. ``Children who aren't healthy can't learn. Adults who aren't
healthy can't earn.''
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa, who has said he plans to push more gun control
bills this year, also said he wasn't deterred by Davis' statement
that laws passed last year needed ``time to work'' _ signaling that
the governor wouldn't support new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   More details on other proposals will be released in the
governor's budget Monday, with Davis promising initiatives in
higher education, environmental protection and additional tax
relief.
</P>
<P>
   With a projected $2.6 billion surplus, Republicans have been
clamoring for tax cuts that would further reduce car fees and
increase dependent deductions.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Assembly Minority Leader Scott Baugh, R-Huntington
Beach, said he wanted more tax relief than Davis had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Jim Brulte, R-Rancho Cucamonga, who leads the
Republican caucus, said Davis had included ``at least seven of our
proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see the details, but there is very little I could
find to disagree with,'' Brulte said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
