r f BC-GM-STUDIO-LADN     01-06 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STUDIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM SHIFTS GEARS, PICKS NOHO SITE FOR CAR DESIGNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Gregory Wilcox  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Paying homage to the San Fernando Valley's rich
car culture, General Motors Corp. has announced that it is
retooling a former bakery in North Hollywood, 10 miles north of
downtown Los Angeles, into a design studio, where it will cook up
Southern California-flavored cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The new campus-style complex in the 5300 block of Biloxi Street,
initially planned to house about 30 designers, is in a corner of
the Valley where cult cars like the ``Batmobile,'' the ``Munster
Koach'' and the Clampett family's jalopy materialized at famed
designer George Barris' shop on Riverside Drive.
</P>
<P>
   It is also purposefully situated in the middle of
``Valleywood,'' the East Valley neighborhoods that provide a lot of
the sizzle to Hollywood's movies, television shows and online
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   GM's studio at the former Oroweat bread plant is the latest in
what has become a Southern California cottage industry. More than a
dozen car makers have studios in the region -- when a new model
flies off a showroom floor anywhere in the world, there is a good
chance its lineage can be traced back to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   It's a homecoming of sorts for the giant international car and
truck manufacturer. GM operated an assembly plant in Van Nuys for
45 years, producing Camaros and employing 2,600 workers at the time
of its shuttering in 1992. For 12 years GM also operated a design
studio in Newbury Park, until it closed the facility in 1996 as
part of a consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be (here) both because of the infrastructure
that's set up around the design teams ... as well as the
electronics industry and the entertainment industry. We wanted to
be tied into all of those things,'' said Wayne Cherry, GM's vice
president of global design.
</P>
<P>
   GM's new studio will be run by Oak Park resident Frank Saucedo,
currently the chief designer at VW America's studio in Simi Valley.
Saucedo is a 1984 graduate of the Art Center School of Design in
Pasadena and worked on the Batmobile used in the movie ``Batman
Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   His credits include a concept for the Chevrolet Corvette now in
production, the car company said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Los Angeles Mayor Rocky Delgadillo said as many as 55
designers could work at the studio and, while they will hold
high-paying jobs, the city is more excited about what GM's decision
says about the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real significance is not the jobs but the commitment of a
world-class manufacturer to put its design genius in the City of
Angels,'' Delgadillo said. ``The message is a very positive one. GM
has validated the fact that Los Angeles is a design capital and the
creative talent is here in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   GM officials agreed. The competition for designers is tough,
they said, and the best ones live in the greater Los Angeles area
and don't want to move to the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talent base aside, finding the right property was
the ultimate deal maker. GM found a complex it just had to have,
which in typical Hollywood fashion required some wheeling and
dealing.
</P>
<P>
   The 55,000-square-foot site is on a dead-end street with
railroad tracks forming the north boundary and an old, quiet
residential neighborhood to the south. The property consists of a
row of former bread-truck garages converted to offices, a two-story
red brick office and the mill. The facility is fenced and
well-shielded from prying eyes, a critical factor because of GM's
super-secret work that will be done inside.
</P>
<P>
   But a design center needs a sense of style, too, and the complex
met that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a building with some character and persona,'' said
Cherry. ``It's got some charm and some personality. It's not just a
clean building with a nice lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rombo bought the site about 18 months ago for his Sports
Tutor Inc., a company that makes automatic ball machines for a
variety of sports, including volleyball, baseball, soccer and
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Rombo said a confidentiality agreement prevented him from
discussing the lease terms, brokered in part by Mayor Richard J.
Riordan's L.A. Business Team.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Team was helping Rombo market a portion of the site
as the NoHo Media Center, focusing on multimedia companies.
Initially, GM agreed to take a portion of the facility, but then
company officials decided they wanted the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was a great offer because now Sports Tutor has to
relocate,'' said Alex Rosas, a business representative in Riordan's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Rosas said he is helping Rombo look for a new site and hopes to
have one in the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rombo, meanwhile, is as determined as a car designer to stay in
the region. He just has no clue where his company will go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to tell you if I knew. I was born and raised in North
Hollywood, and we are committed to keeping our business in the
area. We're not going to move to Omaha or anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM's North Hollywood operation will have an international flair
and work closely with company design centers in Michigan, Brazil,
Australia, Germany, Sweden and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a global facility. It's available to our other
design departments around the world. With the amount of space we've
got, we will be able to vary the size and number of projects we've
got running,'' Cherry said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles and the Valley have a habit of setting trends that
envelope the nation. If a car or truck is snazzy enough to get a
style-conscious Angeleno to buy it, there is a good probability
that same vehicle will end up cruising Main Streets across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hossack, vice president and senior consultant at AutoPacific
Inc. in Tustin, said GM is finally going where the action is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern California has a heritage of being rather more
avant-garde than the rest of the nation. If you are working on
future products it is probably not best to be doing them in Ohio,
Indiana or Mississippi,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The products that come out of North Hollywood could help
jump-start GM's sales. The company has about a 20 percent share of
the California market and early last year acknowledged it had only
a 13 percent share of the rich Valley market.
</P>
<P>
   GM's product line needs some pepping up to compete here, Hossack
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Motors' products are often not expressive, not
interesting and not exciting. They are very middle of the road,
adequate but not great. Californians are oftentimes trying to make
a statement with their cars, and they don't want to make a Caspar
Milquetoast kind of statement,'' he said. ``GM products are very
much a product of the Midwest and they are at their best in the
Midwest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
