<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-LEBANON-LINK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN WAR IN CHECHNYA ECHOES IN LEBANON  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ The Russian attack on Chechnya stretched all the way to
Lebanon Monday when at least two gunmen attacked Moscow's embassy
in Beirut with rocket-propelled grenades, claiming to be
``sacrificing'' themselves for the besieged Muslims of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   After a gun battle lasting almost three hours, in which a gunman
and a Lebanese policemen were killed, it emerged that one of the
attackers was a Palestinian from the refugee camp at Ein el-Helwe
outside Sidon _ the location of one of the largest Palestinian
Islamic groups in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But it quickly became evident that the Chechen war lay at the
heart of the far more serious battles going on in northern Lebanon
between Muslim guerrillas and Lebanese troops in which four more
Lebanese soldiers were killed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict east of the city of Tripoli has been going on since
New Year's Eve after Lebanese soldiers _ seeking bombers who had
attacked at least two Orthodox churches in Tripoli _ demanded that
two men linked to the attacks hand themselves over to the security
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, dozens of guerrillas were still holding out in
caves above the village of Sir ed-Dniyeh where they were under
attack from Lebanese helicopter gunships.
</P>
<P>
   The assault on the heavily-guarded Russian embassy began in a
blast of grenade fire just after 11:30 Monday morning in Corniche
Mazraa, the wide boulevard which bisects the western half of
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers who had not heard such intense gunfire since the end of
the 16-year civil war in 1990 ran in panic into nearby buildings
while motorists careered off the boulevard in terror.
</P>
<P>
   Troops from the local government police barracks _ scarcely 60
meters (200 feet) from the embassy's visa department _ poured into
the boulevard as the gunmen continued firing at the compound, a
bleak square of offices and accommodation blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Before he died, the Palestinian _ later identified as Ahmad Raja
Abu-Kharroub _ ran with his grenade launcher into the Ejjeh
building which houses a shoe store and the local branch of the
British Bank of the Middle East, apparently seeking a position on
the roof to continue firing at the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   But when he reached the fourth floor, he pleaded with a young
woman to use her telephone. Telling her that he was ``sacrificing
himself for Chechnya'' _ the woman was much moved by the incident
and later broke down in tears as she gave her account _ the
Palestinian dialed his home in Sidon to say goodbye to his children
before he died. He was shot a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Lebanese security forces who bore the brunt of
the casualties Monday. One of their policemen was killed at the
embassy and four soldiers were shot dead in battles in the north of
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   An army officer taken hostage three days ago was also found
murdered near the village of Sir ed-Dniyeh, bringing to nine the
total number of Lebanese troops killed in the past week of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Lebanon has been the home of various strict Sunni
Muslim sects for almost three decades. Followers of the Naqshbandi
faith had gathered there in the late autumn, predicting a collapse
of civilization at the dawn of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   More important was the Tawhid Sunni militia which ruled much of
the area during the war. It was widely blamed for the kidnapping
and murder of Arkady Katkov, a Russian embassy diplomat, in
October, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The Tawhid were at the time trying to force Moscow to persuade
the Syrian army to call off its siege of Tripoli. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
