<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 04:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8069 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      01-06 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BANG, BANG, BANG FOR
 YER BUCK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  (PHOENIX) - Like most newspaper
writers, I'm reluctant to praise my own publication in print. It's
a little uncomfortable trying to type with one hand and pat
yourself on the back with the other. Still, there are times when
the paper you work for acts with the kind of institutional courage,
social conscience and public integrity that simply cannot be ig
nored.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thankfully, this is not one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the following notice did not appear in The
Arizona Republic. Instead, it was printed on the front page of the
Arizona Daily Star in Tucson and read, in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time, it has concerned us at the Arizona Daily Star
that people who buy guns from individuals selling them through our
classified ads circumvent the requirement for background checks. In
an age of increasing gun violence, it is difficult to defend our
part in the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, the Arizona Daily Star will no longer allow
individuals to sell firearms through our classified ads. . . . We
will still run ads from dealers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's signed ``Jane Amari, editor and publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   I talked Wednesday, Jan. 5, with Jim Rowley, an executive at the
Star whose job it's been to deal with public reaction to the
company's decision. The Tucson Citizen, which shares advertising
departments with the Star, adopted the same policy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Rowley said calls are running 3-1 against the decision
to limit gun advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've actually been pleased by the amount of positive response
we're received,'' he said. ``You expect to get some negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even a lot of negative, since the right thing often
generates the wrong response.
</P>
<P>
   In grade school, the nuns used to tell us, ``If doing the right
thing were easy, everyone would be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   And everyone isn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic issued a press release Tuesday, Jan. 4, saying,
``It is legal for individuals to buy and sell firearms in the state
of Arizona; therefore, we accept advertising for those products. As
advocates of the First Amendment, we respect people's right to
advertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, respecting people's right to advertise doesn't mean
the news paper will let them advertise any thing. Certain types of
perfectly legal X-rated entertainment don't get space in The
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   And, while we may be advocates of the First Amendment, the
company doesn't allow profanity-laced de scriptions or quotations
to appear in print, placing a terrible burden on any writer trying
to produce an honest story about politics.
</P>
<P>
   In Tucson, the Star and Citizen expect to lose about $20,000 a
year in advertising revenue based on the new policy. Ads from
registered dealers still will be accepted, and should be.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Amari admitted in her state ment that the policy ``will
not stop the unsupervised sale of guns in Tucson, unfortunately.
But we hope it will help.''
</P>
<P>
   And it will.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, when the Seattle Times decided to phase out
tobacco advertising _ taking a $150,000 to $200,000 hit _ the
company said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Times is extremely reluctant to deny access to legal
commercial information. However, as a thought ful newspaper, we
must make ethical decisions about our content.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that simple. A publication as sensitive as this one is to
four-letter words and triple-X pictures must see the obscenity of
this advertised offering from Wednesday's paper:
</P>
<P>
   ``PRE BAN Polytech AK-47, with bayonet, 223 cal., matching
serial numbers, $850 firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Call (623) . . . Reach the reporter at
ed.montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or at (602) 444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 0417EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
