<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 04:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CANDIDATE-AZR &LR;      01-06 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CHIDES MCCAIN OVER BIG-MONEY DO NORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 bycredit Republic Washington Bureau 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (WASHINGTON) _ John McCain depicts himself as a reformer of
Washington's big-money culture, but a watchdog group concluded that
he has been a consistent booster for the ``well-heeled interests''
that bankroll his campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Integrity, challenging McCain's
presidential-campaign image, said he has gone to bat numerous times
over his political career for his largest campaign donors,
including some Arizona corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sometimes hard to tell on which side of `the special
interests' McCain actually stands,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The center conducted an 18-month investigation of all the major
presidential candidates and called the result The Buying of the
President 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The center didn't say whether it considered the Arizona senator
to be any better or worse than the rest of the field when it comes
to having cozy relationships with campaign benefactors. &QL; 
BUSH ASSAILED, TOO &QL; 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, McCain's rival and the front-runner for
the Republican nomination, also was treated critically in the
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout his long business career and in his six years as
governor of Texas, Bush has relied on family connections,
sweetheart deals and the inside track to build a fortune,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Bush, both in private life and since he became governor of
Texas, has always been willing to return the favors.''
</P>
<P>
   But the report could be more damaging to McCain, if only because
his campaign platform rests largely on ending what he has called
Washington's ``big-money-driven status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking Washington's iron triangle of money, lobbying and
special interests is the mission of this campaign,'' McCain said in
a recent speech in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was already facing questions Wednesday, Jan. 5, on
whether he had prodded the Federal Communications Commission on
behalf of a financial backer who wanted a decision on a TV license
request.
</P>
<P>
   While the campaign denied any wrongdoing, the questions
themselves recalled the time in 1981 when McCain was rebuked by a
Senate ethics panel for intervening with federal regulators on
behalf of Charles H Keating Jr., the Phoenix financier who had
contributed a total of $120,000 to various McCain political
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's, Jan. 5, report listed McCain's biggest ``patrons''
over his congressional career, which began in 1982. Topping the
list was US West and its predecessor, Mountain Bell, which, along
with its employees, have collectively given $107,520 to his
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lewis, the center's executive director, cautioned
against trying to find in the data ``an elusive quid pro quo'' _
that is, a favor done by a lawmaker specifically in return for a
campaign donation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that simple, Lewis said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that a more intelligent, sophisticated and reasonable
way to look at money in politics is to look at the relationships,''
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are mutually beneficial relationships. It's not one
dollar, one vote. We're not saying, `This happened today, and that
happened the next day, and it's direct.' We're saying that these
folks are pals. They've been helping each other for years,'' he
said. &QL; 
PUBLISHED REPORTS &QL; 
The examples in the report were based on original research and
reporting a well as previously published reports from newspapers,
including The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The report said McCain helped a lobbyist for Del Webb Corp., a
major Phoenix-based campaign contributor, with a Las Vegas Valley
land swap it was seeking with the federal government in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyist, Donald Moon, turned to McCain to block a bill that
would have scotched the land swap, according to the report. Under
the bill, the land Del Webb wanted would have instead become part
of the Red Rock National Conservation Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Moon) knew McCain would help, for over the years, Del Webb
had helped McCain. And help McCain did. He placed a `hold' on the
legislation (through a letter of notification to Senate Majority
Leader Bob Dole), thus stalling it indefinitely,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Higginson, Del Webb's vice president of government
affairs, said Wednesday, Jan. 5, that the corporation needed help
because the land it coveted had suddenly become part of another
bill _ the conservation protection measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Higginson said it is not clear that McCain was the
corporation's champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any senator can place a hold on any piece of legislation and
not have to disclose it. It's clear somebody put a hold on the
legislation. Whether somebody said, `Yes, it was John McCain,' or
`No, it wasn't,' I have no idea,'' Higginson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Higginson said there should be no taint even if McCain
helped a corporation such as Del Webb that happened to donate to
his campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company feels like they're being treated incorrectly by
the federal government, who else should they turn to but their
federally elected representative?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign did not return calls or faxes seeking
comment on Del Webb or other issues raised in the report.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Del Webb lost its battle to obtain the Nevada land
parcel. But it later managed to trade with the federal government
for another, 5,000-acre Nevada site it is developing. &QL; 
HELPED OTHER BACKERS &QL; 
The report said there were other examples of McCain aiding campaign
backers. It said he:
</P>
<P>
   Introduced the ``Internet Regulatory Freedom Act'' last year
that would boost the efforts of US West, his largest campaign
donor, to offer high-speed Internet service over long-distance
phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an expert on the future of the Internet and what's
good and what's bad,'' Lewis said in an interview. ``I do know that
US West stands to make millions and millions of dollars from this
decision, and a lot of the press that tracks very closely
Internet-type things saw it as a boon to the `baby bells,'
including US West.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidestepped a controversy over television commercials for
alcoholic beverages, raising questions because his wife's family
owns a beer distributorship and the company is one of his largest
campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
   The report says a subcommittee of the Senate Commerce Committee,
which McCain chairs, postponed and then canceled hearings in
February 1997. The beer industry ``got its wish,'' according to the
report, because it had been trying to avoid a public airing of
whether any possible restrictions on hard liquor commercials would
include beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 18 years he has been in Congress, McCain has rarely
taken a stand against the beer industry's interests,'' the book
says.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Buse, a top McCain aide on commerce issues, said McCain
didn't involve himself in matters pertaining to the beer industry.
He also said McCain wouldn't have involved himself in whether a
subcommittee chairman held a hearing or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never votes on anything that affects them (the industry).
He recuses himself,'' Buse said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
