<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV09-C     01-06 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HOW SAFE IS YOUR TELECOMMUTE?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 9.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The recent flap over making firms responsible for
the safety and health of their at-home workers spotlights how
muddled the so-called ``work and family'' issues have become at the
turn of the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Labor Department withdrew its directive, Republicans
sought to zing the administration as an officious nanny. ``This is
an outrageous extension of the Washington bureaucracy into the
lives of working men and women across America,'' said House
Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Big Labor saw the advisory from Labor's Occupational Safety and
Health Administration as a logical extension of workers' rights,
translating the tenets of the child labor laws to Information Age
needs.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA never said whether somebody who works at home and is
injured on the job should be entitled to regular workman's
compensation benefits. But that was implied in the initial ruling,
argued Peg Seminario, the AFL-CIO's safety and health director.
</P>
<P>
   Top corporate managers summoned their lobbyists and their
lawyers to gauge how the policy landscape had shifted.
</P>
<P>
   Had the rule stood, some companies were already thinking of
pulling the plug on their at-home workers, citing the need to
minimize risk. If such moves took wide hold, they could reverse, at
least for a while, the growing ranks of telecommuting employees,
now more than 20 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate bean counternize that letting the hired help
work at home saves them money. Assuming assigned tasks get done,
you need fewer water coolers at which office personnel assemble to
sip and gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Texas-based credit services firm that sought the
official advice had in mind placing a large part of its sales force
into home offices, not to lessen job stress but to fatten profits.
</P>
<P>
   Absent wars abroad or a sag in the economy, such job-stress
issues will play a major role in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Because telecommuting is easy on the environment and tends to
lessen the strain between home and career, politicians of all
stripes are for it. That's why, I've been told, President Clinton
called Labor Secretary Alexis Herman to strongly suggest she
rescind the directive.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Vice President Al Gore says: ``Now if you don't
understand the fatigue of the American working woman, then you do
not deserve to be president of the United States, because working
women are frequently exhausted in our country and we need to
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore favors universal pre-kindergarten and a multibillion-dollar
expansion of federal funding for child care, including tax credits
for businesses and families.
</P>
<P>
   But as a high-tech maven, Gore also knows that computers, cell
phones, fax machines and faster communications links can remove the
physical barriers that once required workers to be in their offices
at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming it can be done safely and sensibly, the simple act of
moving work to the workers, rather than the workers to the work,
could do more to ease the problems of working families than any
fresh set of taxpayer-funded government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
