<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     01-06 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Get your bets down on Coke bottles
 &HT;    (For release Jan. 9, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my new millennium resolutions is to share with you the
really important happenings that often are placed on a sidetrack by
disasters, wars, protests and scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Likely it slipped past a lot of editors last week that
Coca-Cola, a k a Coke, is coming out with a new bottle, one whose
labeling and green glass more closely resemble what was in use
before the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that might not be enough to get excited about, but there's
more. Coke also announced that the bottoms of the new bottles would
carry the names of 12 U.S. cities. This is a token return to what
once was, when Coke's embossed city-named bottoms were the source
of playful workplace gambling, much as is the football pool today.
</P>
<P>
   Embossing Coke bottle bottoms with countless city names began as
early as 1915. They represented the plant where that Coke was
bottled. As you can imagine, some Coke bottles traveled. Bottles of
Coke produced in, say, Chattanooga, found their way to, say,
Roswell, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Someone eventually came up with an idea of how to have fun
buying Coke. Gather some of the office staff around the Coke
machine, or at a gas station, put your nickel in _ yes, a nickel! _
and see who gets a Coke bottle filled at the furthest point.
</P>
<P>
   The winner got the money from the ``Furthest Away'' pool.
</P>
<P>
   As unbeatable as Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak was the
bottle from Nome, Alaska, which popped out of a vending machine in
our Miami News newsroom in the early 1950s. You just couldn't be
further from Miami; it was unbeatable. (I wasn't the one who got
it.)
</P>
<P>
   Today's Coke people are limiting the city names to those who
have a special connection to the drink; just 12. But that ought to
be enough to get the office staff started off.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, heavens! Did I just suggest gambling? Well, no. I'd rather
call it an adjunct to legalized lotteries, or governors betting
cases of their state's fruit or produce with other governors, all
over a football bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier Miami, we just kept looking for ways to gamble with
the Coke machine. When there were lesser crowds in our ``Furthest
Away'' game, we'd resort to putting the nickel into the machine,
hitting the coin return button and betting on whether or not the
coin came back heads or tails.
</P>
<P>
   That Coke is changing its 8-ounce bottles probably is the
biggest modification since the appalling decision in 1985 to alter
the formula of the drink. So upset was the public with the new
(inferior) taste, that within three months, it pressured the
Coca-Cola Co. into restoring the old formula under the name of
Classic Coke.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 alteration should bring nothing but joy to petty
gamblers. Right now my eyes are searching for Cokeville, Wyo., one
of the 12 cities named. It's not Nome but best I can tell, it's
going to be the ``Furthest Away'' from any Coke machines I might
find in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With Coke returning to one of its old patterns, I wonder if the
people at Dr Pepper might think of returning to its 1927-originated
``10, 2 and 4'' identification that appeared on bottles for a
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr Pepper afficionados, the numbers represented the
times of day you needed perking up; and the caffeine in Dr Pepper
was there to offer the boost.
</P>
<P>
   As a Dr Pepper drinker (with salted peanuts poured into the neck
of the bottle for flavor and fizz) the caffeine certainly kept me
alert, alert enough to go over and play the Coke machine games.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
