<HEADER>
A8154 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN07-COX     01-06 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A visit to one of the prettiest spots in Texas
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In wildness is the preservation of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry David Thoreau
</P>
<P>
   HAMILTON POOL, TRAVIS COUNTY, Texas _ Last time I was here, 21
years ago, a group of bikers watched as on a dare I jumped off a
45-foot cliff into the deep waters of this natural pool. It was a
dumb stunt that cost me a few weeks of serious pain when the force
of the water wrenched my arm out of its socket. I drove back home
to Nacogdoches the next day with my arm wrapped tight against my
body, shifting my Volkswagen bus with my left hand and steering at
the same time with my knees. Somewhere there's a color slide my
brother shot, who watched aghast as I took the plunge, my short
body outlined against the rock, bushy hair sticking straight up.
Lord, it's a miracle I survived the follies of my youth.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Hamilton Pool was a popular hangout, a collapsed cave
on ranch land about 30 miles west of Austin, the scene of many
parties _ hippies and rednecks swimming in the cold green water,
the area trashy and trampled from overuse and no management.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's one of the prettiest spots in Texas, since Travis
County bought it in 1985 and turned it and the surrounding 200-plus
acres into a preserve. Even in this drought, the vegetation is
lush, rocks below the stream of water falling from the cliffs
covered with moss and delicate plants, cypress trees now losing
their leaves, covering the creek with brown pods, tiny purple
flowers blooming. I can't do justice to this place with words, and
I didn't bother to bring a camera, figuring that would just reduce
what I saw to an overexposed postcard that also wouldn't capture
Hamilton Pool's beauty. Go there and see it for yourself is my best
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Humans have enjoyed the pool for more than 8,000 years,
according to the brochure I picked up. Tonkawa and Lipan Apaches
lived near the pool until run off by white settlers. Morgan C.
Hamilton bought the property in the mid-1860s, and his brother,
Gov. Andrew Jake Hamilton, apparently enjoyed escaping to the
grotto from the rigors of running Texas. For more than 100 years,
the Reimer family owned the land and kept sheep and cattle on it.
The pool was rediscovered and opened to the public. The combination
of people, sheep and cattle was hard on the land. Gone were the
natural prairies the Apaches had enjoyed. Hamilton Pool when I
first visited was interesting, and the water was still cool and
green, but the place had obviously suffered the worse for wear over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the land is making an impressive comeback, its use
rigorously controlled, visitors confined to winding trails, the
cliff closed off to keep fools like me from jumping off. Past the
pool, one can follow a trail along Hamilton Creek for nearly a
mile, where stands of live oaks and junipers mingle with grassland,
all the way down to the Pedernales River, low this fall with little
rain, sandbars popping up across its width.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin board at the preserve's entrance explains the
history of this place and describes the critters who call it home,
including an impressive array of snakes that thankfully chose to
lay low during my visit. Some type of bird has built mud nests on
the roof of the overhanging cliff. Deer, rabbits, beaver, porcupine
and even mountain lions call this place home, according to what I
read.
</P>
<P>
   On this autumn Sunday morning, I have the place nearly to
myself, though I suspect in the summer the swimming hole is still
quite popular. I spend a time staring up at the cliff, wondering
why I was dumb enough to jump off just because some biker said I
didn't have the guts to do so, and grateful it all turned out OK.
</P>
<P>
   But that's in the past. Mainly what I feel is gratitude that
some folks had the vision and courage to save and restore a place
to which I hope to bring my grandkids someday, to show them a small
part of Texas that looks the way it did hundreds of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many places left like Hamilton Pool. I can't think
of a wiser use of public money than to preserve spots like this for
future generations.
</P>
<P>
   (Hamilton Pool is located about 30 miles west of Austin off U.S.
Hwy. 71. Look for the turnoff just past Bee Cave, and the pool is
about 13 miles down a paved farm road. Call 512-264-2740 for
information.)
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
