<HEADLINE>
`FARSCAPE' AND THE SHAPE OF THINGS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Wayne Pygram
as Scorpius in a scene from ``Farscape.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The end is near ... for now.
 &HT;    ``Farscape,'' the Sci-Fi Channel's top-rated series, concludes
its stellar first season on Jan. 28 with ``Family Ties.'' The last
installment in a breathless four-episode arc, ``Family Ties'' must
tide fans over until the show returns with fresh episodes in March.
 &HT;    ``In the first two parts we discovered a Peacekeeper base in the
uncharted territory where Moya has been hiding out from the
Peacekeepers,'' says Rockne S. O'Bannon, ``Farscape's''
creator/writer/executive producer. ``In `Family Ties,' the threat
of this newly established Peacekeeper presence and Scorpius (Wayne
Pygram) in particular bring to bear so much pressure on our people
that there's really only one way to escape, and a couple of our
people have to be prepared to make the ultimate sacrifice.
 &HT;    ``We go off on a season-ending climax that's not so much one
cliffhanger as it is three,'' he adds. ``Everybody involved with
the show is really excited by the finale.''
 &HT;    For those not deeply into ``Farscape,'' it revolves around John
Crichton (Ben Browder), an American astronaut wheen
inadvertently tossed across space and finds himself caught up in a
brutal war. Crichton lives aboard the sentient ship Moya, which is
on the run from the unsavory Peacekeepers, and he reluctantly joins
forces with Moya's ragtag crew, among them Aeryn (Claudia Black),
an ex-Peacekeeper, and D'Argo (Anthony Simcoe), a Luxan warrior.
Then there's Zhaan (Virginia Hey), a Delvian priestess, and Rygel
(John Eccleston/Jonathan Hardy), a 26-inch-tall, exiled royal, not
to mention Chiana (Gigi Edgley), a Nebari.
 &HT;    The show benefits greatly from the combined talents of the genre
vets behind it. O'Bannon wrote, created and/or produced the updated
``Twilight Zone,'' ``SeaQuest DSV'' and the television version of
``Alien Nation,'' itself based on the 1988 film of the same name,
which he scripted. Then there's Brian Henson, a co-executive
producer and occasional director, and The Jim Henson Creature Shop,
which fashions ``Farscape's'' amazing menagerie of aliens.
 &HT;    ``I'm very proud of `Farscape,''' O'Bannon says by telephone
from his office _ which is in Studio City, Calif., though the show
actually films in Australia. ``It's got humor, and there's a
richness to the characters.
 &HT;    ``There's a wonderful expansive and expanding world that the
series can present for years to come,'' he says. ``We all just want
them to know that it's out there.
 &HT;    ``We've gotten really terrific reviews,'' O'Bannon adds
cheerfully. ``Everyone who watches it seems to latch onto it and
enjoy what they see. We just want people to realize that there's
something interesting out there that may not be in their
consciousness or part of their weekly television habit ... yet.''
 &HT;    Now that ``Farscape'' is off and running, O'Bannon will
relinquish most of his day-to-day responsibilities for the show, in
order to write and direct other television projects. He'll thus
assume executive-consultant status and continue to pen scripts for
``Farscape,'' but David Kemper, O'Bannon's right-hand man during
season one, will run the show.
 &HT;    So what's on tap for season two?
 &HT;    ``One of the things we so desperately wanted to do with the
series was not to allow the characters to become a homogenized,
loving family unit too quickly,'' O'Bannon says. ``Often there will
be a series pilot and it will be real gutsy, with lots of angst and
grit there, and then everybody's getting along by episode three.
Andy Sipowicz is suddenly a sweetheart.
 &HT;    ``I'm proud of the fact that, through our first season, we kept
the notion that these characters are escaping prisoners desperately
on the run from different species and civilizations, and that
they're thrown together and have to work together (out of
necessity) and not _ especially initially _ out of any affection
for each other,'' he says. ``As we get to the end of the first
season, that affection is beginning to grow.
 &HT;    ``Now that we've begun production on season two,'' O'Bannon
concludes, ``we've thrown a pretty big stick of dynamite into that
_ which I can't tell you about _ so that we don't let them become a
family, so to speak.
 &HT;    ``We don't want them to get into a situation where it's one for
all and all for one.'' 
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Introducing the cast of ``The Others.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
