r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX     01-06 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electronic buzz can't ever make us feel as one
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It was OO in the a.m., dawn of the new and
daunting digits. Despite all fears (and some hopes) that we'd all
get stranded in time, the techno-turnstile turned.
</P>
<P>
   Don't know what your sense was that clear morning after, whew, a
night of global palpitation not seen since ``Dr. Strangelove.'' My
sense was to take the morning newspaper and cradle it.
</P>
<P>
   Strange reaction, even for a newspaper man. Isn't this a new
era, a faster-than-instant information era? What's to be known by
picking up that which starts yellowing with the first sun? Weren't
we all watching all the news happen the night before?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange to say, but never has the electronic media had such
an opportunity to show its might and failed so flabbily.
</P>
<P>
   I needed the morning paper, Jan. 1, 00, to remind me that the
Y2K passage wasn't the only major story of Dec. 31, '99. Russian
president Boris Yeltsin resigned. The Indian Airlines hostages were
free.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the hostages? For three, four, five, six news cycles
they spoiled there on a dusty runway, our top story tonight.
Suddenly, they're released. The captors scoot. And ... Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin? Well, he's out. So what? Let the New York Times ponder
it.
</P>
<P>
   What was news that night? That something might happen. Or not.
All night. Something might happen. We're not sure. But we're
prepared. Over here they're prepared. Over there they're prepared.
We're prepared.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening over there? Nothing yet. Over here? Nothing so
far, but we're prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world we went. Prepared here. Prepared there.
Anything happen there? Nope. How about there? If anything happened,
we'd know that instant. As things turned out, the Y2K watch
illustrated the defining irony of the information age: the
condition of knowing everything and nothing at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   This was a night in which if an ATM in Kyoto had coughed, it
would have caused gasps in Omaha. If the world's brain is hooked up
as one by computers, we were watching a gigantic MRI scan.
</P>
<P>
   In one dimension, one could feel globally connected, monitoring
the world's cyber signs time zone after time zone.
</P>
<P>
   But in another way, the end (no, not The End) result was exactly
what the electronic age has wrought _ instant information, not
necessarily worthy information, just the latest, with more to come.
</P>
<P>
   The instant Yeltsin resigned he was old news. The hostages?
Well, they aren't anymore. All right?
</P>
<P>
   More pertinently, while we waited for a Y2K rash to break out
(later to rejoice at the sight of our own flesh), what was
happening down the block? In our neighborhoods? In our streets?
</P>
<P>
   Sometime New Year's Eve a fire broke out in Mount Carmel Baptist
Church in North Waco. Fortunately, someone not trained on distance
digital impulses noticed flames leaping through the roof. The
sanctuary was demolished, but the church's education building _
where services went on the next morning _ was saved.
</P>
<P>
   The insidiousness of our age is that though we are so
electronically connected, so all-knowing, most of us will admit
that if a house _ or a chapel _ were aflame across the street, we
might not know until we heard sirens.
</P>
<P>
   You see, we have all this global information. We have two
problems with all of it.
</P>
<P>
   That which fixates us from afar, like O.J. dismounting from his
Bronco, doesn't really affect us.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, that which might be pertinent from afar is but a
flash point _ instant news, no time to contemplate, only time to
react. In the process we become what we see on TV, people who
react, like rivals on ``Crossfire'' or ``Politically Incorrect,''
or like a guest getting ambushed on ``Jenny Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   And in each case we'll react like we know it all.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
