<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 places that have changed my life
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Places can be mighty powerful, for me
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Geographical spots at various latitudes and longitudes have
affected me like no book, movie or secondhand account could _
especially those places that are far, far away from my own tiny
comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just a little psychic alteration. Maybe I've gotten
an insight into humankind or maybe just a laugh that I could
remember later and laugh again.
</P>
<P>
   Some places I've visited in the past had the power to change my
present. I'll be driving down the interstate here at home, harried
and irked about something, and I'll think of a place, and, for an
instant, I'll be transported, changed in the here and now because
of the memory of another road.
</P>
<P>
   Of backing down a highway at 60 mph in Zimbabwe because an
elephant was running down the middle white line toward me _ his
ears flapping, trunk swinging, a big grin on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, while wishing I had a new car and a membership in a
great gym, I'll think of the Vietnamese boat people packed on an
old junk in Hong Kong or the children in Soweto, South Africa, and
I'll wish they had what I have. Seeing other places sometimes keeps
your priorities in check.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 places that changed me a little and a lot. They are
my suggestions for you, places to consider before the end of this
new century, places that probably weren't on your list. Places that
will keep you up all night, thinking and dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   LANTAU, CHINA: Lantau is for laughs _ the laughing Buddha,
giggling monks, beer in Bugs Bunny cups.
</P>
<P>
   DARWIN, AUSTRALIA: What can an American woman learn from a
kangaroo?
</P>
<P>
   SOWETO, SOUTH AFRICA: ``Where are you going, white people?''
Zulu children ask. An elderly man says, ``We want you to see how
we've survived while you were living comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA FALLS, ZIMBABWE: The traditional name of the falls is
Mosi-oa-Tunya, ``Smoke that thunders.'' There are no guard rails in
places, and people stand on slippery stones in the river.
</P>
<P>
   AMBOSELI, KENYA: In the shadow of Mount Kilimanjaro, an elephant
trudges home at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   ST. CATHERINE'S, EGYPT: The profound silence at this monastery
is broken only by the occasional howl of a jackal.
</P>
<P>
   A CLIPPER IN THE CARIBBEAN: Sleeping on deck is sweet _ until a
squall hits.
</P>
<P>
   PETRA, JORDAN: The grand Nabatean ``Rose Red City'' reveals
itself to the hardy visitor _ you have to hike a mile-long fissure
between mountains to get there.
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM, ISRAEL: A bride goes to pray at the Western Wall.
Prayers are placed in crevices in the stone.
</P>
<P>
   ROVANIEMI, FINLAND: Sleigh ride, anyone? Above the Arctic
Circle, reindeers pull their weight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
