A8161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MENCKEN07-COX     01-06 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MENCKEN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collected works of Mencken - Mrs., that is
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sara Haardt is best-known, when she is
remembered at all, as the wife of H.L. Mencken. The two met when
Mencken began publishing Haardt in the pages of the American
Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his taste for actresses and ``sporting girls,'' Mencken
chose Haardt, perhaps because he learned of her fatal illness _
Haardt died of tuberculosis in 1935, at the age of 37.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from her qualities as an individual, which must have
been remarkable to attract a man like Mencken, she was also a
prolific writer, specializing in stories and memoirs of her life in
the South. The University of Alabama has issued ``Southern
Souvenirs,'' ($14.95) a collection of Haardt's work, and it reveals
her to have been something of a precursor of Eudora Welty _
discerning, tactful, courageous.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her writing is very much of the period, suitable for
such publications as Woman's Home Companion, etc. _ but some shows
real talent, and even more promise.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the reissue front, Da Capo has reissued Hoagy
Carmichael's two autobiographies in one volume. ``The Stardust
Road'' and ``Sometimes I Wonder'' ($17.95) were published in 1946
and 1965 respectively, and when I mention that Carmichael's songs
include ``Stardust,'' ``Georgia on My Mind,'' ``Two Sleepy
People,'' ``Heart and Soul,'' ``I Get Along Without You Very Well''
and ``Skylark,'' you'll know that Carmichael was one of the best
musical minds of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most composers, he was also a delightful performer and a
successful actor in such movies as ``The Best Years of Our Lives''
and ``Young Man with a Horn.''
</P>
<P>
   ACROSS THE ATLANTIC ...
</P>
<P>
   Emma Tennant, one of the younger talented English novelists, has
pulled a Joyce Maynard and written a memoir (``Burnt Diaries'')
about her affair with an eminent older writer. In this case, it was
Ted Hughes, the late poet laureate of England. It seems that
Hughes, who was considerably older than Tennant, never lost his
taste for the fair sex; at the same time that he was having it off
with Tennant, he was also involved with a ``bouncy'' Australian
girl.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Plath would have shaken her head knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Editing is the same thing as quarrelling with writers _ same
thing exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Harold Ross
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
