<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-VARIANFRY07-COX     01-06 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-VARIANFRY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Varian Fry's fight for the desperate chronicled in `Quiet
American'
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Varian Fry had one great and noble year
that should have left him famous.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, Fry left the United States with a shaky promise of
visas from Under Secretary of State Sumner Welles. Fry's mission
was to try to spring 200 artists, writers and intellectuals from
the prison the Gestapo was making of Europe. The effort was backed
by private fund-raising from an ad hoc American Emergency Rescue
Committee, which consisted of a few New Yorkers with contacts.
There was no way it could work.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Fry got most of the luminaries he went for, among
them the painters Marc Chagall and Max Ernst; sculptor Jacques
Lipschitz; writers Franz Werfel, Andre Breton, LionFeuchtwanger,
Heinrich Mann and Hannah Arendt; pianist Wanda Landowska; and 1922
Nobel Prize-winner in medicine Otto Meyerhoff. Legally and
illegally, he got them and another 1,500 (maybe a lot more) Jews,
displaced anti-Nazis and British airmen to safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1940, the Nazi broom had pushed refugees into a
crowded heap in the rump of France that Hitler allowed to be
administered by a regime led by Philippe Petain and an odious
troupe of Nazi-lovers.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rick's Cafe in ``Casablanca'' on a grand scale. Fry set
himself up in Marseille, which was run by two crime families, no
matter who the national government was.
</P>
<P>
   Fry was legal. His country wasn't in the war yet. Some of his
clients had real or forged papers; others had nothing. The credit
card hadn't been invented, and refugees had little cash and no hope
of contacting their banks without arousing the Gestapo. Leaving
France required an exit visa, and the regime found ways to avoid
issuing them. It also required acceptance by neutral Spain and
Portugal, whose borders were loosely or tightly sealed according to
whim and the latest war news.
</P>
<P>
   Escape was one Catch-22 after another. Fry undid the catches.
When all else failed, he smuggled people out. The French government
was unhelpful, but some cops were embarrassed by the regime and
overlooked things. U.S. embassy officials, with few exceptions,
kept their heads down. When Fry started to be conspicuous, they
disowned and disavowed him, put up roadblocks and tried to have him
thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   How he succeeded against those odds is told here by a British
author, and it's a story that deserves telling.
</P>
<P>
   From August 1940 through September 1941, Varian Fry was a
combination of James Bond and the Scarlet Pimpernel. But where did
he come from, and where did he go? Two more good questions.
</P>
<P>
   He came from New York. His father was a stockbroker until the
Crash, a moderately rich one. Mother was a coddler. Fry avoided
school when he wished by feigning illness. He washed out of a
couple of prep schools before making it through Taft, then went to
Harvard, where he made up a personality that was half-Oxford don
and half-Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   He hung out with an artsy, vaguely political crowd, did some
journalism and a bit of fund-raising for good causes. He married an
older woman, who settled him down, but he apparently continued a
homosexual affair she knew about.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, evaluations would have included such observations
as ``does not take direction, does not work well with peers.'' In
France, he had authority _ almost out of touch with his sponsors
because of disrupted communications and censorship _ and aroused
something like devotion from the expatriates and French who worked
with him.
</P>
<P>
   He came home angry. The strain of 13 months of letters that
passed through censors undid his marriage. He let it be known what
he thought about a State Department that strangled desperate people
with red tape. He was so noisy about it he was a risky hire for
anyone doing business with the government.
</P>
<P>
   He underwent analysis. He dabbled in television, taught a
little, wrote a little. He remarried. He died in 1967 without ever
getting a big second act together.
</P>
<P>
   But that first act was great. Marino notes that the cream of
European culture coming to the United States helped to break down
Europe's disdain for the New World. It also gave Americans
confidence in their own work: ``It was Europe that began to look
faintly provincial in the postwar years.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be another book in that observation, but by the time
that story starts, the man who made it all possible had quietly
faded away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quiet American: The Secret War of Varian Fry,'' by Andy
Marino. St. Martin's Press. 403 pages. $26.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
