<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-SIESTAKEY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `You-gotta' energy infectious on Siesta Key
 &HT;    By Mary Thurwachter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIESTA KEY, Fla. _ Matthew Ellis didn't lack enthusiasm for his
corner of the world. We had barely checked in to his Crescent House
Bed &AMP; Breakfast before his litany of ``you gotta's'' began.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta get across the street to the beach for sunset. It's
the locals' favorite beach. The sand is sugar white. The sea oats
are purple this time of year. It's beautiful...
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta try Ophelia's restaurant. You'll love the garlic
mashed potatoes. They're friendly there and it's romantic. Took my
wife there last night. Sit outside on the dock if you can...
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta check out the South Palm Avenue in Sarasota,
especially if you love art. They've got great paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta, you gotta, you gotta... ``
</P>
<P>
   After a tedious drive up U.S. 41 from Naples, Matthew's zing
caught us off guard. We just wanted to get to our room, for gosh
sakes.
</P>
<P>
   But the manager's ardor (or maybe it was his smile?) won us over
after he led us to our spacious, if sparsely decorated, upstairs
suite in the building just north of the main house. It was freshly
painted a cheery pale yellow, with botanical print bed cover.
Sliding glass doors opened to a huge, tree-shaded porch. The pool,
under construction, could be seen from the south bay window. There
was a small kitchen and a little bathroom with little bottles of
soap, shampoo and body lotion. And there was a TV.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew was still with us. We began to think of him as family.
</P>
<P>
   Before he returned to his office, he told us we might see
bunnies on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   My husband envisioned Hugh Hefner's curvy mates.
</P>
<P>
   I thought Peter Cottontail.
</P>
<P>
   I was right. Sure enough, as we left the beach a couple of brown
rabbits crossed our path through the purple sea oats.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Crescent House, we examined our surroundings. The
three-bedroom main house was built around 1908 in Englewood and
moved in 1934 by barge to Siesta Beach. The two-story wooden house
has a glassed-in front porch filled with white wicker and an old
organ.
</P>
<P>
   A fireplace dominates the adjoining, airy living room with high
ceilings. The upholstery on the loveseat matched the bedspread in
our room and the covering on the sofa in our den back home. Indeed,
we felt comfortable here.
</P>
<P>
   We did go to Ophelia's, got an outside table (until it rained
and we had to move indoors). We ate seafood gumbo, salad, pompano
and garlic mashed potatoes. Matthew was right about this place, a
few miles south of the bed-and-breakfast. It was first rate all
around.
</P>
<P>
   We did go to the art district on South Palm Avenue in Sarasota.
My husband still raves about a few of the paintings he saw there.
We also spent a few hours at St. Armand's Key, across the bay from
Sarasota. The area is filled with upscale shops and restaurants,
including some of the same stores found on Worth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   And we saw Matthew again _ at breakfast outdoors near the inn's
new gift shop and deli. His assistant served pancakes and fresh
fruit and yogurt _ all to our liking.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew apologized for the pool not being finished and because
the gift shop, just being set up, didn't have the Three Musketeers
bars we wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time you come, we'll have 'em,'' Matthew said.
</P>
<P>
   You gotta love him.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   ACCOMMODATIONS: Crescent House, 459 Beach Road, Siesta Key, FL.
34242.
</P>
<P>
   RATES: Ten guest rooms/suites that range in price from $85 to
$225. An average rate for a single, private bath is around $150.
Breakfast is included. There's a new pool and two spas and a new
gift shop/deli. All rates are based on double occupancy.
Continental breakfast included. Each additional person is $15 per
night. Children under 8 stay free.
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE: (941) 346-0857.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT: Ophelia's on the Bay, 9105 Midnight Pass Road,
Sarasota, FL 33242. Phone: (941) 349-2212. Great seafood dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
