<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MASTERSON07-COX     01-06 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MASTERSON07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The legend lived on; Bat moved to New York
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It is 1919, and William Barclay ``Bat''
Masterson is playing out his string as a sportswriter and columnist
at the New York Morning Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson has two crises to contend with besides the
disgruntlements of age. The most pressing is the imminent arrival
of the Volstead Act, which will deprive him and hundreds of
thousands of others the right to drink alcohol _ a severe
infringement on both his civil rights and his ability to get
through the days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   The second involves the importunings of a young reporter at his
newspaper named Louella Parsons. She wants to write his life story.
Masterson has been too busy living his life to really give its
meaning that much thought, but he knows a good idea when he hears
it.
</P>
<P>
   Stimulated by Parsons, and by the lies told about him and his
friends over the years, Masterson and his wife, Emma, embark on a
sentimental journey to the places of his youth _ Dodge City, where
he was a marshal; Creede, where he ran a gambling emporium; and
Glenwood Springs, Colo., where he visits the grave of Doc Holliday,
the man who has bedeviled his conscience for years.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson also stops in Los Angeles, where he renews his
friendship with Wyatt Earp, portrayed as a suspicious, grumpy old
man. The trip to L.A. isn't a total waste; Masterson makes a new
friend in William S. Hart, who inveigles him into appearing in one
of his movies.
</P>
<P>
   The loose, reflective structure of Richard Wheeler's novel
allows him plenty of room to bask in an old lawman's entertaining,
pithy mind: ``Words make better bullets. There's an Underwood on my
desk, and I can hammer it with my two trigger fingers, but I prefer
to scribble my columns. I shoot words now and hit whatever I want
to hit, without aiming. I am better with words than I ever was with
a revolver.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an odd but amiable and engaging novel that seems to take
its primary inspiration from history, not storytelling. Wheeler
never strays very far from the historical record, which rather hems
him in.
</P>
<P>
   (The historical record also trips Wheeler up occasionally; I
doubt that the slang term ``broad,'' referring to a woman, was in
common use in 1919, and I'm sure that Errol Flynn was still in
Tasmania and all of 10 years old when Masterson refers to him as
being handcuffed by Prohibition.)
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Wheeler keeps the focus resolutely on the
dyspeptic old man plowing through the present, where he feels
marooned, to get to the truth of the past.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that Wheeler makes a mistake by having Masterson
tell us about the events of his life rather than flashing back and
giving us vividly imagined scenes. This makes ``Masterson'' more
didactic than it needs to be, although it's always entertaining,
and occasionally moving.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that the book is completely character-driven, and
its sense of time is 1919, not 1885. This makes a rough sort of
sense, for Masterson was a solid professional at whatever he
attempted _ he was, for instance, quite a good writer.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler throws in amusing walk-ons from Damon Runyon _ ``Guys
and Dolls''' Sky Masterson was an homage to his friend Bat _ Tex
Rickard and Irvin Cobb, while John Ford passes by at a Hollywood
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Masterson resigns himself to the uncomfortable
reality that history will regard him in a way that has little to do
with the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legend is a form of truth,'' William S. Hart tells him. ``As a
mythic figure you inspire a nation. You are an example of bravery,
courage under fire, daring, enterprise, a sort of good white
knight. And out of that myth of Bat Masterson, little boys grow up
tall, men find heart in tough corners. Who knows? Maybe the myth of
a tough frontier sheriff heartened the doughboys in the trenches.
Don't underestimate the virtue of a legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
