<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-POTTER07-COX     01-06 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POTTER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids wild about Harry will love these books, tooBy Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Harry's a hard act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Carabeth Johnston, a third-grade teacher who began
reading aloud to her students from the Harry Potter books this
fall. The kids _ having fallen in love with the boy wizard and the
other quirky characters in J.K. Rowling's books _ now have taken to
shouting for Harry when they enter the classroom, though they know
their daily H.P. fix comes after lunch. They even conned a
substitute teacher into borrowing a copy from another teacher so
they wouldn't miss a day's adventure.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry isn't the only character up to the challenge of
engaging young readers.
</P>
<P>
   And that's good because lately there's been a clamor for Harry
Potter-like books.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, it's adults who want to know, ``Now what?'' after
their young readers have sailed through the first three volumes of
the projected seven-book series (the fourth is expected this fall).
Perhaps they fear a narrow window of time before the child in
question returns to the Technicolor glow of video games and movies.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry's appeal _ though unique _ isn't without precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Lukenbill, a librarian at Wells Branch Elementary, says
kids who love Pokemon and Harry Potter books most likely will love
their literary predecessors: mythology and folklore.
</P>
<P>
   What it all boils down to, she says, is that children love
fantasy, larger than life contests between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   And in this, what Lukenbill considers to be ``the golden age of
children's literature,'' there are plenty of titles to intrigue
them.
</P>
<P>
   So what do Lukenbill and Tiffany Durham recommend?
</P>
<P>
   Their picks include both classics and newer titles. With the
exception of the Bunnicula books, these are appropriate for
children 9-12 and some younger readers. The books can be read aloud
to younger children.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Redwall series, by Brian Jacques (Philomel Books). Mouse
vs. rat; good vs. evil in mystical, richly told stories. The latest
mouse warrior tale, sure to be full of intrigue and adventure is
``The Legend of Luke,'' debuting this month.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Lost Years of Merlin,'' by T.A. Barron (Philomel Books).
First in a trilogy (two volumes thus far) about the mythical
wizard's origins: action-filled fantasy dripping with ancient
Celtic and Druid lore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prydain Chronicles, by Lloyd Alexander (Bantam Doubleday
Dell). Award-winning fantasy series wherein Taran the Assistant
Pig-Keeper battles evil among rgettable cast of characters,
including Eilonwy, a strong-willed princess, and Fflewddur Fflam, a
hyperbole-prone bard.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Golden Compass,'' and ``The Subtle Knife,'' by Philip
Pullman (Knopf Paperbacks). Fast-paced stories in an eventual
fantasy trilogy in which a young girl discovers the manifestation
of her soul in animal form.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bad Beginning'' and ``Reptile Room,'' by Lemony Snicket
(HarperCollins). The first two titles in a series of dark comedies
are Dickensian tales that tell the stories of Violet, Klaus and
Sunny Baudelaire, three orphans who are charming, resourceful and
exceptionally unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Madeline L'Engle's ``A Wrinkle In Time,'' (Bantam Doubleday
Dell). One of a quartet of award-winning books about children who
travel through space and time to battle cosmic evil. Elegant prose
and uncommon wisdom elevate this tale of two siblings in search of
their father.
</P>
<P>
   _ The books of Roald Dahl: ``James and the Giant Peach''
(Knopf), and others bring fantastic imagery to life. These are
colorful, imaginative books populated by big-hearted giants,
runaway peaches and singing spiders.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chronicles of Narnia, C.S. Lewis (HarperCollins). Classic,
richly told stories of good vs. evil; faith and hope in a place
called Narnia. Lewis' tales of children swept into a place of
enchantment have bewitched readers for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bunnicula books, by James Howe (Atheneum Books and Aladdin
Paperbacks). Mystery/comedies that are sillier than some of the
aforementioned books, and appropriate for slightly younger readers
(second- or third-grade reading level). Quickie synopsis: Dog and
cat suspect newly arrived bunny of being a vampire after watching
him suck the juice out of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
