<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ The big Y2K happening came
and went and for the most part, society as we know it didn't suffer
any ill effects. For those of you just now peeking out of your
bunkers to see what sort of destruction was left in the wake of the
dreaded tick of the clock from 1999 to 2000, it must be a mixed
bag. (Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ HAMILTON POOL, TRAVIS COUNTY, Texas _ Last time
I was here, 21 years ago, a group of bikers watched as on a dare I
jumped off a 45-foot cliff into the deep waters of this natural
pool. It was a dumb stunt that cost me a few weeks of serious pain
when the force of the water wrenched my arm out of its socket. I
drove back home to Nacogdoches the next day with my arm wrapped
tight against my body, shifting my Volkswagen bus with my left hand
and steering at the same time with my knees. Somewhere there's a
color slide my brother shot, who watched aghast as I took the
plunge, my short body outlined against the rock, bushy hair
sticking straight up. Lord, it's a miracle I survived the follies
of my youth. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   this week's column was a reprint 1/5_clMCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN,
Texas _ The Texas governor's inner office could sport a sign like
those increasingly seen at businesses around Texas: ``Se habla
espanol,'' or ``Spanish spoken here.'' (McNeely, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ While we waited for a Y2K rash to
break out (later to rejoice at the sight of our own flesh), what
was happening down the block? In our neighborhoods? In our streets?
(John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald).
MOVED.
</P>
