<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MEDICINE-RAIN-FOREST-     01-06 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-RAIN-FOREST-NYSTF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING NEW MEDICINES IN THE RAIN FOREST  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY DAN WAGNER  
 c.2000 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QL;  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Earth is actually a unique pharmacopoeia, offering a wealth
of pure and untapped resources. In fact, most of the natural,
synthetic or semisynthetic drugs used today come from its soil,
oceans, atmosphere, plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, perhaps it is the rain forest that remains the most fully
stocked shelf of the medicine cabinet that is our planet.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical forests cover nine percent of the world's land surface
(about 7.75 billion acres) and provide the natural habitat for more
than half, or 125,000, of the world's flowering plants and
cone-bearing species. Less than 15 percent of these plants have
been investigated for potential medicinal value.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four or five years, groups of pharmacists have begun
traveling to the rain forests to seek out plants that may have
medicinal uses. Expeditions have included trips to the Peruvian
Amazon as well as Belize, Costa Rica and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Typically such field studies involve bio-prospecting _ field
collection of medicinal plant samples in the wild _ and
identifying, collecting and labeling herbarium samples.
</P>
<P>
   This work also helps ensure the long-term survival of plant
species that may or may not be medicinal (many shamans would say
that all plants have a purpose and medicinal use). Considering that
in the United States today, 29 percent of the 16,000 endemic plants
are at risk of extinction, and that pharmaceutical manufacturers
are increasingly looking to natural plant sources, such research is
more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the early 1980s, no major pharmaceutical
companies were investing in natural rain forest product research.
Today, more than half of the world's 250 pharmaceutical
manufacturers are reintroducing plant-research programs, sample
collection and laboratory testing of jungle plants. The National
Cancer Institute is the current leader in conducting such studies.
</P>
<P>
   Some extremely effective treatments in modern medicine were
derived from natural sources. Two substances isolated from the
Madagascar periwinkle _ vincristine sulfate and vinblastine sulfate
_ are used to combat several afflictions, including childhood
leukemia and Hodgkin's disease.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest natural medicines ever discovered, quinine,
from the bark of the cinchona tree, is an effective treatment for
malaria. Quinine was later converted into quinidine, which helps
treat atrial fibrillation, a condition in which the heart beats
irregularly.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rainforest discoveries commonly used as medicines
today:
</P>
<P>
   Pau d'Arco: A Brazilian tree that has been used for thousands of
years by indigenous peoples of South America. The bark of the tree
is used for treating skin diseases such as eczema, psoriasis and
fungal infections.
</P>
<P>
   Wild yam: Although this homely little tuber is one of the most
illustrious and highly researched plants in all of Central America
(original research led to the development of such products as
cortisone and the birth control pill), today it is used by millions
of women for the relief of menopausal and perimenopausal symptoms
such as hot flashes, vaginal dryness and night sweats.
</P>
<P>
   Red gumbolimbo bark: Locally, this tree has been successfully
used for internal and external infections _ a tea made from the
bark is used to treat urinary tract infections. The most exciting
new use of gumbolimbo bark is for the treatment of topical
psoriasis, eczema, insect bites and fungus. The raw compound can be
mixed with aloe, vitamin E and cortisone or calendula to form a
highly effective topical cream.
</P>
<P>
   Jackass bitters: The leaves of this common tall, bushy Central
American plant contain a potent anti-parasitic agent (sesquiterpene
dialdehyde) that is active against amoebas, intestinal parasites,
candida and giarrdia. It is taken as a tea or a wine.
</P>
<P>
   Maca root: This root from the Peruvian Andes has been used for
centuries as a highly popular cure-all medicine for middle-aged and
elderly men. Most interesting is its support of normal sexual
function in older men and post- and perimenopausal women. Maca root
has been shown to balance estrogen and testosterone levels.
</P>
<P>
   Una de Gato: While this vine from Peru (commonly known as
``cat's claw'') was long used by Peruvian Indians for its power as
a kidney and liver tonic, it was only recently discovered by
Western scientists to have potent immune-boosting characteristics
and as a popular drug store herb. U.S. patients have also found the
tea useful against diverticulitus, hemorrhoids, parasites, colitis
and leaky bowel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   We are seeing an increased focus on holistic medicine _ where
the paradigm is one of healing the patient, not necessarily curing
the disease. Sales of herbals, for example, have skyrocketed to
close to $3 billion annually, and are expected to hit $5 billion in
another two years.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable integration of medicine will not demean the
pharmaceutical phenomena or diminish the role of the diagnostic
physician, but will nicely complement existing therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wagner is a pharmacist and herbalist at Nutri-farmacy
(www.nutrifarmacy.com) in Wildwood, Pa., and frequent visitor to
the world's rainforests.
</P>
<P>
   (The Medical Tribune Web site is at http://www.medtrib.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
