<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ASTRONOMY-$ADV09-COX     01-06 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONOMY-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'NAKED' BLACK HOLES AND BABY GALAXIES
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 9.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scientists have uncovered the first evidence that a
mysterious new kind of black holes may exist in empty space, huge
concentrations of invisible matter and enormous gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the ``normal'' black holes that have been found chewing
up billions of stars at the center of every galaxy, the isolated
holes might have been flung into intergalactic space by rival
objects, astronomers have speculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a hell of a thing to have splatter into the
windshield of your spaceship one morning,'' one astronomer joked a
few years ago when the idea of such phenomena began to circulate.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence for the new black holes will be discussed at the annual
meeting of the American Astronomical Society, being held Tuesday
through Saturday in Atlanta. Other findings to be described at the
convention of about 1,600 astronomers include sightings of what
appear to be baby galaxies in the process of formation and some
remarkable new objects scientists are calling ``mini-quasars.''
</P>
<P>
   These star-like bodies seem to be spewing out matter at speeds
greater than the speed of light, something that is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   Early observations from two new orbiting telescopes, the Far
Ultraviolet Spectroscopic Explorer (FUSE) and Chandra, NASA's
orbiting X-ray telescope that has been peering into deep space,
also are to be presented.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Hubble Space Telescope, which shuttle astronauts
repaired last week, astronomers have been studying huge black holes
in our own galaxy, the Milky Way, and others for several years.
</P>
<P>
   These huge concentrations of matter nest at the centers of most,
and probably all, galaxies. A black hole at the center of the
nearby Andromeda Galaxy has been studied extensively.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby stars swirl around it at enormous speeds, doomed to fall
into it, where they will be crushed into superdensity. The
Andromeda black hole may be small enough that it would fit inside
the orbit of Mars, yet appears to contain as much matter as 30
million suns. Black holes in other galaxies may ``weigh'' as much
as 500 million suns, astronomers say.
</P>
<P>
   While black holes' gravity is so great that even light cannot
escape from them, nearby stars emit fountains of X-rays and light
just before falling to the point of no return. These emissions
provided the first evidence that the theorized black holes actually
existed.
</P>
<P>
   At some galactic centers huge black holes appear to have swept
up all nearby stars and dust, so the telltale light and X-ray signs
no longer exist. The speeds of stars being drawn toward them gave
them away.
</P>
<P>
   If two galaxies were to collide, their black holes would
probably merge into an even great region of dark density.
</P>
<P>
   However, astronomers can visualize an event in which one black
hole would rush close to a second, but the two would not merge.
Gravitational forces would whip one of them back into space in the
same way NASA has used the gravity of the Earth and other planets
to boost man-made space probes on their journeys.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation has been that such black holes might be flung
into intergalactic space or relative empty regions within a galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``naked'' black holes to be described at the astronomers'
meeting exist in Earth's home galaxy, the Milky Way, astronomers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there appear to be small black holes that are neither
in the center of galaxies nor in empty space.
</P>
<P>
   One, which appears to be only about 40,000 light years from
Earth and to weigh only as much as a handful of stars, is tossing
around subatomic particles in hunks about the size of the moon. New
information about its behavior will be presented at the astronomy
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ejected material appears to be moving at speeds
greater than 186,000 miles per second, the speed of light. Such
motion is impossible and astronomers believe they understand how
the illusion is created.
</P>
<P>
   Using an array of ground-based radio telescopes in conjunction
with an orbiting NASA explorer, astronomers are studying the
object, which they call a ``mini-quasar'' because it resembles the
ancient, huge quasars previously spotted in the outer reaches of
the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
