<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-EXPEDITE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW BOARDING: BAR-CODE TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Delta Air Lines gate supervisor Michael Lania looked
into his new computer screen and surveyed the passenger in front of
Gate 31 at Logan International Airport who had just come from
another flight.
</P>
<P>
   Without having ever seen the woman before, Lania confidently
declared: ``That's Evelyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Lania knew the woman's name because one window of Delta's new
computer system for boarding passengers indicated that Evelyn was
the last passenger from one of six connecting flights to board
Flight 2001 to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Her bar-coded boarding pass was passed under an optical scanner
that looks a little like R2-D2 lost in an airport terminal, and her
name flashed on a display for Lania to see.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind Delta's new ``cornerstones'' boarding technology
is not to impress passengers by having gate agents greet them by
name as they show up at the gate, but rather to speed boarding,
improve customer service, and augment security checks.
</P>
<P>
   In operation for two months at Boston's Logan International
Airport and other major airports in Delta's system, the program
represents the latest effort in the airline industry's efforts to
use technology to improve efficiency, which is critical for
maintaining on-time performance.
</P>
<P>
   While Delta is not the only major airline to use magnetic strip
readers in the boarding process _ and cornerstones has a magnetic
reader _ it also has a bar code scanning system that is quicker
than the magnetic reading system and less likely to jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a major savings in time and expense for
airlines, and it allows you to get planes out quicker,'' said
Darryl Jenkins, director of the Aviation Institute at George
Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``These types of things are so important to operations and are
good for everybody,'' Jenkins said. ``That system makes it easier
if you are connecting passenger, because if they know you are in
the terminal, they are more likley to hold the plane for you and
will take a five-minute delay.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as in the case of Flight 2001 Wednesday morning, when
everyone who is checked in for a flight is on board early, the
plane can push back early. Flight 2001, scheduled to depart at
10:15 a.m., left the gate three minutes early. And in a rush-hour
situation, when an airport has 10 flights scheduled to depart at
the same time, leaving the gate three minutes early can save 30
minutes in taxiing.
</P>
<P>
   In the works for nearly 18 months, cornerstones was designed
with the input of Delta gate agents who were flown to Atlanta to
talk with software designers. Delta calls it the most advanced
boarding system of its kind. Delta estimates the new system shaves
about 10 minutes from the boarding time and gives agents more time
to assist passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses Hewlett-Packard computers at the gate, a Windows
NT wide area network with T-1 and T-3 lines connecting it to
Delta's mainframe computer in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And in a throwback to boarding systems of a generation ago _
when gate agents used stickers configured in a seating diagram of
the airplane to assign seats, the cornerstones program has a
seating chart of the airplane and tracks the status of evey seat,
whether it is sold, reserved, the individual has checked in, and
whether they have boarded.
</P>
<P>
   By double-clicking on a passenger's name, agents can determine
whether he checked baggage, how many pieces, whether it was done
curbside or by another airline. That way, if a passenger has
checked in but not boarded, with a double-click of the mouse,
agents can find out whether bags need to be pulled from the
airplane. Similarly, if a boarding pass is used more than once, the
system alerts the agent immediately.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:05 a.m., all checked-in paassengers were on board Flight
2001 expect one, Minh Pham, assigned seat 31D, and connecting in
Atlanta to a flight to Wichita. Lania scanned the waiting area,
which was deserted, and then paged Pham. Two minutes later, the
passenger came running down the concourse, anxiety etched on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' Lania said. ``You have plenty of time.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10:07 a.m., Pham was on board and the cornerstones system
showed all passengers _ 11 in first class, 111 in coach _ accounted
for and on board the Boeing 757. The system even noted that three
special meals has been requested and were on board.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dykes, manager of passenger services for Delta at Logan
Airport, said the airline is spending $1.5 billion on improving
gate area technology and plans to introduce this spring
wall-mounted flash screen televisions at gate area which will
answer frequently asked questions about flights, such as aircraft
type, meal service, flight duration, planned boarding times and
explain any service interruptions. The cornerstones program will be
used to manipulate the screens.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the airline will roll out hand-held boarding
scanners to increase the effeciency of cornerstones if boarding
lines are too long at any gate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
