<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-WOMEN-POWER-BOS &LR;      01-06 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WOMEN-POWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING MOTHERS DEBATE DUAL ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift's practice of relying on
staff aides to help her with child care and other errands reminds
Boston attorney Cheryl Cronin of the hectic days when her three
children were infants.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of pressing business, Cronin, 45, would
occasionally hand her baby over to a secretary, not knowing what
else to do. Perhaps her son was screaming in the background while
she was on the phone with a client.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awkward. It felt like an imposition on someone,'' said
Cronin, whose sons are now ages 11, 7 and 2. ``I will say that I
should not have done it. But I won't criticize (Swift.) I have
great sympathy for what she's going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Swift is one of the state's most powerful people, her
story is in a certain sense the story of Everywoman.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, 60 percent of mothers with children under the
age of six were in the work force at the time of the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   News of the lieutenant governor's habit of turning to State
House staff for help with babysitting touched off a debate among
women about the changing mores of the modern workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Women from all walks of life clash over how a mother should
navigate the still relatively uncharted sea that lies between the
worlds of work and family.
</P>
<P>
   Some say society owes more help to working mothers like Swift.
They point out that men have traditionally turned to secretaries to
perform all kinds of personal tasks, from making dinner
reservations to buying flowers for their wives. Others respond that
times have changed, and that neither women nor men belong in the
boardroom if they cannot leave the dirty diapers at home.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Young, vice president of the Women's Freedom Network in
Washington, said Swift misused the power of her office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have looked up to Jane Swift as a role model,
and this tarnishes the role model image,'' Young said. ``I think
Jane Swift has given critics a pretext for working mother
bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift acknowledges that she has repeatedly asked colleagues to
babysit her 14-month-old daughter Elizabeth, both during the work
day and at night. She has also relied on them to pick up her dry
cleaning and run other errands, saying that the staffers are
friends, and that she would return the favor anytime. But some
staff members have complained privately.
</P>
<P>
   Swift's problems are emblematic of the struggle of women across
Massachusetts, said Elizabeth A. Sherman, director of the Center
for Women in Politics and Public Policy at the University of
Massachusetts Boston. According to Sherman, it is common for women
in executive positions to fall back on their staff for occasional
child care support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are just harried and stressed out, and they're relying
on that extra set of hands and loving heart that's nearest to them
to help out,'' Sherman said. ``It's not a question of money. It's a
question of who can you call at the last minute when nobody else is
around, who you can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Extended family and friends once served that role in a mother's
life, Sherman said, but that web of support has frayed. Swift is
from Western Massachusetts, and Sherman notes that when her
stay-at-home husband is busy, she many not have many others to turn
to in the Boston area besides her co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Young argues that it is unethical to make such demands
on employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's using this pretense that, `Oh, we're just a bunch of
friends or working mothers helping each other out,' '' said Young,
author of ``Ceasefire!: Why Women and Men Must Join Forces to
Achieve True Equality.'' ``But I seriously doubt a lower-level
employee would feel she could ask Jane Swift for the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some working mothers with less-glamorous careers say they resent
what they see as Swift taking advantage of her privileged position.
One is Carrie Sorokoff, 38, a reading teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people do want a career and do want a family. I don't
begrudge her that,'' said Sorokoff as she was shopping for mittens
at Bradlees with her four-year-old son Mason. ``But I do begrudge
her for using state people to do what everyone else pays someone to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other mothers, however, said Swift is only doing what mothers
have always done _ turn to the people around them when there's a
sick baby or a sudden obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe it takes a village,'' said Arlene Cozart, 45.
``Whatever her position is, she needs people around her to help,
and that's okay. I had a mother and a grandmother, and I needed the
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Several women interviewed said that the attacks were sexist
because men have done the same things for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double standard'' to vilify Swift for getting help in
the office, said Judith Casey, director of the New England Work and
Family Association at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Casey argued that society demands too much of working parents
without giving them what they need to perform at work without
abandoning their responsibilities as parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's this talented woman who has a lot to contribute. She
should be able to do that,'' Casey said. ``We should make it
possible for her to do what she wants to do. I don't really think
it's that hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
