<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS' REED APPEARS TO BE A RECEIVER AT THE END OF THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ The lasting image of Buffalo wide receiver
Andre Reed was not one of his trademark dashes after a catch or his
quick, stabbing, velcroed snares of a ball. He departed, instead,
in a dreamy saunter, with those who lingered inside Ralph Wilson
Stadium shouting his name as No. 83 disappeared down a runway, with
tears pooling in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's here, or somewhere else,'' the 35-year-old Reed
said moments later, ``I still feel I have a lot to give to the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Jim Kelly's primary target, the No. 1 throw-to guy in the
Bills' not-so-triumphant run to four consecutive Super Bowl
appearances, Reed is now but a spare and expensive part. He will
suit up for the Bills' wild-card game Saturday against the
Tennessee Titans in Nashville. There remains a chance that the
Bills will play on their home field one more time _ if they advance
to the AFC title game _ but few around Buffalo expect the aging
master pass-catcher, now second all-time in career receptions, to
be back to begin a 16th season in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in my own little shell,'' said Reed, after adding
five more catches in Sunday's 31-6 win over Indianapolis, lifting
his career total to 941 receptions, one ahead of Art Monk. ``That's
the way I do things. It's been tough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The evolutionary process catches up to everyone, no matter what
the sport, no matter how lengthy and impressive the resume. The
current Buffalo passing game centers on fourth-year wide receiver
Eric Moulds (65 catches, 7 TDs), and, to a lesser extent, wide
receiver Peerless Price (31 catches, 3 TDs) and tight end Jay
Riemersma (37 catches, 4 TDs).
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who caught 81 passes and cashed in a career-high 10 for
TDs in 1991, four times has cracked 1,000 yards in reception
yardage. His longtime coach, Marv Levy, often said Reed's greatest
strength was his ability to roll up yards after pulling in a pass.
But this season, Reed has been all but deleted from head coach Wade
Phillips's game plan. New England fans: Think Ben Coates.
</P>
<P>
   Reed caught a touchdown pass in the Bills' Sept. 12 opener vs.
Indianapolis and then zeroed out for the remaining 15 games,
finishing with a respectable 52 catches for only 536 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play the game so many years, and you try to set goals for
yourself every year _ and try to achieve them, both as an
individual and as a team,'' said Reed, who debuted in 1985
following a record-setting career at Kutztown (Pa.) University.
``And now, whether I'm (back) here or not, I've got a whole bunch
of memories that I can put in my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what has brought Reed to the threshold of a Western New
York sendoff is something else he has put in his pocket: the riches
that have followed with his fame. The Bills face significant salary
cap issues for next season, even with the cap about to inflate from
$57 million to $62 million next month.
</P>
<P>
   Two other of Buffalo's aging stalwarts, defensive end Bruce
Smith and running back Thurman Thomas, also could be difficult fits
next season given their salaries. But it's far more likely that
they'll be retained, their pacts reworked to fit more comfortably
under the cap.
</P>
<P>
   According to recent published reports, Reed's deal calls for him
to make $1.775 million next season, with a $600,000 signing bonus,
making him worth almost $2.4 million against the cap. Smith's cap
figure ($5.448 million) is more than double that and Thomas's a
little less (approximately $2 million). Combined, the three would
account for nearly $10 million toward the cap _ on a payroll that
already projects to be some 20 percent over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   It's the NFL of today: Legends often fall prey to the ledger.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, though, a handful of clubs will be willing to work
Reed into their plans. The Bills, with Doug Flutie running the
offense, didn't emphasize the deep pass. Flutie's flings were more
horizontal than vertical, a point emphasized emphatically last
Sunday when Rob Johnson, Flutie's $5 million-a-year understudy,
opened up the Bills' attack with his decisive, longer lobs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's showing was so impressive that the Bills' coaching
staff woke up Monday morning, checked the videotape to verify what
they witnessed, and dumped Flutie for Johnson. In all likelihood,
Flutie will also be elsewhere next season. The irony could be that
Johnson, with his arm making the passing game more diverse and a
greater threat, might pose a far better fit for Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's first pass last Sunday went to Reed, a dump to the
right that was good for 3 yards. The second half started with the
identical pass, only to the left side, also again for 3 yards. The
second play of the second half also went to Reed.
</P>
<P>
   That catch was Reed's 50th reception this season, the 13th time
he has done that, tying him at No. 1 with Jerry Rice. About 3:40
into the fourth quarter, on a second-and-4 play, Johnson tossed to
Reed in the right flat for an 11-yard gain. It tied Reed with Monk
for career catches and jumped him ahead of Steve Largent on the
career yardage list, landing him No. 4 overall. With 10:20
remaining, he hauled in career catch No. 941, leaving him second
only to Rice (1,206) for career catches.
</P>
<P>
   Done for the day, Reed moved to the sideline and accepted the
congratulatory backslaps and hugs of his teammates. Smith, who
raced down the sideline and cheered when Reed caught No. 941, was
among the first to greet him. Moments later, a towel draped over
Reed's head to shield his weeping, he shook hands with the likes of
Flutie and Moulds. Phillips left the sideline, seeking out Reed on
the bench to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Reed stood atop a bench and acknowledged the
thundering chants of ``Andre . . . Andre . . . Andre . . .'' that
tumbled down from the adoring crowd of 61,959. Their words and his
emotion underscored the obvious, that another piece of the Empire
State's near empire stood on the verge of saying farewell forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a standard young guys look at here,'' said Reed, summing
up his decade-and-a-half in the Bills' red-white-and-blue. ``That's
the same for Thurman and Bruce. The young kids look at us, and they
want to know how we did it so long. So I'll know when I'm gone,
there were some people (in the dressing room) that got something
out of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a legacy that I leave, it is that I know I gave 100
percent out there, and no one can take that away from me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
