u s BC-SKI-CANNON-BOS &LR;      01-06 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-CANNON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANNON STILL TOP GUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANCONIA, N.H. _ Cannon Mountain, always and forever
challenging, is changing.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon has long owned a deserved reputation as one of New
England's finest skiers' mountains.
</P>
<P>
   No frills or fancy stuff here. Plenty of thrills. Steep and
demanding. Windy with winding trails. Cold days and mostly tough
ways down the mountain. Hard-packed, icy, at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mountain makes you ski,'' said Terry Lufkin. ``You have
to ski.''
</P>
<P>
   Have had to from 1938 when the first tramway was put in to the
top of the 4,180-foot mountain. No working your way up the
mountain. Straight to the top. And good luck getting down on.
</P>
<P>
   Later came the Front Five, left to right, for all to see from
the Franconia Notch Parkway and sometimes all skiers bother to see
of Cannon _ Avalanche, Paulie's Folly, Zoomer, Rocket, and Gary's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've skied only 43 of my 45 years and they can be intimidating
to me,'' said Dick Andross. ``For the guy who skis six or seven
times a year and sees them, I'm sure they look intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   And he manages the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The Front Five still looks the same these days. But Andross
hopes skiers driving by on their way farther north to Bretton Woods
or those inclined to stop a few miles south at Loon _ areas he
thinks his mountain complements _ check around the corner at
Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are dramatic. A whole new beginner area has been
added, served by its own chairlift and far from the more advanced
skiers. Two more chairlifts, one a detachable quad, replace a
couple of ancient ones in front and to the left of the Peabody
Lodge looking up the mountain. A new lodge houses a learning
center.
</P>
<P>
   Up the mountain, Middle Ravine and Middle Cannon _ a couple of
usually tough-to-ski trails because of their side slope and
narrowness _ have been widened.
</P>
<P>
   The trick was to keep the best _ the trails and approach that
make Cannon Cannon _ and add the rest to make the mountain more
novice-, intermediate-, and family-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Sno.engineering, a Littleton, N.H., firm that plans ski areas
worldwide, went to work with Andross and the state of New
Hampshire, which owns and runs Cannon as the centerpiece of
Franconia Notch State Park.
</P>
<P>
   About $6.5 million later, the bulk of Phase 1, including
improved snowmaking, was completed as this season was about to
start.
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin and her ski mates, well aware improvements were needed
yet a little apprehensive when they started messing with the
mountain, like what they've seen so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big improvement,'' said Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent, it's a six-minute chairlift ride down from 15,''
said Peter Thoma of the trip on the Peabody Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten, 11 minutes roundtrip,'' said Bob Karman.
</P>
<P>
   These, folks, are serious skiers. Serious Cannon skiers. All
live nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Thoma goes back nearly as far as the original tram and has been
sking here since the 1940s, Karman the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin graduated to Cannon about five years ago and quickly
earned her stripes. She skied 120 days last year, mostly at Cannon.
She hit 40 days Tuesday in this snowfall-less winter.
</P>
<P>
   Karman gave his initial stamp of approval to the trail work on
Ravine when he hiked up in the fall and walked off the widths of
the new trails _ ``80 feet on Middle Cannon, 125 on Middle
Ravine,'' he reported.
</P>
<P>
   Karman did have some pre-work concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling they might turn Upper Cannon into a super
highway,'' he said. ``I hope they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Andross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some of the old plans, before the current one, that
called for changing Upper Ravine and Upper Cannon,'' Andross said.
``I told them to find somebody else. I wasn't going to fool with
those trails. The plan was to widen them out, make them a little
straighter so they could carry more people. Sorry, that's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Erlander, a principal of Sno.engineering who calls Cannon
his home mountain, would rather add curves to trails than take them
away. The cost could be prohibitive, but ideally it would be nice
to do some work on Profile, a newer trail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It finishes with a very steep section and you abruptly come to
a lift terminal. It doesn't work very well and the trail is more
like highway construction. The edges are straight. We don't like to
build trails that way. It's much more interesting to put some
curves in it, some rolls where you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Music, no doubt, to the ears of Lufkin and Thoma and Karman. And
those of David Parker of Concord, another longtime Cannon skier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to learn how to do it all,'' Lufkin said. ``You've
got to take the good with the bad. When it's good, it's really
good. Some people don't want to ski like that. I get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top to bottom runs are a gas,'' Parker said. ``Those
faces, Paulie's, Avalanche, Zoomer, you can't beat them anyplace.
It's a skiers' mountain. The mountain itself is great, you can't
beat the terrain and the fall line and all that stuff. A lot of
mountains have cleaned out those small, winding trails.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Elander said the mountain's ``comfortable carrying capacity''
has grown from 2,500 skiers a day to 3,500 with these changes and
there is still some fine-tuning to do on the trails. There is still
another piece left to Phase 1, as well _ including improvements on
the summit building, adding a deck all around it which will take
better advantage of the great views from the top.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the master plan calls for a couple of lifts to
the west, closer to the nearby and no longer open Mittersill ski
area, which will open up more not-too-difficult terrain. Plans for
moving higher on Mittersill, which involves National Forest Service
land, are currently on hold and still a way down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever and wherever things go, Andross and Erlander said they
don't see Cannon losing its best qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real important part of the mandate and goals when we
set out, to make sure it's well recognized that this is a ski area
in a very high profile, high visibility state park,'' Erlander
said. ``One of New Hampshire's treasures, the Old Man of the
Mountain, is right around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cannon is one of those mountains a lot of people have a soft
spot for in their heart. It's such a challenging, rocky, big old
mountain. You either love it or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Count Lufkin and Karman, Thoma and Parker, and many others among
the ones who do. Still.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
