<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FAITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHERS AND SONS: MCCAIN AND BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FAITH OF MY FATHERS 
A Family Memoir 
By John McCain with Mark Salter. 
Random House, 349 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
FIRST SON 
George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty 
By Bill Minutaglio 
Times Books, 371 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone wants to be an author in this presidential election
cycle. Each of the top candidates in both parties has written a
book, alongside a number of journalists who have cashed in on the
opportunity to write about the front-runners, making it easy to
dismiss the whole lot as products of self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   But two books in the pile have something deeper in common. Both
Senator John S. McCain and Texas Governor George W. Bush, the top
two Republicans according to national polls, hail from prestigious
families _ the McCain military lineage and the Bush political
dynasty. Both had powerful, and influential, grandfathers who
helped shape their aspirations. And two recent biographies tell
their stories within that context, offering a fuller glimpse of the
men who would be president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Mark Salter, his legislative aide, co-wrote ``Faith
of My Fathers,'' an autobiography that is far more about war than
politics. It outlines McCain's childhood and ends in the 1970s,
after his release from a North Vietnamese prison camp. And its
focus is on three earlier McCain men, whose careers guided McCain
to his own.
</P>
<P>
   All three were independent-minded hellions who struggled with
authority even as they served it. John McCain Sr. was a Navy
four-star admiral who fought in the Pacific theater during World
War II. John McCain Jr. was a WWII combatant as well, and became an
admiral, too _ an unprecedented family feat in the US Navy at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain 3d was raised in the shadow of his father's and
grandfather's successes, and he defers to their legacies and
passions. ``They never imagined possessing a greater treasure than
a life at sea,'' he writes, ``and they regarded it as a legacy they
were proud to bestow on their descendants, who, they assumed, would
be appropriately grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Which McCain was. He writes that he saw his ``enrollment at the
(Naval) Academy as an immutable fact of life.'' The book traces his
early career _ its stops and starts, his drinking and dating
habits, his less-than-exemplary behavior _ but it is with his
capture in 1967 that McCain's own personal struggles are put into
relief.
</P>
<P>
   He was shot down over Hanoi, the right wing of his A-4 blown off
by a Viet Cong surface-to-air missile. His plane, flying at 550
miles per hour, plummeted to the ground. For the next five years
McCain was tortured, interrogated, and imprisoned in isolation. It
was an unmitigated hell _ one that would horrify and fascinate a
reader even if McCain had never accomplished anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before his release, a newspaper headline read:
``Hanoi to release Admiral's son.'' McCain was still his father's
son even in prison; his father had taken over command of the
Pacific effort. But McCain does not see his war-hero status as the
fulfillment of his family legacy; rather, it is the event that
formed his inner life. He recalls signing a confession under
extreme duress by his captors. While it is described as one of the
greatest regrets of his life, it also fits into the larger
philosophical meaning he extracted from the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both my confession and my resistance helped me achieve a
balance in my life, a balance between my own individualism and more
important things,'' McCain writes. ``Like my father and my
grandfather, and the Naval Academy, the men I had been honored to
serve with called me to the cause, and I had tried to keep faith
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``First Son: George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty,''
author Bill Minutaglio is an outsider looking in on the influence
another set of fathers had on their ambitious son . George W.
Bush's great-grandfather helped found the US Chamber of Commerce.
His grandfather, Prescott Bush, was a Wall Street success who later
became a prominent senator. And his father, of course, was
President George Herbert Walker Bush.
</P>
<P>
   None of which weighed all that heavily on George W., in
Minutaglio's view. He sailed through Andover and later Yale as a
popular glad-hander more interested in having fun than engaging in
serious political debate, the author writes. Minutaglio follows
each step of the young Bush's life in great detail, declining to
entertain rumors of drug use, preferring instead to map out the
ways Bush mirrored, and didn't mirror, his father's career.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is a far less revealing book psychologically than
McCain's, if for no other reason than that Bush refused to play
along. Minutaglio quotes Bush from a TV interview in 1997: ``It's
hard to believe, but _ I don't have time to worry about being
George Bush's son. Maybe it's a result of being confident. I'm not
sure how the psychoanalysts will analyze it, but I'm not worried
about it. I'm really not. I'm a free guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
