<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAT-OUT EXPENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If you're the sort of person who'd pay $25,000 for a car, and
another $40,000 for the windshield, the computer display industry
is looking for you.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when you can get a high-quality PC for $1,000,
companies are offering flashy flat-panel displays costing well over
two grand. I've been tinkering with one of them _ the SyncMaster
TFT700, a sleek 17-inch flat-panel unit from Samsung Electronics of
South Korea, one of the leading makers of liquid crystal screens
for laptop and desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   The SyncMaster is the sort of flat-panel monitor that could give
these devices a good name. I've seen my share of cheesy-looking
15-inch flat monitors that sell for $1,000 or so. Once the
futuristic thrill fades, I notice the lackluster image quality, and
the way the image looks gray and faded if you view the monitor from
even a slight angle.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to the CRTs _ the traditional cathode-ray tube
monitors. CRTs are fat and heavy, compared with the flat-panel
screens. But CRTs offer bright, sharp pictures that don't fade when
you look at the screen from an angle. Besides, CRTs are a whole lot
cheaper _ $350 or so for a 17-incher.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, flat-panels take up a lot less space, and use that
space more efficiently. Some of the surface of a 17-inch CRT tube
is actually hidden behind the monitor's frame, so the viewable area
is smaller. But with a 17-inch flat-panel, you really get 17
inches. Besides, no matter what's on the screen, flat-panel
displays have a Keanu Reeves-ish aura of sci-fi cool that's always
good for impressing the yokels.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still reactionary types like me who think a
monitor is only as good-looking as the images it displays. For us,
the flat-panel people are now serving up monitors that match up
well against the finest CRTs. Too bad I can't afford one.
</P>
<P>
   The Samsung unit weighs in at $2,400, and good as it is, I'm not
completely content with it. Even after careful tuning, the screen
displays text with a slightly jagged quality. The individual
picture elements, or pixels, are more evident than on a CRT
display, and so text doesn't appear quite as smooth. In addition,
moving images don't ``refresh'' as fast on a flat-panel as on a
CRT. I saw some unwelcome smearing and jaggedness as I soared over
the deserts of Iraq in a virtual F-15 fighter plane.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the colors come across rich and sharp. In a
side-by-side comparison with a new Korea Data Systems 15-inch CRT
monitor, I'd give the Samsung a slight edge in color reproduction.
And the Samsung has successfully tackled the viewing-angle problem
that plagues flat-panel units. You can still make out images on the
screen even when standing to one side and several feet away.
</P>
<P>
   One limit on the Samsung screen's quality is its compatibility
with standard computer video cards. These emit a stream of analog
data that a traditional CRT can handle. But flat-panel displays are
actually digital devices, and they deliver their best performance
when linked to digital video cards. Samsung compromised by building
a display that would work with millions of existing video cards, at
the cost of somewhat lower performance.
</P>
<P>
   Other makers of elite flat-panel monitors are more daring. With
its $2,400 1600SW monitor, Silicon Graphics Inc. bundles in a
digital video card designed by Lexington-based Number Nine Visual
Technology Corp., which recently filed for bankruptcy. Silicon
Graphics says another firm will keep making the cards, which is
just as well. The 17-inch 1600SW is quite a stunner, with
spectacularly lavish color.
</P>
<P>
   I'd cheerfully throw my CRT in the trash in exchange for the new
display from Apple Computer Inc. Their 22-incher is called the
Cinema Display, and with good reason: You could set this thing up
in your living room and watch ``Lawrence of Arabia'' on it. It's
decisively the best flat-panel monitor I've ever seen, and at
$4,000 it had better be. Make that $6,500. The Cinema Display can't
be bought as a separate item, so you'll have to take a $2,500 Apple
G4 computer as well.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's got the makings of a good idea here. The complex
manufacturing process for flat panels means that high-quality ones
will be expensive for years to come, even as computers keep getting
cheaper. Here's an idea: Sell the displays, and throw in a computer
for free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
