<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RURAL-LIFESPAN-BOS &LR;      01-06 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-LIFESPAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IOWA, WOMEN OUTLAST MEN AND TRY TO GO ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKWELL CITY, Iowa _ At the old Amvets tavern here, the voices
of Inez Lang and her widowed friends rise with the next round of
vodka sours. While a few burly men are scattered around the fringes
of the wood-paneled hall, all the energy in the room is drawn to
the large round table where Lang, 68, and her spirited posse of
friends have congregated.
</P>
<P>
   Since her husband's death less than two years ago, these weekly
gatherings have been a soothing constant in Lang's life, and a
symbol of how life in this small farming community has adjusted to
its changing population.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a bit hesitant at first,'' said Lois Maulsby, a widow
of 14 years. ``But we understood. We all have been through it.''
</P>
<P>
   In this pocket of America's heartland, where cornfields stretch
across a fertile landscape, is one of the nation's largest
concentrations of senior citizens living alone, according to local
officials. More than 20 percent overall and 26 percent of women 65
or older live by themselves, twice the national average, according
to the Census.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather noticed there was an unusally high number of
widow ladies here,'' said Rockwell City Mayor John Block, ``and
that was 50 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, rural areas like Calhoun County provide a glimpse of
what small-town America will look like decades from now, as
millions of baby boomers forge into old age, women continue to
outlive their husbands, and young people trade the towering grain
elevators for the high rises of Chicago or Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   So these silver-haired matrons, Lang and the hundreds of other
widows, who have become the life in a dying community of 11,000
residents. Desperately missing their husbands but determined to
move on with their lives, they have gritted their teeth and carved
a life of their own without men.
</P>
<P>
   They are the part-time clerks at the craft store, and the music
directors for the church choirs. They deliver hot meals to the
homebound and to farmers in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, no children play outdoors the way they
used to. But a constant stream of elderly women drive up and down
the roads to the two grocery stores. On Sunday mornings, the widows
are the dominant presence in the churches, where membership is
steadily dropping. And during harvest time, Lang rolls up her
sleeves, hops on her green tractor, and combs the corn and soybean
crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we would rather be with our husbands. You miss them
something terrible,'' said Maulsby, 69. ``When you're out with the
girls, you come home and it's lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun County, two hours outside of Des Moines, has always been
a farming and family town. No one knows when the widows began
hanging at the Amvet Center on Friday nights or getting together
for shopping in the town square. It might have started 14 years
ago, when Maulsby's husband died as he was shelling corn at a
friend's farm. But whatever the genesis, the friendships among the
widows have offered a shoulder to cry on and the motivation to pick
up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what hell it is to lose a husband,'' said Maulsby. A
few months ago, Lang, Maulsby, Lilybell Gray and Clarice Martz
spent five days together in Chicago. But the most memorable times
are back in tiny Rockwell City, sitting around the table at the
Amvets Center.
</P>
<P>
   During one gathering, 10 widows bragged about their children and
moaned about their ailments. Lollie Hammen, 67, had the table
howling as she told her jokes about ``Olga,'' a blundering but
quaint Scandanavian wife.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, their conversations veered to a more serious subject,
life without husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, 73, a widow for five years, said she has begun to write
her own checks and make travel arrangements, things she always had
left to her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those things that can't be replaced, that's when you
really miss him,'' said Gray. ``But you have to realize that's the
past and you can't dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the women were at different stages of their lives when
their husbands passed away: Hammen was still raising two of her sixchildren when her husband died 16 years ago. Gray was caring for
her husband, who was struggling with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For Inez Lang, the death of her husband Jack took place during
the most promising time in their lives. They married at age 20 and
had four children, but two years ago they moved from the farmhouse
and into a modern house on the north side of Rockwell City. They
turned over most of the farmwork to their oldest son Craig, now 47,
and began traveling. Once they passed by the home of O. J. Simpson
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be enjoying his retirement with me,'' said Lang.
</P>
<P>
   But one summer day in 1998, their life together came to a sudden
end. Although Jack had retired from farming, he and his wife
occasionally helped Craig work 1,100 acres of farmland.
</P>
<P>
   That particular day, Jack laid ground so he and Craig, who is
also the town's postman, could plant beans a few hours later. But
when Craig finally trekked into the fields, he found his father's
lifeless body leaning out the door of his tractor. Jack, like many
of the widows' husbands, had a massive heart attack and died while
farming. ``It was probably a month when they said, `We are going to
Fort Dodge. We think you should come,'' recalled Lang. ``Lttle by
little I started going to dinner, shopping, or maybe a drive.''
</P>
<P>
   The widows, most of them farmer's wives, believe the stress of
making a living on the land eventually got to their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started seeing the trend of them dying in the 1970s,'' said
one widow.
</P>
<P>
   That was a time when farming evolved from a one-man trade into a
complex industry, said Larry Hood, a farmer and county manager.
Grain prices were high while interest rates on loans were low. Like
farmers across the country, Calhoun County men took advantage of
the good times by taking out large loans for equipment. When
interest rates shot through the roof in the early 1980s, many of
those same farmers couldn't pay off their debt.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers' wives did more than help their husbands work the
fields. Lang, for example, worked at the state-owned liquor store
and the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been for these women, most of these men would
have gone down the tubes,'' said Hood.
</P>
<P>
   But not even the widow ladies of Calhoun County can save the
town now, said county officials. They can not draw manufacturing
companies to the tiny community or even save the churches that have
stopped growing.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Michael Sexton, 38, hopes a proposed
corn-processing plant will create jobs and bring the people in his
generation back to their hometown. But the prospect of that
happening seems as grim as the future of the farming industry.
</P>
<P>
   In just 20 years, Calhoun County and surrounding communities are
projected to lose more than 10 percent of their population while
senior citizens will hit 30 percent of the populatiion that is
left, according to Jerry Chizek, county director for the Iowa State
University extension school in Rockwell City.
</P>
<P>
   The population of women 85 and older, who will probably need
financial and medical aid, will be twice that of men the same age.
While Calhoun County has built attractive senior apartments and
created a home health aid program that keeps the elderly in their
own homes, they have not be been able to find a way to keep the
young from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The same problems resulting from growing senior populations are
facing rural communities elsewhere, such as Brown, Kan., and Kiowa,
Okla. By 2030, Census data project there will be an additional 30
million people age 65 and older spread across the country, the
majority of them women.
</P>
<P>
   The Lang farm has been in the family since 1800, but Craig is
Lang's only child to follow the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Craig don't go working yourself to death like your
father did,' '' said Lang. ``He says, `I have girls to put in
college.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On a brisk but sunny afternoon, Lang drove her 1996 blue
Oldsmobile past rows and rows of crops, and her thoughts turned to
a familiar subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darn, it's a nice day,'' said Lang. ``If Jack was here, we
would go riding through the countryside, maybe drive to Des Moines
or Sioux City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
