<HEADLINE>
FLOWERING OF ANCIENT ROME HASN'T FADED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH FOSTER  
 c.2000The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm sure that by now, we've all read enough about the new
millennium. So, I'll look back to Rome, at the turn of that first
year of the Common Era to see what they were doing in their gardens
with design and magical herbs. Gardens were important to them, and
very sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   I think of the Emperor Tiberius, who was almost a recluse on the
Isle of Capri, where the ruins of his once glorious villa still
crown the main hilltop. The tumbled rocks give scant clue into the
glory that once was Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Roman garden style has remained the prototype through
the centuries, through to today. Geometric shapes, balance,
statues, hedges, fountains and columns are very much in vogue
again, though fashion swings back and forth between restrained
classic and rococo baroque.
</P>
<P>
   I shall pay homage to the call of Rome by leaving the tall
20-foot trunks of my dying ash trees as woodland pillars, and
garlanding them with lights, rather than the classic ivy of ancient
Rome. I saw it on a wall painting at the Getty Villa Gardens in
Malibu, Calif. I think it is the best place to get a feeling of the
glory that was Roman gardens. It's better than any restoration I've
ever seen _ even in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Built to mimic an ancient Roman luxury villa excavated at
Heraculanum from under volcanic mud and ash and re-created as it
would have been 2000 years ago, it was the last hobby of J. Paul
Getty.
</P>
<P>
   The central long, rectangular courtyard garden is surrounded
with a colonnade of marble Corinthian columns as was the ancient
style. A long, central pool provides a slash of blue water, which,
in Roman times, may have grown telapia to supply fresh fish for the
epicurean table. Or it may have been a tribute to the Egyptian
goddess, Isis, whose cult was fashionable then.
</P>
<P>
   The garden beds and paths are meticulously geometric, surrounded
with clipped evergreen hedges and lined with trees pruned into
small balls. If you hate shearing your hedges and foundation
plantings three times a year, you can thank the Romans for that.
</P>
<P>
   The exact plants in the Getty gardens are as authentic as
possible from analyzing ancient pictures and carbonized seeds,
fruits, wood and nuts from Italian excavations. Bay, myrtle and
rosemary are the main traditional greenery in the formal central
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtyard is a vegetable, fruit and herb garden, for
medicine, botany, magic and love potions all slept together in the
same Latin bed.
</P>
<P>
   Try basil for baby's ears, or as an aphrodisiac. Oregano was for
dropsy, earaches, convulsionsand coughs and to drive away poisonous
beasts. Bay leaves were for massages, as a narcotic, for religious
trances, and to ward off lightning. The emperor Tiberius always
wore a wreath of bay during storms. The garden contains coriander,
dill, garlic, saffron, sage and thyme. Seems there's not much new
in 2000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to see ancient garden restorations is Pompeii,
Italy, particularly the House of Vetti. Its interior courtyard has
the most remarkable fountain that shoots out streams of water that
exactly hit decorative raised marble stone basins several feet
away. And all this without electric pumps or plastic piping, just
water pressure and gravity. Oh well, it's said that Greece gave us
philosophy and Rome gave us plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during the first millennium, the glory that was Rome died.
By 1000, there were only some sad medieval courtyards. The Dark
Ages refused Rome's gardens and agricultural knowledge, let alone
its plumbing, in a sorry flat world dominated by religious
fanaticism.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are at another millennium. What's going to be our legacy
when people 1,000 years from now look back at us? And while you're
thinking about that, try a little parsley. The Romans ate it on
bread for breakfast or wore it to absorb the fumes of wine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
