<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING EYES TO THE VIRTUES OF NAPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Art of Napping at Work'' isn't what its title might lead
you to imagine. The book's authors, Camille and Bill Anthony,
aren't promoting the idea of sleeping when you're supposed to be
working. ``We want to make it very clear that what we advocate is
napping during break time, not on the job,'' Bill said, from their
home in Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Well yes, of course. Although, let's face it, the distinction
can get a little muddled sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Anthonys believe that workplace napping is an idea whose
time has come. It has yet to catch on with the majority of those
who control the workplaces. Generally speaking, management takes a
dim view of naps. ``Nappism,'' Bill says of their negative
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the old American work ethic,'' Camille said. ``Sleep is
not something we're supposed to need to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course we do need sleep, and study after study indicates
most Americans are not getting enough rest at night. It's not
surprising so many people tend to flag as the day wears on. Also,
sleep researchers believe that human beings have a natural tendency
to fall asleep during the afternoon. The urge to nap may be due to
our circadian rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that short naps of 15 to 20 minutes energize
workers and improve performance and safety. The New York Times
reported Tuesday that employers are slowly beginning to see the
advantages of employee napping, and that some enlightened companies
are even providing nap rooms (``napnasiums'' the Anthonys call
these sleeping spaces) with reclining chairs, blankets, and alarm
clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep expert Dr. James B. Maas of Cornell told Jane E. Brody of
the Times, ``Napping should not be frowned upon at the office or
make you feel guilty at home. It should have the status of daily
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   A workplace napping movement appears to be underway. The
Anthonys have declared Monday, April 3, the day after daylight
saving time begins, National Workplace Napping Day. However, as
their research indicates, the company snooze break has a long way
to go before it wins acceptance. The majority of those who
responded to a workplace napping survey on the Anthonys' Web site
said they feel they must do their napping secretly. Workers said
they feared being fired if caught napping, even if they were on
their own time. They also feared ``napaphobic'' co-workers would
tease them or turn them in. And some would like to nap but feel
guilty about giving in to the urge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nappers find ways and places to nod off for a few minutes
during the day. They nap at their desks, and under them too. They
nap in cars, in closets, in libraries, in lounge areas, in unused
meeting rooms, in bathroom stalls. Those with offices of their own
are at a nap advantage. Bill is the executive director of Boston
University's Center for Psychiatric Rehabilitation. ``Academia in
general is a pretty nap-friendly place,'' he said. ``I tell my
assistant I'll be indisposed for 15 minutes and close the door.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Anthonys don't advocate napping on company time,
there's no doubt people have been sleeping on the job as long as
there have been jobs. One woman who responded to the survey said
she was able to nap during boring meetings and yet remain alert
enough to provide a response, if called upon to do so. The Anthonys
concede the woman has enviable napping skills but point out that
she might not feel the need to doze through meetings if she spent
15 minutes a day napping under her desk.
</P>
<P>
   The Anthonys' next project will address the special napping
needs of women. Those who'd like to contribute to their research
may visit their Web site, www.napping.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
