<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8321 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-06 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONS OF THE IN (TROUBLE) CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; was looking for a birthday gift for a young female friend
when I came across a pretty pink shirt in the junior section of a
major chain store. It had a row of bright glass beads just along
the line where a strapless gown would begin. Above the beads was
pink see-through net.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the color would flatter my friend's coloring. The spandex
in it would hug her slim body. I turned the shirt around and saw
that the back of it was made of the same sheer net. Haley's smooth
young skin would look tantalizing beneath it. The shirt was sexy
and innocent at the same time, and I was sure my friend would love
it. There was only one small problem. She's only 11 years old.
</P>
<P>
   I ended up buying Haley a lovely blue turtleneck sweater
somewhere else. Though the pink shirt was the height of adolescent
fashion, I wasn't about to send a child that age an article of
clothing that falls into a category referred to as ``slutware.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a little joke the fashion industry is having at our
children's expense: Dress the little girls up like prostitutes.
Tart them up in sheer blouses and tight tube tops that lend an
``ironic'' note to their not-yet-womanly figures. Turn them into
little seductresses in off-the-shoulder dresses with simulated bras
or short twirly skirts that expose their underpants. The industry
is well aware that if you copy styles from TV shows that attract
preteen audiences, you can sell the sensuality of older girls to
youngsters with no firsthand knowledge of adult sexual behavior,
then sit back and watch the cash registers ring.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one informs the girls that they're being paraded
around for the titillation of their elders instead of for their own
satisfaction. (``Can you imagine how hot these babes are going to
be in a few years?'') You certainly don't warn them that they're
more likely to be the object of sexual harassment in schools, which
is increasing. (``People like to blame the victim, but you bear no
responsibility.'') Unless these girls have thoughtful parents, no
one is teaching them how to deal with males who assume they're far
more knowledgeable than they are. For a perfect example, see the
movie ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the TV they watch, most young girls remain
frighteningly naive. As I examined that sexy pink top, a 9- or
10-year-old girl nearby was thumbing through the same rack. All I
heard her say to her mother was ``cool,'' ``cute,'' and ``I want
this sooo bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these clothes require makeup _ if not lipstick, at
least lip gloss and glittery skin lotion _ as well as matching
slutshoes that keep an 11-year-old from walking normally. Not far
ahead lie other markers of sophistication, like cigarettes and
beer. Making the girls more vulnerable consumers are the ads that
drive home the point that each of them is already too fat, too
assertive, too awkward, too ugly, or too badly groomed, to hope to
resemble any of the models chosen for their unattainable
perfection, unless . . .
</P>
<P>
   Here, from Jean Kilbourne's book, ``Deadly Persuasion: Why Women
and Girls Must Fight the Addictive Power of Advertising,'' are a
few examples of how girls' serious concerns are converted into a
search for the right product: ``Think for yourself'' (sweater ad),
``Be amazing'' (cosmetics ad), ``Be extraordinary, not ordinary''
(ad for black nail polish), and ``Free yourself,'' (diet product).
Eleven-year-olds, who are supposed to be discovering their talents,
strengthening their bodies, and finding out how bright and
competent they can be, are instead encouraged to head down a
demoralizing dead-end called ``How-Do-I-Look?''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising promotes a debased version of womanhood, one that
pressures young girls into obsessing about their weight, studying
teen magazines instead of mastering a skill, and aspiring to be
sexually attractive at a time when most of them are going through
an awkward stage. For advertisers, of course, this is the good
news. Insecurity, self-doubt, and the adoption of unrealistic
standards of beauty are great for business, especially if shopping
is the remedy.
</P>
<P>
   I pictured how ``cute'' Haley would look in that tight pink top,
and for a moment I too was a captive of cultural conditioning,
accepting as perfectly normal the idea of a sexy child. It was like
operating in a trance that allowed a widespread advertising image
to take the place of the real person I know. Though we're all quick
to say we're immune to advertising, we swim in a sea of similar
images, as unaware of how they affect us as fish in water.
</P>
<P>
   At least this image has lost its power over me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
