<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNDRAFT IS CAUSING FIREPLACE ODOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The first fire in my fireplace last fall was very nice, until
it went out. Then it began to smell, and now it stinks. In the
past, I've had problems with downdrafts, so I closed the damper.
Things were OK for a while, but the smell returned. There is a
cleanout in the fireplace floor and one that opens into the garage.
Would adjusting them help reduce the odor and cure the downdrafts?
</P>
<P>
   LINDA HOLDSTOCK, Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah yes, the classic stinking fireplace, and I agree, it
really reeks. That is because you do, indeed, have a downdraft,
also called a reverse chimney effect; it occurs when the air
pressure outdoors exceeds that indoors, and air whooshes down the
chimney, bringing that burned, wet wood, creosote smell into the
house. Closing the damper does not always work, because it fits
loosely.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning the chimney also does not work.
</P>
<P>
   One cure is to seal the firebox opening so that it is airtight.
This is not easily done, and is inconvenient when you want to make
a fire.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanouts are a clue as to what you can do. Clean them out,
so they contain no ashes, etc. Leave the one on the hearth open
just a bit (an inch or so should do) and the one in the garage
fully open. Open the fireplace damper. And open a window in the
garage as well. This will allow air to come from outdoors into the
garage, into the lower cleanout, out of the upper cleanout, and up
the chimney. If this doesn't work, it beats the heck out of the
handyman, his first stumper for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   When you make a fire, keep the cleanouts open; the fire will
draw better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought Portland Glass windows in 1985. Now they won't stay
up. The double-hung windows (they slide up and down) are heavy
because they are triple glazed. The company is out of business, and
I can't find anyone who can repair them. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   GERTRUDE SPILLER, North Chelmsford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For now, you can hold the windows up with a stick; that is
what everyone did before there were weight-and-spring balances for
windows. And that is what a lot of people do if their windows don't
stay up. It's an old story with replacement windows, it seems. A
company starts out great guns, then goes belly up. There are many
reasons for company failure; one is an inferior product. In your
case the spring balances failed, perhaps because they were not
strong enough or were defective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house has some nice hardwood floors, but they are 12 years
old and in need of some refurbishing, although not necessarily
resanding and refinishing. I'd like to put on one new coat of
varnish. How can I tell whether the old varnish is water- or
oil-based?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BALUNAS, Northborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ordinarily, you would have to have a paint chip analyzed by a
lab, but that is not necessary here. Being 12 years old, the
varnish is probably oil. And, to refurbish, sand the floors with
medium-fine sandpaper by hand or machine (but not necessarily a
floor machine) to roughen the finish and reduce gloss. Then wash
with paint thinner or a strong solution of Spic and Span and water.
No need to rinse. Then apply one coat of an oil-based polyurethane
varnish. Two will be better. Be sure to apply thin coats, with a
brush. The sanding is essential for proper adhesion of the new
coats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The house I just moved into is really big, and brother, it
echoes. Footsteps, conversation, television, stereo, and every
other sound bounces all over the place. How can dampen those
sounds?
</P>
<P>
   JULIE SILK, Danvers, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Dampen the sounds with soft materials: draperies on the
windows, carpets with pads (but not necessarily wall-to-wall),
upholstered furniture. Heavy draperies on windows are good, but
even a gauzy curtain is better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   You are right about the sound bouncing around; it will do that
when sound waves (actually, vibrations) hit a hard object. Soft
objects will absorb the sound. Put art and other decorations on the
walls; this will break up the expanse, making the walls uneven and
thus dissipating the sound waves so they cannot reverberate.
</P>
<P>
   The technique is illustrated by this experiment: Go up in the
attic; if it is heavily insulated on the floor, you will feel a
very close silence; actually a little oppressive. When you talk,
the sound will be dead, because it doesn't go anywhere, nor does it
return to you. You may not be able to achieve that in the living
areas of the house, but the above suggestions, using soft materials
and breaking up the wall expanse, will make the space more
enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   If the ceilings are high, and you can't break up the upper-wall
expanse, try hanging banners from the ceiling; again, these will
absorb the sound waves and prevent echoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
