<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LS BATTLES LINCOLN'S IMAGE WITH STYLE, SPORTINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000   The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think Lincoln and certain stereotypes leap to mind: the Hot Rod
Lincolns of rock 'n' roll; bodies found in the trunks of Lincolns
left at airports; senior citizens riding through retirement in
Lincoln Town Cars.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is probably the most accurate and lingering image,
and it is the image the new Lincoln LS is meant to fight. Lincoln
wants younger buyers. To lure them, it offers the LS, a snappy
four-door sedan that is to high-priced luxury cars what the new
Nissan Maxima is to lower-range cars: a great buy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a luxury car and $12,000-$20,000 means
something to you, try the LS, because that is the difference in
price between the Lincoln and several good luxury cars. The LS is
meant to go head-to-head with the Lexus GS 400, Mercedes Benz E430,
BMW 540i, Jaguar S-type, and Audi A6 4.2. It runs with all of them
and can be had for less than $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   This is no old-style Lincoln. It doesn't drive like a boat,
doesn't occupy the space of two standard cars. I first encountered
it last summer during a one-day preview on Cape Cod, and the
Lincoln folks then touted its ``Teutonic look, Teutonic feel.''
</P>
<P>
   It does look foreign _ German from the side, Japanese front and
rear _ and it shares its platfrom with the Jaguar S-type. It has
many of the best attributes of good foreign cars. But what is
exciting is that this is an American car, a different, sporty
product from a manufacturer that had grown stodgy. The Lincoln
folks acknowledge this when they say focus groups told the
manufacturer they equate Lincoln with luxury, but that the cars
were not relevant to many of them.
</P>
<P>
   What the focus groups were asking for was sportiness, and that's
what Lincoln has delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, its standard leather seats _ split 60/40 at the rear for
trunk access and big loads _ are broad, firm, and comfortable. The
eight-way adjustable driver's seat, coupled with the power-tilt,
telescoping steering wheel gives myriad seating options.
</P>
<P>
   Legroom is ample, though a fifth passenger, seated in the middle
of the rear bench seat, rides an uncomfortable hump while everyone
else settles into wide leather buckets.
</P>
<P>
   It was disappointing to find that, in a car that so obviously
would be wonderful on long trips, interior storage space is
lacking. The glove compartment, already small, loses much space to
the CD changer; other crannies are just too tiny. Where, on long
trips, do you put glasses, maps, atlases, reading materials,
tissues, games for the kids? Your best bet, unfortunately, is the
pouches on the rear of each front seat.
</P>
<P>
   The LS comes with either a V6 or V8 engine, and though I only
drove the V6 for a day last summer, I could tell it's not a big
enough engine for this car if you're looking for sportiness.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.9 liter V8, which I drove for 10 days recently _ at about
18 miles per gallon _ is another story. It's got a hot-rod rumble
to it when you stomp the gas and it powers the LS smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln offers the first standard transmission it has built
since 1951 in the LS _ but only in the V6 edition. That is a shame.
If you're buying the V8 looking for sportiness, chances are you'd
like to have a manual transmission to play with. Can't have it. The
Lincoln guy told me they can't build a transmission that will
handle the V8's torque (267 lb.-ft.). I don't buy that.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting aside, the LS is a powerful, graceful car rolling on
independent suspension front and rear, featuring coil springs,
anti-roll bars, aluminum control arms, and automatic traction
control backing up the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Generating only slight wind noise, it was smooth and swift on
the highway, moving from lane to lane with no sense of lateral
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than riding soft like a boat, it was firm and confident,
whether surging straight ahead or in quick maneuvers. On back
roads, with sharp corners, its stiffness showed its worth as the
car hugged the line through turns even as minimal side forces were
exerted on the driver.
</P>
<P>
   In a braking test (stomp the brakes at 50 miles per hour and
hold them there), its vented discs brought it to a quick, straight
stop, and its suspension, aided by an almost 50-50 split in front
and rear weight distribution, kept nose dive to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln wants to sell to a younger segment of drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln knows that aging baby boomers are fighting the aging
process in many ways and that one of those ways is buying cars that
offer comfort without giving up sportiness.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln figures the way to sell its cars is to appeal to these
boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln figures the LS is the car that will do this.
</P>
<P>
   And with the LS, they will certainly carve out their share of
this market, because this is not your father's Lincoln, not your
grandfather's Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Hot Rod Lincoln with cushy 2000 amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The broad seats. Ample room while at the same time offering
firm, tight support up the sides and down on the thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The use of plastic to look like wood. It's meant to evoke
European luxury of a bygone era but instead has the tackiness of
modern plastic.
</P>
<P>
   --The CD changer in the glove box. Put it in the trunk and free
up the sorely needed interior storage space.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $34,690 &QL; 
Price as tested: $39,105 &QL; 
Horsepower 252 /Torque: 267 lb-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 114.5 inches /193.9 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 73.2 inches/ 57.2 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3,780 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
