<HEADLINE>
A CARLOAD OF HOPES AND WISHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First day of the New Year, and either first day of the new
millennium or first day of the last year of the old millennium,
depending on your point of view.
</P>
<P>
   All of last year's test cars, trucks, and SUVs are tucked away;
the big auto shows loom in Detroit and New York; the auto industry
is in hyperflux with new models arriving ever more rapidly and the
time between introduction and redesign shorter than ever. It is a
time of promise in engineering, alternative power systems, safety
features, technological advance; a time to dream.
</P>
<P>
   So here's hoping:
</P>
<P>
   --That manufacturers of SUVs, who are reaping huge profits by
turning what are basically trucks into family commuter vehicles,
invest some of those profits in better suspension systems to make
SUVs safer. Mercedes, Rover, and BMW, among others, have already
done so (though given the costs of their models, I doubt they cut
back on profit projections), and Ford is moving in that direction
by putting independent rear suspension on its 2001 Explorer. There
is no reason _ other than profit _ that SUVs need to be as unstable
as they are.
</P>
<P>
   --That some dealer, somewhere, will step forward and offer as
part of the purchase program for an SUV a day's driving instruction
in the vehicle. They are perfectly safe when driven properly, but
almost no new buyer knows what properly means.
</P>
<P>
   --That student driver-training programs be required to include
skid pad and emergency training. Moving carefully in highway
traffic, learning to use your turn signal, and learning how to
parallel park are fine but do young drivers no good when trouble
arises. Besides, how many people have been killed in parallel
parking accidents?
</P>
<P>
   --That dealers selling the hot Honda S2000 roadster _ redline
9,000 _ will not continue what I hear to be instances of excessive
gouging, like $10,000 over the suggested price of about $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   --And that the same sort of gouging by Nissan Xterra sellers
does not become pervasive. Reports that some dealers are getting
$30,000 for an SUV meant to appeal to those looking for basic SUV
performance closer to the $20,000 suggested price are disturbing.
This flies in the face of the manufacturer's intent and can only
hurt the model in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   --That voice-activated technology, already used in some luxury
cars for tasks such as making telephone calls, eventually finds its
way into most cars, particularly for controlling tuning and volume
on sound systems. Too many young drivers are killed because they
take their eyes off the road to fiddle with sound systems. A simple
command, ``louder'' or ``104.1'' would replace the
attention-grabbing tasks of dialing and pushing buttons.
</P>
<P>
   --That Chevrolet gets rewarded for its belated move into
heavy-duty competition with Ford's F-Series SuperDuty pickups
(particularly the 4-door models). The 2001 Silverado and 2001 GMC
Sierra look promising. And heavy-duty competition is a good thing _
for manufacturers and for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   --On the flip side, that Ford's 2001 Explorer SportTrac is a
huge success. It's a lightweight combination of SUV and pickup
truck, good for hauling the family and lumber, and meets the needs
of those not looking for a heavy-duty version of the same.
</P>
<P>
   --That Nissan's search for an economic cure to its ills is
successful. At a time when design at many companies got innovative,
Nissan got stagnant and suffered for it. Personnel cutbacks
worldwide have helped stabilize the company, its new Maxima is a
fine car, and its four-door pickup, the Frontier, helped pull it
partway out of the design doldrums. Nissan manufactures a great
engine _ the 222 horsepower V6 _ but needs to expand its lineup for
better recognition. The rebirth of the Nissan Z should help, and so
would a full-size pickup truck, reportedly under study, to compete
with American manufacturers and the Toyota Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   --That readers relax and accept the fact that I will continue to
refer to Revolutions (or Rotations) Per Minute when describing
engines as RPMs. Yes, I know that purists are correct: RsPM would
be the appropriate abbreviation. But the term RPMs is part of our
auto language, just as RBIs is used in baseball. Did you ever try
to pronounce RsPM?
</P>
<P>
   --That Volkswagen, with its ever-expanding product line, does
something about its Eurovan models. Nice engine, but far overpriced
for what the interior offers. (A full review of the Eurovan coming
soon.)
</P>
<P>
   --That Mazda's RX-EVOLV, a 2-plus-2 sports coupe, is as good as
it sounds: RENESIS (Rotary Engine Genesis) engine redlines at near
10 grand, car weighs 2,750 pounds, does 0-60 in under 5 seconds.
Wheeee!
</P>
<P>
   --And speaking of sports cars, that the Jaguar roadster on the
drawing boards, a la BMW Z3 or Honda S2000, makes it to production.
I was never a fan of Jags, but recent experience with their new
models has converted me. They need the roadster in their lineup and
I'm convinced they could build a good one.
</P>
<P>
   --That someday, somewhere, I see a trooper pull over a car on
the highway because the driver was going so slow (55 or 65 in the
passing lane) and impeding the normal flow of traffic. One driver
causing a backup of 50 or more cars is every bit as dangerous as a
driver doing 75, just like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   --That consumer unhappiness with certain luxury SUVs continues.
Manufacturers are gouging when they take a truck, slap an SUV body
on top, add leather and a few gimmicks, and ask $40,000 and $50,000
for vehicles that aren't very quiet, aren't very smooth, and aren't
very good off road. There's a shakeout coming in this market and
that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   --And, finally, that you continue to flood me with mail and
e-mail, some in praise, some in criticism. Communication is a good
thing (except the threat to break my fingers so I can't type), will
help shape this column (except when talking RPMs), and lets me know
what you are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford covers the automotive world for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
