<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORAGE IS WHERE YOU FIND IT, AND MAKE IT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Storage is where you find it. And, once you find it, you have to
make it work, make it into something that will hold whatever you
want to store.
</P>
<P>
   But we're talking mainly about storage space; places to store
the stuff of a lifetime of collecting, saving, squirreling away and
rescuing from the trash collection.
</P>
<P>
   It's great to have storage space, but there is a hazard to it,
too: The more storage space, the more junk you will keep. Call it a
law: Pack Rat's Law, Hotton's Law, (Martha) Stewart's Law.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck; someday one of those pieces of junk might
sell for $40,000. Store the junk for prosperity _ yours.
</P>
<P>
   Good storage space is not the closet floor, where things get
thrown, willy-nilly. Nor is it Fibber McGee's closet, which
exploded every time he opened the door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Organization, too
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Storage space needs organization: bins, drawers, trays, boxes,
shelves, and, sometimes, a container made just for one item. You
can make these yourself as the need arises, or buy them. It is
amazing what you can find that is already made for storage.
</P>
<P>
   Walls are a great storage space. Look how well your art is
stored on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet walls can be used to hang other things from: In the kitchen,
pots and pans hung on Pegboard hooks. To avoid chaos, hang all your
pots and pans or at least those that fit on the designated wall.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange them to get the most on the space. Then paint black
silhouettes of them, where they hang, on the Pegboard; that way you
will know exactly where each pot and pan goes.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't do that, your helpmate will rearrange them, sure as
shootin', then be annoyed by your annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is also a good place to hang your pots and pans from
the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   In other rooms, walls are limited as to what they can carry.
</P>
<P>
   Except for such things as plate rails. A wonderful invention,
sold in short lengths in stores or made by you and me, a plate rail
can go in any room.
</P>
<P>
   Put a slot in your homemade plate rail so plates will not slip
off. Some plate rails are rimless, others have little gallery
fences around them. They all do the same thing: They hold plates
and other small items on the rail, viewable but out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere, in basement and attic and garage and barn, hang
bicycles, garden tools, woodworking tools, and anything else that
is best kept off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you have a big blank wall outdoors, hang tools to
make a bit of garden art: rakes, hoes, spades, shovels, forks, and
cultivators in an artistic arrangement. Nice looking and
accessible. Wipe the metal with a thin coat of oil to prevent rust.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attic and cellar, within reason
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Obvious storage spaces in the house are the attic and the
cellar. An attic is a better place to store most items, especially
clothing and other cloth goods such as blankets and sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Heat in the summer and cold in the winter are not that hard on
clothing and other cloth items, especially if the attic is vented
to today's standards. It's the moisture that is the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Attics are much better than cellars, which tend to be damp and
musty, two death sentences for clothing, cloth, and paper. A cellar
should also be vented, at least in the summer, but as a rule, avoid
storing clothes in a basement. It is just too much of a chore to
fight the dampness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attic knee walls
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another potential storage space is similar to an attic. In Cape
Cod-style houses, in the second-floor rooms, there is usually a low
wall on one or both sides of the room. A sloping ceiling rises from
this wall, called a knee wall, and behind it is a lot of space _
wasted because it is often inaccessible. The higher the knee wall,
the more space there is behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Open this space by cutting through the wall, and put doors
and/or drawers in the wall. Presto: Some pretty good space,
although it may be awkward getting into and out of. This space is
likely to be cold, so you should insulate bins, drawers, and other
storages units you put in there.
</P>
<P>
   How about under the beds? This is wasted space, but is good for
dead storage, things you don't use every day. Actually, you could
build or buy a platform bed with drawers underneath. Or, buy boxes
(big but shallow) that will fit under the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Or, build your own box, with cover and four wheels so you can
pull it out and push it back without too much grunting. Catalog
stores sell wheels for under-bed boxes. A dust ruffle or
deep-draping bedspread will conceal this storage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basement stairs, carefully
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Check the walls along basement stairs; there might be enough
room to put shelves on these walls, to provide room for anything
from detergent boxes to canned goods. If the stairs are wide
enough, the shelves can be 6 to 10 inches deep; otherwise 3 or 4
inches deep might be maximum. But it is still space that otherwise
would not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful using these shelves; stairs can be treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   And, a bare wall may be a good storage area, with a little
imagination, using 1 x 4 boards, which are just 3 1/2 inches deep,
deep enough to hold many of items.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a blank wall in the kitchen, say, and it is an
inside wall, and you cannot put a chair or cabinet in front of it,
consider this: Mount 1 x 4 shelves on the wall; build a border
around it and put a door on it. It will stick out just 3 1/2 inches
and will hold a ton of glassware.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not on the wall, but in it
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, cut into the wall and set the shelves in the cavity.
That way you will have a cabinet flush with the wall. If you cut
into the walls, actually take off the wall plaster or plasterboard,
you could set the shelves between studs, which are 16 inches apart.
Be careful cutting a stud to make a wider set of shelves; this wall
might be a supporting wall, so you cannot do it without special
support. If in doubt, don't try it, or consult an engineer or
architect to tell you whether you can do it or not, and perhaps
tell you how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Another method is to build the shelves, including sides, top,
and bottom, as one unit and slip this into place in the cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential storage area is the space above the kitchen
cabinets. If this space is open, you can store things in it:
baskets, pots and pans, and other items you do not often use. If
the items are attractive, there is no need to put on doors.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, put doors over that space. Or little curtains,
although such little curtains are considered tacky in some circles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Make the space work
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there is space under the stairs, but it is probably
already being used as a broom closet. With some thought, you can
make that space much more efficient by installing a series of bins.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, closets are designed for storage; your only priority
there is to keep them cleaned out and organized for efficient
storage. Drawers and bins are great storage innovations. You can
buy cardboard boxes with lids, of many sizes, for storing in those
bins.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you have a pantry, say a little prayer of thanks.
They are the best of storage spaces, best because you can close the
door.
</P>
<P>
   A pantry provides space for one of the best inventions around,
invented by enterprising do-it-yourselfers, or those desparate to
find decent space for all those big pans and cookie sheets that are
stacked under the range or other totally inconvenient place.
</P>
<P>
   If you have space for a shelf 18 inches high and 18 inches deep,
set up dividers _ plywood or special wire dividers _ so you can
slide those big awkward pans in place, and take them down, easily
and, most important, quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Garages and tool houses are other great potential storage
spaces, but don't bother; they're already full of that junk you're
going to get $40,000 for some day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
