<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-06 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAYING THE PRICE FOR SLAVE LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER   
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If I bought it on sale for $6.95 in the USA, how
much do you suppose the woman who made it in China gets to take
home from the deal?
</P>
<P>
   Two pennies? Five?
</P>
<P>
   To be truthful, I don't know that it was a female who made the
12-inch poly resin Nativity wreath I bought last month in Indiana.
I just decided _ after looking for a long time at the face of the
Baby Jesus and the angels flying over him _ to imagine a woman with
a tiny paintbrush putting in the eyes and lips and shocks of hair.
</P>
<P>
   She is very young in my mind's eye, not yet 18, and I think her
name is Li.
</P>
<P>
   As most of my friends and family know, I almost never buy
anything made in China. In this era of global sweatshopping, it's
close to impossible to purchase completely exploitation-free
imported goods, but I always figure the odds are at their worst
with China.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the kindly, human-rights-loving institutions
known as the Chinese armies own and operate a good number of
manufacturing enterprises. Plus, the ridiculously low prices of
most made-in-China items scream ``labor abuse!''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. A Prada look-alike handbag, for only $20. A pair of real
leather boots with the name of a fine old American shoe company
embossed upon their soles for $35. How can they do that?
</P>
<P>
   How indeed?
</P>
<P>
   But there was something about the 12-inch poly resin Nativity
wreath that would not allow me to read ``Made in China'' and put it
back on the shelf as I usually do.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was because the Baby Jesus' eyes look more Asian than
Occidental. So do the eyes of the little beige sheep that lies in
the fake evergreen on the periphery of the plastic manger.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, I started to see Li, one of thousands who
work in a noisy, toxic-smelling factory that's located, say, on the
east side of the Huangpu River in Shanghai. I saw her head _ the
long black hair hidden under a kind of operating room shower cap _
bent low over a table stacked with partly colored poly resin
wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   The fake evergreen and holly (Does holly grow in Shanghai?), the
brown manger hay, light blue sky and pea-soup green hills of
Bethlehem probably come straight off the assembly line. But the
finer features of the scene _ Mary's golden curls, Joseph's dark
beard, the leather thongs around the shepherd boy's legs _ surely
some human hand has to paint those.
</P>
<P>
   Does Li know the significance of the infant under the lavender
blanket? Did anyone tell her that millions of people kneel in
churches every day and pray to his mother, often begging her to
comfort their aching hearts or cure their own infants of some
terrible illness?
</P>
<P>
   As she paints the little gold crowns on the heads of the three
magi, does Li know or does she wonder what each of them carries in
his box or bottle?
</P>
<P>
   And does she find it curious that a shepherd boy, a baby lamb
cuddled like a big fur collar around his neck, would be included
among kings and angels?
</P>
<P>
   Halfway around the world, in a bustling store in a busy shopping
mall, 12 hours behind Shanghai factory schedules, I could not let
go of the 12-inch poly resin Nativity wreath.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the tremendous odds against it _ China exports
about $62 billion in goods each year to the United States _ I felt
connected to the very human being who had made it.
</P>
<P>
   So, as if it were fashioned of French crystal, I hand-carried
the plastic Holy Family back to California on one of hundreds of
jam-packed jets that, in just one day, carried tens of thousands of
ordinary Americans across their own country or into foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   When I take down my Christmas tree and return my living room to
its mostly secular state, I will carefully wrap the wreath in cloth
and put it away with all my other treasured Christmas decorations
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe by then Li will make as much money a day as it cost me to
buy her poly resin wreath. The marked-down price, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
