<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-MAC-AND-CHEESE-HNS &LR;      01-06 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-AND-CHEESE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THINK OUTSIDE THE BOX FOR A MAC AND CHEESE TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Call it comfort food made easy. Forget the boxed
version; macaroni and cheese can be cooked from scratch, no sweat.
Honest.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not as fast as stirring powdered cheese and butter into
cooked noodles, but it's not that hard either. And it doesn't have
to be that same old boring glop. You can make it plain, Italian
style, Welsh style, or even Mexican style, with a few simple
additions. But first, you have to choose and cook your macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   The classic mac and cheese recipe calls for classic macaroni:
small, arced tubes of pasta called elbows. It's basic, it's cheap
and it's filling. But if you don't have any in your pantry, don't
hesitate to substitute a different kind. Just keep in mind that
pastas with holes or ridges like mostaccioli (bias-cut, ridged
tubes) or radiatore (ruffled spirals) are better for casseroles
than long, thin types. Flavored pastas can also be used in
macaroni-and-cheese recipes. Try a mixture of egg noodles and
tomato pasta in Italian-style macaroni and cheese for an
interesting appearance and unique flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking the pasta is one of the first things you need to do when
making mac and cheese and one of the most important. If you boil
the pasta until it's al dente, it will become too mushy during
baking. A good rule of thumb is to cook pasta only seven minutes if
you'll be cooking it again in a casserole. Drain the pasta and toss
with a bit of olive oil to prevent it from sticking. To save time
on busy weeknights, cook the pasta on the weekend, place in freezer
bags and store in the refrigerator until you are ready to use it
later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the macaroni under control, you can move on to the
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, cheddar cheese is used, but most cheddars don't
melt smoothly on their own. So, people do one of two things: They
eat chunky macaroni and cheese, or they make a white sauce to help
the cheese melt into a smooth consistency. Both styles are popular,
but a smooth, saucy, mac and cheese seems to be the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   If you consider macaroni and cheese to be dull food for children
who only eat things that are white or yellow, jazz it up with a few
additional ingredients. Italian-style macaroni and cheese uses
oregano and tomatoes to give the casserole punch. Even easier, use
a flavored cheddar to liven up the dish. Cabot of Vermont makes
cheddar cheeses in jalapeno, habanero, salsa, Mediterranean and a
variety other flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best thing about macaroni and cheese is that it
doesn't have to be relegated to a side dish. Serve it with a green
salad and you have a meal.
</P>
<P>
   This very simple version, from ``James Beard's American
Cookery'' (Galahad Books, 1972), can easily be altered by
substituting a flavored cheese such as Cabot's Jalapeno cheddar for
the sharp cheddar and tomato pasta for the macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   MACARONI AND CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound macaroni
</P>
<P>
   8 to 10 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups sharp cheddar cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   Cook the macaroni in boiling, salted water until just tender. Be
careful not to overcook it. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 2-quart baking dish and arrange in it, alternating
layers of macaroni, dotted with butter and shredded cheese. Season
with salt and pepper and top with a layer of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees until the cheese is melted and the macaroni
is heated through.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ITALIAN-STYLE MACARONI AND CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound macaroni
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cheddar cheese, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 (20-ounce) can peeled tomatoes, with juice, cut up
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Cook macaroni in rapidly boiling water for 7 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a 2-quart casserole with cooking spray. Combine macaroni,
tomatoes with juice and cheese in prepared casserole. Sprinkle top
with oregano, dot with butter and then sprinkle with Parmesan
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for 45 minutes to 1 hour or until cheese is
melted and top is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Albany Collection: Treasures and Treasured
Recipes,'' compiled by the Women's Council of the Albany Institute
of History and Art (1997)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   MACARONI AND CHEESE, WELSH STYLE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 8 servings)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon prepared brown mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 pound uncooked macaroni
</P>
<P>
   10 to 12 ounces shredded sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a double boiler, melt 2 tablespoons of the butter over hot
water. Stir in the flour, making a paste. Stir in milk, a little at
a time. Stirring constantly, bring just below boiling and cook for
2 minutes. Stir in mustard and Worcestershire sauce. Remove from
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the macaroni in boiling water until just tender. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 2-quart casserole and rub with garlic. Starting with
the white sauce, alternate the sauce, pasta and cheese. Combine the
bread crumbs and romano cheese and top casserole with mixture. Dot
with 2 tablespoons butter.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 400 degrees for 45 minutes or until brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``Cook's Healthy Handbook,`` by Karen Eich
Drummond, Joseph F. Vastano and Josephine C. Vastano (John Wiley &AMP;
Sons) as reprinted in Redbook Magazine
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   LOW-FAT MACARONI AND CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound elbow macaroni
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/3 cups skim milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brown mustard
</P>
<P>
   Dash cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound low-fat sharp cheddar cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated yellow cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Boil macaroni until tender; drain and
rinse under cold running water.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1-quart saucepan, melt margarine over medium heat. Add
flour and cook, 1 to 2 minutes, stirring frequently. Gradually add
2 cups milk, stirring constantly. Add lemon juice and pepper and
stir until mixture thickens. Remove from stove, and discard 1/4 cup
of the sauce. While the mixture is still hot, toss with macaroni,
mustard, cayenne, low-fat cheese, 1/3 cup milk, Parmesan and
Romano. Spoon into a casserole and bake for 10 minutes. Top with
yellow cheddar and bake for another 15 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
