<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-SELENA-BROADWAY-HNS &LR;      01-06 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELENA-BROADWAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXANS NAMED TO CAST OF `SELENA' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAMIRO BURR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Two Texas women have been chosen for the cast of
``Selena Forever,`` a Broadway-bound musical based on the life of
the slain Tejano music superstar.
</P>
<P>
   The play is to premiere here March 21. A 30-city tour will
follow before the play debuts on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Valadez, a 21-year-old who sang backup for the 1998
Janet Jackson tour, will be one of two actresses to play Selena.
Veronica Vasquez, a 24-year-old New York-based Latin/R&AMP;B singer,
will alternate in the role with Valadez. Both women are from San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Ybarra, 19, a theater major at St. Philip's College in San
Antonio, will play the part of Selena's sister, Suzette. And
11-year-old Denise Stefanie Gonzalez of Los Angeles, described as a
``wunderkind`` by producers, will play the role of Selena as a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Director Bill Virchis said producers chose two actresses to play
the adult Selena because of the part's physical demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be one of the most demanding plays ever,`` Virchis
said. ``The young lady will have to sing 14, 15 songs a night, up
to seven or eight times a week. It's unheard of. I worry about how
that instrument will maintain, especially for people without
theater experience.``
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers, I would have cast four Selenas,`` he
said. ``We may still do that.``
</P>
<P>
   Valadez is thrilled about being chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels fantastic to be a part of this,`` she said from her
San Antonio home. ``I have been practicing and working out, waiting
to get started. I feel good about the singing and the dancing
(required for the role), but the acting is new to me.``
</P>
<P>
   Rehearsals begin in three weeks at the Edgewood Academy of
Communications and Fine Arts, whose students will get an
opportunity to see the play in production.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million musical will have a cast of 30 to 35 people who
already have been chosen. The play is scheduled to open at San
Antonio Municipal Auditorium for eight performances over six days,
coinciding with the fifth anniversary of Selena's death, March 31,
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The first leg of the tour will include Dallas, McAllen, El Paso,
Houston and Corpus Christi, in that order, with additional cities
to be added later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That leaves us about eight weeks for rehearsals, which is not
much for an original musical, especially one that is not fully
developed, but we have a wonderful score,`` Virchis said, adding
that there still is much to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be honest. I never have been comfortable in any
production. I am the kind of guy who is always looking for
perfection. It is very simple. Some people think of this
(production) as a finished process, while I always think of it as
an ongoing process.``
</P>
<P>
   Edgewood officials are looking forward to rehearsals. Academy
spokesman Terry Lowry said producers will grant students access to
rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unprecedented in the district, to have Broadway and
New York professionals to work with our kids on a collaboration
basis, and a win-win situation for the whole Edgewood community,``
Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   The producers are incorporating as much of the original Selena
wardrobe as possible, said Robert Trevino, vice president of
Promotional Management Group, which is handling marketing and
national tour sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Replicas of the now-famous purple suit that Selena wore at the
Houston Rodeo will be part of the costuming. One of Selena's
original seamstresses, Julie Ramirez, has worked closely with
producers.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino said a soundtrack of the show also is in the works with
EMI Latin, Selena's record label. Southwest Airlines has signed on
as a national tour sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino also is negotiating with Coca-Cola, which sponsored
Selena's concert tours.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of the show are Jerry Frankel, Michel Vega, Peter
Fitzgerald, Forbes Candlish and Thomas J. Quinn, whose collective
Broadway credits include ``Death of a Salesman,`` ``You're a Good
Man, Charlie Brown,`` ``The Wiz,`` ``Jekyl &AMP; Hyde,`` ``Capeman,``
``Victor, Victoria`` and the Gershwin review, ``Fascinating
Rhythm.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
