<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIORAMAS (New York) _ The painted backgrounds of the dioramas
at the American Museum of Natural History have a curious place in
the hearts of almost everyone who has grown up in New York City
during the last century. They are some of the most elaborate
landscape paintings in the city and some of the most frequently
viewed pictures anywhere, but almost nobody knows who did them or,
in a sense, even seems to notice them when they're staring straight
at them. Are they art? Of course. Moreover, diorama painting is a
dying art, dioramas being relics from the days when verisimilitude
was a necessary skill among painters, and artists were the ones who
provided the world with pictures from abroad. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-DANCE (New York) _ Dance is upfront on Broadway this
season, very possibly because dance expresses what words cannot. Or
as Isadora Duncan put it, ``If I could write it, I wouldn't need to
dance it.'' More than ever, the all-dance show has virtually become
reality. From ``Swing!'' to ``Tango Argentino,'' by way of
``Fosse'' and ``Contact,'' so-called dance-driven shows are posing
a challenge to the conventional musical. Current revivals that
integrate song, dance and plot (``Kiss Me, Kate'' and ``Annie Get
Your Gun'') and their not-so-integrated new counterparts
(``Footloose'' and ``Saturday Night Fever'') also make room for
dance. Add the naturalness with which dancing weaves through the
parlor setting of ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' and the dance
aficionado can count the ways in which show business acquired new
meaning in 1999. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   NH-MEETING-CANDIDATES (Dover, N.H.) _ There are many idealized
notions about American presidential politics, and they start in the
state of New Hampshire. Here, by popular conception, is where the
race for president begins, the place with the first-in-the-nation
primary, where the candidates are methodically questioned by
informed citizens whose decisions guide a nation. And here, most of
all, is the last remaining spot in the nation where a regular
citizen can shake hands and converse with someone who might very
well be the next president of the United States. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRITICS-AWARDS (New York) _ Which turn-of-the-year movie
horse race do you follow? The one at the box office? Or the
stampede of critical 10-best lists that nudges prestigious films
toward Academy Award consideration? A year ago when ``Saving
Private Ryan'' won many critics' polls and did slam-dunk business,
it looked as if Hollywood was gearing up to steal back some of the
critical thunder that has increasingly accrued to independent
films. But this year, the tables have turned again. On Sunday
evening when the New York Film Critics Circle distributes its
annual awards, mainstream Hollywood will be given a mostly frigid
shoulder. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERSTOOD-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``If You Only Understood'':
