<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-ADOPTED-KIDS-LIFEBEAT     01-06 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTED-KIDS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY CONNECTIONS: PARENTS, CHILDREN, AND ADOPTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a 250-word sidebar) 
 By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 Laura Taxel 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of my three children are twins, so it's not uncommon for
people to mention the fact that they look decidedly alike.
Photographs reveal that they're also the spitting image of their
dad when he was a boy. My oldest son and I both have the same head
of naturally curly hair, and there's no question that his nose is a
duplicate of my father's. These resemblances are affirmations of
our family connections and we take them for granted.
</P>
<P>
   In the language of The National Adoption Center, my husband and
I have a ''homemade'' family: these are our biological children,
and there's nothing remarkable about our physical similarities. But
every year, more than 65,000 children are adopted, and for the
estimated 1.5 million American families created in this way, it's a
different story.
</P>
<P>
   ''People ask questions about Murray that they probably wouldn't
if he looked more like us,'' says Sharon Arons, mother of a
3-year-old Mexican-born child that she and her husband Herbie
adopted as an infant. They say ''Is he yours?,'' ''Are you his
mother?,'' and ''Where were his real parents from?'' I worry about
how those words will affect him when's old enough to understand
what they mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Other adoptive parents tell of similar experiences. It's not
unusual for strangers to ask, they say, ''How much did you have to
pay for your child?,'' ''Couldn't you have children of your own?,''
or ''Are your kids really siblings?'' Questions like this, more
frequent for families who have adopted children from countries or
cultures different from their own, can hurt. Handling the feelings
they provoke is part of the unique challenge of being an adoptive
parent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Adoption is not a one time legal event, but a lifelong process
for all involved,'' says Karen Rosenberg, LISW, of Cleveland.
Roseberg, a clinical social worker who specializes in counseling
members of adoptive triads (birth parents, adoptive parents, and
adoptees), adds, ''It's important not to overemphasize the
differences between adoptive families and others, but it's
essential not to deny those differences either, to acknowledge and
talk about them. Something as simple as a visit to the pediatrician
can be traumatic if parents have no medical history for their
child. This lack of what we call a genetic road map is painful and
the family will have to confront it again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most ordinary family occasions, Rosenberg points out,
can evoke complex emotions; birthday celebrations, for example, may
be bittersweet, reminding couples who are infertile of the
biological babies they couldn't have, and adopted children of birth
parents who gave them away.
</P>
<P>
   So while the job description for moms and dads of adopted
children reads much like the one for parents in general, there's no
denying that a family made by adoption also faces some special
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our day-to-day problems are the same as any family would
have,'' says Natalie Ross Norris, mother of four children ranging
in age from 15 months to 7 years old. ''But our two oldest children
are adopted. And so every problem, every event has other
dimensions. ''
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was pregnant, the kids asked all the typical 'where do
babies come from' questions,'' says Norris, who lives in Shaker
Heights, Ohio. ''Explaining that their brother or sister was
growing inside my body became a time to talk about the fact that
they did not. They already knew this because we're open about their
adoption and the reality that they had other birth parents. But my
daughter had never really understood before that, as she put it,
'she grew in a stranger's tummy' and it made her very sad for a
while. We had to deal with more than just the usual reactions that
accompany a new baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norris's adopted children are biracial, making them a
transracial family. Those who adopt children of another race or
culture must think about how to help a child maintain a connection
to their birth heritage, as well as assure that they do not feel
isolated and alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Arons intentionally make their home in a culturally diverse
neighborhood of Boston where Murray is surrounded by people of
every race, including Hispanics. ''We chose to live here, so Murray
could see himself reflected in his community,'' says Sharon. ''We
didn't want him to feel like a minority.''
</P>
<P>
   But most children, at one time or another, see themselves as the
odd man out and struggle with feelings of alienation. Like
nighttime fears and separation anxieties, these experiences
naturally arise as children develop and mature. Adoptive parents
must constantly try to figure out whether behaviors are related to
a child's adoptive status or just something all kids go through.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I look at Alexandra I don't see an adopted child,'' says
Chris Seibert, of Brecksville, Ohio, a volunteer with the Adoptive
Family Support Association and herself an adoptee. ''I don't see a
Korean child. I see my 5-year-old daughter. All children have
problems as they grow up and all families have issues. Every parent
wonders about how to handle these things. Adoption is one factor in
our lives, so it's something we talk about, a fact we consider. But
it's important not too make too much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband Ernie and don't want to burden ourselves or our
child with adoption baggage. We try to listen well, be aware and
sensitive, and ask plenty of questions to find out what's really
going on. I don't think that being adopted is an issue for
Alexandra now. But I know that can change.''
</P>
<P>
   Most adoptive parents confess that they harbor some deep-seated
concerns and unspoken fears. What biological inheritance does their
child come to them with, what inborn personality traits? Will their
child ultimately seek out birth parents and reject those who raised
them?
</P>
<P>
   As children grow older, it's all too easy to see the search for
identity and independence that all adolescents embark on as related
to adoption, and it can be traumatic for parents. Children, too,
are likely to have anxieties they can't articulate such as the
worry that they'll be given away again if they are bad, or that
people from their past will come and take them away.
</P>
<P>
   These can be overwhelmingly difficult subjects to discuss. But
this doesn't mean that adoption should be a taboo subject, either
within the family or outside it. Research has shown that families
fare better when they can talk openly and comfortably about all
aspects of the adoption experience. The more at ease parents are,
the easier it is for their children, relatives, friends, and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Silence is an adoptive family's worst enemy,'' says Beth
Brindo, of Lake County, Ohio. Brindo is the mother of two adopted
children and an adoption specialist with a county social service
agency. ''There are universal issues that virtually all adoptees
and the families that raise them experience and they must be worked
through,'' she says. ''Children will have questions about who their
biological parents were. Nurturing parents inevitably find that
threatening. They fear losing their child's love.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when adoptive families invest a great deal of time and
effort in exploring their feelings and coming to terms with facts
that defy simple answers and endings, they must deal with the
attitudes of others. And that may be the hardest task of all.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a typical war of words, a child taunted my daughter by
saying, 'Well, at least I'm not adopted,' says Karen Seavers,
Westlake, Ohio, the mother of two adopted girls aged 9 1/2 and 11.
''She used the term to wound her. Like the rest of the world, that
little girl thinks of adoption as a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband and I have taught our girls that adoption is a
wonderful and perfectly normal way to make a family, but
unfortunately not everyone understands that. There's nothing second
best about adoption. John and I came to parenting by a different
route but it's a joyful difference, and we are a real family just
like any other.''
</P>
<P>
   Side Bar:
</P>
<P>
   ''I encourage people to read a lot about the adoption
experience,'' says Karen Seavers, who teaches classes for parents
raising adopted children. ''They need to educate themselves and
they will, inevitably, have to educate others. I had to become an
adoption advocate in my daughter's school, because the students
were told to make family trees, but the project wasn't designed to
include a nontraditional family like ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Books offer helpful information about how to create family
circle diagrams that include biological as well as adoptive
parents; rituals like a homecoming celebration which commemorates
the day an adopted child joined the family; and suggestions for how
to make life books for an adopted child that contain all the
information available about their background and the story of their
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   To get a free catalog listing more than 180 books available by
mail about adoption, call Tapestry Books 1-800-765-2367 The
following are among the most highly recommended: For Children:
''The Mulberry Bird: Story of an Adoption'' by Anne Brodzinsky.
''Tell Me a Real Adoption Story'' by Betty Jean Lifton. For
Parents: ''Raising Adopted Children: A Manual for Adoptive
Parents'' by Lois Ruskai Melina. ''Talking With Young Children
About Adoption'' by Mary Watkins and Susan Fisher. ''The Whole Life
Adoption Book'' by Jayne Schooler
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Taxel is an Ohio-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL;
</P>
