<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PATAKI-TEACHERS-HNS &LR;      01-06 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-TEACHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PATAKI FOCUSES ON EDUCATION IN ANNUAL GOAL-SETTING SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAMES M. ODATO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a State of the State address laden with
education initiatives, Gov. George Pataki said that 50,000 new
teachers could be lured to work in New York's neediest schools by
offering free public university tuition and discounts at private
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this program, we can ensure that every school has the
best possible teachers, so every child gets the best possible
education,'' the Republican governor declared, referring to a
package he labeled ``Schools 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki appeared at ease and confident _ an improved public
speaker, using a tight set of points _ during his seamless
62-minute speech on Wednesday. His remarks opening the 223rd
session of the New York state Legislature came as thousands of
state workers outside the Capitol protested their lack of a
contract in one of the biggest planned anti-Pataki rallies ever.
</P>
<P>
   Before a joint legislative session, the governor presented a
vision of schools where the curriculum both challenges and teaches
values to youngsters, and a state where economic growth extends
upstate.
</P>
<P>
   He also targeted environmental programs that would clean more
toxic waste sites, protect more open space and promote greater use
of clean-fuel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Although he sent scant details about his more important policy
address _ the 2000-2001 budget he is expected to deliver early next
week _ the governor's sixth kickoff speech for a legislative
session indicated he will require millions of dollars to help build
up New York's teaching ranks. And he will be forgoing up to $700
million a year in revenues if he is successful in creating new tax
incentives for companies that expand in upstate urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's abolish the gross receipts tax,'' he said, drawing
perhaps the heaviest applause of the day for a plan he had floated
earlier to repeal the 4-cent surcharge on every dollar spent on
electricity in the state. Noting the enthusiastic response, Pataki
strayed from his prepared remarks to add: ``I think we'll even get
that through this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, R-Brunswick, hailed Pataki
for providing ``one of his best'' annual addresses. He said he was
``very, very pleased'' it included plans to promote high-tech job
development and repeal the gross receipts tax.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, D-Manhattan, said a repeal of
the tax is only a fraction of the cost-cutting needed to make New
York's energy rates more competitive since they are 60 percent
greater than the national average. He said he would push for a
comprehensive energy bill.
</P>
<P>
   Silver conceded he heard many things to cheer in the speech _
particularly the push to add more teachers. He lamented the
omission of items he was hoping for:
</P>
<P>
   a commitment to universal pre-kindergarten programs for all
4-year-olds, and reduced class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has taken a big, giant step today from some of
the things that have been espoused by the radical right,'' Silver
said Wednesday. ``The governor has finally heard the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Several government reform advocates, including Comptroller H.
Carl McCall, criticized Pataki for not mentioning changes in
lobbying or campaign finance laws, nor ways to change New York's
budget process and reliance on debt financing.
</P>
<P>
   Key education initiatives from the governor focus on building up
the teaching ranks by 50,000 in the next decade with
$3,400-per-year scholarships to 5,000 teachers annually. Those who
commit to teacher-poor areas would be eligible. Pataki also would
provide:
</P>
<P>
   _ Temporary licenses in lieu of teacher certificates and $2,000
vouchers to help licensees afford course work.
</P>
<P>
   _ New internship programs in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ A five-year window to achieve required master's degrees, down
from the two-year requirement desired by Regents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many of our children are victims of the most insidious
enemy of excellence _ low expectations,'' he said. ``We must
refocus their sights ... on academic excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner Richard Mills and Regents Chancellor Carl
Hayden said they were thrilled with the education components. ``I
heard it as a persuasive recruiting message for new teachers,''
Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Some education advocates criticized Pataki's proposed cap on
school budget growth. Others opposed his alternatives to teacher
certification.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``not only worrisome, but unrealistic,'' the New York State
United Teachers said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also set a goal of ``restoring character'' by removing
disruptive students from classrooms while creating a curriculum
that promotes values of ``common decency, compassion, tolerance and
good citizenship.'' The proposals come after Lt. Gov. Mary
Donohue's statewide tour of schools to examine causes of school
violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
