<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-SWAPPING-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SWAPPING SAVES VACATION DOLLARS
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color graphic that integrates two photos) 
 By GENO LAWRENZI 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture yourself in Tahiti with a tropical breeze blowing off
the South Pacific and the smell of flowers filling your senses. You
turn to your spouse and the two of you exchange smiles. You did the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Florida, a Tahitian couple will be spending the next few
weeks in your waterfront home. They'll drive your car, eat the food
in your refrigerator and drink the bottle of wine you have
graciously left them. In exchange, you and your spouse will be
spending a few weeks in their Papeete, Tahiti, home. Driving their
car. Raiding their refrigerator. And drinking the rum they left for
the two of you to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of a growing national trend in vacation
accommodations. Home-swapping can save money, result in unique
lodging and make visitors feel a part of their host's community.
That's the experience of two couples from Marco Island, Fla., who
have exchanged their homes with other couples around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy and Trevor Pickering were born in Manchester, England, but
have lived in the United States for 32 years. Trevor was a chemical
engineer with Dow Chemical in Williamsburg, Va., before the couple
retired five years ago and moved to Marco Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''We heard about the house exchange program from friends in
Williamsburg,'' said Pickering. ''People liked it because it was an
inexpensive way to vacation abroad. It's also more relaxed and a
great way to enjoy the cultural values of the country you are
visiting. Most tourists don't get that feeling staying in a
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pickerings have traveled to England three times under the
program. They have also visited Spain, Vancouver, Arizona,
Australia, New Zealand and Holland. They say most of their
experiences were incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only bad experience we had was in Australia,'' said Kathy
Pickering. ''The house simply wasn't the way the owners described
it. The location, a Sydney suburb, was fantastic, but the house
wasn't up to par, and we were disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Their waterfront home on Marco Island has three bedrooms, two
baths and a pool. Any couple that swaps homes with the Pickerings
has access to everything except the Pickering's 23-foot Bayliner
boat, their jet ski and Pickering's red MGB. ''Nobody drives that
car but Trevor,'' said his spouse firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Pickerings inspired neighbors Grant and Judy
Appel to try a house exchange. ''We've gone to Portugal, Spain,
Italy, England, Scotland and Morocco,'' said Judy Appel. ''We
really enjoyed Portugal. Grant and I lived in a medieval village in
a house that was built in the 1800s. The place was called Castle
Hill. When we arrived in Morocco, a festival was going on and you
could smell the sardines outside the door. It was absolutely
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to Cornwall, England, the Appels stayed with the
homeowners, who took the couple to visit friends and even showed
them sunken treasures from the wreckage of a British ship. ''There
were 30 cannons taken from the ship that were being stored in a
warehouse, along with a lot of silver,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, they were the only guests in Comlondon
Castle in southern Scotland. The castle's features included a
dungeon and a four-poster bed that was so high off the floor they
had to climb to get into it.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Pickerings and the Appels give enthusiastic
recommendations to house exchanges. ''The only exception is that if
you're concerned about people living in your house and using your
things, this probably is not for you,'' said Kathy Pickering. ''If
you happen to own two homes or condos, you, of course, have a lot
more flexibility, and you can be much more selective with whom you
exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland and New Zealand were the Pickerings' favorite swaps, and
the Appels liked Majorca, because they could see the king's summer
palace from their penthouse on the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, HomeLink International and Intervac U.S., are in
the business of helping home swappers find each other. HomeLink
publishes a directory with thousands of listings, most of which
include photographs of the homes and descriptions of their
amenities. Intervac also offers a catalog and has a membership
system.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the companies, contact Homelink at P.O.
Box 650, Key West, Fla., 1-800-638-3841; and Intervac U.S. at
1-800-756-4663 or www.intervac.com. Intervac recommends that
house-exchange couples leave a casserole or similar meal in the
refrigerator for their guests ''since they will be tired from their
flight. A bottle of wine would also be very nice.'' The company
also recommends leaving staple foods in the home ''to get your
partners started,'' along with a list of places to shop,
restaurants, grocery stores and information on auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Both Homelink and Intervac give each house-exchange couple a
form to fill out to let the companies know if their experience was
(a) Unacceptable; (b) Disappointing; (c) Satisfactory; (d) Good; or
(e) Ideal. The companies want to know whether the swap couple were
accurate in the way they represented the house. Was it clean and
tidy, were there adequate clean sheets and towels? How well did
your exchange partner look after your home and belongings? Would
you recommend home exchange to a friend? And so on.
</P>
<P>
   The list of home locations changes so that some destinations _
Tahiti, for instance _ may not always be available.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pickerings and the Appels, the hardest part
about setting up a house exchange is communicating with the other
homeowners, who often don't speak English. ''We recommend e-mail,
faxes or writing _ no phone calls,'' said Judy Appel. ''It takes
time to do the job right. But what's wonderful is that you build up
a friendship and relationship with the other owners that can serve
you well in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   What do the Pickerings look for when they're making a decision
on where next to go? ''No kids, no pets and no smoking,'' Kathy
Pickering said. ''And four to six weeks. We have plenty of time,
and we like to take our time enjoying a new place.'' In December,
the Appels are planning a trip around the world. They expect it to
last around a year and _ yes _ they will do house exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fun, it's relaxing and,'' says Judy Appel, ''it works.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Geno Lawrenzi writes for the Marco Island (Fla.) Eagle.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
