<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8415 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-WINTER-WAR-LIFEBEAT-A     01-06 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-WAR-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGING WAR IN WINTER TAKES PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photo of a Marine in winter gear) 
 By JAY ATKINSON 
 c.1999 Jay Atkinson 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A waxing moon has risen, silvering the evergreens and alders and
throwing their ragged shadows across the road. Dug in beneath the
snow-laden branches of a pine tree, Lance Cpl. Jason Legere and
Pfc. Eric Little of the U.S. Marine Corps look down from their
vantage point on Poplar Ridge across an old logging road that
glitters in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature is well below zero, and Alpha Company has
bivouacked for the night in the woods near Rangeley, Maine. Huddled
in his snow parka, an M-16 rifle at his side, Legere silently
watches the road while deeper in the gun hole, Little squats by a
tiny cookstove, heating a canteen of water.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cpl. David DeSantis forms up a patrol of nine Marines
on cross-country skis. Dressed in white parkas and toting automatic
weapons, the patrol sets out, their skis scraping against the icy
road. Their mission is to sweep the area west of headquarters,
keeping watch for enemy observers and infiltrators. For the next
two days, the Marines of Alpha Company, a reserve unit based in
Topsham, Maine, will carry out a number of such maneuvers, risking
hypothermia, dehydration and getting lost in the nearly trackless
military preserve beyond Saddleback Mountain, 20 miles from the
Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one thing to survive out here, it's another to shoot,
move and communicate,'' says Maj. Ron Martin, Alpha Company's
commander.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Marine Corps Mountain Warfare school, Martin's
idea of recreation is ice climbing on New Hampshire's Mount
Washington. ''One way to look at this is, try getting a hundred
civilians to do what we're doing,'' he says. ''From showing up, and
being ready to go, to bringing all the right gear and following
orders _ then you can see it has much more to do with esprit de
corps than experience.''
</P>
<P>
   New Englanders have served as winter soldiers for centuries.
Only a few miles east of Alpha Company's position, Benedict Arnold
and his ragtag American Army passed by in the winter of 1775 on
their doomed march to Quebec. Beset by terrible weather and forced
to portage their heavy wooden boats across long stretches of frozen
wilderness, Arnold's command was reduced from 1,100 to less than
700 men by the arduous 350-mile trip. Then, in a blizzard on New
Year's Eve, Arnold's men made a desperate assault on the walls of
the fortified city. Arnold was wounded in the first minutes of the
battle and the Americans were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Shivering in these same Maine woods, DeSantis of Alpha Company
is neither consoled nor burdened by history. ''I just try to make
sure nobody gets frostbite,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a frigid, restless night, bottoming out at -10 degrees
Fahrenheit. Reveille comes at 0500, and Alpha Company breaks camp
in the dark. Soon the sun begins its low arc across the horizon,
and it's a brilliant morning, the snow shining in the hollows and
the Marines sweating in their field jackets even though it's only 1
degree Fahrenheit. Maj. Rob Sammel, a reservist who will conduct
the exercise, stands in the road surrounded by his platoon leaders.
On a topographical map, Sammel indicates the terrain that must be
defended, marking the likely points of engagement with a grease
pencil.
</P>
<P>
   The mission today is a ''defend and delay'' exercise, aimed at
slowing down an enemy advance. The polar conditions and
inexperience of some reservists all add to the difficulty, but the
biggest problem the Marines face is that they're ''used to
aggressive attacks,'' says Sammel, a trim, bespectacled man.
''Defense is a lot more complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive Officer Capt. Ken LeMoult's ''enemy'' force is several
Marines and an armored truck. Their objective is to travel six
kilometers along the valley floor as swiftly as possible. Alpha
Company must intercept and harass them with M-16s, machine guns,
grenade launchers, and a trio of 60-millimeter mortars. Having
flesh and blood opposition ''adds realism and intensity to the
scenario,'' says LeMoult.
</P>
<P>
   On skis or snowshoes, the defending Marines are entirely in
white camouflage. Second Platoon, led by Staff Sgt. Bill Jones,
sets up an ambush approximately two kilometers down the road. After
placing an observation team a short distance away, Jones and 19
Marines kneel in the dry windless cold, waiting for contact.
</P>
<P>
   The chill is like needles against the skin, and Jones is
concerned that his Marines stay watchful and silent. From across
the road, he hears voices carrying in the morning air. Jones is
furious, rising out of his gun hole to signal the Marines in the
observation post to pipe down. But the noise only grows louder.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Jones scrambles from his cover and scuttles on all
fours to the edge of the road. ''Shut the hell up over there,'' he
says in a stage whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the major,'' a voice calls back.
</P>
<P>
   Jones crawls back to his position as the other Marines grin at
each other. ''A rare moment of levity,'' one of them whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Cpl. Patrick Burke crouches in the snow. An energetic
Marine, Burke has been selected by Sammel to guide Second Platoon
back through their passage point. In pantomime, Burke tells one
glassy-eyed lance corporal to sit on his daypack to prevent direct
contact with the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Under such frosty conditions, inexperienced Marines ''tend to
draw into a shell,'' says Burke. '''Cocooning' is the first sign of
hypothermia, so I get them talking to gauge their responses.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Jones tenses in the snow. An enemy vehicle is moving
slowly up the road, shielding an unknown number of infantry. The
men of Second Platoon ready their weapons, but Jones gives a hand
signal to hold fire. His Marines are bunched forward, and Jones
realizes that an enemy element could be sneaking toward them
through the trees. Quickly directing four Marines to guard his
flank, Jones whispers over his radio that the enemy is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The firefight is swift and noisy. The first blank shots from an
M-16 whine and then snap in echo against the snow-padded hillsides.
Within seconds, more than a dozen weapons are chattering back and
forth. Just as Jones anticipated, an enemy patrol attacks his
position from the south. With the acrid smell of gunpowder
lingering in the air, Jones orders his Marines to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing their skis and weapons, the Marines hurry through the
underbrush while one squad remains behind in an attempt to further
delay the enemy. It's the same tactic used by Allied troops during
the Battle of the Bulge, says Capt. Garrett Hubbard of Weapons
Platoon. To slow the German advance, some units fought and died in
place, allowing others to move back and set up new defensive
positions. ''We lost a lot of men, but the Germans never
recovered,'' Captain Hubbard says.
</P>
<P>
   This grim remembrance underscores the fact that war games are
preparation for war. Even in the snowfields at Rangeley, the
Marines are playing for keeps.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from his concealment, Sammel watches the Second Platoon
ski into the trees, noting that the location chosen by Jones for an
ambush did not offer a clear view of the enemy. ''There are some
things we went over that just didn't happen,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is Maine, not Korea or the Balkans or some winter
conflict area not yet emerged, they'll get another chance to make
it perfect. Tonight they'll all return to homebase with no injuries
and no casualties, maybe not even a case of frostbite.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jay Atkinson is a Massachussetts-based writer and journalism
professor.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
