<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TURTLE-LADY-HNS &LR;      01-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURTLE-LADY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH PADRE ISLAND'S `TURTLE LADY' DIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Iowa) 
 
(Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
(Optional trim included) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas _ Ila Loetscher, who earned the
nickname ``Turtle Lady'' for her campaign to educate children about
sea turtles, died earlier this week at age 95.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Sea Turtle Inc., the nonprofit organization
Loetscher established in 1978, vowed to continue her mission of
rescuing injured sea turtles and educating the public about their
plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never be able to do it in her unique way, but we're out
there trying to get her message across,'' said Mary Laddis, a
longtime Sea Turtle volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   On a makeshift stage behind her beach house, Loetscher held
twice-weekly ``Turtle Talks,'' during which she would dress turtles
in mariachi costumes and ball gowns and hug and kiss them while
chatting about their habits, history and habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out that is the only way _ by loving the turtles _
that I can show the children that turtles are worth loving. The
little children are catching on real well,'' Loetscher once
explained in a nature documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Loetscher quit her turtle shows in 1997 when her health began to
fail. She died of natural causes Tuesday in a Brownsville, Texas,
hospital, Laddis said. Loetscher's funeral will be Saturday in
Pella, Iowa. A memorial service on South Padre is planned but has
not yet been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Loetscher was the daughter of a country doctor who in 1929
became the first woman to earn a pilot's license in Iowa. Loetscher
moved to South Padre Island after her husband died in 1955 and
built a sturdy beach house behind the dunes facing the Gulf of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although not a scientist per se, Ila probably recruited more
people to sea turtle conservation than all the biologists combined
because of her sincere interest and love for these animals, which
was apparent to anyone who ever had the opportunity to experience
one of her educational programs,'' said Pat Burchfield, assistant
director of the Gladys Porter Zoo in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 Loetscher helped Brownsville building contractor Dearl
Adams, who with a group of volunteers successfully established a
second nesting beach on South Padre Island for the nearly-extinct
Kemp's Ridley sea turtle by transporting eggs from remote beaches
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The primary nesting beach of the Ridley _ the smallest of all
sea turtles and a species that nests almost exclusively in the Gulf
of Mexico _ was on the rugged Mexican coast north of Tampico, where
turtle hunters had slaughtered them by the tens of thousands for
their skin, meat and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with her when the first batch of eggs hatched,''
recalled Don Hockaday, acting director of the University of
Texas-Pan American Coastal Studies Laboratory. ``It was really
interesting. Everybody was really thrilled to see those little
(turtles). . . hatching out of the sand and walking into the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockaday, who at the time was a busboy at a South Padre
restaurant where Loetscher worked as a cashier, said his energetic
friend recruited him to help guard the transplanted Ridley eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got interested in this, back in the '60s, people
pretty much looked at sea turtles as a curiosity, a sea animal
without much interest or importance to them. That's all changed,
and she was a major contributor to that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sea Turtle Inc., which has moved operations from Loetscher's
beach house to a temporary facility, plans to construct a large
turtle recovery, exhibit and education center on four acres next to
the South Padre Island Convention Center, Laddis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working hard to continue all the work that is her
legacy to us all,'' Laddis said. ``We're looking forward to our
expansion several years down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Loetscher's family has asked that in lieu of flowers,
contributions be made to Sea Turtle Inc., P.O. Box 3987, South
Padre Island, Texas 78597.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
