A8444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOLS-BETTER-$ADV09     01-06 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-BETTER-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUPS SPREAD 'GOOD NEWS' ABOUT AMERICAN EDUCATION
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 9.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bucking the trend toward ``gloom and doom'' in
debates over public schools, two Washington-based education
organizations have joined to publish a 32-page report on ``the good
news about American education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of an unbalanced, one-way street where only the
brickbats make the news,'' said Samuel Halpern, founder of the
American Youth Policy Forum. ``Too many people have begun to
believe nothing's getting better and nothing works and education is
doomed.''
</P>
<P>
   His forum and the Center on Education Policy compared official
statistics from the early 1980s with the latest available.
</P>
<P>
   They found that in the 1990s, dropout rates and crime rates in
schools fell, more high school students took college-prep courses,
the average score on SAT and ACT college admission exams went up,
and public school teachers became more likely than private school
teachers to have earned a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``These little-known facts show there's a lot to celebrate and
reforms are moving in the right direction,'' said the center's
executive director, Jack Jennings. ``We should get away from all
this gloom and doom and school-bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of the 25,000 copies of their upbeat report was
distributed Wednesday. The center and forum ``deserve thanks for
setting the record straight and giving the American people an
accurate and balanced look at education,'' said Education Secretary
Richard Riley.
</P>
<P>
   But within two days, pessimists had weighed in:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Thomas B. Fordham Foundation reported that only eight
states have adopted strong academic standards for their public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, this means that 42 states still hold mediocre or
inferior expectations for their K-12 students, at least in some
subjects,'' said the foundation's president, Chester E. Finn.
Moreover, only five of the eight (Alabama, California, North
Carolina, South Carolina and Texas) enforced their standards
through tough, ``high-stakes'' tests with serious consequences,
Finn said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Civil Rights Project, based at Harvard University, held a
briefing at Halpern's forum on two new studies criticizing the
high-stakes tests.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, Linda McNeil of Rice University and Angela
Valenzuela of the University of Texas concluded that the state
tests required in grades 3 to 10 in Texas are ``shifting funds,
public attention and scare organizational and budgetary resources
away from schools and into the coffers of the testing industry
vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other, Gary Natriello of Columbia University's Teachers
College and Aaron Pallas of Michigan State University reported that
minority students continue to perform ``less well than their
majority-group peers'' on state tests in Texas, New York and
Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Education Week announced that this year's edition of its
influential 50-state ``Quality Counts'' survey, which is to be
released next Wednesday, will show that when recent college
graduates enter teaching, ``the brightest are most likely to
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that reformers have decided that the only way
to get Americans to move on reforms is to tell people that
everything is going to hell in a handbasket,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what they do is discourage teachers and students, which
adds to the problem,'' Jennings said. ``I can't count how many
public school teachers I talk to who say, 'We're trying to change
things, but all we hear is that everything's awful.' That makes
some of them want to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites of organizations mentioned in this story are
American Youth Policy Forum (www.aypf.org), Center on Education
Policy (www.ctredpol.org), Thomas B. Fordham Foundation
(www.excellence.net) and the Civil Rights Project
(www.law.harvard.edu/civilrights).
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
