<P>
   EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   The following stories will move in advance from the New York
Times Education Life section which is being published Sunday, Jan.
9, 2000. The stories will move with an ``a'' category code and
their will carry the slug prefix ``EDLIFE.''
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES (Northampton, Mass.) _ The number of
older adults returning to college continues to rise: Eating dorm
food, living in a 9-by-9 room and sharing a bathroom with 14 other
women. What could be better? By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   With photos: NYT21, 22, 23, 24.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-GIFTED-STUDENTS (Seattle) _ Colleges have long
experimented with ways to engage gifted students who are bored in
high school. But can children survive higher education? By Blaine
Harden.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-SCHOOLS-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ The question is no longer
should computers be used in schools. The question is how. By Lisa
Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photos: NYT28, 29.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-COMPUTER-SAFETY (Undated) _ Some specialists worry that
amid the technology rush, children are not learning to use
computers safely. By Pamela Mendels.
</P>
<P>
   With photo: NYT30.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RECS (Undated) _ Last year, a parent asked a
friend's advice about his son's application to Harvard. He
suspected a teacher had written a less-than-stellar letter of
recommendation and wondered whether he should call undergraduate
admissions in Cambridge to try to persuade a secretary to yank it
from the boy's folder. The parent was no different from thousands
of high school students and interested adults. He need not have
worried. Most recommendations do not help, and they virtually never
harm, college applicants. By Glenn C. Altschuler, Dean of
Continuing Education and Summer Sessions at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-HOME-LEARNING (Undated) _ What's new in home learning:
Globes that talk back, pens that read and crustaceans that teach
lessons in life, love and death. By Douglas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo: NYT27.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-STUDENT-DECLINE (Undated) _ Professors have been
complaining about the lack of connection between faculty and
students at least since the 1980s, with growing dismay at poor
lecture attendance and attention, reading assignments that students
suddenly find too onerous and courses that must be ``dumbed down.''
Such disengagement, along with the binge-drinking party culture
that predominates at many universities today, seems to be part of a
broader pattern _ a general decline in academic, intellectual and
community life on campus. By Richard Flacks, a professor of
sociology at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-BLACKBOARD (Undated) _ Education notes and news: Through
the keyhole via Webcams, venture capitalists for education, a
gentler Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   With photos: NYT25, 26.
</P>
