<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9
--EDLIFE-HOME-LEARNING -- Guy Martin, 9, and his brother, Roy, 11,
injecting air into their sea monkeys' (They are actually brine
shrimp) tank. What is new about the sea monkey enterprise is the
way the tiny crustaceans are packaged. Educational Insights
($19.95) offers a package that comes with food, a little tank, a
plastic galleon that glows in the dark and a tool that shoots air
into the water. (Philip Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9
--EDLIFE-BLACKBOARD-2 -- A drawing of Patrick Henry College. On 44
acres of secluded land in Virginia, about an hour west of
Washington, the foundation is being laid for an experiment in
higher education. Patrick Henry College will be both the nation's
first post-secondary institution designed for home-schooled
students and a training ground for Christian political advocates.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9
--EDLIFE-BLACKBOARD-1 -- When Montefiore Medical Center in the
Bronx opens a children's hospital next year, every child's bedside
will be equipped with a computer that has Internet access. Similar
plans are under way for new children's facilities at the
Westchester Medical Center in Valhalla, N.Y., and the
Columbia-Presbyterian Center in Manhattan. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9
--EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-4 -- Liz Land, 72, who sings in the
