Mass., and three in Westport, Conn., with her husband, Gay. Mrs.
Land was a 16-year-old freshman when she first arrived in
Northampton from Manhattan in 1943. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 9 -- EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-3 -- Alyssa Mahoney reviewing
animal physiology with her 4-year-old son. Ms. Mahoney, 36, a
former hospice caregiver, is juggling her studies at Smith as a
premed student with her responsibilities as a single parent. ``In
your heart, you think, 'I'm here under false pretenses,' `` says
Ms. Mahoney. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 9 -- EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-2 -- Sandy Colvard, 43, left,
and Laurel Mutti, 19, take a study break in Ms. Colvard's dorm
room. Ms. Colvard did not simply go back to college. She did
something far more daring: she quit her job as a logistician with
the United States Navy, packed up a U-Haul and moved into a
dormitory with 84 other undergraduates. ``When I got the letter
that I had been accepted, I sat on the floor of my living room and
I cried,'' she says. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 9 -- EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-1 -- In 1932, Anne C.
Martindell's college career was sidetracked by a stern father's
restrictive dreams. ``He wanted me to get married, and he thought
it was a complete waste of time for me to be here,'' Mrs.
Martindell says. ``He thought I'd scare men off by being
overeducated.'' Now 85, she's back at Smith College, working toward
her bachelor's degree in a special program for nontraditional-age
students. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
