<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-06 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHAT TO DO WITH A PRESIDENTIAL HAS-BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, already fretting about how to
stay busy after he is forced out of the White House next year,
mused the other day that he is tempted to run for Congress from
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   That seems like a bad idea although the concept of Clinton
huddled in committee sessions as a co-equal beside the conservative
Republican House members who impeached him has a certain ironic
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not alone in wondering just what a used but still
perfectly serviceable former incumbent can do in retirement. It is
a problem for every ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   We give our chief executives virtually unlimited power and
prestige and then abruptly take everything away when their terms
are up, putting them out to pasture with no responsibilities or
duties. We treat them comfortably and kindly, letting them keep the
title of president, but we don't know what to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's quandary is more acute than most because he will be
only 54 years old when he departs, still full of energy and
ambition. Recent former presidents have been on the elderly side
and content to make speeches, write memoirs, collect big bucks for
serving on corporate boards and play a great deal of golf. When
they left office, Ronald Reagan was 78 and not in good health,
George Bush was 69 and Gerald Ford was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reached for inspiration all the way back to John Quincy
Adams, our sixth president, who served Massachusetts for 17 years
in the House of Representatives after being defeated for
re-election as chief executive in 1829. ``He's one of my heroes for
an ex-president,'' Clinton said coyly in a television interview.
Adams is the only American, however, who took a lesser elective
office after holding the nation's premier political prize.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton previously indicated he intends to spend much of his
retirement in his native state, supervising his presidential
library and reconnecting with his home base despite his wife's new
residency in New York. But it may be testing the limits of Arkansas
hospitality to expect a warm welcome back after a distant,
controversial eight-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also praised Presidents Theodore Roosevelt, William
Howard Taft, Herbert Hoover and Jimmy Carter for leading productive
lives after the cheering stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, only Carter measures up in the modern era as a
consistently good citizen working for the public well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt, at 51 an even younger has-been than Clinton,
quarreled with his successor-protege Taft and tried to recapture
the presidency in 1912 on a third-party ticket. He succeeded in
splitting the Republican vote with Taft, thus electing Democrat
Woodrow Wilson. Four years later, TR returned to the GOP fold to do
penance and try for that party's nomination. He lost, to nobody's
surprise. It cannot be said he spent his retirement in a way
terrifically useful to the country.
</P>
<P>
   As for Taft, he went on to further glory as chief justice of the
United States, a route that is not an option for Clinton, who could
never get Senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover, after his defeat by Franklin Roosevelt in 1932, became a
major critic of his rival's New Deal, trying to undercut the
inventive programs designed to bail out the millions who lost their
jobs while the Hoover administration twiddled its thumbs. But Harry
S Truman rehabilitated Hoover by naming him coordinator of the U.S.
program to feed war-torn Europe and head of a commission to study
government efficiency. Truman later took credit for rescuing Hoover
from boredom and mental decline.
</P>
<P>
   It is Carter who has set the highest standard for good behavior
out of office. He has traveled the globe as an unofficial diplomat,
intervening in Bosnia and other international crises, assisting
impoverished countries with humanitarian aid and encouraging human
rights causes. And he has been a leader in Habitat for Humanity,
helping to build homes for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy, only 46 when assassinated, would have retired
at a younger age than Clinton had he lived through a second full
term. Kennedy once speculated to me that after the White House he
might do something on the international stage, perhaps at the
United Nations or World Court. He was thinking of a broader
leadership role, not exercising diminished influence as one of 435
members of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Clinton will have exciting employment
opportunities outside of government. His successor, no matter what
party he belongs to, is unlikely to want Clinton hanging around in
an official capacity. But the world is full of academic and
foundation presidencies, corporate CEO posts, committee
chairmanships and high-profile media projects.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this work can even be done from a home base in New York
City, where his wife lives.
</P>
<P>
   The three active, healthy former presidents have chosen to live
out their twilight years in different ways. Their's is the most
exclusive political club in the world, guided by no rules and few
precedents. But the partisanship of their active years recedes as
the desire rises for a respectable place in history.
</P>
<P>
   They support one another's libraries and generally keep their
mouths shut about the policy decisions of the current incumbent. No
one knows better than they do that we can have only one president
at a time. Clinton may find adapting to that last part of the deal
a tad difficult.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
