<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-HURRICANE-HNS &LR;      01-06 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HURRICANE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HURRICANE' FORCE: WASHINGTON, JEWISON FIGHT FOR TRUTH IN NEW
MOVIE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At first glance, ``The Hurricane looks redundant
for director Norman Jewison and star Denzel Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Each has explored racism repeatedly on screen, from Jewison's
Oscar-winning ``In the Heat of the Night'' and ``A Soldier's
Story'' (which featured Washington) to the actor's star turns in
``Cry Freedom,'' ``Malcolm X'' and ``Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   But looks can be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane,'' which opens this weekend nationwide, is a
story we haven't seen before. The film, based on boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter's racially motivated conviction for 1966
murders he didn't commit, is driven less by racial concerns than by
one man's spiritual journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``In prison (for two decades, serving three life terms), Rubin
went inward and began to meditate, pray and learn more (about) who
he was,'' Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He learned that though hate got him into prison, love could
get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   That love came from a group of Canadian activists, who took up
Carter's cause after celebrities had tried and failed to get him
released. (Bob Dylan's '70s song ``Hurricane'' was inspired by the
Carter case.)
</P>
<P>
   As depicted in the film, the Canadians (played by Deborah Kara
Unger, Liev Schreiber and John Hannah) were inspired to their
unlikely crusade by Lesra (Vicellous Reon Shannon), a black youth
from the United States whom they virtually adopted to quench his
thirst for learning.
</P>
<P>
   Lesra's first book purchase was a battered copy of Carter's
``The Sixteenth Round,'' about the boxer's unjust incarceration. If
Lesra hadn't bought that book, Carter might still be imprisoned
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had only so much energy,'' Jewison said of initial
efforts by celebrities to free Carter. ``This was a battle that
everyone felt was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not this kid and this group of Canadians. They said,
`Let's take one more look,' and of course, they found all kinds of
evidence that had been perjured, changed or hidden.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a movie whose power stems from its truth, Jewison
believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an age of hype,'' said Jewison, who directed 1975's
``Rollerball,'' about a violent future sport controlled by
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved into the `Rollerball' period now, of a corporate
society where materialism is all-important, money is worshiped like
never before, and grosses of films are supposed to indicate what's
the best film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost frightening how people's tastes are programmed in
the cinema and television. It's pretty insidious. But maybe this
picture will find an audience simply because it happened. It's not
hype _ it's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison, 63, was hard pressed to think of a scene in ``The
Hurricane'' that was fabricated for dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything here is substantiated,'' he said, then recalled
that one scene showed Carter in a courtroom when he would actually
have been in prison. ``But everything they said is quoted from his
book or the official record.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison was relieved after screening the film for Carter, now 62
and living in the director's native Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very apprehensive, because he's still a tough man who's
in great shape, and I wouldn't like to get hit by him,'' the
filmmaker said with a laugh. ``But Rubin was crying at the end. He
called me brother and threw his arms around me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's seen the film a half-dozen times,'' said Washington,
who's known Carter since he tried and failed to buy rights to the
boxer's story nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still getting to know each other. But I feel like we're
brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jewison, Carter's tears were the supreme validation, though
he's also hopeful the film will get Oscar attention. (Jewison
received the Irving Thalberg Award for lifetime achievement during
last year's Oscar ceremonies, and his films have earned 45 Oscar
nominations.)
</P>
<P>
   Many critics have hailed Washington's performance as
Oscar-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about it, but I'm always hopeful. Who
isn't?'' Jewison said. ``But the problem is there's so much hype.
Because of TV and the hype, the (Oscar) show has become such a
commercial stamp of approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, 45, won a best-supporting-actor Oscar for Glory.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Hurricane'' he trained rigorously, starting in October
1997. The final boxing scenes were shot last January. By the end,
the actor had dropped from 215 pounds to a lean 175.
</P>
<P>
   ``This role required a physical commitment that worried me,''
Jewison said. ``But besides being an incredible actor who brings
honesty to his roles, Denzel spent months training for two hours a
day. Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My hand is still swollen,'' Washington said with a grimace.
``But I really like boxing. It's a sport where you can't be
anything less than cocky, and I started to take on that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison required a different toughness. Carter experienced what
he later called ``a quiet revolution'' of prayer, meditation and a
fight for dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing he was innocent, Carter refused to behave like a guilty
man. He spent weeks in solitary confinement for refusing to wear
prison uniforms. When prisoners were told to sleep or eat, he'd do
the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed a lot of rules,'' Washington said. ``This is a
tough, tough man. They never broke this guy. Everybody gets broken
in a penitentiary, but not him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's story on the screen ``works on several levels,''
Washington said. Besides spiritual and sociological aspects, it's
educational.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son, who's 15, got into that kid's (Lesra's) head, so I
think it's a great opportunity to reach young people and show them
this kid's incredible transition from illiterate inner-city youth
to saving Rubin and eventually becoming a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington has begun to see his career as an education, not just
another paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first you're just glad to have the job,'' he said. ``Now
I'm also interested in what I and other people can learn from a
film.''
</P>
<P>
   The hatred that condemned Carter still exists, he emphasized,
referring to the notorious dragging death of James Byrd Jr. in
Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening right now may have more of an effect on
people, especially young people,'' Washington said. ``But this film
and `Malcolm X' are still a real opportunity to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison's zeal against racism was triggered by his travels
through the South after he'd served in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I then experienced apartheid for the first time in my life,''
he said. ``People who weren't allowed to drink at public fountains
had been asked to give their life for this society, which I thought
was totally absurd. I started to get angry about it, and I never
forgot it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Jewison directed a landmark TV special starring
black singer Harry Belafonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost 26 stations in the South while we were on the air,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He directed 1967's ``In the Heat of the Night,'' a crime drama
woven into a fabric of racism, which won an Oscar for best picture.
One of its stars, Rod Steiger, plays a judge in ``The Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jewison didn't approach his new film from the racial
standpoint of his earlier work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rubin was just another African-American handed a tough deal in
the '60s,'' he said. ``To me, this story wasn't about that. It was
more of a rich, heartwarming, uplifting, hopeful and inspiring
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington feels the key is Carter's revelation ``that hate is
binding and love is freeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about people doing awful things to a great
guy,'' he said. ``Rubin had hatred, too. This was a journey he
needed to take to become the thoughtful and spiritual man that he
is today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
