<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WHISTLE-FILM-REVIEW-N     01-06 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISTLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIFE IS TO WHISTLE': HAVANA ORPHANS UNDONE BY THE PASSION AND
PROBLEMS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at and of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like so many characters in Latin American literature, the three
major characters in Fernando Perez's lush, hallucinatory film
``Life Is to Whistle'' walk around with an awareness of the
supernatural that simultaneously inspires and oppresses them.
</P>
<P>
   As these passionate, troubled residents of Havana, all three of
them orphans, go about their lives, we have an acute sense of their
being haunted and held back by religious and ancestral specters.
</P>
<P>
   The director's master stroke is his portrayal of their internal
conflicts as a metaphor for the political and economic anxieties
gripping Cuba in the twilight of the Castro era. Although the
Communist government is barely mentioned, all three characters
ultimately find themselves forced to choose between clinging to
their self-restricting beliefs and shucking them off to live more
autonomously.
</P>
<P>
   Elpidio Valdes (Luis Alberto Garcia), a swarthy young musician
and fisherman abandoned by his mother (symbolically named Cuba), is
consumed with guilt because he hasn't fulfilled his revolutionary
destiny. Elpidio's chance for liberation arrives in the form of
Chrissy (Isabel Santos), a Greenpeace worker who sails into Cuba in
a hot-air balloon. The two carry on a passionate affair until it's
time for her leave, and she invites him to fly away with her to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Julia (Coralia Veloz), a middle-aged social worker with a job in
a home for the aged, is subject to spontaneous fainting spells set
off by the word ``sex.'' Pressured by her friends to consult a
psychiatrist, she uncovers a traumatic love affair in her past.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as the patient and her doctor stroll through the streets
of Havana, Julia discovers that half the city is living in a
similar state of denial, with people keeling over right and left on
the pavement when certain forbidden words are uttered.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is Mariana (Claudia Rojas), a beautiful, ambitious
young dancer with several lovers who vows to God that she will be
celibate if she wins the coveted title role in a production of
``Giselle.'' When her prayer is answered, she is overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   But the moment she and her handsome young co-star, Ismael (Joan
Manuel Reyes), set eyes on each other, they fall wildly in love,
and Mariana finds herself in a state of almost unbearable torment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is to Whistle,'' which opens Friday in New York City ,
views these characters through the eyes of Bebe (Bebe Perez), 18,
an enigmatic spirit who appears in various settings, including
underwater. The film crosscuts among the three characters she
conjures up for our amusement.
</P>
<P>
   As their frustrations escalate, all three find themselves
propelled at the same moment on the same day to confront their
possible destinies in Revolution Square in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The movie strings out its characters' inner dramas a bit longer
than necessary. Well before their rendezvous with fate we are
impatient for them to make the break. Yet if ``Life Is to Whistle''
drags toward the end, it has many charms. Its surrealist imagery,
inspired by Magritte paintings, lends it a thread of visual
zaniness (although there are several too many images of shaved
fish). And the movie is so deeply in sync with its characters'
passions that it sustains a mood of heady sensuality.
</P>
<P>
   Love seems to bloom on every Havana street corner, and the
throbbing music of Bola de Nieve and Benny More, which punctuates
the film, makes its erotic pulse race even faster. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LIFE IS TO WHISTLE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Fernando Perez; written (in Spanish, with English
subtitles) by Perez, Humberto Jimenez and Eduardo Del Llano;
director of photography, Paul Perez Ureta; edited by Julia Yip;
music by Edesio Alejandro; produced by ICAIC and Wanda Distribution
S.A.; released by New Yorker Films. Running time: 106 minutes. This
film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Luis Alberto Garcia (Elpidio Valdes), Coralia Veloz
(Julia), Claudia Rojas (Mariana), Bebe Perez (Bebe), Isabel Santos
(Chrissy), Joan Manuel Reyes (Ismail) and Rolando Brito (Dr.
Fernando). &QL;
</P>
