<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIAM:'   CLUELESS IN BANGKOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lily Tuck's lapidary new novel, ``Siam, or the Woman Who Shot a
Man,'' takes a Joan Didionesque heroine and deposits her in Graham
Greene's Far East. It works a variation on Greene's novel ``The
Quiet American'' while employing an elliptical narrative and
staccato phrasing reminiscent of Ms. Didion's ``Democracy'' and
``The Last Thing He Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The wonder of ``Siam'' is that it transcends its derivative
roots. Although the reader is distracted for the first dozen pages
or so by the novel's obvious antecedents, Ms. Tuck's authoritative
story-telling skills and distinctively musical prose quickly take
over, immersing the reader in her heroine's strangely resonant
life.
</P>
<P>
   That heroine, a woman by the name of Claire, has arrived in
Bangkok in March of 1967, the day after news breaks that U.S.
aircraft are bombing North Vietnam from bases in Thailand. Claire
has just married a soldier named James, who is a member of the
Joint U.S. Military Assistance Advisory Group. James frequently
travels to northeastern Thailand to supervise the building of
runways, and Claire spends her free time in Bangkok learning the
Thai language, studying Thai history and going on sightseeing tours
with the other JUSMAAG officers' wives.
</P>
<P>
   An innocent who will blunder into trouble, Claire has the very
best intentions, but before her sojourn in Bangkok is over, she
will cause the senseless death of a man. Indeed her story will come
to reverberate tellingly with echoes of America's own fateful
involvement in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for the reader, Ms. Tuck _ the author of two smaller,
more self-contained novels called ``Interviewing Matisse, or the
Woman Who Died Standing Up'' (1991) and ``The Woman Who Walked on
Water'' (1996) _ does not italicize these parable-like aspects of
Claire's story but instead focuses on the daily rituals and
routines of her life, goading the reader to share her experiences
as a stranger in a foreign land.
</P>
<P>
   Those experiences are given to us through a series of
crystalline snapshots (Claire going shopping for some bright red
silk, Claire going to a dinner party that ends in a violent
outburst, Claire flirting with a young soldier at an outdoor
restaurant) that underscore the fact that, like so many of Joan
Didion's heroines, Claire seems to experience her life third-hand.
She has married a man she barely knows, a man she met on an
airplane, and she has picked up and left her old life behind to
accompany him to Thailand. There she tries to contain her growing
sense of panic and emptiness by swimming laps in the backyard pool,
by practicing her Thai grammar and by trying to solve the mystery
of what happened to a man named Jim Thompson whom she and James met
at a dinner party shortly before he disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, of course, was a real-life person who has been
inserted into this novel to lend it an air of verisimilitude: he
was a former American intelligence agent who devoted his life to
revitalizing the Thai silk industry after World War II and who
vanished in 1967 while on vacation in Malaysia. Claire initially
sees Thompson as an enigmatic, Gatsby-like figure, a magnet for
rumors and innuendo _ he is said to have been kidnapped by the
Communists or sabotaged by rivals in the silk business _ but as her
obsession with him grows, he comes to signify to her both the
dangers of American involvement in Southeast Asia and her own sense
of displacement and cultural vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Siam'' progresses, Claire's precarious grip on her life
begins to slip. She suspects her servants of stealing a gold pin
and her grandmother's china sauce boat. She worries about intruders
in the house at night. She imagines she sees Jim Thompson out of
the corner of her eye. She contemplates using another woman's photo
in her new passport. As for her marriage, it soon devolves into a
toxic alliance of suspicion and resentment: Claire becomes
convinced that James is having an affair with his best friend's
wife, and she begins secretly going through his things each night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tuck orchestrates Claire's accelerating hysteria with cool
aplomb, skillfully showing us Bangkok through her eyes _ a
hallucinatory city of haunting beauty and frightening squalor, an
increasingly unreal city, where nothing is quite what it seems, and
``each event, no matter how mundane or trivial,'' seems to possess
a hidden significance. She shows us how small cultural
misunderstandings _ an improperly inflected adjective, a mis-judged
gift _ can snowball into larger grievances and betrayals. She shows
us how Claire's own emotional agenda and willful desire to
translate lessons learned from books to the real world skew her
reactions to people around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Siam'' would be a more impressive achievement were it not so
indebted to the fictional worlds created by other authors, but in
the end Ms. Tuck has managed to turn her borrowings into something
new. She has written an elegant novel that gives us a telling
portrait of a woman, a marriage and a culture all at the same time.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SIAM: OR THE WOMAN WHO SHOT A MAN '
</P>
<P>
   By Lily Tuck
</P>
<P>
   192 pages. Sewanee Writers' Series/Overlook Press. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
