<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-EGGE-HNS &LR;      01-06 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-EGGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGGE IS TAKING CARE OF BUSINESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: N.M.) 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Good afternoon, Grace Records,'' offers Ana Egge from the
Austin, Texas-based office of her record label. ``Can I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters trying to find most musicians often have to go through
a phone-tree obstacle course _ a run past record label
interference, a hurdle over management and a dodge of media
relations firms _ all for a few precious moments on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Egge (the G's are hard, like the word egg) has streamlined the
interview bureaucracy by wearing the hats of record label, manager
and PR firm herself. Talking to the Austin singer-songwriter
requires only a call to Grace Records when she's home. If she's on
tour, it might take two calls to track her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually enjoy the business side of music,'' Egge said. ``I'm
sitting here trying to make decisions about my next record. There's
a lot to do because I've been on the road so much lately.''
</P>
<P>
   If her brief history in the Austin folk scene is any indicator,
Egge should get prepared to spend more time out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   In less than five years, she has put out a critically acclaimed
debut of folk and blues balladry, ``River Under the Road.''
Recently, she released a live album of mostly new material, ``Mile
Marker.'' In between, there have been tours with Shawn Colvin,
Jimmie Dale Gilmore and a slot on the Southern dates of last year's
Lilith Fair tour.
</P>
<P>
   At 23, Egge, is positioning herself to be much more than just an
indentured musician. Following the lead of Ani DiFranco, the Artist
Now Known as Prince, and a few others who create, release and
market their own music, Egge is looking for freedom from record
label constraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Creating my own record label) was by far the best thing I
could do,'' Egge says. ``I now know so much about the way things
are done, how much things cost. It will give me more creative power
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of business smarts for a folkie the age of most new
college graduates. She herself eschewed higher education, but if a
degree in Austin music culture were offered, Egge would be
graduating with honors right about now.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Saskatchewan, Canada, Egge started writing and
performing music as a teen-ager in Silver City, N.M. Before she
left her hippie household to pursue a career in singing, she
accomplished an instrumental feat that DiFranco and most of her
folk and bluegrass contemporaries never will: She became a junior
luthier _ a stringed-instrument builder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my high school astronomy teacher built guitars because
he gave one to a friend of mine for Christmas,'' Egge says. ``I was
so jealous. I kept visiting him at his shop until he offered to
help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Working from the frame of a Gibson B-25, Egge spent six months
of her senior year in high school molding and shaping spruce and
mahogany into a guitar. Like a baseball mitt, the one-and-only Egge
model has been broken in and changed, but it is still the only
guitar she plays on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent all that time on it, and when I finally played it I
realized that the sound was pretty good,'' says Egge, who only
recently bought a costly case to protect the instrument. ``I was so
proud that it played so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Egge could have opted for Los Angeles or New York to kick-start
her career, but she never really gave either idea much thought. She
had visited Austin several times and recognized it as the community
for a singer-songwriter steeped in blues and country music. In
1995, she made the city her adopted home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin is such a friendly environment for musicians,'' Egge
says. ``I was really welcomed into the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   She became friends with longtime Austin country-blues guitarist
Steve James, who introduced her to other musicians in the
community. He also gave Egge a valuable piece of advice: If you
want to have your music heard, get in the car and start driving.
</P>
<P>
   Egge hasn't stopped logging miles since.
</P>
<P>
   Those with whom she has gone on the road include Gilmore, Jane
Siberry, Richard Thompson and Iris Dement.
</P>
<P>
   ``River Under the Road,'' her debut album, was released by Lazy
S.O.B. records in 1997 to overwhelming response in the Austin music
community. She won awards in the ``best singer/songwriter'' and
``best folk artist'' categories at the 1997-98 Austin Music Awards,
which led to a national tour with new-folk stalwart Colvin.
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge step in terms of recognition, but not nearly as
big as Egge's appearances at last summer's Lilith Fair. For three
dates _ in Austin, Dallas and Atlanta _ Egge put her bluesy-folk
and charming warbles on display on an alternate stage for the
throngs at the she-rock event. Each night she waited for the show's
finale and her chance to join the main-stage sing-along.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the Indigo Girls invited Egge to join them as a
special guest during their set to sing a verse of their popular
``Closer to Fine.'' She says that brief opportunity to sing on a
grand stage in front of thousands was a narcotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of drugs and alcohol, I can't imagine a bigger high than
singing in front of all those people,'' Egge says. ``I can't wait
for the next opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance might not be that far down the road if the reception
of ``Mile Marker'' follows the ever-escalating path of her career
to date. The album is live but is not a rehash of past work with
the exception of spare new versions of ``Bless Me Mother'' and
``Mind Over Matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seven new songs never recorded in the studio,
``Mile Marker'' includes covers of fellow Canadian folkies,
including Ron Sexsmith's ``Lebanon, TN'' and Ferron's ``Ain't Life
a Brook.'' It ends with Egge's interpretation of Rodgers and
Hammerstein's ``Edelweiss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the live album was so I could be heard in
performance,'' Egge says. ``I wanted people to hear how I sound
with my voice and guitar. My next record might be a combination of
studio and live.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, she is at Grace Records deciding how to best put
together her next album, which is scheduled for release in the
spring or summer. She's also working to promote the one other band
signed to Grace Records, the Barbers, and looking for new acts to
add to the label's stable. She feels that if musicians maintain
control it keeps the talent from getting burned on the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artists shouldn't have to suffer,'' Egge says. ``I'm a
musician before businesswoman, but this label will be here to help
other musicians. The reward is allowing myself and others the guts
to say, `This is what's going to happen now.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Music by Ana Egge and other Grace Records artists can be found on
the Web at www.anaegge.com, or by calling 877-594-7223.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
