<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRANS': ON A SPREE TO NOWHERE, A TEENAGER IN TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The following is a recap review) 
(af) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trans'' was shown as part of last year's New Directors/New
Films series. Following are excerpts from Lawrence Van Gelder's
review, which appeared in The New York Times on April 10. The film
opens Friday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Prisons, real and metaphorical, frame ``Trans,'' the atmospheric
first feature written and directed by Julian Goldberger.
</P>
<P>
   Its poignant focus is Ryan Kazinski (played by Ryan Daugherty),
a 16-year-old inmate who escapes from a work detail at the
Southwest Florida Juvenile Detention Center and embarks on a
frenetic, yearning adventure to nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of relaxation among good ol' boys at a rural general
store, Ryan speaks his inchoate dream: Move out to Colorado. Just
live.
</P>
<P>
   But as sketched by Goldberger in ``Trans,'' Ryan is a prisoner
of his youth, his ignorance, his lack of money and the
psychological wounds represented by absent parents and solaced only
by an adoring younger brother (Jon Daugherty).
</P>
<P>
   As Ryan makes his way home and struggles toward freedom,
``Trans'' is at its best in depicting a night world of speeding
cars, roadside markets and fast-food shops, knots of young people
out too late: all cast in the beams of headlights and the glow of
street lamps and neon signs and surrounded by the intermittent wail
of police sirens.
</P>
<P>
   At its weakest ``Trans'' overstays its welcome among the
real-life characters at the general store and pads Ryan's thieving
supermarket visit.
</P>
<P>
   Living in the moment, the slim narrative slights the story of
Ryan's past, but ``Trans'' remains a sensitive evocation of
youthful turmoil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1620EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-SNOW-SPI &LR;      01-06 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SNOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMPTUOUS FILM LACKS BOOK'S DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Author David Guterson's 1994 historical mystery ``Snow Falling
on Cedars'' has the distinction of being the most popular novel to
be set in the Pacific Northwest since Betty MacDonald's 1946 ``The
Egg and I.''
</P>
<P>
   More a mainstream literary effort than a genre thriller or
whodunit, it was a huge critical hit. The book's poetically precise
prose, bold structural devices, riveting delineation of character
and heartbreaking tale of anti-Japanese prejudice in 1940s
Washington state established Guterson as a major novelist.
</P>
<P>
   The film version, as adapted by Ron Bass (Hollywood's top
screenwriter) and director Scott Hicks (``Shine''), goes after
these same qualities. Their film is visually poetic, non-linear in
structure and relatively uncompromising. Even though it's a
big-budget studio release, it's very much an ``art'' film.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it has _ perhaps inevitably _ lost much of the
novel's drive and core of originality, and its characters have, to
a large extent, been reduced to movie stereotypes. As good as it is
in many ways, the film is not as emotionally gripping as it should
be, and comes off as a rather predictable liberal statement.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a fictionalized version of the San Juan Islands in the
'40s (but mostly filmed in British Columbia), it's the story of a
murder trial that arises when a white fisherman is found drowned in
his nets with a bashed-in head, and a young Nisei Japanese war hero
(Rick Yune) with a gripe against the victim is charged with his
murder.
</P>
<P>
   But the main character is the young, small-town newspaper editor
(Ethan Hawke), who grew up loving the woman who is now the
defendant's wife (Youki Kudoh) and lost her because of their
opposing backgrounds, tragic events of World War II, and his own
subconscious racial prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a kind of symphony that follows the course of the
murder trial as a blizzard is raging and flashbacks are constantly
weaving in and out of the hero's Romeo-and-Juliet childhood
romance, his tragic experiences in the war and the shameful
internment of his island's Japanese-American citizens in a
California internment camp.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, it's a sumptuous movie that gives a cozy, idyllic,
almost rapturous (and, yes, slightly bogus and cliched) vision of
the moody beauty of the Northwest _ forests of tall trees bending
under the weight of snow, the dewy undergrowth of a rain forest in
the full flush of summer, emerald green islands rising from the
mists of Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the fact that it has deliberately chosen not to be a
thriller, a conventional murder mystery or a nail-biting courtroom
drama, the story that emerges between all the scenery (especially
the star-crossed romance subplot) is quite compelling, and the bulk
of the performances (most prominently Max von Sydow as a crusty
defense attorney) are strong.
</P>
<P>
   Still, something is missing, because the film fails to be a
truly engrossing drama or a profoundly memorable experience. Its
outcome seems predictable, its noble characters are familiar and
often one-dimensional, and it has nothing particularly new to say
about the mistreatment of homefront Japanese Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In their all-out effort to make not just a good movie but a
``great'' movie, Bass and Hicks have borrowed perhaps a bit too
liberally from some classics, including the 1959 ``Anatomy of a
Murder'' and _ most glaringly _ the 1962 ``To Kill a Mockingbird,''
which it comes perilously close to plagiarizing in its final,
somewhat sanctimonious, courtroom scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Falling on Cedars. Directed by Scott Hicks. Written by
Hicks and Ron Bass. Cast: Ethan Hawke, Max von Sydow, Sam Shepard,
Youki Kudoh, Rick Yune. Universal. 130 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
murder and prejudice themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1620EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
