<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8479 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-HURRICANE-SPI &LR;      01-06 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HURRICANE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HURRICANE' AN ENGROSSING AND UNCONVENTIONAL BIOPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The starring role in Spike Lee's 1992 ``Malcolm X'' was such a
slam-dunk for Denzel Washington that you'd think he wouldn't try to
top it with another biographical movie about another famous black
martyr for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is in ``The Hurricane'' playing Rubin ``Hurricane''
Carter, the New Jersey middleweight boxing championship contender
who was railroaded into prison in the early '60s and spent close to
two decades trying to prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the movie engrossing and powerful, but Washington is
immensely effective in the role _ displaying some of the same
presence, poise and strength he brought to ``Malcolm'' but styled
to fit a more passive character the script depicts as the Jean
Valjean of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by the veteran and much-respected Norman Jewison
(``In the Heat of the Night,'' ``Moonstruck''), the film is also
enjoyably unconventional, with an opening that instantly dashes the
conventions of the biopic genre by giving us most of the facts
about Carter's life in its lengthy title sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping around in time, we quickly learn he was a slum kid who
became a ring contender; he was arrested near the peak of his fame
for a shotgun massacre in a white bar in 1963; and he educated
himself in prison, wrote a book about his life, and became a cause
celebre _ immortalized in a Bob Dylan song.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's first act then picks up his life after a second
trial has brought a second guilty verdict, his new appeals have
been denied, the celebrities have all lost interest in his case,
and a Toronto ghetto kid (Vicellous Reon Shannon) happens upon his
autobiography in a library book sale.
</P>
<P>
   As the boy reads it, the film flashes back to fill in some of
the holes in Carter's life, and then forward to trace the
fascinating detective story of how this boy and a trio of his
older, white friends devote their lives to proving the boxer's
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   If this story has a drawback, it's that it ultimately portrays
Carter as a total and blameless victim. From the age of 10 and
throughout the rest of his life, he's shown to be persecuted by one
monstrous, Inspector Javert of an obsessively racist and crooked
New Jersey police detective (Dan Hedaya).
</P>
<P>
   Real life is rarely this simple, but _ assuming the story is
true _ it has to be one of the most dramatic miscarriages of
justice in the postwar era, and an extraordinary chronicle of one
man unknowingly caught up in the side currents of a great turning
point of American history.
</P>
<P>
   Jewison handles this rich tapestry of non-linear scenes with the
skill of the old-pro he is, and carefully modulates the drama to
create the maximum emotional impact: the film ends up being a
moving testament to the power of love, the written word and a boy's
faith in his hero.
</P>
<P>
   As Carter, Washington gives the role an ``edge'' that's often
uncomfortable, and a determination that's finally heroic and
transcendent. In fact, it's such a terrific movie-star performance
_ and so perfectly keyed to the requirements of the historical
biography _ that he may well be on his way toward becoming the Paul
Muni of the new decade. Muni scored his biggest screen successes
with a series of biographies in the '30s, including an Academy
Award-winning portrayal of Louis Pasteur.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricane. Directed by Norman Jewison. Screenplay by Armyan
Bernstein and Dan Gordon. Cast: Denzel Washington, Vicellous Reon
Shannon, Deborah Kara Unger, Liev Screiber, Dan Hedaya, Rod
Steiger. Universal. 126 minutes. Rated R for violence. Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8481 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-MAGNOLIA-SPI &LR;      01-06 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAGNOLIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAGNOLIA' BLOOMS UNDER DIRECTION OF YOUNG MASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on his first two films, ``Hard Eight'' and ``Boogie
Nights,'' it's obvious twentysomething director Paul Thomas
Anderson is that one in a thouand young American Indie directors
who is ``the real thing'' and on the threshold of a big career.
</P>
<P>
   Both those films have their detractors, and he's currently
working so fast that he could burn out early, but there's no
denying he has his own unique vision and a flair for visual
storytelling that hasn't been shown by any other debut director of
the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   And his audacious new three-hour film, ``Magnolia,'' is only
likely to boost his stock. It, too, will draw criticism from many
quarters, and it doesn't stand up to any analysis, but it's filled
with amazing scenes, and seems uncannily hooked into the zeitgeist
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of Robert Altman's ``Short Cuts,'' the movie takes
place during one day in Anderson's native San Fernando Valley and
follows a large ensemble of characters, each of whom seems to be in
the midst of the most profound crisis of his or her life.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup includes an altruistic LAPD cop (John C. Reilly) who
stumbles on a murder scene while investigating a domestic
disturbance; an elderly game-show host (Philip Baker Hall) with
terminal cancer; and his estranged, coked-out daughter (Melora
Walters).
</P>
<P>
   There's a dying man (Jason Robards); his male caretaker (Philip
Seymour Hoffman); and his much-younger wife (Julianne Moore), who
married him for his money but has since fallen in love with him and
is now pathologically guilt-ridden about her original motives.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a child genius turned television ``quiz kid''
(Jeremy Blackman); a former TV quiz kid from the '60s fallen on
hard times (Milliam H. Macy); and an infomercial pitch man (Tom
Cruise) hawking an improbably mysogynistic self-help program called
``Seduce and Destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   The film starts out with a whimsical prologue meditating on the
nature of bizarre coincidences, and then proceeds to cut around
this symphony of characters, often skewing time, and gradually
revealing how they are all, by birth or coincidence,
interconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone predisposed to dislike the film could certainly make the
argument that Anderson's basic dramatic situations _ incestuous
fathers, lonely singles, children denied their parents' love _ are
written with the depth and played with the intensity of
afternoon-TV soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   And critics who thought ``Hard Eight'' showed little knowledge
of gambling and ``Boogie Nights'' a shocking ignorance of the
pornography business have more evidence that Anderson tends to go
off half-cocked. Did no one bother to tell him, for instance, that
the Quiz Kids were a TV phenomenon of '50s _ not the '60s and '90s?
</P>
<P>
   But, clearly, verisimilitude is not what he's after (this gets
even clearer when he opts for an absurdist climax right out of the
``Twilight Zone'') and he has a way of playing his melodrama that _
like ``American Beauty'' _ celebrates, satirizes and spiritually
transcends his material at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a way with his actors, most of whom _ Hall, Moore,
Reilly, Hoffman, Macy, Walters _ are veterans of his two earlier
films. Except for slumming superstar Tom Cruise _ whose egotistical
character is so impossibly exaggerated he seems an unpleasant
cartoon _ all come off well.
</P>
<P>
   And, even more than in ``Boogie Nights,'' Anderson's eye is so
commanding and accurate, and every angle of every shot so perfect,
that we always feel we're in the hands of a master. Like Spielberg,
even if the content is questionable or the performance is missing,
his scenes always manage to be visually thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Magnolia. Directed and written by Paul Thomas Anderson. Cast:
Tom Cruise, Philip Baker Hall, Philip Seymour Hoffman, William H.
Macy, Julianne Moore, John C. Reilly, Jason Robards. 179 minutes.
Rated R for language and sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-$ADV09-C     01-06 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN PUTIN, RUSSIA GETS A NEW LEADER, AND A BREATHER FROM THE
CHAOS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russia remains a fragile democracy, as evidenced by
the message Acting President Vladimir Putin felt compelled to
deliver in televised remarks to his country as 1999 became 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After assuming power from Boris Yeltsin following the old man's
abrupt retirement on Dec. 31, the 47-year-old Putin began the
traditional New Year's address from the Kremlin with a chilling
warning: Anyone who might perceive a power vacuum and take
advantage of it by violating the constitution would be ``decisively
crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   To Western ears, it sounds ominous. But in Russia, with its long
history of tsars and communist dictators, they like their leaders
hard. Tough words are particularly welcome after the past decade of
wearying political and economic upheaval, rampant corruption and
the ailing Yeltsin's absences.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of talk that got Putin where he is today, and has
made the former KGB spy and domestic security chief the most
popular Russian politician since Yeltsin stood atop the tanks in
1991 and led the democratic reformers toward the break-up of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Putin need not worry about coups, at least not now. He has
inherited the vast powers of the Russian presidency, what amounts
to a throne under the current Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Putin enjoys unprecedented popularity after four months as prime
minister while leading the popular and brutal war against the
breakaway republic of Chechnya. Now, as acting president, he is
almost certain to win the presidential election in March with a
mandate to steer Russia where he wishes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Putin's agenda for Russia appears to consist of two
basic components: stability for Russia and power for himself.
Ideology does not figure in the equation.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the Soviet Union's collapse, there is a
sense in Russia of optimism and national purpose. The notion of
Russia's obligatory choice between its communist past and a
democratic future has been supplanted by a strong patriotism,
embodied in Putin, that says Russia can choose its own middle
course free of Western advice or influence.
</P>
<P>
   Putin reflected that thinking in a political treatise he
published last month: ``For perhaps the first time in the past 200,
300 years, we face a real threat of becoming a second- or
third-rate state. To avoid this, we need an enormous concentration
of the nation's intellectual, physical and moral forces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will do it for us,'' he concluded. ``Everything depends
on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The tract, published and placed on an Internet Web site, is
short on specifics of how Putin intends to achieve Russia's
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   His first priority is power, and consolidating his image as a
national leader in the face of creeping setbacks in recent weeks in
the war in Chechnya and continuing economic woes across Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's image-makers were hard at work in the first week of his
presidency seeking to sustain the high public approval rating he
gained since he was appointed prime minister in August.
</P>
<P>
   His tough talk was supplemented with humane and empathetic
tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that in the new millennium _ thanks to the devotion of
people like you _ humankind will be gentler and more courageous.
That means taking greater care of the weak and defenseless,'' he
said in a televised address. ``I think politicians should listen
more closely to the alarm signals you are sending.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually stern Putin also conceded in another interview last
week that he had struggled to fight back tears when Yeltsin, 68,
announced his resignation. Putin said Yeltsin reminded him of his
own father, who was reluctant to retire from his job as a factory
foreman until forced to quit at age 76.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, along with the political treatise, are designed to
expand Putin's range and depth as a politician. His popularity has
come almost solely from the war against the Islamic separatists in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   His rapid and unexpected rise to become world leader is not
necessarily a good thing in the short term for Russian democracy.
The coming presidential elections will not be a fair fight.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's surprise resignation triggered early elections set for
March 26 (rather than mid-summer, when Yeltsin's term was scheduled
to end), giving Putin a clear advantage over his primary rivals,
who include Grigory Yavlinsky, of the pro-reform Yabloko party,
former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Vladimir Zhirinovsky,
the flamboyant nationalist politician.
</P>
<P>
   Putin will benefit from his incumbency, positive coverage on
Russia's state-controlled media and the financial backing of a
corps of business tycoons _ the so-called ``oligarchs'' _ that
aided Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Putin's much publicized firing last week of Yeltsin's
daughter, Tatyana Dyachenko, from the Kremlin staff, and the
re-assigning of other top aides, the changes were more cosmetic
than substantial, many Russia analysts believe. It served to
distance Putin from the unpopular and scandal-tainted crowd who
steered Yeltsin's presidency. But the Kremlin inner-circle
``created Putin from zero'' and he will need them to win the
election, noted Andrei Piontkovsky, director of the Center for
Strategic Studies in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yavlinsky last week sounded like a man fully expecting to lose.
``Right now, it isn't serious to speak about anybody other than
Putin winning the election,'' Yavlinsky told a radio interviewer.
``But if we ever want to change things for the better in our
country, if we want to preserve openness and democracy, other
people also must run in the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is an unpredictable place. Over the next 11 weeks of the
campaign, Putin could fall as fast as he rose to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems unlikely. Putin and the Kremlin have fashioned a
winning combination of power, patriotism and the political
organization Yeltsin relied upon to win reelection in 1996 and
retain his office during the depths of unpopularity.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Putin offers something Russians have been yearning for:
a leader whom they can feel good about, and an articulated policy
that promises no great highs and risks no new lows. That may be the
kind of breather Russia's shaky democracy needs to survive in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers correspondent Charles W. Holmes recently
returned to Washington, D.C. from Moscow after covering Russia and
the former Soviet Union from 1997 to 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
