<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT     01-06 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE FAMILIAR MOP OUT OF HIS PAWS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `FANTASIA/2000' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eight animated vignettes set to music performed by the Chicago
Symphony Orchestra, conducted by James Levine.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Various directors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 75 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Using one part of the original ``Fantasia'' (1940) as an anchor,
Disney's update reaches for new ways to synchronize music and
animation. After 60 years ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice'' from the
first film, with Mickey Mouse's mop toting buckets of water to
music at a gallop, composed by Paul Dukas and conducted by Leopold
Stokowski, does the job as well or better than most of the new
concoctions.
</P>
<P>
   Watching it unfold on the giant Imax screen is certainly a
departure. In the first episode, abstract shapes battle one
another, set to Beethoven's Fifth Symphony. Then a school of
whales, driven from arctic waters by a supernova, flies off into
the heavens to Respighi's ``Pines of Rome.'' In one of the more
engaging vignettes, sectors of Jazz Age New York swirl about, set
to Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue'' and drawn in the style of the
caricaturist Al Hirschfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Cavorting to Elgar's ``Pomp and Circumstance,'' Donald Duck
temporarily gets separated from Daisy while embarking on Noah's
ark. Flamingos get tangled up in a yo-yo, to Saint-Saens'
``Carnival of the Animals.'' In the most standard animated tale,
accompanied by Shostakovich's Piano Concerto No. 2, a tin soldier
rescues a ballerina from a nasty jack-in-the-box.
</P>
<P>
   Finally a woodland sprite soars and whirls to Stravinsky's
``Firebird'' Suite on her way to rejuvenation in the proverbial
shining new era. (Dare we say millennium?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Characters like the sprite sometimes land in
threatening situations, but like the film itself, trouble passes
quickly and is packaged with plenty of Disney uplift. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 Viewers this age are used to traditional narrative and
while each episode tells a story, the film's swirling abstract
creations may be too vague for many. But that won't matter much
because the episodes are so short. For some, the action could be
mildly disturbing. All told, though, they'll bask in the
spectacle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-10 If they find the movie a bit artsy, it will be
enjoyable nevertheless. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP For many older children setting animation to
music doesn't come across as the most compelling entertainment. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ANGELA'S ASHES' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Emily Watson, Robert Carlyle, Joe Breen, Ciaran Owens, Michael
Legge, Shane Murray Corcoran &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alan Parker &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 120 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things are so bad for the McCourt family in Parker's film,
adapted from Frank McCourt's novel, that its members are forced to
travel the immigration route backward and leave America to return
to an Ireland in which they couldn't survive in the first place.
``The only Irish family in history to say goodbye to the Statue of
Liberty,'' recalls young Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Limerick, relatives of Angela (Ms. Watson) have no use
for her husband, Malachy (Carlyle), who is from Northern Ireland. A
loving drunkard, Malachy can never find work or hold it if he does,
and he has always gone out for cigarettes two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the dole, the McCourts are jammed into a hovel. ``We've got
no dinner'' is a familiar complaint. A sheep's head is the sole
offering on the Christmas table.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly it rains. Puddles of rain and sewage claim the downstairs
parlor. Upstairs a baby dies in bed. Adored by his children,
Malachy regales little Frankie (Joe Breen) and his siblings with
folk tales. Frank goes to school, where he brawls and learns. Dad
disappears. Angela suffers and holds the brood together, or what's
left of it. The boys survive into young adolescence, hounded by
poverty and death. Finally a bit of luck enables Frank to again
pass the Statue of Liberty, this time in the desired direction. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE A couple of brawls and beatings are realistic if not
particularly brutal. Otherwise, some of the traumatic situations
have a violent feeling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX A group of boys masturbate in unison, Frank has sex with a
young woman, and there is some brief nudity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Frequent but fitting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER 14 Despite the celebrated literary connections, the film
is clearly out of the question for small children, and will be
disturbing to older ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP Many teen-agers have read the book, and some will
be interested in the movie. Others won't be attracted in the least.
In any event, while the hardships are apparent, glossy
cinematography takes the edge off the suffering. In a soggy kind of
way poverty becomes downright picturesque. Some parents will
disagree, but the result is one of the more palatable R-rated
films, if not an especially beckoning one, for young viewers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
