<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-MOORE-PROFILE-HN     01-06 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MOORE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE SUFFERS MORE IN DRAMA TWIN BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Julianne Moore has crammed a career that any
actress would be proud of into just one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' and ``The End of the Affair,'' opening this
weekend, are the third and fourth highly lauded films that she has
seen released in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   She was widely praised for her amusing supporting role as a
pliable, dim-bulb, small-town actress in Robert Altman's warmly
humorous ``Cookie's Fortune'' and for her knockout lead as a
dangerous, clever seductress in ``An Ideal Husband.'' (She also has
a supporting role in ``A Map of the World,'' but that has not yet
been widely released.)
</P>
<P>
   Though it would be highly unusual, it would not be a surprise if
Moore _ Oscar-nominated as best supporting actress for 1997's
``Boogie Nights'' _ got two nominations this year. Her roles in
``Magnolia'' and ``The End of the Affair'' are outstanding
performances in films already on many 1999 10-best lists. Moore has
been repeatedly named as a likely Academy Award contender.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Magnolia,'' Moore is Linda Partridge, the cheating wife of
a much older man (Jason Robards). He is dying, and Linda, torn by
remorse, charges from friends to therapist to druggist in a
sustained panic attack.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The End of the Affair,'' she is again a cheating wife. Her
Sarah Miles is tormented not just by her broken vows to her
husband, but also by a secret that keeps her from the man she
really loves (Ralph Fiennes).
</P>
<P>
   What a difference between all that on-screen agony and the
bubbly, broadly grinning woman sitting across a table in the Four
Seasons-Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 38, has a big presence on screen, where she looks a lot
larger than the reality of her presence: She is slight, though too
healthy-looking to be called delicate. A classic redhead, she has
green eyes and a fair complexion with pale freckles.
</P>
<P>
   She's wearing a snug, long-sleeved knit shirt, and, as she
talks, she pulls the ends of the sleeves over her hands like a kid.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business is to congratulate Moore on her
recent Golden Globe nominations as best actress in a comedy (``An
Ideal Husband'') and in a drama (``The End of the Affair''). That's
followed, undiplomatically, with the suggestion that perhaps the
proliferation of dubious awards such as the Golden Globes waters
down the honor of getting the nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many of them, I know,'' Moore says. ``But people
are acknowledging your work, and that's great. When people say it
truly is an honor to be nominated, they really mean it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of winning an award, I don't know if that is as
important. When somebody wins best whatever, we all know that's not
necessarily the best. So it isn't about who wins. It's just nice to
be acknowledged.''
</P>
<P>
   An actress could hardly hope for better roles to show off her
talents than ``Magnolia'' and ``The End of the Affair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' is a brilliant, daring and _ to this viewer _
highly irritating tour de force for writer and director Paul Thomas
Anderson (``Boogie Nights''). Incredibly intense, it follows about
a dozen contemporary Los Angeles characters in perhaps a half-dozen
loosely related stories during a short span of time.
</P>
<P>
   For serious moviegoers who can take it, it's a not-to-be missed,
three-aspirin experience, with huge tension, pounding music and
many outstanding performances: William H. Macy, Philip Seymour
Hoffman and Tom Cruise (as a really nasty woman-hater).
</P>
<P>
   Moore says her character was intimidating to play since she is
in misery from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard _ really, really hard. I was thinking of asking
Paul, `Can I play another part?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to hook into what her feeling was at the end of the
movie. I was really afraid of being fake. I don't like a lot of
emotion for emotion's sake. I had to find a way to make it very
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Her most memorable scene takes place in a drugstore. Linda waits
for medication while the druggist, obviously suspicious, checks her
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved playing that,'' Moore says. ``You see a woman standing
at a drugstore counter and feeling like she's nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   A long, humiliating silence is followed by a verbal outburst of
ferocious intensity. Anderson is known for making actors stick to
his script, but the scene looks so natural, it's easy to believe it
is improvised. But Moore says every word was written.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was sooooo hard, because it was all
stream-of-consciousness stuff. Paul doesn't finish sentences. I'm a
big believer in sticking with the script, because there is a rhythm
to it, and there is certainly a rhythm to Paul's language _ when
you hear it. So you have to buckle down (and learn it).''
</P>
<P>
   In style, ``The End of the Affair,'' directed by Neil Jordan
(``The Crying Game,'' ``Interview With the Vampire'') could hardly
be more different. Set in London around World War II, it is a
focused character study of three tormented souls.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's Sarah Miles has been bored with _ but faithful to _ her
bureaucrat husband (Stephen Rea) until writer Maurice Bendrix
brings passion and dishonesty into her life. When the film begins,
Sarah has broken off her affair with Maurice, although he has no
idea why. We won't learn the reason until a revelation late in the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on a somewhat-autobiographical novel by Graham
Greene. Greene, who was a convert to Catholicism, usually included
spiritual overtones in his serious books, and it is quite present
in this story. So is the question of whether love justifies
betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah is a woman who is ``struggling morally,'' Moore says.
``That's her big problem. She's a person who has her own moral
standard. She only makes promises she believes she can keep, and
yet she finds herself incredibly at odds with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in a marriage based on friendship, not passion, but
she's not able to leave him because she's made a promise to him.
And then she becomes involved with Maurice and makes a promise to
God that she'll never see him again. But she finds it difficult to
keep that promise, too. She's a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   While making these movies, Moore was convinced her characters
had nothing in common. But talking about them together has led her
to adjust her views somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought of it before, because I actually played them
back-to-back. I was here for `Magnolia' and then flew right to
London to do `The End of the Affair' and didn't think of them being
at all alike. But in a sense they are very, very much defined by
the love relationship they are involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   Really good, serious romantic films are rare. When they happen,
like ``The End of the Affair,'' they can be deeply moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great romances speak to us personally, for the most part
because we do have that kind of love in our lives,'' Moore says.
``If we don't, we're sort of working toward it. So romances are at
once very personal and very universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is special because it is about how love ultimately
transforms you and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore speaks from the heart about transformation. After watching
her suffering in both films, it's a relief to hear that she is
happy in her personal life. She lives with filmmaker Bart
Freundlich, her director in 1997's ``The Myth of Fingerprints.''
They have a 2-year-old son, Caleb.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time I thought you could have control over your
career, but you never had any decision about your personal life. I
thought you were supposed to wait around and it would happen. As a
result, my personal life ended up in'' _ she laughs _ ``a
shambles.``
</P>
<P>
   All that changed with motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the luckiest woman in the world,'' she says, sounding
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Being a mom ``is the ultimate transforming experience. You are
suddenly able to access emotion in a completely different way. It
gives you a sense of your place in the universe. It gives you back
your parents. You have a whole understanding you didn't have
before.''
</P>
<P>
   She says her happiness, her relationship and her child have made
her a better actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you do _ everything you feel _ makes you a more
informed actress. It's up to you what you do with the information.
Some of my best work has been since I've had Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1645EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
