<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-2NDTAKE-NY     01-06 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: young viewers.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `ANY GIVEN SUNDAY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz, Jamie Foxx, James Woods, Dennis Quaid,
Ann-Margret, Matthew Modine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Oliver Stone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 120 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As her top quarterback is carted off the field with a rib
injury, the Miami Sharks' owner, Christina Pagniacci (Ms. Diaz), is
already working the phone for a replacement. With teams from the
Associated Football Franchises of America ( Stone's commerce-crazy
equivalent of the National Football League) beginning their playoff
drives, it's a little late in the game to bring in an outsider.
Looks as if the Sharks are stuck with their own backup, Willie
Beamen (Foxx).
</P>
<P>
   ``A 26-year-old mystery man on his fourth team, or is it his
fifth?'' one commentator notes. Willie has quick feet and throws a
tight spiral, often to the opposition's cornerbacks. To vent
nerves, he vomits in front of 80,000 people, but Willie is really
an up-front young man from a deprived background who determines
that he has been kicked around long enough and will do things his
own way on the field and off.
</P>
<P>
   That includes making up plays in the huddle and not showing a
whole lot of respect for his teammates. Uncomfortable with
freelancers, the team's coach, Tony D'Amato (Pacino), heatedly
points out that this is a team sport with every move regimented to
the last step.
</P>
<P>
   Having built the club with Christina's father, now deceased,
Tony is totally dedicated to the game, and he has the photographs
of his estranged family to prove it. And here's another thing the
coach is sure of: A team that doesn't play with devotion to one
another will fail.
</P>
<P>
   It will take Willie a while to understand this. Meanwhile he
gets hot and becomes a celebrity. Christina wants to scrap old
Tony. ``The players aren't responding to you,'' she says. She also
wants to sell the team, provided she can get a new stadium built,
which would raise her price to $800 million. ``I honestly believe
that woman would eat her young,'' says the league's commissioner
(Charlton Heston). On the field the Sharks wage gladiatorial
battle. On the sidelines Tony sticks to his standards. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Games are brutal, and injuries can be life-threatening.
In the locker room players beg for drugs to ease the pain while
trainers scrounge for anything they can get into a syringe that
will get the wounded back on the field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Coach D'Amato goes to bed with a football groupie, and there
is some boyish sexual horseplay. As if to underscore what this game
is all about in the minds of the filmmakers, there is full frontal
nudity in the locker room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 Here we are again: another R-rated movie to tempt the
under-17 crowd and vex their parents. For many the answer will be a
flat no. For others there is a decision to make. With no apologies
from Stone, the film is as exuberantly vulgar and violent as the
subject it depicts. It is also full of keen observation and in no
way bereft of feelings and values. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17 If not necessarily recommended, the movie shouldn't
be routinely prohibited either. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matt Damon, Jude Law, Gwyneth Paltrow, Cate Blanchett, Philip
Seymour Hoffman, Jack Davenport, James Rebhorn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Anthony Minghella &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 135 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it better to be a fake somebody than a real
nobody,'' reflects Tom Ripley (Damon) near the end of Minghella's
film, adapted from Patricia Highsmith's novel.
</P>
<P>
   With that goal in mind, Tom insinuates himself into the life and
gradually the identity of Dickie Greenleaf (Law), an archly playful
young blood fresh out of Princeton and loose in Europe with wads of
Dad's money and no plans beyond Continental drift. It will get
messy.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting Dickie home, the elder Greenleaf (Rebhorn) dispatches
Tom, whom he mistakes to be a classmate of Dickie's at Princeton,
to persuade his son to return. Without dwelling on the details of a
complex and adroitly managed process, Tom tracks down Dickie and
his girlfriend, Marge (Ms. Paltrow).
</P>
<P>
   With guile and self-deprecating charm, he gains their friendship
to the point where he is invited along on their sojourns to Venice,
San Remo, Cortina and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Dickie is particularly amused by Tom's ability to mimic. Little
does he know. Suspicious of Tom from the start, Marge questions his
freeloading and eventually so does Dickie. On a jaunt with Dickie
in a small open boat, Tom gets his walking papers. ``You can be a
leech,'' Dickie tells him. Not only that. ``You can be quite
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing more is seen of Dickie. Tom says that he's gone to live
in Rome. Marge feels deserted. Tom, on the other hand, is
continually mistaken for Dickie and leverages himself into the good
life. But there are challenges from those who know him as Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Dickie's jaded pal Freddie Miles (Hoffman) smells something
amiss. A young textile heiress (Ms. Blanchett) Tom met on his way
to Europe gets too close. Tom finds he has to be Tom and Dickie at
virtually split-second intervals. Then there is Marge, who catches
him red-handed. So how talented is Ripley? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE One death by bludgeoning is extreme and graphic. Two
other killings are less so but convincing enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Dickie and Marge make love but aren't seen entirely. There
are also strong homosexual undercurrents between Tom and Dickie
and, later, Tom and another friend (Davenport). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Some. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 15 Inappropriate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP Those interested _ and with Damon, Ms. Paltrow
and a big glossy mystery-thriller to digest, there will be many _
will see the film. Parental reactions will vary, but attendance
should be discussed.
</P>
