<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-DIORAMAS-ART-1100(     01-06 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIORAMAS-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: TROMPE L'OEIL ON NATURE'S BEHALF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The painted backgrounds of the dioramas at the
American Museum of Natural History have a curious place in the
hearts of almost everyone who has grown up in New York City during
the last century. They are some of the most elaborate landscape
paintings in the city and some of the most frequently viewed
pictures anywhere, but almost nobody knows who did them or, in a
sense, even seems to notice them when they're staring straight at
them.
</P>
<P>
   You might call them windows on the world for generations, not
just of kids, who could briefly imagine, while their noses were
pressed to the glass, that they were at the base of Mount
Kilimanjaro or on a savanna in Angola or on Gunflint Lake in
Minnesota at midnight with the northern lights shooting straight up
like pink beacons on the winter horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the oldest of the dioramas, the ones in the Hall of
Asian Mammals, have just gone back on view in their original state,
having been obscured for the last six years by two museum shops.
The dioramas look quaint today, but even in the age of virtual
reality, when the museum is updating many of its displays with
computer technology, dioramas are still more realistic than most
photographs or films. This isn't just because they're in 3-D, with
taxidermied animals and foregrounds with reproductions of plants
and grasses or sand or snow. It's also because the background
paintings, on curved walls and ceilings (to avoid illusion-busting
corners), are made to be viewed the way one sees a panorama in
nature: with equal focus across the field of vision, and with
precisely modulated color, foreground to background, suggesting
depth in a way that even the best large-scale photographs or
70-millimeter film cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Are they art? Of course. Moreover, diorama painting is a dying
art, dioramas being relics from the days when verisimilitude was a
necessary skill among painters, and artists were the ones who
provided the world with pictures from abroad. Dioramas descend from
the old curiosity cabinets that mixed paintings and stuffed birds.
You might go so far as to call dioramists the original installation
artists if you were stretching for a link to contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the diorama painters, who worked mostly during the
first half of the 1900s, had a goal that was the virtual opposite
of the ambition of American landscape painters like Bierstadt or
Church, who painted some of the same kinds of scenes in the 19th
century. Diorama locales may be as eye-catching as what Bierstadt
and Church chose to paint, but the dioramists wanted to make images
that went entirely unnoticed as art.
</P>
<P>
   ``True art is to conceal art'' was a phrase of the best of the
American Museum of Natural History's diorama painters, J. Perry
Wilson, and as a motto it applied to his colleagues, too. Like
Wilson, they would have been flattered to be told that people loved
their pictures without even registering the fact that the pictures
were painted.
</P>
<P>
   This is why you can't really say that these men are forgotten.
They were never known outside their circle; besides Wilson they
included Francis Lee Jacques, William R. Leigh, Hobart Nichols,
Clarence Rosenkrantz, Dudley M. Blakely and Robert Kane. Carl
Rungius had something of a reputation as a big-game painter outside
the museum, but he was hardly a household name either.
</P>
<P>
   They went on expeditions with people who collected plants and
flowers for the foregrounds and with master taxidermists like
Robert Rockwell and Carl Akeley, who collected the animals in the
displays and developed a technique of sculpturing, rather than
stuffing, them.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Stephen C. Quinn keeps records on all the old
dioramists, among them Akeley and Wilson. He also helps put
together new displays like one in the Hall of Biodiversity and
restores some of the dioramas.
</P>
<P>
   He is a friendly, talkative man who can be spotted around the
museum in his standard uniform of khakis, navy blazer and dinosaur
tie. (He has a closet full of each at home, he admits.) Outside his
cluttered office under the skylights of the museum are plaster
casts of rhinos and birds and a life mask of a man from the Bering
Sea that the anthropologist Franz Boas cast a century ago. Quinn
arrived 25 years ago, a long-haired, bell-bottomed young painter
from Ridgefield Park, N.J., to watch these quiet, modest craftsmen
who were making a science out of recreating the Kalahari desert or
the Serengeti plain in the middle of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being the sorcerer's apprentice,'' he says. ``They
taught me all these tricks of the trade. My whole way of looking at
painting and sculpture turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day Quinn led a mini-expedition into one of the most
popular dioramas, the gorilla display in the Hall of African
Mammals. Getting in required maneuvering. Most of the dioramas are
sealed. The only way to get inside is to remove the plate glass
window in front, a gigantic production, which is why many of the
displays have not been touched since they were installed half a
century or more ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the gorilla display has an entrance, sort of: a narrow,
rather dangerous little chute, barely wide enough to squeeze
through, that drops from a cramped catwalk 15 feet or so above the
diorama. Catwalks run above all the dioramas because that is where
lights are installed to shine through glass along the front of the
ceilings of the displays, an area invisible from viewers except to
those who crane to look straight up. Every few months a technician
who changes the bulbs must crawl through the dust that seems to
settle like thick snow on these catwalks.
</P>
<P>
   Not incidentally, over the years lighting in the dioramas has
deteriorated badly, a headache for Quinn and his colleagues.
Backgrounds were painted to take the lighting into account: the way
light falls more strongly on the foreground than the background,
and the way some fluorescents cast a bluish tone. This was part of
the background painter's art. The lower parts of the backgrounds
were more highly keyed, with blue often mixed in where the walls
meet the foregrounds. In some cases the foreground plants were
inauthentically colored to ensure smoother transitions.
</P>
<P>
   The artists had other tricks. The rear of one black rhinoceros,
the part of the animal invisible to a viewer, was whitewashed to
reflect light back onto the wall behind it and eliminate shadows.
In the display of white-mantled colobus monkeys, where metal
cutouts simulated a dense canopy of trees, glints of sun were
cleverly mimicked by the reflections of the overhead lights on the
metal.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights go awry the illusions are lost and the
dioramists' best efforts thwarted. That includes the taxidermy.
Over the years the fluorescent lights have discolored some of the
animals. The zebras' stripes, for example, have faded.
</P>
<P>
   So Quinn has been busy lately helping to get things back in
order and to preserve what people at the museum have generally come
to agree are not just nostalgic exhibits but historical artifacts
of the collection that need to be saved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The gorilla diorama is one of the best-preserved. From the
inside it is in a way more realistic than from outside, not least
because it is as sweltering as the Belgian Congo was, where it
happens these gorillas are from. In the display the animals are
gathered about a hillside under cusso trees thick with lichen. The
background is a view of the Kivu range: three fuming volcanoes,
Nyiragongo, Nyamlangira and Mikeno. Akeley, the taxidermist, found
the gorillas at this spot. Having died nearby in 1926, he was
buried on Mikeno at a place visible in the painting, which was done
by William R. Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell Leigh's backgrounds by the violet and pink
undertones, the dappled light and sometimes eccentric trees. Once
you begin to look past the animals at the backgrounds in the
dioramas, other differences emerge. Dudley M. Blakely's backgrounds
are heavily impastoed, almost like Signacs, so that the paintings
have a density akin to that of the foregrounds, as in the diorama
of gemsbok antelope in the Hall of African Mammals.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Lee Jacques, who did the bongo antelope display in the
same hall, was a master illusionist with a dramatic touch. His
background in the Hall of North American Mammals for the musk ox is
a glaciated sheet called the Bellows on Ellesmere Island in Canada,
500 miles south of the North Pole. Clarence Rosenkrantz, who
painted the background for the giant sables, was more decorative,
leaning toward patterns that turned his work almost into wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson set the standard. He concocted a grid system for
reproducing an image on a curved wall. On expeditions to sites he
was going to paint (he traveled around Yosemite and elsewhere on a
bicycle, looking for the best views), he made innumerable
watercolors, took stereoscopic and Kodachrome photographs and
produced exacting records of what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   He was a tall, courtly man who, when he was at work, often
dressed in sneakers, T-shirt, shorts or khakis and an apron, as if
he were flipping burgers in his backyard in the suburbs. Sometimes
he'd set up a tray for tea in the diorama. During breaks he would
sit beside an electric fan and stare at the half-painted wall. One
day it was a view of Tanzania, another day, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1889 in New Jersey, he studied architecture at Columbia
University and worked as a draftsman in New York until the work ran
out with the Depression. Making trips to Maine each year to paint
landscapes and views of the night sky, he met Marian Lockwood there
in 1931. She worked in what was then called the astronomy
department at the museum. Through her he met Leigh, who hired him
to paint dioramas three years later. Wilson stayed through 1957,
and spent the rest of his life (he died in 1976) as a freelance
painter for museums.
</P>
<P>
   Like a chef, Wilson incessantly tinkered with ingredients and
techniques. At one point he decided to coat his pictures with
diluted buttermilk to remove sheen. Horizontal brushstrokes picked
up and scattered light from overhead bulbs, so he figured out how
to paint vertically whenever he wanted a matte surface. The
exception, he learned, was with deep blacks, to which it was
necessary to add a little varnish to achieve sufficient darkness.
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly proud of one of the museum's most peculiar
dioramas, the redwood display in Forestry Hall. The window of the
diorama is a slit in the wall, only two feet wide, and the display
is only seven feet deep; an illusion of tremendous depth and scale
was created by placing full-size plants next to the glass and
rapidly diminishing the size of the plants behind them until they
became tiny cutouts. The foreshortening was so precisely calibrated
that even the direction of the painted leaves scattered on the
ground was shifted accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's biggest achievements, though, were the backgrounds for
dioramas like the Libyan desert in the Hall of African Mammals, a
vast red receding plain under a hard, raking light. For the spotted
skunk and racoonlike cacomistle diorama in North American Mammals,
he painted Shiprock, a volcanic spire in New Mexico, rising into
the air, its top catching the setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   The background for the wapiti deer diorama is more spectacular:
the White River flows from Trapper's Lake in Colorado, yellow
cumulus clouds float over Himes Peak, and a line of cliffs called
the Chinese Wall zigzag straight back beneath a full moon, all
visible in the soft light of a late fall afternoon. Clusters of
spruce and pillowy, orange quaking aspens carpet the middle ground.
Everything is crisp and perfectly still.
</P>
<P>
   To get a sense of why Wilson was so much better than other
background painters, compare his view of a site in southeast
Wyoming for the bison display with the one in the Alaskan moose
diorama by Carl Rungius directly across from it in the Hall of
North American Mammals. Rungius was vague. Wilson was detailed,
methodical, sensitive to effects of sun and shadow, and above all
humble before nature.
</P>
<P>
   His background for the jaguar diorama is a peak. This is
first-rate landscape painting. Wilson recreated Box Canyon, a
valley near Guaymas in western Mexico, during the dry season, when
the shrubs have lost their leaves and are putting out flowers. A
wreath of clouds drifts above a sinking purple sun. The valley, in
shadow, is a haze of pink, green and blue that seems to stretch for
miles, although the display is only a few feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of Quinn's favorite dioramas, a particular dreamy
but precise view of the world that for him is the essence of what
makes these displays evocative. He compares the jaguar diorama to
the gorilla diorama, which he thinks creates a similarly convincing
environment. ``But of course children love this one most because of
the gorillas,'' he says, standing inside that display.
</P>
<P>
   Just at that instant, a little boy stops by and gawks at the
sight of two disheveled men beside a family of gorillas in the
mountains of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   The American Museum of Natural History is at Central Park West
and 79th Street. Hours: Sundays through Thursdays, 10 a.m. to 5:45
p.m.; Fridays and Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 8:45 p.m. Admission
(suggested donation): $9.50; students and the elderly, $7.50;
children 12 and under, $6; under 2, free. There are also special
prices for combination tickets including museum admission and a
film or special exhibition. Information: (212) 769-5100; to buy
tickets by phone: (212) 769-5200.
</P>
