<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAY-Z: ``Vol. 3: The Life and Times of S. Carter''
(Roc-A-Fella/Def Jam).
</P>
<P>
   Remember those recent advertisements for the Gap with the slogan
``Everybody in khakis''? The frighteningly autocratic undertone of
the phrase only reinforced the sense that people would, of their
own free will, make it come true, adopting the chain's latest
offering as a reliable uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The same aura surrounds the third album by the Brooklyn-based
rapper Jay-Z. Even casual hip-hop fans will buy this album
immediately, and its simple, sturdy tracks will soon make many
others lay their money down.
</P>
<P>
   Jay-Z is not exactly a poet, nor is he that dexterous vocally.
But he knows good product, which in hip-hop means sticky hooks and
flashy but credible gangster tales. Enlisting top producers,
including Timbaland, Swizz Beats, DJ Clue, Dr. Dre and Rockwilder,
and calling in favors from his fellow stars Mariah Carey and
Juvenile, he has made a dependably engaging collection of macho
boasts lifted by bouncy rhythms, memorable samples and interesting
guest turns.
</P>
<P>
   The baby-voiced Amil does well as Jay-Z's female foil, while the
Texas-based duo UGK stands out among the many guest rhymers.
Unsurprisingly, Jay-Z himself acts just as his fans will expect:
nastily cool, invulnerable, his arrogant persona as tight as a
well-stitched seam. Everybody into Jay-Z! Don't bother trying to be
different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1649EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SAN-FRAN-VEGAS-HNS &LR;      01-06 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAN-FRAN-VEGAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO MAY BE THE NEXT METROPOLIS ON VEGAS STRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Las Vegas already has Paris and New York. Now real
estate magnate Phil Ruffin wants to add San Francisco to the
metropolises on the gaming capital's Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin says his $700 million casino and retail development will
be called the City by the Bay and will open in about two years. He
is not the first investor to plan such a theme, and may face legal
wrangling with another developer planning a Las Vegas project with
a San Francisco theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my favorite city in the world,`` said Ruffin, a native
Texan who runs the Ruffin Companies from Wichita, Kan. ``It'll make
a great tourist attraction.``
</P>
<P>
   The project will feature replicas of Fisherman's Wharf,
Chinatown, Lombard Street, Coit Tower, Alcatraz and Napa Valley.
Visitors will walk into the development over a miniature Golden
Gate Bridge that will start on the Strip.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ruffin's plans, a copy of the Bay Bridge will
connect casino-goers to a 40,000-square-foot retail area with some
145 stores.
</P>
<P>
   The complex is to be built on the 25.5-acre site of the New
Frontier casino. Ruffin, who bought the predecessor hotel in 1998
for $165 million, plans to implode the aging 1,000-room
hotel-casino in June or July and start building the City by the Bay
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin's plan for a San Francisco-themed casino is not the first
of its kind. In 1997, Mark Advent, of the Advent Group in Las
Vegas, announced plans to spend $500 million on a similar project.
Now Advent, which is best known for building the New York-New York
casino in Las Vegas, is threatening to sue Ruffin for stealing his
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin questions the merits of such a suit. ``First, you have to
have a plan, the location and the money to do it,`` Ruffin said.
``It's not just a matter of saying you'd like to do it. I'd like to
walk on the moon. We have our own design. We didn't copy their
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Advent told the Las Vegas Sun he had warned Ruffin that any
announcement of a San Francisco-themed resort could lead to a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working with Phil Ruffin and Craig Dudley for two
years or more with the intent of joint venturing a San Francisco
resort,`` Advent told the newspaper. ``We've shared a tremendous
amount of information with them based on their assurances that any
San Francisco-themed resort would be done with us, or they'd go in
a different direction with a different theme.``
</P>
<P>
   In the same interview, Advent said Ruffin had initially offered
him $1 million for the right to the concept, which Advent rejected.
Later, Advent said, Ruffin raised the buyout offer to $5 million,
then $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ruffin and Advent, San Francisco developer Luke Brugnara
said last October he might build a similar project on 8 acres
across the Strip from the Stardust casino and hotel, the Sun
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The other metropolis theme is the Paris-Las Vegas, opened Sept.
1. The 2,916-room hotel and casino complex features a replica of
the Eiffel Tower. That project was developed by Park Place
Entertainment Corp., owner of Bally's, Caesars Palace, the Flamingo
Hilton and the Las Vegas Hilton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1655EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NH-MEETING-CANDIDATES     01-06 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-MEETING-CANDIDATES-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND EXCURSION: A REAL TASTE OF POLITICS INSTEAD OF A SOUND
BITE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic and
map are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, N.H. _ There are many idealized notions about American
presidential politics, and they start in the state of New
Hampshire. Here, by popular conception, is where the race for
president begins, the place with the first-in-the-nation primary,
where the candidates are methodically questioned by informed
citizens whose decisions guide a nation.
</P>
<P>
   And here, most of all, is the last remaining spot in the nation
where a regular citizen can shake hands and converse with someone
who might very well be the next president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   What is nice about this particular notion is that it is mostly
true. New Hampshire may not have the influence that it likes to
think it has or, more precisely, that it once had. But there is
absolutely no better place to see the American political process up
close and personal. And you don't have to live in New Hampshire to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   It is arguably less of a hassle to spend a weekend in New
Hampshire now than it is to make your way out to the Hamptons in
August. You can leave Manhattan at 7:45 a.m. on a Saturday and be
in Dover for an 11 a.m. town hall meeting with John McCain, the
Arizona senator seeking the Republican presidential nomination, and
200 other voters seated on folding chairs, sipping coffee and
eating doughnuts provided by the campaign, as we did a few weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The next three weeks are the prime season for anyone interested
in presidential politics. The primary is Feb. 1, and from then on,
the window begins to close: it's all Secret Service and controlled
access and swarms of photographers and camera crews and young
advance workers demanding credentials. And for any student of
American politics and electoral history, it is hard to imagine a
more engaging way to spend a January weekend.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire is a state of wonderful little towns and winding
roads spotted with antiques stores and stark, rolling winter
vistas. It is also home to engaging and genial people whose respect
for the political process stands strong, which is saying a lot
these days. If you make your way into a candidate kaffeeklatsch in
a voter's living room _ and you most assuredly should _ what is
most striking is how informed the questions are, be they inquiries
about Social Security and Medicare or provocative inquiries about
what aspects of a candidate's personal life is appropriate for
public examination. No boxers-or-briefs here.
</P>
<P>
   There is more than enough to do to fill up a weekend. With a
little planning and just a touch of luck, it's possible to catch
three or four candidates on the stump, although that is probably a
bit much for all but the most devoted follower. There are historic
sites to visit, places to watch journalists at work and helpful
exhibitions of photographs and memorabilia from 28 years of New
Hampshire primary history. Towns like Hanover would be charming
even in the off-political season, and they are utterly engaging
now; Concord, the state capital, is bunting to bunting with
campaign headquarters filled with volunteers ready to hand out
literature and buttons and position papers. And there are the
unexpected encounters that are inevitable on a stage this small,
like settling in for dinner to find a candidate for president at
one table and a familiar face from television's ``McLaughlin
Group'' at the next.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it's easy. The candidates want you there to fill
the hall, so no one is about to demand proof of New Hampshire
residency to let you through the door. Their schedules are,
generally speaking, readily available, and except for Vice
President Al Gore, none has the barrier of Secret Service
protection. A small warning: the New Hampshire primary is moving
into its quadrennial January frenzy, so it is wise to reserve a
hotel room and rent a car before you leave. And yes, January in New
Hampshire is as cold as you think it is.
</P>
<P>
   On the Stump
</P>
<P>
   The best way to get to New Hampshire from New York is to fly to
Boston, particularly if you have reservations about hopping onto
the tiny commuter planes that serve Manchester. From La Guardia the
Delta Shuttle leaves every hour on the half-hour and the US Airways
shuttle on the hour; each will land you at Logan International
Airport within the hour and has discounted fares that last through
most of the weekend. From there, a car, which will be easier to
rent in Boston than in New Hampshire these next few weeks, will get
you to the state border within the hour on either Interstate 95 or
Interstate 93, depending on where you want to start.
</P>
<P>
   As for accommodations, stick to the Concord-Manchester-Nashua
triangle if you can. There are nicer cities and towns in New
Hampshire _ Portsmouth, on the coast, or Hanover, where Dartmouth
College is _ but the triangle is where most of the campaigning
takes place. (The best hotel here is without a doubt the Bedford
Village Inn, whose spacious rooms include fireplaces and Jacuzzis,
but expect heavy competition from the journalistic regulars on
expense accounts who have booked suites here years in advance.) The
Marriott in Nashua and the Center of New Hampshire Holiday Inn in
Manchester are more than adequate, as are the Fairfield Inn and the
Comfort Inn in Concord. Bill Clinton had no complaints about
setting up camp near the airport in Manchester in a musty old Days
Inn that smelled of chlorine in January 1992, and look where he
ended up.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a hotel and a car, the other advance detail worth
tending to is the candidates' schedules, which you should check
right before you leave since they come together at the very last
minute. Then plan your weekend around their appearances. There are
no particular reporting skills required here. A day or two before
you head up, click on the Web site -www.newhampshireprimary.com,
set up for the primary by The Manchester Union Leader, and look
under the calendar tab; it usually displays the candidates'
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republican candidates, you can call the state Republican
Committee in Concord at (603) 225-9341. ``If you call in the
morning, we can tell you, say, what John McCain's schedule is, and
directions to the place,'' said Steve Duprey, the state Republican
chairman. ``They like us to help them build their crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer spontaneity, you can just stop by the candidates'
headquarters in Concord or Manchester, where you'll be provided
with a schedule, directions and, this being New Hampshire, maybe
even an offer of a ride (but don't be surprised if you're asked to
lick a few envelopes).
</P>
<P>
   Winners and Losers
</P>
<P>
   A smart way to start a visit is by stopping at two exhibitions
clustered around the gold-domed Statehouse in Concord, the oldest
statehouse in the nation and a recognizable landmark. The first is
the Museum of New Hampshire History on Eagle Square, where a
second-floor corner is devoted to ``Road to the White House: New
Hampshire's Presidential Primary,'' a history of the state primary.
It follows the evolution of the primary from its effective start as
a direct popular election in 1952 with buttons and lawn signs and
photographs and news articles that recall some famous triumphs and
stumbles that are now part of the state's lore.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition notes how every president since 1952 had won the
state primary until Clinton came along, in 1992. The Arkansas
governor came in second to Paul Tsongas, the former senator from
Massachusetts, although Clinton, in an early display of his
political and verbal skills, presented a loss as a victory by
declaring himself the ``Comeback Kid'' before Tsongas found his way
to the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to see in the museum, including a still-gripping
film clip of Ronald Reagan, shimmering with anger in 1980 as he
declared, ``I paid for this microphone!'' during the debate in
Nashua that was the beginning of the end of George Bush's
presidential hopes that year.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend 10 minutes or an hour here, but be sure to take a
moment to examine the photograph of Michael Dukakis, the former
governor of Massachusetts who ran for president in 1988. There at
his side, unidentified, is a very young George Stephanopoulos.
Stephanopoulos served as a press aide in this undistinguished
campaign, a period in his otherwise notable career that he tends
not to highlight.
</P>
<P>
   From here, walk across the square to the second floor of the
Tuck Library of the New Hampshire Historical Society at 30 Park St.
for ``First in the Nation,'' an exhibition organized by the New
Hampshire Photojournalists Association, with a roomful of pictures
taken by New Hampshire photographers who have captured some of the
best-known moments in the state's political history. The first is
probably the most familiar: the photograph of Sen. Edmund Muskie,
standing on a flatbed truck in front of the Manchester headquarters
of The Union Leader, denouncing the newspaper for attacking his
wife, Jane. This was the moment in the snow where some journalists
described Muskie as breaking down in tears, though not,
interestingly, in the article that appeared in the anti-Muskie
Manchester Union Leader the next day, which can be read back in the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph in the Tuck Library, clear and blown up, suggests
that Muskie kept his composure, although the candidate never
survived the portrayal of the incident. The room is filled with
first-rate photographs that are not arranged in chronological
order, which makes the exhibition unpredictable and fascinating. It
is a self-guided tour and admission is free, but be warned: the
Tuck is closed on Sundays. Stop by the Statehouse if it's open;
this is where people sign their declarations of candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   A walk along North Main Street leaves no doubt about the extent
to which presidential politics takes over this state: there are
more campaign headquarters per square block than Starbucks cafes in
Seattle. Vice President Gore has campaign headquarters right next
to those of George W. Bush, which are right next door to the
Republican state headquarters. All these offices are likely to be
open, and they welcome visitors. Most of the campaign headquarters,
though, are 20 miles south in the slightly grittier city of
Manchester. There you can also stop by the old offices of The Union
Leader, which have since been converted into the District Court
Building.
</P>
<P>
   The studios of WMUR, the local television station, in converted
warehouses down by the river, are a must-stop for all the
candidates, the site of many debates. Just strolling around, you
might catch a candidate holding a news conference or walking down
the street. ``I go to a lot of Democratic events because I want to
see them,'' Duprey said. ``I've seen the vice president. I met Bill
Bradley twice. He was just walking down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates use different hotels as their bases _ ask around
if you want to find out _ but one place where there is sure to be
something going on is the Wayfarer Inn in Bedford, a 10-minute
drive from Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   A Bustling Place
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the Sheraton Wayfarer, this has historically been the
place that most out-of-state newspapers and the television networks
have adopted as their headquarters. The networks in particular are
drawn to its picturesque grounds (not immediately apparent, since
the hotel is surrounded by asphalt and a line of shopping centers),
which include a waterfall that seems to scream stand-up to all the
network correspondents. Even if you can't get a room here, stop by
and walk around, either during the day or especially in the late
evening, when you should head right for the bar, which will
probably be lit up by the television klieg lights set up outside
its windows. The days of the hard-living journalists and
politicians may be gone (the hotel long ago shed its gamier if
unofficial designation as the ``Sheraton Philanderer''), although
the bar at night is usually bustling with journalists and campaign
aides and sometimes a candidate or two.
</P>
<P>
   The state is scattered with spots that have had their moments in
political history. Dartmouth College in Hanover, a 90-minute drive
from Manchester, has been host to presidential debates in almost
every cycle, usually in the great hall of the Alpha Delta house at
the center of the college. It's worth stopping at Robie's Country
Store in Hooksett, along Route 3A, an irresistible draw for
candidates looking for a setup homey picture of them shaking hands
in a general store.
</P>
<P>
   There is always the Elks Hall in Dover, where you can see the
spot where Clinton, under siege after the release of a letter he
wrote that gave new insight into his efforts to avoid the draft,
declared Feb. 12 that he was in the race ``until the last dog
dies.'' Indeed, as Clinton's friends point out, if you want to go
someplace he visited in 1992, you can pretty much stop by any
Dunkin' Donuts in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Earl Bourdon Senior Center in Claremont is where Clinton and
Newt Gingrich, the former House speaker, shook hands in June 1995
on a pledge to create a commission to recommend reforms in the
nation's campaign finance law. Bill Bradley, a Democratic candidate
for president, and McCain, a Republican, visited the center last
year to mark the spot of the unkept promise.
</P>
<P>
   If you have time, drive north to tiny Dixville Notch in the
White Mountains, which arguably exists mainly to cast the first
votes in presidential primaries and general elections, as it has
been doing since 1960, by opening its polls at 12:01 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, there's not that much politicking in Portsmouth, but
so what? It's a wonderful sprawl of a New England town, worth an
afternoon of wandering streets filled with arts and crafts stores,
restaurants and shops selling coffee and chocolate and taffy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for the campaigns themselves, keep an eye on the newspapers
and WMUR for breaking news, and don't hesitate to head over and sit
in on a speech or a news conference. Short of that, the town hall
and living room sessions, which are scheduled days in advance, are
the most informative of campaign events. These are not rallies;
they are discussions with candidates, up to 90 minutes long and
entirely unscripted.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for Newcomers
</P>
<P>
   It's worth getting there a little early, particularly if the
candidate is popular, if you want a seat and a good chance of
having a question answered. Take a camera and something to read;
delay is built into the candidates' schedules, and people in New
Hampshire tend to be a little more patient about these things than,
say, New Yorkers. The living room sessions are cozier, but at a
price: there are usually fewer chairs and no sound system, so if
you arrive late, you may find yourself crushed against the coats by
the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, people really don't go to New Hampshire for the
restaurants, and it's not unknown for out-of-staters to drive an
hour to Boston for a dinner. But it's not necessary. Try Richard's
in Manchester, a friendly and upscale spot in walking distance of
the Center. The Bedford Village Inn has a restaurant, a warren of
cozy small rooms, some with crackling fireplaces, an extensive wine
list and a menu with a heavy emphasis on game and fish. The fare is
hearty and generally quite good with prices that would fit well on
any Manhattan menu.
</P>
<P>
   If it's Saturday evening, skip the nightcap so you're ready for
an early morning of politics. Not that you'll have to go very far.
On Sunday mornings in New Hampshire _ as in the rest of the nation
_ there's no better place to catch the presidential campaign than
on your television set. If it's any consolation, that candidate
you're watching on ABC's ``This Week'' could very well be giving
the interview via satellite from a chair in a hotel room right next
door.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Primary Education
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in presidential politics, here are
attractions in New Hampshire and travel information.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates' Schedules
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: Click on the calendar tab at
-www.newhampshireprimary.com. The state Republican Committee in
Concord: (603) 225-9341; state Democratic Committee, also in
Concord: (603) 225-6899.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations
</P>
<P>
   BEDFORD VILLAGE INN, 2 Village Inn Lane, (603) 472-2001.
Fourteen suites; rates, based on double occupancy, from $185 to
$285. Fully booked through early February.
</P>
<P>
   NASHUA MARRIOTT, 2200 Southwood Drive, Nashua, (603) 880-9100.
Weekend availability through Jan. 22; afterward, fully booked.
Daily rates, based on double occupancy, $59 to $65.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER OF NEW HAMPSHIRE HOLIDAY INN, 700 Elm St., Manchester,
(603) 625-1000. Daily room rate based on double occupancy, $149.
Booked Jan. 24 through Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD INN BY MARRIOTT, 4 Gulf Street, Concord, (603)
224-4011. Daily rate, based on double occupancy, $59 through Jan.
19; from Jan. 19 to Feb. 6, $95. Fully booked Jan. 29 through Feb.
11.
</P>
<P>
   COMFORT INN, 71 Hall St., Concord, (603) 226-4100. Daily room
rate, based on double occupancy, $59 through Jan. 22; Jan. 23
through Feb. 1, $150. Fully booked Jan. 30 through Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   WAYFARER INN, 121 South River Road, Bedford, (603) 622-3766.
Rooms, based on double occupancy, $99 to $129. Fully booked Jan. 21
through Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD'S BISTRO, 36 Lowell St., Manchester, (603) 644-1180.
</P>
<P>
   BEDFORD VILLAGE INN, 2 Village Inn Lane, (603) 472-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   CONCORD STATEHOUSE, Main Street, (603) 271-2154. Open for
self-guided tours Mondays through Fridays, 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF NEW HAMPSHIRE HISTORY, 6 Eagle Square, Concord, (603)
226-3189, extension 200. Operated by the New Hampshire Historical
Society. Through March 5, ``Road to the White House: New
Hampshire's Presidential Primary,'' an exhibition on the history of
the New Hampshire primary, featuring photographs, manuscripts,
posters, banners and other memorabilia. Open Tuesdays through
Saturdays, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. (Thursdays to 8:30 p.m.). Admission:
$5 for adults, $4 for the elderly; $2.50 for children 6 to 18; $15
for families; free on Thursdays, 5 to 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TUCK LIBRARY, 30 Park St., Concord, (603) 226-3189, extension
200. Also operated by the historical society. Through Feb. 8,
``First in the Nation,'' a photography exhibition about
presidential politics, sponsored by the New Hampshire
Photojournalists Association. Open Tuesdays through Saturdays, 9:30
a.m. to 5 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   DISTRICT COURT BUILDING (old offices of The Union Leader), 35
Amherst St., Manchester, (603) 624-6510. Open for self-guided
tours, Mondays through Fridays, 8 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WMUR-TV (ABC, Channel 9), 100 South Commercial Street,
Manchester, (603) 669-9999. Free tours on Thursdays at 2 p.m.;
reservations necessary.
</P>
<P>
   DARTMOUTH COLLEGE, Hanover, (603) 643-9821. The great hall of
the Alpha Delta house is at the center of the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ROBIE'S COUNTRY STORE, 9 Riverside St., Hooksett, (603)
485-7761.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   BY AIR: The best way to get to New Hampshire from New York is to
fly to Boston, a little over an hour's flight. Fares vary depending
on how far ahead the flight is booked. Delta offers hourly service
from La Guardia Airport starting at 6:30 a.m; round-trip fare
leaving Friday evening with no advance booking, $266; information,
(800) 221-1212. US Airways, (800) 428-4322, offers hourly service
from La Guardia starting at 6 a.m.; round-trip fare, $266.
Continental Airlines offers service from Newark International
Airport; round-trip fare ranges from $140 when booked 21 days in
advance to $425 with no advance booking. (800) 525-0280.
</P>
<P>
   RENTAL CARS: Rental cars are available in Boston at Hertz, Logan
International Airport, (800) 654-3131, and at Avis, 41 Westland
Avenue, (800) 331-1212. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
