</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MALCOLM IN THE MIDDLE': THERE'S NOT A BRADY IN THIS BUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Marge and Homer Simpson ruled the world, every family would
be as funny, warm and wryly inappropriate as the one in Fox's
glowing new comedy, ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' And every mother-son
relationship would be as reassuring as this:
</P>
<P>
   When Malcolm, the neglected middle child, is unexpectedly told
he has a genius' IQ and is being shipped to the gifted students'
class, he howls that he doesn't want to be a geek. His mother tells
him how lucky he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at those Parker boys across the street,'' she says,
matter-of-fact and full of motherly concern. ``They may be healthy,
but honest to God those are the ugliest little boys ever born.''
She adds lovingly, ``Any kid who makes fun of you is a creepy
little loser who'll end up working in a car wash.'' It's hard to
imagine anyone other than Marge Simpson getting away with such
common sense comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'' is the obvious example, and not merely because
it appears on Fox immediately before ``Malcolm'' (which begins on
Sunday night at 8:30). Just as the cartoon ``Simpsons'' displays
the most realistic of family dynamics, ``Malcolm'' uses a similar
trick, bringing a hint of cartoonish exaggeration to a nearly
normal family. As the series opens, Malcolm and two of his brothers
(the oldest has been sent to military school) sit around the
breakfast table watching Mom shave mounds of hair off Dad's back.
</P>
<P>
   With a perfect, unlikely balance of qualities, the series is
irreverent about issues most family comedies take to heart.
Malcolm's mother sets up a play date with a nerdy boy in a
wheelchair and lectures her resistant son, ``Now you are going to
be friends with that crippled boy and you're going to like it,
understood?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile it is accepted and unmentioned that Stevie, the nerd
in the wheelchair, is black. And although the irreverence is
leavened by generous emotions, anything approaching ``cute'' is
avoided as if it were lethal, which it would be given the show's
satiric tone.
</P>
<P>
   That precariously balanced tone depends on the smooth, appealing
portrayals of Jane Kaczmarek as the mother and Frankie Muniz as
Malcolm. ``You want to know what the best thing about childhood
is?'' Malcolm asks in one of his occasional asides to the camera.
``At some point it ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Muniz says this with such down-to-earth believability that he
seems to be talking to us rather than using an annoying narrative
device. He is that rare thing, an uncloying child actor.
</P>
<P>
   And on a typical Saturday morning, as the boys watch television
in their underwear and squabble, their mother walks around
half-naked doing the laundry. In a running visual joke, her breasts
are hidden from the camera by a laundry basket, then a pile of
clean clothes, then the front door as she opens it to greet
Malcolm's teacher. Ms. Kaczmarek makes this comic rather than
sleazy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much about ``Malcolm'' sounds as if it should be awful
yet plays with easy charm. It is unaccountably funny when, in a
future episode, the boys and their mother go on the warpath, and
Malcolm's 6-year-old brother dives under the bed yelling, ``We're
going to die!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle'' is still a sitcom, so everything turns
out fine in the end. But that never happens neatly or politely.
Unlike more reverent series, here a funny, happy ending can turn on
the mistaken idea that Stevie, Malcolm's new friend in the
wheelchair, is attacked by the school bully.
</P>
<P>
   The first of January's midseason series to arrive, ``Malcolm''
brings what the entire fall season did not: an inventive, likable
comedy. ``I want a better family,'' Malcolm complains, but there is
no better television family this side of ``The Simpsons.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MALCOLM IN THE MIDDLE'
</P>
<P>
   Fox, Sunday night at 8:30
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 5 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Created by Linwood Boomer; Todd Holland, Alan J. Higgins and
David Richardson, co-executive producers; Jimmy Simons, producer;
Michael Glouberman and Andrew Orenstein, supervising producers;
Boomer, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Frankie Muniz (Malcolm), Jane Kaczmarek (Jane), Bryan
Cranston (Hal), Christopher Kennedy Masterson (Francis), Justin
Berfield (Reese), Erik Per Sullivan (Dewey), Craig Lamar Traylor
(Stevie) and Catherine Lloyd Burns (Caroline Miller). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
