u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     01-06 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CURTAINS FOR 8 SHOWS, PLUS ITEMS ON A NEW MAMET PLAY, A MAMET
REVIVAL AND 30 NEW PARTS FOR DAN CASTELLANETA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ T.S. Eliot's April had nothing on January on
Broadway. The cruelest month descended on the theater business with
a bang, with closings and belt-tightening. No fewer than eight
shows will have shuttered between last Sunday and next, including
long-runners ``Ragtime'' and ``Smokey Joe's Cafe.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word of another show that will not make it out of the
tourist- deprived winter months. Producers announced Thursday that
``Putting It Together,'' the Stephen Sondheim revue at the
Barrymore Theater, will end its run on Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, the producer, Cameron Mackintosh, said
the closing was based on an inability to find a replacement for the
star, Carol Burnett, whose contract expires in late February. But
the show, which opened Nov. 21 to decidedly mixed reviews, had
struggled to find an audience, with box office sales lagging far
behind fall's musical hits, ``Kiss Me, Kate'' and ``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   The closing is likely a disappointment for Mackintosh, a 1980s
and early 1990s hit maker (``Les Miserables,'' ``Miss Saigon'')
whose more recent efforts have been less successful, as well as for
Sondheim, whose other major fall project, a new musical, ``Wise
Guys,'' has been postponed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both men have projects in the offing, with Mackintosh's
``Martin Guerre'' on a pre-Broadway tour and Sondheim's earliest
musical, ``Saturday Night,'' receiving its New York debut next
month.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW MAMET PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Despite the general gloom and doom, there were springtime
stirrings in boardrooms, with plans for two new American plays
inching forward. One intriguing possibility is a production of
``Boston Marriage,'' a new play by David Mamet, which received its
premiere last June in Cambridge, Mass. Now, the producing team of
Carole Shorenstein Hays and Stuart Thompson hopes to remount the
play with a new cast.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hays declined to comment on the possible production _ deals
for actors and the director are not signed, and producers are
superstitious lot _ but an agent close to the negotiations says
that several marquee actresses, including Sharon Stone, Anne Heche
and Frances McDormand, have been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   The play, a comedy, follows a pair of upper-class Victorian
women and their working-class maid through typical Mametian terrain
of love, lust and quicksilver language. New to Mamet's canon is the
setting (blue blood, not blue collar) and the protagonist's gender
(female, not male).
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a consortium of investors is being assembled in hopes
of shifting ``Trudy Blue'' by Marsha Norman from its home at the
99-seat MCC Theater to a Broadway venue.
</P>
<P>
   The plan envisions 10 to 12 partners each raising $100,000 to
capitalize the show. So far, said Bernard Telsey, MCC's co-artistic
director, about eight producers have committed, including Eric
Krebs, Anne Strickland Squadron and Mike Nichols. A surreal comedy,
``Trudy Blue'' stars Polly Draper as a writer suddenly faced with
the possibility that she is dying.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``Boston Marriage'' and ``Trudy Blue'' are aiming for late
spring openings, though theater availability will play a big part.
</P>
<P>
   Telsey and Ms. Hays said part of the motivation for moving the
shows was the dearth of new plays on Broadway. ``Wrong Mountain,''
which opens Thursday, is the sole new play currently playing.
</P>
<P>
   A `GLENGARRY' REVIVAL
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Marriage'' may not be the only Mamet play circling
Broadway this spring. The McCarter Theater in Princeton, N.J., will
revive Mamet's ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' next month, with an
impressive ensemble headed by Charles Durning. It opens Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Durning, 76, last seen in 1997s ``Gin Game'' on Broadway, will
fill the role of Levene, the aging salesman battling for his job in
a run-down real estate office. Joining him will be two other stage
veterans: Daniel Benzali and Ruben Santiago-Hudson, a Tony winner.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Zigler, who brought Mamet's last play ``The Old
Neighborhood,'' to Broadway, will direct.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSCENDING `D'OH!'
</P>
<P>
   Dan Castellaneta doesn't have a comedian's face. No floppy ears
or bulbous nose here. Just a mild-mannered, middle-aged man. But
ask him to do a voice _ or voices _ and Castellaneta is suddenly a
very live wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who do you want to talk to?'' he says, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Walken, maybe? Just like that Castellaneta breaks
into a pitch-perfect Christopher . . . Lloyd. (D'oh!)
</P>
<P>
   He has good reason for being a little confused. As a regular on
``The Simpsons'' for the last decade, Castellaneta, 42, has handled
the voice-over duties for a dozen very animated characters, most
famously Homer Simpson, the show's dimwitted hero whose signature
expression (``D'oh!'') has become universal shorthand for dumb
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Castellaneta will turn his talents to ``The
Alchemist,'' Ben Jonson's 1610 play about an Elizabethan con man.
It opens Feb. 17 at the Classic Stage Co.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the Second City comedy troupe in Chicago,
Castellaneta has performed in classics but never in New York. Later
this year he'll perform his own one-man show, ``Where Did Vincent
van Gogh?'' at the Aspen Comedy Festival. The number of voices?
About 30, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Homer remains his best-known creation, a voice he began as a
Walter Matthau imitation, which became something ``very odd.'' He
opens his mouth to demonstrate and suddenly Homer is there
``D'oh''-ing. Then, just as quickly, Dan Castellaneta settles back
into his seat, a mild-mannered middle-aged man once again.
</P>
<P>
   ALONG THE WAY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Penumbra Theater Co., a Minneapolis-based company devoted
to the work of African-American artists, is the winner of the
$50,000 Jujamcyn Award for 1999. The prize, for artist
developement, is to be presented by the actor Danny Glover on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jack Wagner, the ``General Hospital'' and ``Melrose Place''
alumnus, will be putting his soap opera talents to use as Dr.
Jekyll (hair back) and Hyde (hair forward) in ``Jekyll and Hyde.''
He begins Jan. 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
