<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDRIAN DONATIONS  
 MORE VELAZQUEZ  
 NEW STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two rare paintings by Mondrian have recently entered
major museums, one in Cambridge, Mass., the other in London. Both
were given to the institutions partly because their owners would
receive tax benefits, and the circumstances of the gifts underscore
the difference between American and European tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States collectors who donate fine or decorative
art to museums can take tax deductions based on the fair-market
value of the art minus the amount they paid. The result is
generally a rush of gifts to museums as the tax year ends.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Harvard University Art Museums announced that they
had received Mondrian's ``Composition With Blue, Black, Yellow and
Red.'' Unlike so many Mondrians on the market, this 1922 painting
has never been cleaned, restored or damaged and even retains its
original wood-strip frame.
</P>
<P>
   Its pristine condition shows the artist's painterly technique:
shiny black lines and fine brushwork, subtle gray tones and sharp
primary colors. It also illustrates how he carefully adjusted the
lines and planes as they reached the edge of the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The work's journey to Harvard began with Paul Sanders, a Dutch
critic and composer who was a close friend of Mondrian. In 1925,
when both were living in Paris, Mondrian had influenza and Sanders
helped take care of him. Realizing that the artist needed money,
Sanders wrote to his brother, Martijn, and asked if he would buy a
painting. Martijn sent money, which Mondrian considered so generous
that he insisted on giving him two paintings, of which
``Composition'' is one.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the painting has remained with members of the Sanders
family, some of whom live in the United States. They chose the
Busch-Reisinger Museum at Harvard, known for its Central and
Northern European art, because it is a leading teaching and
research institution. The painting is the museum's only Mondrian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no doubt the most important 20th-century painting we
have been given,'' said James Cuno, director of the Harvard
University Art Museums. ``It is an illuminating example of a rare
painting that tells us so much about the way the artist worked.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Composition'' goes on view early next week, it will be
only the second time it has been publicly exhibited. In 1995 it
appeared in a Mondrian retrospective at the National Gallery of Art
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another Mondrian from a private collection, ``Composition B With
Red,'' from 1935, entered the permanent collection of the Tate
Gallery in London last month under very different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, with only one color punctuating the
black-and-white grid, went to the Tate in lieu of paying
inheritance taxes to the British government. It had belonged to
Nicolette Gray, an English collector who died about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The museum bought it from her estate for $4.4 million, $3
million of which was tax deductible for the estate. The painting
was bought with money raised from the National Heritage Lottery
Fund and the National Art Collections Fund, along with $80,000 from
the Friends of the Tate.
</P>
<P>
   Living collectors in Britain cannot earn tax breaks by donating
art to museums, unlike their American counterparts. But if a work
is important enough, an estate may negotiate a deal with a British
institution in lieu of paying estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country you have to die to get any tax relief,'' said
Sir Nicholas Serota, director of the Tate. The painting is to be
part of the inaugural exhibition at the Tate Gallery of Modern Art
when it opens in May.
</P>
<P>
   MORE VELAZQUEZ
</P>
<P>
   Because of the success of ``Velazquez in New York Museums,''
which opened on Nov. 16 at the Frick Collection, the institution is
extending the exhibition to now be on view through Jan. 30th.
</P>
<P>
   NEW STARTS
</P>
<P>
   The new year is always a time for comings and goings in the art
world. Here are a few of the latest:
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosenthal, curator of 20th-century art at the Solomon R.
Guggenheim Museum since 1996, will join Christie's next week as a
senior vice president and international director for its 19th- and
20th-century art department. He will be involved in worldwide
client development and attracting business for the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Doreen Bolger, director of the Baltimore Museum of Art, plans to
expand the museum's programs and exhibitions by increasing its
curatorial staff. She appointed Katherine Rothkopf as the curator
of painting and sculpture. Ms. Rothkopf had been an associate
curator at the Phillips Collection in Washington since 1993. She
will work with Sona Johnston, the Baltimore's senior curator of
painting and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Peter C. Sutton, director of the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford,
is starting a six-month sabbatical to write and research exhibition
catalogs. Two catalogs in the works are on Michael Sweerts and
Rembrandt's Apostles and Evangelists. Elizabeth Mankin Kornhauser,
the museum's deputy director, is acting director. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DEBATES07-COX     01-06 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    15 PERCENT POLL THRESHOLD SET FOR PRESIDENTIAL DEBATES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The panel that controls presidential debates
announced the formats and sites of this year's events Thursday, and
immediately faced criticism that Reform and other minor party
candidates might be blocked from participating.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Presidential Debates said candidates must win
an average of 15 percent in the polling of five nationally
recognized groups next fall in order to participate in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the 15 percent mark is a fair and reasonable
measure and threshold and strikes a balance between reality and
fairness,'' commission co-chair Paul Kirk said at a news
conference. ``There have to be rules to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the candidate's name must appear on enough state
ballots to have a mathematical chance of winning an Electoral
College majority, and the candidate must fulfill the constitutional
requirements for becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarian Party immediately denounced the commission's
decision, saying the 15 percent threshold would exclude Jesse
Ventura-like candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``National debates play such a crucial role in presidential
politics that the Debate Commission has an obligation to be open
and inclusive,'' said Steve Dasbach, the Libertarian Party's
national director. ``The Commission has failed to meet that
obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dasbach noted that Ventura polled only 10 percent in Minnesota
in late September 1998 before being invited to participate in five
debates the following month. Ventura, the Reform Party nominee, won
the state's gubernatorial election with 37 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the election of Jesse Ventura demonstrates, debates can
change the outcome of an election,'' Dasbach said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Reform Party has been the only minor party
with enough popular support to win a place in the presidential
debates. The party, which may face an internal struggle among Pat
Buchanan, Donald Trump and others for its nomination, had no
immediate comment on the commission's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party sued the commission in 1996 in an unsuccessful
effort to get its nominee, Ross Perot, into debates with President
Clinton and Republican nominee Bob Dole. But the courts backed the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 general election, Perot got 8 percent of the popular
vote. But in 1992, when Perot participated in debates with Clinton
and then-President Bush, he went on to receive 19 percent of the
popular vote. He did not win any electoral votes in either
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which has run presidential election debates
since 1988, will rely on technical advice from the Gallup
Organization for determining which candidates meet the 15 percent
threshold in polls by ABC News/Washington Post, CBS News/New York
Times, NBC News/Wall Street Journal, CNN/USA Today/Gallup and Fox
News/Opinion Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The commission announced that it will hold three presidential
debates next fall: Oct. 3 in Boston, Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem,
N.C., and Oct. 17 in St. Louis. The commission also plans a vice
presidential debate Oct. 5 in Danville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Each debate will be 90 minutes long and will be broadcast
nationally at 9 p.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fahrenkopf, who serves as co-chair with Kirk, said the
debates would be a mixed series of formats, with candidates
answering and responding to questions, but with a single moderator
rather than a panel of reporters, as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   He said the commission favors the town hall format, in which
between 150 and 200 people are invited to ask questions of the
candidates. He said the town hall format is ``clearly the most
popular'' with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Fahrenkopf noted, however, that the candidates will have ``some
say'' in the debate formats.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that there is no law requiring a candidate to
participate in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we can require any candidate to do anything
that he or she doesn't want to do,'' he said. But debates have
become such an integral part of presidential elections that it
would be difficult for any candidate to not participate, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
