<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8523 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-BLOODLETTING-IRON-DIS     01-06 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOODLETTING-IRON-DISORDER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOODLETTING RELIEVES BODY'S IRON OVERLOAD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By JULIANNE REMINGTON  
 c.2000 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not many disorders can be helped by draining the body of blood.
But healers in Medieval Europe may have cured a few people
inadvertently with a good bloodletting.
</P>
<P>
   People with a disorder called hemochromatosis, or iron overload
disease, can actually benefit from regular bloodletting.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, hemochromatosis was thought to be rare. Now
experts say hemochromatosis is the most common, life-threatening
genetic disorder in North America--affecting approximately 1 in
every 300 Caucasians. It's most prevalent in people of Irish,
Scottish, and British descent. It's also common in Hispanics, but
is not frequent in Asians or Blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Hemochromatosis begins when the body absorbs too much iron from
the diet, eventually storing the iron in different organs. Such
people absorb 300 percent more iron than a normal person.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases faulty genes trigger this abnormal iron
absorption. As the iron builds up over several decades, it slowly
eats away at healthy organs until a disease which appears unrelated
sets in. Only then do people usually see a doctor. Sometimes it's
too late. Without treatment, people can and do die of
hemochromatosis.
</P>
<P>
   SILENT CONDITION
</P>
<P>
   Travis Hudson found out about iron overload's silent destruction
when he suddenly couldn't walk one morning after waking up. ``I
couldn't imagine what was wrong,'' says Hudson. Unfortunately, when
he told doctors about the trouble he'd been having with a sore
ankle and memory problems, he was misdiagnosed as having arthritis
and depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disorder is so variable, many doctors don't recognize its
signs,'' says Dr. Vincent Felitti, director of the Department of
Preventive Medicine, Southern California Kaiser Permanente. ``If
you had 10 patients with hemochromatosis, probably 9 of them would
be totally different from one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Because hemochromatosis involves excessive iron deposits in many
body systems, damage to the liver, pancreas, heart and other organs
can be fatal. Untreated, the disease can advance to severe
cirrhosis and liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Early detection and periodic blood drawings (phlebotomies) spare
many patients from severe symptoms. But most people with the
disorder, like Hudson, don't realize they're accumulating dangerous
stores of iron.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Hudson was scheduled to have surgery on his
arthritic ankle, blood tests revealed the truth--Hudson suffered
from iron overload disease. Surgery was cancelled and weekly
phlebotomies began. Hudson had members of his family tested. He has
a sister and a son with the same genetic mutation.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Hudson couldn't even swing a golf club. Now, with
regular phlebotomies, his depression and memory lapses have
disappeared, and the joint pain eased up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, I played 18 holes,'' he said. ``What does that tell
you? How many diseases can you take care of like this?''
</P>
<P>
   SYMPTOMS
</P>
<P>
   Hudson showed only a few of the symptoms of iron overload.
Frequently symptoms don't appear until later in life; usually
between the ages of 40 and 70. Hemochromatosis can be the
underlying cause of common chronic conditions such as heart
failure, infertility, or diabetes. Occasionally no symptoms appear,
even in advanced stages with cirrhosis. A September 21, 1999 study
in the Journal of the American Heart Association shows people with
hemochromatosis are at increased risk of heart attack and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.Centers for Disease Control and Prevention list the
following possible symptoms:
</P>
<P>
   --fatigue, weakness and joint pain
</P>
<P>
   --elevated liver enzymes, enlarged liver
</P>
<P>
   --arthritis
</P>
<P>
   --impotence, infertility
</P>
<P>
   --diabetes mellitus
</P>
<P>
   --increased skin pigmentation or bronzing
</P>
<P>
   --arrhythmia or irregular heart beat
</P>
<P>
   --endocrine dysfunction
</P>
<P>
   --frequent colds, flu, infections
</P>
<P>
   -- headaches
</P>
<P>
   --irritability, depression
</P>
<P>
   --hair loss
</P>
<P>
   --weight loss
</P>
<P>
   --congestive heart failure
</P>
<P>
   Although scientists have identified the genes responsible for
almost all cases of hemochromatosis, the exact mechanism by which
the body absorbs too much iron from food remains unknown. Red blood
cells need iron to make hemoglobin, which binds with oxygen in the
lungs and delivers it to the body's cells.
</P>
<P>
   But in people with hemochromatosis, something goes wrong with
the system. Carrier molecules in the blood become saturated with
iron. The excess iron spills over into the liver, pancreas, heart
and other organs. The iron starts to oxidize those cells, and over
time ``rusty'' organs fail.
</P>
<P>
   Iron is also deposited in the skin, making some people with the
disease look like they have a constant tan. Sometimes it's called
``bronze diabetes.'' Women who menstruate most of their adult lives
often don't express symptoms until after menopause.
</P>
<P>
   IRON DETECTORS
</P>
<P>
   People with two copies of a defective gene on chromosome 6 are
the most likely to develop iron overload disease. Other people,
with only one copy of the defective gene, can be carriers. Early
diagnosis remains critical for optimum treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A genetics test can pick up the faulty gene. Or a person can ask
a physician for an inexpensive blood test called a ``transferrin
saturation test.'' In the test, serum iron levels are divided by
the blood's total iron binding capacity. In adults, transferrin
saturation values higher than 60 percent for males and 50 percent
for females suggest hemochromatosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of screening for hemochromatosis is approximately the
cost of a pack of cigarettes,'' says Felitti. ``And it can
literally save people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Another blood test that measures what's called the ``serum
ferritin level'' can also give useful, but imperfect estimates of
total body iron load. Alcoholism and undiagnosed hepatitis can
negatively affect test results.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD BANKS WANT ONLY ALTRUISTIC DONATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The only way the body can rid itself of excess iron is to bleed.
Weekly or monthly phlebotomies prevent or alleviate many symptoms
of iron overload. In cases where damage has already set in, therapy
can prevent the damage from getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   A solution to the problem would be to regularly donate blood
under a physician's care. Hemochromatosis cannot be transmitted
through blood donation.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. blood banks historically only accept altruistic
donations. Most decline iron-overload blood. But some
hemochromatosis experts are lobbying to change that practice.
Victor Herbert, M.D., Chief of the Mount Sinai Hemotology and
Nutrition Laboratory in New York, New York argues that recurring
blood shortages could end in 24 hours if blood banks would accept
and donate blood from hemochromatosis patients. Instead, the
organizations throw it away.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention concluded that it
costs $1.10 to diagnose a case with simple blood screening.
Lifetime treatment cost is calculated at $6,400 per patient. In
contrast, the lifetime cost of caring for an undiagnosed case of
hemochromatosis is estimated at $46,000.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC and National Institutes of Health are investigating
nationwide screening but many factors come into play. For instance,
at what age should people be screened? Who should pay? Inexpensive
blood tests will miss 15 percent of people with hemochromatosis.
Genetics tests would be more accurate, but much more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Felitti says a patient who wishes to know his or her iron
profile should ask his or her doctor for a transferrin saturation
test. But Felitti warns patients not to be surprised if a health
care provider has never heard of this hidden disease.
</P>
<P>
   MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   The Iron Disorders Institute (http://www.irondisorders.org) is a
non-profit resource center providing information about many
iron-related conditions. The site is reviewed by physicians,
researchers and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site is at http://healthsurfing.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
