<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8525 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-MALCOLM-SPI &LR;      01-06 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MALCOLM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX HAS A KEEPER IN SMART, FUNNY `MALCOLM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the sitcom genre having its obituary read at every
opportunity, there's no assurance that ``Malcolm in the Middle''
will be a hit. It is smart, irreverent and funny, which means
diddly in the carpeted offices of TV execdom, where high quality
may be salve for the soulless but completely irrelevant to the
bottom line. Besides, it's on Fox, which had a smart, irreverent,
funny comedy in ``Action'' just a few months ago and gave up on it
before most of America had heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will probably be willing to stay with ``Malcolm'' a little
longer because it's safer than ``Action.'' But not completely safe.
In its first episode Sunday, the show has the nerve to knock over a
kid in a wheelchair, show a mom running around the house half-naked
and have the same woman give her husband _ simply naked and chimply
hirsute _ a body shave in the kitchen while the kids are eating
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry if this leaves you cold. ``Malcolm in the Middle'' isn't
as tasteless as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not as raunchy as Fox's animated ``Family Guy,''
which barbecues sacred cows on the assumption that satire isn't
satire unless it's done to a crisp. ``Malcolm'' creator Linwood
Boomer knows satire of the American family can be effective when
it's medium rare: a little bloody, perhaps, but still tasty.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer was a gifted child who did some TV acting before getting
into production: He played Adam Kendall, the blind teacher on
``Little House on the Prairie.'' His memory of being a smart kid
with a non-traditional first name infuses ``Malcolm'' with a
disarmingly funny authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Muniz plays Malcolm, one of four more-or-less normal
kids in a more-or-less normal family, until it's determined that he
has an IQ of 165. All of a sudden Malcolm is ``gifted'' and his
world changes accordingly, despite his overwhelming desire to
remain ``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Muniz's portrayal of Malcolm is as endearing as anything on
television in the past five years: poised, powerful and precious.
And Jane Kaczmarek's take on his harried but well-meaning mom,
Lois, is the stuff of Emmy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The thesis of ``Malcolm'' is that childhood is difficult enough
without adults adding more labels to an already vicious class
system. It can be hard on one's self-esteem _ appropriately, we
never learn Malcolm's last name _ not to mention one's physical
well-being. (A ``Krelboyne'' _ Malcolm's word for a geek _ is
synonymous with bully prey.)
</P>
<P>
   Like most stuff on Fox, ``Malcolm in the Middle'' has a slight
case of potty mouth, which the network seems to require of its
comedies. Still, with writing that crackles and acting that
sparkles, it's as close to the smart-alecky brilliance of ``The
Simpsons'' as a live-action series has come in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm in the Middle. Half-hour comedy about a young genius
trying to stay normal in a middle-class family. Starring Frankie
Muniz, Jane Kaczmarek, Bryan Cranston, Christopher Kennedy
Masterson, Justin Berfield, Erik Per Sullivan and Catherine Lloyd
Burns. Season premiere Sunday. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
