<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Jan. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winds averaging 20 mph to 40 mph will mark a chinook along the
Front Range of the northern Rockies on Thursday. Higher gusts are
possible, particularly in southeast Wyoming and northeast Colorado.
As air cresting the lofty, jagged peaks descends down the leeward
side of the mountains, it will warm, pushing afternoon temperatures
into the 40s and 50s from eastern Colorado to Montana. The warming
effects of the chinook will spread into the western high plains
from southwest North Dakota to Nebraska and parts of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, broken areas of rain will develop across parts of
southern and eastern Texas as moisture from the Gulf of Mexico
flows inland ahead of an upper-air disturbance approaching from the
Rio Grande Valley. Thunder may accompany some of the rain during
the day along the southern Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will sweep eastward into western Washington and parts of
western Oregon ahead of a Pacific warm front. Meanwhile, cold air
banked across parts of eastern Oregon and Washington will hold its
ground, forcing invading Pacific air to glide over it. Thus, the
stage will be set for areas of snow or freezing rain east of the
Cascade Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Snow showers and snow flurries will follow on the heels of a
cold front speeding off the Northeast coast from the southern and
eastern shores of the Great Lakes to the northern and north-central
Appalachians. However, the air in the wake of the front will not be
exceptionally cold, thereby limiting accumulations in the
traditionally heavy lake-effect snowbelts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Psuedo Cold &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely and Elko, Nev., along with Baker, Ore., registered minimum
temperatures just below zero on Thursday morning. However, at
10,000 feet over eastern Oregon and northern Nevada, readings near
20 degrees were measured by weather balloons. The frigid air was
gathered in a very shallow layer along the ground, but the rest of
the air mass was seasonably mild. Snow cover helped to chill the
air at the surface and create a false sense of arctic cold. Indeed,
once the sun rose, temperatures quickly rose in these gelid spots
and by mid afternoon resembled readings in surrounding locations.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
