<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TLC-GRAMMYS-SPI &LR;      01-06 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TLC-GRAMMYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO `SCRUBS' HERE: TLC GLOWING WITH PRIDE OVER GRAMMY NOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ TLC's Rozanda ``Chilli'' Thomas insists that ``No
Scrubs,'' the song that earned the pop/R&AMP;B vocal trio two of six
Grammy nominations this week, isn't an anti-guy diatribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``All girls go through this,'' an effervescent Thomas said in a
phone call from Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about this guy who has no life. He won't take care of his
kids, he has no intention of getting a job. He's a leech.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys have friends like that. That's why I like to
stress that it's not a male-bashing song. It's about a certain type
of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No Scrubs,'' one of the strongest message songs in TLC's
10-year career, earned nominations for record of the year and best
R&AMP;B performance by a duo or group with vocals. The song also was
nominated for best R&AMP;B song _ not for TLC, but for songwriters
Kevin ``Shekspere'' Briggs, Kandi Burruss and Tameka Cottle.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based TLC _ featuring Thomas, Lisa ``Left Eye''
Lopes and Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins _ also was nominated for album
of the year (for ``FanMail''), song of the year (for ``Unpretty''
by Watkins and producer Dallas Austin), best R&AMP;B album
(``FanMail'') and best short-form music video (``Unpretty'').
</P>
<P>
   In overall nominations, TLC, the top-selling female group in pop
history, trailed only Carlos Santana, who received 10 nominations.
</P>
<P>
   TLC released its first album in 1991 and became a
million-selling supergroup in 1994 with the hit album
``CrazySexyCool,'' which yielded the singles ``Creep, ``Red Light
Special'' and megahit ``Waterfalls.'' The group's sexy, sultry
sound was a huge success.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the group survived a number of setbacks and
personal dramas, including bankruptcy, management squabbles and
Lopes' highly publicized argument with her boyfriend at the time,
former Atlanta Falcons receiver Andre Rison. In a drunken rage,
Lopes set fire to Rison's $800,000 home and smashed two cars; she
was later fined $10,000 and required to go through rehab.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the group's affairs have been far less tumultuous
since manager Bill Diggins signed on about nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best manager ever,'' Thomas said with a tone of
relief. ``I can't say that he hasn't gotten a few gray hairs. But
he is superb.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's slew of Grammy nominations has helped salve old
wounds reflected in the songs on ``FanMail.'' The nominations are
also a source of great pride for the trio, as well as producer and
guiding light Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started working with Dallas, we never really knew what
he was going to do,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started on `FanMail,' we just kind of put the ball in
his hand and told him pretty much what we wanted. We never sat down
with him and said, `OK, we want a more futuristic sound.' He just
came up with that stuff himself. It's incredible to me how he took
us to a new level and gave us a completely new sound.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No Scrubs'' isn't the only message song on ``FanMail.''
``Unpretty,'' based on a poem by Watkins, offers solace for those
who feel unattractive in a world that emphasizes physical beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just for girls, because guys feel unpretty also,''
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys go through being overweight and there's the loss of hair.
You know what I'm sayin'? You guys go through the same stuff we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas admitted that TLC members aren't always as gorgeous as
their photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, when you see us, we do look airbrushed and glamorous
and beautiful. But that's not what it's all about. That's the point
we want to get across in the song.''
</P>
<P>
   The current leg of the group's ``FanMail'' tour began in October
and continues at least through January.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's concert here includes sets by Vega, Blaque and
19-year-old Christina Aguilera, a budding superstar who began her
career on Disney's ``New Mickey Mouse Club.'' Last year, Aguilera's
self-named debut album reached No. 1 on The Billboard 200 album
chart.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilera received Grammy nominations this week for best new
artist, female pop vocal performance (for ``Beautiful Stranger'')
and pop album (``Genie in a Bottle'').
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five cents from each ticket sold will go to local and
national charities, including the Sickle Cell Disease Association
of America. (Member Watkins developed the disease as a child and is
now a spokesperson for the organization.)
</P>
<P>
   Appearing throughout the show on video is a robot named Virtual
Vic-E. Fans will recognize her as the voice in the opening sequence
of ``FanMail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes to life on the screen,'' Thomas said. ``She's like
C-3PO of `Star Wars.' She's very sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   The set was designed by John McGraw, who has worked with Prince
and Madonna. Visual elements and special effects abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lights everywhere and lots of video,'' Thomas said.
``The video screen is like an oval shape, and it's in the center of
the stage. And we have a set of stairs coming down right underneath
the video screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Lopes and Watkins, dressed in futuristic costumes,
perform solo during a segment featuring the trio's favorite songs.
</P>
<P>
   The group also reaches into its distant past, which for younger
fans is ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who come to see us now don't know about that
first album,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we come out and we're dressed just how we were back in
those days _ in huge, huge oversize clothes and the big hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we show clips of the old videos, so that people can tie
everything together. Yep.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the condoms the group used to wear as costume
jewelery?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that, too. It's cool, man. I'm serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
