<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATES07-1STLEDE-COX     01-06 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES07-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    15 PERCENT POLL THRESHOLD SET FOR PRESIDENTIAL DEBATES
 &HT;    Inserts grafs 5-8 with Buchanan, Trump reaction.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The panel that controls presidential debates
announced the formats and sites of this year's events Thursdaween
reality and fairness,'' commission co-chair Paul Kirk said at a
news conference. ``There have to be rules to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the candidate's name must appear on enough state
ballots to have a mathematical chance of winning an Electoral
College majority, and the candidate must fulfill the constitutional
requirements for becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   Former Republican Pat Buchanan, who is seeking the Reform Party
nomination, immediately denounced the commission's 15 percent
threshold as a ``conspiracy'' by the Republican and Democratic
parties and promised legal action against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing but a Beltway conspiracy by the two
establishment parties to corner the market forever on the
presidency of the United States,'' Buchanan said, noting that the
commission's co-chairs are former heads of the Democratic and
Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Coke and Pepsi saying no other soft drink can enter
the market unless they meet a certain criteria,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   New York real estate developer Donald Trump, who also is
planning a campaign for the Reform Party nomination, said in a
statement, ``I am not surprised that the two-party political
establishment wants to keep the American people from having a third
choice. But he expressed confidence that if he chooses to run he
would register ``strong poll ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Trump polls about 10 percent nationally, and Buchanan
about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarian Party also denounced the commission's action,
saying the 15 percent threshold would exclude Jesse Ventura-like
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``National debates play s its nominee, Ross Perot, into debates
with President Clinton and Republican nominee Bob Dole. But the
courts backed the commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 general election, Perot got 8 percent of the popular
vote. But in 1992, when Perot participated in debates with Clinton
and then-President Bush, he went on to receive 19 percent of the
popular vote. He did not win any electoral votes in either
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which has run presidential election debates
since 1988, will rely on technical advice from the Gallup
Organization for determining which candidates meet the 15 percent
threshold in polls by ABC News/Washington Post, CBS News/New York
Times, NBC News/Wall Street Journal, CNN/USA Today/Gallup and Fox
News/Opinion Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The commission announced that it will hold three presidential
debates next fall: Oct. 3 in Boston, Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem,
N.C., and Oct. 17 in St. Louis. The commission also plans a vice
presidential debate Oct. 5 in Danville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Each debate will be 90 minutes long and will be broadcast
nationally at 9 p.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fahrenkopf, who serves as co-chair with Kirk, said the
debates would be a mixed series of formats, with candidates
answering and responding to questions, but with a single moderator
rather than a panel of reporters, as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   He said the commission favors the town hall format, in which
between 150 and 200 people are invited to ask questions of the
candidates. He said the town hall format is ``clearly the most
popular'' with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Fahrenkopf noted, however, that the candidates will have ``some
say'' in the debate formats.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that there is no law requiring a candidate to
participate in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we can require any candidate to do anything
that he or she doesn't want to do,'' he said. But debates have
become such an integral part of presidential elections that it
would be difficult for any candidate to not participate, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
