 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Jan. 7, 2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _ MIAMI _ With emotions running high following the
decision by the INS to return 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to his
father in communist Cuba, what will it take to actually make this
happen by the Jan. 14 deadline? Developing. (Williams, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Palm Beach Post Photos from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Post reporter Bill Douthat is in Miami and will offer
feeds for Williams' lead story.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-YELTSIN _ BETHLEHEM _ Former Russian President Boris
Yeltsin begins a two-day visit to Palestine to attend Orthodox
Christmas celebrations. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOPDEBATE _ BEDFORD, N.H. _ Coverage of GOP debate in New
Hampshire. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES _ WASHINGTON _ The Commission on Presidential Debates
has proposed three debates involving the major presidential
candidates nexts fall. But the commission plans to exclude any
candidate who does not meet a 15 percent threshhold in the polls.
That could be trouble for the Reform Party and other minor parties.
(Shepard, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTERS _ WASHINGTON _ A new poll says Gov. George W. Bush
quickly loses his appeal among women voters once they take a closer
look at his record in Texas. The poll, conducted for Emily's List,
suggests the Democratic Party will try to build on its support
among women in this year's election. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   JEB _ In a rare campaign venture out of state, Bush, Jeb that
is, and about 130 of the Flordia governor's Republican faithful are
boarding a charter flight Jan. 19 to spend the day stumping the
streets of Hanover, N.H. for Texas Gov. George W. Bush. (Crowley,
Palm Beach Post). 6.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STRATEGIST06 _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Three weeks before the
voting begins, the top strategist for Gov. George W. Bush's
presidential campaign says there is no way that Arizona Sen. John
McCain can win the GOP nomination. Karl Rove also believes that
McCain's strategy, targeted at four states, is fatally flawed. Bush
would be flogged in the media if he had plotted anything less than
a nationwide strategy, he said. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story developed Wednesday night. It is being offered
again on the budget for Friday papers.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DIET _ WASHINGTON _ C. Everett Koop, head of Shape Up
America!, holds a news conference to announce a new Internet-based
weight loss initiative that allows Internet users to manage their
weight-loss programs online. (Turay, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   BACTERIA-RESIST _ ATLANTA _ The CDC reports today that a
63-year-old woman who died in Illinois last April was infected with
a Staph infection that had become partially resistant to
vancomycin, one of the ``drugs of last resort'' against
drug-resistant bacteria. She represents only the fourth case of
VRAS found in the United States, but in an accompanying paper CDC
says that there may be more such cases not yet recognized because
labs the agency has surveyed may not be equipped to identify the
resistant bugs. The continuing development of drug-resistance in
bacteria is of great concern because so few drugs are left to
combat the infections, and because the resistance has developed in
bacteria that are very common in hospitals - where large numbers of
sick and immune-weakened patients provide a fertile breeding
ground. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTIONS _ Abortions in the US have reached a new all-time low,
continuing a trend that has held steady for 20 years, the CDC says,
even with the addition of medical abortions (performed by the
administration of RU-486 or other drugs). In a paper released
Thursday, the agency reports on abortions in 1997, the most recent
year for which full data are available. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The Florida Senate on
Thursday gives final approval to allowing Floridas death row
inmates to choose to die by lethal injection. With electrocutions
on hold pendingreview, the Senate voted 37-0 to pass a bill
giving prisoners the choice to get a lethal injection. Lawmakers
are hoping to make moot the question the U.S. Supreme Court is
considering: whether death in the state's electric chair is cruel
and unusual punishment. The House was considering a similar bill
and both chambers have until Friday afternoon to work out their
differences. (Date/Gelbart, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FLAGFIGHT _ The South Carolina Heritage Coalition is planning a
big march in support of the Confederate flag on Saturday, Jan. 8.
An advancer on how the march is likely only to make both sides in
the debate dig in their heels. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
