<HEADLINE>
STYLISH `CROWN' HAS FLAIR TO SPARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE THOMAS CROWN AFFAIR'
</P>
<P>
   Modernized remakes can be shaky affairs. Remember ``The
Haunting''?
</P>
<P>
   But ``Thomas Crown,'' '90s-style, improves vastly on the
now-dated grooviness of the 1968 original, adding gusto, style and
debonair flair.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Brosnan gets to open up nicely beyond his stoic James
Bond persona as Crown, a billionaire businessman who cherishes art
that he cannot buy.
</P>
<P>
   He also adores thrills, whether flying gliders or breaking into
a museum. So Tommy boy steals paintings _ albeit in strangely
playful and inventive ways.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's a thief, no less than the lowest thug who robs a
liquor store. Picky, picky. Crown seduces us with bloodless crimes
enacted with irresistible panache.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Russo plays the impossibly glamorous insurance investigator
who rightly reasons Brosnan has stolen a famed Monet from a New
York museum.
</P>
<P>
   Although she bluntly tells him she's onto him, she and Brosnan
engage in a heady romance, sparring in a civilized quarry-prey way.
</P>
<P>
   Like a good cat burglar, this movie is light on its feet,
whether its lovers are whisking away on exotic holidays or Brosnan
is staging his ingenious heists.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Leary lends some grounding as the beleaguered Manhattan
detective on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McQueen and Faye Dunaway played the leads in the original,
a film that used split-screen gimmickry to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   Its theatrical trailer is included on the new film's DVD, along
with the remake's trailer and audio commentary by director John
McTiernan (``Die Hard'').
</P>
<P>
   As caper flicks go, this remake is far more fun, elegant and
sophisticated. Yet it's also quite raw during its love-making
scenes. Be advised that Russo often bares more than her soul for
her art.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, MGM, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`DON'T LOOK BACK' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This documentary of Bob Dylan's 1965 English concert tour is an
intriguing time capsule of some hard days and nights in the folk
great's life.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Beatles _ just on a smaller scale _ Dylan attracts
crazed, screaming fans who stalk his hotels and pound against his
getaway cars. Director D.A. Pennebaker, who also helmed ``Monterey
Pop,'' captures that fervency nicely.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly his film is an insider's look at dressing rooms,
hotel hideaways and interview rounds, as a surly Dylan spars
belligerently with the press and accosts over-eager admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking himself seriously to a fault, he's rarely charming or
humorous. But Pennebaker's nonjudgmental personality portrait shows
a man doing his best to maintain focus amid a hurricane of hysteria
and scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Pennebaker neglects the music.
</P>
<P>
   In public and in private, Dylan performs many of his classics
(as well as Hank Williams songs), leading to a triumphant
engagement at London's Royal Albert Hall. There, the man armed with
a guitar and a harmonica has thousands enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in black-and-white, the film has a starkness and intimacy
well suited to Dylan's simple, solo approach _ his last folk hurrah
before shifting to electrified rock.
</P>
<P>
   On DVD, ``Don't Look Back'' includes a feature-length audio
commentary by Pennebaker and Dylan's road manager, Bob Neuwirth,
who's quite prominent on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Their ruminations add a revealing layer to the film, making it
more of a true documentary than the original cut.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are production notes, the original ``cue-card''
trailer and an outtake version, as well as previously unissued
audio-only performances of ``It's All Over Now,'' ``Baby Blue'' and
four more songs.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1967, unrated, New Video, VHS $19.95, DVD $24.95 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PHANTOM': APRIL 4 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As expected, ``Star Wars: Episode I'' _ The Phantom Menace will
reach VHS April 4. But no DVD date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Creator George Lucas may be standing by his threat not to issue
any ``Star Wars'' film on DVD until all six have played
theatrically. That would mean 2005 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   For the original trilogy, maybe so. But some industry insiders
still expect ``Phantom Menace'' to launch on DVD this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A LATE ARRIVAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sayonara,'' a sensitive story of love and culture clash in
postwar Japan, was released in 1957, but it's just now debuting on
video (MGM, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Brando and Red Buttons star in the story of U.S. military
men stationed in Japan and romancing Japanese women in the early
'50s. The film had 10 Academy Award nominations and won four
statuettes, including Oscars for Buttons and Miyoshi Umeki for
their supporting roles in the drama.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the same price are ``Alexander the Great,'' ``Marty,''
``Never on Sunday,'' ``The Party,'' ``Topkapi'' and ``The World of
Henry Orient.''
</P>
<P>
   Newly available for $9.94 are ``Blame It on Rio,'' ``Born
Losers,'' ``F/X,'' ``Caveman'' and ``Jason's Lyric.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
