<HEADLINE>
U.S. INTERVENTIONIST POLICY MAKES US TERRORISM TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB ROBB  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - The people of the United States were spared a terrorist
attack on Millennium Day. But let us not spare ourselves serious
reflection about our vulnerability to terrorist attack, and how our
current foreign policy puts us at greater risk than is necessary.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 273 international terrorist incidents,
according to the counterterrorism office of the State Department.
Forty percent of them were directed at U.S. targets, mostly U.S.
government offices and the corporate assets of American companies
in foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   International terrorists struck on American soil, however, in
1993, when the World Trade Center was bombed. A similar attack may
have been planned this year for Seattle, which prudently canceled
its millennial celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional explosives do damage enough. But the threat of
broader-scale death and destruction is growing.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department estimates that 26 countries currently
have a chemical-weapons capability and that 12 more are developing
one. Ten nations are thought to have or be developing biological
weapons. It is not at all inconceivable that these weapons will
become available to international terrorists intending to use them
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, President Clinton cited the threat of chemical or
biological attack on U.S. soil as one of the biggest challenges the
United States will face over the next century. For once, he was not
being hyperbolic.
</P>
<P>
   America is a target of international terrorism in part because
of our status as the leading economic power in the world and an
exporter of capitalism. Free markets rattle settled patterns of
life and are regarded as a threat by authoritarian regimes and
those who fear the corrupting influence of materialism often
unleashed by improved living standards and expanded economic
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   America is also a target because we are the champion of liberty
and democratic governments, unsettling notions to some in a world
much of which is still evolving from tribalistic or theocratic
governing structures.
</P>
<P>
   In short, we are a target of international terrorism, in part,
because of who we are. We cannot, and should not, do anything to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   But we are also a target of internationalism terrorism because
of what we do.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has asserted the right to arbitrate
territorial disputes all over the globe, even if the outcome
doesn't directly affect our national security.
</P>
<P>
   The world seethes with ethnic and religious conflict,
territorial disputes and irredentist movements. According to the
National Defense Council Foundation, a third of the globe, 65
nations, was involved in some kind of armed conflict last year. The
United States seeks to exert influence, in some way, in virtually
every such dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Even if we don't intervene militarily _ as we have, during just
this decade, in Iraq, Somalia, Bosnia, Haiti and Serbia _ we
generally try to influence the outcome and the behavior of the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   If we insist on taking sides in these disputes, we should not be
surprised when those against whose interests we intervene regard
us, accurately, as their enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Our current policy regarding terrorism is unrealistic and
dangerous. We fail to acknowledge that our interventionist foreign
policy not only puts our armed forces at risk, but our civilian
population as well.
</P>
<P>
   And we claim that we will never negotiate with terrorists or
have decisions affected by terrorism. The latter is a lie, and the
former is unwise.
</P>
<P>
   We abandoned our military mission in Lebanon after a suicide
bomb killed 241 marines. An elusive and deadly local warlord ran us
out of Somalia, after we decided he ought to be ousted.
</P>
<P>
   India recently negotiated for the release of passengers on a
hijacked plane, successfully working through an Afghan movement
that the U.S. regards as a terrorist organization and, as a matter
of policy, would refuse to deal with. The Indian prime minister
defended negotiating with the hijackers, Himalayan revolutionaries,
with simple eloquence: Saving 155 lives justified it.
</P>
<P>
   There are risks in acknowledging the need sometimes to yield to
and to negotiate with terrorists. But not risks any greater than
those resulting from the interventionist foreign policy conducted
by both our political parties. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bob Robb at bob.robb(at)ArizonaRepublic.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1800EST &QL; 
