<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-VOTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GENDER GAP NOT A PROBLEM FOR BUSH SO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The gender gap that plagued the last Republican
presidential campaign is so far not a threat to Texas Gov. George
W. Bush in the current contest, according to a poll released
Thursday by Emily's List, a Democratic-aligned organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Monitor poll of 1,202 likely voters _ 801 women and
401 men _ showed Bush, the Republican frontrunner, leading
Democratic Vice President Al Gore among women, 42 percent to 41
percent, and tied with former Sen. Bill Bradley among women, at 39
percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Men preferred Bush over Gore 47 percent to 31 percent, and over
Bradley 42 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the same poll in April 1996 found President Clinton
leading former Sen. Robert Dole, then the leading Republican
challenger, 57 percent to 38 percent _ a 19 point gap. Among men,
Clinton led Dole 51 percent to 45 percent. In the general election
Clinton beat Dole among female voters by 17 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush or any Republican to even approach equality in the
women's vote this November would be a serious blow to Democratic
prospects of retaining the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is ``clearly better positioned among women voters than
other Republican candidates have been in the past,'' said
Democratic pollster Geoff Garin, who conducted the survey with
pollster Celinda Lake. ``This is a challenge for Democrats,'' Garin
said. ``There's no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that in party preference and in so-called
``generic'' congressional contests this fall between Democrats and
Republicans, Democrats still lead among women.
</P>
<P>
   But it also showed that while women prefer Democrats on issues
such as Social Security, education and health care, they rate
Republicans higher on ethics and moral values. These issues include
reforming the campaign finance system and President Clinton's
impeachment and near-removal from office last year in the Monica
Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Garin and Lake said Thursday that Bush's support among women is
thin and is based more on women's opinion of his character and
background rather than his stand on issues.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that after women listened to campaign-style
attacks on Bush's gubernatorial record, his anti-gun-control views
and his opposition to strong regulation of managed care health
plans, they found his candidacy less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Before hearing the attacks, 34 percent of women said Bush
appealed to them a great deal or quite a bit while 37 percent said
he did not. Afterward, 29 percent said they found him appealing
while 45 percent did not.
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List president Ellen Malcolm said of Bush: ``He's got a
lot of sizzle, but when you get to the steak, it doesn't sell. The
good news for Democrats here is that when women start paying
attention to his positions on the issues, they'll move away from
him.'' Emily's List is a group that raises money for pro-choice
Democratic women candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the poll showed
that Bush had received dividends from campaigning as a
``compassionate conservative'' and focusing on family issues such
as tax cuts and quality of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it confirms Gov. Bush has broad-based support among
people from all walks of life, including women,'' McClellan said.
Bush won 65 percent of the female vote in his 1998 re-election as
governor of Texas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Emily's List poll attempted to identify women who will be
swing voters this year, similar to the so-called ``soccer moms'' of
the 1996 election. Lake listed the following groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Suburban women, most of them married, in their 30s and 40s who
prefer Democrats on issues such as education and health care and
Republicans on moral values. These women make up 18 percent of the
female electorate, and at this point they favor Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women between 60 and 74, the majority of whom also at this
point support Bush. They make up 10 percent of the female
electorate, and their interests are Social Security, moral decline,
health care, crime and education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hispanic women, who are traditionally part of the Democratic
base and who are 6 percent of the female electorate. They still
prefer the Democratic Party and Democratic congressional candidates
generally but right now they too are leaning toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lower-income non-Hispanic white women, who comprise 10 percent
of the female electorate and work in blue collar, clerical or
service-oriented jobs. They live in households with annual incomes
below $40,000. Although generally Democratic, they are now equally
divided between Bush on one side and either of the two Democrats on
the other. They say they are concerned about health care, moral
decline and education, and many confess they are not yet paying
attention to presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
</TEXT>
