<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-YELTSIN-0107-     01-06 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-YELTSIN-0107-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 12th graf, clarifies age of Orthodox Church to read '...
more than 1,500-year history.'
 &HT;    ON FIRST TRIP AS 'FIRST PRESIDENT,' YELTSIN SEES HOLY LAND
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On his first trip since his resignation, Boris
Yeltsin hit the Holy Land Thursday saying he is adjusting ``little
by little'' to no longer being Russian president.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Yeltsin was in for a slow adjustment indeed. The
man whose lavish lifestyle and tempestuous rule earned him the
nickname ``Tsar Boris'' was draped in the pageantry of Orthodox
Christianity, surrounded by heads of state and toasted as a man of
power.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin wept with joy, according to the Associated Press, in
wishing Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat luck with his
hoped-for Palestinian state. ``Spasibo, spasibo, spasibo,'' Arafat
said, using Russian to thank Yeltsin for his support in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the silver-maned, 68-year-old rose from the middle
of dinner at a Bethlehem hotel, the 70-year-old Arafat, with his
signature khaki uniform walked Yeltsin hand-in-hand through the
lobby to his limousine.
</P>
<P>
   The former Russian leader came to the birthplace of Christianity
to celebrate the Christmas of the Orthodox churches Friday. He
pledged to work for peace, even while promising that Russia's army
would complete its assault on rebels in Chechnya within two months.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, he updated the prediction to a month, even as
Russian generals back home were acknowledging setbacks in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin traveled on his official presidential plane with his
usual entourage of cooks, doctors, family members and aides.
Clarifying his new title, Press Secretary Dmitri Yakushkin
insisted, ``he is not the ex-president, he's not the former
president, he's the First President.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli President Ezer Weizman toasted Yeltsin as ``president of
a great country.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin resigned his presidency unexpectedly on Dec. 31 after
eight years as Russia's first democratically elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the second day of the three-day trip described by
aides as a personal pilgrimage. At the invitation of the Greek
Orthodox Church, he was joined by heads of state from eastern
European countries with large orthodox populations.
</P>
<P>
   Also present were the clerical leaders of the 15 branches of
Orthodoxy _ such as the Russian Orthodox, Greek Orthodox, and
Romanian Orthodox churches. They were draped in their black robes,
red sashes and diamond-crucifixes. Some carried silver-tipped
staffs, and wore white cylindrical hats and Byzantine necklaces
supporting icons of Christ and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Orthodox Metropolitan Timothy, a high-ranking member of
the church's Jerusalem branch, said it was the largest meeting of
church leaders in the church's more than 1,500-year history. There
are about 200 million Orthodox believers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   At the Greek Orthodox Patriachate in Jerusalem's walled Old
City, Yeltsin and the other leaders received the golden medallion
of the Order of the Knights of the Holy Sepulchre. The medal was
founded for the soldiers who protected Christ's Jerusalem tomb in
the Fourth Century.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the ceremony, Yeltsin told reporters the war in
Chechnya would end in two months when ``we will plant the Russian
flag in Chechnya.'' U.S. officials have criticized Russia for
bombardments that have killed or displaced thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the ceremony, Yeltsin signed a document urging peace in
the Middle East and said, ``I swear to do my best to promote
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli President Weizman, Yeltsin touted Russia's
cooperation with Israel and said Russia has done away with
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have put an end to that,'' he said, chopping his hand into
his palm. While speaking, he gazed at Natan Sharansky, a former
Russian political prisoner now a minister in the Israeli
government.
</P>
<P>
   And, meeting Arafat in Bethlehem, the ``First President'' waxed
sentimental about his resignation and his hand-picked successor,
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed session shown on Russia television Thursday night,
Yeltsin said, ``Russians are crying like I cried about my
resignation. They are scared about the unknown of having a new
President, but I am sure I chose the right person to take my
place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Moscow Correspondent Margaret Coker contributed
to this story.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
