<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     01-06 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES OVER, BACK TO BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The New Year is past, and that means two things in
the movie business: It is time to get serious about the Oscars, as
opposed to throwing every name studio executives can think of
against the wall to see what sticks, and it's time to look beyond
the winter releases for an idea of what the summer movie season,
the most lucrative box office period of the year, will look like.
</P>
<P>
   It's often easy to look at the accumulation of year-end critics'
awards to get some idea of what is likely to dominate when the
Academy Awards are handed out. But this year, that's almost
impossible. The critics were all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   The National Board of Review named Sam Mendes' ``American
Beauty'' the year's best picture and gave the top acting awards to
Russell Crowe for ``The Insider'' and Janet McTeer for
``Tumbleweeds.'' The New York Film Critics Circle picked
``Topsy-Turvy,'' Mike Leigh's semi-musical about Gilbert and
Sullivan, as the year's best and liked Richard Farnsworth's
performance in ``The Straight Story'' and Hilary Swank's in ``Boys
Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Film Critics Association liked ``The Insider''
best and gave acting nods to Crowe and Ms. Swank. And this week the
Online Film Critics Association picked ``American Beauty,'' its
star, Kevin Spacey, and Reese Witherspoon, who plays a high school
student running for class president in ``Election.''
</P>
<P>
   So roll the dice.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's your impression that more and more awards are
cropping up each year, it may interest you to learn that Daily
Variety, which has been keeping track of the proliferating honors,
reports that 3,182 entertainment awards were handed out in 1999 at
332 ceremonies, an average of 9 prizes every day of the year.
That's up from 3,138 awards at 252 ceremonies in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As for the summer, the jostling has already begun for the two
most prized weekends. Tom Cruise in ``Mission: Impossible 2'' is
all by himself on Memorial Day weekend. Two big action pictures are
vying for Independence Day, though, with Roland Emmerich's
``Patriot,'' starring Mel Gibson as a Revolutionary War hero,
opening on June 28, and George Clooney as a wave-tossed fisherman
in Wolfgang Petersen's ``Perfect Storm'' on June 30. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making Waves &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The small flotilla bobbed in the gentle swells off Dana Point,
south of Los Angeles, one recent afternoon. It was during the final
days of shooting Petersen's adaptation of ``The Perfect Storm,''
the nonfiction best seller by Sebastian Junger. The soup boat had
just arrived from shore, delivering a snack (today's flavor:
cheese) to the crew jammed aboard the film's main set, the Andrea
Gail, a semi-decrepit fishing boat that carries the story's heroes
into the middle of what many considered the storm of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo-ho-ho-ho, a pirate's life for me,'' sang George Clooney,
who plays the ship's captain, as he waited for the next camera
setup. Mark Wahlberg, in waterproof overalls slick with stage
blood, leaned against the railing, woozy from the rolling of the
waves. ``I'm just trying to keep the soup down,'' he said.
Petersen, a scarf around his neck, talked over the shot with John
Seale, the cinematographer.
</P>
<P>
   The Andrea Gail (actually, it is a sister ship to the boat that
went into the real perfect storm, in 1991, from the same
manufacturer) swayed precipitously in the swells, as members of the
crew stepped over the props, giant rubber swordfish cut into pieces
on the narrow deck.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the filming was completed in Gloucester, Mass., where
the actual Andrea Gail had been berthed, and on the Warner Brothers
lot in Burbank. A few pre-storm shots were all that were needed
now. In the one being filmed at the moment, Clooney informed the
others that their ice machine had broken down, making it impossible
for them to keep the swordfish fresh while working the North
Atlantic and compelling them to head back to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen said he was intent upon making the film as authentic as
possible. But what the film may be remembered for is its new
generation of digital effects to simulate the storm's 100-foot
waves.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Elswit, an effects supervisor at Industrial Light and
Magic who was visiting the set, described it this way: The first
generation of the company's computer-generated effects were those
used in the early ``Star Wars'' movies, mostly shot against the
black background of outer space. The second generation came with
``Jurassic Park,'' when new computer modeling could create
realistic three-dimensional creatures that seemed to reflect light
and actually exist in the movie's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing in `The Perfect Storm' is the next step,''
she said. One of the most difficult effects to create has been
water because it is so multifaceted and, well, fluid. But new
coding written for the movie will make it possible to create
authentic-looking waves of a height and ferocity never before seen
on the screen, she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, pausing to munch on a grilled-chicken sandwich on the
ship's bridge, described how he was able to see exactly what the
Andrea Gail would look like if caught in an enormous wave, by using
computer story-boarding programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say to them, `Put the camera on the ship's stern and
give me a 60-foot wave,''' Petersen said. ``And they would click
the keys, and suddenly it would appear on the screen in full
motion. You could see how the ship would move and what the wave
would look like. If you wanted it bigger, you could say, `OK, make
it a 62-foot wave.' Or move the camera to the bow, or whatever you
want. It's an amazing tool for a director because I was able to
figure out where I wanted to place my cameras on the deck when
shooting the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   The desired goal, he said, was not to see how big he could make
the wave or how jaw-dropping the effect, but to create a
computer-generated storm to look _ and be _ as authentic as
possible. ``I'm not doing it for the effects, but to make it
believable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the actors were taking their places. Crew members
watered down the deck, smeared a little more fake fish blood all
around and with a spray can gave the actors a final spritz to make
their faces glisten as if with sweat and sea mist. ``OK, here we
go,'' Petersen said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Submarine Story &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Mostow sat in an editing room in the back of a bungalow
on the Universal Studios lot, just around the corner from Steven
Spielberg's Amblin Entertainment compound, watching some of the
underwater scenes from his movie ``U-571,'' to be released in
April. His partner, the former Universal production executive Hal
Lieberman, sat on a nearby sofa, and they watched the digital
editing machine as the sounds of depth charges rattled through the
room. Boom! Boom!
</P>
<P>
   The film, loosely based on an incident in which a German coding
device was recovered from a stranded U-boat, stars Matthew
McConaughey and Bill Paxton. Shot at studios in Rome and on a big
set on Malta, the movie is intended, Mostow said, like Petersen's,
to be as authentic to the period as possible. This includes
recreating the dangerous, dripping, cramped conditions inside the
World War I-vintage submarines used early in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Mostow said he became a submarine freak during his research on
the film, his first since ``Breakdown'' (1997). And he was
delighted to inherit the seaside set in Malta where ``Cutthroat
Island'' and other movies have been made over the years, he said.
But he was chagrined to find that his was not the only major
Hollywood production under way on the relatively tiny Mediterranean
island.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``We'd have people come and tour our sets, and they'd
say: `Whoa! Wow! This is big! This is terrific!''' Then they'd go
over the hill to visit the set of Ridley Scott's ``Gladiator'' (due
on May 5) and find an entire Roman street, including arches,
temples, arcades and most of a life-size Coliseum. (The top of the
arena will be added digitally in post-production.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little disconcerting to be only the second biggest
movie set in Malta,'' Mostow said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miracle Worker &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ed Harris, fresh from directing himself and Marcia Gay Harden in
``Pollock,'' a biography of the painter Jackson Pollock being
released this year, said he was relieved to step from behind the
camera and focus solely on his character in Agnieszka Holland's
``Third Miracle.'' Harris plays a priest who specializes in
debunking alleged miracles. It also gave him a chance to explore
his own notions of spirituality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a luxury to remove myself from day-to-day life
and consider the twists of faith,'' said Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The film, shot in eight weeks in Toronto, opened in New York and
Los Angeles on Dec. 29 and will extend to more cities. While he
hopes it connects with audiences, he said, he also recognizes that
the subject matter may be a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a film that needs to be handled carefully,'' Harris said.
``I don't think it's one of those where you put it in 2,000
theaters on Friday and then look at the box score on Monday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
