<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, January 7, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WEIZMAN (Jerusalem) _ Israeli president, whose verbal
excesses have never landed him in any serious trouble with public,
suddenly is under intense pressure to resign over alleged
indiscretions in accepting large sum of money as gift from
non-Israeli friend. By Aliza Marcus. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-FLU (Montreal) _ A flu epidemic, an acute shortage of
nurses and too many doctors off sunning in Florida transform
emergency rooms across Canada into disaster zones. And everyone in
Canada's ailing socialized medical system, it seems, is blaming
someone else. By Colin Nickerson. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-DEBATE (Durham, N.H.) _ Two leading and four other
Republicans meet for a debate in New Hampshire. By Michael Kranish
and Jill Zuckman. 1000 words. (Late)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-MCCAIN (Undated) -- Sen. John McCain's recent behavior
is a more vivid example of the stranglehold that special interests
exert on Washington decision-making than the public denunciations
of the system that have become a staple of his presidential
campaign. By Walter V. Robinson. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-UN (New York) _ For the first time, the UN Security Council
will be the venue for a speech by a US vice president. Bradley
people say Al Gore speech on AIDS in Africa Monday is nothing but a
high-profile campaign venue. By Joe Lauria.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-TAAS (San Antonio) _ Throughout Texas, thousands of
students have failed a test needed to graduate. But another
troubling development has emerged: Latinos and blacks are failing
at higher rates than whites. Now, a federal judge expected to rule
on a suit alleging the exam is discriminatory. By Cindy Rodriguez.
1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EDUCATION (Undated) _ The Civil Rights Project at Harvard
University says Texas education reform deepens the educational gap
between whites and minorities, affluent and impoverished students.
By Doreen Iudica Vigue. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FDA-SUPPLEMENTS (Undated) _ In a major victory for manufacturers
of dietary supplements, the FDA will now allow greater latitude in
the health claims made for these products. By Judy Foreman. 700
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HMO-BAILOUT (Boston) _ As New England's largest health plan
enters the uncertain terrain of state receivership _ a notch above
bankruptcy _ state regulators, lawmakers, insurance experts, and
major customers stress the need for urgency in putting Harvard
Pilgrim back on track. By Richard A. Knox. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOTUS-PAPOWS (Undated) _ Jeffrey Papows, the embattled head of
Lotus Development Corp., quits, following a year in which he was
sued for sex discrimination and accused of lying on his resume
about his education and military record. By Ross Kerber. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEATING-OIL (Undated) _ Fuel oil prices soar from last winter's
abnormal lows -- not the 50 percent some doomsayers foresaw, but
still enough to push up home heating bills as much as 37 percent.
By Jerry Ackerman. 600 words.
</P>
