<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PREVIEW07-COX     01-06 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PREVIEW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everyone out to catch Woods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Duval has returned as a leader in ousted body
fat, looking more like a distance runner than the world's No.
2-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman won a pricey preliminary to the PGA Tour season four
days ago, pocketing $1 million for his first victory since the 1997
Loch Lomond Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, without a victory in 1999 for the first time
since turning pro, pledges that it won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Sergio Garcia, 19, will play 16 to 18 events on the PGA
Tour this year.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Operation Catch That Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   It is the dominant theme as the PGA Tour stages its first
official event of the season, the Mercedes Championships, beginning
today at Kapalua's Plantation Course on the Hawaiian island of
Maui. Duval is defending champion at the Mercedes, which assembles
tournament winners from 1999, but Tiger Woods was the PGA Tour's
runaway player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the mere mortals of the PGA Tour were dominated by
Woods, 24, during an eight-title season that produced $6.6 million
in official earnings. Woods' competitors realized that they must
either improve or risk getting stomped again.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seriously believes that a player in today's game can
equal Byron Nelson's 11-tournament winning streak of 1945, but when
Woods tees off today he will be trying to win his fifth event in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Duval dominated the spring with four victories before the
Masters _ he shot a final-round 59 to win at the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic _ but was doubled by Woods by the end of the season.
Arguably the best player who hasn't won a major tournament, Duval
needed no more messages. After working out obsessively since
October, he reported to last week's Williams World Challenge, where
he finished behind Lehman in Scottsdale, Ariz., with a
stripped-down, strengthened physique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like if I can be a more fit and stronger athlete, then
that will translate into better golf,'' said Duval, who will focus
on the majors. ``I really feel like it's an important piece of the
puzzle I need to put together to really get beyond where I've been
and improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Tour has other important story lines:
</P>
<P>
   _ Casey Martin, with a tour card and cart key in hand, will make
his PGA Tour debut at the Bob Hope in Palm Springs, Calif., Jan.
19-23, unless a 1998 court ruling is overturned. Afflicted by a
deteriorating circulatory disease in his right leg, Martin finished
in the top 15 last year on the Nike _ now Buy.com _ Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nicklaus, 30, son of Jack, qualified through PGA Tour
School in November and also will make his debut at the Bob Hope.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two of golf's three rotating majors are appropriate for a 2000
season _ the June 15-18 U.S. Open at Pebble Beach, Calif., and the
July 20-23 British Open at St. Andrews, Scotland. The PGA
Championship returns to less than storied Valhalla Golf Club in
Louisville, Ky. Its designer, Jack Nicklaus, is healthy after
hip-replacement surgery and plans to play in all four of the majors
he missed last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Masters fills its field differently in 2000, no longer
guaranteeing a spot for PGA Tour winners from the previous year,
but inviting the top 40 from the money list and top 50 from the
world rankings. Six players who won PGA Tour events last year _
Olin Browne, J.L. Lewis, Rich Beem, Tom Pernice Jr., Brian
Henninger and Brad Faxon _ probably will not get to Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two events have been added to the PGA Tour schedule _ the
Sept. 14-17 Pennsylvania Classic at Waynesboro Country Club in
Paoli, Pa., and the Oct. 19-22 Tampa Bay Classic at the Westin
Innisbrook Resort.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Ryder Cup takes the year off, with the return of the
Presidents Cup at the Robert Trent Jones Golf Club in Gainesville,
Va., Oct. 19-22. The U.S. team will try to reverse an embarrassing
loss to the Internationals in Australia in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Payne Stewart's absence will be felt all season, but more at
the two Pebble Beach events where he would have defended _ the Feb.
3-6 AT&AMP;T tournament and the June 15-18 U.S. Open. Close friend Paul
Azinger, who volunteered his services, will replace Stewart at the
AT&AMP;T's media day next month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
