<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CATHOLICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AFFRONT TO VATICAN, CHINA'S CHURCH CONSECRATES BISHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a move that the Vatican says will damage efforts to
mend its relations with Beijing, China's state-sanctioned Catholic
Church consecrated five new bishops here Thursday, just hours
before Pope John Paul II consecrated 12 bishops at St. Peter's
Basilica.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour ceremony, on a wintry morning in an unheated
Beijing cathedral, adhered closely to the rites of a traditional
Roman Catholic consecration. But the bishops, who range in age from
35 to 73, were named by the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association
_ a sort of parallel church that answers to the Chinese government
_ and not by the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   China's Communist government does not recognize the pope's right
to appoint bishops in China, arguing that it would violate national
sovereignty. Formal relations with the Vatican were severed a
couple of years after the Communists came to power in 1949. The
Vatican has recently tried to re-establish relations with China,
but its diplomatic recognition of Taiwan has been a sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ceremony may throw up another hurdle. China brushed
aside a strong protest by the Vatican in holding the consecration,
and although one of the new bishops asked the congregation to pray
for Pope John Paul II, the ceremony _ and its timing _ amounted to
a show of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``An agreement between China and the Vatican would require a lot
of compromise on both sides,'' said Beatrice Leung, an expert in
religion and politics at Lingnan University in Hong Kong. ``This
kind of challenge is not a way to compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese authorities seemed seemed well aware of the
sensitivity of Thursday's ceremony. Plainclothes police officers
were outside the Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception, an austere
building made all the more forbidding by a chilling winter wind.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the congregation of 300, including representatives of
the Communist Party's religious affairs bureau, shivered as the
presiding bishop, Liu Yuanren of Nanjing, bestowed miters and
golden staffs on the new bishops. Liu, who is chief of the National
Bishops' Conference, exhorted the five men to lead a ``growing and
flourishing Chinese church'' into a new golden age.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriotic Catholic Association says it has 4 million members
who worship at 5,000 churches across China. But the Roman Catholic
Church remains a potent force here, with as many as 10 million
members who worship secretly, risking arrest and imprisonment for
their practices.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of estrangement from Rome, Mass is still
celebrated in Latin, as well as in Chinese. But the opening of
China in the past two decades has opened the church as well. As it
grapples with familiar problems, like attracting young people in a
secular society, the line between the official and unofficial
church sometimes seems blurred. In the gift shop of the Beijing
cathedral Thursday, a postcard of the pope was displayed alongside
portraits of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really two churches,'' said the Rev. John Russell, a
Jesuit in Hong Kong who has worked in China for more than three
decades. ``In theology, they differ very slightly. The sticking
point is the appointment of bishops, which is why this consecration
is seen as a slap in the face to the pope.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rome Thursday, the pope marked the feast of the Epiphany by
ordaining bishops from Hungary, Angola, the United States and
several other countries. None of them was Chinese. Earlier this
week, the Vatican expressed ``surprise and disappointment'' at the
Chinese appointments, saying they would hamper efforts to restore
ties between the Vatican and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision has been taken at a time when hopes were raised
in various quarters of moves toward a normalization of relations
between the Holy See and Beijing,'' said the Vatican spokesman,
Joaquin Navarro-Valls. ``This act, however, raises obstacles that
will certainly impede this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Church officials said the Vatican and Beijing have held secret
talks in the last year about improving relations. But the
negotiations seem to be going nowhere. Last summer, the Chinese
government rejected a proposed visit to Hong Kong by the pope,
citing the Vatican's continued ties to Taiwan. The Vatican has said
it would be willing to move its apostolic delegate, or ambassador,
from Taipei to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a Foreign Ministry spokesman reiterated that the
Vatican must sever relations with Taiwan, which Beijing regards as
a renegade province, if it wants to restore relations. The
spokesman, Zhu Bangzao, also said the church must not interfere in
China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Patriotic Catholic Association, it maintains that the
ordinations were merely an effort to rejuvenate its leadership.
``Since the average age of the current Chinese bishops is nearly
80, to have more younger bishops is of crucial importance for the
church's development,'' Fu Tieshan, the chairman of the
association, said in an interview with the state news agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
