<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROADWAY-DANCE-3TAKES     01-06 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-DANCE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY'S DANCE CARD IS FULL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance is upfront on Broadway this season, very
possibly because dance expresses what words cannot. As Isadora
Duncan put it, ``If I could write it, I wouldn't need to dance
it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, the all-dance show has become a reality. From
``Swing!'' to ``Tango Argentino,'' by way of ``Fosse'' and
``Contact,'' dance-driven shows are posing a challenge to the
conventional musical. Current revivals that integrate song, dance
and plot (``Kiss Me, Kate'' and ``Annie Get Your Gun'') and their
not-so-integrated new counterparts (``Footloose'' and ``Saturday
Night Fever'') also make room for dance. Add the naturalness with
which dancing weaves through the parlor setting of ``James Joyce's
`The Dead,''' and the dance aficionado can count the ways in which
show business has acquired new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   If 1998 saw a remarkable attempt to make choreography on
Broadway so much of an organic whole (``Cabaret,'' ``The Lion
King'') thatsequences were not readily visible as such,
productions that opened since have veered mostly in the opposite
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Yet dance-dominated shows do not necessarily spell Son of
``Riverdance.'' Not all these productions are the same. It has been
tempting to call them bookless musicals or revues; but the absence
of a narrative thread does not a revue make, and numbers can be
linked in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother to call ``Swing!'' and ``Tango Argentino'' musicals?
They offer displays of terrific dancing. Why not leave it at that?
As for ``Contact'' at Lincoln Center, scheduled to move upstairs
from the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater to the Tony-eligible Vivian
Beaumont Theater in March, the choreographer Susan Stroman calls it
a ``dance play.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow it all suggests the dance equivalent of Opera Comique,
where the singers are allowed occasionally to speak. Here, the
dancers talk (for instance, two words in the first of the three
segments of ``Contact'').
</P>
<P>
   This is not the place to lament the demise of the American
musical's golden age. The current, vibrant ``Kiss Me, Kate'' tells
us how much we have lost. But the foray of dance shows into
Broadway does suggest that new musicals are still floundering about
for something to say. Pastiche has usually been the dubious
response.
</P>
<P>
   If the dance-dominated shows are not strictly musicals, they
offer an alternative. Theater audiences are discovering what the
ballet and the modern-dance world already knows: Dance has a
metaphoric power that succeeds because of what it leaves unsaid.
``Tango Argentino,'' which ends its run on Sunday, is a reprise of
the 1987 production that sparked the worldwide tango craze.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Swing!,'' which has arrived in the midst of the
10-year-old swing-dance revival, it has flashy artistry and
virtuosity that work on a formal level. But the dances in these
shows also speak of human relationships, time and place.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why so many of the new Broadway productions use
dance as an overblown metaphor. Dance is suddenly seen within these
shows as the road to salvation and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, characters who can't dance don't teach.
Instead, they get rhythm and stop being misfits. In the third
section of ``Contact'' the suicidal hero learns to swing and gets
his ideal girl (sort of). In the second section an abused housewife
finds release in balletic fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Swing!'' the lack of sustained narrative does not stop some
of the performers from being transformed. Uptight man or woman is
liberated once he or she learns to snap fingers and dance. In
``Footloose'' dancing has even been outlawed. It takes a city boy
to teach a small town how to find its soul through rock 'n' roll
dance. Even in ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' the two gangsters make their
escape by brushing up their footwork in a music-hall number
reminiscent of the ``Popular Song'' duet in Frederick Ashton's
ballet ``Facade.'' Annie drops her gun and gets her man, like Agnes
de Mille's cowgirl in ``Rodeo,'' by shedding her buckskins for
social dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is a klutz. The hero of ``Saturday Night Fever''
is the local disco king, but dance is potentially his way out of
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Dance on Broadway made a comeback in 1992, regaining equal time
with songs and dialogue after British musicals had kept
choreography subordinate to music. Since then, there has been
considerable seesawing among musicals that use dance as set pieces
or, in integrated fashion, to move the action along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' which opened in 1989, spawned
shows like ``Fosse'' that are anthologies of a choreographer's
work. One unexpected spinoff is the souped-up variety show with a
dance emphasis, including ``Lord of the Dance'' and ``Riverdance,''
scheduled to hit Broadway in the spring after appearances since
1996 at Radio City Music Hall. ``Burn the Floor,'' a showcase of
ballroom dancing with competitive dance champions, is also
scheduled to arrive this year.
</P>
<P>
   If you want dance with artistic quality, why not just go to
ballet and modern-dance performances? Good question. Ballet, for
instance, has superstar dancers that Broadway usually lacks,
although Julio Bocca of American Ballet Theater is coming in to
pump up ``Fosse'' in February.
</P>
<P>
   By and large there is terrific ensemble dancing on Broadway.
Whatever you call it, there is a place for the show that makes
dance its subject, as a selective overview suggests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   `SWING!'
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Taylor-Corbett, familiar from her works in American Ballet
Theater and New York City Ballet as well as on Broadway, has done a
fabulous job in fusing show dancers with swing-dance champions. The
whole thing jumps and jives with pulsating energy and never
resembles a ballroom contest.
</P>
<P>
   Neo-swing is what this style is about: swing dancing, especially
the Lindy hop, from a current perspective. The stylization is
discreet but present; this is very much a choreographed show with
singers as the links between the visibly different numbers. It is
not a compilation. There is no mistaking the explosive energy and
variety. There is more to Lindy hopping than throwing your partner
around!
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no surprise that the lead Lindy hoppers, Ryan
Francois and Jenny Thomas, who execute their own choreography, are
professionals from Britain, where jitterbugging is all the rage.
Show dancers nonetheless carry the load, modulating the acrobatics
when needed in Ms. Taylor-Corbett's distilled emotional vignettes.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin Carter, one of the standouts, makes love here to a bass
more than to a bass player, Conrad Korsch, in the ``Harlem
Nocturne'' number, which alludes to Ms. Taylor-Corbett's early
works in the jazz dance idiom. In ``Blues in the Night'' Ms. Carter
and Edgar Godineaux have a sexy hip-thrusting encounter.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this quite matches the power of the jitterbugging.
Swing dance is so popular that the audience is in the know, calling
out the equivalent of ``Ole!'' when niceties are appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   `KISS ME, KATE'
</P>
<P>
   Brian Stokes Mitchell and Marin Mazzie, as thespians whose
battles are paralleled in ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' are hardly
slouches when it comes to moving onstage. But the dance numbers
belong to the supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Swing dancing is back, if you haven't heard, and ``Too Darn
Hot'' has Stanley Wayne Mathis leading Kathleen Marshall's take on
1940s jive with elegance and energy. This is the big number, and
toward the end the ensemble section runs a bit out of inventive
steam.
</P>
<P>
   But there is sophistication when Amy Spanger and the limber
Michael Berresse get together, in the initial apache dance, and in
the gymnastic chinning that Berresse tosses off so smoothly as he
sings ``Bianca.''
</P>
<P>
   The dances in the show within the show transmit Ms. Marshall's
mock period flavor with a modern wink toward the original
production's own era. All step lively in this show. `Contact'
</P>
<P>
   Anything Susan Stroman choreographs on Broadway or more recently
for the New York City Ballet and the Martha Graham Dance Company,
instills respect. There is more than craft and pastiche in this
three-part suite; there is a new-found impudence that is
refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   The first section, ``Swinging,'' is the most original. Like
Eugene Loring, Lincoln Kirstein's protege who called his own
company Dance Players, Ms. Stroman is experimenting with mixed
forms: speech and dance. ``Swinging'' was inspired by ``The
Swing,'' a 1768 painting by Fragonard that openly suggests illicit
pleasure. In the painting an 18th-century aristocrat reclines in a
garden, looking up the skirt of a woman on a swing. Stephen Jones,
a British art historian, says she is pushed forward by a cleric!
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman turns the cleric into a sullen man dressed like a
servant. As Jones writes, ``The girl probably wore nothing under
the skirt.'' Ms. Stroman suggests as much when the putative
servant, Sean Martin Hingston, wonderfully persuasive in his brawny
pouting, clambers onto the swing for some frank acrobatics while
the other man (Scott Taylor) is absent. It may not be conventional
dance, but it is precisely choreographed. Stephanie Michels conveys
the air of a knowing ninny. When Taylor returns, we find out he was
a servant disguised as a nobleman while Hingston puts on the
aristocrat's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Did the woman dress her swain in humble attire as part of a
love-with-a-perfect-stranger fantasy? ``Well played,'' he says at
the end. Maybe. Too many other possibilities come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Did You Move?'' Karen Ziemba, the victimized wife of a
thug, escapes into fantasy as a ballerina with a love life in a
restaurant. Choreographed for food carts and trays as well as
people, the vignette makes one uneasy: too funny about a brutal
situation?
</P>
<P>
   Swing dancing, in a more abstract version than elsewhere, gets a
knockout performance by the dancers, especially the men, in the
last section, also called ``Contact.'' Boyd Gaines, highly likable
as the executive who wants to drop out of the rat race, does well
as an actor who still has to get over some partnering glitches with
Deborah Yates, whose performance is not so much remarkable for her
siren image as for her ability to switch from cool to hot in the
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The pretext harks back to 19th-century Romantic ballet. The hero
searches for an ideal and finds love at home. Stylistically there
is an American twist. The repressed Puritan finds release in dance,
which equals sex. George Balanchine's ``Slaughter on 10th Avenue''
comes to mind, right down to the use of a billiard table as a
runway for the seductress. Or is it Roland Petit's ``Jeune Homme et
la Mort,'' in which a girl in a yellow dress visits a man who hangs
himself?
</P>
<P>
   `SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER'
</P>
<P>
   If you fancy disco dancing onstage, and you want to end up
dancing in the aisles, this is the musical for you. Arlene
Phillips, the choreographer-director, has an unusually young cast
of dancers. Not all are smooth, but they give their all in
theatricalized disco that becomes repetitive. Yet here, too, swing
dancing pops up in the club where the final dance contest has a
welcome parodistic touch.
</P>
<P>
   James Carpinello, in the lead as Tony, is obliged to lock
frequently into a signature pose, knee bent to one side and finger
up. One should give him credit for stamina in continually fitting
into cardboard-cutout choreography. `Footloose'
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose'' also uses a dance idiom with which teen-agers can
identify. There is something of the television special in the way
A.C. Ciulla, a choreographer new to Broadway, projects a lead
dancer with a backup group. Here, too, the dancers are amazingly
young, which helps in the big gym number when they not only
simulate athletics but also engage in them. The variety of shapesizes in bodies suggests real people, not leggy chorines.
</P>
<P>
   There is the right urban feel to the first dance, which is
glorified disco, and as the city boy obliged to relocate to a small
town, Jeremy Kushnier has an energetic versatility. There is a
scene with country-and-western dancing, but even here it becomes
clear why kneepads are necessary. Back flips and splits, not
nuance, are the norm. In the gym finale, one man dribbles another
like a basketball. It's basic stuff without a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   `FOSSE'
</P>
<P>
   ``Again?'' a child in the audience said as still another group
of dancers slinked in, splayed hands to the brim of a bowler hat. A
signature style is one thing, a tic is another. Bob Fosse's
choreography once worked in context, but as a string of excerpts it
rarely holds up.
</P>
<P>
   After a year in New York, ``Fosse'' lacks conviction. Chet
Walker and Ann Reinking, the choreographers in charge with Gwen
Verdon as adviser, failed to realize that Fosse had little to say.
His protest against American puritanism has outlived its time. When
Bocca steps in on Feb. 15, his powerful technique might make the
balletic solos look less ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Only the more conventional numbers work: the weary whores draped
over a bar in ``Big Spender''; the inimitable ``Steam Heat'' trio
that introduced the isolation of body parts essential to Fosse's
style, and ``Sing, Sing, Sing,'' which pays homage to the old-time
production number that Fosse helped destroy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `ANNIE GET YOUR GUN'
</P>
<P>
   Graciela Daniele, who also directed, and Jeff Calhoun are
credited with the choreography in this revisionist staging (play
within a play). Two pros of this caliber could have made dance more
distinctive. But of course the songs, by Irving Berlin, have it.
</P>
<P>
   There are folk touches, as in the Indian hoop dance that is
standard in ``fancy dancing'' competitions among American Indians.
But some of the moments are mystifying. Tom Wopat as Frank is in
danger of being pulled down both literally and by a male ensemble's
risque mime as he sings, ``My Defenses Are Down.'' When
Annie-Cinderella goes to a ball, decorum is deliberately lost among
the waltzing couples to the tune of ``I Got the Sun in the
Morning.'' Suddenly it's hoedown time.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Peters was replaced by Valerie Wright at my
performance. But something else seemed missing: dance motivation.
</P>
<P>
   `TANGO ARGENTINO' AND `THE DEAD'
</P>
<P>
   Unless you hate the tango, ``Tango Argentino'' is the best
showcase for authenticity in a specific dance tradition. The
newcomers are flashier than the elderly veterans of the pioneering
original production. Some of the old-timers appear briefly to
demonstrate what the soul of tango is about (virtuosity, not sex).
</P>
<P>
   Sean Curran has done a magnificent job in ``James Joyce's `The
Dead,''' integrating Irish step dances, line dances and less formal
outbursts of dance at this Christmas gathering in Joyce's Dublin.
An experimental choreographer for his own company, he fits right in
with a cast that has a downtown edge. Not the least is Christopher
Walken, a terrific dancer. Here, he refrains from pulling out all
the stops.
</P>
<P>
   That is the point of the choreography: It fits each character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     01-06 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN MOVIE,' featuring Mark Borchardt and friends. Directed
by Chris Smith (R, 104 minutes). An insightful, funny,
not-to-be-missed documentary about a no-budget Wisconsin filmmaker
who makes a horror film as if his life depended on it. And as Smith
so affectingly reveals, Borchardt's hopes really do hang in the
balance. This knowing and often hilarious look at try-anything
indie filmmaking becomes a moving portrait of one man's uphill
struggle and finds Borchardt often describing success and
prosperity as his goals. Meanwhile his own life is eloquently
presented as a very different, no less authentic kind of American
Dream (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ANNA AND THE KING,' starring Jodie Foster and Chow Yun-Fat.
Directed by Andy Tennant (PG-13, 140 minutes). The same story that
inspired the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical ``The King and I'' is
the basis for this movie about the British schoolteacher Anna
Leonowens (Ms. Foster), who travels to Bangkok in 1862 to educate
the 58 children of King Mongkut (Chow). Although the story has been
given a contemporary multicultural perspective that is critical of
British imperialism, the picturesque film tells essentially the
same story but without the beloved songs, which are badly missed.
Ms. Foster's Anna is another of her nobler-than-thou ice queensChow's king is authoritative but less than thunderous (Stephen
Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BICENTENNIAL MAN,' starring Robin Williams, Embeth Davidtz, Sam
Neill and Oliver Platt. Directed by Chris Columbus (PG, 132
minutes). This year's gushy Christmas card from Robin Williams
follows the 200-year quest of a household robot named Andrew to
become human. Directed by the schmaltzmeister Columbus, who steered
this star through ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' the movie is a joke-strewn
sentimental man-machine allegory determined to make us feel good
about being human that is punctuated by corny speeches exalting
freedom, the joys of sex and the mystery of mortality. Except for
Williams, the acting is strictly of sitcom caliber (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `DOUBLE JEOPARDY,' starring Ashley Judd, Tommy Lee Jones and
Bruce Greenwood. Directed by Bruce Beresford (R, 106 minutes). In a
touristy thriller that roams from the coastline of Washington state
to the French Quarter of New Orleans, Ms. Judd plays a woman who is
free to kill her husband because she has already gone to prison for
the crime (see title). Not even she is beautiful enough to get away
with rote acting and a far-fetched plot, but she perks up as her
character becomes less of a victim. In this coed homage to ``The
Fugitive,'' Jones is on hand as another weathered sourpuss with a
knack for barking orders. Beresford directs so unremarkably that it
takes a line like ``I feeI've grown in the last six years''
to signal the passage of time (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `EVEREST,' directed by David Brashears with Greg MacGillivray
(not rated; 45 minutes). This account focuses mainly on the efforts
of three people to scale the peak in 1996 despite yawning chasms of
ever-shifting ice, thundering avalanches, the perils of air so thin
that it addles the brain and sudden, blinding storms. While this
expedition was on the mountain, as many articles and books were
later to relate, other teams made their way into the so-called
death zone, at 25,000 feet, where a violent storm overtook them.
Eight people perished in the worst single disaster on the mountain.
``Everest'' makes it possible for armchair adventurers to share the
risks and glory of the team's climb toward heaven. (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   `FANTASIA/2000,' with James Levine and the Chicago Symphony
Orchestra and introductions by Steve Martin, Bette Midler, Levine,
Itzhak Perlman, James Earl Jones, Angela Lansbury, Quincy Jones and
Penn and Teller. Various directors (G, 75 minutes). The new
millennial version of Disney's 1940 groundbreaking fusion of
animation and classical music includes seven new segments and keeps
one from the original film (the wonderful ``Sorcerer's
Apprentice,'' starring Mickey Mouse). Despite the science-fiction
title and the IMAX-size screen on which it's being shown,
``Fantasia/2000'' is more backward-looking than futuristic. The two
best segments are ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' a witty
Manhattan-in-the-Jazz Age homage to the caricaturist Al Hirschfeld
set to the music of George Gershwin, and the finale (set to
Stravinsky's ``Firebird Suite'') in which a cometlike sprite
whooshes around the globe explosively creating, destroying and
renewing the planet's life forms. Movie star introductions lend the
film the feel of a deluxe corporate promotion. `FLAWLESS,' starring
Robert De Niro and Philip Seymour Hoffman. Written and directed by
Joel Schumacher (R, 110 minutes). De Niro is a retired New York
City policeman recovering from a stroke and Hoffman the drag queen
upstairs who gives him speech therapy in the form of singing
lessons in this stridently campy comedy. Their flashy performances
can't add dimension to a movie that is a message-laden duet for two
caricatures, a homophobe and the angry, self-loathing drag queen
who gets him out of his depression (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `GALAXY QUEST,' starring Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver and Alan
Rickman. Directed by Dean Parisot (PG, 102 minutes). Whether you
love ``Star Trek'' or laugh at it, your starship has come in,
docking in the form of this amiable comedy that simultaneously
manages to spoof these popular futuristic space adventures and
replicate the very elements that have made them so durable. The
film spins out of a single joke, about a bunch of washed-up actors
from a canceled television series who are enlisted by some
credulous interplanetary simpletons to champion them in a conflict
with a scaly, bellicose villain who has all but exterminated their
people. And soon they are off on a genuine space adventure. If
``Galaxy Quest'' never attains consistently giddy heights as it
plays out its combination of knowing satire and heroic adventure,
it nevertheless keeps its tongue firmly in its cheek, offer
genuine laughs, moves swiftly, if not at warp speed, and is led by
a talented cast (Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   `HOUSE ON HAUNTED HILL,' starring Geoffrey Rush, Taye Diggs and
Peter Gallagher. Directed by William Malone (R, 115 minutes). If
the ever vigilant Federal Reserrman, Alan Greenspan, is
truly determined to snuff out inflation aborning, then he can do no
better than to take sharpened pencil in hand, make his way to the
nearest theater showing this film and strike fearlessly until its
feeble pulse beats no more. This is a sorry reincarnation of the
1950s William Castle horror film in which an eccentric millionaire
played by Vincent Price offered five strangers $10,000 each to
spend the night in a spooky old mansion. In the new version the
ante for survival has been raised to $1 million apiece. Even
allowing for inflation in the 40 years since the original opened,
the reward in 1999 should come to only $57,113.47, according to the
Federal Reserve Bank in Minneapolis. But some things have not
become devalued over the years: words like junk, for example.
``Hill'' was pronounced junk in these pages in 1959. And it is
still junk (Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `THE LIMEY,' starring Terence Stamp and Peter Fonda. Directed by
Steven Soderbergh (R, 89 minutes). From a director for whom the
quirky stylistic exercise is standard style, this is a handsome
throwback to the salad days of its two iconic stars. Stamp, in a
stony, magnetic performance punctuated by flashbacks to his early
career an ex-con seeking revenge for the death of his
daughter. He becomes the nemesis of Fonda's slick Hollywood
hipster, another role that's piquantly tailor-made. Soderbergh
resurrects the lean, hard-boiled look of John Boorman's ``Point
Blank'' as he dissects and considers these two tough customers from
every conceivable perspective (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MANSFIELD PARK,' starring Frances O'Connor and Jonny Lee
Miller. Written and directed by Patricia Rozema (PG-13, 105
minutes). In Ms. Rozema's skillful screen adaptation of Jane
Austen's third novel, the protagonist, Fanny Price (Ms. O'Connor),
has been sharpened into a protofeminist heroine who triumphs over
the materialist, patriarchal values of her wealthy relatives
through a combination of wit, beauty and daring. Without bearing
down too heavily, the screenplay (which incorporates fragments of
Austen's letters and diaries) equates early 19th-century slave
trading with the oppression of women. The message is leavened with
smart humor and warm three-dimensional performances (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE MESSENGER: THE STORY OF JOAN OF ARC,' starring Milla
Jovovich, John Malkovich, Tcheky Karyo and Faye Dunaway. Directed
by Luc Besson (R, 130 minutes). The Hundred Years' War feels twice
that long in this shrill, frenetic account of Joan of Arc. It's a
film whose main revelation is that the Middle Ages may have been a
lot more lurid than previously reported. Besson directs plenty of
grisly, hand-held battle scenes and absurd scenes of royal
scheming, while Ms. Jovovich talks. Like this. And doesn't seem
faintly plausible as France's teen-age martyr. Here's a case where
``Don't shoot `The Messenger''' would have been sound advice
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MUSIC OF THE HEART,' starring Meryl Streep, Aidan Quinn, Angela
Bassett and Gloria Estefan. Directed by Wes Craven (PG, 110
minutes). Not many of us enjoy being lectured by dressed-down
Hollywood stars in gritty classroom situations. But the true story
of Roberta Guaspari, a music teacher in East Harlem and a single
mother surviving a nasty divorce, has been given a blunt,
no-nonsense tone that works. Ms. Streep gives a down-to-earth
performance that is sheer award bait. The story is inspirational
enough to take Ms. Guaspari from no job prospects to watching her
proud students play alongside Itzhak Perlman, Isaac Stern and other
violin stars. Not a bad reason for Craven to have sidelined the
claws and hatchets for a while (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``ONEGIN,'' starring Ralph Fiennes, Liv Tyler and Martin
Donovan. Directed by Martha Fiennes (not rated, 106 minutes). As
the directorial debut of Fiennes' sister Martha, ``Onegin''
diminishes Pushkin's epic 19th-century novel ``Eugene Onegin'' into
a cramped little soap opera whose two stars are painfully
mismatched. While Fiennes acts up a fine storm as the arrogant,
cynical title character who doesn't believe in love, Ms. Tyler, who
plays his romantic nemesis, is an inert cipher. Somehow, even the
grand ballrooms of 1820s St. Petersburg look drab and chintzy
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PRINCESS MONONOKE,' with the voices of Billy Crudup, Claire
Danes, Billy Bob Thornton and Minnie Driver. Directed by Hayao
Miyazaki (PG-13, 133 minutes). A landmark feat of Japanese
animation from the acknowledged master of the genre. This
complicated, exotically beautiful epic features gods and demons
locked in battle for the future of the forest, and its visions are
breathtakingly rendered. But it is the film's stirring use of
nature, myth and Japanese history that makes it so special. Worth
seeing just for its Forest Spirit, which takes animal form by day
and roams the night as a diaphanous, Godzilla-like divinity. The
image of plants and flowers springing to life beneath his hooves is
ravishingly presented. Despite a superb blend of hand-drawn cels
and fluid, computer-generated animation, the film's look is
gratifyingly understated (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ROSETTA,' starring Emilie Dequenne. Directed by Luc and
Jean-Pierre Dardenne (R, 90 minutes). This grim quasi-documentary,
filmed with hand-held cameras (it's almost as jiggly as ``The Blair
Witch Project''), picked up the Palme d'Or (the top prize) at the
Cannes Film Festival last year. Ms. Dequenne was also chosen best
actress for her portrayal of a miserable 17-year-old Belgian girl
living in a trailer camp with her alcoholic mother. Her desperate
quest for a job and what she calls a ``normal life'' leads her to
betray her only friend, who works at a waffle stand, by stealing
his job. Unlike the Dardenne brothers' last film, ``La Promesse,''
this movie's social realist angst feels contrived, and its main
character never fully comes to life (Holden).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SNOW FALLING ON CEDARS,' starring Ethan Hawke, James Cromwell
and Max Von Sydow. Directed by Scott Hicks (PG-13, 130 minutes).
This director's follow-up to ``Shine'' is the cinematic equivalent
of an arty coffee-table book. It is so busy illustrating the story
(with elaborate flashbacks and montage sequences) that it forgets
to be dramatic. Set in the Pacific Northwest in 1950, the movie
looks back to World War II and the charged relationships between
Japanese-Americans and whites on an island north of the Puget
Sound. Hawke is the brooding reporter covering the trial and Von
Sydow the defense lawyer who is the film's official conscience.
Robert Richardson is responsible for the gorgeous cinematography
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `STUART LITTLE,' starring Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie and Jonathan
Lipnicki. Directed by Rob Minkoff (PG, 92 minutes). E.B. White's
1945 children's classic has been adapted into a lovely family film
about a little mouse (with the voice of Michael J. Fox) who is
adopted by humans but runs afoul of their fluffy white Persian
house cat, Snowbell (Nathan Lane). The movie creates an enchanted
storybook version of New York and has what may be the most exciting
toy boat race (in Central Park) ever filmed. Thanks to Lane's sly,
wise-guy vocal impersonation, Snowbell nearly steals a movie that
is funny and sweet but never cloying (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `T-REX: BACK TO THE CRETACEOUS,' starring Peter Horton and Liz
Stauber. Directed by Brett Leonard (not rated; 45 minutes).
Passions for the prehistoric that remain unsated after the two
``Jurassic Park'' films are likely to be requited by this latest
Imax 3-D film. Drooling and menacing, the monsters of the Mesozoic
are on the march again in this brief, enjoyable dip into
paleontology, teen-age adventure and parent-child relationships.
Seen in 3-D and set against the lush ferns, moss and ancient trees
of the Olympic rain forest in the state of Washington, these
creatures seem marvelously lifelike. Better yet, ``T-Rex'' written
by Andrew Gellis and Jeanne Rosenberg, doesn't rest on its
technological splendors. Its time-tripping story takes the viewer
to a paleontological dig, raises unanswered scientific questions
and introduces some of the major figures in the history of the
subject. To be sure, seeing ``T-Rex'' won't qualify anyone for a
doctorate in paleontology, and an intriguing subplot that hints at
a troubled family background for its teen-age heroine is left
unresolved; but the film is likely to whet active young minds to
learn more about the past. (Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   `THREE KINGS,' starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Ice
Cube. Written and directed by David O. Russell (R, 105 minutes).
The prodigiously talented writer-director of ``Spanking the
Monkey'' and ``Flirting With Disaster'' has made a much more
ambitious film, with mixed results. His gimlet-eyed Persian Gulf
War film has a ``Catch-22'' absurdist edge, but it also has an
oversupply of visual affectations. Vertiginous music-video camera
tricks jazz up the otherwise straightforward story of American
soldiers who have larcenous designs on Saddam Hussein's captured
gold and then develop conscience pangs about their own roles in
Iraq. There are many clever peripheral touches, but there's
something tamely conventional at the film's core (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TOY STORY 2,' with the voices of Tom Hanks and Tim Allen.
Directed by John Lasseter; a Pixar Animated Studios film (G, 98
minutes). A wonderfully playful sequel, sustaining the first film's
wit and novelty while bringing new sophistication to
computer-generated animation. And here is welcome proof that
Hollywood can still make movies to please audiences of any age or
persuasion. From its opening (a perfectly adorable ``Star Wars''
parody) to its Capraesque conclusion, this is seamless work with
more metaphorical cleverness than that usually found in the toy
bin. Colorful new characters and more adventurous action enhance
the story of how Woody falls into the clutches of a sleazy toy
dealer, experiences new-found celebrity and needs to be rescued by
his fabulous old friends (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WAR ZONE,' starring Freddie Cunliffe, Ray Winstone, Tilda
Swinton and Lara Belmont. Directed by Tim Roth (not rated, 99
minutes). Roth is an actor known for roles in tough films, but
never for anything quite as raw as this. In this searing first
feature, the title battlefield is a rural English home where a
teen-age boy looks upon his own family with helpless rage and
astonishment. Sensing the incestuous relationship between his
father and older sister, the film's wordless, baleful young hero
struggles to come to terms with this household horror. Understated
but extremely graphic at times, and shot with mournfully expressive
simplicity by Seamus McGarvey (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH,' starring Pierce Brosnan, Sophie
Marceau, Dame Judi Dench, Robert Carlyle and Denise Richards.
Directed by Michael Apted (PG-13, 128 minutes). This director is
much admired for his ``Up'' series chronicling the lives of former
schoolchildren as they mature. And he has managed to make James
Bond grow up a little, too. Brosnan has become much more
comfortable with the role of Bond, and most of the other characters
are also more interesting than might have been expected. Ms.
Marceau slinks memorably through the role of a treacherous oil
heiress. Ms. Richards seemed a lot smarter playing high school
vixens than she does as a brilliant scientist here. The itinerary
roams from Scotland to Central Asia. And Apted handles the action
as well as he does the talk (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
