<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-KYOCERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS TO WORK WITH KYOCERA ON INVESTING IN JAPANESE
COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Goldman Sachs Group and the Kyocera Corp., the
world's largest maker of ceramic packages as well as a substantial
player in the mobile telephone business, are expected to announce
Friday that they will collaborate in an investment fund to take
stakes in Japanese companies.
</P>
<P>
   The fund will combine Goldman's expertise in using its own
capital to make investments with Kyocera's deep pockets and entree
in the clubby world of Japanese business.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Kyocera and Goldman declined to comment.
People connected to the collaboration, however, confirmed a story
in Thursday's Nihon Keizai Shimbun, which said the fund's size was
$385 million.
</P>
<P>
   Private equity investors have been active throughout Asia since
the region's economic crisis hit two years ago, but until recently,
Japan had remained relatively aloof to their advances.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, as old barriers to entry fall to deregulation and
companies once financed by bank loans find themselves struggling to
tap other sources of capital, more companies are taking a second
look at foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
   Direct investment by foreign companies and investors hit a
record 1.34 trillion yen, or about $12.9 billion, in the fiscal
year that ended March 31, small by global standards but still seen
as indicative of the potential here. That was a 97 percent increase
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   And foreign direct investment into Japan in the first six months
of the current fiscal year nearly equaled the total investment for
all of fiscal 1998, at 1.33 trillion yen. Ripplewood, a private
equity firm, is in the final stages of completing its deal to buy
the bankrupt Long-Term Credit Bank from the government, the largest
such deal so far.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been smaller deals taking place. Last week,
Olympus Capital Holdings Asia, a $250 million private equity fund
established in 1997 to make investments in Asia, bought half of
Tomen Mediacom, a group of five cable television companies that
serve roughly 1 million households in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a role for private equity in Japan now,'' said
Lawrence S.K. Miao, one of Olympus' founding partners. ``The
Japanese like to have partners who are committed for the long term,
and in that sense, private equity investors are more attractive
than institutions that simply raise capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's proprietary investment activities, which include
investments in Kookmin Bank in South Korea, luxury hotels in Asia
and several high-tech ventures in the United States and Europe,
generated $950 million in revenue after interest expenses last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kyocera is a long-time Goldman client. Most recently, Goldman
was adviser to the DDI Corp., Japan's second-largest long-distance
telephone service operator, on the merger announced last month with
the KDD Corp. and the IDO Corp. Kyocera will be the largest
shareholder of the combined company with a 15.8 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with people you know and who know you is an enormous
benefit in Japan,'' Miao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
