A8598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-BOS &LR;      01-06 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGATIONS AGAINST WEIZMAN REPORTEDLY MADE BY PUBLISHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ An Israeli newspaper publisher charged with hiring a
hitman could be behind allegations that President Ezer Weizman
accepted gifts of nearly a half-millon dollars in a scandal that
has politicians already jockeying to replace the sharp-tongued
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The latest disclosures in the scandal concern publisher Ofer
Nimrodi, in jail pending trial for conspiracy to commit murder, who
asked Weizman in August for a pardon on a wiretapping conviction,
Israeli media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman rejected the request of the powerful publisher of
Israel's mainstream daily Ma'ariv, incurring Nimrodi's wrath and
possibly sparking the release by a Ma'ariv reporter of information
concerning money Weizman received years ago, sources close to
Weizman told Israeli media.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations about Nimrodi's involvement in the Weizman
affair bring together the two biggest political scandals to hit
Israel since Shas Party leader Aryeh Deri was convicted last year
of accepting a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   It further complicates an already murky story about money given
to Weizman between 1988 and 1993, when he was a member of
parliament and a government minister. Weizman has admitted that he
received an unspecified of money from a French businessman
friend, but says it was just a gift.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations come amid claims by Weizman's lawyer that files
relating to the financial transactions have disappeared from his
office, raising suspicions that the files were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   But the deepening mystery of how investigative journalist Yoav
Yitzhak acquired the information has not quelled voices clamoring
for Weizman's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers have called for Weizman to step down, as have various
politicians and political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office is also planning to investigate
the claims. It has requested that Weizman's office turn over
documents and offer explanations related to the alleged $453,465
given to Weizman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the suspicion of a criminal offense but rather his
failure to comply with the standards of ethical behavior expected
of public officials that requires Weizman _ for his own good _ to
bid a hasty farewell,'' political columnist Dan Margalit wrote in
Thursday's Ha'aretz.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers say Weizman should be given a chance to explain
the money transfers, but they warn that it is difficult to escape
the appearance of impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't smell very good,'' said Reuven Rivlin, a
Knesset member from the opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows exactly what are the details, but from a moral
point of view a great section of Israelis are asking how come a
minister or president of Israel can receive any kind of present of
half a million dollars?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman has not commented specifically on the financial gifts he
received from businessman Edward Sarousi, who owns a home in Israel
and funded a political party that Weizman once led.
</P>
<P>
   But the journalist who broke the story with a well-documented
report _ he did it by calling a news conference rather than write
about it _ said some of the money was transferred to Weizman's
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarousi bought himself a member of Knesset and a cabinet
minister who is now president,'' Yitzhak said at his news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators may not find it easy to prove that Weizman
broke any laws. Public officials are allowed to receive financial
gifts if the gifts are given to them as private citizens for
private use.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Weizman say the president used the money to pay
for medical treatment for his son Shaul, who was seriously injured
while a soldier. In a country where every Jewish man is a soldier,
such a tale, if true, would probably exonerate Weizman. But Yitzhak
said the payments continued even after Shaul died in a car accident
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Weizman has been implicated in something
with legal ramifications. His blunt way of talking and brash manner
often get him into trouble for other reasons: sexist comments about
wo mocking statements about gays over the past few years
raised questions about whether he should represent Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A former fighter pilot, Weizman has gone from hawk to dove in
his political career, angering former hard-line compatriots along
the way. Last week, he again angered hardliners when he threatened
to resign if Israelis did not vote in favor of a peace agreement
with Damascus if Prime Minister Ehud Barak brings a deal to a
public referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Some Likud parliamentarians say Weizman shouldn't wait to go.
His statements, they say, politicize the largely ceremonial
position he holds, giving him another reason to quit well before
the completion of the investigation into the money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
