<SLUG> BC-FAA-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA MOVES TO CONTROL SECURITY COMPANY OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration proposed rules Thursday that
would make private security companies _ which are contracted by
airlines to screen passengers and baggage _ fall under FAA
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the FAA can only regulate the airlines that hire the
security companies, but the agency has no direct oversight of the
companies themselves, or how the security guards at airport
screening facilities are hired and trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport security screeners play a crucial role in
protecting the flying public,'' said FAA administrator Jane Garvey
in a statement. ``Today's rule-making will give us the tools we
need to regulate screening companies and make sure screeners meet
our rigorous standards for detecting dangerous objects and keeping
those objects from being brought on board passenger planes.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes at a time when the nation's airport security
is on heightened alert. The Boston Globe reported last year that
security breaches at Logan International Airport were commonplace
in the last two years _ a situation the FAA acknowledged was common
at major airports. Many of the breaches involved screeners
routinely failing to detect test items such as pipe bombs and guns
hidden in bags carried by FAA agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new rules are long overdue,'' said David Stempler,
president of the Washington-based Air Travelers Association, a
passenger representation group. ``But if they want to get serious
about security, a federal force and computer imaging should be
employed. When the airline is responsible for security, they will
go to the lowest bidder and the lowest bidder pays the least for
labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirements would make security companies accountable for
screener performance and training. With this accountability, the
FAA believes the companies and the employees will perform better.
</P>
<P>
   To evaluate performance, the FAA is using a system that projects
electronic images of guns, knives and explosives into bags being
X-rayed. FAA officials said the system gives the agency the data
needed to implement certification standards.
</P>
<P>
   The public comment period for the proposed rule-making is 90
days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
