<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ OFF FOR THIRD DAY; DOW RECOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index Thursday fell for a third day in a
row, plunging 150.41 points as investors continued to sell their
high-flying technology stocks and plow money into financial, oil,
and consumer company issues.
</P>
<P>
   Investors snapping up traditional stocks pushed the Dow Jones
industrial average up 130.61 points. The broad Dow index has now
recovered more than two-thirds of the losses suffered in a
360-point pummeling on Tuesday. The Dow finished Thursday at
11,253.26, up 1.17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's recovery could not have contrasted more with the
performance by the technology-heavy Nasdaq, which continued a slide
that started with a record 229.5-point plunge on Tuesday. Lucent
Technologies Inc. plunged more than 19 a share Thursday, and the
world's biggest telephone-equipment maker lost $50 billion in
market value after an announcement that first-quarter profits would
be far below profit levels a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Lucent, the Nasdaq closed Thursday at 3727.13, down 3.88
percent for the day and 8.4 percent for the year-to-date. The
Nasdaq had climbed 86 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is getting beaten up but the Dow's up,'' said Jeff
Davis, an investment strategist for State Street Global Advisers, a
unit of State Street Corp. ``You've got a tale of two markets
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Nasdaq's decline, the overall market performed well
Thursday. There were 19 advancing issues for every 11 that declined
in a day of heavy trading that surpassed 1 billion shares changing
hands on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer for FleetBoston
Financial, said investors are becoming more ``rational'' and buying
non-technology companies because they are better values. The
Nasdaq's 1999 climb was so spectacular that little attention had
been drawn to the fact that much of the market was lagging in what
O'Neill called a ``stealth bear market'' dating back to April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is the pendulum swinging back from excess in
the technology sector'' to better-priced stocks in other sectors,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger for Thursday's tech-stock selloff came after Gateway
Inc. announced its profits would fall short of expectations,
analysts said. While the personal computer maker specifically
blamed Intel Corp. for a shortage of microprocessors, a spate of
technology companies have recently foreshadowed disappointing
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent blamed its lower profits on weaker than expected sales;
the company's stock fell 19 3/8 and closed at 53 a share, down 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech decline caused Microsoft Corp., the world's
biggest software company, to lose 3 13/16, closing at 110.
</P>
<P>
   Investment experts call it ``sector rotation'' _ shifting large
volumes of money from one industry or stock category to another _
and it was a bright and shining trend in the market.
</P>
<P>
   On the upswing were a wide variety of industries.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was lifted by diversified manufacturer Minnesota Mining
&AMP; Manufacturing, which finished up 7 1/2 to close at 100 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil Corp. added 4 3/16, finishing at 85 3/16; consumer
products giant Procter &AMP; Gamble Corp. gained 4 3/4, closing at 107
7/8. Citigroup Inc. gained 2 3/8, closing at 54 1/8, while oil
services company Schlumberger Ltd. rose 3 11/16, closing at 57 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good solid companies that people believe in long
term but have underperformed as technology shares gained,'' said
Hugh Whelan, who manages the Aeltus Enhanced Index Plus fund in
Hartford, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
