<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-STYLE-RESOLUTIONS07-C     01-06 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-RESOLUTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    20 personal fashion resolutions for 2000
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Give your willpower a ring _ it's time
for everyone's favorite stock-taking, list-making rite: New Year's
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   For those who need help calling up their resolve, we asked
several health, fashion and beauty experts for their best bit of
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Want to drop a few pounds? Here are some hints. Want to present
a more pulled-together image? Catch these clues. Just want to be
happier with what you see in the mirror, without doing a major
overhaul? There are tips for that too.
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to be realistic about exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``People try to overexceed their goals. My suggestion would be
to set a goal and stick to it, nothing too hard. Something that's
easily accomplishable and then go from there. A good basic goal
would be resistance training twice a week and cardio training three
times a week for 30 to 40 minutes. It all depends on your fitness
level. And before you start any training program, consult a
physician.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don Sullivan, personal trainer at Ultima Fitnntown in
West Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to ask for a doggy bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can eat everything you want, but watch the portion size.
If you want a piece of candy or a slice of cake, eat half of a
piece or a quarter of a piece. But don't deny yourself because then
you'll want more. If you go to a restaurant, eat half of what's on
your plate and take the other half home. And keep exercising
because you still have to put out more than you put in. That's the
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Doris Lock of Doris Lock Fitness in West Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to protect my skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wear a sunscreen with both UVA and UVB protection every day,
with an SPF of at least 15. You can get sun damage walking from
your car to your office, even through the car window.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Miami dermatologist Fredric Brandt
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to experiment with my wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The millennium gives women permission to dress for themselves.
We're encouraging them to ignore fashion dos and don'ts. Nothing is
wrong. There are no rules. Dare to step outside the image that you
usually have.'' (Her example: Pamela Anderson Lee dons a
three-piece suit.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Nancy Lewinter, owner of Mode magazine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to make peace with my laugh lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resist the surgeon's scalpel yet another year. I think
everybody's doing too much right now. Just relax and be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ George Elliott, national artistic director of Babor Institut
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to invest in my appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Products are very important, and you should put your pennies
aside and concentrate on getting good products for the skin and
hair. In the long run, it costs more money to repair (the damage
done by poor products).''
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Miloscia, owner of Delfino's salon
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to take matters in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women typically look in the mirror twice a day. You look at
your hands 100 times a day, minimum. If your hands look pretty,
you'll feel prettier. Eve you do is with your hands ...
whether you're on the computer or you're a nurse or you're a cook.
Women don't realize how self-conscious they are about their hands
until they have a manicure done.'' _ Michelle Longhini at Nails by
Michelle
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to clean up my act.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about good skin, so when you go to bed, no matter how
tired you are, cleanse, tone and moisturize. When you're asleep is
when your skin cells renew themselves. And when you have nice skin,
the makeup just goes on much more smoothly. I'm guilty too, so this
is my personal resolution.'' _ Kim-Van Dang, beauty director for
InStyle magazine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women today should use makeup as an accessory. You don't need
to buy new clothes, almost, bec ause makeup is so fun. It's the
year 2000, and you should try the glitter lipstick and the
glow-in-the-dark products. It's all about playing, it's all about
expressing yourself, and that's really where the future is. The
days of beige eye shadow and nude lipstick are over. Don't be
afraid to go for something completely wild; you can always wash it
off.'' _ Andrea Pomerantz-Lustig, editor in chief of sephora.com
and contributing beauty editor of Self magazine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to take some things
</P>
<P>
   lying down.
</P>
<P>
   Commit to a preventative massage therapy program, which could be
once a week or once a month. ... Whether you're a mom or an office
worker or an athlete or teacher, you're using your muscles in
similar ways everyday. Because of that, your body sets up a stress
pattern. And all of a sudden you've got lower back pain. If you're
regularly reducing that, you're reducing how that sets up in the
muscles and you're reducing emotional stress.'' _ E. Houston
LeBrun, Seattle massage therapist and board member of American
Massage Therapy Association
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to eat my vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, start to focus on good eating habits, not
diet or weight loss. When people can start looking at good eating
habits _ and we all know what those are, five fruits and vegetables
a day, just good nutrition _ the weight loss will happen on its
own. Stay away from the quick-fix diets, but if you do go on them,
follow up with a professional to set up long-term goals so you can
maintain your weight loss. Only 5 percent of people keep the weight
off, so 95 percent of people who go on diets gain the weight back.
And learn to listen to your own body, to eat only when you're
hungry.'' _ nutritionist Cindy Kepler of Palm Beach Nutrition
Consultants
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to say cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at ile as an important feature in the overall
aesthetics of your face. See what maintenance you can do _the usual
hygiene, not avoiding trips to the dentist or the hygienist _ or
investigate the conservative approaches that are now available in
dentistry to improve the smile.'' (His example: The faster,
simpler, more affordable methods of tooth whitening.) _ Manhattan
dentist Jonathan Levine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to take care of No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treat yourself the best you can. That includes not just beauty
and taking time out for yourself, but making a plan and deciding
where you want to be a year from now. Be adventurous, try new
things. Take a beauty attitude and apply it to different aspects of
your life, in the same way you would try a shimmery new eyeshadow
that's really hot. Your physical appearance tends to be a
reflection of what goes on inside.'' _ Belen Aranda-Alvarado,
beauty editor of Latina magazine and editor of the upcoming book
Latina Beauty
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to find my second skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find yourself a piece of color that you're comfortable with.
It takes a lot of time and a lot of effort and a lot of trying-on.
But you know when you feel good about something. And that relates
to my second piece of advice: Feel good about yourself for the new
year. Know that you set the trends for yourself. Style is very
individual as we approach the new millennium. It's not about what
you wear, but how you wear it and how you define your own style.''
_ Pamela Macklin, fashion director at Essence magazine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to get off the bandwagon when it becomes crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you see everybody wearing a trend, don't wear it. The
twin sweater set was on my must-have list for 10 years, but if a
woman walks into a room and sees every other woman there with a
cardigan wrapped around her shoulders, it's time to wear hers a
different way. Go with a trend if you want to, but develop some
personal style.'' _ Patricia Stephenson, West Palm Beach-based
image authority
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to shake things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid to change. Every season you should do at least
three new things to change your look and keep it interesting for
yourself and others. ... If you look like you looked in high
school, it's time to change. There are so many women, the older
they get, the better they look, because they know the trick of
changing and taking care of themselves.'' _ Charla Krupp, editor in
chief of eve.com
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to love my curves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should be healthy, but not get caught up in
stereotypical types of beauty, especially those seen in Hollywood.
... We have to learn to love ourselves a little bit more and look
internally rather than wanting to look like Lara Flynn Boyle or
Calista Flockhart. Don't strive to have somebody else's body; we're
all shaped differently.'' _ Diana Chabis, designer and president of
Diana Chabis Shapely Intimates
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to celebrate little changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key to keeping your resolutions is to make them
manageable. Not to say you're going to do something everyday, but
to incorporate your resolutions more frequently into your life and
regard that as progress. We all need to drink more water, so
replace one soda or one coffee each day with a glass of water. We
all need to take more exercise, so you can add 20 minutes a week
one month and then the next month add 20 minutes twice a week. We
all need to eat more fruits and vegetables, and just having one
more serving a day can be your goal.'' _ Cara Kagan, beauty and
fitness director at Elle magazine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to break new beauty ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've been thinking about for myself. ... Get
out of your beauty rut, whether it's a hairstyle you've had since
high school or a lipstick you've worn for the past five years. The
process of finding something new can really be invigorating for the
way you feel about yourself, and it's fun.'' _ Kristin Perrotta,
beauty editor at Allure magazine
</P>
<P>
   I resolve to know my limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whomever you go to, get the best professional advice you can.
No more home (hair) remedies. Too many people want to save money.
Saving money is one thing, but you're being pennywise and dollar
foolish if you try to do-it-yourself at home. ... And you also need
to establish a relationship with your stylist that is customized to
your needs.'' _ Cosmo DiSchino, owner of Cosmo &AMP; Company salon in
West Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
