<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HNMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      01-06 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEEPING TOM; LAKE PLACID; MYSTERY MEN; DETROIT ROCK CITY; DEJA VU 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The critically unacclaimed may be everywhere among new video
releases at the moment, but consider the curious case of ``Peeping
Tom,'' recently issued on DVD by the Criterion Collection. Now
recognized by some as a fine, complex piece of filmmaking, Michael
Powell's movie, about a disturbed young man who kills women while
photographing them with a movie camera, set what must still be some
kind of paradigm for the negative review when it was screened for
the press in London in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Critics didn't simply dislike this film. ``Salacious, rapacious,
pornographic,'' wrote one. Another turned Churchillian. ``I have
carted my travel-stained carcass to some of the filthiest and most
festering slums of Asia,'' he wrote, ``but nothing, nothing,
nothing _ neither the hopeless leper colonies of East Pakistan, the
back streets of Bombay nor the gutters of Calcutta _ has left me
with such a feeling of nausea and depression as I got this week
while sitting through a new British film called `Peeping Tom.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That nauseating? For all the outrage, most critics stopped short
of placing the film on the lowest rung of the horror ladder. ``The
acting is good,'' wrote the man who had been to East Pakistan.
``The photography is good.'' Powell, after all, had stature as the
director of ``Stao Heaven,'' ``Black Narcissus'' and ``The
Red Shoes.'' Watching ``Peeping Tom'' today one sees something of a
dated curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The psychopath, creepy, well-groomed and polite to a fault, is
portrayed by Carl Boehm, a German actor noted for his gentlemanly
roles in saccharine films. The killer's object is to record his
victim's fear as the blade approaches. On the disc an admiring
commentary by the film scholar Laura Mulvey goes into much detail
about the symbolism in every scene. A livelier view is presented in
``A Very British Psycho,'' Chris Rodley's documentary about the
movie's reception and its screenwriter, Leo Marks.
</P>
<P>
   In Rodley's film, also on the disc, one commentator says the
critics weren't prepared for the film and felt professionally
threatened by it. ``Peeping Tom,'' he says, is like a Chinese box,
full of symbols, puns and allusions. To whatever degree that is the
case, the story was the work of Marks, who makes an intriguing
character in the documentary. A renowned code breaker during World
War II, he briefed secret agents headed out on suicide missions.
Their fear found its way into ``Peeping Tom,'' he says. ``Every
briefing room was full of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell and Marks jumped in with relish. The most disturbing part
of the movie, uncomfortable to watch and contemplate, is a film
within the film showing a small boy being systematically terrorized
by his father, a psychologist who is studying fear. The father is
portrayed by Powell and the boy is Powell's son.
</P>
<P>
   Rescued by Martin Scorsese in the '70s, ``Peeping Tom'' made a
splash at the New York Film Festival in 1979 but never succeeded at
the box office. In Britain it was pulled from theaters afteek. Powell, who died in 1990, moved to Australia. In an
interview, Thelma Schoonmaker, Powell's widow and Scorsese's film
editor, said her husband never was bitter. ``His career was
ruined,'' she said, ``no doubt about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID
</P>
<P>
   Remember ``Anaconda'' and the big snake that ate Amazonian
outposts and the people in them? Well, this is a crocodile, 30 feet
long, that starts off as if it were in ``Jaws'' by picking off a
swimmer in a lake while the sheriff (Brendan Gleeson) eats a
Twinkie. The game warden (Bill Pullman) suspects a bear. But a
big-time New York paleontologist is consulted. ``You want me to go
to Maine to look at a tooth?'' asks Kelly Scott (Bridget Fonda).
But this tooth is prehistoric. A wisecracking mythology professor
(Oliver Platt) shows up. The horror is cheesy but fun, and the gore
not too realistic. Beyond the croc, Steve Miner's film, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``provides a good cast with the
challenge of keeping straight faces.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $107.37; DVD, $34.98. 88 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY MEN
</P>
<P>
   After reading too many comic books, several aspiring supermen
and one superwoman (Janeane Garofalo) band together to fight crime.
Some, like the Shoveler (William H. Macy) and the Bowler (Ms.
Garofalo), are named for their weapons or tactics. The Furious (Ben
Stiller) battles evil with temper tantrums. Captain Amazing (Greg
Kinnear) employs a raised eyebrow. The Blue Rajah (Hank Azaria)
throws dinner forks. ``We've got a blind date with Destiny, and it
looks like she's ordered the lobster,'' says the Shoveler. While
Kinka Usher's film occasionally sinks into the same silliness it
mocks, in the main it serves ``a terrific offbeat cast operating on
one shared, loony wavelength'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 100 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT ROCK CITY
</P>
<P>
   Cloned from assorted coming-of-age tales, Adam Rifkin's film
offers four boys from Cleveland who aspire to travel to Detroit to
attend a Kiss concert (the year being 1978). That's the plot. But
first they steal a car, smoke dope and beat up some disco fans just
for the fun of it. Then there is a nun called Sister Gonorrhea and
a scene involving a cheerleader on a toilet, and so forth. Although
the film would still be pretty bad, ``the idea might have promise
if it had even a trace of self-mockery, but no such luck''
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1999. New Line. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 100 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEJA VU
</P>
<P>
   A fictionalized and wildly romantic retelling of meeting and
falling in love with his wife and collaborator, Victoria Hoyt,
Henry Jaglom's film can get redundant and narcissistic. It also
provides an opportunity to ask qs many happily married
couples choose not to ponder over the course of 30 years. Feeling
an instant attraction, Dana (Ms. Foyt) and Sean (Stephen Dillane),
an English painter, bend and adjust in ``a movie whose insights
into tenacious grown-up longing are more penetrating than many of
us would like to admit'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $99.98. 116 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE ART OF BUSTER KEATON. Three more Keaton feature films (and
seven shorts) join eight other Keatons on DVD. In ``The Saphead''
(1920), the film that made him famous, he saves the family fortune.
``Seven Chances'' (1925) originates a scenario duplicated more than
once on the big screen: young man forced to marry by 7 p.m. or lose
his inheritance finds true love among hundreds of prospective
brides. Finally, the athletic fields hold little promise for Keaton
in ``College'' (1927). The shorts present various predicaments, but
here's one for insurance experts: in ``The Electric House'' (1922),
a botanist tries to install electricity in a millionaire's house.
Kino. $29.95 each. Running times from 114 to 130 minutes.
Information: (800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   THE MASTER POETS COLLECTION. Four videos from the PBS series
present dramatized readings from the verse of William Blake,
William Butler Yeats, D.H. Lawrence and Thomas Hardy. 1999.
Monterey. $24.95 each. 30 minutes each. Also from Monterey, and
from PBS, ``An Evening With Mark Twain,'' with two videos and two
audiocassettes, includes ``Mark Twain: A Musical Biography'' on
video, ``The Adventures of Mark Twain'' on audiocassette, and ``The
Man That Corrupted Hadleyburg,'' with Robert Preston, also on
video. $59.95. 288 minutes. In ``An Evening With Emily Dickinson,''
Claire Bloom and Julie Harris portray the poet. $39.95, two
cassettes. 60 minutes total. Information: (800) 424-2593.
</P>
<P>
   ART PEPPER: NOTES FROM A JAZZ SURVIVOR. The rocky career of the
alto-saxophonist, from playing with Stan Kenton at 17 through drug
troubles and prison stretches. 1999. Shanachie. $19.95; DVD,
$24.95. 50 minutes. Information: (800) 497-1043.
</P>
