<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-WORKERS-COMP-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS' COMP WEB SITE OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL POLLICK   
 Herald-Tribune (Sarasota, Fla.)   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Alex Lancaster, a workers' compensation
attorney, has unveiled a Web site that he hopes will be the premier
online source for information on workers' compensation, a topic
that affects many people's lives and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster and his Webmaster-partner, Bob Wilson, opened their
site to the public on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they've collected information on California, Texas and
Florida. They expect to extend the database to all 50 states before
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Each state creates its own set of workers' comp rules, often
building quite a maze for workers and professionals to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' compensation laws provide money and medical benefits to
employees who have been injured on the job or have occupational
diseases. The system is designed to protect workers as well as
employers. The employee receives payments _ weekly or biweekly_ and
medical benefits in exchange for forfeiting the common law right to
sue the employer.
</P>
<P>
   The site _ www.workerscompensation.com _ seeks to present as
much information as possible in a convenient format. On the opening
page, a viewer selects a state. Each state's home page has links to
the state's workers' compensation statutes; law digests and
annotated statutes; forms; rules; compensation rates established by
law for various degrees of impairment, and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Information geared specifically for employees, insurers,
employers, adjusters, medical care providers and lawyers is also
available.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a medical care provider in Florida can find answers
to these questions: Who can I treat? What reports must I submit?
What can I charge for? How do I get authorization for treatment?
</P>
<P>
   An employee might want to learn how to report an injury, choose
an attorney or a medical provider, or when an insurance company can
deny benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The information on the site is free.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster and Wilson expect to make money from court reporters,
doctors, adjusters, attorneys and other practitioners who can post
listings on the site for $9.95 a month per city.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster has owned the Internet domain name
workerscompensation.com for about four years.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
