u w BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS &LR;      01-06 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO DEFENDS DECISION TO REUNITE CUBAN BOY, FATHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday it was
unlikely she would reconsider an INS decision to return a Cuban boy
to his father despite a second day of rallies and protests by Cuban
expatriates in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Saying she understood the desire of Elian Gonzalez' relatives
and the Cuban exiles in Miami to keep him in the United States,
Reno nevertheless spoke of the important ``bond'' that exists
between a father and son.
</P>
<P>
   That connection would be broken if U.S. immigration officials
refused to honor Juan Gonzalez' wish to be reunited with his son,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, stepfather and nine other passengers drowned
when the rickety boat she and her son used to flee Cuba capsized
short of the United States in November.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who oversees the INS, said she supports agency chief Doris
Meissner's decision to reunite Elian and his father. The attorney
general said the decision was reached only after INS interviews
with Juan Gonzalez revealed a strong bond between him and his son
that survived the end of Elian's parents' marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something about a 6-year-old boy and his father,''
Reno said in defending the decision. ``There is a relationship that
the law recognizes, that morality and the sense of right of all
people recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you feel if you were told you couldn't do what you
wanted and that you couldn't live where you wanted if you had a
6-year-old boy someplace else?'' Reno asked at her weekly briefing
with reporters. ``Just think of it in human terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Elian's extended family, who have cared for the boy
in Miami, have retained lawyers to fight the Immigration and
Naturalization Service order that he be returned to his father in
Cuba by Jan. 14. Elian has been staying with his great-uncle and
other relatives in Miami since he was plucked from the sea Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's plight has galvanized South Florida's large community of
Cuban expatriates, many of whom risked their lives, as the boy's
mother had, to escape the rule of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Expatriates protested at Miami transportation outlets Thursday,
snarling traffic on the city's heavily traveled Biscayne Boulevard
and holding rallies at the city's busy port. They also gathered
outside the INS office.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 people were arrested, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Osberg-Braun, an attorney for Elian's Miami family,
questioned whether the government sufficiently quizzed Juan
Gonzalez to ensure his professed love of Elian was sincere and that
he was not speaking under duress from Castro.
</P>
<P>
   She added that immigration officials should be more concerned
about the boy's welfare than they are about the father's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has to make sure that they're not sending
that individual back to harm'' either from the father or from
having to live under a ruthless dictator, Osberg-Braun told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer also reiterated that she would ask a federal judge to
block Elian's return to Cuba if Reno stands firm.
</P>
<P>
   Osberg-Braun and her co-counsel, Spencer Eig, sent a letter to
Reno urging her to reconsider Elian's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Thursday she has not reviewed the letter but added
that she and Meissner reviewed the issues in Elian's case before
the decision was made and didn't expect the ruling to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never say that I won't reverse myself,'' Reno said. ``I try
to be as open-minded as I can. But based on all the information
that we have to date, I see no basis for reversing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno declined to say exactly when she would respond to the
lawyers' letter, saying only that she would be providing an answer
``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One major issue left unresolved in the INS order was how Elian
would be returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the father has been ``extended the opportunity'' to
come to the United States to retrieve his son.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez' failure to make plans has raised speculation among
exiled Cubans that Castro is refusing to allow the boy's father to
come to the United States out of fear that he and his son would not
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned, I don't pay any attention to what
Castro says,'' Reno said. ``I am interested in trying to do what's
right based on the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a Miami native who spent her childhood and most of her
professional life in South Florida, indicated her hope that family
members and the Cuban community would overcome their objections to
the decision and help Elian be reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all think about the issue of freedom, and we all hope that
the day will come when this won't be an issue anymore between Cuba
and the rest of the hemisphere,'' Reno said. ``But this is a little
6-year-old boy. He has got just his father left in terms of
parents. Let us work together to get him the relationship that the
law ... suggests is proper.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who served for 15 years as chief prosecutor for Miami's
Dade County before becoming attorney general, expressed confidence
that the city will survive its current unrest over the decision to
send Elian back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view it's a community I know well, it's a
community I love, and I think it will, in the end, work together to
see that justice is done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a community that reflects America, reflects the hopes
and dreams of so many different people who have come from so many
different places,'' Reno added. ``It has provided hope, it has
provided opportunity, it has provided argument and discussion and
sometimes disruption. But it is a community that I think reflects
the best of America in terms of people coming together in this new
century, and we will work through this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
