</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-PROTECTED-SNAKES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA CONSIDERS PROTECTING RARE POISONOUS SNAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BRIAN FEAGANS   
 Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ In an experiment often cited in wildlife
circles, a rubber turtle and a rubber snake were placed on a rural
road.
</P>
<P>
   Most drivers swerved to avoid the turtle, sometimes even
stopping to move it to a safer spot.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a skidmark was observed in front of the fake snake,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody would drive into the opposite lane just to run over
the snake,'' said Randall Wilson, manager of North Carolina's
endangered w program. ``Some would back up and do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't put that pickup in reverse so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Under a proposal before the North Carolina Wildlife Commission,
it would become illegal to kill four species of rare poisonous
snakes unless it's in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern coral snake, eastern diamondback, pigmy rattlesnake
and timber rattlesnake have become so rare in North Carolina that
they need added protection, ng to a Wildlife Commission
advisory panel.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommends adding the diamondback and the coral snake
to the state list of ``endangered'' species. The pigmy snake and
the timber rattler would be listed as ``species of concern'' under
the plan, which will be the subject of a public hearing next month
in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   The listed snakes would be off limits to collectors and could
only be killed in self-defense. Violators would be fined $100 while
repeat offenders would pay $500 per snake.
</P>
<P>
   The idea isn't to stop a homeowner or farmer from chopping up a
venomous snake, Wilson said. It's to put a dent in the trade of
rare snakes while at the same time trying to dispel the notion that
the only good snake is a dead snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary purpose of the state endangered species list is to
call attention to the problems and the plights of these animals and
their habitats,'' Wilson said. ``Bald eagles needed help and they
got it. People need to know that there are other things that need
protection as well.''
</P>
<P>
   State health officials have recorded fewer than a dozen deaths
from snakebites in the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The rule wouldn't prevent people from killing or capturing
snakes in their yards but simply curb the gratuitous slaughters,
including a mountain tradition of shooting rattlesnakes as they
come out of hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is warming up to the idea, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd,'' said Jerry Brewer, owner of the Tote-Em-In-Zoo
in New Hanover County. ``It's like passing a law against dealing in
drugs. You can't control it.''
</P>
<P>
   Killing snakes is second nature to most people, even when
they're in the woods and far from their property, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine percent of any people who see a rattlesnake and
know it's a rattlesnake will kill it on the spot,'' he said. ``No
rule is going to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
