<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ENDOFAFFAIR07-COX     01-06 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDOFAFFAIR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'End of Affair' drips with '40s look but lacks compelling
performances
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Quick, check your calendar. Seeing Neil
Jordan's ``The End of the Affair,'' you will swear you've been
transported back to the 1940s, for the atmosphere of Graham
Greene's wartime London novel has been re-created so authentically.
Then check your watch, because you'll swear as well that this is
one of the longest, least involving movies under two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has also turned back the clock in his filmmaking style,
going to great lengths to make a staunchly old-fashioned,
sentimental tear-jerker that could have been filmed in the '40s.
Except for the several scenes of languorous nudity, presumably
inserted for those less drawn to the story's spiritual side.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's autobiographical novel, which thinly fictionalizes his
own affair with an American woman, was first filmed in 1955 with
Deborah Kerr and Van Johnson. Jordan's version, which casts
Julianne Moore and Ralph Fiennes as the illicit lovers, reeks of
prestigious, literary pretensions, but is no less driven by
romantic hogwash, followed by heavy-handed themes of religious
awakening and retribution.
</P>
<P>
   We first see Maurice Bendrix (Fiennes, standing in for Greene)
as he begins pounding out the novel we will be viewing. Broken and
confused, he calls the work his ``diary of hate,'' born out of the
love affair of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The action then flashes back to a rainy encounter with civil
servant Henry Miles (a jowly Stephen Rea), followed by the memory
of Maurice's first encounter with Henry's bored wife, Sarah,
(Moore) at a party at her well-appointed home.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, at Henry's insistence, Maurice escorts Sarah to a
movie. It is one that Maurice had written, with clips of a Laurence
Olivier romance flick that Greene adapted _ a nice touch. From
there, it is a short sprint to hands across the table at dinner,
followed by a love affair that, yes, rekindles in Sarah the
passions that had withered in her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, though, Sarah develops a persistent cough that
sounds suspiciously like Ali MacGraw's in ``Love Story.'' That's
what you get for fooling around. In fact, though, it is Maurice who
gets struck down first. As they are making love during the 1944
London Blitz, a bomb blast hits the house and Maurice takes a
header over a staircase, seemingly to his death. But Sarah prays
for him, negotiating with God that she will give up Maurice forever
if his life can somehow be saved.
</P>
<P>
   This scene, like several others throughout ``The End of the
Affair,'' is replayed from both characters' perspectives, though
little new is illuminated. Between the point-of-view shifts and the
time shifts, Jordan seems to want to echo Greene's narrative
structure, but it comes off as mere story padding.
</P>
<P>
   Following her pact with God, the film explores the power of
prayer and the possibilities of miracles. Sarah grows increasingly
religious, while Maurice agrees to help the jealous Henry by
employing a private detective to find her lover. This, of course,
is not much of a mystery, except for a miraculous transformation
that occurs to the detective's disfigured son.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film is so emotionally muted, in that terribly
repressed British way, that the performers have little opportunity
to make much of an impression. They are fine, as far as they go,
but it is hard to shake the feeling that they have each been more
compelling elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The whole movie looks much better than it plays, thanks to
Anthony Pratt's production design, shot by Roger Pratt through
near-continuous rainfall or drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the first film whose water budget is higher than
its wardrobe costs. Perhaps the visual evocation of the period will
be enough for some moviegoers, but dramatically this is a throwback
that was hardly worth going back for.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
