<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CARTIER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SPACE FOR FAT CATS TO STRETCH OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A turf battle is being fought in the pile-carpeted footwells of
the black sedans that carry white-shoe lawyers and other masters of
the universe.
</P>
<P>
   When Lincoln redesigned its Town Car for the 1998 model year,
customers of executive car services complained that the new car
seemed more cramped than the old one. More recently, Cadillac has
used the extra legroom of its all-new 2000 DeVille _ 43.2 inches,
vs. Lincoln's 41.1 _ to woo car-service operators.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lincoln, the domestic-luxury division of the Ford Motor Co.,
is deploying some new, bigger foot soldiers in the Battle of the
Back Seat.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at the press preview of the Los Angeles Auto Show,
Lincoln is showing half-foot-longer Town Cars that will soon go
into production. They have a longer wheelbase, thicker center
pillars and bigger rear doors. The 6 inches of added legroom is
given over entirely to rear passengers.
</P>
<P>
   One version, the Cartier L, comes with heated rear seats, a
folding armrest with storage bins, rear audio and climate controls,
an extra set of seat controls, ``mood lighting'' and a
``cigar-sized ashtray with illuminated lighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Another model, the Executive L, will have fewer amenities but an
equal amount of space, and will be aimed at livery and limousine
operators. Since Cadillac stopped offering rear-drive cars several
years ago, Lincoln has claimed an 85 percent share of the livery
market.
</P>
<P>
   The Town Car uses the same underbody as the Ford Crown Victoria,
New York's quintessential yellow cab, so Ford could conceivably
also offer a stretched taxicab. Indeed, a Detroit-based
photographer snapped one recently while it was being tested. Ford
officials would not comment on whether a longer, roomier cab is in
the works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
