<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FIJI-GROG-ART-NYT &LR;      01-06 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIJI-GROG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON AN IDYLLIC SOUTH PACIFIC ISLAND, POLITICAL TENSIONS SIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMOSOMO, Fiji _ On his knees, the herald bent toward the acting
chief, fingering his gift of a whale's tooth as he murmured the
standard apologies of greeting.
</P>
<P>
   He had come, he said, to introduce a foreigner who asked leave
to wander around the village, and begged forgiveness in advance for
any breaches of protocol.
</P>
<P>
   The circle of elders, lounging on their hilltop porch, grunted
their approval, ``Ahh, oi, oi, oi, kui!''
</P>
<P>
   One dipped the half shell of a coconut into their communal tub
of kava, a mildly narcotic beverage, and passed it to the acting
chief, Naiqama Lalabalavu. He drank and they all clapped three
times with cupped palms.
</P>
<P>
   The coconut shell was passed among the elders in order of status
until it reached the herald, Sikeli Vasu, a farmer with thickly
calloused hands and a tattoo on one shoulder that read, ``Yoa love
is my great treza.''
</P>
<P>
   Handed the cup, the foreigner drank the bitter brown liquid and
his mouth and tongue grew numb. His hosts clapped three times.
</P>
<P>
   A few more rounds of kava and the world would seem a happier
place, where all people are friends and the disputes among them
seem comically insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how we solve our problems,'' said the acting chief of
the Fijian island of Taveuni, known by his princely title as Ratu
Naiqama (pronounced nine-GAH-mah). ``We just sit around the grog
and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a deceptively simple formula.
</P>
<P>
   Ratu Naiqama is currently in a tense standoff with a cousin,
Epeli Ganilau, to inherit the chiefly mantle from his father,
Glanville Lalabalavu, who died in November.
</P>
<P>
   In a month or so, after a 100-day mourning period, the members
of the chiefly clan here on Taveuni are to sit around the kava
bowl, with their heralds as spokesmen, and come to a consensus over
the succession.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many rounds of kava that will take. At the
moment, all people here are far from friends.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the placid surface of this sunny island, where people
move slowly to what they call Fiji time and smile what the acting
chief called Fiji's ``endless smile,'' Taveuni is seething with
intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   There are whispers of corruption and vote-buying, of personal
impropriety, of unseen power plays and of supernatural curses.
</P>
<P>
   People here no longer kill and eat each other as they did a
century ago, but it seems they would sometimes like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work on Capitol Hill and I have to say that politics here
are much more intense,'' said Daniel Bob, a Senate aide who knows
Fiji well. ``Here, it's non-stop, 24-hours a day, because everybody
is related and everybody lives together and everybody always knows
what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside a hotel swimming pool, Bob stopped suddenly and
looked around. ``Let's lower our voices when we talk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There always seems to be somebody listening.
</P>
<P>
   Some people here say the real power on Taveuni is wielded by
Ratu Epeli's younger brother, known as Ratu Joe, a stolid,
stone-faced man who seems to be everywhere, shielded by dark
glasses and saying nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratu Joe owns everything on Taveuni,'' one of his retainers
said.
</P>
<P>
   And what does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means he can eat you if he wants to,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   But looking in from the sunny surface of life in the islands, it
is impossible to know for sure. Fijians love to joke.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, villages like Somosomo are an idyll of South
Pacific languor, where people fish in the morning, then spend the
afternoons playing cards under the palm trees beside the calm surf.
</P>
<P>
   Women take their sewing machines and rolling pins out onto the
grass and men sit in the shade around the kava bowl, gossiping and,
as they call it, ``yarning,'' shaping and reshaping their world
with words until their problems seem to melt away.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, no matter how many yarns are told, only one man
will become the new chief, either Ratu Naiqama or his cousin Ratu
Epeli.
</P>
<P>
   Their hereditary claims seem equal. Ratu Epeli's father was the
predecessor of Ratu Naiqama's father.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates have already had a trial run, in May, when
they competed for the parliamentary seat that roughly coincides
with Taveuni's chiefly domain.
</P>
<P>
   In this Western-style face-off, where votes are counted one by
one without the saving rituals of kava and talk and handclasps,
Ratu Naiqama won.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Ratu Epeli, accepted defeat with a Fijian smile.
But since then, a whispering campaign has flourished on the island:
``Ratu Naiqama cheated.''
</P>
<P>
   The smiling campaign for the chieftainship has now embroiled the
mourning period for the late chief, Ratu Glanville, during which by
tradition all merrymaking and fishing is to pause for 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   This was the edict of the acting chief and bereaved son, Ratu
Naiqama. By various analyses, it was either rash or cunning.
</P>
<P>
   The edict set off a storm of protest from tour and resort
operators who stood to lose a season's worth of business from skin
divers and from visitors for millennium celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting by the kava bowl, Ratu Naiqama sounded uncompromising.
``Tradition is tradition, taboo is taboo,'' he said. ``Once we make
a decision, that's it. We can't change it. You're not allowed even
to take a dip.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were his words. In Fiji, it seems, words have their own
role to play, especially around the kava bowl. For even as he
spoke, the resorts were full, people were skin diving and
preparations were under way for New Year's merrymaking.
</P>
<P>
   As always, there were whispers.
</P>
<P>
   With a ban in place, said the whisperers, somebody had to pay
somebody for the right to ferry divers out to Rainbow Reef and to
set off fireworks on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the sharks.
</P>
<P>
   In Fiji, it is said, the souls of chiefly ancestors inhabit the
sharks, swimming benignly beside the righteous and attacking and
biting wrongdoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who swim,'' said Ratu Naqama, ``swim at their own
peril. If they are bitten by sharks, that is their peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the mourning period began, one diver off the shores of
Taveuni has been bitten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-MAGNOLIA07-COX     01-06 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MAGNOLIA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What a gorgeous mess
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Magnolia'' is a beautiful disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the most ambitious movie in a spell _ and hands-down the
most pretentious _ Paul Thomas Anderson's follow-up to ``Boogie
Nights'' is another Altmanesque crossweave of fractured lives set
in the San Fernando Valley. This time, though, the writer-director
treads dangerously out of his emotional depth _ and drowns. After a
spectacular start, the movie, absent of anything compelling to say,
crumbles under the weight of its splashy self-importance.
</P>
<P>
   The porn-biz opus ``Boogie Nights'' was an exercise in hollow
showmanship, but at least it was fun. It had energy to burn, most
of it derivative and aimless, little of it in the service of good
storytelling. A young director who wears his cinematic influences
on both sleeves, Anderson tries frantically to outdo himself with
``Magnolia.'' You can see him sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' reveals a director encumbered by visions of
grandeur and immortality. The movie's three hours crackle with
greatness and artistic abandon, and it's hard not to be exhilarated
by Anderson's blazing talent, every last drop of it wrung onto the
screen. But his strenuous efforts to stagger spell the movie's
ruin. ``Magnolia'' is the sort of overwrought calamity only a truly
gifted filmmaker could achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have I recommended a film with so many reservations;
``Magnolia'' is one of the worst must-see movies I can recall. A
supremely assured opera of forced anguish, Anderson's folly ends up
being the world's longest setup without a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is a punch line of sorts, in the form of a
wonderfully rendered biblical plague, whose sheer craziness makes
you giddy. But the scene functions more as an emergency cork to the
director's overflow than an earned punctuation mark, and it's
finally a little embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' opens with a flourish of comic vignettes that shows
Anderson at his tidiest, wittiest best. The stories, narrated by
professional con-man Ricky Jay, are outlandish examples of tragic
coincidence and intersections of fate. They're a surreal prologue
to the upcoming narrative. ``These strange things happen all the
time,'' Jay says wryly.
</P>
<P>
   OK. They do. Unfortunately, nothing of the sort happens in the
loosely entangled stories that follow, and so the opening is a
sham. Anderson works hard to make the characters' chance encounters
look like thunderbolts of serendipity. None is more or less
interesting than a pious cop (John C. Reilly) coming across a
despondent ex-game show whiz (William H. Macy) in the midst of a
crime at film's end. We've watched both of them throughout the
movie in separate story lines, and now, by gosh, here they are
together. Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course the biblical plague scene, goofy and gross, is
strange. But it has nothing to do with cosmic coincidence and
everything to do with directorial panic.)
</P>
<P>
   Anderson knows how to thrill us. His visual bravado is peerless
_ Scorsese on amphetamines. The daredevil structure of his script
creates a layered tapestry that hypnotically unfurls. His dialogue
is funny and literate. He artfully uses (and abuses) music. And he
coaxes stunning performances from his actors, who seem to want to
lay it all down for the hip director.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes place over a 24-hour stretch in the
showbiz-drenched 818 area code. It carries nine semi-related plot
lines and 12 major performances, most of them exceptional. Tom
Cruise, unshackled and electrified, gives a breakout turn as a
repulsive leather-clad TV guru, who instills in his male audience
venomous misogyny with slogans like ``seduce and destroy.''
Reilly's earnest cop is a marvel of botched good intentions and the
most appealing character in the bunch. Julianne Moore, in the badly
underwritten role of a wife in crisis, impressively nibbles the
scenery, and Jason Robards as her cancer-ridden husband manages
affecting interludes from a deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   Each character totes personal baggage that would be tedious to
reveal in print. I know that because it's tedious in the movie. The
banality of their troubles is shocking. More shocking is that
Anderson believes his insights are profound and urgent. He tells us
all about love, and forgiveness and how important it is to be nice
to each other. Essentially, he says we should be good.
</P>
<P>
   It takes him three hours to reach this conclusion. For the first
two hours Anderson neatly layers the characters' lives, slowly
linking them. The structure prevents the characters from becoming
more than one-dimensional sketches, but it allows all of them to
have simultaneous emotional meltdowns. The screen convulses with
tears, hysterics, painful confessions and soul-baring
confrontations _ an actor's nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   The movie at this point should be climaxing, but Anderson cannot
stop. You can't believe there's another hour to go, and for good
reason: There shouldn't be. Anderson has no idea what to do with
what he's wrought, but he marches on. His artistic instincts grope.
They become reckless. And deadly. When the characters start singing
an Aimee Mann tune that spells out his message (``It's not going to
stop/till you wise up''), you're sure the man has lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson may be the most gifted director of his generation. He's
also the most indulgent, and this is his curse and blessing. He's
too in love with his characters and far too impressed with the
dialogue he's given them, but his cinematic literacy astonishes. He
deploys every camera trick in the book, so overusing whooshing
Steadicam shots that they lose meaning. In the end, Anderson is
sabotaged by his own prodigious talent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
