u e BC-REVIEW-SNOW07-COX     01-06 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SNOW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poetry of `Cedars' lies in lush images, musicBy Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When a movie's editing is its best performance,
it's safe to assume the picture has problems. ``Snow Falling on
Cedars'' _ edited with a kind of lyrical rapture by Hank Corwin,
who shaped the dense canvases of ``Natural Born Killers'' and
``Nixon'' _ somehow eludes this fate.
</P>
<P>
   Director Scott Hicks' adaptation of the best-selling David
Guterson novel is a wonder of filmmaking alchemy. Image and music
eloquently dovetail as Hicks (``Shine'') translates the written
word into challenging movie poetry. His unconventional approach is
at the expense of full-blooded character development, but Hicks
achieves something remarkable in the bargain: He altogether skirts
the dreary legal-thriller cliches codified by the John Grisham
school of potboiler, requesting from us Zenlike indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   The results will not work for everyone. Purists are bound to
grumble that the movie is dramatically barren and visually
overripe, but I found the swirling imagery _ it twists and eddies
like snow in a flurry _ a compelling vehicle for the story's
intricate flashback structure.
</P>
<P>
   The visual fretwork complements the tough mystery at the heart
of ``Cedars,'' which spins a web of murder, courtroom theatrics,
star-crossed romance and a frank confrontation (and depiction) of
the internment of Japanese Americans during World War II. Hicks'
feverish mosaic, ebbing and flowing like melting wax, creates a
pictorial puzzle whose resolution slowly pulls into
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the reliably reticent Ethan Hawke, who stars as
heartsick, war-wounded reporter Ishmael Chambers, will feel
shortchanged. The film's aggressively cinematic storytelling
depends on the memorylike jumble of images; their significance
doesn't emerge until the final scenes, when Ishmael's selfless
devotion to the Japanese girl who spurned him (Youki Kudoh) is
poignantly realized.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic: For all its lushness, ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' is
finally a minimalist portrait of uncommon precision. Corwin's
cutting, Robert Richardson's wintry-gray cinematography and James
Newton Howard's elliptical, Phillip Glass-ish score powerfully
conjure the novel's descriptions of time (the '40s and '50s) and
place (a mixed-race fishing village in wet Puget Sound), while
stripping the story to its haunting essence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
