<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES EDGE HIGHER AMID CONCERNS ON STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities rose modestly Thursday,
up for the second time in three days as a downturn in overseas
stock markets and expectations of further losses in the U.S. equity
market encouraged traders to buy fixed income securities.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year benchmark bond increased 23/32 to 94
12/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
its price, fell to 6.56 percent from 6.62 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, market analysts saw investor expectations of further
interest rate increases by the Federal Reserve Board as limiting
the day's price gains. The central bank's monetary policy committee
is expected to raise rates by at least 25 basis points, or
one-quarter of a percentage point, at the conclusion of its two-day
meeting on Feb. 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically the market has priced in a Fed move and given the
central bank a green light to raise short-term rates,'' said Robert
Pugliese, senior vice president amd director of the fixed income
department at J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca Raton, Fla. ``It
now becomes a question of how much of an increase the Fed is
planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Few expected the market to mount any sort of significant rally,
particularly ahead of Friday's employment report. Bonds found some
support Thursday from the weekly jobless claims report issued by
the Labor Department, which said claims rose by a
more-than-expected 33,000 last week to 309,000. The number was well
above the increase of 12,000 that was anticipated, indicating the
labor market's tightness may be easing, potentially reducing
pressures on wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Activity was thin and any uptick today is not justifiable
until we see the jobs report on Friday,'' Pugliese said.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the market has already priced in strong numbers in
the jobs report and probably won't go much lower unless Friday's
numbers prove far stronger than expected. The report is expected to
show the economy added 250,000 new payroll jobs in December, with
the unemployment rate remaining at 4.1 percent. The average hourly
earnings are expected to rise 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the market got both good news and bad news in the home
sales data. ``The positive implication was the decline in home
sales for November and the very sharp downward revision to the
statistics for October,'' said Marilyn Schaja, an economist with
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. The bad news, she said, was the sharp
increases reported in home prices on both a monthly and a
year-to-year basis.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, Treasuries also rose fket talk that
the Treasury will announce details of its buyback program, and that
it will increase the number of callable issues.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the World Bank announced it plans to sell $3 billion
in debt securities in what would be the first fully integrated
global electronic bond offering to be sold, distributed and traded
online.
</P>
<P>
   Lead managers for the offering will be Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
