<SLUG> BC-CANADA-FLU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN HEALTH CARE SYSTEM BESEIGED BY FLU EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A raging flu epidemic, coupled with an acute shortage
of nurses and the absence of too many doctors off sunning in
Florida on wintertime vacations, has transformed emergency rooms
across Canada into disaster zones.
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, people with non-critical ailments, including broken
bones and serious flu, are waiting up to 48 hours to see a doctor,
while the grievously ill or injured are routinely receiving
treatment on stretchers in corridors.
</P>
<P>
   The city's 17 emergency rooms Thursday were overwhelmed by
patient loads representing ``209 percent excess of capacity,''
according health officials. The onslaught stretched doctors, nurses
and other medical staff nearly to the breaking point while creating
dangerous shortfalls of beds, equipment and, in a few extreme
instances, even medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis was nationwide, affecting nearly every major city
from Halifax to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an overload situation, and it's getting worse,'' said
Dr. Hugh Scully, president of the Canadian Medical Association.
``The people who are sick enough to need a bed can't get one.''
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, emergency staff at overcrowded hospitals issued
radio appeals to ambulance drivers to stop delivering patients _
but the ambulances keep on coming.
</P>
<P>
   In Winnipeg, fire inspectors say jammed hospitals have become a
safety hazard, and they have started descending on emergency rooms
to clear away stretchers blocking corridors and exit doors. In
Vancouver, emergency rooms are so overwhelmed that emergency
vehicles carrying patients are idling in long lines waiting to
unload.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emergency room situation is desperate and getting worse,''
said Dr. Pierre Masson at Montreal's Maisoneuve-Rosemont Hospital,
where there were 88 patients requiring immediate admission, but
only 34 beds available. That was typical for hospitals in Canada's
three largest cities _ Toronto, Montreal and Vancouver _ where
Thursday there were nearly three times as many emergency patients
as there were available beds.
</P>
<P>
   The medical crunch started slipping into crisis over the past
few days as a staggering outbreak of influenza _ coupled with the
usual seasonal surge of heart attacks, pneumonia, and broken limbs
from slips on the ice _ arrived right at the peak of the New Year's
holidays, when neighborhood clinics close and many specialists and
doctors in small practices are off soaking up sun in winter havens
such as Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But many health professionals say beseiged ERs and overflowing
wards point to deeper ills in Canada's national health system, a
system reeling from budget cuts, bureaucratic interference, and
political indifference. One of the most glaring symptoms of trouble
in Canada's socialized medical care has been the flight of large
numbers of doctors and nurses to better-paying, better-equipped
hospitals in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, okay, there's been an outbreak of flu, a serious one,''
said James Gibson, a registered nurse in Ontario. ``But an outbreak
of flu isn't the only reason we have people slumping sick in
emergency room chairs and heart attack patients getting treated in
hallways. . . It's the system that's truly sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent days have proven a particular calamity for hard-pressed
hospitals in many of Canada's major cities. The epidemic of flu hit
just at the time when hospitals are at their lowest staffing
levels.
</P>
<P>
   In some emergency rooms, the floors Thursday were slick with
blood, vomit and other body substances, and littered with medical
material, including used syringes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing twice as many patients as we have the capacity to
deal with, and there are no backups to call in,'' said Dr. Lorne
Wiesenfeld, an emergency doctor in Montreal. ``This is really about
a failure in government planning, not just a busy season or unusual
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In Quebec, provincial Health Minister Pauline Marois announced a
$17 million infusion of cash this week to alleviate the emergency
room crisis. But it will be days before the funds are flowing and
weeks _ or months _ before new beds actually become available. And
the emergency cash does not address the much more critical
shortages of doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   At Montreal's St. Luc Hospital, Marie Dubeau was took no cheer
from the news. Clutching the numbered stub she'd taken from a
dispenser when she entered, the 77-year-old woman was in the sixth
hour of waiting to see a doctor. She had come to the emergency room
after suffering chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so uncomfortable, I'm so frightened,'' she said, raising
her frail voice in order to be heard above the wails of feverish
children, moans of car wreck victims, and the terse back-and-forth
of hospital staff. ``But everyone here is sick and frightened. This
is our health care reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In British Columbia, hospitals in Vancouver reported that
``acutely ill'' patients were waiting in ambulances parked outside
emergency rooms too busy and crowded to permit unloading.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was once a rare occurrence in emergency rooms is now
commonplace,'' said Maureen Whyte, vice-president of clinical
services at Vancouver General. ``You can imagine the distress of
people with chest pains or suffering strokes. . . it is very, very
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, 23 of the city's 25 hospitals appealed to ambulance
services to ``re-direct'' patients in need of critical care to
other hospitals. But there were no other emergency rooms able to
handle the overflow, so ambulances just kept delivering patients to
hospitals incapable of providing rapid treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staffs are burning out,'' said Sandy Cruickshank,
spokesman for Toronto's Sunnybrook and Women's College Health
Sciences Center, a Toronto hospital. ``They are exhausted and
getting sick themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manitoba, hospitals in Winnipeg were treating acutely ill
newcomers on beds wheeled into observation rooms and were jamming
the less critical patients into hallways and storage closets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become par for the course, unfortunately,'' said Ann
Bennett, spokeswoman for Grace and Victoria Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario, Quebec and other provinces have seen scores of
hospitals closed in recent years and millions of dollars lopped
from basic health care programs by budget-balancing politicians.
Health care bureaucrats tried to blame vacationing doctors for the
overflowing emergency rooms, but physicians scoffed at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors have been taking holidays at Christmas and New Years
for many years,'' said Dr, Ronald Wexler, president of the Ontario
Medical Association. ``This is the first year we have had a problem
to this extent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
