<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8635 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     01-06 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RELIGION IS AGAIN AN ISSUE IN PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service Clients  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As it has been at various times since the republic
was born, religion once more has become an issue in a presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet a major matter. But controversy has arisen over
George W. Bush's declaration that Jesus is the philosopher who had
the most effect on his life because he ``changed my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, little has been said of the fact that in the same
Dec. 13 Republican debate Gary Bauer, who has conducted a concerted
campaign to win the votes of the religious right, and Utah Sen.
Orrin Hatch made similar comments about the role of Jesus in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush declaration was criticized by some who believe religion
should be kept out of politics and others who argue that Bush's
declaration was simply a political statement dictated primarily by
his determination to win the fundamentalists' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Although his remark reportedly has bolstered his standing with
the Christian right, only Bush can attest to his true motives.
</P>
<P>
   But he refused, when urged by Bauer, to promise that, if he wins
the nomination, his running mate will be an opponent of abortion.
Instead, Bush said he would choose a vice presidential nominee
based on his or her ability to become president.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush were to pledge that his running mate would be a staunch
anti-abortionist, he would rule out such pro-choice politicians as
Govs. George Pataki of New York, Christine Todd Whitman of New
Jersey and Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comment on Jesus won favor with America's most admired
cleric, the Rev. Billy Graham. While stating that he will play no
part in the presidential campaign, Graham lauded Bush as a man of
integrity and decency in a recent CNN interview with Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   Among religious fundamentalists, opposition to abortion has
emerged as the kind of issue that advocacy of prohibition was in
the 20th century. It is a litmus test by which a candidate is
judged and by which votes are cast.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the Catholicism of Democrats John F. Kennedy, who
ran in 1960, and Al Smith, who ran in 1928, and the lack of
organized religion in the lives of Thomas Jefferson and Abraham
Lincoln have been issues. When Michigan Gov. George Romney launched
his unsuccessful bid for the 1968 GOP presidential nomination, he
faced questions about his membership in the Mormon Church, which at
the time considered blacks inferior.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear that he did not accept that view.
</P>
<P>
   Americans always have taken their religion seriously. It was to
achieve religious freedom that the Pilgrims set sail for the New
World. But later whole communities fell under the spell of
religious zealots who were intolerant of citizens who did not abide
by their dictates.
</P>
<P>
   Religious intolerance played an important role in the Salem
witch trials at the end of the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   When the Founding Fathers gathered in Philadelphia to write a
Constitution in the summer of 1787, they included a presidential
oath of office that did not mention divine providence.
</P>
<P>
   They were wary of any suggestion that the newly created United
States would sanction a state religion. And, indeed, the first of
the 10 amendments known as the Bill of Rights, added to the
Constitution in 1791, directed that ``Congress shall make no law
respecting an establishment of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was George Washington who, upon taking the oath in 1790,
added the words ``so help me God.'' And every succeeding president
has repeated that plea for divine guidance.
</P>
<P>
   In general, there were two main denominations in the 13 new
states, according to Christopher and James Lincoln Collier in their
book, ``Decision in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In religion,'' they wrote, ``much of the North was dominated
by the lingering effects of the Calvinist Puritanism on which New
England and other areas had been founded: in the South an
easygoing, worldly Anglicanism, which wished to interfere with
neither pleasure nor profits, held sway.''
</P>
<P>
   The new republic included Methodists, Episcopalians,
Presbyterians, Lutherans, Quakers and members of other Protestant
denominatons as well as a scattering of Catholics and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the men who wrote the Constitution assumed that
Washington, the general who had won the war against England and the
presiding officer at the constitutional convention, would become
president. The office, therefore, was created to some degree to fit
the leadership and character of the Virginia planter who was a man
of strength, honesty, integrity and high intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was an Episcopalian, Washington did not appear to
let religion play a major role in his life. According to William
Degregorio in ``The Complete Book of U.S Presidents,'' Washington
``fashioned a moral code based on his own sense of right and wrong
and adhered to it rigidly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing two centuries, religion often has been an issue
in politics. But the strongest and most enlightened declaration on
the subject probably was made by Kennedy before the Greater Houston
Ministerial Association in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' said the presidential nominee, ``in an America
where the separation of church and state is absolute, where no
Catholic prelate would tell the president how to act and no
Protestant minister would tell his parishioners for whom to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
