<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-WOMEN-VOTERS-0107-COX     01-06 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-VOTERS-0107-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH'S APPEAL AMONG WOMEN COULD EVAPORATE, DEMOCRATIC POLLSTERS
ASSERT
 &HT;    Moving in (p) politics and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush's appeal among women voters
evaporates rapidly when Democrats aggressively attack his record as
the chief executive of Texas, according to a new survey for a major
political organization that helps finance campaigns of pro-choice
Democratic women.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted for Emily's List by two prominent
Democratic pollsters, Celinda Lake and Geoff Garin. It determined
that the depth of Bush's support, especially among likely women
voters, is ``tenuous and shallow'' and could be undermined with a
rigorous campaign that focuses on ``family value'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women voters know very little about Governor Bush's views on
issues or his record as governor of Texas,'' Ellen Malcolm,
president of Emily's List, said at a news conference Thursday. ``As
women voters take a closer look at George W. Bush, they will see he
is a lot more conservative than he is compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said in response to the poll that
Bush has ``broad-based support'' stemming from his campaign as a
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   While the poll puts Bush ahead of both Democratic presidential
candidates among likely male voters at this point in the
presidential campaign, he is in a virtual tie with Vice President
Al Gore among women _ 42 percent for Bush, 41 percent for Gore.
Democrat Bill Bradley polls 39 percent from women.
</P>
<P>
   However, 47 percent of the women who preferred Bush over Gore or
Bradley in a hypothetical match-up by Garin and Lake said they know
little or nothing about Bush's positions or gubernatorial record.
That presents an opportunity for Democrats, according to Garin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Democrats go out and do their job, which is to go tell the
truth about George Bush's record in powerful terms, it will make a
difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide poll was conducted last month among 1,202
registered voters who are likely to vote in the 2000 election,
including 801 women and 401 men. Its margin of error was not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Garin compared the job of Democrats to that of Republicans in
1988 when the elder George Bush faced a 28 point lead in the
general election by the Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis and
ultimately won a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans figured out what they wanted to tell the world
about Michael Dukakis,'' he said. ``Well, we've figured out what we
want to tell women voters about George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Garin and Lake found that Gov. Bush's support among women
dropped significantly when their pollsters asserted to those being
surveyed that Bush had not supported anti-hate crime legislation
and gun control in Texas, had weakened clean air regulations in his
home state, had backed a GOP tax cut plan being debated in Congress
that threatened Medicare, had opposed strong regulation of managed
care health plans, and that Texas pays teachers poorly and does not
offer kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Before those assertions, 34 percent of the women polled said
Bush appealed to them and 37 percent said he did not. Afterward,
they said, 29 percent found him appealing and 45 percent did not _
a shift of 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush, the current leader for the GOP presidential
nomination, runs stronger among women than any Republican candidate
since the gender gap between Republicans and Democrats appeared
with the 1980 presidential campaign of Ronald Reagan. He won 65
percent of the female vote in his 1998 re-election campaign in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is ``clearly better positioned among women voters than
other Republican candidates have been in the past,'' said Garin.
</P>
<P>
   Lake, who also is associated with the Gore presidential
campaign, said surveys show that Democrats already enjoy an
advantage with women voters because they trust Democrats on such
issues as education, health care, retirement and Social Security,
``the key issues'' of the current campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for Democrats is to strengthen their position _
and weaken the Republican advantage _ on these 'value' issues,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's e-mail address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
