<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD STUDIES CITE INEQUITY IN TEXAS EDUCATION REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Harvard University studies of Texas education reform being
released Friday say there is a deepening inequity in the
high-stakes test results between white and minority students and
rich and poor students.
</P>
<P>
   The studies, commissioned by the Civil Rights Project at
Harvard, show that between 1996 and 1998 almost twice as many black
and Hispanic students as white students had not completed the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills (TAAS) exit-level tests required to
obtain a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The TAAS exam has been administered since 1991, and requires
minimum passing scores for students to move to the next grade and,
ultimately, to graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Orfield, co-director of the Civil Rights Project, said
Massachusetts should take heed of what's happening in Texas and
rethink making a high-stakes exam the only measure of educational
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to figure out how to separate high standards and
accountability,'' he said. ``And they should be very careful not to
replace already inadequate infrastructure with an even worse test
drill.''
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts Education Commissioner David P. Driscoll said
Thursday that although he has not seen the Harvard studies, other
ones on TAAS have shown the gap is steadily closing between whites
and minorities, the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a model,'' said Driscoll. ``It's ludicrous to blame
MCAS for what has been a historical neglect of minority and poor
kids in schools. MCAS is what I hope to be the tool, or at least
the leverage over time to close the gap. If it doesn't there is
something drastically wrong with the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time Latinos and blacks took the 10th grade TAAS exam,
75 percent failed. Now, the failure rate is about 40 percent. But
civil rights leaders say one reason for the improvement is teachers
failing ninth graders who they don't think will pass TAAS in tenth
grade.
</P>
<P>
   While the retention rate for Latinos and blacks was 10 percent
in the 1980s, and rose to 30 percent in the 1990s, other studies
have shown students left back are more likely to dropout than
struggle through, improving rates since they aren't tested.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks and Latinos in the Bay State are performing as poorly on
MCAS as their Texas counterparts. About 83 percent failed the exam
in 1998, and many expect similar numbers to fail the 1999 test when
the state releases results soon by race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Other key findings of the Harvard studies:
</P>
<P>
   --Pressure to raise scores leads teachers to spend class time
drilling students on practice exam materials such as learning how
to bubble-in answers, weed out obviously wrong answers and become
accustomed to multiple-choice, computer-scored formats.
</P>
<P>
   --Although the passing rate for the reading section of TAAS in
high schools has been raised, few students are able to use the
skills to complete reading assignments outside class.
</P>
<P>
   --Teachers are encouraged to suspend or interrupt lessons on
subjects not tested by TAAS to prepare for the exam. Library
research, independent projects, science experiments and long-term
writing assigments different from those being tested are being
elminated or reduced in schools with low TAAS scores.
</P>
<P>
   --In low-performing schools, the exam encourages the diversion
of school resources into TAAS prep materials instead of the
instructional resources available to children in middle-class and
wealthy schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing this nationally almost as a fad without
thinking about what happens to kids lives and the schools where
impoverished minority kids are concentrated,'' Orfield said.
``These policies sound good, but the results are bitter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
