<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COX-FOX06-COX     01-06 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-FOX06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senators enter the fray as Fox and Cox squabble
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's nothing like the threat of missing
professional football on television to get the attention of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Northern Virginia suburbs are facing the grim
prospect of missing the National Football League playoffs because
of a dispute between Cox Communications and the Fox network. That
has spurred four U.S. senators into action.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Mike DeWine (R-Ohio), Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.), Herb Kohl
(D-Wis.) and George Voinovich (R-Ohio) issued a letter Thursday
calling on these two media giants to settle a dispute that has seen
some local Fox television stations removed from Cox's cable TV
channel lineups.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the senators called for an extension of something
called a retransmission agreement between Fox and Cox
Communications. It expired at the turn of the new year, and Cox
Communications cannot legally air Fox's programming without it.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been that Cox Communications last weekend stopped
carrying the signals of Fox-owned stations in Northern Virginia,
Cleveland, part of Texas and Arkansas. Other Fox stations remain
unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Cox should add two new Fox cable TV channels
as part of payment for carrying the stations. Federal law requires
cable TV operators to compensate broadcasters for the airing of
their channels.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications welcomed the call from the senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wholeheartedly agree with your suggestion that Fox grant Cox
an extension of our recently expired retransmission consent
agreement so Cox customers can continue to enjoy Fox programming,''
Cox Communications President and Chief Executive Jim Robbins
replied in an open letter to the senators. ``In fact, we have made
this request twice in recent weeks only to have it rejected by Fox
corporate officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox officials did not return phone calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
