<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEXAS-TAAS-BOS &LR;      01-06 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TAAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LATINOS, BLACKS HIT HARD BY HIGH SCHOOL EXIT EXAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Two days before her high school graduation, a
guidance counselor broke the news to Kelly Martinez: ``You are not
graduating.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't want anyone to know. But by second-period, she
learned almost half her senior class at John Jay High School wasn't
graduating, either. They had all failed TAAS, the state's exit
exam. In the halls, students sobbed as teachers tried to console
them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, eight months later, after taking the exam for the eighth
time, she got the results: a 69, one point shy of passing. It means
Martinez still can't get into a four-year college or even get a
decent-paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,''said Martinez, who remains
determined to pass. ``My first job was McDonald's. That's not going
to be my last job.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Texas, thousands of young people each year wind up in
the same situation. And it falls into an all too-familiar pattern:
Latinos and blacks are failing the exam at twice the rate of
whites.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge is set to rule Friday on whether TAAS
discriminates against minorities, a decision that could affect
state-mandated exams throughout the country. Education officials
and academics here and across the nation have used Texas'
high-stakes approach to education reform as a model.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican-American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, which
sued Texas in 1997 on behalf of minority students, wants the state
to do away with TAAS because schools aren't preparing minorities to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills became a
graduation requirement, the percentage of Latinos and blacks
graduating on time fell 11 points, from 60 to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991 when TAAS became a graduation requirement, about
100,000 students have been denied diplomas, most of them Latino and
black. It's created a firestorm of complaints from critics who say
underfunded schools in poor districts are not properly educating
these students.
</P>
<P>
   The state, however, argues that without the exam, students would
just continue to be passed on from grade to grade without teaching
them the basic skills they need. Although minorities failed in
large numbers when TAAS was first implemented, the gap has
narrowed, school officials said, proof the exam has forced
districts to expect more from their students.
</P>
<P>
   Leticia Saucedo, a MALDEF attorney, said the group is aware the
case is important to people outside of Texas as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are watching it all over the country,'' Saucedo said.
``It'll have implications in Massachusetts, where people are going
to see the affects that these tests have.''
</P>
<P>
   As Massachusetts begins looking toward 2003 when passing the
Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System will be a graduation
requirement, critics here point to Texas with worry.
</P>
<P>
   What Texas has taught the nation is that in the name of
education reform there will be casualties, and the majority of them
will be minorities, civil rights organizations say.
</P>
<P>
   The reform effort did away with the social promotion, an
assembly-line approach that produced mediocre students. But now,
because of TAAS, critics say that students in poor communities _
most of them minorities _ are being cheated out of real schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Because Texas school districts come under strict penalities if
their students fail TAAS, they've had to come up with quick
solutions for helping students in poor communities pass. In many of
those schools, critics say, teachers spend hours drilling students
on TAAS, instead of teaching them critical thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's robbing these children of an education in the name of
administrative accountability,'' said Linda McNeil, director of the
Rice University Center for Education.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ramon, a sixth grade teacher at Pearsall Junior High
School, a small, working-class town 50 miles south of San Antonio,
said his students hate TAAS. ``There's not a day that goes by that
they don't hear us talk about TAAS,'' Ramon said. ``There's so much
emphasis placed on it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest fallouts, say civil rights leaders, has been
the surge in dropouts. It has prompted criticism of the state's new
definition of a dropout.
</P>
<P>
   Before TAAS, the percentage of Latinos and blacks who graduated
on time stayed steady at 60 percent. For whites, it was 78 percent.
After TAAS, the percentage of Latino and black students who
graduated on time dropped to 50 percent. For whites, it dropped to
75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kauffman, the attorney who tried MALDEF's case, says most of
students who don't graduate on time wind up dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   But the state refutes that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Lozano, a spokesman for the Texas Education Agency, is
confident U.S. District Judge Edward Prado will rule in the state's
favor. He said when the NAACP complained about the exam to the US
Department of Education's Office of Civil Rights several years ago,
they opened an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made no findings of it being discriminatory,'' Lozano
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he said, just 2.3 percent of Latinos dropped out of
school, compared to 2.1 percent of blacks and 0.9 percent of
whites.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the lower dropout rates is because the state
redefined what constitutes a dropout. It no longer considers those
who leave and get a GED as dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't count them as drop outs because they continue to get
their education,'' Lozano said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it count people like Martinez, who has a certificate,
not a diploma, but continues to take the TAAS math exam, hoping to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   On the west side of the city, where concrete ranch-style homes
stretch across tiny lots, Kelly Martinez, 19, sits curled on a red
sofa, watching the Gen X drama ``Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   During the day, she works a part-time boutique job. At night, if
she's not at a math tutoring class, she's at home with her mother.
The two talk constantly about TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw she didn't pass TAAS the first time, I yanked her
from the Pep Squad,'' said her mother, Mary Martinez. ``She's
worked so hard. She was a good student. I feel like the school
failed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she said most of her math teachers in high school gave
busy work and didn't really teach, Kelly Martinez blames herself
for not passing TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should've gone to someone else for help,'' she said. In her
senior year, she scrambled to learn algebra, geometry,
trigonometry, and statistics, her scores rising each time she took
the exam.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez' counselor told her, ``Just get your GED and get it
over with.'' But her mother doesn't want her to give up.
</P>
<P>
   The next time she takes the exam, in March, Martinez, says
she'll pass. Until then, she's keeping her class ring tucked in a
drawer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
