<HEADER>
A8673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOND-NORRIS-COLUMN-NY     01-06 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOND-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATION-INDEXED BONDS: BORING, IGNORED, MAYBE A GOOD INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   May you live in interesting times.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the ancient Chinese curse. And these days the stock
market is nothing if not interesting. Internet stocks double within
days, then lose most of the gains within a few more. The Nasdaq
composite index has 100-point swings within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When a show is providing a thrill a minute, there is a risk that
the competing act down the block will be ignored. That is what has
happened to the least risky _ and therefore least exciting _
investment around. As cash flooded into Nasdaq stocks, nobody
seemed interested in a boring investment that can't lose money, but
that has only a limited upside. So it kept getting cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The competing investment is inflation-indexed bonds. They are
not very exciting, and, to tell the truth, they have not been very
good investments in the three years during which they have been
available. Inflation has been quiet, and interest in the bond,
never high, has declined.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the real yield on such bonds _ the amount a holder
gets in addition to the increase in the Consumer Price Index _ has
risen to 4.39 percent, half a percentage point higher than the
yield last spring.
</P>
<P>
   That is about what the yield is expected to be when the Treasury
auctions a new issue of 10-year inflation-indexed bonds Wednesday.
Buy one, and you will get a coupon payment of that amount that will
rise with inflation. And when the bond matures, the principal you
get back will be increased to reflect all the inflation there was
during the life of the bond.
</P>
<P>
   By any historical standard, 4.3 percent is an extraordinary real
return on a safe investment, and it is not easy to explain why it
is available. Inflation-indexed bonds in other countries _ Canada,
Britain, France and Australia offer them _ used to offer higher
yields than the American bonds. Now the situation is reversed.
Perhaps it indicates a strong demand for capital in this country,
which pushes real rates higher.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly it reflects the fact that there is little fear of
either inflation or bear markets. ``Investors are expecting great
things from the equity markets, so inflation-indexed bonds have to
have higher yields,'' says Dan Bernstein, the director of research
at Bridgewater Associates, a money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years that such bonds have been available, the
public interest in them has gone from moderate to something close
to nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   This week's stock market volatility is not all that greater than
the volatility at peak points last year. That volatility did not
scare investors away from speculative stocks, and this turmoil may
not either. Many investors see all stock market declines as buying
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be interesting to see if individual investor demand
for inflation-indexed bonds does rise at next week's auction. For
there are basically two ways to use historical patterns in making
investment decisions. One way is to assume that Mr. Market, as
Warren Buffett likes to say, sometimes offers things cheap and
sometimes offers them dear, and good investors buy them when they
are cheap. By that standard, these bonds are very attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The other way is to go with the theory that stocks have been
proved to be the best long-term investment, period, and that there
is no need to worry about things like valuation or the risk of
losing money over the long term. Those who subscribe to that theory
no doubt will ignore this auction. Time will tell which view was
the more profitable one.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
