A8674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MRSWINNERS07-COX     01-06 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSWINNERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winners International revamped
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winners International Restaurants has formed a
partnership with BankBoston Development Co. and RTM Restaurant
Group in a deal that will allow the company to nearly double its
size over five years.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, BankBoston Development Co. will invest $5
million in Winners, which owns the Mrs. Winner's Chicken &AMP; Biscuits
and Lee's Famous Recipe Chicken Restaurants brands. Other companies
made additional undisclosed capital investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving along with our turnaround strategy,'' said Morgan
Hill, president and chief executive of Dunwoody, Ga.-based Winners
International. ``We needed a new game plan that would allow us a
bigger future as far as growth is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the company has worked to increase sales in its
core brands. Sales have been sluggish because of an aging image and
low market penetration.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the recapitalization, RTM owns about 20 percent of
Winners, and the executive management team of Winners International
and BankBoston owns the rest. BankBoston has the largest stake.
</P>
<P>
   The capital will allow the company to grow and increase its
franchising efforts, particularly focusing on minority franchisees
and development in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking across the board, but we do want to do more with
minorities just because it makes sense within the communities in
which we operate,'' Hill said. About 40 percent of Winners'
restaurants are in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the company plans to grow from about 350 company-owned
and franchised units to 600 within the next five years. Eventually,
he said, the company is interested in acquiring other concepts and
exploring new opportunities in nontraditional areas such as vending
and selling products in grocery and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   John Gray, senior vice president of corporate communications for
RTM, said his company ``will remain very much involved in and
support Winners International in all areas of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, RTM owned both the Mrs. Winner's and Lee's brands.
With this deal, Winners becomes a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco De Jesus, vice president of the private equity group
of BankBoston Development Co. of Boston and treasurer of Winners
International, said his firm is interested in investing in minority
or female-owned businesses that operate in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through this vehicle we hope to provide wealth-creating
opportunities for the employees, franchisees and the management
group,'' he said. He said the brands do well in both urban and
suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Winners International announced the signing of a deal with
Atlanta-based DIWA Group. The deal is to develop 10 Mrs. Winner's
restaurants across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The first will open late this year in the Athens/Winder area.
Each will be a Mrs. Winner's and A&AMP;W co-branded unit located near
or connected to a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
