<P>
   FILM-SNOW (Undated) _ Author David Guterson's 1994 historical
mystery ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' has the distinction of being the
most popular novel to be set in the Pacific Northwest since Betty
MacDonald's 1946 ``The Egg and I.'' The film version is visually
poetic, non-linear in structure and relatively uncompromising. At
the same time, it has _ perhaps inevitably _ lost much of the
novel's drive and core of originality, and its characters have been
reduced to movie stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
