<P>
   FILM-MAGNOLIA (Undated) _ Based on his first two films, ``Hard
Eight'' and ``Boogie Nights,'' it's obvious twentysomething
director Paul Thomas Anderson is that one out of a thousand young
American Indie directors who is ``the real thing'' and on the
threshold of a big career. And his audacious new three-hour film,
``Magnolia,'' is only likely to boost his stock.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LOVE (Undated) _ The 1998 film, ``Show Me Love,'' was the
biggest box office hit in Sweden and it's easy to see why. It's an
awkward, unapologetic, unconventional _ and ultimately winning _
look at first love, one that unabashedly portrays the complications
and confusion that result from those first crushes and rushes of
attraction and passion.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-MALCOLM (Undated) _ With the sitcom genre having its obituary
read at every opportunity, there's no assurance that ``Malcolm in
the Middle'' will be a hit. It is smart, irreverent and funny,
which means diddly in the carpeted offices of TV execdom, where
high quality may be completely irrelevant to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e''
category.)
</P>
