u p BC-GORE-POWELL-NYT     01-06 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-POWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S CAMPAIGN MANAGER UNDER FIRE FOR REMARKS ABOUT BLACK GOP
LEADERS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gen. Colin Powell sent an aggrieved letter to Vice
President Al Gore Thursday, saying he had been ``disappointed and
offended'' by recent remarks by his campaign manager, Donna
Brazile, suggesting that Republicans had no interest in helping
black children.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Bloomberg.com last week, Ms. Brazile is
quoted as saying: ``Republicans bring out Colin Powell and J.C.
Watts because they have no program, no policy. They play that game
because they have no other game. They have no love and no joy.
They'd rather take pictures with black children than feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gore, Chris Lehane, said the campaign did not
feel an apology was necessary. ``There's no question that Colin
Powell is a great American hero we all admire,'' he said.
``However, having Colin Powell and J.C. Watts in the Republican
Party no matter how distinguished they are is no substitute for an
agenda that supports African Americans and that was simply Donna
Brazile's point.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brazile ``is doing a great job as campaign manager and will
continue to do a great job as campaign manager,'' Lehane added.
Asked whether she or anyone else at the campaign now regrets her
choice of words, he said, ``The bottom line is the Republican Party
does not have an agenda for African Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In Powell's letter, a stern but exceedingly measured response
completely devoid of incendiary language, Powell enumerated his
many activities on behalf of young people and said, ``I do so to
help feed, educate and spiritually nourish all of America's
children, black and white, and not just for a photo op. And I do so
as a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Watts' legislative efforts on behalf of children,
saying ``Ms. Brazile has paid him a great disservice.'' And he
ended the letter by saying, ``We can debate and disagree over
specific programs and approaches, but let's not start the new
century by playing the polarizing `race card' which immediately
contaminates and destroys the opportunity for open debate on issues
of importance to all our children.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate letter sent to Gore on Wednesday, Watts also
complained of Ms. Brazile's ``racist remarks'' and called them
``appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am particularly outraged by her claim that black Republicans
would rather `take pictures of children than feed them.' She has
personally attacked two black Americans who have worked hard to
help African Americans, particularly children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it particularly ironic,'' the letter continued, ``that
she would condemn black Republicans for having `no love and no joy'
when her own remarks are so bitter and hurtful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brazile, who is also black, was fired from the 1988 Dukakis
campaign for suggesting that reporters should look into rumors that
her candidate's opponent, Vice President George Bush, was having an
affair. On Thursday, Pat Harrison, co-chairwoman of the Republican
National Committee, said Ms. Brazile was ``at it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harrison also sent a letter to Gore, demanding that he fire
Ms. Brazile and calling her comments ``the meanest, nastiest
rhetoric we have heard in this campaign to date.''
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview, Ms. Harrison said Democrats typically used
offensive words to characterize Republicans and Gore bordered ``on
this kind of thing himself'' when ``rather than saying what
positive things the Democrats would do, he prefers to say why they
shouldn't be Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said he did not think there would be any response to any
of the letters. And a spokesman for Watts said at least in his
case, none was expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not holding our breath,'' said the spokesman, Bill
Shapard. ``These comments are not new or unique. The other side of
the aisle takes any opportunity to inject race into anything they
can.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
