<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0107-COX     01-06 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0107-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXILE PROTESTERS DISRUPT MIAMI, ANGRY OVER DECISION TO SEND BOY
BACK TO CUBA
 &HT;    With Photos by The Palm Beach Post.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Angry Cuban exiles staged sit-ins and marches that
tangled traffic and temporarily shut down the street entrance to
Miami's bustling port Thursday, demanding a reversal of the federal
government's decision to ship 6-year-old rafter Elian Gonzalez back
to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The protests halted commerce, inflamed drivers and turned
downtown Miami into a roiling stage for political theater. As news
helicopters hovered noisily overhead, a few hundred chanting,
flag-waving demonstrators faced off with riot-clad police officers
carrying night-sticks and plastic shields.
</P>
<P>
   A few scuffles broke out as police wrestled some of the
protestors to the ground, but most of the demonstrations appeared
peaceful. By late in the day, law enforcement officials said more
than 100 people had been arrested, arrested, mostly on misdemeanor
disorderly conduct charges.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Miami's streets simmered, U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno said she supports Immigration and Naturalization Service
Commissioner Doris Meissner's decision to send Elian back to his
home in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully agree with her determination that the father has the
legal right and the legal authority to speak for his child in
immigration matters,'' Reno said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, however, didn't completely slam the door on reversing the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any information that we are not privy to _ I never
say that I won't reverse myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the boy's Miami relatives, who have had custody of
him since he was found clinging to an inner tube on Thanksgiving
Day, claimed they have that information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have new and important evidence,'' attorney Spencer Eig
said in a television interview. ``Commissioner Meissner said her
decision was based on what was best for the child psychologically.
But she had no evidence on Elian's psychological state. We're ready
to present full psychological profiles to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Eig plans to file a federal lawsuit seeking to halt Elian's
return to Cuba if appeals to Reno and President Bill Clinton are
ignored. Meissner announced Wednesday that she wants the boy sent
back home by Jan. 14, although she left open exactly how that would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   She appealed to the boy's father in Cuba and his relatives in
Miami to reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed unlikely Thursday as tempers boiled over. Elian's
Miami relatives said they spoke by telephone with the boy's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, but failed to reach any conclusions about
what will happen in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Elian remained in seclusion much of the day, although late in
the afternoon he was brought to the modest Little Havana home of
his great-uncle. He smiled and rode on a relative's shoulders as a
small crowd of supporters cheered.
</P>
<P>
   His family in Miami believes the boy's father is being
manipulated by Cuban leader Fidel Castro, and can't speak freely
about his true wishes. They insist the boy be given an asylum
hearing and that Gonzalez travel to Miami to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts doubt the courts will allow such a hearing
following Meissner's decision, which they say was solidly grounded
in both U.S. and international law.
</P>
<P>
   But the emotional protests in Miami raise the question of just
what might happen if the boy is actually taken back to Cuba. There
has been no indication that Elian's Miami family would try to block
or hinder the transfer _ but neither has there been any discussion
of when or where such a transfer might happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have hope,'' said Marisleysis Gonzalez, Elian's
cousin, who has cared for him much of the time he has been in
Miami. ``There was a miracle that he's here, and I'll hope there
will be another one.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, INS officials confirmed that Gonzalez asked that
the National Council of Churches act as an intermediary in
returning his son back to Cuba. Representatives of the group met
with Gonzalez at the request of Cuban church officials earlier this
week and offered to broker the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   But angry Cuban exiles in Miami have vowed to form a human chain
around the boy to stop his return. Short of that, they did their
best to disrupt traffic in Miami and gain media attention Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with several large trucks slowing down to a crawl
on a major Miami expressway, with cars stacking up in a huge line
behind them. Police quickly broke up the slow-down by ticketing the
truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Next came a noon protest near the federal building in downtown
Miami, which drew several hundred protestors who waved Cuban flags
and anti-Clinton signs while chanting ``libertad'' or ``freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   After a short rally, hundreds of protestors suddenly broke
through a police line, shoving past mounted officers and bolting
for the city's waterfront, about 10 blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers split into several groups, dashing in different
directions and paralyzing traffic for several blocks. Many of them
proceeded to Miami's sparkling new waterfront arena, where they
staged a sit-down in the streets leading to the Port of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our right to protest,'' said Henry Perez, 58, a Cuban
immigrant. ``We're sorry for the inconvenience, but it's a
statement that has to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested several dozen protestors, hauling them away in
waiting paddy wagons. The new arena, just opened in the past few
days, was scheduled to host a Miami Heat professional basketball
game Thursday night. Late in the day, the game was still scheduled
to take place, although a heavy police contingent was on hand in
case more protestors arrived.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon wore on, other demonstrations broke out across
the city, with a large one at Red Road and Flagler Street slowing
traffic and resulting in a few scuffles as protestors were
arrested. Television video showed several men being wrestled to the
ground by officers, one with a bloody head as he was led away.
</P>
<P>
   One frustrated driver stopped by protesters in Little Havana
jammed on his accelerator, flinging two protesters to the ground in
a heap. There was no immediate report on their condition, but the
driver reportedly turned himself into police.
</P>
<P>
   Miami City Commissioner Tomas Regalado jostled briefly with
officers as they made arrests, but was not taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Other Miami officials, including State Attorney Katherine
Fernandez-Rundle and Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, called for calm,
pleading with the protestors not to disrupt the community but to
send their pleas to Washington in the form of letters and telephone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   But tempers seemed likely to grow only shorter if the protests
continue in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   One man who called himself ``100 percent Cuban'' fumed quietly
on a side street near the Port of Miami, unable to drive his
semi-truck into the facility to pick up a load of cargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are with them on their idea, but this is no good,'' said
Ariel Rodriguez. ``I've got to work. I've got to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
