<HEADER>
A8681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HMO-BAILOUT-BOS &LR;      01-06 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-BAILOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE AGREES, HARVARD PILGRIM HMO NEEDS FIX, FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For Harvard Pilgrim Health Plan, the number one problem
right now isn't money. It's time.
</P>
<P>
   As New England's largest health plan enters the uncertain
terrain of state receivership _ a notch above bankruptcy _
regulators, lawmakers, insurance experts, and major customers
Thursday stressed the need for urgency in putting Harvard Pilgrim
back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner we find a resolution the better,'' said state
insurance commissioner Linda Ruthardt, the court-appointed
``receiver'' who assumed management of the $2.8 billion-a-year
health plan Tuesday. ``We recognize that speed matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The health maintenance organization expects to have enough cash
to operate in 2000, even though its reserves are projected this
year to sink deeply into negative numbers. But the adequacy of
ongoing cash flow is predicated on a big and possibly shaky ``if.''
</P>
<P>
   If a path back to financial viability is not reasonably clear in
the next few months, many observers said, nervous subscribers and
their employers may start to bolt.
</P>
<P>
   Major defections would drain the ongoing revenues that Harvard
Pilgrim needs to stay afloat while Ruthardt, the Supreme Judicial
Court, and possibly the Legislature build and activate an orderly
mechanism to pay hundreds of millions of dollars in past debts.
State tax dollars could be part of the plan, key legislators said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO this week announced that its 1999 losses alone could
total $177 million and that available assets to cover losses may
fall to a negative $100 million _ another way of saying the
nonprofit insurer has, or sometime soon will have, a negative net
worth.
</P>
<P>
   A health plan can operate with a negative net worth for some
time as long as cash keeps coming in to meet current expenses. But
cash can dwindle rapidly if customers start to exit a health plan,
like nervous depositers pulling their cash out of an ailing bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state needs a clear idea soon whether the health plan can
be rehabilitated,'' Turnbull said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason time is short is that thousands of employers, who
make health insurance decisions on behalf of their workers, will
have an opportunity to cast a vote of no-confidence in Harvard
Pilgrim in the next months.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of Harvard Pilgrim's subscribers are locked in
to annual contracts that went into effect January 1. Another
200,000 of the HMO's million or so Massachusetts subscribers have
contracts that expire June 30, but employer decisions on those
agreements are made as long as four to six months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Another 400,000 or so subscribers have reenrollment
anniversaries that occur throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To allow this to drag out will clearly worsen the situation,''
said state Senator Robert A. Bernstein, a Worcester Democrat who is
cochairman of the Legislature's Joint Insurance Committee. ``If
this thing kicks around for six months. . .you would see widespread
defections. If uncertainty is allowed to linger and fear among
consumers and providers is allowed to fester, the weight of that
itself could prove fatal. That's why time is clearly of the
essence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein and others are beginning to worry about the impact on
other Massachusetts HMOs _ Harvard Pilgrim's competitors _ if large
numbers of subscribers jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other insurers may or may not be able to absorb the volume,''
the legislator said. ``I'm not sure that would be a positive thing
for Tufts Health Plan or Fallon. I don't think you're seeing
celebration in the halls of Harvard Pilgrim's competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come renewal time, there's going to be a lot of pressure,''
said Ed Maguire, senior vice president of benefits at Sapers &AMP;
Wallack, a Boston consulting firm. ``We're hearing from a lot of
people today.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, executives at Massachusetts HMOs said they are hastily
attempting to gear up for an onslaught if Harvard Pilgrim is
liquidated or sold, as occurred last fall with its Rhode Island
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Such a situation ``would create a fair amount of chaos,'' said
one Massachusetts HMO executive, who asked to remain anonymous.
``We'd get deluged in a very short period of time, and that's an
operational nightmare. We'd live through it, but it won't be
pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   A major worry, that executive said, is that ``Harvard Pilgrim is
losing money on a lot of those people, and we don't have a whole
lot more money to lose ourselves.'' Under terms of a state HMO
receivership law enacted last November, HMOs that absorb
subscribers from a failed competitor may not jack up rates for the
transferred customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated, however, that consumer flight from Harvard
Pilgrim may be limited by the precarious situation of other Bay
State HMOs, combined with many subscribers' reluctance to change
health plans and disrupt physician relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tufts Health Plan and Fallon Community Health Plan suffered
major losses last year, and last month were placed on a state
watchlist giving the insurance division authority to examine
finances and participate in planning. Harvard Pilgrim was put on
the watchlist at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Harvard Pilgrim going to lose some subscribers?
Absolutely,'' said state Representative Nancy Flavin, an East
Hampton Democrat who is the Insurance Committee's House
cochairperson. ``But employers will look at all their options. And
let me tell you, Tufts and Fallon are fragile too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are starting to think there's no safe place,''
agreed Susan Connolly, a partner at William M. Mercer, a Boston
benefits consulting firm. ``I've been telling clients to sit tight,
which is tough because employers are very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard Pilgrim spokesman said the company has detected ``no
sense of panic'' from its customers, although ``they all want more
information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first indications from employers we've spoken to is they
continue to have confidence in the plan,'' said Alan Raymond of
Harvard Pilgrim. ``The first day and a half there was a sense that
everything had gone wrong. Now there's a sense we have an
opportunity and some breathing room to work our way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer Charles Stein contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
