<HEADLINE>
HOW TO ANNOY YOUR BOSS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Have you annoyed your boss today?'' asks Details magazine,
which provides a multitude of quotes from bosses who have been
irked.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Some people take so much time perfecting a memo that it
loses its power and value because it's so late,'' said one boss.
``I don't want perfection. I want the information. Says another,
``Speed is important, but don't hand me written work that has not
been proofread. I find myself distracted by the mistakes. ... I
quickly lose respect.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't dress better than the boss. ``Deep down,'' says a San
Francisco boss, ``I feel like you're angling for my job, like
you're already dressing as if you had it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Never send me a folded resume,'' says a boss. ``I can't file
it easily and it rolls up like an armadillo on my desk. If you
knock and I don't answer, don't knock again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``There's nothing worse than a guy who wants to problem-solve
while you're at the urinal.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Never stand up in a meeting to talk about something you
haven't first discussed with your boss. We hate to be blindsided by
information.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Over-communication is what really gets to me,'' said one
boss. ``I can't stand it when an employee floods me with
information.'' Said another, ``Holding off telling me about a
serious problem in the hopes that you can fix it yourself is a very
dangerous strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Page numbers, or the lack of them: ``Say someone gives me a
20-page report to read, and there are no page numbers on it.''
That's what makes another guy angry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THROUGH THE VATICAN LENS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sandy Phillips &LR; , senior curator of photography at the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art, is off at the end of this month to
the American Academy in Rome _  &UR; Linda Blumberg &LR; , formerly of Capp
Street, is arts director at the Academy _ a base from which she'll
spend six months studying the Vatican collection of photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody with any knowledge of photogrs ever looked at
it,'' she says. Phillips has no idea what she'll find in the
archive, which is likely to include pictures taken by photographers
commissioned by the papacy to document the history of Christianity,
``not only in Rome, but worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   It's particularly interesting, she says, ``because photography
came into being at the moment when the Italian state was coming
into being, so it's politically connected to the birth of
nationalism there and the changes in the papacy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Washington Monthly got hold of a note sent to Yalies who
were  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; 's fellow members of the secret society Skull
and Bones: ``In view of the political happenings in the world,''
said the memo, ``I feel compelled to remind all of the tradition of
privacy and confidentiality essential to the well-being of our
Order and strongly urge stout resistance to the seductions and
blandishments of the Fourth Estate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In a perfect demonstration of precise New Year's Eve timing,
at midnight: The shouted countdown at ``Beach Blanket Babylon''
reached zero, the show's extendable pyramid reached its zenith
height and, in the audience,  &UR; Paul Gordon  &LR; proposed to  &UR; Sandra &LR; 
 &UR; Fregosi &LR; , whom he had met there two years ago. She said yes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Washingtonian magazine reveals that the Smithsonian is
planning to stuff the late panda  &UR; Hsing-Hsing &LR;  and put him on
display at the Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUFFS OF SMOKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; President Clinton &LR;  has named Philip Morris lobbyist  &UR; William &LR; 
 &UR; Oldaker &LR;  to the National Bioethics Advisory Commission, and
anti-tobacco advocates are not happy about it. Oldaker helped
defeat a tobacco regulation bill sponsored by Sen.  &UR; John McCain &LR; ,
R-Ariz., in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reader  &UR; Walter Nelson-Rees &LR;  writes that when he
complained to the manager's assistant at the Williamsburg Inn in
Virginia _ a major tobacco-growing state _ about smokers in the
lounge, he was told that the room couldn't be designated nonsmoking
because it had a fireplace in use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to do whacked-out, avant-garde, twisted stuff that
makes you think a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; John Darin, Hollywood hair colorist to the stars (Kurt
Russell, Illeana Douglas), who has just released a solo recording,
``Fans of Insanity.'' Darin is profiled in Los Angeles magazine,
which describes one of his tunes as a mixture of sexual moans and
African drums.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOTE TO EDITORS: PERSONALS WILL BE ON VACATION UNTIL JANUARY &LR; 
 &UR; 31. &LR;
</P>
