<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNIST PARTY LEADER TO SEEK RUSSIAN PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Another candidate entered the race to succeed Boris
Yeltsin as president on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist Party leader, said he will run
for president, joining a small field that is challenging the acting
president, Vladimir Putin. Others in the race are Grigory
Yavlinsky, leader of the liberal Yabloko party, and Vladimir
Zhirinovsky, a flamboyant nationalist maverick.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, once considered the
leading candidate, has yet to announce his decision. But Oleg
Morozov, a politician close to him, said he doubted that Primakov
would run against Putin, considering that their views are not so
different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
