<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Jan. 7. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   AUDITORS-STOCK (New York) _ Most partners of
PricewaterhouseCoopers, the world's largest accounting firm,
violated rules requiring that they not have investments in
companies audited by their firm, the Securities and Exchange
Commission says. The firm says that five partners had been
dismissed as a result of the investigation. By Floyd Norris. (We
plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,600
words.
</P>
<P>
   Top center: 3-column photo reefer to MCCAIN-FCC and
REPUBS-DEBATE; stories inside.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEATH-PENALTY (Houston) _ In his five years as governor of
Texas, George W. Bush has presided over the executions of 111 men
and one woman, nearly one of every five carried out in the United
States since the Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty in
1976. By any measure, Bush's commitment to capital punishment is
unquestioned. But as he runs for president as a more compassionate
kind of Republican, his death penalty record also offers insights
into his distinct views of mercy and justice. By Jim Yardley.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   A Special Report; 2,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ When Clinton administration
officials interviewed Gen. Charles Krulak for the job of commandant
of the Marine Corps in 1995, he recalls, no one asked him for his
views on any social issue facing the military. And so he said he
was dismayed when he read that the two Democratic candidates for
president, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley,
would require their appointees to the Joint Chiefs of Staff to
support allowing homosexuals to serve openly in the military. Gore
went even further than Bradley to say it would be a litmus test for
any nominee he selected. By Steven Lee Myers. (Scheduled to move by
9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ India intensifies its
efforts to blame Pakistan for the Indian Airlines hijacking,
announcing that four accomplices had been seized in Bombay and that
they have identified the five hijackers as Pakistanis and
acknowledge official Pakistani sponsorship of the hijacking. By
Celia W. Dugger. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-INCENTIVES (Undated) _ On Wednesday, only hours after
New York's Gov. George Pataki asked lawmakers in Albany to
subsidize tuition for anyone who commits to teach in a New York
public school, Gov. Gray Davis of California addressed the
legislature in Sacramento with what, in effect, amounted to a
counteroffer. California, Davis proposed, should offer candidates
for its teaching jobs $10,000 home loans, $30,000 bonuses if they
attain advanced certification and $11,000 to repay college loans if
they agree to work in low-performing schools. By Jacques Steinberg.
(Scheduled to move by 8:45 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo reefer to: CUBA-BOY; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok) _ After enduring bitter street fights
in Grozny and mountain battles with hundreds of rebels, the Russian
military is facing a new threat: sabotage in rear areas supposedly
controlled by Russian forces. Senior Russian commanders said
Thursday that rebel fighters crept through a dense fog on Tuesday
and set fire to a major Russian field hospital. The rebels have
also been mining roads behind Russian lines. Russian commanders
also fear the militants may try to send small groups of saboteurs
into Russian-controlled settlements, like Gudermes, Chechnya's
second-largest city. By Michael R. Gordon. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-ROCKER _ John Rocker is ordered by baseball to
undergo psychological tests before deciding whether to punish the
outspoken reliever for remarks he made disparaging gays, minorities
and immigrants. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-OBRIAN (Undated) _ Patrick O'Brian dies.
</P>
