<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AIR-TRAFFIC-430&AMP;ADD-N     01-06 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-TRAFFIC-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA COMPUTER MALFUNCTION CAUSES FLIGHT DELAYS IN NORTHEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Pa., Washington D.C., N.C., Va., Ga., Fla.,
N.H., Ind.)  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in category `w') 
(rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The air traffic control system might have
functioned normally through the transition to 2000, but ``normal''
for the system has come to mean sporadic failures. Thursday, one of
those failures affected thousands of air travelers around the
eastern United States by delaying departures for up to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of flights from Boston, New York, Philadelphia,
Washington and Raleigh, N.C., were delayed for much of the morning,
and chain-reaction problems persisted well into the afternoon. The
malfunction was traced to a computer at the Federal Aviation
Administration's Washington Air Route Traffic Control Center in
Leesburg, Va., which handles mostly long-distance and high-altitude
flights over an area of 200,000 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   The computer began showing problems at 6:15 a.m. and had to be
turned off. It was restarted at 9:50 a.m., according to the FAA.
Even after the computer was working again, the tasks of re-entering
data and cleaning out the backlog of planes took most of the day.
Most of those airplanes were then late for flights later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians said the flaw appeared to be a software problem in a
1960s-vintage program and did not appear to be related to the
changeover to 2000. Computer experts said a program that stores
flight plans as they are received from airlines and from other FAA
offices overloaded because it stopped deleting the flight plans
when flights are completed or leave the area.
</P>
<P>
   The malfunction forced controllers to switch to a less capable
backup system, reducing the number of flights they could handle at
one time. The backup required controllers to type in information on
each flight's identity and destination. Tasks usually done with the
click of a mouse, like passing the information off to the next
controller when the plane goes from sector to sector, suddenly had
to be done by controllers carrying slips of paper across control
rooms. Others had to dictate by telephone data that usually
traveled by high-speed modem.
</P>
<P>
   William Shumann, a spokesman for the FAA, said the Washington
area was hit hardest, because nearly all flights from the region's
three airports are handled by the Washington center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were in New York and going to Boston, you should not
have had a problem,'' Shumann said. ``If you were in New York and
going to Atlanta, or going from Boston to Miami, you would have had
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of traffic in and out of New York goes through
the Washington center, he said, adding that the FAA would not know
until Friday how many planes were delayed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Computer equipment in the center is old and chronically
trouble-prone, although some of the mainframe computers were
replaced last year with newer models because the old ones were not
updated for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the system is still prone to breakdown. On Monday night, the
same type of computer in another air route traffic control center,
the Boston center, in Nashua, N.H., broke down, delaying scores of
planes in New England and New York.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger delayed Thursday, Rep. Ed Pease, R-Indi., said he
boarded a 9:25 a.m. flight on US Airways from Washington National
Airport to Indianapolis and then sat on a taxiway until a little
after 11. Then the plane returned to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   It eventually became obvious that something major was wrong,
Pease said, because of the number of planes on the ground. ``I've
never seen that many planes on the runway at National,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pease, who was supposed to address a group of employees at
Cinergy, the electric utility based in his district just outside
Indianapolis, eventually went back to his office on Capitol Hill
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do better,'' said Pease, who added that Congress
should finish work on the FAA's budget for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is operating on a budget extension, partly because of
a dispute over whether it should have easier access to the money in
the Aviation Trust Fund, which comes from taxes on tickets and
other aviation expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But money is only one reason the air traffic control system is
antiquated. FAA officials acknowledge that part of the problem is
the agency's limited ability to manage big software projects.
</P>
<P>
   At US Airways, a spokesman, Richard Weintraub, said that about
100 flights had been delayed or canceled. The delays averaged 90
minutes, Weintraub said.
</P>
<P>
   The system the FAA uses to issue flight clearances began running
slow early Thursday morning, he said, ``and finally ground to a
halt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
