<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: EMERGENCY DECLARED
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a collapsing currency and the threat of renewed
strikes and street protests that his government attributes to
groups seeking his ouster, President Jamil Mahuad has declared a
national emergency for the fourth time in less than 18 months in
office. The currency has depreciated by 15 percent against the
dollar this week, leading to fears of higher prices and
unemployment. The decree gives the government special powers to put
troops in the street to monitor protests.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: SOLDIERS INVESTIGATED
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have begun an investigation into complaints by a
human rights group, Provea, that security forces committed abuses
during relief efforts after deadly floods and landslides last
month. The group accuses soldiers of summarily executing thieves
who were looting abandoned homes, beating residents of
storm-damaged neighborhoods, illegally entering homes and
restricting freedom of movement. Minister of Defense Raul Salazar
has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: AIR QUALITY IMPROVES
</P>
<P>
   The air in Mexico City last year was cleaner than at any
previous time in the decade as a result of stricter enforcement of
laws limiting the emission of pollutants by vehicles and factories,
according to a government study. Air pollution forced authorities
to adopt emergency measures like keeping schoolchildren inside
during recess only 5 days last year, compared with 62 days in 1990
and 37 in 1998, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: PAPON IN HOSPITAL Maurice Papon, the highest ranking
Vichy government official to be convicted of crimes against
humanity for collaborating with the Nazis, has been taken to a
hospital with heart problems. Papon, 89, tried to flee the country
in October rather than begin his 10-year jail term. But he was
quickly apprehended and has been held in prison in Paris. Papon's
lawyers have been hoping for a presidential pardon on medical
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: PRESIDENTIAL HEAD START
</P>
<P>
   A former interior minister, Charles Pasqua, has given the race
for the French presidency an early start, throwing his hat into the
ring more than two years in advance of the next elections. Pasqua
broke from President Jacques Chirac's Gaullist party last year to
start his own party. His bid is expected to weaken Chirac by
splitting his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SUSPECTED NAZI LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   A suspected Nazi war criminal left Britain and headed for
Australia, as the British government insisted that the police did
not have enough evidence to arrest him. Home Secretary Jack Straw
recently ordered that Konrad Kalejs, 86, be deported, but Kalejs
left on his own and paid for his own ticket. He is accused of
having led a group responsible for more than 30,000 deaths in
Latvia in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: IRA EXTRADITION REVIEWED
</P>
<P>
   The High Court agreed to review an extradition order sending a
convicted Irish Republican Army killer, Angelo Fusco, 43, to
Northern Ireland, but it ordered him held in prison without bail
until a hearing this month. Fusco was arrested and was being driven
to the border to be turned over to the Ulster police on Tuesday
when the Dublin court intervened. He faces life imprisonment for
shooting a British captain, Herbert Westmacott, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   UZBEKISTAN: SUNDAY ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   Uzbekistan appears certain on Sunday to grant its autocratic
president, Islam Karimov, a second five-year term in elections that
independent observers have already said will be rigged. The
nation's 24 million citizens voted for a pro-Karimov parliament in
December in an election that the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe refused to monitor, saying it was
anti-democratic. The group is also boycotting Sunday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   WEST BANK: 2 ARAFAT CRITICS FREED
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority released from a Jericho jail two
dissidents who signed a petition called ``A Cry from the
Homeland,'' which directly criticized the Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and condemned corruption in the Palestinian Authority. Dr.
Abdel Sattar Qassem, 56, and Ahmad Shaker Doodeen, 63, were freed
after 40 days in detention without charges, the last of the
petition's signers to be released after a swift, harsh crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: VOTE SET FOR MARCH
</P>
<P>
   Dispelling confusion about the date of the next national
elections, President Robert Mugabe announced that the parliamentary
vote would be held in March. It will be the first time that
Mugabe's party, the Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic
Front, will have strong opposition from rival parties. Mugabe and
his party have dominated the country's political life since
independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI: REFUGEES INCREASING
</P>
<P>
   The flow of refugees from fighting in southeast Burundi swelled
to at least 30,000 last month, the United Nations reported. The
number rose especially over the holidays, with nearly 3,000 people
arriving in refugee camps in western Tanzania on New Year's Day. In
November nearly 10,000 refugees reached Tanzania, with another
8,000 arriving in October, all fleeing an upsurge of fighting
between soldiers and rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
