<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TALKS (Shepherdstown, W.Va.) _ President Clinton returns
to the secretive peace talks between Israel and Syria amid reports
that negotiations are not going well between the two longtime
adversaries. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTE (Washington) _ So far in this election campaign, the
gender gap that has aided Democrats in the past is not a political
albatross for Texas Gov. George W. Bush. In a new poll by Emily's
List, which raises campaign cash for pro-choice Democratic women
candidates, Bush ran one percentage point ahead of Vice President
Al Gore among women voters and dead even with former Sen. Bill
Bradley. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Also filed in ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-GORE (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Democratic Presidential
hopeful Bill Bradley turns up the heat on Vice President Al Gore as
Bradley tries to win Iowa in order to maintain a viable race. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE (Portsmouth, N.H.) _ It is the Republicans' turn to
debate in New Hampshire, with the tax plans of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain likely to take center stage.
McCain's lead over Bush is tightening in the first primary state
and the presidential hopefuls are beginning to get scrappier. By
BENNETT ROTH and R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno says it is
unlikely she will reconsider an INS decision to return a Cuban boy
to his father despite a second day of rallies and protests by Cuban
expatriates in Miami.By PATTY REINERT and STEVE LASH. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAN-FRAN-VEGAS (Las Vegas) _ A Las Vegas casino owner plans to
build a $700 million replica of San Francisco on the famous Strip,
making it the latest metropolis being erected in the gaming
capital. Real estate magnate Phil Ruffin has announced plans to
build a casino called the City by the Bay, which is scheduled to
open in about two years. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-TITANS (Nashville, Tenn.) _ The Tennessee Titans may have a
new nickname, new team colors, a new stadium and a new home, but
the former Houston Oilers still can't totally escape their
checkered past. And there will be plenty of reminders of that past
this weekend as the Titans face their old nemesis, the Buffalo
Bills, in their first playoff
</P>
<P>
   game in Tennessee. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Miami) _ The injury-depleted Houston Rockets get
their first look at Miami's brand-new basketball arena tonight as
they take on the Miami Heat in an NBA game. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros sign former New York
Mets star Dwight Gooden to a minor-league contract. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) - President Clinton is already
fretting about what he'll do when he is forced to leave the White
House in a year. We give our presidents virtually unlimited power
and then take it away when their terms are up, putting them out to
pasture with no responsibilities. The Constitution doesn't envision
a role for them. Nor does the public. Clinton will be only 54 when
he departs, but you can bet he won't just evaporate. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
