<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE CHIEF PLEDGES TO RAISE MILITARY HOUSING ALLOWANCES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Wash., Texas)   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said Thursday
that next year's Pentagon budget would include a $160 million
increase in housing allowances for military members who live off
base, as another incentive to encourage them to stay in the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, the military will provide that housing
entirely cost-free, said Cohen, who added that such a policy would
cost $3 billion more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason in the world you should pay more out of
your pocket,'' said Cohen when he announced the increases in an
address to troops at Camp Pendleton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Last year service members living off base were paying an average
of 18.8 percent of their rents from their own pockets. With the
increase in allowances that will be reduced to no more than 15
percent and service members will immediately begin saving $30 to
$50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, those savings will rise anywhere from $110 to
over $250 a month, a senior defense official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we felt at a minimum we had to have if we're
going to maintain the quality force that we have,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the military live off base, a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In his last year as defense secretary, Cohen has made improving
the life style of the military his top priority. He promised
Thursday that next year's budget will also include improvements in
the military's health care program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do our level best to make sure you and your
family have the best we can provide, '' he told the troops at the
Marine base.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's budget, the military received a 4.8 percent pay
increase and improvements in its pension program. Initially
President Clinton recommended a 4.4 percent pay increase but the
Republican-controlled Congress increased it and since then has said
it is responsible for strengthening the military.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Thursday that he expected a similar response to his
housing allowance proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that Congress may decide to do even more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The military is also trying to improve the housing on military
installations across the country. A senior defense official said
Thursday that 200,000 of the 300,000 housing units on those bases
are substandard and in need of repair or replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Military construction crews are working on some of those
problems, but the Defense Department is hoping that private
concerns will eventually take over construction on the bases. Pilot
programs are underway at three bases in Texas, Washington state and
Maryland to put private contractors in charge of all these
improvements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
