u a BC-SCI-MARS-LANDER-NYT &LR;      01-06 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-LANDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS LANDER MAY HAVE FALLEN INTO A DEEP CANYON NEAR LANDING SITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lost $165 million Mars Polar Lander may have fallen into a
canyon nearly a mile deep and five miles wide that yawns across the
Martian landing site, NASA officials said Thursday. But they added
that they could not rule out a long list of other possibilities,
including a simple rough landing, the failure of the descent system
or an explosion just before entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew about this deep valley and this crater right from the
beginning of our site selection,'' Richard Zurek, the scientist in
charge of the lander project at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory,
said in a news conference Thursday. ``We knew this was an area we
didn't want to particularly set down in.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials said the canyon occupied only about 10 percent of
the prospective landing area. As a result, Zurek said, it was ``by
no means conclusive that that's the cause of us not being able to
communicate with the lander.'' Failures of the spacecraft itself,
he said, were just as likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Polar Lander was supposed to touch down on Dec. 3 for a
90-day mission to analyze the planet's atmosphere and search for
frozen water beneath its south pole. No signal has been heard from
the craft since it started its descent that day, after an 11-month
journey, and NASA is still trying to discover what caused its
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Post reported Thursday that members of the Lockheed
Martin team who directed the spacecraft were surprised to learn
that the yawning fissure was inside the landing zone. During the
mission, Lockheed scientists steered the craft under the direction
of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   But Zurek said the existence of the canyon had been no surprise
to anyone at NASA or Lockheed. ``It was an important part of our
site selection,'' he said, ``and we made a plan to nudge us away
from there'' but were unable to do so because the move would have
set the craft on terrain even more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Zurek added that Martian winds might have sent the lander toward
the canyon's hazardous slopes, but said there were no signs that
such winds were blowing on landing day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our assessment is there are surface hazards where
the lander may have set down,'' he said, ``but it's not such a
probability that we think it's a cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The canyon and its steep slopes cover 10 percent of the selected
landing site, a 1,500-square-mile ellipse near Mars' south pole.
That means there was about a 90 percent chance that the lander
touched down outside the danger zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know where it went,'' said Douglas Isbell, a
spokesman at the Washington headquarters of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   NASA continues to search for signs of the lander's parachute,
which in theory should just be visible to satellites orbiting Mars.
Its discovery, Zurek said, could help determine whether the craft
plunged into the canyon or perhaps failed mechanically instead.
</P>
<P>
   The lander disappeared less than three months after its sister
spacecraft, the $125 million Mars COrbiter, was lost when
Lockheed Martin failed to convert critical navigation data from
English to metric units as called for by NASA. Experts say the
orbiter probably burned up in the thin Martian atmosphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
