<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANTASY TRADING GAME EASES WALL STREET BURDEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's say you're bummed about your portfolio taking a beating
during this week's plunge of the Nasdaq market. The last thing you
want is to play a fantasy sports stock-market game.
</P>
<P>
   Aw, c'mon. Give it a shot.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTSDAQ.com (www.sportsdaq.com), a free online sports trading
market based in San Francisco, might take your mind off the real
stock market's losses. SPORTSDAQ.com members trade online
fictitious securities based on a team's performance in the five
major sports leagues for end-of-the-season prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Wall Street Sports _ the popular online game that
features securities based on a player's performance _ SPORTSDAQ.com
focuses on team value as it relates to market psychology. A team's
stock price is a direct reflection of shareholder confidence in its
future performance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Cowboys' value earlier this week was at $6.72,
which was 11th out of the 12 teams (the Detroit Lions were last
with $6.03) in the NFL playoffs. That means SPORTSDAQ.com members
believe the Cowboys have a 6.72 percent chance of winning Super
Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Jacksonville Jaguars are valued at $12.73. If
the Jaguars win, they'll be worth $100 in fantasy currency
(SPORTSDAQ.com members get $100,000 when they sign up) and every
other team has zero value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our market moves strictly on supply and demand,'' said Eric
Dubin, president of Sports Futures Inc., which operates
SPORTSDAQ.com. ``The valuation of a team can go up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   A real trader would consider the 8-8 Cowboys a beaten-down
stock.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTSDAQ.com is apparently not for the average sports fantasy
player _ it's more like a game for day-traders. The game can be as
complex as real stock trading. SPORTSDAQ includes a price spread
(the difference between ask and bid prices) and commissions _ all
built in to make the game more challenging. Players can also
complete market orders, limit orders, buy to cover orders, short
stop loss orders and even sell short.
</P>
<P>
   Dubin and Andrew Hoppin, Sports Futures' chief executive
officer, launched SPORTSDAQ.com in October as an opportunity to tap
into online fantasy sports, which according to analysts, is turning
into a cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTSDAQ.com has grown mostly from word of mouth, said Dubin,
who offers advice on techntocks on Microsoft's site. The
site has advertising and collects e-commerce commissions. Plans are
for SPORTSDAQ.com to include interactive and community features in
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, SPORTSDAQ.com boasted in a news release that its
members had correctly predicted all of the teams that qualified for
the NFL playoffs. The timing of the release wasn't the best for
SPORTSDAQ.com, Dubin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine people are little shell-shocked and trying to stay
away from their computer monitors,'' Dubin said.
</P>
<P>
   BYTES: ESPN.com has scheduled two interesting features for
viewers of Sunday's ESPN2 telecast of the Colorado
Avalanche-Chicago Blackhawks game at 7 p.m. Users will be allowed
to interact with on-air analysts during the telecast, and they'll
also be allowed to chat live with players between periods of the
game. Players will be chosen in a pregame poll on ESPN.com. ...
Florida State defeated Nebraska in the Virtual Bowl Championship
Series on FANSonly (www.fansonly.com/virtual).
nn
</P>
