<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEGAULLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DENIGRATION OF DE GAULLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History matters, and each of history's episodes shapes the
chapters to follow. That is the lesson to be drawn from the release
of secret wartime telegrams in which Winston Churchill, reacting to
pressure from Franklin Roosevelt, suggested to colleagues in the
British Cabinet that they should ``eliminate de Gaulle as a
political force.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians have long known about the pique provoked in Roosevelt
and Churchill by General Charles de Gaulle. The telegrams
declassified this week, however, reveal mistrust and contempt that
go well beyond the common conception of Anglo-American
exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomatic memo to Roosevelt from the US Embassy in London _
a text that was shown to Churchill _ reported that a de Gaulle
speech read like ``pages from Mein Kampf.'' Roosevelt wrote to
Churchill that de Gaulle had a ``messianic complex.'' Churchill
informed his deputy prime minister, Clement Atlee, and Foreign
Secretary Anthony Eden that he agreed with the Americans that de
Gaulle was ``too dictatorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind these intemperate phrases, and the plot to depose de
Gaulle as leader of the Free French, were false and misleading
intelligence reports from American sources and a crude power
struggle. In May 1943, at the time of the telegrams, American
forces had just invaded Algeria, then a French colony, and were
hoping to install General Henri Giraud, a pro-American officer
senior to de Gaulle, as their preferred Free French partner. Giraud
proved to have none of the political acumen that made de Gaulle a
true leader.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Atlee and Eden rebuffed the proposal to remove de
Gaulle. But de Gaulle never forgot the treatment _ which he
regarded as an affront to the nation he wished to incarnate. His
resentment of the Anglo-American effort to subordinate the Free
French to the interests of London and Washington cast a long
shadow. In 1963, when de Gaulle vetoed British membership in the
European Economic Community, and again in 1966, when he withdrew
France from NATO's integrated command structure, he was reenacting
what must have seemed to him a primal drama. French resentment of
the ``Anglo-Saxons'' did not end with the death of de Gaulle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0294 </DOCNO>
