<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFT AWAY FROM HIGH-TECH STOCKS CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors accelerated their shift from
high-technology into less expensive smokestack and consumer stocks
on Thursday as the Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq
market moved in opposite directions for the third time this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite suffered a mid-afternoon swoon and finished
150.41 points, or 3.88 percent, lower at 3,727.13, to bring its
loss since Monday's record close to 9.8 percent. A decline of 10
percent in any stock gauge is widely regarded as a correction.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after normal trading hours, prices of many of the Nasdaq's
high-fliers slumped further when Lucent Technologies, the maker of
telephone equipment, warned that profits and sales will be well
below Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by a 7{-point gain in Minnesota Mining, to 100}, the Dow
ended up by 130.61 points, or 1.17 percent, to 11,253.26. That was
2.1 percent below its Dec. 31 record. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 1.34 points, to 1,403.45.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very pronounced rotation'' into stocks like DuPont,
Caterpillar and Exxon, said Donna Van Vlack, head trader at
Brandywine Asset Management in Wilmington, Del., which invests in
such issues. As for computer-related stocks, she added, ``it seems
everybody is headed for the same exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the swing from high-tech into blue-chip standbys _ some
money also moved into bonds, pushing interest rates down _ analysts
noted that various calendar-related factors were at work and that
the sell-off in technology might prove little more than a normal
pullback after a giant 1999 run-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to ride this horse you have to realize there's
a lot of bucking in this group,'' said Andrew M. Brooks, head of
stock trading at T. Rowe Price in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Among the seasonal cross-currents were investors taking profits
this year instead of last year to defer capital gains taxes and the
usual January inflow of pension and bonus money and reinvested
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said the warning by Lucent, which plunged as low
as 53 after its warning, compared with 69 1/16 at the close and 73
3/16 at its best level of the day, made them nervous ahead of
Friday morning's government report on the nation's job market in
December.
</P>
<P>
   A big jump in jobs or a decline in the unemployment rate,
already at its lowest level in three decades, would add to the
pressure on the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates again. Fed
policymakers, who are to meet the first two days of February, are
already expected to raise the short-term rate target, 5.50 percent
since mid-November, by at least a quarter percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest rate rise is cause for concern,'' said Alex
Meitzner, chairman of Ranson and Associates in Wichita, Kan., which
runs a mutual fund indexed to the Nasdaq 100. But he pointed to
financial history in contending that a correction in technology
stocks from ``not sustainable'' levels would probably be limited to
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several pretty dramatic corrections and it's always
come back,'' Meitzner said of this group. ``It's pretty
resilient.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading remained heavy, with 1.6 billion shares changing hands
on the Nasdaq, the seventh busiest on record, and 1.1 billion on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and Europe set a negative tone for the day, with the main
London index down 1.4 percent, Frankfurt and Paris lower by less
than 1 percent, and Hong Kong and Tokyo down 4.4 percent and 2
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Minnesota Mining among the Dow's biggest gainers were
Procter &AMP; Gamble, which was raised to a strong buy from accumulate
by Prudential Securities, Exxon Mobil and J.P. Morgan, all up more
than 4 points.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast, the three biggest drags were all technology
companies. Intel was down 4~, to 78}, Microsoft 3 13/16 to 110, and
Hewlett-Packard 2 15/16 to 104 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks gained, aided by strong earnings at Lehman
Brothers, which added 2 15/16 to 72~. Goldman Sachs surged 3], to
82\ and Merrill Lynch 2 15/16 to 76]. Citigroup rose 2{, to 54\,
and Bank of America was up 3 15/16, to 50.
</P>
<P>
   Utility stocks gained, though not as much as on Wednesday, as
did drug shares and such sectors as chemicals and railroads. Union
Pacific, Burlington Northern Santa Fe and Kansas City Southern each
advanced more than 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany fell 3\, to 77, despite reporting exceptionally strong
holiday sales, while AnnTaylor Stores fell 6, to 24, after
reporting a slim sales gain that failed to meet some estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
