<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUSE TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some scientists want the computer mouse to read human emotions
and be our friend. Bad idea _ the clicking is annoying enough.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers developing the ``Emotion Mouse'' at IBM, and an
array of other techonological mood sensors in labs around the
country that are exploring the growing field of ``affective
computing,'' send a chill down the low-tech spine.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are way too patronizing now, with their intrusive
spell-checking, grammar corrections, customized sales pitches,
constant offers to craft our memos and letters, and impenetrable
``help'' files.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butt out, chip brain,'' many of us growl into the screen,
pounding the ``delete'' key and often wanting to yank the plug of a
machine that thinks it is smarter than we are _ and is often so
frustratingly correct.
</P>
<P>
   The friendly mouse, coated in copper, wired to pick up
sensations from the skin, is supposed to register this frustration
and turn off the cloying editing functions. The device could also
slow down a program for an operator who appeared to be lost or
repeat prompts to a person whose attention was wandering or,
perhaps, trigger a disk to play peppy music for someone who was
falling asleep.
</P>
<P>
   It is supposed to be a boon to mankind, but like so many gifts
from the lab, this mouse could bite, nibbling away the already
crumbling privacy of the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want on-line lecturers to know that we're bored? Do
we want e-commerce advertisers measuring which of their products
quicken the pulse? Do we want the boss tracking exactly how much we
hate doing an assignment?
</P>
<P>
   It would be a short walk from this kind of Big Brother
monitoring to worse _ messages on the screen, or voices, perhaps
accompanied with a little electric shock, telling a person to ``get
with the program or log off.'' Someday the thing might even shout,
``And stop calling me `chip brain!' '' The possibilities are
hideous, and scientists should let bad enough alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
