<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-CEDARS07-COX     01-06 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CEDARS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love story can't warm up `Snow'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're supposed to be moved by the star-crossed, cross-cultural
love affair at the heart of ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' But it's a
romance as chilly and indifferent as the flakes blanketing its
upstate Washington location.
</P>
<P>
   Set shortly after the end of World War II, the movie stars Ethan
Hawke as Ishmael Chambers, a small-town newspaper reporter whose
latest story is the mysterious death of a fisherman (Eric Thal),
discovered tangled in his own net. When Japanese-American Kazuo
Miyamoto (Rick Yune) is arrested for what seems to be murder, it
stirs up the town's collective memories of its wartime mistreatment
of anyone Japanese. For Ishmael, it also stirs up memories of his
youthful affair with Hatsue (Youki Kudoh), now Kazuo's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The movie re-creates the deportation of Japanese-American
citizens to internment camps and shows authorities confiscating
families' firearms and valuable personal property. While this
period remains a blight on our history, ``Snow'' uses the
internment as a simplistic symbol of racism to give itself the
illusion of importance.
</P>
<P>
   Director Scott Hicks (``Shine'') tries to maintain that illusion
by filming the best-selling novel in stylish ways meant to distract
from the plot's thinness. He presents the story as an
impressionistic mosaic, using swift edits that constantly shift
between the snowy present and the idyllic love affair of young
Ishmael and Hatsue (played by Reeve Carney and Anne Suzuki, who
frolic picturesquely through the forest and along the beach).
</P>
<P>
   The film drowns scenes in swelling organ music and chorales that
try to goose up audience emotion. It's fascinating to watch if
you're the sort of movie buff who goes to the multiplex primarily
to see a director flex his muscles and try to jump-start a
flat-lining plot. But those expecting an engrossing story might
tire of ``Snow's'' substitution of style for substance. Filled with
moody images of slate-gray water and snow-silvered trees, the movie
is one of the most visually beautiful in a season full of gorgeous
movies. But dramatically, it's terminal.
</P>
<P>
   That's due in part to Hawke's role, a largely passive character
who spends much of the film's running time dwelling on the past, or
not trying to solve the mystery of the fisherman's death. It
doesn't help that the romance between his and Kudoh's characters is
something we hear about instead of feel.
</P>
<P>
   The fine but underchallenged cast includes Sam Shepard as
Hawke's enlightened father, a newspaper editor; James Cromwell as
the courtroom judge; and Max von Sydow as the defense lawyer whose
big summation speech manages to stir a little passion into the
movie's final act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Falling on Cedars''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ethan Hawke,Youki Kudoh and Max von Sydow. Rated PG-13
for disturbing images, sensuality and brief strong language.
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Pretty but chilly.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar prospects: Could land a nomination for its stunning
cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8718 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MAGNOLIA07-COX     01-06 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MAGNOLIA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Magnolia's' mosaic unfolds as bittersweet symphony
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a movie even more ambitious and muscular than his ``Boogie
Nights,'' writer-director Paul Thomas Anderson presents a sprawling
vision of society as one extended dysfunctional family that might,
just might, have the strength to heal its wounds.
</P>
<P>
   It's about the need to forgive, the difficulty of doing so, the
ways in which parents imprint their children's lives and the
impossibility of leaving the past behind. Unfolding at fever pitch
and studded with small miracles of acting, ``Magnolia'' is
exhilarating and exhausting, the sort of movie you live through as
much as watch.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering about the title, Magnolia is the name of a
street in the San Fernando Valley. It's also a name that applies
metaphorically: This three-hour domestic epic consists of separate,
multiple parts that, like petals, unify at the end to form a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The core of this big blossom is dying television producer Earl
Partridge (Jason Robards Jr.), whose young wife, Linda (Julianne
Moore), is, in his words, ``a little daffy.'' She's overmedicated
but almost out of pills, so, luckily, a nurse named Phil (Philip
Seymour Hoffman) is there to monitor Earl.
</P>
<P>
   It's Phil who tries to contact Earl's estranged, black-sheep
son, Frank Mackey (Tom Cruise), a motivational speaker and huckster
whose self-help program ``Seduce and Destroy'' is an outrageously
blunt rallying cry for men to treat women as sex objects and
nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Percolating through other story lines (there are about nine) are
a good-hearted cop named Kurring (John C. Reilly), who meets
Claudia (Melora Walters). A coked-up waif with a chronic sniffle,
she's a compendium of insecurities and self-hatred, best summed up
by one of the more memorable lines ever heard during a dinner date:
``Now that I've met you, would you object to never seeing me
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a young boy genius named Jeremy (Stanley Spector),
who's getting ready to appear on a live game show, emceed by Jimmy
Gator (Philip Baker Hall), who's also dying of cancer. Finally
there's Donnie Smith (William H. Macy), a former whiz kid now grown
into a sad sack with a crush on a boy bartender. (His is the only
story line that doesn't feel organic to the film; it plays as more
of a quirky footnote than a vital part.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the movie's multiple plots begin, Anderson delivers a
hyper-adrenalized prologue, presenting three unrelated stories that
hinge on bizarre coincidences and chance occurrences. It makes us
anticipate a plot designed like a Rube Goldberg contraption:
something that sets its characters on diverse paths that intersect
unexpectedly for one wild, climactic moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly what happens. The movie is less about
coincidence than it is an exploration of themes, via characters who
are linked in differing ways. The climax doesn't find them all
together, but instead simultaneously dealing with a biblical deluge
that's the movie's most audacious, inexplicable invention. (Hint:
Keep an eye out for references to the book of Exodus.)
</P>
<P>
   In his two previous feature films, Anderson focused on surrogate
father figures: Burt Reynolds as the porn czar of ``Boogie
Nights,'' who takes rookie star Mark Wahlberg into his family, and
Hall playing mentor to the penny-ante gambler of Reilly in ``Hard
Eight.'' With ``Magnolia,'' the focus turns to biological fathers
and their children. It's an examination of bad dads and lost boys
(and sometimes girls). ``What Do Kids Know'' is the name of Hall's
game show, and that title becomes increasingly weighty as the
father-child grievances among all the characters grow clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, a boy says, ``You have to be nicer to me, Dad.''
It's a heartbreaking moment that sums up the movie's major thrust.
In a way, ``Magnolia'' suggests that that's all it takes: something
as simple and as difficult as loving your own, or following the
cop's words, ``We should try to do good.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, ``Magnolia'' offers its actors some astonishing
dramatic arias. Rambling with an incoherence that verges on poetry,
Robards reminds us why he has won two Oscars, playing a man
stranded between reality, memory and dreams as he slides toward
death. Moore, who does beautiful and totally different work in
``The End of the Affair,'' pulls off two breathtaking scenes in a
pharmacy and a lawyer's office, shifting through too many emotions
to count. (It helps that Anderson writes crackling dialogue that's
a mixture of naturalism and verbal steroids.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cruise gives the sort of performance that would have
made the muffled ``Eyes Wide Shut'' worth watching. As a
leather-wearing, greasy-haired wolf, he gradually lets us see how
Frank's sweaty machismo is the shield he uses to hide painful
childhood damage.
</P>
<P>
   With its shifting tempos and themes, ``Magnolia'' plays like a
symphony. It's an idea that Anderson pumps up by using Aimee Mann's
songs as a unifying musical undercurrent, culminating in a song
that's shared by all the characters. It's a shivery, beautiful
vision of connectedness that is only one of two climaxes that let
Anderson flirt with the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's sustaining a prolonged, single-take tracking shot
through a TV studio, hiking the musical soundtrack to make it
intentionally difficult to catch dialogue or filming an ambulance
wreck as a moment of weird beauty, Anderson never stops finessing.
He's like Robert Altman, buzzed on ecstasy. The first 15 minutes of
the movie alone _ a breathless, lightning-edit montage that
introduces us to all the major characters _ are some of the most
dazzling, pulse-raising frames of celluloid from all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Like two of his characters, Anderson is something of a whiz kid
himself. His look-what-I-can-do virtuosity might wear some viewers
down, especially because the fragmented plot and multiple
characters already take of concentration. But your endurance
pays off. Unlike the flashy but hollow ``Boogie Nights'' or the
studied tough-guy attitude of ``Hard Eight,'' ``Magnolia'' grounds
its stylistic pyrotechnics with genuine emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the movie sometimes overreaches. Occasionally it's a mess,
but it's a glorious mess that shows Anderson becoming more
ambitious and assured with each project. And he just turned 30 on
New Year's Day. If that's not good news for the future of movies in
the new century, I don't know what is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jason Robards Jr., Julianne Moore, William H. Macy, Tom
Cruise and John C. Reilly. Written and directed by Paul Thomas
Anderson. Rated R for strong language, drug use, sexuality and some
violence.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 59 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A mesmerizing tapestry about broken families, love
and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar prospects: Tom Cruise will probably get a best supporting
actor nod. Other possibilities include best picture, director (Paul
Thomas Anderson), supporting actress (Julianne Moore), screenplay,
song, cinematography and editing.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
