<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pursuing dream pays off for Alabama lawyer
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, Birmingham attorney Mike Stewart quit a secure
job as general counsel to a health care company to write a novel.
He was chasing a dream, but he soon realized he had stepped off a
professional cliff into the gaping chasm of life as an unemployed
novelist.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife thought I was crazy,'' said Stewart, 44. ``She's an
accountant and a lawyer, and to her this wasn't logical. But she
did support me.''
</P>
<P>
   The support paid off. After months of writing 12 hours a day,
Stewart completed ``Sins of the Brother'' (Putnam, $23.95), found a
literary agent and signed a lucrative publishing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Stewart is a lawyer and his main character is a lawyer,
comparisons to John Grisham are inevitable. Stewart's flattered,
but he doesn't consider his novel a legal thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ``My protagonist is a young lawyer named Tom McInnes, but he's
definitely not an idealistic, Grisham-type lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sins of the Brother,'' McInnes travels to Coopers Bend, a
fictional town on the Alabama River, to attend his younger
brother's funeral. He soon discovers that what appeared to be an
accidental drowning was really coldblooded murder. When McInnes
discovers that no one in town seems particularly interested in what
happened to his brother, he begins to delve into the murder and
finds his own life in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Like his protagonist, Stewart grew up in a small sawmill town on
the Alabama River. As a teenager, he worked for his father's
forestry company cutting weeds and underbrush with a sling blade
and machete. Later, while attending Auburn University, he worked
summers as a farmhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to be a writer since I was 13,'' Stewart said,
``but I went to law school because I needed a more reasonable way
to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   The father of two girls, Stewart coaches his older daughter's
softball team and spends his mornings writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted when I started, and what I still want, is a long
career as a mystery writer,'' says Stewart, whose second novel,
``Dog Island,'' will be published this fall.
</P>
<P>
   As for achieving the kind of success Grisham has had, he simply
laughed. ``I might as well dream about being crowned the King of
Siam. The odds are about the same.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Love and crime: Adam Dalgliesh fans may be pleased _ or maybe
not so pleased _ to learn that British author P.D. James has
romance in mind for her fictional detective.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent BBC radio interview, James revealed her plans to
find a mate for the lonely widower in her next novel. ``I think it
is time that man got moving on the emotional front,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dalgliesh, who was introduced to readers in the 1954 novel
``Cover Her Face,'' lost his wife in childbirth. The baby also
died. ``That was a bit cowardly in a way,'' James told London's
Guardian. ``But I felt that in the detective novel, you are coping
with one great absolute, which is death. I am not sure that at the
same time you can cope with another great absolute, which is
love.''
</P>
<P>
   At 80, James is not sure how many more novels she will write,
but she promises not to follow in the footsteps of fellow novelist
Colin Dexter, who killed his detective Chief Inspector Morse last
year. Such an act, James said, would seem like ``vicarious
suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Holiday sales: The Christmas season's big books, according to
Publishers Weekly, were the Harry Potter novels and anything that
had ``century'' or ``chicken soup'' in the title. Health
Communications reported that the 10 ``Chicken Soup'' titles sold
more than 500,000 copies each in 1999. Other top sellers were
``Life: Our Century in Pictures,'' ``The Century'' and ``ESPN
Sports Century.''
</P>
<P>
   As for worldwide sales, Publishing Trends newsletter reported
that John Grisham's ``The Testament'' led the pack in 34 countries,
followed by Isabel Allende's ``Daughter of Fortune,'' John Irving's
``A Widow for One Year,'' Arthur Golden's ``Memoirs of a Geisha''
and Thomas Harris' ``Hannibal.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
