<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8723 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SHOSTAKOVICH09-     01-06 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SHOSTAKOVICH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Composer gets new `Life,' but Shostakovich remains a puzzle
despite exhaustive research
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world is ready for a good biography of Dmitri Shostakovich,
the Soviet composer whose long love-hate relationship with his
government produced some of the most profound and troubled music of
this century.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a highly suspect ``autobiography'' called
``Testimony'' (1994), written with, or perhaps by, Solomon Volkov.
Purporting to be extracts from the composer's secret diaries,
``Testimony'' painted a murky picture of a closet dissident who
wrote ``music of the people'' to please the Communist Party and
music of depth and complexity to please himself.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Testimony'' raised more questions than it answered. The
public actions of the composer's later life don't support the
book's image of a heroic nonconformist. No one has yet explained
why Shostakovich signed an open letter critical of Andrei Sakharov
in 1973 or broke with his longtime friend Mstislav Rostropovich
when Rostropovich stood up for Alexander Solzhenitsyn. Why, as the
eminence grise of Soviet music, he felt he had to be a government
mouthpiece, when as a young composer he had refused to be that, is
still a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the hype when it appeared in the West, ``Testimony''
was not the biography we'd been waiting for. Nor was Elizabeth
Wilson's ``Shostakovich: A Life Remembered'' (1994), a valuable
collection of interviews with friends, family and colleagues but
more of a source book than a biography.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel E. Fay's biography isn't the answer to our prayers
either. A writer who has studied Russian and Soviet music since
1971, she has put an exhaustive amount of research into this life
of Shostakovich but to very little effect.
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich is a fascinating figure. His life (1906-75) and
career parallel the rise and fall of Soviet Communism: the great
hope of the Russian people in its youth, their dark oppressor in
its mature strength, the haggard remembrance of things past as the
system collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The October Revolution took place the year before Shostakovich
was born, and he grew up believing in the ideals of the socialist
state, which rewarded him with prizes, commissions and acclaim for
the first three decades of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1936, when the composer was 29, Joseph Stalin attended
a performance of Shostakovich's most ambitious work, the opera
``Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District.'' Two days later, an
editorial called ``Muddle Instead of Music'' appeared in Pravda,
holding up this dark and dissonant opera as an example of
``formalism'' in music. The golden days were over.
</P>
<P>
   Formalism was a code word for art so allied to its own formal
values that it baffled the common worker (according to the party).
Dissonance, abstraction, complexity, anything that called attention
to the music instead of its message was considered evil. In so many
words, the party required that music be uplifting and noble, in
keeping with the progressive spirit of a workers' state. For the
next 30 years, ``socialist realism'' was the official language of
Soviet art. The result was a spate of ``tractor ballets,'' in which
boy encountered girl on a collective farm and set off into the
sunrise to meet the goals of the latest Five-Year Plan. Such art
survives today only as historical kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Shostakovich was lucky. Many died for their artistic
integrity during the Stalinist purges. Shostakovich and others like
him were merely cautioned, though the cautionary notice often came
with a prohibition on performance.
</P>
<P>
   So Shostakovich suppressed his Symphony No. 4 and kept his
compositional skills honed by writing chamber music ``for the
drawer.'' Despite many promises, he never wrote another opera, so
badly had the ``Lady Macbeth'' episode frightened him.
</P>
<P>
   Fay covers all of this thoroughly, if prosaically, but with
precious little musical or political insight. Her research is of
the kind that announces a letter hitherto dated March 14 was
actually written three days earlier, though neither the original
nor the revised date matters a whit in fixing a musical or
biographical detail.
</P>
<P>
   But some of that detail is wonderful. Early on, she describes
the perpetual food shortages of post-revolutionary Russia and notes
that Shostakovich's mother sent her frail son away for a few weeks
to the country, ``the better to feed him.'' It's easy to understand
his lifelong health problems in light of such stories.
</P>
<P>
   There are fascinating glimpses of important but now neglected
figures, such as the composers Vissarion Shebalin and Nikolai
Myaskovsky, a tireless symphonist; the novelist Mikhail Sholokhov
(``And Quiet Flows the Don'') and the painter Egon Petri. And there
are snippets of insight: Shostakovich's admiration for Stravinsky
(whose music was banned by the party in 1935) dates back to his
playing one of the four piano parts in the Russian premiere of the
ballet ``Les Noces'' in 1926.
</P>
<P>
   If only Fay wrote more perceptively about the music! The cello
sonata ``scarcely hints at the turmoil in his personal life.'' (His
depressed emotional state could not be more clear in its dark
lineaments.) Shostakovich was brave enough to use Jewish folk
material even at the height of the anti-Semitic Stalinist purges,
yet Fay somehow misses a most obvious example: the Piano Trio, Op.
67, whose Jewish colors have made it the signature work of the
Jerusalem Trio. She ignores the ``war machine'' scherzo of the
Symphony No. 8, an outright challenge to the official Soviet view
of World War II as the ``Great Patriotic War,'' which kept the
Russian people fighting through siege and starvation past all human
levels of endurance. Here, in fact, is some proof of his dissident
underside.
</P>
<P>
   At least a third of the biography is notes, bibliography, a
glossary of names, a list of works and the index. A composer as
significant and prolific as Shostakovich, backed up by so much
research in primary source material, deserves more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich: A Life. By Laurel E. Fay. Oxford University Press.
$35. 458 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not the biography we've been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes about classical music, dance and theater for
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
