<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8724 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SKUBE09-COX     01-06 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Open a book: Other worlds await discovery
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``On top of everything, the cancer wing was Number 13.''
</P>
<P>
   An engaging enough opening sentence for a novel, portending
uncertainty and crisis. But more of that shortly.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, I only wonder whether it would engage Oprah. Or
Alice McGee. What about Dianne Hudson?
</P>
<P>
   No one, especially in publishing, needs to be told who Oprah is.
But who are Alice McGee and Dianne Hudson? It happens they are
producers of ``The Oprah Winfrey Show,'' and people in publishing
know very well who they are.
</P>
<P>
   It was McGee and Hudson, D.T. Max learned, who proposed the idea
of an Oprah Winfrey book club _ an idea Winfrey did not immediately
embrace but one the publishing industry has taken to like catnip.
And why not? In the three years the program has aired, it has been
responsible for 28 consecutive best sellers, sold more than 20
million books and, Max reports in The New York Times Magazine,
``earned publishers $175 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers compel disbelief, but also a certain unease.
Americans read, they almost say, what Oprah wants them to read.
Nonetheless, when the National Book Foundation, sponsor of the
National Book Awards, gave Oprah its 50th anniversary medal last
November, it was both an acknowledgment of gratitude and a
recognition of her marketing power. And implicit in the latter was
this: Oprah's Book Club has to a considerable degree set the tone
for the kind of fiction publishers want.
</P>
<P>
   And what kind is that? This was the question Max set out to
answer _ how a book comes to be blessed with Oprah's imprimatur.
</P>
<P>
   In the two months he waited for an interview with Oprah, Max had
time to spend with the 28 books she has chosen for the show. ``My
aim,'' he writes, ``was to read as naturally as possible, giving
myself the same out Winfrey gives herself: if a book doesn't grab
her in 50 pages, she moves on.''
</P>
<P>
   When the interview finally came, Max was ushered into Oprah's
office, where she sat in an easy chair with two cocker spaniels
nearby. Also nearby, in fold-out chairs, were Alice McGee and
Dianne Hudson. After a few minutes of introductory chit-chat
Winfrey asked Max which books he had liked. He mentioned ``I Know
This Much Is True'' by Wally Lamb, ``A Lesson Before Dying'' by
Ernest Gaines, and was about to mention novels by Toni Morrison,
Kaye Gibbons and Jane Hamilton when he was cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're gravitating to the guys,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Classic,'' said McGee. ``Two male characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's invisible gatekeepers had sized him up. ``I was about
to say I didn't see much connection between myself and the
condemned prisoner in Gaines' novel,'' Max writes, ``when Winfrey
interjected: `Reading is like everything else. You're drawn to
people who are like yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   And there, in a Solomonic nutshell, is the secret:
Self-discovery, self-realization, self-validation. And the self is
usually _ 22 books out of 28 _ a woman. ``In eight novels,'' Max
writes, ``young women are abused, raped or murdered. A dozen men
commit adultery or act abusively toward their families. Women
nurture, men threaten.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could dislike Oprah, but consider that premise: We read
about people like ourselves. If that's the case, there's no point
in wasting time with Dickens, Garcia Marquez, Flannery O'Connor,
Anne Tyler or so many other novelists whose stories reveal worlds
quite unlike our own _ stories that nonetheless deepen our
understanding of life. We read novels for all kinds of reasons, but
this must be the first time in history that self-reflection trumps
all others.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of everything, the cancer wing was Number 13.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first sentence in Alexander Solzhenitsyn's novel
``Cancer Ward,'' a portrayal of a collection of people in a
provincial Soviet hospital in the 1950s. Solzhenitsyn himself had
been a cancer patient, after eight years in a labor camp, but the
novel clearly is not about childhood wounds or a dysfunctional
family. It is not even about any one character in particular _ a
large risk to undertake in a novel _ but rather an entire people
and the ideas that control them.
</P>
<P>
   Probably it is not the sort of thing Oprah would like _ or her
producers either. In a Russian novel there are all those
patronymics and diminutives to keep up with, and we tend not to see
much of ourselves. Not on the surface anyway. It reveals worlds
different from ours, and this is the point.
</P>
<P>
   So on the night before the night before Christmas I lay in bed
with a thermometer jammed in my mouth, in no need to be checked
into Wing 13 but one sick puppy just the same. A few weeks earlier
I had picked up a Noonday paperback edition of ``Cancer Ward.'' It
was one of those novels I had always meant to read, and now I
would. The first 50 pages flew by _ it met my test even without the
mirror of self-reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pavel Nikolayevich Rusanov,'' Solzhenitsyn writes, ``had never
been and could never be a superstitious person, but his heart sank
when they wrote `Wing 13' on his admission card.'' Nothing of me in
that. But here was a novel that did what great fiction should do.
It transported me elsewhere, and invited me to reflect upon a world
larger than my own.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
