r t BC-GREETING09-COX     01-06 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREETING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A photo journal from Whistler, Cananda
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 09.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner Photos by David Tulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHISTLER, CANADA _ Intent on ``getting lost in a mountain of
powder,'' staff photographer David Tulis journeyed recently to
Whistler-Blackcomb in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could the ski magazines be right when they proclaimed Whistler
as the No. 1 resort in North America? And is bigger better?''
wondered Tulis, an avid skier.
</P>
<P>
   Yes and yes, he decided.
</P>
<P>
   He liked the myriad runs at neighboring Whistler and Blackcomb
mountains and the European-style village nestled between them
(especially the pubs). He went dog sledding, snowmobiling,
snowshoeing and some other ``ings.''
</P>
<P>
   But what pleased him even more than the deep sports massage he
got after a long day swooshing the slopes was the snow _ some of
the 30 feet that blankets here annually.
</P>
<P>
   His images capture the beauty, pleasure _ and even warmth _ of a
mountain of white.
</P>
<P>
   A LONE SKIER negotiates a black-diamond area atop Whistler,
adjacent to the Burnt Stew Trail beginner run. Rookies and veterans
can get a high-mountain experience from the same lift.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-STYLE PUBS, New Age-y restaurants and danceterias
provide backdrops for skiers to unwind at Whistler Village. Here,
locals get in on the act at Tapley's Pub.
</P>
<P>
   ``IF YOU CAN WALK you can snowshoe,'' claims the sign at Outdoor
Adventures. For about $30, visitors can take a snowshoe trek from
the mid-mountain gondola into a wonderland of ancient cedars and
whisky-jacks(Canadian jays), with stops for hot apple cider.
</P>
<P>
   A THOUSAND-YEAR-OLD CEDAR is in the gaze of Rob Drynan of Cougar
Mountain at Whistler outfitters. The tree, in the Cougar Mountain
Wilderness Area five miles north of Whistler Village, is accessible
only via snowmobile, snowshoes or cross-country skis.
</P>
<P>
   THE HARDEST-WORKING hounds in the sled business, Alaskan racing
huskies, charge ahead along the Soo River bank. Cougar Mountain at
Whistler outfitters offer the two-hour, back-country tour for about
$80.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
