<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-PAPOWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPOWS EXITS LOTUS, LEAVING MANY QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chief executive Jeff Papows resigned Thursday from Lotus
Development Corp., after a controversial year during which he faced
allegations he had falsified his resume and sexual harassment
charges filed against the Cambridge software division of IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Papows oversaw an era of rising sales and employment at Lotus,
whose Notes email program became vastly more popular with the
growth of the Internet in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But Papows also leaves amid many unanswered questions from
Lotus' business partners about the management of the company once
known for its progressive workplace culture.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Al Zollar, also represents the first time IBM
has installed one of its own executives to head Lotus since it
bought the firm in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Papows said it was his decision to leave, and that IBM never
raised concerns regarding the various controversies, which IBM
backs up. ``It was a personal decision he made himself, and I'm
sorry he resigned,'' said John Thompson, head of IBM's software
division.
</P>
<P>
   Papows said he plans to step down Feb. 1 and begin a job search
he hopes will land him as head of an independent company again.
``We're at a point where the performance of the company (Lotus)
allows me to make a decision to leave with no lack of confidence
about where the company is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus was once the world's largest software company, but it sold
itself to IBM in 1995 after it failed to best Microsoft Corp. in
the market for word-processing and spreadsheet software.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the company had about 5,600 employees; it now has
nearly 8,500, of which about 3,000 are in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Papows joined Lotus in 1992 and was named to head the company in
1996 after the departure of former chief executive Jim Manzi and
another officer.
</P>
<P>
   IBM doesn't disclose Lotus' exact sales and revenues, though
financial analysts are satisfied with its performance in
competition with Microsoft Corp.'s communications programs.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rasmus, analyst at Cambridge-based Giga Information
Group, credited Papows with finding ways to capitalize on his
company's relationship with IBM. These included adapting Notes for
IBM's corporate-service division and creating a mainframe version
of the program, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Papows became a magnet for controversy following a series of
allegation that began last spring. First, a story in the Wall
Street Journal cast doubts on details Papows was said to have
provided about his military experience and educational background.
</P>
<P>
   Papows has declined to discuss the story's claims in detail,
except to say it included ``false allegations.'' Thursday, IBM's
Thompson concurred. The story ``never affected his relationship
with me,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Next were a set of discrimination complaints brought by several
women who worked at Lotus, one of which included detailed
allegations against Papows. Among other things, a former executive
named Arlene Greene alleged that she and other women were
discriminated against by an assistant to Papows with whom he had a
``long-term intimate relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene's complaint remains pending before the Cambridge (Mass.)
Human Rights Commission, said Quoc Tran, the agency's director, who
said rules bar him from discussing it.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus has denied Greene's charges, though it declines to discuss
them in detail or to say whether it has made any formal response to
the filing.
</P>
<P>
   The suits raised eyebrows because Lotus had long been known for
its forward-looking human-resources policies, including being among
the first Massachusetts companies to offer benefits to employees'
domestic partners. Now, some customers and business partners say
they had hoped to hear more specifics from Lotus.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a small company, you hate to see the big guys trying to get
away with this stuff. You don't want to be associated with a
company that does these things,'' said Mike MacEwen, president of
Beacon Interactive Systems LLC, which uses Lotus software to create
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   By declining to discuss the specifics of the allegations by
Greene and others, he said, IBM ``communicated that there was
something to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's resignation has prompted much talk among Lotus'
alumni community, many of whom are now scattered among other
high-tech firms in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Many expressed concern that by installing an IBM executive to
run the company, IBM was signalling it would exercise more
influence over Lotus, a signal made stronger with the approach of
the big Lotusphere user conference in Orlando later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the end of any semblance of independence for Lotus,''
said Russ Campanello, a former human-resources director at the
company who now holds the same post at drugmaker Genzyme Corp.
``It's now firmly in IBM's control.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Thompson said Zollar's ascension doesn't mean Lotus will
lose more of its independence. ``The Lotus brand is very important
and they will continue to have a strong marketing thrust,'' he
said. ``Lotus has the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Zollar comes to Lotus after 23 years with IBM, most recently as
head of a network computing software group in Westchester County,
N.Y. In a telephone interview Thursday, Zollar said he plans to
take over Papows' role in stages. Zollar will also replace Papows
on Lotus' 12-member operating committee, which otherwise won't
change.
</P>
<P>
   Zollar said he wasn't familiar with Lotus' corporate culture and
seemed to downplay its significance. ``I believe that culture has a
lot to do with winning, and Lotus has been a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was too soon to discuss specific directions for Lotus
or how they might relate to other parts of IBM. ``I'm new here and
I'm still learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
