<SLUG> BC-STYLE-PEETE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WB sitcom star trades minis for more lengthy appeal
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally, phone interviews with celebrities are real snorers. A
recent phoner with Holly Robinson Peete, though, was more of an
eye-opener; a closer glimpse into the 35-year-old
mother-actress-NFL player's wife's life than one would expect.
</P>
<P>
   She was calling from ``somewhere in Virginia,'' where her
husband, Rodney (the Washington Redskins' backup quarterback),
lives during the season. She'd brought their 28-month-old twins
(Rodney Jr. and Ryan) with her from the family home in Los Angeles.
She tried _ in vain _ to get the twins to entertain themselves and
Daddy to quit interrupting her long enough for her to chat up the
two galas that'll bring her to Atlanta twice this month: TBS' 2000
Trumpet Awards on Monday night at the Omni Hotel, and the
``Gridiron Glamour'' celebrity fashion show Jan. 29 at the Fox
Theatre's Egyptian Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, Holly, do you have a hard time finding clothes for events
like these?
</P>
<P>
   A: Holly's wearing the blue, backless number (below) that
Brazil's Fause Hatten made for her to wear to the Trumpets. Other
designers who provide her with clothes include Giorgio Armani,
Germany's All About Eve and Pamela Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   I've got a nice little dossier of designers who provide me with
things. ... If I show up in New York for something at the last
minute, Pamela always finds something for me to wear in her closet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you get to keep the clothes from your TVsitcom (``For
Your Love'') wardrobe?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't get to keep those, (but) every now and then there's
something my character wears that I really wouldn't wear in real
life anyway. They want to put me in all these minis. I used to wear
minis and show a lot of leg, but I don't do that as much anymore
... I think long skirts are sexier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw you stripped down to your panties a few weeks ago in
that BET movie, ``After All''; how, after having twins, have you
stayed so trim?
</P>
<P>
   A: Holly's exercise regimen includes ``power yoga'' and
flexibility training.
</P>
<P>
   Really, I'm so busy and spread so thin and on the go so much
that I must just be burning calories naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The ``After All'' film crew implored her to wear a thong during
the sex scenes, but ``that was all they were getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every woman's style evolves; how has yours?
</P>
<P>
   A: I definitely go for the longer skirts now. I like the
covered-up look that shows the shape of your body without showing
too much skin ... the sheer stuff and the minis? I'm so past that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the main thing you keep in mind when dressing for
special events?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you go to a big event, you want to know you'll be the
only one wearing that dress. That way they can't put you in some
magazine like InStyle next to somebody else wearing the same thing
and looking better than you.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Trumpet Awards are at 6 p.m. Monday at the Omni Hotel
and will be broadcast at 8 p.m. Feb. 26 on TBS. The ``Gridiron
Glamour'' fashion show is 11 a.m. Jan. 29 at the Fox's Egyptian
Ballroom. Confirmed celebrity models include Peete, Falcons
quarterback Chris Chandler, Star Jones of ``The View,'' supermodel
Niki Taylor and Pat O'Brien of ``Access Hollywood.'' Tickets
($3,750 and $7,500) are sold by the table, with proceeds benefiting
breast cancer charities. For more info, call 404-605-7181.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
