u a BC-TEACHER-INCENTIVES-2T     01-06 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-INCENTIVES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES AND CITIES OFFER VARIETY OF INCENTIVES IN EFFORT TO RECRUIT
TEACHERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Fla., Ga., Miss., Mass.)   (sw) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wednesday, only hours after Gov. George Pataki asked
lawmakers to subsidize tuition for college students who commit to
teach in a New York public school, Gov. Gray Davis of California
addressed the legislature in Sacramento with what, in effect,
amounted to a more lucrative counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   Davis proposed that candidates who agree to teach in
low-performing schools be given $10,000 home-purchase loans,
$30,000 bonuses for attaining advanced certification and $11,000 to
repay college loans.
</P>
<P>
   But even before such incentives can be proffered, the two states
_ neither of which apparently had any idea what the other was
planning _ already face heavy competition across the country in
their attempts to woo prospective teachers and to keep good ones
from fleeing to other states or professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bidding war,'' said Richard Mills, the New York state
education commissioner. ``And you can't recruit with rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, as the nation began to feel the effects of a
virtually unprecedented wave of teacher retirements, the city of
Baltimore offered badly-needed special education teachers starting
salaries equivalent to those of teachers with four years'
experience, as well as reduced-rate mortgages and reimbursement of
moving expenses. During the same period, El Paso, Texas, lured new
math teachers with $2,000 signing bonuses, which it was forced to
do after Dallas began a similar effort.
</P>
<P>
   Such offers have multiplied and intensified in recent months: at
least 20 states _ including Florida, Georgia, Mississippi and
Massachusetts _ have begun to pay bonuses of up to $6,000 a year,
sometimes for several years, to teachers who pass a new, rigorous
national certification test.
</P>
<P>
   New York has traditionally had difficulty keeping pace. The
state is among several that produce thousands of new teachers a
year who choose, often for reasons of quality of academic life or
salary, to teach outside the state's borders. Of the 21,000
students who graduated with teaching certificates from colleges and
universities in New York last year, fewer than 7,000 took teaching
jobs in the state, according to Carl Hayden, the chancellor of the
state's Board of Regents. This outflow is happening at a time when
New York City alone is seeking to replace nearly 10,000 teachers
who have temporary licenses
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are driving the proposals by New York,
California and other states.
</P>
<P>
   With tens of thousands of teachers, many of them born in the
first years of the baby boom, becoming eligible for retirement, the
nation must recruit and hire two million new teachers in less than
a decade. There is also a national effort, much of its subsidized
by the federal government, to reduce class sizes, particularly in
burgeoning urban school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the demand for highly skilled teachers has, arguably,
never een greater: new high-stakes tests often link a teacher's
job status to student performance, and new state standards, written
or in place in every state but Iowa, seek to outline what teachers
should be teaching, and when.
</P>
<P>
   The need for good teachers has also been affected by the
persistence of flush times, making education more of a public
concern than the economy is. Voters have told pollsters, for
example, that improving education is among their greatest
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   And the growth in technology jobs and other employment tied to
the Internet has further sapped the ranks of potential science
teachers, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Mills and Hayden said that women, once the backbone of
the nation's teaching force, now can seek out opportunities in more
lucrative fields once closed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the perks that states are offering teachers, few
politicians have been willing to take the far more costly step of
increasing teachers' salaries, permanently and across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all good things,'' said Sandra Feldman, a former New
York City elementary school teacher who is president of the
American Federation of Teachers, the nation's second-largest
teachers' union. ``But ultimately the salaries will have to be
raised. You are talking about a need for 250,000 teachers a year
for the next 10 years. You are talking about a full-employment
economy where knowledge workers are in great demands. It's going to
take a significant increase in base salaries to attract the
educated people we need to become teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to figures provided by the union, the average
beginning teacher's salary nationally, at the outset of the 1998
school year, was $25,735. This compared to $42,862 for beginning
engineers, $40,920 for new computer scientists, and $33,702 for
accountants. The gap between teachers and those other professions
only widens with each year of service.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few officials who has stepped forward to advocate
boosting teachers' base pay is Vice President Al Gore who, if
elected president, said he would propose federally-financed salary
increases of up to $10,000 for veteran teachers willing to serve in
the nation's poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his sixth annual address to the New York state Legislature,
Pataki proposed an annual tuition subsidy of $3,400 a year _ enough
to cover full tuition at a state university, and to reduce much
larger fees at private schools _ to those college students who
commit to teach for at least four years in New York public schools
with teacher shortages. Most, presumably, would be placed in New
York City, though few details have been worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration estimated that the proposal would cost
the state about $25 million a year, and attract perhaps 50,000 new
teachers over the next 10 years. New York City is expected to lose
more than half that number, most to retirement, over that period.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, also said the state should pay for more
than 9,000 uncertified teachers across the state to take the
courses they need to become licensed teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The sweetners by Davis of California, a Democrat, would be even
more generous.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers would be eligible for $10,000 home loans that would be
forgiven after they had taught in the state's public schools for
five years. Those who agree to teach in schools ranked among the
lowest 50 percent in the state would also have $11,000 in college
loans forgiven if they teach in those schools for five years.
</P>
<P>
   And $30,000 bonuses would be awarded to teachers who work in
low-performing schools and who take the courses and tests required
to be certified by the National Board for Professional Teaching
Standards, a non-profit organ seeking to raise standards for
good teachers to the same level across the country. The governor
did not specify the cost of those proposals, but said he hoped to
devote a significant portion of an expected $3 billion budget
surplus to education.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our youth, let me say, there is no higher calling, no
greater public service, no contribution more valued than to join
the frontlines of the future in the classroom,'' Davis said. ``This
is our generation's call to arms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
