<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TELLURIDE09-COX     01-06 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELLURIDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A rich vein of natural beauty runs through upscale locale
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELLURIDE, Colo. _ Looking at the Ah Haa School for the Arts, a
sunny yellow clapboard building, you'd never guess it has a tawdry
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the Silver Belle, the most popular of the two dozen
bordellos on the shady side of Telluride,'' notes Ashley Boling, a
local thespian and part-time historian who conducts walking tours
here.
</P>
<P>
   Boling's ``shady'' description is literal. Nestled in a valley
between the San Juan Mountains in the southern Rockies, Telluride
gets sun on its north side for most of the day, while its southern
half remains largely in the dark. It was on the shadowy side that
such ``soiled doves'' as Big Billie and Diamond Tooth Leona
entertained the miners who flocked to this once gold-rich canyon
around the turn of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   It also serves as a striking metaphor for the contrast between
the quaint hamlet's roughneck past and polished present. The
floozies and gold rushers are long gone, replaced by Wall Street
refugees and Hollywood types escaping the glare of Tinseltown. The
bordellos are now historic landmarks, the saloons serve up
microbrews and Absolut. The bank where Butch Cassidy pulled off his
first armed robbery in 1889 is now a boutique that sells pricey ski
togs.
</P>
<P>
   As mining dwindled to a trickle in the late 1960s, the ski
industry took over. Slowly, Telluride began to build a reputation
as a cozy, classy alternative to bigger and glitzier resorts such
as Aspen and Vail.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the eight-square-block downtown twinkles with upscale
charm. Skiers and boarders sip lattes at the Steaming Bean Coffee
Co. and cocktails at the New Sheridan Saloon. Tourists leaf through
volumes by Colorado poets at Bookworks and peruse the works of
regional artists at the Elinoff Gallery. Foodies spoon up creme
brulee at La Marmotte and linger over chef Chad Scothorn's
chocolate concoctions at the Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sophisticated crowd here,'' says Bookworks manager
Matthew Kapsner. ``For instance, we'll easily sell out of the most
recent National Book Award winner, whereas I think we have one
Danielle Steel title in stock, and nobody buys it.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from being snooty, though, Telluride seems to take pride in
projecting a tolerant atmosphere. Though not ethnically diverse _
Boling estimates a mere six of the 1,600 residents are
African-American _ the city accommodates an array of classes and
lifestyles. Dreadlocked hippies camp out in the ``bus village'' on
the north side of the valley, while business tycoons and movie
stars, including Oprah Winfrey, Tom Cruise and Daryl Hannah, hide
out in the hills to the west. Ralph Lauren has a 16,000-acre cattle
ranch just outside town _ a source of amusement to local ranchers
because the perimeter fence was built with the crossties on the
outside. It's an invitation for the bovines to push their way
through.
</P>
<P>
   Boling thinks that Telluridians get along because ``they're just
happy to be here. There are so many different ways to appreciate
where we live.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them, a panorew of snowcapped mountains
dotted with aspens, Douglas firs and blue spruce. In the winter,
the frozen cascade of Bridal Veil Falls marks the origin of the San
Miguel River, which ripples through town, flanked by cushy banks of
snow. Off in the distance looms Wilson Peak, at 14,017 feet one of
Colorado's tallest mountains.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty here for the outdoor enthusiast _ snowshoeing
and, of course, skiing in winter; hiking and mountain biking in
summer.
</P>
<P>
   While many ski resorts gear down in warmer months, Telluride
flourishes, hosting a festival virtually every weekend from May
through September. The Bluegrass Festival is the biggest, drawing
an estimated 18,000 people every June. The Telluride Film Festival
is the most prestigious event _ more than 7,000 movie fans and film
industry bigwigs flock here each Labor Day weekend to catch the
latest in cutting-edge cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The town takes pains to maintain its pristine beauty. Residents
aren't allowed to have wood-burning fireplaces because the smoke
creates a haze in the canyon. Businesses must point all outdoor
lighting downward, so stargazers can enjoy an undiluted overhead
view. And you won't find any Burger Kings or Gaps here _ strict
building codes have scared off all but one or two chain retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, beneath it all beats the heart of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still that spirit of helping your neighbor here,''
says Jim Lincoln, owner of the Hotel Columbia, one of Telluride's
many luxurious lodges. ``If someone loses their house in a fire or
gets hurt in an avalanche, strangers will come out to donate food
or a place to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Boling, who 10 years ago quit an academic career on the East
Coast to move here, loves the laid-back, anything-goes atmosphere.
``The town attracts people who are tired of the rat race. Here, you
can leave your door unlocked. You can walk into the bank and
everyone knows your name. If you don't fit in somewhere else, you
can come here and fit right in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Telluride and Mountain Village Visitor Center,
1-888-605-2578, or www. teluride.org. Historical Walking Tours of
Telluride, 970-728-9746.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Telluride is 330 miles southwest of Denver, 67
miles south of Montrose, Colo. Fly United to Denver, then United
Express from Denver to Montrose, for about $500 round trip with a
14-day advance purchase. A 75-minute shuttle bus ride from Montrose
to Telluride is $56 round trip. Telluride Express Shuttle Service,
1-800-800-6228.
</P>
<P>
   Or fly America West to Phoenix, then a Mesa Airlines commuter to
Telluride for about $765 round trip, with a seven-day advance
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hitting the slopes:
</P>
<P>
   To access Telluride's ski area, take the free skylift, or
gondola, from the south side of town to the Mountain Village. Lift
tickets are available at kiosks near the gondola's base station and
in the Mountain Village. Daily rates are $37 adults, $20 children
6-12, $30 seniors 65-69. Over 70 and under 5 ski free. For advance
purchase, call 1-800-801-4832 or visit www.telski.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ski season ends April 9. Ski area is open 8:45 a.m.-4 p.m.
daily.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Group and private lessons: The Telluride Ski &AMP; Snowboard
School offers daily classes for all ability levels. A Full-Day
Adventure package, including lift ticket and lesson, is $99. A
three-day Beginner Adventure package, including lift tickets,
lessons and snowboard or ski rentals, is $235. Private lessons
available for $265-$460. 970-728-7507 or www.telski.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Snowboarding packages: Telluride Slopestyle's $30-a-day
snowboarding package includes boots, board, bindings and wrist
guards. Helmet, fanny pads and kneepads available for $10 a day.
Multiday discounts available. 1-888-743-3321.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ski packages: Paragon Ski &AMP; Sport offers packages for junior,
recreational and advanced skiers, from $15 to $32 a day. Multiday
discounts available. Snowboard packages are $28, including boots
and board. 1-800-903-4525. Other ski and snowboard rental packages
available at Telluride Sports, 970-728-4477.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay: Proudly shunning the big hotel chains,
Telluride boasts many intimate inns and B&AMP;Bs. The Hotel Columbia,
across the street from the gondola station, offers 21 large rooms
with fireplaces. There is a hot tub on the roof and a ski locker
room and boot-drying facility off the lobby. Winter rates range
from $215 for a standard room with no balcony to $360 for a
penthouse suite with kitchen. 1-800-201-9505 or
telluridemm.com/hcolum.html. Other accommodations: The Peaks Resort
&AMP; Golden Door Spa, 1-800-789-2220. The New Sheridan Hotel,
1-800-200-1891. The San Sophia Inn, 1-800-537-4781.
</P>
<P>
   For ski and lodging packages, call Telluride Central
Reservations at 1-888-288-7360.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to eat: Options abound. For upscale fusion fare, try the
Cosmopolitan in the Hotel Columbia, 970-728-1292. For a hearty
Mexican meal and Southwestern ambience, go to Sofio's on Colorado
Street, Telluride's main drag, 970-728-4882. For breakfast, you
can't beat the scrambled eggs on foccaccini at Wildflower Cooking
Company (970-728-8887) or the bagels at Baked in Telluride
(970-728-4775). In the Mountain Village, Pizza Chalet serves up
slices quick and hot (970-728-7499).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tellurideuntain Village Visitor Services,
1-888-288-7360 or www.telluride.org.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
