<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8737 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-SUNDAY-LADN &LR;      01-06 2064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUNDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SALESMAN' GETS THE RESPECT HE DESERVES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Sunday, Jan. 9; today is Sunday thruout; all
times PST. Fact box material below) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the majority of the planet not lucky enough to make it to
New York or Chicago to see Brian Dennehy, Elizabeth Franz and Ron
Eldard in the Tony-winning revival of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a
Salesman,'' Showtime has been thoughtful enough to bring us a
taping of the production. For those who aren't lucky enough to have
Showtime, well, this is where sponging off your friends comes in.
As anyone who's taken a high-school lit class knows, the play
introduces us to Willie Loman, a deluded, down-on-his-luck
salesman, tremulously confronting the final dissipation of both his
career and his dysfunctional family. A traveling salesman in charge
of the New England territory, he's been given over lately to
smashing his car up while on the road and chattering pathetically
with ghosts representing the unfulfilled promise of his past.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the poetry in the language, the wonder of the play is
Miller's accumulation of telling details summing up the life of a
man reeling in the final stages of the gradual process of admitting
defeat. Almost in passing, we learn of the loss of the trees in the
back yard, the garden that no longer grows anything, the mounting
debts and the withering paychecks. Willie Loman's life has been a
series of losses and missteps, of inconveniences and annoyances, of
insults and humiliations _ a life of, above all, flat-out
disrespect _ and now, in his 60s, he has finally been beaten down.
It's tragic, it's easy to sense its inevitability and, in this age
of accelerated impersonality in society, it rings more true than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Though Loman is written as a small, miserable creature, Dennehy
uses his impressive girth as a porous armor against Willie's world,
to make Willie all the more empathetic; it's a wonder that a man
struggling against the truth of his own meagerness can even drag
that much heft. When he first strides into his kitchen, one is
struck by the claustrophobia Willie is trying to keep at bay.
Throughout the production, Dennehy digs at his temple, as if Willie
is desperately trying to burrow into his brain to locate the source
of his pain and pluck it out.
</P>
<P>
   Franz, too, is a wonder as Willie's long-suffering wife,
apoplectic with grief even before the truly grim stuff occurs and
powerless to stop anything that's coming. Eldard sensitively
evinces son Biff's roiling inner struggle, between pleasing a
father whose faults he understands all too well and creating a life
of his own insufficient devices.
</P>
<P>
   Even given the challenges of adapting performances calibrated
for live theater to the more intimate environment of TV cameras,
these performances are both full-bodied and subtle. One quibble _
the cameras rarely capture the full measure of the production's
acclaimed stage design, occasionallly making for some momentary
disorientation as we see a piece of the set rolling out of the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   As the ghost of Willie's brother Ben, describing a financial
opportunity the timorous salesman neglected to take him up on,
observes, ``It's dark there, but full of diamonds.'' Attention,
certainly, is worth paying to Dennehy and company. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MALCOLM IN THE MIDDLE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Malcolm, the gifted, precocious youngster who delivers his
observations on life directly to his audience, Frankie Muniz is a
natural charmer, with a wit and an unforced delivery that promises
pure comic gold. His vehicle, ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' is less
accomplished, with its broad sense of humor frequently straining
credibility. Kids should fall for it, since Malcolm's good company
and the humor is mildly risque; parents will smile indulgently and
remind themselves that there are far worse things on TV vying for
their kids' attention.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot boasts such placid hilarity as shaving Dad's hirsute
back and Mom answering the door topless. Future episodes feature
such low jinks as Malcolm setting off a stink bomb during a school
picnic and Mom forgetting her anniversary dinner with Dad because
she's too busy trying to wring a confession out of the kids as to
who ruined her favorite dress. Too infrequently does the show get
its humor from a smartly crafted line of dialogue. Instead, it
relies heavily on Muniz's abilities and the other actors' mugging
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the characters are all securely in place (Malcolm has a
bully, a whiny wimp and a chronic underachiever as brothers) for
decent character conflict. The writers, however, are trying a bit
too hard to deliver the laughs at this point. As Willie Loman might
say, ``He's liked, but he's not well-liked.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE VIRGINIAN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Owen Wister's 1902 novel ``The Virginian''' has thrived for a
century, inspiring, essentially, the entire western genre. It's
credited with creating the cowboy as an icon. It also spawned four
movies and a long-running TV series _ one of the rare programs that
ran 90 minutes _ that aired on NBC from 1962-71. And now, it's put
Bill Pullman in the director's chair, behind the producer's desk
and in front of the camera for a TNT teleflick.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pretty simple story. The Virginian (Pullman) _ no other
name needs to be given _ metes out justice to those helping a
corrupt landowner (played by Dennis Weaver) poach horses and
livestock from others in the Wyoming territory, even if they happen
to have been friends, and even if it threatens his burgeoning
romance with new schoolmarm Molly (Diane Lane).
</P>
<P>
   Pullman posits his hero as a lonesome cowhand who's fairly
clumsy in matters of the heart and is hardly oppressively
intimidating as a gunman; he's hardly any ultra-cool, laconic
western icon, and yet he strives for mythicism all the same: He
certainly means business when he's been wronged. As a director,
Pullman makes sure the dialogue doesn't sound contemporary, and if
he hasn't quite figured out the best place to put his camera _ it
roams restlessly, rarely finding the perfect vantage point from
which to suss out the action _ he has plenty of time to learn. And
Nathan Burr's gloriously evocative score makes the movie
compulsively easy to listen to, even when it's not completely
watchable. As Willie Loman might say, ``I still feel kind of
temporary about myself.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BRITANNIC' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fact: ``Titanic'' grossed well over a billion dollars, making it
the all-time box-office champion. Fact: There was a sister ship,
the ostensibly even more unsinkable Britannic, that went down
during World War I, the target of German saboteurs. Shame on
everyone else in the world for not cashing in on those two facts.
Shame on the Fox Family Channel for exploiting them so baldly and,
ultimately, badly.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Britannic,'' a fetching young British intelligence officer
(played by Amanda Ryan, who pointedly resembles Kate Winslet in a
number of scenes) battles prejudice, a serpentine spy network and
her own libido to unearth the German spies seeking out the weaponry
hidden away on the ship as it travels from London to Cairo. (This
apes the speculative fiction of the film ``The Hindenburg.'')
Unfortunately, she falls for the very man she should be
investigating _ Chaplain Reynolds (Edward Atterton).
</P>
<P>
   ``Britannic'' actually has several things over its lofty,
phenomenally successful predecessor. The stakes in the illicit
romance here are amplified exponentially from simple, dreary class
warfare and, for a time, Ryan and Atterton exude some palpable
chemistry. The script has more droll moments than ``Titanic's''
leaden dialogue ever allowed, and _ this is the capper _ it tells
its story briskly, mercifully shaving more than an hour off James
Cameron's leviathan. (Tape it and excise the commercials, and it's
well under half ``Titanic's'' running time.)
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it blows it all in the last half-hour with a series of
risibly dopey plot convolutions and a blitheriation on
``Titanic's'' climax. Moreover, Jacqueline Bisset struts through
the film in a blandly blustery fashion that fairly screams
``faded-star turn.'' Some moments of violence and sexuality seem
somewhat out of place on the Fox Family Channel. But, then,
``Titanic'' was hardly a model of narrative integrity or decorum,
and look how well it did. As Willie Loman's son might say, ``I'm
mixed up very bad.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE DAVID CASSIDY STORY' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, Get Happy,'' a docudrama about the TV series ``The
Partridge Family'' that aired on ABC last year, was clunkily
uneven, but up against NBC's ``The David Cassidy Story'' it's
downright brilliant. ``Cassidy'' covers some of the same territory,
but in a significantly duller fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The two films can only agree on one thing: Susan Dey, who played
Laurie Partridge, had a crush on Cassidy, though they're at odds on
how that was resolved. ``Come On'' suggests the two finally
consummated Dey's unrequited love; tonight's movie leaves things at
a chaste kiss, which tells you a lot about the insultingly
disingenuous ``The David Cassidy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The only improvement here over ``Come On'' is Dey Young's
spot-on turn as Shirley Jones; otherwise, everything is drearily
sanitized to the point of tedium. Here, the erstwhile Keith
Partridge (Andrew Kavovit) is a team player on the crummy sitcom
despite his artistic leanings. (For a guy who complains about his
show's lame pop songs, Cassidy _ this teleflick's executive
producer _ happily shoehorns as many as he can into this
production.) David is so wrapped up in making his show a success,
he can't find time for a date, and when he encounters groupies in
his hotel room _ ``good hotels'' won't accommodate him, he pouts _
he promptly boots them out. This straight-shooting bastion of
integrity even insists to a Rolling Stone reporter, against her
expectations, that his profile be hard-hitting, not mere puffery.
Do the words ``Yeah, right?'' come to mind?
</P>
<P>
   According to this bio-pic, Cassidy's problems stem from his
father, Jack Cassidy, portrayed fatuously as a vain womanizer and
fading actor, who at one jaw-droppingly campy point notes that his
initials are the same as Jesus Christ's and wonders which of the
two should be more impressed with the other. And yet David is such
a swell and sensitive guy that when this bully-sociopath plays the
role of marshmallow in a self-inflicted apartment fire, he manages
to weep real tears. Malcolm McDowell, a formerly respected actor,
takes this crummy role and chews up as much scenery as he can get
his teeth on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cassidy'' does cop to a brief interlude of drugging and
drinking _ perfunctorily, as if such a lame plot device is required
in this sort of movie _ but, predictably, ends up with its hero
happy and healthy and rocking once more. Had Cassidy not cooperated
with this venture, it would have been deemed idiotic hagiography;
with his name in the credits, it can only be chalked up to
breathtaking narcissism. As Willie Loman might say, ``I'm very
foolish to look at.'' He'd add, ``Sometimes it's better for a man
just to walk away.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
