<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-CARTER-JORDAN07-C     01-06 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CARTER-JORDAN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter more than a flashy dunker
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vince Carter does not jump so much as he levitates, as
if from a magician's table. Only higher. And faster. If you don't
believe it, you haven't seen the Toronto Raptors guard do his
remarkable work.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's aerial spectacle comes to Philips Arena tonight against
the Hawks as the best one-man show in the NBA. Dominique Wilkins
was the ``Human Highlight Film;'' Carter is the ``DVD Director's
Cut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince has got wings, man,'' the Los Angeles Lakers' Kobe
Bryant said. ``I've seen him do stuff that's just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Including the 360-degree dunk in Dallas last week. Carter
received the ball near the foul line on a fast break, took two
steps and elevated. He spun completely around in midair with the
ball in one hand as a waiter would carry a tray. When he completed
the turn, Carter put his other hand on the ball and flushed it
through the hoop with power.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, instead of spinning counter-clockwise on the 360, as
everyone else does, the 6-6 Carter twirled the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten so we don't even get amazed anymore,'' Toronto
teammate Dee Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors were not amazed when, in San Antonio, Carter made a
speedy crossover move around former Hawk Chucky Brown and exploded
to the basket to dunk in the face of Spurs center David Robinson
for two of his 39 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some shots I still can't believe,'' San Antonio coach
Gregg Popovich said. ``He took some shots we wanted him to take,
and he stuck it right down our throats.''
</P>
<P>
   A Carter gravity-defying, above-the-rim exhibition has become a
nightly ritual. It has made him the most awe-inspiring player in
the league _ and led to the proverbial comparisons to the
incomparable Michael Jordan. Not that he likes so much attention or
the Jordan talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life's not real easy right now, but I guess I'd rather have it
this way than not at all,'' Carter said, referring to the adulation
and the comparisons. He also is leading the balloting for the NBA
All-Star game, another indication of his prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am who I am,'' he said. ``There's a lot of pressure being
the next `man.' I'm my own person, and I want to establish my own
identity. And everybody in the NBA has flashes of playing like
Mike, sometime. I'm just honored by the comparison, but I want to
be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's true identity is much more than that of a dunking
wunderkind. He averages 24 points a game because he spent most of
the offseason working on his ball-handling skills and perimeter
game. The results have been frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say give him the jump shot, which is ludicrous,''
Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``He's got the ability to post,
he has the intermediate game, he can get to the rim, and he can get
to the (foul) line, and last year against us hit two late threes to
seal the deal. So, offensively, he has the whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, 22, finds it difficult to believe that most teams are
just realizing he has a credible outside game. ``I guess everyone's
probably starting to notice it more because last year it was dunk
this, dunk that,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really puts pressure on them if he makes those jump
shots,'' coach Butch Carter said. ``If he makes two or three, they
have to come up on him, and that opens up everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening up everything else'' for Carter means granting him
runway space for a liftoff. For all his overall improvement, it
always comes back to Carter playing above the rim. ``Nobody in the
league dunks better than Vince,'' Brown said. ``He dunks those real
`old-days' dunks. He makes it easy, like Michael and Dominique used
to do. It's just the finesse of it, and the way it looks like he's
not even struggling when he's doing it. Those are things you can't
plan. You come up with them in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's name did not come up Tuesday when USA Basketball
announced the final three members of the Sydney Olympic team, a
development met with outrage by most people in Toronto _ everyone
except Carter, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed for Vince,'' Raptors general manager
Glen Grunwald said. ``He deserves to be on the team. He's one of
the best players in the world right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter wanted the position, but he handled the news with grace.
``The Olympics is in the summer,'' he said ``If I didn't make it, I
didn't make it. If I can get over it, everyone else should, too.
Yes, it's a chance of a lifetime. But I'm young, there's Olympics
four years from now. I'll never say that's a bad decision because
Ray Allen (who was selected) is a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Having established in less than two years his prowess as a
player, the next major feat, according to coach Carter, ``is to
make his team a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   That might take some time yet. If the playoffs started today,
the Raptors (17-13) would be in, which is a nice first step. If
Toronto goes as Carter does, you can bet the rise will be
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   VINCE CARTER AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Born: Jan. 26, 1977
</P>
<P>
   Height; weight: 6-foot-6, 225 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   College: North Carolina
</P>
<P>
   SEASON STATS
</P>
<P>
   FG Pct.AssistsRBPts.
</P>
<P>
   45.23.56.123.9
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
