<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SPENT BIG DURING THE HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Costco, shoppers hoarded batteries. At Bloomingdales' they
gorged themselves on day-after sales, and at Tiffany's they
indulged in white gold. But everywhere Americans went this holiday
shopping season they spent big.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy, combined with fears and celebratory impulses
related to the new century, propelled sales in big chain stores
open a year, a crucial industry measurement, to rise 5.1 percent in
December, according to the Goldman Sachs retail index. The gain was
particularly impressive because it came on the heels of an
unusually strong 5.4 percent gain in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were sales strong, but merchants reported that they
kept inventories tight and controlled price cutting so that
fourth-quarter earnings would be robust as well. Industry analysts
could not effuse enough. ``It was a barn burner of a holiday
season,'' said Jeff Feiner, an analyst with Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Many patterns that dominated Christmases past reappeared like
Marley's ghost this season. Discount stores reported the strongest
sales, while department stores trailed. Americans held back their
shopping, postponing purchases until just before Christmas and even
the week after the holiday to get the biggest sales _ a habit that
was abetted this year by the fact that both Christmas and New
Year's fell on Saturdays. ``When the day after Christmas is a
Sunday, it gets people out to take advantage of gift certificates
and sales,'' said Bruce Van Kleeck, vice president of the National
Retail Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise of the month were the warehouse clubs,
which as a group turned in a spectacular numbers. At BJ's Wholesale
Club, sales rose 14.7 percent. At Sam's Club, a unit of Wal-Mart
Stores, sales advanced 14.2 percent, and at Costco Wholesale, sales
jumped 18.2 percent. Costco said it had benefited from Year 2000
concerns, selling precautionary items like generators and
flashlights, as well as celebratory products like wines and
champagnes.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief financial officer of Costco, Richard Galanti,
bragged that the chain, which has been doing well all year, did
well across the board this holiday season _ especially in such
nonbasic items as electronics, computers and jewelry. Diamonds were
a particularly coveted purchase. As if to drive home the point that
warehouse clubs are not just for canned tuna and toilet paper
anymore, Costco said it had sold a ``six-plus carat diamond'' by
special order for $98,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry retailers also experienced outsized sales increases in a
category that has historically been tied very closely to the
economy. At Zale's, sales for November and December climbed 16.3
percent over the comparable period a year earlier; at Tiffany &AMP;
Co.'s U.S. operations, sales soared 27 percent. Michael Kowalski,
president and chief executive of Tiffany, said that in addition to
good economic conditions the chain had done well because it had
sped up the rate of new product introductions. A square-cut
engagement ring called the Lucida was especially popular this year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores as a group only experienced a 1.4 percent
gain, but they were loaded down by the fact that the two giants in
the category, J.C. Penney and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. continued to
struggle, losing market share to both low-priced specialty
retailers like the Gap's Old Navy and discounters like Target, a
unit of the Dayton Hudson Corp.
</P>
<P>
   However, some of the big name department store chains did
experience a very respectable holiday season. Neiman-Marcus, which
focuses on more upscale customers, saw December sales rise 14.4
percent over the year-earlier month. Saks, which had a bumpy summer
and fall, had a nice Christmas recovery, reporting a sales increase
of 5 percent. Federated Department Stores, owner of Bloomingdale's
and Macy's, reported a sales rise of 6.4 percent
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts also credited the department stores with planning
far enough in advance to preserve profits even in the face of
widespread cost-cutting and coupon promotions. ``Federated has been
doing a great job of planning for promotions and building awareness
of private brands,'' said Jeff Edelman, an analyst with Paine
Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sears, which had a slight sales decrease for December, has
said that earnings will rise far in excess of expectations, partly
because it did not engage in heavy price cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Among the specialty store chains, AnnTaylor Stores, which was
expected to be a big winner as women snapped up velvet and beaded
slip dresses for New Year's Eve parties, reported December sales
rose only a modest nine-tenths of 1 percent. In a statement, the
retail chain said that it ``could have benefited from traditional
gift-giving items like classic twin sets.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Federal Reserve likely to raise interest rates in the
coming months, analysts were skeptical that merchants could
continue to expand at the same pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see some hangover as early as January, as some of
that Y2K merchandise comes back,'' warned George Strachan, an
analyst with Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
