<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-FCC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING HIS FIRST CAMPAIGN CRISIS, MCCAIN STANDS FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Pa.)  (See also MCCAIN-ETHICS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic
is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
(th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ John McCain smiled his way through his
campaign's first crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with persistent questions about how he could be running as
a campaign finance reformer and yet could have written to a federal
regulatory agency on behalf of a contributor, McCain was right back
in his accustomed seat in his ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign
bus on Thursday morning, bantering with reporters and showing off
his thick-soled ``lucky shoes'' that he wears to every Republican
debate.
</P>
<P>
   And for a second straight day, displaying no signs of the temper
his opponents like to talk about, he patiently insisted again and
again that he had done nothing wrong by asking the Federal
Communications Commission to make a decision on whether to allow
Paxson Communications to buy a television station in Pittsburgh.
Executives and lobbyists for Paxson have been contributors to his
campaign,
</P>
<P>
   The only hint the 63-year-old senator gave that this was not the
best of days came when he said, ``If I let things get under my
skin, I wouldn't have gotten out of bed this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign for president, McCain has put himself forward as
the anti-establishment outsider who fights entrenched special
interests and will give the little guy a voice in Washington. So it
could well hurt his candidacy if he should come to be viewed by
voters as just another member of Congress helping the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The risk was evident Thursday night at the Republican debate
when the first question posed to McCain was whether he had shown
poor judgment that made him look hypocritical. He answered that he
had worked hard to change the campaign finance law because `'all
this money washing around Washington and all these uncontrolled
contributions taint all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee he
had been trying to prod a truculent bureaucracy that had not acted
after two years, not favoring a donor.
</P>
<P>
   When his questioner said that he had not been forthcoming in his
answer, he shot back, ``What was not forthcoming?'' and repeated
his explanation.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, there was no sign that voters in the nation's
first primary state cared about McCain's dealings with the FCC. In
Bow at 7:30 a.m., an enthusiastic crowd of several hundred strong
questioned McCain closely on virtually everything else _ from
health care to cold fusion to whether women should be allowed to
serve on submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, audience members mobbed the senator and others
grabbed handfuls of campaign literature. ``There's just something
about John McCain that struck a chord that I liked,'' said
Elizabeth Foy, 40, a teacher who said she was now leaning toward
voting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Television news crews, by contrast, descended on him at every
public appearance to ask about his letter to the FCC. ``I
understand the suspicion,'' McCain said. ``But I'm perfectly happy
with what I did and would do exactly the same thing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who is lagging behind McCain in
the polls in New Hampshire, used the controversy to stoke doubts
about his opponent, leading into Thursday night's debate. ``I think
it's really important for people who are advocating reforms to live
up to the spirit of the reforms they are advocating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At another moment, even as he sidestepped questions about
McCain, Bush sought to undercut his rival's portrayal of himself as
an opponent of the establishment. ``Senator McCain is chairman of a
very powerful committee in the United States Senate,'' Bush said.
``He's a committee chairman. He's been there for a period of time
to the point where he can earn this chairmanship. Ask him
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who comes from Texas,'' Bush said. ``I'm not a
committee chairman. I'm an outsider.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain hammered away at the differences between his own tax cut
proposals and those of Bush in his town hall meeting and did not
back away from his signature issue of campaign finance reform. He
vowed that as president he would fight to ban the kinds of
unregulated donations to political parties known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day that I am inaugurated as the president of the United
States,'' he said, ``I would say, `my friends I campaigned on this
issue. I asked for the support of the American people. I told them
I would get this changed. Now my dear friends it is time that
Congress reacted to the will of the American people.'' Of those
lawmakers who tried to oppose him, he said, drawing laughter and
applause, ``I'd make 'em famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he stopped by the Manchester Fire Department Central
Station to eat a bowl of firehouse chile with firefighters. One of
them, Bruce Phillips, asked him to hold hearings on a proposal to
create a federal grant program for fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have that support in return for this delightful
meal,'' McCain pledged as 10 television cameras filmed. ``Every
politician has a price,'' McCain added wryly. ``Mine is obviously a
chile lunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
