<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titans finally at home, loud home
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ They lived in a nomadic state for three
seasons, jumping from Houston to Memphis to Nashville. Finally, the
Tennessee Titans have a home _ surprisingly, one of the NFL's
loudest stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   When the Titans host Buffalo on Saturday in an AFC wild-card
game, Tennessee will be seeking its ninth victory in a row in
Adelphia Coliseum. It would tie the 1971 Dallas Cowboys for the
best record in christening a new stadium in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been absolutely a great, great experience,'' Titans
kicker Al Del Greco said. ``People that have played here will tell
you that it's a tough place to play, and that means a lot to the
home team.''
</P>
<P>
   Just having a home has meant a lot to the former Houston Oilers
franchise. The Titans finished 13-3 this season after going 8-8
each of the previous three years. In its final two seasons in
Texas, and during lame-duck years in Memphis and Vanderbilt
Stadium, Tennessee often played in front of more empty seats than
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years were about a lot of traveling and not
having a home,'' Titans offensive tackle Brad Hopkins said. ``It
was about not getting any attention from anyone who cared about
this football team. There was no excitement or energy, and that's
probably why we finished with an average record.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee isn't average anymore. The Titans have won four in a
row and scored 30 points or more in their last three victories.
Tennessee is the only team that beat the Rams, the No. 1 seed in
the NFC, and twice defeated the Jaguars, the AFC's top seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves a winner,'' Hopkins said. ``Nashville has
embraced us, and there's a lot of excitement around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans set a franchise attendance mark of 528,890 this
season, an average of 66,111 fans a game, after being ignored in
Tennessee the past two years. The team's first playoff game since
1993 sold out last week in 18 minutes, and scalpers are demanding
as much as $300 for wild-card tickets with face values of $30 and
$40.
</P>
<P>
   Those fans have turned Adelphia into one of the NFL's toughest
stadiums to visit. In the Titans' final five home games, opponents
were flagged for 18 false-start penalties, including eight by St.
Louis. Oakland receiver Tim Brown, who this season visited Denver's
Mile High Stadium, Green Bay's Lambeau Field and Minnesota's
Metrodome, called Adelphia the most difficult for an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought (Adelphia) would be the easiest one to play
in because it's so open, but it was very, very loud,'' Brown said.
``(It) had to be the loudest place we've been in.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans players have noticed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably one of those guys that didn't think home-field
advantage mattered that much,'' Titans safety Blaine Bishop said.
``But the 12th man has been the difference for us in a couple of
close games. It has just given us a fresh start. Now, we can erase
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Titans' first season in Nashville has helped the
franchise bury one of the ugliest chapters in NFL history. After
owner Bud Adams announced that his team was leaving Houston, the
then-Oilers drew fewer than 30,000 fans for five of eight home
games in 1996, with just over 15,000 attending the final game in
the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The team played its games in Memphis' Liberty Bowl in 1997 and
averaged about 28,000 for eight games. Last season, the Titans
played in Vanderbilt Stadium and failed to sell out half their
games, despite playing in the league's smallest venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just made it tough, in that there weren't a lot of people
at the games,'' Bishop said. ``When there were people at the games,
most of them were rooting for the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   During the transition, the Titans also lacked the practice
facility and amenities of most NFL teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our facilities over the last three years were worse than some
high schools,'' free safety Marcus Robertson said. ``That was
disappointing, being a professional. You had to laugh to keep from
crying. Everything was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a joke anymore. The Titans opened a new $19 million
training facility this summer. Representatives of the Falcons and
several other teams building new facilities have toured the
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say you were a police officer,'' Hopkins said. ``What
makes your job more enjoyable _ working in Beverly Hills or working
in Compton? We've got great facilities now, and we enjoy coming to
work. Now, it's not a place where you can't wait to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
