<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-MIDSEASON-REVIEWS-     01-06 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MIDSEASON-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS GO BACK TO THE DRAWING BOARD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Saturday, Jan. 8) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent fall TV season wasn't the disaster fall seasons are
usually touted as being: The networks didn't hemorrhage nearly as
many viewers as they have in the recent past. But there's always
room for improvement. Herewith, a midseason check-up on each
network, and the new shows on which they have pegged their hopes
for said improvement. Unless otherwise stated, the series have no
premiere dates set in stone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If not for a certain game show that became an inexplicable
national phenomenon, ABC would be really hurting. As it is, the
network's not in such great shape _ how long can it ride that one
horse before it collapses and gets shipped off to the glue factory?
</P>
<P>
   WHO WANTS TO BE A MILLIONAIRE:You may have heard of this one. It
begins an eight-night run Sunday before assuming its thrice-weekly
schedule of 9 p.m. Sundays, 8 p.m. Tuesdays and 9 p.m. and
Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   CLERKS: An animated version of Kevin Smith's no-budget comedy
about two waste-oid buddies stuck in dead-end convenience and video
store jobs.
</P>
<P>
   WONDERLAND: Formerly titled ``Bellevue,'' this examines the
quirky challenges undertaken by the staff and patients at a
psychiatric hospital. Peter Berg _ Billy Kronk on ``Chicago Hope''
and the director of ``Very Bad Things'' _ serves as executive
producer.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Me: Kyra Sedgewick is a New York radio talk-show host
who has extremely different views on life from the radio shrink
(Beverly D'Angelo) who follows her on the air in this sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Then Came You: Mmm, mmm, leftovers! This sitcom about a
thirtysomething woman's affair with a twentysomething guy never
found its way onto ABC's fall schedule, but it'll air eventually. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS has a nice problem _ finding time slots in which to schedule
its midseason replacement shows. New dramas ``Judging Amy,'' ``Now
and Again'' and ``Family Law'' all performed significantly better
than most forecasters expected, and returning hits ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' and ``JAG'' scored even higher ratings.
</P>
<P>
   WINNING LINES: CBS jumps on the game-show bandwagon with this
effort from the creator of the British version of ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire,'' hosted by Dick Clark. Debuts Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   CITY OF ANGELS: The travails and triumphs of an underfunded
inner-city hospital and its efforts to get city politicos to
provide greater support are essayed by ``NYPD Blue's'' dream team
of Paris Barclay and Steven Bochco. Blair Underwood stars as chief
of surgery Ben Turner; Vivica A. Fox plays Lillian Price, hired to
stem the tide of hospital problems as medical director _ darned if
they didn't once have a fling and there's tension in the air.
Debuts Jan. 16, moves to Wednesdays at 8 p.m. on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE: Here's an oddity: This single-camera sitcom was
actually on the air before, back in 1992, and returns with a new
cast, still focusing on the romantic foibles of a group of Miami
twentysomethings. Kristy Swanson _ who, by playing ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' in the original movie, has become a trivia
question before her time _ and George Eades star. Warning:
Continuing the trend started this fall, characters talk directly to
the camera (signaled hereafter as CTTC).
</P>
<P>
   FALCONE: Based on the FBI agent whose exploits inspired the film
``Donnie Brasco,'' this drama stars Jason Gedrick as an undercover
Fed who poses as a mobster to infiltrate the gangster underworld. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC's doing fine, like CBS, except their new comedies stank. But
then, so did everybody's. Still, the network has assembled an
aggressive array of midseason series, and is determined to produce
one good comedy this year.
</P>
<P>
   MYOB: A midseason night's dream. Don Roos essentially retools
his hilarious film ``The Opposite of Sex'' into a single-camera
situation comedy. Here, a precocious teen-ager, always at the ready
with a sardonic quip, rooms with an attractive but uptight high
school principal who may or may not be her aunt. Warning: CTTC, at
least in voice-overs.
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Battery Park: Gary David Goldberg (``Family Ties'')
created this sitcom that updates, approximately, ``Barney Miller.''
It's set in a police precinct run by Elizabeth Perkins, playing a
chief with political aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHERS: This supernatural thriller seeks to cash in on the
success of ``The Sixth Sense'' more than the usual template, ``The
X-Files,'' even though the executive producers are former ``X''-men
Glen Morgan and James Wong. It concerns folks with extrasensory
abilities that let them explore this world, as well as other
dimensions, particularly ``the other side.'' Premieres at 10 p.m.
Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   GOD, THE DEVIL AND BOB: From Carsey-Werner, home of ``3rd Rock
From the Sun'' and ``That '70s Show,'' comes an animated fantasy
about a guy who, like the others, enjoys close relations with ``the
other side'' _ in both directions. James Garner and French Stewart
provide voices.
</P>
<P>
   SAMMY: Animated parody of Hollywood mores focusing on a hot
young actor and his weaselly estranged father (both voiced by David
Spade). Other voices offer an impressive comedy pedigree: Bob
Oedenkirk and David Cross of HBO's ``Mr. Show,'' and comics Andy
Dick and Harland Williams (``Dumb and Dumber,'' ``There's Something
About Mary'').
</P>
<P>
   TWENTY-ONE: Game Show hosted by one-time journalist Maury
Povich. Premieres at 8 p.m. Sunday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox had as disastrous a fall season as a network could have. It
canceled a series (``Manchester Prep'') before it ever hit the air
for the third straight season. Its best-reviewed new shows,
``Action'' and ``Harsh Realm,'' already have been canceled, as has
``Ally,'' its half-hour dose of ``Ally McBeal.'' The new shows
still on the schedule _ ``Time of Your Life'' and ``Get Real'' _
are sucking wind, and a few stalwarts _ ``Party of Five,'' ``King
of the Hill,'' ``The X-Files'' _ are underperforming. On top of all
that, the network elected not to crash a plane on live TV, as
earlier reported, to instill a little class around the joint.
Presenting a mere two new replacement shows seems a little like
rearranging deck chairs on the Titanic, the profits of which in
Fox's film division may have to underwrite this season for the
network.
</P>
<P>
   GREED: Return of the Chuck Woolery-hosted game show. 9 p.m.
Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLM IN THE MIDDLE: Life as seen through the eyes of a
precocious and witty 10-year-old, played by Frankie Muniz, who has
charmed the hearts of critics. Will America follow? Debuts Sunday.
Warning: CTTC.
</P>
<P>
   TITUS: Imagine a more demented Al Bundy as Paul Buchman's dad,
and you've got some idea of this sitcom's sensibility. It's about
an average Joe named Christopher Titus, an auto detailer in the
perfect relationship, if he can just shake the profound influence
of Stacy Keach as his boozing, womanizing and traumatizing pop. The
show's pretty hilariously unflinching in its depiction of abject
dysfunction. Due in March. Warning: CTTC. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The WB made the mistake of allowing near-dead UPN to gain
significant ground on it. Its new shows were moderate successes at
best, abject failures at worst, while franchise series ``Felicity''
and ``Dawson's Creek'' underperformed. And the network !ital!still
hasn't come up with a viable sitcom. Onward they press.
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Baby Blues: Animated version of the popular comic strip
about parents shlepping through the everyday drudgery of family
life. Mike O'Malley _ he of the quickly canceled sitcom earlier in
the season _ and Julia Sweeney provide voices.
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Brutally Normal: Single-camera sitcom about life in the
sundry caste systems of high school. Three sophomore _ and at times
sophomoric _ buddies keep each other honest and sane amid the
back-stabbing and bickering that is the American educational
system. ``Ally McBeal-esque'' fantasy vignettes crop up on
occasion. Debuts Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   D.C.: Five young, fresh-faced college grads take on the
establishment _ and try to keep their clothing stain-free _ in
Washington. Premiering in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Young Americans: Another slice of idealized life among the
young, set at a prestigious New England boys' prep school.
Conflicts with the blue-collar locals, along the lines of
``Breaking Away,'' are promised, along with much romantic intrigue.
Premiering in the summer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UPN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The moribund network was resurrected by wrestling, but its other
programming still hasn't clicked satisfactorily _ last season's
sure-fire network salvation, ``Dilbert,'' routinely dwelled at the
absolute bottom of the ratings. But hope springs eternal.
</P>
<P>
   The Beat: This cop show represents an interesting creative
butting of heads _ the gritty sensibility of ``Homicide: Life in
the Streets'' executive producers Tom Fontana and Barry Levinson
take on the UPN network's slick and stupid facade.
</P>
<P>
   I Dare You! The Ultimate Challenge: Evel Knievel hosts this
concoction of wacky and dangerous stunts performed by folks who no
doubt wouldn't be able to tell if they suffered brain damage from a
daredevil act since they were foolish enough to try it in the first
