<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-ETHICS-ART-2TA     01-06 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ETHICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGING THE ETHICS OF AN ETHICS REFORMER
</HEADLINE>
 (See also McCAIN-FCC)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eleven years ago, Sen. John McCain defended himself
against ethics charges for his ties to a corrupt savings
association and a campaign contributor by saying that he had
performed a legitimate constituent service when he met with
regulators who were preparing to seize the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done this kind of thing many, many times,'' McCain,
R-Ariz., said in 1989, explaining that helping Charles Keating, who
had lent him his company jet and whose associates had contributed
$112,000 to his campaign, was like ``helping the little lady who
didn't get her Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, a Senate ethics inquiry concluded that McCain had
exercised poor judgment but had not violated any rules. The senator
would go on to make reform of the political system a central part
of his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   While it was a seminal case, the Keating investigation never
persuaded the Senate to adopt clear standards for when legitimate
constituent service crossed the line into undue influence into a
regulatory matter. The line remains murky.
</P>
<P>
   The issue re-emerged for McCain this week when he faced
questions about his intervention at the Federal Communications
Commission in a case that involved a contributor to his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very difficult area to write bright-line rules,'' said
Robert S. Bennett, the Washington lawyer who was special counsel to
the ethics panel during its investigation of five senators with
ties to Keating. He said tension was inevitable in a system that
both encouraged political contributions from people with interests
before the government and also relied on lawmakers to ride herd on
federal agencies that could be arrogant and bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem will always be with us as long as these guys are
required to raise tons of money and are allowed to receive them
from those who have business before their committees,'' Bennett
said. ``What happens is that when your political opponent accepts a
contribution from someone with interests before Congress, that's
called unethical. But when you yourself receive the money, you
claim you are engaging in the time-honored tradition of constituent
service.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, has
written repeatedly to urge the FCC to complete its reviews on
several license applications affecting many of his largest
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, his letters were written a few months after the
applications were filed; in others, it was years later.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in New Hampshire on Thursday, McCain defended his
actions. The Commerce Committee, he said, has jurisdiction over 80
percent of the nation's businesses, so there will be a ``natural
suspicion'' about any decision that ultimately helps supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It renews my vigor for campaign finance reform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks McCain has sent two letters to the Federal Trade
Commission demanding that commissioners vote on two license
transfers in a case that ultimately benefited Paxson Communications
Inc., whose executives and lobbyists have been major contributors
to his campaign. The letters are among many he has sent to the
commission over the years in regulatory cases involving his
fund-raisers and contributors.
</P>
<P>
   After issuing a statement last year suggesting that a large
merger of two telephone companies showed the shortcomings of a 1996
telecommunications law, for instance, he sent two letters
complaining about a commission staff official who had been publicly
quoted as questioning the deal, while another letter said the
agency was setting too high a standard.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Notebaert, head of one of the companies, Ameritech, is a
major fund-raiser for McCain, while the lobbyists for the other
company, SBC Communications, had organized a series of
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has also written to the chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, William Kennard, to complain that the
agency has moved too slowly in permitting the Baby Bell telephone
companies to enter the $80 billion long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the senator's largest contributors have been executives
from US West, who have given more than $107,000, and from BellSouth
Corp., who have given at least $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the chairman of US West, Solomon Trujillo, is one of
McCain's top fund-raisers, while Notebaert of Ameritech is another
top fund-raiser for the senator. In a letter sent April 16, McCain
was one of two senators who asked Kennard to respond to testimony
by Trujillo that the agency's 14-point checklist for completion of
the merger had become a 1,014-point checklist.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McCain has taken other action as a senator that would assist US
West. In May, he introduced the ``Internet Regulatory Freedom
Act,'' which would assist the company's efforts to offer high-speed
Internet service over long-distance telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, the political problem is not that writing such
letters or proposing such legislation flouts any ethics rules.
Indeed many experts said that based on what had come out, the same
types of letters and legislation were routinely written by other
lawmakers. And in the case of McCain's letters concerning the
license transfers, several other senators had also urged the FCC to
approve the deals.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the problem facing McCain is that because he is a
champion of cleaning up the corrupting influence of money in
politics, his dealings on behalf of contributors, even when they
conform to the norms of Washington, raise the issue of whether his
record matches his rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, McCain will be the Velcro man on these types of
issues because of the standards he's set for himself and the issues
he's highlighted, as unfair as that may be,'' said Kenneth Gross, a
Washington lawyer who specializes in campaign finance and ethics
issues.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's chief campaign spokesman disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has never said he is above reproach,'' said the
spokesman, Howard Opinsky. ``It would be one thing if he had said,
`I never do this.' But he doesn't. He says `We are the problem.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But others see it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The portrait McCain likes is the one of the plain-talking
crusader who's bucking the system,'' wrote Charles Lewis in his new
book, ``The Buying of the President 2000'' (Avon Books). ``The one
many others see is that of a politician who rarely breaks ranks
with the special interests that finance his campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists in Washington working for other candidates noted
Thursday, for instance, that McCain's fund-raising staff was filled
with lobbyists who had issues before the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who are raising money for McCain are Kenneth
Duberstein (whose clients include Comcast, General Motors,
Time-Warner and United Airlines), Vin Weber (who represents
Microsoft, Boeing and AT&AMP;T), Timothy P. McKone (SBC
Telecommunications Inc.) and Robert S. Aiken (Pinnacle West).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
