<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-06 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TALK ABOUT A FAST FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While average Americans were busy with holiday shopping and
storing up canned goods for the coming apocalypse, the 2000
presidential primaries were secretly drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, we may only have a couple of weeks left to go. Bill
Bradley and John McCain are running around New Hampshire like
overstimulated gerbils, tortured by the knowledge that if they lose
there on Feb. 1, the game is over. Al Gore and George W. Bush are
nearly as hyperactive, both apparently under the impression that
early victory and a nine-month-long Bush-Gore presidential race
would be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The single bright spot, for anybody who can focus on the
presidential campaign before the Christmas trees are carted away,
is that so far the primaries have been a fine show. Each party is
offering voters at least two viable candidates who are neither
crazy nor under indictment. Position papers abound. You are going
to be hearing so much about issues, people, you'll be begging us to
start writing about sex again.
</P>
<P>
   Debates occur so regularly that Alan Keyes is now on television
more than Regis Philbin. Miraculously, the Democratic encounter
Wednesday was actually interesting. Bradley has learned how to
stand up to Gore, who will run right over anybody who doesn't fight
back. And while the vice president still has not quite acquired the
TV demeanor of a normal earthling, he does now manage to stick to a
single personality throughout the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The policy disagreements between the two men are almost
invisible, but the debate did reveal differences, a divide between
practicality and ambitious reach.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley supported registration of all handguns, while Gore said
it was more feasible to limit the proposal to new sales. Bradley
wants to create a big new health care initiative, Gore wants to
take what we've got and extend it. You really did get a picture of
two very smart guys, one of whom would probably seize the political
moment to do whatever looked most doable, and the other in love
with sweeping ideas and visionary leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But it would still have been hard for an audience to stay
focused without the occasional cheap thrills _ I particularly liked
it when Bradley said, ``Let me explain to you, Al, how the private
sector works. OK?'' Gore's spinners said that Bradley came across
as too testy _ voters, especially women, have always been
uncomfortable with candidates who yell. But Gore does frequently
exhibit a Dudley-Do-Right manner that seems to beg somebody to tell
him to come off it.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Democrats suggests that a good debate should
not run any longer than an episode of ``The Sopranos'' and feature
only two candidates. But none of the Republican also-rans seem to
be planning to go away _ don't these people have lives?
Nevertheless, Thursday night the Republican debate's moderator, Tim
Russert, managed to keep the focus on the two real candidates while
the rest of the field yelped for equal time.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose stump speech about compassionate conservatism and
education opportunity leaves a lot of Republican crowds cold,
carved a very careful path to the right while McCain, who may
actually be the more conservative Republican, followed his own
drummer and embraced the mantle of group moderate.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of forum is win-win for Bush. Thursday night he dodged
making any commitment about whether he personally believes
non-Christians can go to Heaven. But as long as he's sharing the
stage with people like Keyes, who devoted part of his time to
attacking the concept of separation of church and state, anything
he says is going to sound middle-of-the-road.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Democrats, the Republicans are getting more skillful as
they gain experience. McCain, who's been trying to fight rumors of
a bad temper, had developed a terrible tendency to grin maniacally
no matter what he was talking about. But Thursday night he had
returned to fairly normal facial expressions for the first time in
weeks. Bush, who one-upped his father and took a vow of no new
taxes and many large tax cuts, also managed with some effort to
suppress the smirk.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the spectacle, and watch the winners emerge. The rest of
the field can move to New York and run for office there, like
everybody else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
