<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Settlement to Help A Tobacco Region &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of the $206 billion legal settlement that 46 states
reached with the tobacco industry in 1998, a North Carolina
foundation will be able to provide help to areas damaged by
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit organization, Golden LEAF, for Long-term Economic
Advancement Fund, could begin making grants as early as late spring
in regions of the state tied to tobacco, including parts of eastern
North Carolina heavily damaged by the hurricane last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of these dollars is to bring about some action to
immediately relieve that suffering, and that's what were going to
do, as promptly as we can,'' said William Friday, the retired
president of the University of North Carolina system who is
chairman of the foundation's board.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the foundation has received $29.3 million from the
settlement and expects to receive nearly $4.6 billion through 2025.
Each state receives part of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Cohen &QL;
</P>
