<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BACTERIA-RESIST07-COX     01-06 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-RESIST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: `Superbugs' resisting a leading antibiotic
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the fourth time in three years, a U.S. hospital
patient has been infected by a strain of bacteria that has
developed partial resistance to a treatment of last resort, the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A 63-year-old woman, who was in the last stages of kidney
disease in an Illinois nursing home, died of a heart infection last
April in a hospital. She was found to have been infected with
Staphylococcus aureus that had become partially resistant to the
drug vancomycin, the CDC said. Vancomycin, an extremely potent
antibiotic, is one of the few still effective against bacteria that
have developed resistance to other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a heads-up, alerting us that there may be a new
problem on the horizon and warning us to take action,'' said Dr.
Julie Gerberding, director of the CDC's Hospital Infections
Program. The CDC has made reducing antibiotic resistance a
priority, calling on doctors to prescribe drugs sparingly and
urging institutions to conduct careful surveillance for problems.
</P>
<P>
   Infectious disease experts have warned for years that
antibiotics are used too generously in medicine and agriculture.
That practice fosters the growth of ``superbugs,'' whose ability to
develop resistance outpaces science's ability to produce new drugs.
Consequently, there's a heightened possibility of returning
medicine to a pre-antibiotic stage in which simple infections could
be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Most bacteria have developed immunity to at least a few of the
more than 150 antibiotics in use, but the problem has become acute
as major pathogens have developed resistance to the most powerful
drugs. Staph is one such pathogen: It is one of the most common
causes of major infections contracted after patients are admitted
to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see resistance emerging in Staph aureus, we take it
more seriouslythan we would in other organisms,'' Gerberding said.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of Staph germs that could resist vancomycin had
been predicted for years; the first partially resistant bugs
(called VISA for ``vancomycin-intermediate S. aureus'') were found
in Japan in May 1997. The first U.S. cases followed quickly, in
Michigan and New Jersey in 1997, New York in 1998 and now the
Illinois woman, whose name was not disclosed by the CDC, last year.
All four patients have died, though no evidence suggests the germs'
antibiotic resistance caused their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Though infections caused by germs with resistance to a less
potent antibiotic, methicillin, have been found in communities,
VISA has been transmitted only in health care settings. It is
important, the CDC said Thursday, that potential patients not be
overly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to frighten anyone away from hospitals,''
Gerberding said. ``These infections are rare, they are important,
and they serve to remind medical professionals how important it is
to combat them.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is still unclear precisely how rare they are. In a second
report released Thursday, the CDC warned that laboratories are
doing an inadequate job of detecting drug-resistant pathogens.
</P>
<P>
   In a voluntary survey of 416 labs in eight states, conducted in
August and September 1998, the CDC found 40 percent were not
performing confirmatory tests for vancomycin susceptibility in
Staph and almost 70 percent were not testing for a second
resistance pattern, to drugs called cephalosporins, in a different
class of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The labs, which are part of a nationwide network that alerts the
CDC to emerging infections, perform analyses for hospitals and
other health care institutions. Those that belonged to managed care
organizations were less likely than independents to perform the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Given the uncertainty about the spread of resistance, it is even
more important that health professionals and the public become
judicious about antibiotic use, Gerberding said. ``We have some
scientific evidence to suggest that if you do reduce the use of a
class of antibiotics, the resistance to that class will fade,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
