<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DEATH-PENALTY07-COX     01-06 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida adopts lethal injection
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart and S.V. Date
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ After 77 years, Florida lawmakers adopted a
new way to kill its condemned murderers Thursday, making lethal
injection the state's primary method of execution instead of the
electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   But the historic change during this week's special three-day
session was accompanied by a setback for Gov. Jeb Bush and the
Republican-led Legislature, as they watched the initial unravelings
of Bush's carefully orchestrated plan to limit the court appeals of
Death Row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: a lack of five votes.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the unanticipated events left Speaker
John Thrasher (R-Orange Park) talking about the possibility of
holding another special session, at no certain time, to ensure that
the appeals process is shortened.
</P>
<P>
   The special meeting of legislators is being held in response to
the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in October to hear arguments that
the electric chair is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Flames have erupted during two electrocutions in the last
decade, and the last condemned man, Allen Lee ``Tiny'' Davis,
suffered a massive nosebleed during his electrocution.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders believed they could skirt the constitutional
argument, and continue killing the 365 inmates now on Death Row if
they adopted lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he would hold the special session only if
legislators also agreed to change the way appeals are handled to
prevent them from dragging out. His goal is to limit appeals to
five years from the current average of 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has remained so intent on passing the legislation his way
that he went with Lt. Gov. Frank Brogan to lobby senators in Sen.
President Toni Jennings' office Thursday afternoon _ while she was
still presiding over the chamber in session.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, across the rotunda, the House was voting
on his prized appeals reform proposal _ and coming up five votes
short of the necessary two-thirds majority to repeal current court
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The event quickly sent leaders into a tizzy. Bush, Jennings and
Thrasher exchanged phone calls trying to figure out how to undo the
mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all need help. Y'all need a doctor,'' Jennings told House
Majority Leader Jerry Maygarden (R-Pensacola), who had come to the
Senate to explain the news.
</P>
<P>
   Without those votes, the Legislature can offer the court its
suggestions on speeding up appeals, but cannot throw out the
criminal procedure rules followed by the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, there was a flurry of confusion as Thrasher met
with his lieutenants at the podium for more than 30 minutes.
Finally, the House, following the Senate's unanimous vote, approved
the lethal injection bill 102-5.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to sign the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But the quandary over the appeals bill remains.
</P>
<P>
   Five House Republicans were absent Thursday because one was out
of the country; one was sick; two were with their ill spouses; and
one was attending his sister's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thrasher said he would spend Thursday night trying to
see if any of them can return today. ``We're going to find out who
is available.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP may also pick up support from two Democrats who didn't
vote: Rep. Lori Edwards of Auburndale and Rep. John Cosgrove of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Thrasher rejected any notion of defeat. ``We
accomplished 90 percent of what we set out to do,'' noting the
decision to render the electric chair to the back seat and leave
only three states _ Georgia, Alabama and Nebraska _ that require
execution by electrocution.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, sending the Supreme Court ``advice with 75
votes is pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in the long run there will be any setback,''
said Rep. Tom Feeney (R-Oviedo) and in line to be the next House
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Liz Hirst was also hopeful. ``Well, we don't
want to speculate on the ifs,'' she said, ``but he's optimistic
that tomorrow will be a good day to achieve the goals.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, shortening the appeals process was far more
controversial than debate over whether to ditch the electric chair
as Florida's primary method of execution. That was evident Thursday
because House lawmakers spent hours quarreling over appeals
changes; they didn't debate the lethal injection bill at all.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining support from 80 lawmakers today is also no guarantee
that the court won't reject the Legislature's law anyway; that's up
to the justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can always watch what the (the Supreme Court justices) do,
and if they don't change things, we can always come back in a
special session,'' Thrasher said. ``It's not the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats didn't quite see it that way. ``It screws
things up pretty majorly,'' said Senate Minority Leader Buddy Dyer.
``It kind of points out that maybe we shouldn't have done it all
this way to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, and in both chambers Thursday, Democrats continued to
criticize the GOP's intention to pass the appeals bill in a few
days instead of during the regular session that begins in March.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Smith of the Florida Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers said the Republican de-emphasis now on passing the reforms
is a retreat. ``That is an admission of guilty by the governor and
the Republican leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Mary Ellen Klas contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
