<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN TREATED LIKE HEAD OF STATE IN VISIT TO ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Boris Yeltsin's first pilgrimage to the Holy Land
offered up a series of curious juxtapositions on Thursday: the man
who entered politics as a Communist received a high honor from a
senior Orthodox cleric; Russia's first president pronounced his
historically anti-Semitic land free of anti-Jewish sentiment; the
convert to democracy who has just quit politics sat at lunch
opposite Natan Sharansky, a major political force in Israel who
spent nine years in Soviet jails defending freedoms that Yeltsin
only later brought to his country.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere he went, Yeltsin was treated like the head of state
he so recently was, before his stunning resignation on New Year's
Eve. And everywhere, church and political leaders eagerly sought
his embrace.
</P>
<P>
   He started his day with a ceremony at the Greek Orthodox
Patriarchate in the walled Old City of Jerusalem, where he was
named a Knight of the Holy Sepulcher, the church that is
traditionally considered the site of Jesus' tomb. Yeltsin seemed
moved by the honor, which Patriarch Diodoros I, the top Orthodox
cleric in the Holy Land, also bestowed on the leaders of Ukraine,
Georgia, Belarus, Bulgaria, Romania, Moldova and Greece _ several
of the countries where the Orthodox Church predominates. More than
a dozen Orthodox hierarchs attended the ceremony, including the
Russian Orthodox patriarch, Aleksy II, who blessed the transfer of
power last Friday from Yeltsin to his prime minister, Vladimir
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   That Kremlin ceremony, Yeltsin's attendance at Christmas
services here and his words as a pilgrim underlined how far Russia
has moved in the past decade to restore Orthodoxy after decades of
Communist suppression.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the year 2000 of Christianity, I find myself in the Holy
Land for the first time,'' Yeltsin said. ``I am glad to see that we
have made our influence felt. Of course, we are constantly troubled
by the question of division of countries and churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Next on a schedule that provided copious breaks _ in apparent
acknowledgment of his health problems _ Yeltsin was received by
President Ezer Weizman of Israel with trumpets and an honor guard.
</P>
<P>
   In his official toast, Yeltsin raised a glass to ``the
flourishing of Israel and close cooperation between us,'' assuring
his hosts that the anti-Semitism that thrived for centuries in
Russia and drove millions of its Jews to emigrate to Israel or
elsewhere is no longer so rampant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask anyone in the streets of Moscow or any other city what
their attitude is to Jews, and I'm sure they will say normal, like
any other people,'' Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   But in his toast earlier, Weizman mentioned the troubled history
of Jews in Russia, singling out Sharansky, a former Soviet
dissident who is now Israel's interior minister. Sharansky sat
across the table from Yeltsin at the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky said both Israel and Russia faced a threat from
Islamic fundamentalism. But he echoed Western criticism that the
Chechnya war is making civilians suffer. ``It is very dangerous to
turn the struggle against terrorism into a struggle against a whole
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin predicted a swift end to the Chechnya conflict. ``In
another month we will finish off the terrorists,'' he said of the
rebels in Grozny, the Chechen capital. ``We are not fighting the
civilian population.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, Yeltsin hugged and held hands with Yasser Arafat,
the Palestinian leader, and promised that ``Russia will do
everything it can so that full peace and concord can be
established'' in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news agency quoted him as saying that Russia
remained committed to ``helping Palestine achieve statehood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor S. Ivanov, who is traveling
with Yeltsin, told reporters earlier that Russia planned to be host
to talks between the Arab states and Israel next month on issues
like arms control, economic development, water and the environment.
The talks have been suspended for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who is accompanied by his wife, two daughters and a
granddaughter, attended a Christmas Eve service on Thursday night
at the Russian Orthodox Cathedral of the Holy Trinity in Jerusalem.
He was scheduled to attend a Christmas service on Friday at the
Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem before returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter how he was adjusting to life as a private
citizen, Yeltsin replied, ``Gradually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
