<HEADLINE>
TUNING IN THE COMPUTER: ONE VIEWER'S GUIDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BACKSLASH-WEB) 
(af) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some sites I visited last weekend while trying to
follow football without benefit of television.
</P>
<P>
   _ NFL.com Scrolling text play-by-play, great statistics. Alas,
the site sometimes freezes up. The National Football League says
680,000 mostly male users joined me there.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.raiders.com The Oakland Raiders site. As with many team
sites, it offers stats, merchandise for sale, still photographs of
game in progress and audio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ http://espn.go.com/ncf/bowls99/rose/index.html Statistics,
in-depth analysis and video replays that my apparently outdated
browser could not display.
</P>
<P>
   _ http://fullcoverage.yahoo.com/Full_Coverage/Local/ &QL; 
Stanford_in_Rose_Bowl/ Yahoo's Rose Bowl coverage. Much news about
the game, but the site misses some important details. Late last
week, it still said that Stanford's All-American receiver, Troy
Walters, missed the game because of injury. He played.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.cnnsi.com/football/college/scoreboards/today.html Game
previews, recaps and box scores, with score updates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8790 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BACKSLASH-WEB-$ADV09-     01-06 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSLASH-WEB-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT QUITE READY FOR THE BIG LEAGUES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BACKSLASH-WEBSITES) 
(af) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With its bonanza of hard-fought bowl games and
National Football League rivalries, last weekend was one of the
most sacred in all of sports. In my home, the games set the stage
for an epic battle between appliances.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and family hunkered down on the couch with mounds of
guacamole to watch the action unfold on a 27-inch television. I
retired to the home office, logged onto the Internet and vowed to
follow the games on various sports Web sites. For a snack, I
countered with spinach sour cream dip.
</P>
<P>
   The question at hand was this: Can an upstart medium like the
Internet compete against the wily old veteran TV for the hearts and
minds of sports fans? As it turns out, the question is not
academic. Across the world, growing millions of rabid fans are
logging onto computers to get text and audio updates of games,
particularly when they are precluded from watching on TV by prickly
obstacles like day jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But when a TV is readily available, enthusiasm for the Web is
about as warm as a fan on a January day at Giants Stadium wearing
only wool socks. ``That's idiotic,'' a friend said when I asked him
to abandon the TV coverage of the Rose Bowl and join me
keyboard-side for spinach dip. ``I'd rather watch two terrible
teams on TV than read play-by-play of my favorite teams on the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Idiotic? I countered that my appliance could out-process his
television (italics)and(end italics) his mother's television, but
the fact is that he pretty much had me dead to rights. When it
comes to sports, TV does offer one major advantage: you can
actually see the game. On the Internet, you have to read it.
</P>
<P>
   The more primitive sites offer only updated scores, while the
more elaborate sites offer scrolling play-by-play text and
sometimes live broadcasts. The experience is like reading a
constantly updating newspaper, accompanied by a radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not exactly a substitute for watching great
athleticism and drama _ any more than you'd want to skip Whitney
Houston's rendition of ``The Star Spangled Banner'' for a silent
reading of the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Net has its advantages, too, and in the spirit of
competition, I sought to make the most of them. It offers an
all-you-can-eat buffet of sports trivia, which fans can ingest like
nachos with cheese. There are statistics and copious background on
players and teams. In the days leading up to the Rose Bowl, I
learned during the game, the Wisconsin Badgers met with the actor
Henry Winkler at practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, did you guys hear about the Fonz?'' I asked, proudly
emerging from my home office with my new-found revelation. A cheer
erupted, but not for Winkler.
</P>
<P>
   It was for Ron Dayne, the Wisconsin running back, who had just
made a great run. I sat down on the sofa to watch a replay, and I
didn't leave. Television 1, Internet 0.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I vowed to stick with the Internet for the NFL
games. When a friend called to invite me to a sports bar to watch
the Philadelphia Eagles play the St. Louis Rams, I countered by
asking him to watch on NFL.com. ``I'd actually like to
(italics)see(end italics) them lose,'' he said, ever the Eagles
fan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Net offered one advantage here. Because the Eagles game
was not on a network TV station, he had to find a bar where it was
shown by satellite. I could remain at home in sports fan heaven _
wearing only a light film of snack foods and wool socks. Internet
1, Television 1.
</P>
<P>
   As the day progressed, I wound up enjoying another advantage of
computer-based sports viewing. I managed to get some work done
while listening to the thrilling Oakland-Kansas City overtime game
in audio and reading three other games in separate browser windows.
</P>
<P>
   One persistent problem was that the play-by-play updates would
simply quit working at times, so I would have to hit refresh, or
log off the Internet and on again. Eventually, I head-butted my
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I concluded that the Internet simply isn't ready to
play in the big leagues. It's a stopgap, a snack, something to tide
over the drooling sports fan who can't find a TV to belly up to.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Internet informed me of a long pass play or great
defensive stand, it was all I could do to stop myself from
drooling, heading to the tube and watching the replay.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there is a bigger picture. ``It's a beautiful day.
You really shouldn't waste it staring at that screen,'' declared my
mother, who was in town for the holidays and tired of seeing me
sitting at my computer. Well, I countered, what if I watch the TV
instead?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she sighed, ``not that screen either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
