<SLUG> BC-SHELLEY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hotel sued for mishandling valuable Shelley piece
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Percy Bysshe Shelley, the 19th-century
English poet, was well acquainted with the ravages of time on human
handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   But he probably imagined a more romantic demise for his own
writings than having them lost in the shuffle at a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in February 1998 to a ``rare manuscript
letter'' written by Shelley, a lawsuit filed Thursday claims. The
suit, filed by insurer Lloyd's of London in Palm Beach County
Circuit Court, says that the Sheraton West Palm Beach botched the
delivery of a $40,000 Shelley manuscript to a British book dealer
in town for a book fair.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, the manuscript was sent by Federal
Express to Simon Finch at the Sheraton from Finch's London office.
Finch wasn't told of its arrival before he checked out. Later, a
Finch employee was told ``a bell hop had delivered the package to
an unaccompanied minor child'' who checked into the room Finch had
left, the suit says. The child's mother denied knowledge of the
package.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd's reimbursed Finch for the lost letter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheraton's manager and representatives of the hotel's
corporate parent couldn't be reached late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley, who with other Romantic poets lyricized loss, wrote in
the sonnet ``Ozymandias'' of a traveler coming upon the statue of a
king with an inscription proudly imploring, ``Look upon my works,
ye Mighty, and despair!''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the traveler finds, the statue is in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Shelley: ``Nothing beside remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
