<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DRYEL-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRY CLEANING: SHOULD YOU TRY THIS AT HOME? 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BIZ-DRYEL-REACT) 
(af) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some men watch football. Others putter around in the garage or
clean their guns. I do laundry. It's relaxing. Orderly. And I don't
trust anyone else to do it.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my excitement upon hearing about Dryel, the new
at-home dry-cleaning product from Procter &AMP; Gamble. No more broken
shirt buttons! Dry-cleaning ``in the comfort of your own home,'' as
the product's literature boasts. A neatnik's dream. Or so I
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Dryel's two-pronged marketing strategy, including a 275-mall
tour, appeared to be aimed at people like me: impecunious control
freaks. A starter kit _ I'll get to what's in there in a second _
goes for about $10. And the brochure says Dryel ends up costing
about $1 a garment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just so you understand my madness, or in case you share it,
I used to trudge down the stairwell of my old fifth-floor walk-up,
out the door, then down into the dank basement of the building next
door to load my quarters into the washer and dryer. I also ironed.
</P>
<P>
   I've relented somewhat since then. A housekeeper does my laundry
once a week, sometimes without destroying anything. She irons my
shirts, because I'm too cheap and lazy to take them to the dry
cleaner across the street. But if I could get the dry-clean effect
for next to nothing myself, without excessive angst, I would. That
would be the Dryel test.
</P>
<P>
   I selected four garments _ all my girlfriend's, of course. (You
think I was going to risk my own clothes?) They were of different
fabrics and were, as Tolstoy might have said, dirty in different
ways. The laundry list:
</P>
<P>
   _ One pair of wool pants, with a light spot.
</P>
<P>
   _ One cashmere sweater, in need of freshening.
</P>
<P>
   _ One pink Ultrasuede skirt, lightly soiled.
</P>
<P>
   _ One pair cotton-linen pants, violently soiled with ketchup,
chocolate and olive oil. (Don't ask.)
</P>
<P>
   Four items are the recommended maximum for the big white plastic
Dryel bag, which eventually goes into the dryer. But before putting
the stuff into the bag, you're supposed to treat any stains with
the bottle of cleaning fluid and one of the four absorbent pads
that come in the $10 starter kit.
</P>
<P>
   I obeyed the recommended stain-removal technique: Place the
CD-sized pad under the fabric, behind the stain. Then ``erase'' the
stain by rubbing the fluid from the bottle's nozzle over it, moving
from the outside of the stain in. Once the spot is gone, you put
the clothes in the bag _ along with a treated moisturized cloth
that feels like a Wet-Nap _ and they get clean in the dryer.
Theoretically.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions say to keep rubbing the fluid on the stain
until it's gone. Well, the pads did get mildly discolored; they had
clearly absorbed something. But the problem with this system is
that once you've soaked the fabric with the fluid, you can tell
only that it's wet, not if it's dirty or clean.
</P>
<P>
   On faith that I had done enough rubbing, I threw the two pairs
of pants into the bag. I didn't treat the skirt, which had more
diffuse dirt with no one particular stain, or the cashmere sweater,
which just needed freshening.
</P>
<P>
   The Dryel literature tells you that it is ``not a substitute for
dry cleaning.'' Nor, we are told, should Dryel be expected to fix
``harsh stains,'' like blood or ink. But I would soon find that
ketchup, chocolate and oil seemed to be problems, too.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the clothes for the alotted half-hour in the
commercial dryer at the end of the hall in my current apartment
building, I pulled out the bag and ripped open the Velcro seal. The
clothes were hot.
</P>
<P>
   Clean? Not exactly. The gray wool pants still had that light
spot. The pink Ultrasuede skirt was only slightly cleaner. The
sweater smelled nice. The gray cotton-linen pants were still a
disaster. I took them to the dry cleaner across the street. They
came back spotless.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I wasn't doing it right, or expected too much, but I felt
as if I had spent the better part of an hour getting my clothes
smelling like fabric softener. The plastic bags can be reused 20
times, but the thought of just one more use filled even a laundry
fanatic like me with alternating feelings of dread and boredom.
</P>
<P>
   I asked my girlfriend, who has sent many a dry cleaner's
children to college, for her thoughts on the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disrespectful to your better clothes to just throw them
in the dryer,'' she said. ``You send them to the dry cleaner
rumpled and soiled and they come back like new, wrapped in plastic
and somewhat fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to do it myself was degrading, she said. The magic of the
dry cleaner, she believes, is an art that no mortal should attempt:
``It's a mystery you shouldn't try to solve.''
</P>
<P>
   After my own doomed experiment to unravel that mystery, I think
she may be right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
