<HEADER>
A8799 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV09-NYT     01-06 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EXODUS OF THE RISK TAKERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERT E. ABUEVA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend from my days at a big company that makes beauty care
products recently left to become vice president for marketing at a
start-up that sells luxury items on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Her departure sent shock waves through headquarters. She had
been seen as having high potential. Everyone knew that she was
talented, and she led the company's most promising new-product
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Her success in a traditional corporate environment was
attributable to her mix of common sense, strategic thinking,
political savvy and ability to drive a project timetable.
</P>
<P>
   And it was those skills that eventually led her to the dot-com
world. She was creative, and she was not afraid of risk.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, risk! That word was starting to get her colleagues down at
the beauty products maker. The company, it seemed, was no longer
taking the kinds of risks it had just four years ago, when the
bottom line was soaring. Now, it was overreacting to retailers'
demands, slashing advertising budgets and delaying product
introductions, and its future with its corporate parent was not as
secure as it once had been.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend recently left his job at a direct-marketing music
retailer. He had many reasons for the move, the most notable being
the company's unwillingness to take a risk on the Canadian market.
He and his team had developed what they thought was a foolproof
strategy, but it was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was able to take his belief in this market to the
online arm of a large music retailer; he became president and chief
executive of the business, whose marketing is widely regarded as
among the most innovative in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably hundreds of other stories about people who
have jumped corporate ships in favor of start-up rafts. These
people are the least risk-averse of the risk takers; their new jobs
may mean lower salaries, but also the far greater potential of
initial stock offerings. Yet for many of them, the biggest carrot
may be an open door to taking chances, building something and
making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both of my friends face uncertain futures. Stock
offerings may never happen at their new companies, and there are a
million potential reasons for failure. The rest of us, however,
have little reason to feel smug.
</P>
<P>
   The draining of innovative people is creating a vacuum in
traditional corporate America that is increasingly difficult to
fill with the people who remain _ people who are more effective in
structured, layered and, yes, less risky settings where they don't
mind being told what to do as long as the direct-deposit stubs keep
rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   While such employees may be brilliant at their work, they are
also shackled to their comfort zones and aren't likely to push
their companies aggressively into new territory.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of risk takers is putting some fixtures of
American industry at risk of becoming mired in the same type of
inertia that once hobbled Detroit in the face of nimble competition
from automakers in Japan. This time, however, the competition is as
likely to come from risk takers at home as from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   It has been widely reported in the news media that many
established companies couldn't fill their recruiting rosters in
1999, as record numbers of business school graduates bypassed them
to jump into fledgling dot-coms, sometimes of their own design.
Undergraduates, meanwhile, were being wooed into entry-level jobs
with unheard-of compensation packages. Overwhelmingly, these
recruits were essentially turned off by what they perceived as an
inherent lack of risk-taking among monolithic corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The situation calls for fundamental changes in the way we manage
risk. And the solutions must be free of the corporate bugaboos that
seem to be souring a generation of executives on corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   We need to bring real risk back into the traditional corporate
equation by relaxing profit margins and recalibrating Wall Street
expectations of performance. Innovation is meant to be messy, not
sterile. We should encourage the risk taker and allow room for
mistakes _ or consider going the way of vinyl LPs.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I am still a comma in this dot-com world. But I am
willing to take on some risk and have just reserved a few Web
domains for myself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jobert E. Abueva is on a writing sabbatical from his position as
an international marketer. Submit your account of struggling or
succeeding as a worker, consumer, investor or entrepreneur to My
Money, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036, or by e-mail to &QL; 
mymoney(AT)nytimes.com. All submissions become the property of The
Times. They may be edited and may be republished in any medium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
