<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLAGFIGHT07-COX     01-06 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAGFIGHT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flag fight: Activists converge on S.C. capital
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ South Carolina's fight over the Confederate flag is
drawing activists on both sides of the issue to the state Capitol
in Columbia this weekend in a clash of symbols that threatens to
spill into other Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest gathering yet in support of the Rebel battle flag
atop the Statehouse, more than 2,000 heritage group members,
including several hundred Georgians, begin arriving today. On
Saturday, during a parade of re-enactors in Confederate gray, 200
South Carolina NAACP leaders will assemble in Columbia to review
plans for intensifying economic sanctions against South Carolina
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Elijah Coleman, 58, of Mableton, Ga., among the Sons of
Confederate Veterans traveling to Columbia, said if the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People succeeds in
forcing down the flag, it next would target the Confederate emblem
incorporated into the Georgia and Mississippi state flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to hold the line somewhere. They want to eradicate
all of our heritage,'' Coleman said. ``That is why all of the (old)
Confederacy is so concerned about South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the NAACP has announced no action beyond South
Carolina, and efforts in Georgia and Mississippi to remove the
Confederate emblem have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Groups on both sides of the flag fight hope to get the attention
of the national media corps arriving in Columbia today for a
televised debate among Republican presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of opposing forces on the flag issue also
foreshadows another disruptive legislative session in South
Carolina. As the General Assembly convenes Tuesday, some leaders
fear the flag flap will oveshadow issues such as education and tax
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the potential of being damaging in the sense of
dominating the session,'' said House Speaker David Wilkins
(R-Greenville), and a flag supporter. ``It's my job to make sure
... that this doesn't monopolize or paralyze this session.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joining the tourism boycott New Year's Day, the national NAACP
efforts are intended to pressure the state Legislature to vote to
remove the last Confederate flag to flutter above a Southern state
capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Some influential groups _ the South Carolina Chamber of
Commerce, the state Baptist Convention and University of South
Carolina trustees _ have urged legislators to move the flag,
hoisted in the early 1960s as part of a centennial celebration of
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   But flag backers hope to rally support during this weekend's
events, promoted with radio commercials saying the flag represents
not racism but ``a state with a tradition of independence, an
entrepreneurial spirit that believes economic rewards will follow
hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia barbecue restaurateur Maurice Bessinger, a conservative
Republican who backed the presidential campaign of the late Alabama
Gov. George Wallace, blamed ``the carpetbaggers and turncoat
politicians'' for trying to ``force the flag down.''
</P>
<P>
   In Columbia, the NAACP says it plans no protests of the
Confederate activities. The heritage groups say events will range
from a cemetery reading of the names of Confederate casualities to
a festive barbecue at the state fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side shows any inclination to budge from their
positions. That's despite Gov. Jim Hodge's plea in November for
compromise and a show of mutual respect for the flag.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the rancor appears to be deepening, as the battle
portrays South Carolina as still fighting the Civil War 135 years
after Robert E. Lee's surrender at Appomattox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the flag's elevation, but the flag's meaning that we
are arguing over,'' said Chris Sullivan, chairman of the South
Carolina Heritage Commission, sponsoring the weekend's Confederate
activities. ``It is Pollyannaish to think it is going to be
resolved anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic that we will prevail, but we do not see this
necessarily as short term,'' said Dwight James, executive director
of the South Carolina Conference of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Among the group's initiatives to sway public opinion is a
Statehouse parade and rally on Martin Luther King Jr. Day on Jan.
17. James said a state NAACP boycott of South Carolina tourism had
cost the state more than $40 million in conventions and other such
business since it was launched last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage officials dispute that the boycott has taken much of an
economic toll. They also questioned whether the NAACP's forthcoming
efforts to write letters and othewise advise convention groups to
avoid South Carolina will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer (the boycott) goes on, the more apparent it becomes
that their boycott is weightless,'' Sullivan said. ``South
Carolina's economy is booming.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers returning for next week's start to the legislative
session worry the flag issue could create a logjam _ especially in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the governor is optimistic that there could be
a compromise,'' said Nina Brook, Hodges' press secretary. Hodges
``continues to talk to people. But it is doubtful that in a week
there would be a significant solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts and legislators say Wilkins holds the key to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly the issue everyone wants to talk about,'' said
Wilkins, whose strength in his own party faded a bit last session
when Republicans blamed the speaker for letting Hodges and other
Democrats push their agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue won't educate one child, it won't pave one mile of
road, it won't immunize one kid,'' he said. ``There are other
important issues of health care and tax relief. ... We need to stay
focused on budget matters.'' House Minority Leader Gilda
Cobb-Hunter (D-Orangeburg), a social worker and a member of the
Legislative Black Caucus, is among those who says progress won't be
made until Wilkins and other House Republicans compromise. With the
start of each legislative day, Cobb-Hunter refuses to join other
lawmakers in facing a stand of flags at the end of the chamber _
including the Confederate battle flag. Instead, she turns and says
the pledge of allegiance to a small U.S. flag and a state flag
she's placed on her desk on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Like many lawmakers, she professes optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is movement,'' Cobb-Hunter said. ``All of that
has occurred behind the scenes. I think the atmosphere is
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Republican constituencies _ including the state
Baptist Convention and the state Chamber of Commerce _have called
for compromise. Some large companies, like tire giant Michelin,
with headquarters in Greenville, have lobbied to remove the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has galvanized the business community,'' Cobb-Hunter
said, ``and everybody's going to be competing (in election season)
for that business money. This is bottom-line economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
