<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LUCENT-WARNING-NYT &LR;      01-06 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT STOCK FALLS AFTER WARNING ON EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing a week of Wall Street disappointments,
Lucent Technologies Inc., the maker of telephone equipment, said
Thursday that its first-quarter sales and earnings would fall well
short of analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's troubles, which analysts insisted Thursday were
primarily confined to the company, are expected to spark a further
selloff in technology stocks on Friday. Lucent issued its earnings
warning after the New York Stock Exchange had closed Thursday, but
investors still rushed to sell their shares.
</P>
<P>
   After closing down $4 at $69, Lucent's stock plunged 24.7
percent, or $17, in after-market trading. Other technology stocks
were also caught in the down draft. Shares of Cisco Systems closed
at $100, but fell 5 percent, or $5.25 a share, to $94.75 in
after-hours trading. Nortel Networks stock dropped 8.4 percent, or
$7.125 a share, in after-hours trading after closing earlier at
$85.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said that they were surprised that Lucent's
earnings would be weaker than expected. Earlier this week,
Amazon.com, the popular online bookseller, warned that its losses
would be greater than previously thought. Lucent's setback was
considered a more serious problem because technology stocks have
been the market's big gainers during the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that Lucent not meeting its earnings
expectations will create some negative psychology in the market,''
said Eric Buck, a vice president at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
``Lucent is the bellwether stock for technology. This may create an
excellent buying opportunity in the tech stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Lucent, which is based in Murray Hill,
N.J., to earn 54 cents a share in its first quarter. The company
said Thursday that it would earn between 36 cents and 39 cents a
share, at least an 18.7 percent drop from the 48 cents it earned in
the comparable quarter a year ago. The company also said that its
revenue would be around $9.9 billion, well below the $11 billion
that analysts had forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent blamed its financial woes on several factors. The company
said that it could not keep up with customer demand for its
80-channel optical system, which is used in long distance networks.
As a result, many of Lucent's customers bought similar equipment
from its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said that its software revenue was lower than
expected because customers had begun to buy products throughout the
year, instead of primarily in December. Adding to those ills,
Lucent said that the costs of introducing new products had lowered
its gross margins.
</P>
<P>
   While those problems were troublesome, analysts believed
Lucent's financial ills had been caused primarily by the company's
push to grow too fast. News reports had begun to surface last fall
that Lucent used several unusual accounting tactics to stretch its
earnings. Lucent's methods were legal, and most analysts had
nothing but praise for the company's earnings gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people who followed Lucent long-term, the earnings
announcement was a surprise,'' said Greg Geiling, an analyst at
J.P. Morgan Securities. ``Some there had been some signs of it.
Lucent had done some pretty heavy discounting on their pricing in
September.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent and Nortel have been involved in a tight race to control
the fiber optic market. Analysts said Thursday that Nortel's sales
of fiber optic systems were growing faster than Lucent's, which may
also have contributed to the company's shortfall in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between the two companies remains intense.
Shortly after Lucent warned investors about its earnings, Nortel
released a statement that reaffirmed its expectations for a strong
performance.
</P>
<P>
   John Roth, Nortel's chief executive officer, said that the
company was ``extremely positive'' on its outlook for 2000. Nortel,
which is based in Brampton, Ontario, said that it expected its
revenues for last year to be about $22 billion, while earnings per
share from operations should grow 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were confident Thursday that Lucent's problems would
not appear in the entire telecommunications industry. Regardless of
Lucent's earnings setbacks, the company has been a sound performer.
Its shares increased 31 percent last year, while its market cap
swelled beyond $150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent simply tried to grow to fast, and it came back to haunt
them,'' said Steven Levy, a telecommunications analyst with Lehman
Brothers. ``This is not a mortal wound for Lucent. But it will take
them some time to build back their credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent was spun off from AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
