<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8812 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV0     01-06 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFANGING THE GREAT INFLATIONARY FORCES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of spot oil price is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When oil prices double or triple in less than a year, that is a
momentous event in America. Or at least it once was. The stock
market would plunge. The economy would slow, or fall into
recession. Presidents wearing sweaters would ask the public to turn
thermostats down. And the inflation rate would rise alarmingly.
</P>
<P>
   All this was standard in the 1970s and 1980s, but no longer. Oil
has quietly lost its hold on the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like an epitaph, let me soften it. Petroleum
prices, which have more than doubled since last March, still have a
little clout. Gasoline prices are higher; so is heating oil. Cargo
rates and some airline fares have gone up.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index itself is rising at a 2.6 percent
annual rate, up from 2.1 percent last spring. Oil, directly or
indirectly, accounts for all of the rise.
</P>
<P>
   But 2.6 percent is pretty mild, and crude oil now appears to be
edging down from its November peak of $28 a barrel. ``We have
already seen the worst of the inflationary impact, unless you think
oil prices are going to double again, which no one does,'' said
Davids Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a
forecasting service. Clearly, one of the great inflationary forces
in America is no longer performing up to its old standard.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are two others. One is empty shelves. Consumers are
buying everything in sight, but no shortages have developed to
drive up prices. There always seems to be more available, from
abroad if not from domestic suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Workers, on the other hand, are in short supply. But instead of
demanding higher wages, forcing companies to raise prices to cover
higher labor costs, workers are settling for very small raises. The
old militancy is gone, wrung out of the work force through 20 years
of union setbacks, downsizing and corporate migration to cheaper
labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder is that none of this seems to lessen the concern
about inflation on Wall Street or at the Federal Reserve. Bond
traders and policy makers are bracing for an upswing in inflation
any day now. An overly robust economy, they say, makes higher
inflation inevitable, and in anticipation they are gradually
pushing up interest rates, a tactic that endangers the economy. Oil
has been their latest concern. Only lately have they focused on why
a doubling in petroleum prices has lost its kick.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason is that oil plays a shrinking role in the
economy. These days, spending on oil products is equal to only 3
percent of gross domestic product, which is the total dollar value
of all of the nation's output of goods and services. That 3 percent
share is down from 8.7 percent in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And oil consumption, currently 19.9 million barrels a day, is
barely above the 18.8 million recorded in 1978. ``That, in essence,
is why oil does not have the impact on the Consumer Price Index
that it once did,'' said Larry Goldstein, president of the
Petroleum Industry Research Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation plays a role. Americans are driving more, but their
autos also get more miles to the gallon, even allowing for
gas-guzzling sport utility vehicles. Gasoline prices jumped sharply
last year, as every driver knows, but the outlay for gasoline comes
to only 3 cents of every dollar spent, down from 6 cents in 1980,
according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, which compiles the
Consumer Price Index. That 3 cents is up only marginally from the
2.5 cents spent on gasoline a year ago, just before the jump in oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, natural gas has become a big substitute for oil _ not
only in the heating of homes, but also as a raw material for
petrochemical products like plastics and as fuel for electric power
generation. Natural-gas prices also rose last year, but only by 50
percent, not 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The nation gets almost all its natural gas from within the
country or from Canada, while crude oil is a global commodity whose
production is subject to quota restrictions imposed by OPEC. By
limiting supply, quotas can drive up oil prices, as they did in
1999 _ to $25 a barrel today from less than $12 last February.
</P>
<P>
   Against a 27-year backdrop, $25 is not so startling. All of the
increase only retraces ground lost since January 1997. And oil
prices today, even at $25, are below their levels through most of
the 1970s and '80s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell all this to Wall Street traders and Federal Reserve policy
makers and they nod in agreement. They know the changes as well as
anyone. But they still look anxiously toward the horizon, expecting
the arrival of the old inflationary triumvirate _ shortages, wage
pressures and oil shock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
