<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JAN. 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CUBA-BOY-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 3,
about Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old boy rescued off Florida on
Nov. 25 while fleeing Cuba in a crowded boat, misstated the number
of people on the boat who died. (Similar errors occurred on Dec. 5,
9, 12, 13, 17, 18, 20, 23 and 31.) The Coast Guard says the number
was 10, including Elian's mother.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LYNTON-AOL-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Jan. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Jan. 5,
about the resignation of the publishing executive Michael Lynton
referred to his company incorrectly. He was chief executive of the
Penguin Group, the worldwide consumer publishing arm of Pearson's;
Penguin Putnam is the group's United States division.
</P>
<P>
   BC-UNITED-WAY-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Jan. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Jan. 4,
about a compensation claim by the former president of the United
Way of America misspelled part of the name of the law firm
representing him. It is Falcone, Houdek &AMP; Curd, not Flacone.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GRAMMIES-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Jan. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Jan. 4,
about nominations for the Grammy Awards misstated the year of a
previous award to one nominee. Carlos Santana, whose band led the
nominations with 10, won an individual Grammy for best rock
instrumental in 1988, not 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
