<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: re-works top to updates with briefing following Clinton
meetings; picks up 18th graf, begins xxx 'Albright's decision ....
'
 &HT;    CLINTON REJOINS, SEEKS TO JUMPSTART SLOW-MOVING NEGOTIATIONS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ For the third time in four days,
President Clinton journeyed Thursday to this rural village to try
to jump-start a staggering round of Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   In closed-door sessions stretching deep into the night, Clinton
met first with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and then,
separately, with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions apparently remained high, however, between the two
Middle East negotiators, who have held face-to-face talks just
once, and then for only one hour, since negotiations opened here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for ways to accelerate the pace,'' State
Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters. ``That doesn't
mean that nothing is happening, but it just means that we'd like to
do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said from the outset the Israeli-Syrian
peace talks would be tough going.
</P>
<P>
   None predicted, though, that four days into the process the two
sides would be refusing even to allow their technical experts to
bat around the issues of territory and water control near the heart
of five decades of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, two committees set to deal with those matters
had yet to meet. Clinton's mission, in part, appeared to be to try
to break that logjam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes out here for more than the scenery and the lovely
fresh air,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
``He comes here with a purpose. The purpose is to move this
along.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of measured progress _ or at least fervent hope of
some _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has begun compiling a
scorecard to mark whatever give-and-take Barak and Sharaa might
agree to here.
</P>
<P>
   And, hoping to generate additional steam to power the broader
Mideast peace process forward, Albright's office announced that she
would go to Moscow Feb. 1 for a meeting of all the major countries
involved in the quest for peace between Israel and its Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has set those efforts near the center of his foreign
policy agenda. Next month's meeting in Moscow is meant to boost
momentum for a peace process the White House has struggled to
re-invigorate after three years of modest, at best, gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the meeting will be to mark the formal
revival,'' of the process, Rubin said, ``and to resume the work of
the multilateral-track peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   The process groups the United States, Russia, the European
Union, Japan and the central players in the Middle East _ Israel,
Syria and the Palestinians among them.
</P>
<P>
   The group came together shortly after the U.S.-led Allied
victory in the Persian Gulf War set in spin a new dynamic in
Mideast peace talks. By 1993, Israel and the Palestinians had
agreed on a broad framework for peace. The next year, Jordan made
peace with Israel. Against that background, Syria and Israel
entered into talks.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, though, meaningful progress on all fronts ground to a
near standstill amid violence, recriminations and the toll of
decades of bloodshed and mutual mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   The talks here this week between Barak and Sharaa are Clinton's
latest gesture toward advancing the process, in the hope of
brokering a comprehensive set of peace agreements between Israel
and its Arab foes before he leaves office in one more year.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were scheduled to continue here on Friday. Lockhart
said Clinton's schedule was clear to return here then if
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's decision to map out in writing even the smallest
parcels of common ground reached between Barak and Sharaa came a
day after the two sides haggled for some seven hours over Israeli
security demands.
</P>
<P>
   The talks revolve around the terms under which Barak would
return to Syrian control the Golan Heights, strategic territory
Israeli troops seized in 1967 after Syria joined Egypt and Jordan
in attacking the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning the Golan territories, though, Barak is
insisting on a detailed and complex system for ensuring that the
territory can't be used to launch future attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has handed Clinton a wish list of U.S. military assistance
some analysts value at up to $17 billion to help safeguard the
Golan Heights and strengthen Israel's defense forces following any
Israel-Syrian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have declined to discuss the details of the
request, but Israel has sought a wide array of advanced U.S.
military gear in the past, including cruise missiles, AWACS
surveillance aircraft and Apache attack helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be specific, because it is very much a work in
progress,'' Adm. Craig Quigley, a Pentagon spokesman, told
reporters at a news briefing Thursday. ``But it is safe to say we
have had consultations, discussions with the Israelis, as to what
they think might be necessary, if such a peace agreement with Syria
is signed, to ensure their security posture within the Middle
East.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley stressed, though, that the issue isn't whether the
United States would provide substantial military assistance to
Israel as part of a peace accord with Syria, but rather, how much
assistance and in what form.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has said repeatedly that the United States is
committed to that Middle East peace process,'' Quigley said, ``and
that will include substantive commitments of
</P>
<P>
   perhaps items or money or people over a period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
