<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8818 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LINES-TEX     01-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINANCE OF COWBOYS' LINES COULD BE DETERMINING FACTOR AGAINST
VIKINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Way back in the dark ages of the 1900s, before
Minnesota turned the NFL into a game won down the field and on the
edges with electrifying pass catchers such as Randy Moss and Chris
Carter, behemoths in the trenches determined football games.
</P>
<P>
   That smash-mouth football has, for most part, given way to
high-wire football is one reason the throw-back Cowboys (8-8) are
thought to have little chance of beating the Vikings (10-6) in
Sunday's NFC wild-card playoff game at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it's that stark contrast that serves as the basis of
the Cowboys' confidence in pulling an upset.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can give the new-age Vikings trouble, it's the Cowboys
and their old-school trench-war style, they believe. So, while
there's no question the Vikings have the edge on the outside with
Moss and Carter, there's also no discounting the dominance in the
middle the Cowboys showed in the team's first meeting this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of games are still won in the trenches, a lot of
games,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``And I do have a lot of
confidence in both sides of our line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' confidence is highest on offense where their power
running game behind massive left guard Larry Allen (6-foot-3, 326
pounds) and left tackle Flozell Adams (6-7, 335) represents a
physical mismatch for the Vikings' smallish defensive front. That
was certainly the case in the Nov. 8 game, won by the Vikings,
27-17. The Cowboys punished the Vikings unmercifully on the ground
in the first half of that game, a fact that weighs heavily on the
minds of both teams heading into Sunday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys rushed 17 times for 163 yards in the first half,
including 140 by running back Emmitt Smith, whose touchdown runs of
63 and 24 yards powered Dallas to a 17-0 lead. Smith left the game
in the second quarter with a fractured hand. Quarterback Troy
Aikman left the game in third quarter with a concussion. Minnesota
rallied after they left.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings defensive coordinator Foge Fazio, whose defensive front
is keyed by undersized standout tackle John Randle (6-1, 287) is
bracing for a similar assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a big, strong, physical offensive line,'' Fazio
said. ``Their little guys are 6-5, 325. Any time you have a line
like theirs and Emmitt running behind a big, old fullback who's 252
pounds \RRobert Thomas\S, you've got size on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   And how.
</P>
<P>
   Humpty-dumpty tackle Tony Williams (6-1, 292) is the biggest of
the Vikings' starting front four. The two ends, Chris Doleman and
Duane Clemons, weigh in at 287 and 280 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   They are a group of pipsqueaks compared to the Cowboys. Adams
and Allen form arguably the league's most dominant left side, and
the Cowboys' right side consists of tackle Erik Williams (6-6, 311)
and guard Everett McIver (6-5, 325) with 6-2, 265-pound center Mark
Stepnoski in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Cowboys, who employ a similar strategy of having
fast quick defensive linemen, have confidence that they can have
their way with the Vikings' huge offensive front as well.
</P>
<P>
   Again, that outlook is rooted in what transpired during the
early stages of the first meeting. The Cowboys sacked Vikings
quarterback Jeff George three times in the first half and limited
him to four completions for 33 yards on 11 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries and Smith's departure on offense, the
Cowboys altered their strategy and began blitzing more in the
second half. George burned them with touchdown passes to Moss and
Carter in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nobody is forgetting what happened in the first half,
least of all Vikings Pro Bowl left tackle Todd Steussie, who gave
up 21/2 of the Cowboys' four sacks in the game and was penalized
twice.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Cowboys' success was their ability to rotate
defensive linemen with varying styles into the game. Ends Greg
Ellis, Kavika Pittman and tackle Alonzo Spellman lined up at
defensive end opposite Steussie.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who had two sacks, won't be there this time; he is out
for the season with a fractured leg. Rookie Ebenezer Ekuban, who
has had 21/2 sacks in the past two games, is playing well in Ellis'
spot.
</P>
<P>
   And, the Cowboys have tackle Leon Lett, whom coaches believe is
playing his best football of the season. Lett was suspended for the
first eight games and didn't play in the first Cowboys-Vikings
game. He alternates at end on passing downs but he's also part of
what the Cowboys believe is the league's best tackle rotation with
Spellman and Hennings.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman said getting to George is crucial to stopping what the
Vikings do outside with Moss and Carter. He said the defensive
linemen are confident they can do the job, again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel good going into this game,'' Spellman said.
``We like our rotations. That gives them trouble. I think we are
going to do some really good things.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
