<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-BANK-NYT &LR;      01-06 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA WANTS TO REPLACE CENTRAL BANK GOVERNOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia's government has carried a
simmering feud with its central bank governor into the open,
risking the precarious financial footing achieved by the
International Monetary Fund's $43 billion aid package in an attempt
to root out the corrupt remnants of former President Suharto's
34-year regime.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators said this week that President Abdurrahman Wahid had
asked them to exercise their power to replace Bank Indonesia's
Suharto-appointed governor, Sjahril Sabirin. The request came after
a state audit faulted the bank's bookkeeping methods, leaving
enough assets in dispute that both sides are warning that
Indonesia's lender of last resort faces insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, a central bank cannot go bankrupt unless its
government forces it to: the central bank controls the keys to the
mint and can print money, though doing so would undermine the very
value of the money it prints. Calling into question the bank's
soundness, however, risks the same result.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the impact of the dispute on Indonesian financial
markets has been muted. Sabirin said the bank did not face a
shortage of funds despite its predicament. The scandal threatens to
hurt the currency, the rupiah, and raise the cost of bailing out
Indonesia's commercial banks. But some bankers say that removing a
central banker who is seen by many as an obstacle to reforms that
would make the financial system more transparent could help the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A clean sweep of Bank Indonesia could be positive for investor
sentiment,'' said Desmond Supple, a director at Barclays Capital in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   In the crosshairs is Sabirin, a Vanderbilt University graduate
and 30-year Bank Indonesia veteran who is said by bankers to be
resistant to the kind of swift reforms that the newly elected
government wants.
</P>
<P>
   Sabirin owes his job to Suharto, who appointed him governor in
February 1998 after firing his predecessor. Sabirin was
controversial then for his support of a proposal to peg the rupiah
to the value of the dollar, which the IMF adamantly opposed. Since
then, bankers and regulators have accused the central bank of
standing in the way of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency and
of withholding cooperation from international bodies such as the
IMF and from outside auditors. Sabirin and other central bank
officials have denied they are uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   A hindrance to replacing Sabirin is a change in the law that
made the central bank independent of the president in May during
the administration of Suharto's successor B.J. Habibie. However,
the change included provisions for an independent audit, which the
Supreme Audit Agency concluded in early December after two months
of work.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary speaker Akbar Tandjung said Wahid has proposed
replacing Sabirin with one of two deputy governors who are relative
newcomers to the bank. But the decision now rests with Indonesia's
new parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is applying pressure for a quick resolution to the
affair, saying it will include demands for the central bank's
recapitalization and for corrective measures to be applied in a new
letter of intent it is due to sign with Indonesia this month on
resuming emergency loans to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Aid discussions were suspended late last year over another
scandal involving the diversion of bank bailout funds to a company
connected to the former ruling party. That scandal also implicated
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
   In another recent scandal, the bank allegedly bent its own rules
at Suharto's request to lend money to a conglomerate controlled by
one of his friends. The central bank has denied any wrongdoing and
has disputed the new audit, challenging the competence of the
independent Supreme Audit Agency and its consultant, KPMG, to
conduct it.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of auditors' concerns are 164.5 trillion rupiah in
emergency loans that Bank Indonesia doled out in a desperate
attempt to keep banks afloat as depositors withdrew their savings
during the worst of the economic crisis of 1997 and 1998. The
government subsequently took over or closed many of those banks.
The central bank maintains that in doing so the government had
assumed responsibility for repaying a portion of those emergency
loans from Bank Indonesia, a conclusion the audit disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we say we cannot trust the numbers, it implies there is
some false bookkeeping or something else wrong at the bank,'' said
Satrio B. Joedono, the Supreme Audit Agency's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The government has ordered an investigative audit into the
emergency loans. But the central bank warned in a letter to
parliament that the questions the audit had raised could force the
bank to post a loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
