American Museum of Natural History, a diorama painted by J. Perry
Wilson for the Hall of African Mammals portrays a trio of addax, an
oryx and an addra gazelle in the vast red receding plain of the
Libyan desert. They are some of the most elaborate landscape
paintings in the city and some of the most frequently viewed
pictures anywhere, but almost nobody knows who did them or, in a
sense, even seems to notice them when they're staring straight at
them. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
