<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-DEATH-PENALTY-475     01-06 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DEATH-PENALTY-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS IT REVISES DEATH PENALTY LAW, FLORIDA CONSIDERS RACIAL BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The state Legislature, voting overwhelmingly
to replace the electric chair with lethal injection as Florida's
method of execution, paused briefly Thursday to consider the matter
of racial justice. At the initiative of the Black Caucus, the
debate turned from how to execute convicts and how to speed
executions to a discussion of who is being executed on Florida's
death row.
</P>
<P>
   With the legislature meeting in special session to consider the
execution method and Gov. Jeb Bush's proposal to speed up the
appeals process for death row inmates, the caucus, with support
from other Democrats, Thursday proposed an amendment that would
allow convicts to try to show that racial bias played a role in
their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus' amendment, which was modeled after legislation
passed in 1998 by the Kentucky legislature, was later defeated in
both the House and the Senate. ``Justice should be blind, but
evidence shows us that justice may not be colorblind when it comes
to the death penalty,'' said one caucus member, state Rep. Les
Miller, D-Tampa. ``We all know that disproportionately
African-Americans and other minorities are sentenced to death row
much more frequently than whites in Florida. We need to talk about
race.'' Although 12.5 percent of the state's population is black,
about 35 percent of the 368 people on death row are black.
</P>
<P>
   The method of execution was the initial reason for calling the
special session which began Wednesday, but that discussion was
overwhelmed by the heated debate over Bush's accompanying proposal
to expedite the appeals process. With the Supreme Court set to
review whether the state's electric chair constituted cruel and
unusual punishment, the state Senate on Thursday voted unanimously
and the House voted 102-5 to replace the electric chair with death
by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Two highly publicized incidents in which a malfunctioning chair
resulted in particularly gruesome deaths prompted concerns over
protections against cruel and unusual punishment and Florida's
ability to carry out executions competently.
</P>
<P>
   In meeting with the caucus, Bush said he remained skeptical
about contentions that the death penalty is plagued by racial bias,
but he said he would create a commission to study the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts around the country said the caucus' amendment
raised important issues about the role of race in capital cases.
``It's impossible to talk about the death penalty without talking
about race,'' said Elizabeth Semel, the director of the American
Bar Association's Death Penalty Representation Project in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the American Bar Association called for a
halt to executions in 1977, Ms. Semel said, was because of ``the
pervasiveness of racial discrimination in the application of the
death penalty.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In offering the amendment Thursday, Democrats referred to a 1991
study commissioned by the Florida Supreme Court's Racial and Ethnic
Bias Study Commission that showed that people who kill whites are
3.4 times more likely to receive the death sentence than people who
kill blacks. The study was conducted by Professor Michael Radelet,
the chairman of the sociology department at the University of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the death penalty, the race of the victim is
more important than that of the defendant, Radelet said in a
telephone interview Thursday. ``Florida has had 44 executions in
the last 20 years,'' he said. ``In those 20 years, almost half of
all homicide victims were black. But of the 44 executed, only five
were executed for killing blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Caucus members said they were disappointed by the defeat of
their amendment, and by Bush's response to their concerns. ``As an
African-American, I'm sick and tired of being studied,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Victor Crist, R-Temple Terrace, said on the floor that
he did not believe there was racial discrimination in how the death
penalty was imposed. He said of the state's criminal justice
system: ``It's beautiful. It works.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation to switch to lethal injection will be sent to
Bush, who is expected to sign it. Of the 38 states with capital
punishment, Florida is one of only four that require execution by
electrocution. The others are Georgia, Alabama and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush's proposal to speed up the appeals process
prompted an outpouring from all sides of the issue again today.
Republican lawmakers have said that they hope Florida, by moving to
more swiftly execute inmates, can be more like Texas. Texas has
executed more people than any other state since the Supreme Court
allowed the death penalty to resume in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I looked, we were all citizens of the state of
Florida,'' Rep. Stacy Ritter, D-Tamarac, told lawmakers. ``We
should be acting like Floridians, not Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's proposal has been criticized by the editorial
writers of newspapers around the state, including The Miami Herald,
The St. Petersburg Times, The Tampa Tribune and The Fort Lauderdale
Sun Sentinel. In his meeting with the caucus Thursday, Bush
complained about getting ``grief'' in the media for pushing the
death case appeal limits. ``But somebody needs to be standing up
for the families of these victims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers have objected to the hastiness of the
three-day legislative session, which Bush called in early December.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is expected to make its final vote on the
appeals matter on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
