<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-LEE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTED SCIENTIST'S LAWYERS SEEK BETTER ACCESS TO CLASSIFIED
MATERIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Wen Ho Lee have asked a federal court
in New Mexico to ease restrictions on their access to classified
information so they can defend him against charges that he
transferred and copied nuclear secrets from Los Alamos National
Laboratory, where he worked until he was fired in March.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the scientist's lawyers asked for access to
classified material, including the portable computer tapes
recovered from Lee's office. Those tapes include vast amounts of
classified data about U.S. nuclear weapons and have provided the
government with some of its most important evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   At the government's request in December, a federal magistrate
imposed tight restrictions on the release of nuclear secrets in
court in Lee's case. U.S. Magistrate Don Svet in Albuquerque
ordered that all classified information to be used in the case had
to be screened under the Classified Information Procedures Act.
That law was enacted in 1981 to prevent defendants in national
security cases from using the threat of divulging secrets to force
the government to drop its prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate's order remains in effect until Chief U.S.
District Judge John Conway decides whether to alter the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was arrested Dec. 10 and charged in a 59-count indictment
with transferring vast amounts of nuclear data from a classified
computer system at Los Alamos into an unsecure system and then
copying the material onto portable computer tapes. Of the 10
high-volume tapes of classified information that he made, the
government says seven are still missing. Lee has not been charged
with giving the secret information to any unauthorized person or a
foreign country and has not been charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In the motion filed on Wednesday, Lee's lawyers accused the
government of seeking to impose excessively broad limits on their
ability to review classified materials that they might need in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office in Albuquerque,
which is prosecuting the case, said Thursday that the government
had not yet filed a response to the defense motion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to covering classified documents and records, the
defense motion argues that the government is seeking to have the
limits on the use of classified information expanded to cover far
too much information. In the order under classified information
law, the motion said, the government seeks to include
``information, regardless of place of origin, that could reasonably
be believed to contain classified information or that refers or
relates to national security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-ESSAY-2TAKES-     01-06 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-ESSAY-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 HOW TO SAVE A MARRIAGE TO A MUTUAL FUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The (star) word should be replaced with the symbol) 
(af) 
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Telltale signs are everywhere. Your partner no longer excites
you, and you find yourself looking at other, flashier potential
mates. You wonder where the thrill has gone, and fantasize about
whether you'd be happier just going off on your own.
</P>
<P>
   Has the passion gone out of your love affair with mutual funds?
Sounds like it. But if you're a mature investor, you know that what
you have now is not an infatuation, but a long-term commitment to
investing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you realize that one offering is pretty much as good as
the next and have given up the hunt for the super fund. Perhaps you
have hitched your portfolio to a stock index _ thus removing
decision-making from your investments.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you're not alone. Signs of mutual fund fatigue are popping
up everywhere. Indexing, which substitutes a computer and a stock
index for a human stock picker, is getting more and more attention,
despite a recent spate of outperformance by active managers. And
mutual fund advertising has grown more demure.
</P>
<P>
   Once obsessed with trumpeting performance and celebrity fund
managers, fund companies seem to have adopted a lower-key approach,
perhaps in part because so few funds can beat benchmarks like the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index over the long term. (``A wise man
listens to advice,'' counsels Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, citing
the Old Testament in a newspaper advertisement. ``We help you
invest responsibly,'' Fidelity Investments says in another.)
</P>
<P>
   The data on mutual fund inflows also implies disillusionment.
Adjusting for redemptions, cash flows into mutual funds in 1999
were about the same as they were the year before and well below the
inflows of 1997 and 1996, according to the Investment Company
Institute, a fund trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   And while actively managed funds have been kicking up their
heels of late with some market-beating returns, index funds still
reaped 39 percent of the new cash for the first 11 months of 1999,
according to the Financial Research Corp., a mutual fund consulting
firm based in Boston. That compares with just 11 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One factor is revolutionary _ the rise of inexpensive online
investing. Roughly 12 million households have online trading
accounts, and the number is growing. At one time, mutual funds were
the most sensible, cost-effective way to build a diversified equity
portfolio. In the eyes of many investors, the alternative was an
overpriced stockbroker who always seemed to make more money than
they did.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, online investors can achieve reasonable
diversification _ say, a dozen stocks _ at less long-term expense
than if they bought mutual funds. At just a few dollars a trade,
they can buy shares of Wal-Mart Stores, Intel, General Electric and
so forth, then reinvest any dividends and get on with life. But a
fund charges management expenses year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The avid phase of growth for the industry has largely been
exhausted,'' said Avi Nachmany, director of research at Strategic
Insight, a mutual fund consulting firm in New York. He noted that
after growing so fast for so long, mutual funds are now near an
astounding $7 trillion in assets. As he put it, ``You cannot grow
in an exaggerated way when you are so large.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts point to several factors that help explain the
shrinking flow of cash into funds:
</P>
<P>
   _ Investors are spending some of their enormous gains, which is
one of the reasons that the consumer economy keeps booming.
</P>
<P>
   _ People are squirreling away some of their profits in cash.
Some are also nervous about pouring more money into a market that
has already come so far.
</P>
<P>
   _ Because the booming stock market has propelled so many people
beyond their investment goals, they feel less compelled to invest
further.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But something more fundamental is at work, too: People's
irrepressible search for the new, the novel and the untried has
dimmed the attraction of funds, which are now as familiar as an old
shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this means that mutual funds are going away.
On the contrary, they are likely to remain central to the
investment landscape for decades, even if our flaming passion for
them continues to mature into a steady, comfortable attachment.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, mutual funds have given millions of Americans the
courage to invest, helping them to overcome their fear of Wall
Street by letting them entrust their money to well-paid
professionals in nice suits and fancy offices who surely have some
idea what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you forced them to do something else,'' Nachmany says of
many mutual fund investors, ``they'd stay in a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, mutual funds have become something of an investment
comfort zone for people who don't have the knowledge, confidence or
time to invest by themselves. After all, even mediocre equity funds
have outperformed money market funds over the long haul, no matter
how much the average equity fund is lagging behind the S&AMP;P 500
Index.
</P>
<P>
   As for indexing, the religion is likely to keep spreading.
Fidelity recently introduced its Four-in-One Index fund, which
gives investors a simple way to invest in large stocks, small
stocks, foreign stocks and bonds, all passively managed and all
with low management expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Barclays Global Investors, an indexing giant that has
traditionally served mainly institutional investors, plans a
boatload of index offerings aimed at individual investors. And
E(star)Trade, the big online broker, offers some index funds of its
own to customers.
</P>
<P>
   But indexing, sensible though it may be, isn't helping the
mutual fund industry generate sex appeal or excitement. Here is one
conversation you'll probably never hear in a bar:
</P>
<P>
   ``My index fund trailed the S&AMP;P 500 by just four basis points
last quarter,'' one investor crows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah? Well, mine trailed the index by just three basis
points!''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of index funds may be a sign that mutual fund
investors, after an ``I'll conquer the world'' adolescence, are
finally developing realistic expectations _ something that most
grown-ups will tell you is a key to a good marriage. If people
continue to expect 30 percent annual returns from their mutual
funds, you can count on the relationship to end in tears sooner or
later. But with dampened expectations, funds and their investors
can look forward to growing old together.
</P>
<P>
   Another key to an enduring marriage is give and take. In the
future, I suspect, the fund industry is going to have to give a
little more and take a little less. Fees will have to come down _
indeed, there is evidence that they are already headed that way.
And one reality will have to be acknowledged: It's tough to beat
the averages over the long term and silly to pretend otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, suggests the true cornerstone of any good
marriage: honesty. Or, rather, just enough of it. Too much
frankness (like telling investors that fund managers are basically
useless) could drive the average Joe and Jane back to certificates
of deposit, which will only make things worse. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Akst is a novelist and financial journalist. His column
tilting at conventional business wisdom appears the first Sunday of
each month. E-mail: culmoney(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-PERFORM-2TAKE     01-06 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PERFORM-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING THE TECHNOLOGY TSUNAMI TO A ROBUST '99 FINISH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though technology stocks took a drubbing in the first week of
the new year, fund investors fell into two groups throughout 1999:
the have-techs and the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   By loading up on technology stocks, particularly companies with
an Internet component, many fund managers outperformed the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. But, as in 1998, managers who shunned
such hot growth stocks and kept the faith that undervalued
stalwarts of the ``old economy'' would bounce back were generally
not rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Investing abroad, especially in emerging markets, also paid off
in the fourth quarter, but not so handsomely as it had earlier in
the year. On average, international stock funds gained 25.99
percent in the quarter, compared with a return of 18.36 percent for
the average United States diversified stock fund, according to
Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The growth style of investing, as it has for the last five
years, trumped value investing: the average domestic large-cap
growth fund gained 28.05 percent in the quarter, more than
quadruple the 6.01 percent gain of the typical domestic large-cap
value fund, Morningstar said. ``There will be a value market again
someday, but I may not be alive to see it,'' said Scott Cooley, 31,
a Morningstar analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Technology funds again ruled the domestic roost, racking up an
average gain of 61.88 percent for the quarter, according to
Morningstar _ although technology stocks, always volatile, have
been hammered recently. Of the 20 best-performing specialized stock
funds last quarter, all but two had ``technology,'' ``Internet'' or
some variant in their names. Heading the list was PBHG Technology
and Communications, which surged 111.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And technology is providing widespread access to investment
data. That information, in turn, is helping drive money into funds
holding the hottest technology stocks, said Richard Kauffman,
managing director of equity capital markets at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``The Internet has allowed individuals to assess the
good-performing mutual funds and that has tended to concentrate the
cash'' going into them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger you are, the harder it is to get performance,''
Kauffman continued. ``That's part of the reason you've had this
bifurcation in the market toward growth stocks and Internet stocks
and away from everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fund managers are trying to ride the wave. David D. Alger,
chief executive of Fred Alger Management in New York, cranked up
the technology holdings in some of his funds last year and posted
impressive returns. Spectra Fund, a large-cap growth fund that
Alger manages with Dave Hyun, increased its weighting in technology
stocks to 58 percent in October from about 35 percent a year
earlier, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Spectra ended last year up 72.01 percent. Alger Capital
Appreciation Retirement, another fund for which Alger is a
co-manager, made a similar leap into technology and gained 88.73
percent for the year, Morningstar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't tech funds, but we want to own the best
companies, the most exciting companies, the growth companies,''
Hyun said. ``We want to be where the action is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fund buyers shared that sentiment. Robert Adler, president of
AMG Data Services in Arcata, Calif., said investors loaded up on
technology stocks in the second half of 1999 by snapping up shares
of technology funds and aggressive-growth funds. In late December,
he said, cash was pouring into those two categories at a weekly
rate of $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has never happened before,'' said Adler, whose company
tracks fund flows. ``There has never been a focus on any sector the
way it has appeared over the last six months in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In joining the new-technology parade, many investors appear to
have shed all fear of risk, continuing to shift money out of more
conservative funds and pouring it into the riskiest, least
diversified funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bond funds, for example, drew only about 4 cents of every dollar
that went into mutual funds for the year through November, the most
recent data available, down from 34 cents in the corresponding
period of 1998, according to the Financial Research Corp. Through
November, more than $5.6 billion flowed out of tax-free bond funds;
$943 million left government bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal bond funds, on average, lost 1.29 percent in the
quarter and 3.55 percent for the year. The average taxable bond
fund returned just 1.2 percent for the quarter and 1.51 percent for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, there was a phenomenal surge of cash into the
aggressive-growth funds managed by Janus Capital of Denver. More
than $35 billion flowed into Janus's 30 funds in 1999, second only
to about $45 billion that went to the indexing king, the Vanguard
Group, and about 65 percent more than went into Fidelity
Investments, the nation's largest fund company. Total assets in
retail mutual funds at Janus more than doubled last year, to $172
billion.
</P>
<P>
   If one fund best represented mutual fund investing at the end of
the 20th century, it might be Janus Twenty. A concentrated
portfolio laden with fast-rising technology stocks, it has spawned
a raft of imitators. Since 1995, the fund's annual returns have
ranged from 28 percent to 73 percent as its assets have swollen to
more than $31 billion, even though it closed to new investors in
April. It was up 38.35 percent in the fourth quarter, and 64.9
percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It even lost a manager during the spree, when Thomas Marsico
handed the reins to Scott Schoelzel and left to run his own fund
firm, Marsico Capital in Denver. Marsico started a similar fund,
Marsico Focus, which has returned more than 50 percent in each of
its first two years, largely through big bets on technology stocks,
including Qualcomm. The fund already has more than $3.2 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Marsico is starting to swim against the tidal wave into
technology. He has trimmed his Qualcomm stake to less than 8
percent of the Focus portfolio from more than 10 percent in
November. He is now buying shares of Citigroup, Fannie Mae and
Sony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we saw with pharmaceutical stocks in 1991,''
Marsico said of the technology mania. ``When people are this
aggressive about getting into a group, most of the gains have
already been had.''
</P>
<P>
   Concentrated investing _ making relatively big bets on a small
number of stocks _ was not always a winning strategy last year. One
of the fund industry's biggest disappointments was the Sequoia
fund, which had amassed an enviable long-term record by seeking out
undervalued companies. Dragged down by a big stake in Berkshire
Hathaway, the holding company run by Warren E. Buffett, Sequoia
returned just 1.33 percent in the quarter and lost 16.54 percent
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Across the board, value funds lagged behind. Returns for value
funds _ large-cap, midcap and small-cap _ were around 6 percent in
the quarter. The only categories of stock funds that fared worse
were those investing in precious metals, down an average of 11.41
percent; natural resources and real estate, each of which returned
around 0.25 percent, on average; and financial funds, which
returned 5.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The second-best performers among stock funds, behind technology,
were those invested in communications _ up 40.03 percent in the
quarter and 81 percent in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Among international funds, the best-performing categories last
quarter were those that specialized in Latin America, up 38.38
percent on average, and emerging markets, up 34.69 percent. Showing
how much things can change in a year, Lexington Troika Dialog
Russia roared back from one of the worst years any fund has ever
had to post the best return of all international stock funds for
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which holds shares of Russian companies, rose 95.36
percent in the quarter and 159.76 percent in 1999, after losing 83
percent the previous year, when Russia defaulted on debt.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, the top three _ and six of the top 10 _
international stock funds were Japan funds, including two handled
by Nick Edwards, a managing director of Credit Suisse Asset
Management, which acquired Warburg Pincus Asset Management in July.
Those funds, Warburg Pincus Japan Small Co. and Warburg Pincus
Japan Growth, gained 328.66 percent and 266.1 percent,
respectively. ``It was a remarkable year,'' Edwards said. ``All of
us fund managers ought to sit down and have a cold shower.''
</P>
<P>
   While Edwards said he did not expect a repeat performance in
2000, he predicted that Japanese stocks, like Sony, would continue
to benefit from corporate restructuring and an economic recovery.
``What is quite healthy about Japan is there are still a lot of
skeptics out there,'' he said. ``People still love to hate Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversified Asia Pacific stock funds were the second-best
international performers last year, up 89.58 percent on average,
followed by emerging-markets stock funds, at 71.7 percent, and
Latin America stock funds, at 60.63 percent. European stock funds,
up 29.89 percent, also outperformed their American counterparts. up
26.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most big losers among international stock funds specialized in
stocks of gold producers and other metals companies. Worldwide,
precious-metals funds took a big hit in the fourth quarter, losing
11.41 percent on average; they were up just 3.01 percent for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their generally much stronger performance, funds that
invest in foreign stocks drew relatively little notice from
American investors, Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   The intense and narrow focus on domestic technology stocks has a
scary side, he added. ``The question remains, when the market
begins to correct, will focused outflows begin to drive the market
in reverse?''
</P>
<P>
   What is certain, he said, is that fund investors have more and
faster access to information about their investments today than
ever before. ``They're aware of what they've made,'' Adler said,
``and they're aware of the risk of losing what they've made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
