<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accounting Firm Charged With Violating SEC Rules
</P>
<P>
   Most partners of the accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers
violated rules requiring that they not have investments in
companies audited by the firm, the Securities and Exchange
Commission said. As a result, five partners have been dismissed.
The SEC said that 31 of the firm's 43 partners had committed at
least one violation, as had six of the 11 partners responsible for
enforcing the rules requiring that senior employees of accounting
firms have no stake in the companies whose financial reports they
are certifying as independent auditors. Other accounting firms will
be reviewed to see if they have also violated the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Home Sales Rate Fell in November
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said the number of new single-family
homes sold in November fell 7.1 percent, to a seasonally adjusted
annual pace of 865,000 units, which was slower than expected.
Separately, the Labor Department said the number of initial claims
for jobless benefits rose last week. Both are indicators that the
nation's economy may have begun to slow.
</P>
<P>
   Dow and S&AMP;P Up, but Nasdaq Falls
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 130.61 points, to
11,253.26, while the Nasdaq composite index declined 150.41 points,
or 3.88 percent, to 3,727.13, as investors continued to move from
high technology into smokestack and consumer stocks. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 1.34 points, to 1,403.45. The yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond dropped to 6.56 percent, down from 6.62
percent.
</P>
<P>
   December Retail Sales Rose Sharply
</P>
<P>
   Sales at retailers open at least a year increased 5.1 percent in
December, which is likely to mean strong fourth-quarter profits.
Merchants reported that they kept inventories tight and controlled
price cutting, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Earnings Exceed Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers said its fourth-quarter profit quadrupled to
$301 million, or $2.08 a diluted share, surpassing Wall Street
forecasts and helping to reverse a slide in the stock price of
financial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Feud Over Indonesia's Central Bank
</P>
<P>
   An attempt by the Indonesian government to replace the governor
of the country's central bank following an audit has turned into a
public feud that is threatening the country's precarious financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
   Fungicide Found in Nike Jerseys
</P>
<P>
   Several leading retailers in Germany took soccer jerseys made by
Nike off their shelves after televised reports contended they
contain a potentially harmful fungicide used on boat hulls. The
reports claimed that the chemical, tributyltin, or TBT, had been
found in souvenir jerseys made by Nike with the name and logo of
Borussia Dortmund, a popular professional soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines in New Ad Campaign
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines will begin a new ad campaign built around its
name, replacing the ``rising'' theme, which had upset some of its
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs in Japanese Fund
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs and Kyocera, the maker of ceramic packages, are
expected to announce Friday that they will collaborate in an
investment fund to take stakes in Japanese companies. The fund will
combine Goldman's expertise in using its own capital to make
investments and Kyocera's deep pockets and entree to the clubby
world of Japanese business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
