<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     01-06 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROCKY SITUATION IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball commissioner Bud Selig has ordered Atlanta Braves
pitcher John Rocker to undergo psychological testing. Selig may yet
discipline Rocker for making idiotic remarks about minorities and
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   This is a slippery slope. Rocker, in his recent Sports
Illustrated interview, managed to offend virtually every minority
group in this country, but Rocker does not make his living on the
basis of his opinions and it's not against the law to be an
ignorant pig.
</P>
<P>
   ``If saying stupid things was a crime, there would be no talk
radio,'' notes Globe radio-TV critic Howard Manly.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home in Milwaukee Thursday night, Selig said,
``Obviously, I've given this a lot of thought. I'm sensitive about
the ramifications and I understand the ramifications, and I'll make
my future decisions based on what I perceive those ramifications to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, most of you have probably read Rocker's stupid rant in
SI. Lowlights include: ``Imagine having to take the (No.) 7 train
to the ballpark, looking like you're (riding through) Beirut next
to some kid with purple hair next to some queer with AIDS right
next to some dude who just got out of jail for the fourth time next
to some 20-year-old mom with four kids. It's depressing . . . The
biggest thing I don't like about New York are the foreigners. You
can walk an entire block in Times Square and not hear anybody
speaking English. Asians and Koreans and Vietnamese and Indians and
Russians and Spanish people and everything up there. How the hell
did they get in this country?''
</P>
<P>
   He also called a black teammate a ``fat monkey,'' and said,
``How bad are Asian women at driving?''
</P>
<P>
   The article appeared several weeks ago and prompted public
outcry and a limp apology from Rocker (who has since been ordered
to keep quiet by his agents, the Hendricks brothers). Rocker said
he was not a racist. Now he's going to have to prove to baseball
that's he's not crazy, either. Selig is a firm believer in social
responsibility and it appears he wants to punish the pitcher, but
only if Rocker is deemed mentally healthy.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare for a pro athlete _ one not under arrest _ to be
ordered to undergo psychological testing. In 1986, the Red Sox
ordered Oil Can Boyd to be examined by a psychiatrist. Two years
later, when Wade Boggs went on television and told the world he was
addicted to sex, the Can asked, ``Who needs the psychiatrist now?''
</P>
<P>
   There is some disagreement regarding the Players Association's
role in the Rocker edict. The commissioner's release said the order
was issued ``following consultation with the Major League Baseball
Players Association,'' but PA executive Gene Orza said the
organization did not authorize the release.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said, ``There's no question about that (consultation with
the Players Association) and I don't think you'll see any more of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   What now? It's one thing to dump Wil Cordero when he beats his
wife. It's logical to dump Christian Peter when his record of
crimes against women is disclosed. Announcers Jimmy the Greek and
Ben Wright lost their jobs because of comments that were deemed
racist or sexist. But Rocker is not an announcer and he hasn't
committed any crime. Baseball found it difficult to dump Reds owner
Marge Schott for saying that Hitler was a swell guy.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear Rocker needs some help. Sadly, he said things that a
lot of other people think and say in private, but few individuals
are stupid enough to go public with such trash.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have turned the case over to Major League Baseball.
Atlanta team president Stan Kasten said his first inclination was
to release Rocker, but Braves executives met with the pitcher and
said he was extremely contrite. Rocker has reportedly started
calling teammates to apologize. During his years in the minors, he
lived with at least three players who would qualify as
``foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Players Association is also on thin ice. The PA normally
fights all fines and suspensions, but this is a case in which an
association member has offended just about everyone in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, Rocker will be shunned. He should at
least do some serious community service with the disenfranchised.
And maybe he should swallow a 100-mile-per-hour comebacker off the
bat of Sammy Sosa (one of those ``Spanish people'').
</P>
<P>
   Kasten is the son of Nathan Kasten, who was hauled out of his
native Poland in 1939 and ordered to build a concentration camp
called Theresienstadt. He worked in the camps for six years and
carried bodies to the incinerator at Auschwitz. Of the 53 Kastens
taken to camps, Nathan Kasten was the only survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Nathan's son said this about John Rocker:
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time he goes to New York, he needs to take a trip to
the Statue of Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
