<HEADLINE>
NEW HOME, OLD MEMORIES FOR CLINTONS IN CHAPPAQUA
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., Ark., W.Va.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton and her husband, the
president, were up past 1 a.m. unpacking boxes, accepting champagne
from the neighbors, talking about where to hang paintings and not
watching the Democratic presidential debate between Al Gore and
Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a television yet,'' President Clinton said
cheerfully in a joint appearance Thursday with his wife at the foot
of their new Westchester County driveway. ``I had it taped for
me,'' he added. ``I'm going to watch it tonight when I get home.''
</P>
<P>
   So begins America's most watchable commuter marriage. By
``home,'' the president meant the White House, of course, and if he
was a little unfocused about where, exactly, home is supposed to
be, it was perhaps because he had just spent less than 18 hours in
the $1.7 million Dutch colonial that is to be the base for Mrs.
Clinton's campaign for the U.S. Senate. Nonetheless, Clinton said
he would be registering to vote in New York. He now votes in
Arkansas. ``Yeah, I've got a particular interest in the election up
here next year,'' the president said, chuckling. ``So I want to
make sure my vote counts.''
</P>
<P>
   After moving Wednesday evening into the first home of their own
in 17 years, Chappaqua's most-talked-about couple emerged from the
white columns of their front porch at 11:30 a.m. Thursday and
strolled past the rhododendrons and fir trees to meet the
supposedly vicious New York press. But there was exactly one
question about Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's unannounced
opponent, who attacked her this week for accepting so-called
soft-money donations to her campaign. Mrs. Clinton laughed, then
deflected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to talk about our house this morning,'' she said,
and then did, saying that ``it's a lot of fun for us to be able to
do this again for the first time in such a long time,'' and that
even though they worked hard to keep the White House ``in good
shape,'' it is ``different when you are doing it in your own
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Clinton is the most famous Senate candidate in the
country and was standing on what is symbolically and politically
her turf, her husband is still the president, and the first lady
noticeably deferred to him. Clinton did most of the talking, and
also said he had no intentions of joining Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., the
investment banking house in New York City, when his term is up, as
had been reported in Washingtonian magazine. ``I was amazed to see
that in the paper,'' he said. ``No one has even suggested that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons said they were amazed to unpack possessions that
had been in storage for as long as 17 years, and a friend from
Pound Ridge, N.Y., Jill Iscol, who brought over shepherd's pie for
the Clintons' first dinner in their new home, said the two stayed
up late telling stories about the things they unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters: ``We've got a table in there that we
bought shortly after we got married in 1975, that we haven't used
in a long time. So we've had a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons left their house around noon Thursday to head back
to Washington _ the president to attend the Middle East peace talks
in Shepherdstown, W.Va., and Mrs. Clinton to pack up more things at
the White House. Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary,
described the Chappaqua house as at the moment ``semifurnished.''
Mrs. Clinton's campaign, which has been on hold since the Christmas
holidays, is to begin again in New York next week, when the two are
expected to stay in the house again.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the Westchester County Airport, the Clintons
stopped their motorcade near downtown Chappaqua to jump out and
shake hands with the hamlet's volunteer firefighters, who had just
returned from a call and were outside the firehouse to greet them.
When Barry Zezze, the fire commissioner, told the president that he
was going to call the fire department the ``Hill-Billy'' fire
department after the upscale community's new residents, the
president replied, ``There's got to be something hillbilly about
this if I'm going to move here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
