<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-BONDS-2TAKES-ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A TROUBLED YEAR FOR BONDS, A WAY TO PLAY THE GAP IN YIELDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When people in the bond market talk about spread products, they
don't mean peanut butter. They are referring to issues like
corporate and mortgage-backed bonds that consistently yield more
than United States Treasuries of the same maturity. The difference
in yields is the spread, and it exists because these bonds, unlike
Treasuries, are thought to pose a more-than-trivial risk of
default.
</P>
<P>
   Spread products appeal to two kinds of investors: those who want
regular income and those who want to protect their stock-market
gains by shifting capital out of equities. For people in either
category, now may be an especially opportune time to buy bond
funds, experts say, because spreads are relatively wide, making the
bonds especially cheap and high-yielding when compared with
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you buy a spread product, you have time on your side,''
said Ian A. MacKinnon, a managing director at the Vanguard Group
who heads its $135 billion fixed-income funds division. ``For every
day that goes by, you are earning that extra income. You are paid
to wait; the question is: How well are you paid to wait? At this
time, you are paid very well.''
</P>
<P>
   High yields for bonds go hand in hand with low prices, which are
attractive for buyers but disappointing for holders, who took a
beating in 1999 in nearly all categories of bonds. The price of the
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 14.78 percent, according to
Ryan Labs, a New York investment manager, and government bond funds
suffered accordingly, with the average long-maturity fund losing
7.33 percent for the year, according to Morningstar. About the only
bright spot was emerging-market bond funds, which were up 26.21
percent in 1999, Morningstar said.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market sent investors on a wild ride again last week,
with the benchmark 30-year bond losing 1.11 percent in total return
through Thursday, according to Ryan Labs. But the worst may be
over. ``The damage predominately is in the past, not the future,''
MacKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   His view reflects Vanguard's belief that the economy will slow
down this year, because consumers are ``tapped out,'' in his
phrase, and because interest rates are higher than they were a year
ago. He expects further tightening by the Federal Reserve this
year, probably a quarter-point in February and perhaps as much as a
full point for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this outlook is already factored into the bond market,
said William Gross, who manages about $180 billion in bonds for the
Pacific Investment Management Co. In his view, Treasury bond prices
are unlikely to break out of their current trading range, at least
for the next few quarters, leaving yields on the 30-year bond stuck
between 6.25 and 6.75 percent. Yields are unlikely to move higher,
Gross said, because factors like strong productivity, new
technology and globalization will keep inflation in check. But he
believes that they will not fall much below 6.25 percent, either,
as long as the Fed is standing pat or tightening short-term rates.
</P>
<P>
   The implicit floor under Treasury bond yields means that their
prices may have little room to rise soon. So investors who want
positive returns will turn to spread products, Gross predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a range-bound world, when there is not much to be said for
timing or trading,'' Gross said, ``the best thing to do is to go
for the gusto, and get some yield into your portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Spread products are not the first place that many ordinary
investors should turn for yield. Municipal bonds are paying well,
too _ nearly as well as Treasuries before taxes, and much more
afterward. So for taxable accounts, yield-hungry investors would do
well to start with a plentiful helping of municipals, said Eric
Jacobson, fixed-income editor at Morningstar. Spread products are
better suited for tax-deferred accounts like 401(k)s, or for large
bond portfolios that are already well stocked with municipals, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are dangers in straying from the security of Treasury and
insured municipal issues. Meltdowns can occur when adverse news
sends investors into a ``flight to quality,'' as happened in late
1998, when the Russian currency crisis and the near-collapse of
Long Term Capital Management sent shock waves through bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a cataclysmic implosion somewhere _ Russia,
Argentina, the stock market, who knows _ in that type of world,
Treasuries become more dominant,'' Gross said. Given the risks, he
added, buying spread products ``is really a strategy for Goldilocks
_ a steady state economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But buy-and-hold investors who seek yield rather than capital
gains need not take on much risk to do better than Treasuries.
Bonds issued by agencies like the Federal Home Loan Bank; the
Government National Mortgage Association, known as Ginnie Mae, or
the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. (Freddie Mac) yield as much as
two-thirds of a percentage point more than Treasuries and are seen
as only slightly riskier, because of explicit or implied government
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Half of the $1.7 billion Pimco Total Return bond fund, managed
by Gross, is invested in these spread products, compared with about
30 percent for an important barometer of the broad bond market, the
Lehman Brothers Aggregate bond index.
</P>
<P>
   The main danger in agency-issued mortgage-backed securities is
not default, but the possibility that homeowners will refinance the
underlying loans sooner and in greater numbers than expected _ a
distant threat when interest rates are rising.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate bonds are another vehicle for adding yield to a bond
portfolio. A barrage of new issues in early 1999, when rates were
low, flooded the market at a time of little demand, said MacKinnon
at Vanguard. That resulted in wider-than-usual spreads over
Treasuries. Those spreads have since narrowed a bit but remain
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Credit risk is the main danger with these bonds, and not just
among those rated below investment grade, known as junk bonds. Even
the strongest companies can encounter problems that lead agencies
like Moody's Investors Service and Standard &AMP; Poor's to lower their
ratings a bit, causing prices to fall. A faltering economy could
set off a wave of such downgrades.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy that MacKinnon foresees _ one that slows
slightly without slipping into recession _ poses little danger to
corporate bonds, in his view. In fact, he favors the bonds of
relatively vulnerable companies toward the bottom of the investment
grades, which offer high yields with little current credit risk.
</P>
<P>
   Gross also sees corporate bonds as good values. One-fifth of his
portfolio is in corporates, and he especially favors securities
maturing in less than five years whose spreads are almost as wide
as those of their longer-term counterparts, but with less risk.
</P>
<P>
   An A-rated corporate bond maturing in five years yields 1.2
percentage points more than a five-year Treasury note, he said;
extending the maturity to 30 years widens the spread only to 1.35
points.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the economy is steady, funds that buy the better
grades of junk bonds should also be a good bet. Yield spreads have
narrowed a bit lately in this category, too, but they are still
very wide: Merrill Lynch's Master Index of such securities is
yielding 4.5 percentage points more than comparable Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those willing to assume more risk, a high-quality
high-yield fund is a good alternative,'' Gross said. Such funds are
yielding 8.5 percent to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For emerging-markets bonds, which have much in common with
high-yield corporates, his advice is the same: Concentrate on funds
that concentrate on quality. High-yield and emerging-markets bonds
together make up about 6 percent of Pimco Total Return, Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jacobson of Morningstar, the best strategy for
investors interested in pursuing spread products is to buy a
diversified bond fund whose manager has demonstrated a knack for
finding undervalued securities. He says that approach is more
likely to deliver good returns than trying to time the market by
adding funds in specific sectors or repeatedly rebalancing a
portfolio of bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   But how to identify that one great fund to buy? He advises
setting aside the performance of recent quarters and concentrating
instead on long-term track records.
</P>
<P>
   The more speculative stuff is another story. Investors who want
a taste of the highest yields should pursue them separately, he
said, not in a single diversified bond fund. ``It gives you more
control over your risk,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
