<SLUG> BC-LEHMAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN'S NET PROFIT QUADRUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. helped to reverse a slide in
financial stocks Thursday by reporting better-than-expected fiscal
fourth-quarter earnings, powered by a rebound in profit from
trading stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, the fourth-largest investment bank on Wall Street,
reported that its earnings quadrupled to $301 million, or $2.28 a
diluted share, in its fourth quarter, which ended Nov. 30. In the
period a year earlier, when Lehman was recovering from a global
financial crisis that wreaked havoc on bond markets, the firm
earned just $74 million, or 51 cents a diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent results easily exceeded analysts' consensus
expectation of $1.97 a share, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial, which tracks corporate earnings, and gave a lift to
shares of Lehman and other financial companies, which had been
falling this week on concerns about rising interest rates. Shares
of Lehman rose $2.9375, to $72.875, in trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Lehman's results, combined with high levels
of stock trading and underwriting in December, boded well for
coming earnings reports from big securities firms whose financial
years ended Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did have a challenging bond market in the fourth quarter
and what these firms have shown is that they can anticipate adverse
market conditions and make that work in their favor,'' said Richard
Strauss, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the nation's biggest brokerage firm, is
scheduled to report fourth-quarter earnings in a few weeks, along
with Bear Stearns Cos, the investment bank, and PaineWebber Group,
the brokerage firm. Merrill Lynch shares rose $2.75 Thursday, to
$76.375; Bear Stearns gained 50 cents, to $37.9375, and PaineWebber
advanced $1.50, to $36.1875.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most analysts factored in a slowdown'' on Wall Street as the
dawning of the new year approached, said Joan Solotar, an analyst
at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. Instead, she said, activity in
stock trading and underwriting remained strong well into December.
The fees that Merrill Lynch and Bear Stearns took in for
underwriting issues of stock rose about 60 percent in the fourth
quarter from the third quarter, Ms. Solotar said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's per-share earnings last quarter were its best since the
firm was spun off from American Express five years ago. But the
quarter was not the firm's best in terms of net income.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy resulted from Lehman's obligation to pay up to
$50 million of its annual profit to American Express and the Nippon
Life Insurance Co. in dividends on preferred stock they own. Last
year, Lehman set aside $50 million in the second quarter, when it
had record net income of $330 million, and paid it out in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good quarter and a very good year,'' said John
L. Cecil, Lehman's chief financial officer. He said Lehman raised
more money through stock offerings it managed, including 16 initial
public offerings, than it ever had, about $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's net revenue _ revenue minus interest expense _ more
than doubled from a year earlier to $1.41 billion. By far the
biggest contributor was revenue from trading stocks and bonds,
which soared to $623 million, from just $90 million in the fourth
quarter of 1998. Investment banking revenue rose 72 percent, to
$432 million, from $246 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lehman did not rack up the sort of extraordinary numbers
that two bigger investment banks, Goldman Sachs Group and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, reported last month for the same earnings
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are maintaining their market share and when you do that
in a market that is rising as quickly as the investment banking
market is, you're going to have rising revenues,'' Strauss said.
The challenge Lehman faces, he said, is how to maintain its revenue
and profit growth when the Wall Street boom starts to fade.
</P>
<P>
   For now, analysts give high marks to Lehman's chief executive,
Richard Fuld, and his management team for rebuilding a troubled
bond franchise and broadening it into a balanced investment bank.
Last quarter, Lehman's revenue was almost evenly split among its
stock, bond and investment banking businesses.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Cecil said, Lehman plans to build its private equity
business by raising funds from investors to buy stakes in
not-yet-public companies in various industries. Lehman is raising a
fund to invest in early-stage telecommunications companies and is
considering funds that will invest in real estate and distressed
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lehman started investing a $350 million
venture-capital fund. One of its first purchases was about 1.5
million shares in VA Linux Systems, a software company that went
public a month ago. Those shares are now worth more than $250
million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
