<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS' AIDE WELL VERSED IN COWBOYS' PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. _ The Minnesota Viking with the most playoff
experience is a familiar face to the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard Alexander won three Super Bowl rings as Dallas'
receivers coach in the 1990s. Now, leading a group that features
Cris Carter and Randy Moss, he hopes to win another ring and get a
little revenge on the team that fired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that you have to do is, when you change teams, you
completely cut yourself away from another team,'' said Alexander,
who coached the likes of Michael Irvin, Alvin Harper and Kevin
Williams in Dallas for nine years. ``You have to do that. There's
no other way to get around it. You're very competitive toward those
guys. You want to beat them. Actually, there's an extra incentive
to beat them, and they want to beat us just as bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Vikings coaches, including head coach Dennis Green,
Alexander has the most playoff experience. He has coached in 17
postseason games, and he has as many Super Bowl rings as the rest
of the staff combined. Alexander said only one of his players has
seen any of the world championship rings, which he keeps in a
safety deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been there, so he knows what it takes to get that
title,'' said Minnesota's No. 4 receiver, Matthew Hatchette. ``Any
time you have an older guy that's seen it all, you have to take
into consideration what he tells you.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, fired by Dallas after the '97 season, has detached
himself from the Cowboys' organization. But he can't disassociate
himself from Irvin, whom he coached at Miami as well as Dallas.
Irvin has missed most of the season with a neck injury that
threatens his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, I have feelings toward him,''
Alexander said. ``Naturally, you have feelings for Michael because
of the situation that occurred with him. You hate to see that
happen to somebody who's so close to you. You'd like to see him in
the game.'' MOSS GROWS
</P>
<P>
   Publicly chastised by team owner Red McCombs last month after
dropping several routine passes and walking away from a defender
who had made an interception, receiver Randy Moss says he has
matured entering his second postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I'm better,'' Moss said. ``I probably feel the same.
But as far as mental preparation toward my second playoff, I think
I've prepared for it, and hopefully, if the team wants to ride my
shoulders all the way to the Super Bowl, I think I'm going to have
to take that challenge and meet it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss responded to McCombs' criticism by saying the boss had
every right to say what he did, and admitted that he did get bored
sometimes when he wasn't directly involved in the play.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Moss' five catches for 131 yards and two
touchdowns lifted Minnesota over Green Bay, 24-20. His five-catch,
155-yard performance Sunday against Detroit included a 67-yard TD
and helped the Vikings earn a home wild-card game against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Moss is the first Vikings receiver to lead the NFC in yardage
since Ahmad Rashad in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to cover me if you're used to me going down
the sideline,'' Moss said. ``Me catching slants, me catching
hitches, stops, whatever. Now, you've got to cover me all over the
field ... and you don't know what I'm going to do.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Starting middle linebacker Ed McDaniel is expected to play
Sunday despite missing the second half of the regular-season finale
with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Vikings' 40 turnovers are the most of any playoff team,
and their minus-10 on turnover margin is the worst.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only rafter tickets and luxury suites are available for
Sunday's game. Price tag for your own luxury-room-with-a-view? At
least $10,000. Of the suites sold this week, 12-seaters went for
$11,000, 16-seaters for $12,000 and the few 18-seaters for $13,000.
The league takes most of the ticket revenues after a payout of only
$360,000 to the Cowboys and $380,000 to the Vikings. As for the
suites, the league captures half of all the increased rental fees.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
