<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS SECONDARY WARY OF COWBOYS' WEAK PASSING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. _ The resistible force vs. the movable
object.
</P>
<P>
   Something's got to give when the Dallas Cowboys' punchless pass
offense meets the Minnesota Vikings' porous pass defense in
Sunday's NFC wild-card playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' 23rd-ranked passing scheme has been cautiously
redesigned after injuries to receivers Michael Irvin, Ernie Mills
and James McKnight. Don't expect a sympathy card from the Vikings,
who've experienced a seasonlong shakeup in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a game in which he threw for 288 yards against the
New York Giants' backup cornerbacks, Troy Aikman faces a Minnesota
defense that finished 30th against the pass and plans to give
significant playing time to undrafted Anthony Bass, rookie Kenny
Wright and converted receiver Robert Tate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worry about being young, or inexperienced, or
whatever,'' said Bass, who has three career starts. ``This is the
NFL, and people are going to come after us every week. We can't let
those guys or their game plan scare us. We're young, but we can
play. We've been doing a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Only five Minnesota defenders retained their starting spots all
season and the team used a remarkable 30 players on defense, but
the Vikings won eight of their past 10 games. Cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock and strong safety Robert Griffith have anchored the
embattled secondary, with Wright (a fourth-round pick from
Northwestern State) starting at cornerback, Bass (a second-year
player from Bethune-Cookman) starting at free safety and Tate
(originally a receiver drafted in the sixth round in '97) in on
Nickel coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings give up 349 yards per game and finished ranked 27th.
But, considering the personnel carousel, defensive coordinator Foge
Fazio is somewhat satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in September we thought these kids would have very
limited roles, if any at all,'' said Fazio. ``Now, we're getting
ready for the playoffs and we're asking them to grow into men real
fast. It's a little scary, but so far they've done about as well as
we could expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock and Griffith saw Wright take over at cornerback for
Ramos McDonald, and rookie free agent Chris Rogers replace Wright
as the nickel back. It wasn't until early December that Tate beat
out Rogers, and first Antonio Banks, then Bass replaced injured
starter Orlando Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through a lot of stuff around here,'' said starting
middle linebacker Ed McDaniel. ``We had a lot of personnel changes,
but we held up pretty good, and actually we're winning games.
Regardless of where you're ranked at, you've got teams ranked
higher than us and not even in the playoffs. Where are they? I
think they'll be watching us this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright was inserted into the starting lineup because Vikings
coaches believed he was a better tackler than McDonald, who was
benched and later cut. Bass' speed and aggressiveness earned him
playing time over Banks. But it's Tate who symbolizes Minnesota's
travails.
</P>
<P>
   The team's sixth receiver when training camp broke, Tate is now
a major contributor on special teams and in Nickel situations. He
had kickoff returns of 37 and 44 yards last week against Detroit
and, despite wearing a huge bulls-eye, made his first interception.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman exploited the absence of Giants starters Phillippi Sparks
and Jason Sehorn last week, and Tate knows he won't be able to hide
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't \Rthrow at me\S, then something's wrong with
him,'' said Tate, who plays left cornerback when the Vikings play
five defensive backs. ``Anytime a wide receiver moves to DB, you
have to try to test them. If you keep playing your cards right,
they are going to leave you alone sooner or later. I have to be up
to the challenge every time they come my way. I can't come in here
with my head down. I've got to be up to the challenge every play.''
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the strange season: On a field boasting Deion Sanders
and Randy Moss, the key matchup Sunday could come down to Jason
Tucker vs. Robert Tate. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
