<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEOPLESOFT-PEOPLESOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PeopleSoft Shares Soar on Profit Forecast  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
While many of its high-tech brethren helped drag the Nasdaq down
for the third consecutive day, PeopleSoft shares soared yesterday
almost 22 percent after the company said fourth-quarter profits may
top analyst estimates.
<P>
   The Pleasanton maker of business management software expects to
report earnings, including results from recently acquired Vantive
Corp., of 2 to 4 cents per share for the quarter ended December 31.
</P>
<P>
   The average consensus estimate was 2 cents, according to
research firm First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company expects fourth-quarter licensing revenue
for the combined companies to rise 30 to 35 percent over the
previous quarter, a decline in service revenue will largely offset
those increases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street reacted positively to the early estimates as
the company's stock jumped $3.94 yesterday to close at $22.
PeopleSoft Peoplesoft  &LR; expects to release its final earnings
results early next month.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft's forecast is ``an effort to show that they are
holding up the fort in an otherwise tough technology market,'' said
Andrew Roskill, an analyst at Warburg Dillon Read. ``A lot of these
companies are suffering from a Y2K hangover'' and are having a
difficult time coming up with earnings to match last year's stellar
results.
</P>
<P>
   For the same quarter 12 months ago, PeopleSoft posted net income
of $26.1 million (10 cents per share), including a write-off for
research and development. Excluding the write-off, net income was
$40 million (16 cents).
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft's optimistic earnings preview contrasts sharply with
profit warnings issued earlier this week by competitor Baan NV,
which contributed to a drop in its shares as well as those of other
softwaremakers.
</P>
<P>
   Baan, Europe's second-largest maker of business-management
software, saw its stock plummet 47 percent in Amsterdam this week
after the company's chief executive quit, and Baan said it expects
to post a fourth-quarter loss of as much as $250 million, its sixth
straight quarterly loss.
</P>
<P>
   David Gremmels, analyst at SG Cowen Securities in Boston, called
PeopleSoft's fourth quarter figures ``reassuring.'' ``It suggests
that (back-office software) recovery is occurring somewhat sooner
than what some people had expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft, which makes software that automates financial, human
resources and inventory operations, has struggled recently with
management turmoil, a slowdown in sales and increased competition.
Although it is the No. 2 business softwaremaker, PeopleSoft has
lost ground to competitors Oracle Corp., SAP and J.D. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to its problems in the third quarter was the specter of
the Y2K problem, which the company blamed for a sharp decline in
sales. According to PeopleSoft, corporate customers focused time
and money on repairing existing systems rather than purchasing new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   As Y2K concerns have receded, PeopleSoft still has much work
ahead, particularly in integrating Vantive's customer relationship
management software with its own offerings.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft acquired Santa Clara's Vantive on December 31 for
about $599 million, adding what analysts call a critical piece of
the puzzle to its suite of products as more and more clients look
to automate their sales force, call center and field service
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Customer relationship management) was a hole they filled with
Vantive,'' Gremmels said. ``Now they have a full product line; it's
just a question of execution.''
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft said it will take fourth-quarter charges related to
the Vantive acquisition of $50 million to $70 million and gains
from the sale of equity investments of $45 million to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
