r f BC-NORTEL-NORTEL_SFCHRON     01-06 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-NORTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Nortel Buys Promatory for $778 Million  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Promatory Communications Inc., an obscure DSL company in Fremont
with just $1 million in 1999 sales, was sold yesterday to Nortel
Networks for $778 million in stock.
<P>
   The 3-year-old company makes equipment to help telephone
companies deliver high-speed Internet service over conventional
wire phone lines. The hot technology is called digital subscriber
line or DSL. The purchase price includes $73 million contingent on
meeting financial targets.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel, the giant Canadian maker of telephone equipment, said
the deal, expected to be completed in the next two months, will
help it compete against rival Lucent Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Promatory just rolled out its first product in March, but it's
one that phone companies urgently need.
</P>
<P>
   The product, called an Intelligent Multiservice Access System,
allows a traditional copper line to carry multiple voice-telephone
lines and superfast Internet-access line. It typically costs cost
 &LR; $100,000 to $150,000. Nortel executive Steve Schilling estimates
Promatory's sales will exceed $200 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive growth in telephone and Internet traffic has set
off a race among phone-equipment-makers, like Nortel, Lucent and
Cisco, to equip next-generation phone networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good move for Nortel,'' said Shannon Pleasant,
an analyst with Cahners In-Stat Group. ``Alcatel, Cisco and Lucent
... need to be very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent sells a rival DSL product called Stinger, developed by
Ascend Communications Inc. New Jersey's -based  &LR; Lucent bought
Ascend of Alameda for $20 billion last year. Several other
networking-equipment-makers, including Copper Mountain Networks,
Cisco Systems and Alcatel, have also entered the market.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's sale made at least 10 Promatory employees
millionaires, though chief executive Chief Executive  &LR; Roger Dorf
declined to give the exact number. It was founded by four workers,
led by Chief Technology Officer Steve Eich, in 1996. About 85 of
the 100 workers are in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few people use DSL today, but analysts say the number
is about to explode. Pleasant predicts there will be 12 million DSL
subscribers by the end of next year, up from 1.4 million last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, including Pacific Bell, NorthPoint
Communications and Covad Communications, have started offering the
service to Bay Area homes for about $50 per month. And many more
companies are going after the business market.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed Internet access is also available via cable TV lines.
Redwood City's ExciteAtHome is the largest provider of this
service, which is typically 50 times faster than conventional 56K
dial-up modems. ExciteAtHome has about 1 million users nationwide.
But Cahners In-Stat Group predicts DSL will overtake cable modems
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Both cable and DSL promise much faster connections to consumers,
without tying up conventional phone lines. But DSL proponents also
say it will let small businesses carry voice and video.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of buying five phone lines, Promatory marketing vice
president Tim Waters said a small business could handle all the
phone calls on a single DSL line _ for $75 per month _ and let
several computers access the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also benefited outside investors. Promatory The &LR; 
company  &LR; received $47 million in venture capital in three rounds of
fund raising. Investors included Brentwood Venture Capital,
Institutional Venture Partners, Walden International and Generation
Partners. Mitsui &AMP; Co. (USA), Telesoft Partners, Hook Partners and
MeriTech Capital Partners were also investors. Nortel said it plans
to keep the company in Fremont with Dorf running the operation,
though it is already scouting for a larger building in the city to
accommodate future  &LR; growth. Both Nortel and Lucent fell yesterday,
after Lucent warned of slowing sales. Nortel slipped $12.89, to
$77; Lucent closed at $52, down $20.38. After the market closed,
Nortel issued a statement that its sales remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
