<SLUG> BC-BOFA-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 BofA Pressed for Details Of Cutbacks in Workforce  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Responding to reports of accelerated local job cutbacks at Bank of
America, a top San Francisco official is pressing for details about
the retrenchment that the bank has previously refused to make
public.
<P>
   Treasurer Susan Leal wrote BofA Wednesday seeking information
about the elimination of jobs in the city, where more than 9,000
employees worked until North Carolina's NationsBank bought the bank
and took its name 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As one of Bank of America's largest customers in California, I
believe that the City and County of San Francisco deserves and
should receive current information regarding significant reductions
in your workforce or the elimination of business units,'' Leal
wrote in a letter addressed to Connie Beck, BofA's president of
Northern California banking.
</P>
<P>
   Beck called Leal yesterday and was preparing a written response,
a bank representative said. ``They had a good conversation,'' said
spokesman Peter Magnani.
</P>
<P>
   The treasurer's move comes as job cuts stemming from the 1998
takeover of BofA hit home. In the past few months, according to
current and former employees, the bank has eliminated hundreds of
Bay Area positions once needed to run a major international bank,
but now superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second-largest bank has said it expects to
eliminate over the next few years about 10 percent of the 180,000
jobs that existed when the old BofA and NationsBank combined,
either through attrition or layoffs. BofA has never spelled out
when and where those job cuts would take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The context of staffing decisions is companywide,'' said bank
spokesman Magnani. ``We don't talk specific numbers in specific
geographical areas.''
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, the bank projected it would cut 9,464 jobs nationwide,
according to internal planning documents obtained by The Chronicle.
It isn't clear whether the bank met that projection.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, reports have surfaced about cutbacks in a
broad range of BofA businesses as well as the elimination of some
business units.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, for example, about two dozen jobs disappeared
late last year when the office that sells corporate loans to other
banks was closed. Roughly an equal number of jobs were eliminated
in the financial planning and reporting office of BofA's San
Francisco-based global and corporate bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it offered jobs to most of those displaced
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks come as BofA strains to meet Wall Street profit
expectations. The bank has said its revenue growth is sluggish,
forcing deeper-than-expected cost cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Leal, the top official responsible for managing San Francisco's
banking relationships, said she contacted BofA because she fears
cutbacks could harm the quality of service the bank provides the
city. San Francisco keeps its operating funds and a variety of
special accounts, such as the one used to pay welfare recipients,
with BofA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very legitimate concern as to the status of services
the bank provides us,'' said Leal in an interview. ``I need
reassurance that services we are being provided will not be
negatively affected.``
</P>
<P>
   Leal said she is specifically concerned about the bank's promise
to upgrade computer system, an important selling point in winning
the city's business..
</P>
<P>
   BofA disclosed a month ago that it has pushed back converting
BofA branches in California to NationsBank computer systems from
this year to next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials said the delay won't affect service. ``Beck
assured Leal that the bank will provide the same level of service
it has throughout the years,'' Magnani said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
