<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-RETAIL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Retailers Ring Up Big Holiday Sales  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Retailers turned in robust end-of-year sales reports yesterday,
confirming the exceptional strength of the 1999 Christmas shopping
season.
<P>
   The Credit Suisse First Boston retail index rose 6.4 percent
last month against December 1998, compared with projected growth of
4 percent to 6 percent. The index is a weighted measure of
same-store sales, or sales at stores open at least a year, at about
50 major retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strong finishers were jewelry seller Tiffany, whose
same-store sales jumped 27 percent. Wal-Mart handily beat forecasts
with 9.1 percent growth. And San Francisco's Gap Inc. posted a 5
percent gain, compared with analysts' expectations of 2 to 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's numbers reflect ``a very strong finish to the
holiday selling season,'' said Tom Filandro, an analyst with J.P.
Morgan Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best news is that merchants didn't have to use
markdowns, which would have harmed profits, to achieve the sales
gains. Analysts expect solid profits next month when retailers
report their fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key things I think we saw going into Christmas this
year was well-managed inventory levels,'' said Filandro. Retailers
were able to mark down less merchandise both before and after
Christmas than in years past, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some retailers fell short.
</P>
<P>
   Burlingame's Gymboree, maker of children's clothing, brought up
the rear among yesterday's announcements with an extraordinary
same-store sales decline of 36 percent and a drop in total sales of
29 percent, despite the introduction of new merchandise and a new
branding initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Gary White, Gymboree's chief executive, called December's $66.3
million in sales ``disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Visibility remains cloudy'' for Gymboree, Filandro said.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration Hardware, a home furnishings merchant headquartered
in Corte Madera, continued to suffer from poor inventory
management. Same-store sales for November and December dropped 8.1
percent, while new store openings boosted total sales 30.6 percent
to $92.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Restoration Hardware Chief Executive Officer
Stephen Gordeon blamed most of the sales shortfall on ``difficulty
in having the right goods in the right stores at the right time,''
particularly lighting, furniture and fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   The company revised downward its earnings forecast to between 22
cents and 27 cents per share from 35 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Kramer Tonneson, an analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q, noted that
Restoration Hardware has scaled back its store-opening plans this
year to 15 from 25 as it struggles to correct its ``weak
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of San Francisco's Williams-Sonoma Inc. declined on its
report yesterday that same-store sales grew 4.3 percent, which was
on the low end of estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Companywide sales for the eight weeks ended December 28 totaled
$413.3 million, a 22.4 percent increase compared with last year.
Catalog and Internet sales jumped 33.5 percent compared with a
forecast for 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tonneson called the stock drop of $8.50, to $34, an
``overreaction.'' The same-store sales number was ``somewhat
disappointing, but I wouldn't call it a huge miss,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company's Williams-Sonoma Web site and bridal
site racked up $6 million in sales in the past quarter. ``That's
huge,'' Tonneson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc. posted sales of $2 billion in December, a 27 percent
gain compared with December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Same-store sales at the flagship Gap chain came in flat compared
to last year, while GapKids sales rose 1 to 3 percent, the company
reported. Gap Inc.'s Banana Republic and Old Navy chains posted
gains of 7 to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Navy increase was ``surprisingly strong,'' since it was
up against last December's gain of more than 30 percent, said
Richard Baum, director of equity research at Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Gap stores had been posting declining same-store sales, but ``it
seems that the business has stabilized,'' Baum said. ``They still
have a lot of work to do, but it's clear their holiday
(advertising) campaign had much broader appeal than the fall
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Another San Francisco retailer, Sharper Image, posted a 22
percent sales gain, coming in at $81.8 million in December.
Internet sales rose from $2 million last December to $9.7 million
while same-store sales increased 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the Net could be 10 percent of sales this year''
for Sharper Image, which sells electronic equipment, gadgets and
luggage, said Filandro. ``They're an impressive multichannel
operator.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
