<SLUG> BC-R-CONGRESS-REPUBS-ART-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP CHIEFS ANNOUNCE AGENDA FOR THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders Thursday announced a
cautious, election-year legislative agenda that relies on growing
budget surpluses to pay for a modest set of tax cuts, reduce the
national debt and shield Social Security's surplus.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging news conference, Republicans also vowed to
clear away government obstacles to electronic commerce, promote
trade, cut wasteful spending in federal agencies and return more
decision-making on education to local officials.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing really new in all this.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the $792 billion tax cut bill that Republicans approved
last year and President Clinton vetoed as too expensive. Instead,
Speaker Dennis Hastert said the House would take a piecemeal
approach to tax relief when lawmakers return to work Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans plan to take three of the most popular elements of
last year's tax package, and send them to the floor as separate
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The three bills would eliminate the so-called marriage penalty,
establish tax-free savings accounts for education and create tax
incentives to help revitalize the nation's poorest urban and rural
areas. Together, the package would provide $135 billion in tax cuts
over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried the big bill last year and it didn't work,'' said
Majority Whip Tom DeLay. ``Now we'll try to pass these one at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting tax relief at the top of the Republican legislative
agenda underscores its appeal to the party's conservative base, and
tracks with the issue's ascendancy in the debate between the two
front-runners for the Republican presidential nomination, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But scaling back their legislative ambitions also puts pressure
on Clinton to enact the individual tax breaks or justify vetoing
popular programs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The legislative slate laid out Thursday also read as a campaign
platform. Hastert and DeLay spent as much time ticking off the
accomplishments of the last five years of Republican control as
they did in sketching out an incremental agenda for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the 21 open House Republican seats (compared with 6 for
the Democrats) reflected a lack of confidence in his leadership,
Hastert bristled and voiced a line that will undoubtedly become a
common refrain in this campaign year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will have a choice between a party of new
ideas and new energy or a party of old ideas, more debt and bigger
government,'' he said in ridiculing Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Republican promises seemed to collide with each
other. DeLay pledged that House Republicans would restrain
spending, but Hastert pointedly refused to say whether Republicans
would honor the spending caps in the 1997 balanced-budget
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert promised to unveil details next week on a plan to
eliminate the $3.5 trillion national debt, but he also said the
Republican program could afford the three tax bills announced
today, and others later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans sloughed off any conflicts, pointing to the soaring
surpluses. ``We're going to have plenty of money to pay down the
debt and give tax relief to the American people,'' DeLay said.
``The surplus is growing as we speak.''
</P>
<P>
   In a bow to American business, Majority Leader Dick Armey said
the House might take up bills related to China's entry into the
World Trade Organization sooner than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Philip Crane, a senior Illinois Republican on the Ways and
Means Committee, had said a few weeks ago that the legislation
might not reach the House floor until June or later, pushing a
divisive vote for Democrats closer to the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Armey, who is responsible for scheduling floor action on
bills, said in an interview that he would schedule the major trade
votes ``as soon as possible,'' adding, ``I expect them to be before
June.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
