<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8879 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COMPETE-COMPETE_SFCHR     01-06 1530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPETE-COMPETE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Battling the Startup Lure  &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Internet startups, armed with oodles of stock options and
promises of princely wealth, stalk Silicon Valley. They look to
lure legions of bright young information technology workers at
large, established firms to join their startups with pitches as
blatant as Regis Philbin shrieking ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?''
<P>
   The Big Guys _ your Cisco Systemses, Intels and Hewlett-Packards
_ may offer employees some form of stock plan, but they can't
dangle the instant riches a pre-IPO company can. Large, privately
held compaies, such as Levi Straus, can't even offer stock to
attract and retain key employees.
</P>
<P>
   So what do these companies do when headhunters descend upon
their campuses, intent on plucking top engineers, tech support and
marketing whizzes for their dot-com clients?
</P>
<P>
   Anything they can, short of matching those stacks of stock
options that may or may not pay off down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big job,'' said Jackie Watkins, director of human
resources for HP's information technology sector. ``IT people have
tremendous choices. It's a huge management challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Large public companies such as HP emphasize stability and
benefits and occasionally offer restricted stock, which can only be
sold under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss stresses ``competitive base pay, work-life balance
and working for an iconic brand name,'' according to a company
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   And some Bay Area law firms, hit hard recently by associates
jumping to in-house counsel roles at startups, have started equity
sharing arrangements and reduced the number of billable hours
lawyers must log.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many firms cannot compete with the allure of options,
which let workers purchase stock at a preset price at some time in
the future. Employees can't buy the stock until they have worked at
the firm long enough to become ``vested.'' If the stock price
rises, the employee buys the stock at the preset price, then sells
it on the open market for a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Even though numerous surveys have shown that 70 percent of
startups don't even make it to an IPO, much less command high stock
prices, employers know that the high-profile success stories lead
to a Gold Rush-style exodus among workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone nuts,'' said Eric Campbell, vice president for human
relations at established softwaremaker Docent Inc. in Mountain
View. ``And it'll probably continue to go nuts. How do you fight an
IPO frenzy? You really can't. You just try to tell people the risks
and tell them that it'll be more work than they ever dreamed of
with no reward guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   HP executives don't impart cautionary tales of startup failures
when they're wooing employees. Watkins says HP emphasizes the
positives of its workplace culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe IT people have tremendous choices these days,''
Watkins said. ``We look at studies that tell us that, yes, (more)
money will help keep them in the short term, but it won't hold them
forever. We try to follow the law that people want to be involved
and make a difference when they're at a big company.''
</P>
<P>
   HP reminds employees that magazine surveys consistently rank the
company among the best places to work, that its total compensation
_ base pay and 401(k) plans _ is more of a sure bet than the
options route and that it will train less-experienced workers and
give them challenging assignments upon joining the firm.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy works, most of the time. Watkins says that before
HP split off its test and measurement business this spring, the
attrition rate among employees was between 5 and 8 percent. Most
large computer companies, according to industry reports, have
higher than 10 percent attrition among IT workers.
</P>
<P>
   One strategy that backfired, Watkins said, was HP's short-lived
``bonus retention'' packages, offered to some employees nervous
about the split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't afford to lose anybody during the split,'' Watkins
said. ``We needed more people and IT people are hard to attract in
the first place. We knew we couldn't compete with the startups but
we tried to combat them with restricted stock. It backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``One big problem was that some people got the (stock) and some
didn't. It became an open secret. A person came to me and said,
`Why didn't you give me the retention package? Am I not valuable to
you?' Some employees who did get it thought we were putting the
golden handcuffs on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as HP can only hope their culture brings people
back to the fold after nascent Internet startups fizzle or fold.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'90s, software engineer Michael Suever left HP after
12 years to roll the stock-option dice. Three failed startups
later, he now works at Cisco. Suever said many of his friends at HP
left, too _ not out of dissatisfaction, but for the promise of
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hewlett Packard was great with the 401(k) and everything, but
a bunch of us still left,'' Suever said. ``After two to four years,
half of my friends went back to HP. And the good thing about a
company like HP is, they don't hold leaving against you. My friends
tell me they came back several years later and were able to get the
same benefits and seniority (for pensions) as they had before they
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins says HP executives ``don't dare'' bad-mouth Internet
startups because they hope employees eventually will return to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do say is, `We want you to leave here feeling that
we're still a great company to work with, because we want you to be
a customer and buy our products,''' Watkins said. ``We want them to
know they can come back. And, if not, we ask, `Can we come ride on
your yacht?' We try to keep all doors open.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Watkins says all HP managers are instructed to call
former employees once every few months and ``ask, `How's it
going?'''
</P>
<P>
   One prodigal employee is Mike Brozda, a public relations manager
at National Semiconductor in San Jose. Brozda left National
Semiconductor in 1997 for an Internet startup where he did
marketing, media relations, employee communication _ ``the whole
nine yards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brozda stayed more than a year and left before the company went
public. Then he took his Internet stock _ 25 percent of it had
vested _ and went back to his old job, which didn't have the crazy
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``My six-month vesting period is over in a couple of months,''
Brozda said. ``We'll see how it goes. I came back to National
because I'd done all I could do at a small company. Plus, every
little wind shift at a small company means it changes directions.
National always treated me well. And I knew the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Nontechnology companies also find their top marketing and human
resources people lured by Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree, a retailer of children's clothing is based in
Burlingame, about halfway between Silicon Valley and San
Francisco's Multimedia Gulch. Della Berger, Gymboree's vice
president for compensation, says her employees field a ``barrage``
of job offers from dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ripe for picking and we just can't compete with the
high-tech money,'' Berger said. ``But we've been pretty successful.
Our attrition rate is between 8 and 10 percent. We have a great
culture with lots of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree's benefits range from free career training to weekly
``recesses'' for employees that include games of hopscotch and four
square.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people go to startups and they hate it _ the
relentless hours, the fact that decisions aren't made in a timely
manner, the (lack of) infrastructure,'' Berger said. ``We're
banking on people wanting to work at a place where they can see
progressive growth, where they are getting skills to be to be
marketable. We try to let them know that if they go to one of these
startups, their lives could be miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree does dole out stock options to all employees, but not
nearly the vast amounts of options that startups dangle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do the matching game,'' Berger said. ``It could go on
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, dueling startups find themselves throwing increasing
amounts of options at workers just to get them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Anu Shukla, CEO of Rubric Inc., a private company that sells
Web-based marketing automation software, made her millions off an
early stock-option windfall and says she keeps her employees
``satisfied`` through options.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to or they leave,'' Shukla said. ``Options are part
and parcel of Silicon Valley startups. The difference now is, with
the labor market so tight, you're giving options and high salaries.
Before, you could keep salaries down. My employees are savvy. They
calculate the worth and compare it to other offers. It's not a
headache for me, just something I have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not all strictly money with Shukla. She offers the usual
employee perks, such as weekly parties, telecommuting and massages
for workers in their cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to do it,'' Shukla said, ``or else your people will
get lured away by the dot-com deal of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
