u f BC-UAL-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-06 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AFTER AD CAMPAIGN CATCHES FLAK, UNITED TAKES FUZZIER
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A major new campaign for United Airlines, replacing a
contentious recent series of advertisements carrying the theme
``Rising,'' has no theme. But if there were one, it might proclaim
``United we stand, divided we fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``fall'' is not quite the type of word fliers want to
see invoked in airline advertising. But as it turned out,
``Rising,'' as in rising above the difficulties that vex customers,
was not a word they _ or United's almost 100,000 employees _
welcomed either.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? ``Rising'' took a nontraditional approach to
convince customers that United was tackling the travails of travel,
detailing the problems as well as the solutions. But, according to
executives at United, part of the UAL Corp., and at Fallon
McElligott in Minneapolis, the United agency, that only reminded
passengers how unfriendly the skies can get and put off employees
who felt they were being chastised for lost luggage or delayed
flights.
</P>
<P>
   So after almost three years of ``Rising,'' which was abruptly
curtailed in October while Fallon McElligott explored other ideas,
United is bringing out a feel-good campaign centered on its name:
``Be United,'' ``Worlds United,'' ``Feel United.''
</P>
<P>
   The warmly emotional appeals, underscored by reprises of
``Rhapsody in Blue'' and reassuring words from the actor Liam
Neeson, evoke the pitches that epitomized United during the days
when the carrier and its previous agency, the Leo Burnett unit of
the Leo Group, promised perfection to those who chose to ``Fly the
friendly skies.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch in strategies, which begins Saturday on television
and Monday in poster-style newspaper advertisements, is emblematic
of the midcourse corrections that marketers must make when they
realize their decisions to take different directions in advertising
require rethinking. Sometimes, it seems in this instance, you have
to leave home to learn there was, all together now, no place like
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get back to the heart of United, some of our
roots, what makes us unique,'' John D. Kiker, vice president for
advertising and corporate communications for United in Chicago,
said in an interview Thursday as he presented a preview of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, senior management's opinion is that `Rising'
did us a lot of good,'' he added. ``It was interesting, intriguing
and made us focus on what we had to fix. But employees felt it laid
a lot of blame on them and that was unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Another shortfall came, Kiker said, when research determined
that ``Rising'' was believed to ``be talking to `road warriors' and
global travelers, the people in the front of the plane; we gave the
agency the challenge to be more inclusive, to talk to all our
passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was the new campaign, which Kiker characterized as
striving to portray the airline as ``United to create a better
journey.'' The budget for the ads domestically in 2000 was
estimated at around the $80 million spent in 1999. United spends
another $40 million or so on campaigns abroad, which are created by
offices of Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York; that agency's
new work is due in March or April.
</P>
<P>
   ``A client once told me, `A brand is the sum of everything it's
been,' and those are wise words,'' said David Lubars, president and
creative director at Fallon McElligott, which landed the United
account when United stunned Madison Avenue by dismissing Burnett in
1996 after 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back to the core values that are relevant today,''
Lubars said. ```Friendly skies' was meant back then to have people
feel comfortable about going up in the air. Now people are more
concerned about efficiency, achieving what needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what's as relevant now as it was to the guys who started
United is that it's all about uniting people,'' he added. ``Others
can say they bring you together, they connect you, but it's not in
their name.''
</P>
<P>
   On TV, the theme is brought to life in one spot by Neeson's
narration of scenes of people from Japan to New Orleans to Spain
gathering in courtyards, plazas and squares: ``Why is it that every
city, every town, every neighborhood, no matter where you are in
the world, has something in common? A place for people to come
together. It's quite simple. Humans are a social bunch. That's why
we fly more places than anyone else. Because it's important for the
human race to stay United.''
</P>
<P>
   That spot, and a second one centered on the fast pace of
contemporary life, both end with heroic shots of United pilots
flying their planes through skies that look even more majestic, if
that's possible, than Burnett made them appear during the
``Friendly'' decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an airline to say it's time for us as an industry to do
better for our customers was a controversial point of view to
take,'' said Eric Block, general manager at Fallon McElligott.
``Much of `Rising' focused on better flights, better seats, better
meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the comments that the employees felt undue pressure were
fair because when you raise the ante, say `We have to do better,'
that puts the pressure on,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new management team at United feels it's important now to
focus on why our improvements are better than our competitors' and
on how United cares about its customers and its people.'' Block
said. ``We'll continue to talk about the planes we fly, such as
Economy Plus, taking seats out to give more room to our best
customers in coach, but in the context of what's true to the soul
of this brand.''
</P>
<P>
   How the new campaign fares is crucial for Fallon McElligott,
still stinging from the failure of a midcourse correction on ads
for another high profile account, Miller Lite beer; that client,
the Miller Brewing Co. unit of the Philip Morris Cos., deemed the
agency's revampings ineffective and the account was lost to the New
York office of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, part of the WPP Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confident about Fallon,'' Kiker said. ``They
understand the business, they understand the category and they're
putting 110 percent into this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
