A8886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOPDEBATE07-COX     01-06 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPDEBATE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush promises tax cuts during testy debate
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ Going even further than his father's famous
pledge, Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday night promised tax cuts,
not just ``no new taxes,'' in a debate that was the most
contentious so far between the Republican candidates for president.
</P>
<P>
   The gentlemanly tone that has prevailed between Bush and his
closest rival, Arizona Sen. John McCain, evaporated as the two
sparred on campaign finance reform and Bush's tax proposals. The
latest polls in New Hampshire, which will host the nation's first
primary on Feb. 1, show Bush and McCain running almost even.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush's ``no new taxes'' pledge, a central theme
of his 1988 campaign, backfired in 1990 when he broke it during
budget negotiations with the Democrats. The broken pledge helped
sour conservatives on Bush's 1992 re-election bid, and he was
defeated by Bill Clinton. But the younger Bush, cognizant of
projections that show substantial budget surpluses far into the
future, took an even bolder stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only no new taxes. This is tax cuts, so help me
God,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of campaign finance reform, Bush reiterated his
charge that McCain's plan would favor the Democrats, but he
declined to criticize McCain for intervening in November with the
Federal Communications Commission on behalf of a wealthy
contributor seeking a TV license. The Boston Globe broke that story
Wednesday, leaving McCain, who has portrayed himself as a campaign
finance reformer, to answer questions about whether he has been
practicing what he preaches when it comes to keeping big money out
of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a decision that had been delayed for over 700 days.
People deserved to know the answer. I told them to give them an
answer. I think that's appropriate,'' McCain said in answer to a
reporter's question during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to criticize McCain's action, saying ``I trust
your integrity. I trust your judgment.'' But, Bush added, ``I don't
trust the (campaign finance) plan that you're outlining. It is bad
for Republicans and it is bad for the conservative cause.'' McCain,
in turn, criticized Bush's five-year, $483 billion tax cut
proposal, saying it would eat up the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's wise or conservative to take the entire
surplus and put it into tax cuts,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No it doesn't,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it does,'' McCain shot back, in a testy exchange not
unusual for the evening's debate.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP rivals _ Bush, McCain, Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer, Alan
Keyes and Orrin Hatch _ are set to meet again tonight in South
Carolina and in Michigan on Monday. The debate marathon is a signal
that the contest is in full swing thanks to a compressed primary
schedule this year. The GOP nomination could be all but decided in
little more than a month, after the Jan. 24 Iowa caucuses, the New
Hampshire primary and the Feb. 19 South Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining debates could be crucial for the candidates,
especially for Bush and McCain. McCain has campaigned heavily in
New Hampshire and his blunt, outspoken style had made him popular
enough to eclipse Bush briefly in the polls, which earlier this
week showed them in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's sparring, Bush faced questions about his
religious beliefs. In a previous debate, Bush named Jesus when
asked who was the philosopher he most admired. Thursday, moderator
Tim Russert of NBC's ``Meet the Press'' suggested his response
might have made non-Christians uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make me any better than you or anybody else. ...
It's me, it's what I'm all about,'' Bush told Russert.
</P>
<P>
   There was an incendiary exchange over gays in the military that
followed the pledges Wednesday night by both of the Democratic
presidential hopefuls that they would make sure that homosexuals
could serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that Democratic stance would further the ``radical
homosexual agenda,'' and Keyes said, ``I will return to the ban on
homosexuals in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that policy could be fine-tuned, but he added, ``I
cannot change a policy that's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bush, ``I'm a don't-ask, don't-tell man.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
