<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-W     01-06 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,020(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MILITARY LEADERS DENOUNCE GORE, BRADLEY FOR POSITIONS ON
GAYS IN SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (DELETES line about insubordination in 11th graf; INSERTS ``often''
into 15th graf) 
 (See also GORE-POWELL) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Clinton administration officials interviewed
Gen. Charles Krulak for the job of commandant of the Marine Corps
in 1995, he recalled Thursday, no one asked him for his views on
any social issue facing the military. And there were certainly many
brewing at the time _ from women in combat to the integration of
the sexes in boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   And so he said he was dismayed with the way that the two
Democratic candidates for president, Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley, so strongly endorsed allowing homosexuals
to serve openly in the military. Bradley said he would expect his
appointees to the Joint Chiefs of Staff to carry out his policy.
Gore went even further to say it would be a litmus test for any
appointee he selected.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents, Krulak explained, have historically selected
nominees based on their professional experience and military
expertise, not on their views on political issues _ particularly
divisive social ones. To do otherwise, he said, ``is in my opinion
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with the rightness or wrongness of gays
in the military,'' said Krulak, an opponent of allowing homosexuals
to serve openly who retired as Commandant last year. ``It has
everything to do with how a commander in chief goes about getting
the best officers in the land.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Gore and Bradley _ which came during Wednesday's
debate in New Hampshire when they were asked if they would support
a ``litmus test'' for nominees on the issue _ have inflamed what is
already shaping up as one of the most contentious issues in this
year's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Pentagon, military officers widely and strongly
oppose allowing gay men and lesbians to serve openly in the armed
services, saying their presence would be disruptive in the confined
conditions of barracks life and austere conditions of combat.
</P>
<P>
   While both candidates have previously expressed support for
allowing gays to serve, Krulak and other former chiefs said that
Gore and Bradley crossed a traditional boundary between social
politics and military policy, which could undermine what they
believe should be an apolitical selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regard that as a ridiculous assertion, that that should be a
qualification for office,'' said Gen. Merrill A. McPeak, who served
as chief of the Air Force when Clinton settled on the current
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy for gays in the military in 1993
after a tumultuous debate in Congress and the Pentagon. ``I suppose
winning the nation's wars should be the primary qualification.''
</P>
<P>
   While most officers say they would follow any president's lawful
orders, or resign as a matter of principle, the former chiefs said
they believed that senior officers needed to feel free to offer the
best military advice, even if it contradicted the commander in
chief's views.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job of the chiefs, and particularly the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs, is to give the president their best military
advice,'' said Gen. John W. Vessey Jr., who served as chairman
under President Reagan from 1982 to 1985. ``To have the president
give him the advice beforehand doesn't seem to make a lot of sense
_ whatever the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of homosexuals in the military has been one of the
most roiling issues facing the Pentagon in the last decade. As a
candidate in 1992, Clinton said he would end the military's blanket
ban, and would allow gay men and lesbians to serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   Once in office, however, he retreated after Gen. Colin Powell,
then chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and the chiefs of the
other services publicly opposed the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year Congress voted _ by a veto-proof margin, as
Clinton noted Thursday _ to block a complete lifting of the ban and
instead to approve the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy,
which allows homosexuals to serve as long as they do not do so
openly and do not engage in homosexual acts, which remain a
violation of the Uniform Code of Military Justice.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Gore or Bradley would almost certainly face a
renewed political fight over the policy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican debate Thursday night inNew Hampshire, the
candidates all criticized the Democrats' position on gays. The two
front-runners, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, said they support a continuation of the ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy but said they would oppose allowing gays to serve
openly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism from Republicans and former chiefs, aides
Thursday touted Gore's remarks as a political coup in the fight
between the vice president and Bradley for the more liberal
Democrats who often hold sway in primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Socarides, a former administration official who oversaw
gay and lesbian issues for the White House, said that despite
criticism from former chiefs, Gore was right to demand future
commanders' support and criticized Bradley's position as
``incredibly naive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to make this kind of fundamental change in this kind
of very static institution, you need someone at the top who
believes in it enough to make it a priority,'' he said. ``If you
don't have that, as we have not so far, it will not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides in Bradley's camp clarified his views somewhat Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Bradley suggested that he did not expect his
appointees to agree with him philosophically, but that he would
expect them to carry out his policies. ``I'm sure that there are
people in the military today who don't agree with President Clinton
on 50 things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the aides declined to say whether Bradley would ask
prospective appointees in advance whether they agreed with his
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reserves the right to implement the changes as he sees
fit,'' a spokeswoman, Kristen Ludecke, said. ``The bottom line is
he would abolish `don't ask, don't tell.' He would certainly
consult with the military community, but then he would expect the
military to follow his orders as the commander and chief.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Within the Pentagon, however, opposition to a further loosening
of the restrictions on homosexuals remains deeply rooted among
junior and senior officers.
</P>
<P>
   Vessey said that if Reagan had required a litmus test for
candidates for the chiefs in the 1980s, he ``would have had pretty
slim pickings.'' Krulak said Gore, in particular, could face the
same problem today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, knowing people who have held the position before
and some who serve now, that there are some who would take
themselves out of the running rather than submit to such a litmus
test,'' Krulak said.
</P>
<P>
   McPeak said that it was naive to believe that politics had not
entered into the selection of chiefs in the past, but he believed
that the candidates missed the point of the chiefs' traditional
role as military advisers, not political appointees of any
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has to be able to pick people who believe in his
views to a certain extent, but the whole idea is to have people who
don't serve a political administration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers on active duty are loath to discuss issues like this,
but one active general who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Thursday that Gore's position could raise legal difficulties.
Unless Congress changes the law, the general said, asking a
prospective nominee to support a change in the policy would amount
to asking him to take a position in violation of current law,
something all officers take an oath not to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this goes through, I think the country would be surprised
by the number of officers who would walk,'' the general said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about a litmus test Thursday, Clinton restated his
belief that anyone should be allowed to serve provided they obeyed
the Uniform Code of Military Justice's prohibitions on homosexual
acts. He said his focus now was to ensure that the current policy
works, citing an effort by Secretary of Defense William Cohen to
write new guidelines for field commanders to ensure that gay men
and lesbians who do serve did not face harassment.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, however, he declined to discuss whether a litmus
test was appropriate. ``I'm going to leave the appointment process
to the next president,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
