<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER07-COX     01-06 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker may get new chance
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the same day Atlanta reliever John Rocker was
ordered by Major League Baseball to undergo a psychological
evaluation, his team offered the possibility that one of the best
closers in the game could be back in a Braves uniform next spring.
</P>
<P>
   While indicating his first impulse was to release Rocker after
his now infamous racial and ethnic characterizations appeared in
Sports Illustrated, Braves president Stan Kasten said Thursday,
pending further actions by MLB, that Rocker might remain with the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we release him? Yes, we can,'' Kasten said in his first
comments on Rocker's future. ``Sure, we can, and that continues to
be an option. But what we have here is a case of a player who, to
me at least, has expressed a great deal of remorse immediately and
hasn't backed away from that at all, who has accepted the
responsibility and sought help.
</P>
<P>
   ``And under those circumstances, I'm not going to abandon a
player or an employee or friend who's in those circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, baseball commissioner Bud Selig, saying
Rocker's comments ``were reprehensible and completely
inexcusable,'' ordered him to undergo a psychological evaluation,
which might measure anything from racial attitudes to anger
management.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is in Baltimore, Md., today to begin those tests.
</P>
<P>
   Because Rocker's comments have affected the baseball industry,
the Braves will yield jurisdiction for his review and possible
discipline to MLB.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rocker has made no comment since the story appeared, his
father Jake Rocker, said his son ``is OK with'' submitting to
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker probably saved his job with the Braves in a head-to-head
meeting with Kasten and general manager John Schuerholz on Dec. 29.
Though the team had little initial response, the story shook the
Braves organization, as well as the top levels of Turner
Broadcasting and Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought we had someone here who really was the person as
portrayed in this article, then we would have to wonder,'' Kasten
said. ``But what we had was a player who was remorseful,
acknowledged not just a horrible mistake on his part but also
serious wrongdoing and was eager to take whatever steps he could to
fix this, to get whatever help that would be required to ameliorate
this problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was important for me and John (Schuerholz) to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rocker is unsigned for next season, he is under
contractual control by the Braves, who offered him a contract,
believed to be worth $350,000, before a tendering deadline of Dec.
20. Schuerholz said that contract remains on the table.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocker's future with his teammates and the community at
large is another matter. Politicians' calls for a formal apology
have been ringing for weeks while the economic repercussions to the
Braves may be significant.
</P>
<P>
   Kasten described one corporate sponsor as ``irate. The rest were
merely highly concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of town, Rocker's case has become a public relations
football. The Major League Baseball Players Association, which
negotiated with Selig the decision to have Rocker examined, still
reacted harshly Thursday when his statement was released
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not authorize the release, nor do we necessarily agree
with the characterization of the procedure being discussed
concerning Mr. Rocker,'' said Gene Orza, MLBPA associate general
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But the association walked a fine line of protecting a player
who has openly offended not only his own teammates but fellow
member unions. Whatever Selig determines to do after the
examination is complete _ fine, suspension or further evaluation _
Rocker's case could force a legal maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lawyers on both sides of this issue, on both sides
of the table here with differences of opinion as to what kind of
discipline, if any, is warranted or authorized, or could be upheld
after a grievance or legal action,'' Kasten said. ``That is a
matter of some controversy in professional baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rocker has begun systematically calling teammates to
apologize _ with mixed success _ management is monitoring results.
Right fielder Brian Jordan is on record that ``you might as well
put him on the trading block, because the respect factor is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fondest hope,'' Schuerholz said, ``is that after this
process ends and John Rocker demonstrates sincere and heartfelt
remorse, that there is a possibility at least his teammates may
reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is the issue of New York City, with which Rocker had
dueled for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the next time he goes to New York, he needs to take a
trip to the Statue of Liberty, because race and people of ethnic
heritage are pretty important in New York, too,'' said Kasten, who
grew up in suburban New Jersey. ``We're brought up there knowing
what it says on the base of the Statue of Liberty. That's very
important. It's kind of a point of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
