<HEADLINE>
HONORING THE TEACHERS WHO INSPIRE EXCELLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last spring, 21 New York City high school students
who had overcome great difficulties to excel in their studies
received the first New York Times College Scholarship Program
awards. Now, each winner's high school has won an award of its own:
a $10,000 grant that will be presented in the names of teachers who
played a key role in the lives of the scholarship recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The grants, known as the Teachers Who Make A Difference Awards,
will finance projects as diverse as technology training for
teachers and a mentoring program for immigrant students. Many of
the projects are intended to help teachers improve their skills,
while others are to prepare students for college through workshops,
tutoring and internships.
</P>
<P>
   The grant money, a total of $550,000 over two years, is being
provided by the Charles H. Revson Foundation. Eli Evans, the
foundation's president, said the idea for the grants developed last
March, after The New York Times published an article about the
scholarship winners and the hardships they had endured.
</P>
<P>
   All of the students had excelled academically despite having to
contend with extreme poverty, and in some cases with homelessness,
drug-addicted parents and memories of fleeing their home countries
because of political or religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear that these were special kids whose teachers had
made a big difference in their lives,'' Evans said. ``It seemed
like one element of this initiative should be the recognition of
those teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   At the High School for Law and Public Service in the Washington
Heights section of Manhattan, teachers and students will use the
$10,000 grant to create a guidebook of their neighborhood that will
include a detailed history of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Students will not only write and edit the guidebook but will
also design it, translate it into Spanish and market it. The grant
will also finance a spring trip to Washington for the 40 students
whose academic performance has most improved over the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln High School, in the Coney Island section of
Brooklyn, will use part of its grant to give English lessons to the
parents of students, many of whom speak Russian. The school is also
creating a mentoring program, pairing students who have just
arrived from other countries with natives of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   At Urban Peace Academy in Manhattan, the grant will finance an
after-school program for students who need to improve their writing
skills as they prepare for college. The center, with a staff of two
teachers and three student interns, will be open to students in
every grade, three days a week after school.
</P>
<P>
   And at Brooklyn Technical High School, the grant will finance a
three-week program to hone the writing and interview skills of
11th-graders as they prepare to apply to college. The grant will
also finance a weeklong workshop for eighth-graders planning to
attend the school, to help them prepare for its rigorous academic
program.
</P>
<P>
   Budget cuts have forced Brooklyn Tech to scale back its
orientation program for incoming freshmen in recent years, said
Gail Reilly, the school's coordinator of college services. ``Many
of these kids are big fish in little ponds at their junior high
schools,'' Ms. Reilly said. ``When they get here, they have a huge
adjustment period. Instead of a whirlwind tour, we need to help
them with study skills and time management.''
</P>
<P>
   In its first year, The New York Times College Scholarship
Program attracted hundreds of applicants. But the program limited
awards to a handful of students so that the money _ $12,000 a year
for four years _ would be substantial enough to make a significant
difference in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the program awarded scholarships to only six students.
But after The Times published the article about the winners,
private donors contributed enough money to send 15 more students to
college. After the scholarship winners were selected, the Revson
Foundation asked them to name the teachers who had made a major
difference in their lives. The foundation then informed their high
schools of the grants and asked them to submit proposals for
projects.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are delighted that the program is not only benefiting the
students who have received scholarships, but is running much
deeper,'' said Arthur Gelb, who is stepping down in February as
president of The New York Times Co. Foundation to direct the
college scholarship fund. ``With the Revson grant, we can honor
their teachers by creating projects of their choice that will help
the faculty and students at each of their schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times has received about 1,700 applications for the next
round of college scholarships, and a committee of editors and
reporters will begin reading the applications of 152 semifinalists
later this month. This year's scholarship recipients will be
announced in March, and the Revson Foundation will provide a second
round of grants in the names of teachers who inspired those
students.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the schools receiving the awards, and the teachers in
whose names they were made:
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln High School: Larry Wittlin, Vinny Loud, Linda
Eidelberg.
</P>
<P>
   Academy of Mount St. Ursula: Joseph Arcoleo, Monica DeLaurentis,
Klara Lomartire.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn Technical High School: Maxine Stein, Henry Jackson, Ben
Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   Cathedral High School: Sister Eileen Regina, Ben Adams, Marie
Kehrli.
</P>
<P>
   Edward R. Murrow High School: James Kiernan, Stuart Benas,
Georgia Scurletis.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Hills High School: Victor Shapiro, Janice Woo, Gwen
Scherr.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Cleveland High School: Elaine Guthrie, Carol Grubman,
Emanuel Schiller.
</P>
<P>
   High School for Law and Public Service: Suzanne Block, Neil
Garfinkle.
</P>
<P>
   High School for Leadership and Public Service: Heather Ordover,
Brian M. Donnelly.
</P>
<P>
   Humanities Preparatory Academy: Perry Weiner, Caleb Perkins,
Jorge Cordero, Doug Knecht.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Van Buren High School: Joan Lisecki, Daniel Ruben, Marc
Comerchero.
</P>
<P>
   Newtown High School: Lance Gary Lester, Dympna Joyce, Shara
Berkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Regis High School: Father Arthur Bender, Terese Whang.
</P>
<P>
   Seward Park High School: Maureen Lonergan, Susan Chan, Mary Ann
Fastook.
</P>
<P>
   Sheepshead Bay High School: Janet Isquith, Linda Rosen, Alan
Shweky, Daniel Beauzil.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's Boys High School: Patricia Mulligan, Maria
Montalbano, Patrick Bradley, Sal Castelano.
</P>
<P>
   Stuyvesant High School: Lloyd Williams, Dalia Bulgaris, Frank
Mazzetti, Stanley Teitel.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt High School: Rosetta Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Peace Academy: Edison Teano.
</P>
</TEXT>
