<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-VIRGINMARY-MIXUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGIN MARY SEEN IN NEW JERSEY PAPERWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ On its face, it seemed a simple computer error,
albeit an incongruously beatific one.
</P>
<P>
   A search of Middlesex County's computerized land records this
week showed that the Virgin Mary owned some 365 parcels in the
county that on closer examination actually belonged to such
earthbound entities as Public Service Electric and Gas and the
Hungarian Boy Scout Association.
</P>
<P>
   But the appearance of Mary's name is just part of the county's
larger problem in carrying out its move from the ancient realm of
dusty, paper-filled halls of records to the new era of
computer-stored images of documents. It has been a journey fraught
with frustration, errors and a lawsuit by title searchers who view
the new system as anything but an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   And although all parties agree that no land transactions have
been seriously affected by the problems, state regulators who have
been monitoring the county's transition say they cannot certify the
new system until the bugs are ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   A search of the new computerized records this week by a title
searcher seeking someone with a last name beginning with the
letters ``Vir'' turned up an index of properties and transactions
that listed ``Virgin Mary'' as a seller or buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Walter A. DeAngelo, Middlesex County administrator, said the
error resulted from the mistaken installation of a test file used
by programmers who had been transferring land records from an older
mainframe that could not handle the necessary imaging to a newer
system.
</P>
<P>
   The errant test file was designed, for indexing purposes, to
truncate long names in transactions, and did just that when it came
upon ``The New Brunswick Greek Catholic Church of the St. Virgin
Mary.'' But it went on to mistakenly overlay the shortened name on
hundreds of other indexed transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the computer records were intact and only the index
was in error, DeAngelo said that the problem would be fixed within
a week or 10 days. In the meantime, title searchers will have to
use the old paper records.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake came as no surprise to Ann Sardone, spokeswoman for
the Middlesex County Title Searchers Guild, whose group sued the
county in October over the new system, which they say has made
their lives miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Luddites and we understand that computers are here
to stay,'' Ms. Sardone said. ``But this system has been a problem
from the start with inputting errors and an indexing system that is
very unforgiving. We just laughed hysterically when we saw the
Virgin Mary entries.''
</P>
<P>
   Albin Wagner, chief of the Bureau of Records and Management in
the Secretary of State's office, said that under a 1994 state law
allowing counties to dispense with paper records in favor of
computer-based records, his office must certify that a county has
adequately made the transition before the older, more costly,
storage methods can be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Although Middlesex was among the first counties to begin the
transition, Wagner said, it has fallen short. He said the county's
problems stemmed from a storage and indexing system that had been
cobbled together from a number of programs rather than purchased
``off the shelf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
