<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-SEXY-ADS-1STLD-     01-06 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SEXY-ADS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST JAPANESE DAILY BANS SEXUALLY EXPLICIT ADS  
</HEADLINE>
   (CLARIFIES lede replacing ``previews'' with ``promises'') 
 (rk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For years, the ads have been a titillating, early week
staple, anchoring the inside pages of the biggest newspaper in
Japan with promises of photo layouts of nude women and scoops on
the sex lives of the stars.
</P>
<P>
   But in a blow that it is claiming for women's rights, the paper,
Yomiuri Shimbun, has decided to ban advertising for two of the
raciest weekly magazines, saying they constitute and encourage
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper officials said that the decision, which means a weekly
sacrifice of $600,000, had been prompted by complaints from
employees and readers, as well as by the recent passage of a law on
discrimination in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years, the content of these advertisements has
become drastically more sexual, and voices have been raised both
inside and outside our company about this matter,'' a spokesman for
the paper, Tsuokazu Momoi, said. ``Teachers were even complaining
that they couldn't distribute copies of our newspaper for use in
class because of the blunt sexual content.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the full effects of the decision could not be
immediately determined, it is generally expected to increase
pressure on other major dailies to revise ad policies for sexually
explicit materials. Yomiuri Shimbun, the industry leader, has an
audited daily circulation of 10.27 million.
</P>
<P>
   Large, color advertisements for the weeklies also hang from the
ceilings of Japan's subways and commuter trains.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Tokyo's Rapid Transit Authority would also ban the
ads, Ryuichi Kinoshita, a spokesman, said: ``We have our own rules
on advertisements. Since this is a mass transit company, we must
make efforts to not make people uncomfortable, and to preserve the
dignity of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial on Tuesday, Yomiuri Shimbun explained its
decision, noting that 99 percent of its circulation is through home
delivery. Allowing sexual material to be delivered to homes ``where
it could possibly be seen by children cannot be called normal,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, another important daily newspaper, Mainichi
Shimbun, said it was considering a revision of its ad policy. Asahi
Shimbun, the most liberal major daily, said in a recent article
that it had received many readers' complaints about the sexual
content of ads and that revised standards would start this month.
</P>
<P>
   A debate among publishers about sexual material began last year
after the issue was taken up by the Japan Bar Association. Miki
Tanikawa, the author of a paper that prompted the Bar Association
to discuss the matter, said in an interview that the advertisements
reflected the low status of women in Japanese society.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that in so many aspects of the society, from
politics, where the ratio of women to men is very low, to the
workplace, where women often earn half as much as men,'' Ms.
Tanikawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Yomiuri changed its ad policy at a time of substantial _ if
glacial by the standards of much of the West _ progress on women's
rights here. High-profile campaigns in the subways encourage women
to complain about sexual molestation. And women are increasingly
suing over discrimination in the workplace and sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   A case of this type that is seen as a social landmark was a
harassment ruling in civil court last month in favor of a college
student against the mayor of the second largest city in Japan,
Osaka. The mayor was subsequently indicted on criminal charges and
forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a visit to any major company, including an interview at
Yomiuri this week, involves being greeted at the reception desk by
young women seemingly chosen for their charm and, inevitably, being
served tea or coffee by other ever-smiling young women after being
seated in a meeting room. At Yomiuri, the meeting room even
happened to have a rack of magazines, including the two whose ads
had just been banned, that featured comely young women on the
covers and plenty of nude pictures inside.
</P>
<P>
   In their breathless advertisements, complete with partly
obscured pictures, the two weeklies affected by the ban, the Weekly
Gendai and the Asahi Geino, commonly boast of items like ``displays
of 16 ordinary women showing their pubic hair'' or ``first-time
photos of former models with beautiful bosoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Asahi Geino wrote in statement, ``We have no intention of
complaining about the fact that Yomiuri has its own standards.''
The magazine did, however, express surprise that Yomiuri's rules on
ads seemed to have suddenly changed. A statement from the Weekly
Gendai called the decision ``truly incomprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though she saluted the Yomiuri decision, a leading
feminist, Mizuho Fukushima, said she was surprised that the ban had
been applied only to two of Japan's weeklies, most of which offer a
rich staple of nude women and sexually explicit cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all of the ads for the weeklies are distasteful,'' Ms.
Fukushima, a member of parliament, said. ``They openly speak about
women's breasts and bodies, and you have to wonder if children
reading this sort of thing in the large ads on trains and in the
newspapers don't begin to take it for granted that this is how you
should treat women.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fukushima added, however, that she was regular reader of the
two banned publications, as well as many of the other weeklies that
carry sexual material. That, she added, is because only the
weeklies regularly engage in investigative reporting and political
muckraking. The large dailies, which have long-established close
relations with government and industry through so-called press
clubs, which distribute news releases to members only, are highly
conservative and seldom break ground in reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women should take the initiative for eliminating nudity in
these magazines, but the problem, which is rather unique to Japan,
is that political reporting is mixed up in the midst of all of
these displays of nudity,'' Ms. Fukushima said. ``I buy them
because they always carry stories on subjects that I need to know
about, stories that don't appear in the daily newspapers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper industry sources partially explained the choice of the
newspaper's target by saying that Yomiuri Shimbun has had a
long-running battle with the Weekly Gendai, which has often
attacked the newspaper and been critical of the baseball team it
owns, the Yomiuri Giants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
