<HEADER>
A8905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-SHOW07-COX     01-06 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-SHOW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connectivity, reliability focus of Consumer Electronics Show
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In the keynote address opening the 2000
international consumer electronics show, technology executive Eric
A. Benhamou and an assistant attempted to demonstrate wireless
digital conferencing with a pair of laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   A few long, embarrassing moments after the assistant entered the
command that was to connect his laptop to Benhamou's, it became
clear the attempt had failed. The assistant was forced to cross the
stage and quickly adjust Benhamou's computer before the connection
could be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for helping me make my point about simplicity and
reliability,'' Benhamou said. ``Simplicity and reliability are keys
to making technology attractive to the consumer. Our industry is
not necessarily where we need to be on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The business of the consumer electronics show is selling new
technology to retailers and to the public, and Benhamou said the
prospects for future sales are bright. But he said there are also
obstacles the industry has to overcome, such as technology that can
be hard to use.
</P>
<P>
   He said another serious threat is the ``digital divide''
separating the poor who tend to have no access to computers from
the more affluent who benefit from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,500 exhibitors representing manufacturers, inventors
and developers of every kind of electronic device from portable
tape players to complex computer systems gather in Las Vegas every
January to show off their latest wares.
</P>
<P>
   There, displays can be one-person booths set up to sell tiny
gadgets to mail order houses, or they can be spectacular multimedia
extravaganzas with giant video screens, dancers, acrobats and
pounding music to sell the latest lines of big-ticket home
entertainment gear.
</P>
<P>
   And 90,000 corporate buyers, software engineers, government
officials, financial analysts, journalists, and others from more
than 100 countries showed up Thursday to elbow their way through
crowds around more than a million square feet of displays.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz word at this year's show seems to be connections, and
Benhamou spent much of his keynote address talking about bringing
interactive networks into homes.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou is chairman and chief executive officer of 3COM
Corporation, a $6 billion-a-year company based in Santa Clara,
Calif., that specializes in networks for businesses, individuals
and Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Through products currently available on the open market,
Benhamou said, families can wire their homes to communicate with
each other and with the outside world in ways unheard of just 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But for the revolution to continue, he warned, the electronics
industry must continue working to develop standards and systems
that allow products from different manufacturers to communicate
with one another.
</P>
<P>
   One such system is Blue Tooth, a communications protocol which
is an integral part of news released Thursday by Delphi Automotive
Systems. Delphi announced that it has signed contracts with seven
different companies around the world to sell its Communiport brand
Mobile MultiMedia products. The contracts total $2.5 billion over
the next three years, according to company projections.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi's Mobile MultiMedia Business Group is using the show to
display products for navigation, mobile computing, communications,
entertainment and information functions for use in private and
commercial cars, vans and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are devices using Blue Tooth technology that will
allow computers installed in cars to communicate with devices such
as cellular telephones that also have Blue Tooth capability.
</P>
<P>
   John Shea, manager of product publicity for Delphi, said the
technology will allow a driver to make a hands-free call by having
his car's on-board computer communicate with a Blue Tooth phone
inside a nearby briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Other products under development include MP3 players for cars,
navigational systems and DVD players that can be played on a screen
in the back seat of a car.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
