<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-2TAKES-     01-06 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO CUT TAXES AS HE AND OTHER CANDIDATES TRADE BARBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ Eight years after his father learned the hard way
about making promises on taxes, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas on
Thursday night offered an unequivocal pledge never to raise taxes
and in fact promised to cut them.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a fierce competition with Sen. John McCain with less
than a month to go before the presidential primary here, Bush
sought to overcome his father's famous reversal of a ``no new
taxes'' pledge, which cost then-President George Bush critical
support in the 1992 primary here and haunted his campaign against
Bill Clinton that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only no new taxes,'' said Bush in a debate with
his five rivals for the Republican presidential nomination at the
University of New Hampshire. ``This is tax cuts, so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Rather than create more government, I think we ought
to pass money back to the working in people in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's promise was a dramatic point of an hourlong debate in
which he and McCain abandoned their months of cordiality and
sparred aggressively over their prescriptions for campaign finance
and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was also called upon to defend his recent intervention
with the Federal Communications Commission in a matter that
ultimately benefited a major campaign contributor.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, the fourth featuring all six Republican candidates,
was the most spirited, and at times the most entertaining, of the
campaign. McCain suggested that Bush was behind an independent
group's advertising campaign attacking him. Bush, in turn, scolded
McCain for backing a campaign finance bill that ``Al Gore is
applauding.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tense moments between Bush and McCain set the tone for
an increasingly strained competition between the two politicians,
who are neck and neck in the polls here, in the run-up to the New
Hampshire primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and McCain battled each other, the other four
candidates, struggling for attention, sought to portray them as not
sufficiently conservative for Republican primary voters. To do
that, they seized on the issue of homosexuals in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Every candidate took issue with comments Wednesday night by Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley _ standing on the
same stage at the University of New Hampshire _ strongly endorsing
the right of homosexuals to serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republican contenders argued that McCain and Bush did
not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we accept the radical homosexual agenda,'' said Alan Keyes,
a former State Department official, ``be it in the military or in
marriage or in other areas of our lives, we are utterly destroying
the concepts of family.'' He added, ``those candidates up here
unwilling to face that fact and playing games with this issue are
doing so irresponsibly at the price of America's moral
foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said he objected to comments by Bush, who did not rule out
appointing openly gay people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what their policies are,'' Bush said. ``Depends on
what their views are.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain voiced support for the military's current ``don't ask
don`t tell policy'' saying, ``I would make sure that a policy
that's working and is working and should work was continued.''
</P>
<P>
   With only an hour to share among the six of them, the candidates
often interrupted one another and often ignored the questions posed
by the moderator, Tim Russert of NBC News, and three local
journalists. Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah replied to a question about
Internet taxation by talking about U.S. policy toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic between McCain and Bush was particularly notable.
For months, McCain and Bush had hardly seemed like rivals, to the
point that they were praising each other in debates. But Thursday
night McCain turned to Bush and suggested that he was behind an
advertising campaign by a conservative tax group that has broadcast
commercials attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, a supporter of yours is running ads morphing Bill
Clinton's face into mine,'' McCain said. Then, seeking to inject
some levity into his accusation, he added, ``And by the way, ask
him to get a better picture, will you?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said, ``I don't think you have an idea of how
important campaign finances reform could restore the confidence of
young Americans in their government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush shot back: ``What you don't need to do is tell me what I
have an idea about or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange grew so testy that Russert interrupted: ``Boys,
boys, let's get on with the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has a tradition of opposing taxes, and Bush has
made his $483 billion, five-year tax cut plan a centerpiece of his
campaign here. In the first major policy dispute with McCain, Bush
this week accused McCain of shortchanging the middle class on tax
cuts. But McCain argued that the governor's proposal would go to
tax breaks for the upper class - at the expense of money for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, McCain said, ``Governor Bush said the other day
we're awash in cash. We've got a $5.6 trillion debt that we're
saddling young Americans with. We ought to pay down the debt. But
we also ought to make Social Security solvent.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher who advocates the abolition
of the current tax code, took issue with Bush's efforts to come
across as a tax cut crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He signed a pledge in 1994 promising not to put in a business
tax or to raise the state sales tax,'' he said of Bush's record in
Texas. ``Two years later, he violated that pledge.'' Forbes added,
``We know what happens in the Republican Party when we violate
no-tax pledges.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to be drawn into questions about McCain's dealings
with the FCC on behalf of a major contributor, Paxson
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, who is campaigning in New Hampshire on a reform
mantle, tried to smile throughout the questions about his conduct.
``The reason why I've worked so hard for campaign finance reform
because all this money washing around Washington and all those
uncontrolled contributions taint all of us,'' he said. ``No matter
what we do we are unde a cloud of suspicion and I am one of those
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was asked why, after spending millions of dollars of his
own personal fortune on his campaign, he has not made inroads in
the polls. He was asked by one reporter if he was too aloof.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes drew laughs when he glanced at McCain and replied,
``Maybe you want me to give a hug to John.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be glad to, Steve,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, who is also battling for conservatives' support,
cast himself as far more responsive to those voters than Bush. He
accused President Bush of making ``a colossal mistake'' by
appointing Associate Justice David Souter to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would defend his father, Bush said, ``Listen,
I'm the only one on stage who's appointed judges.'' He added, ``My
dad can defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate, the candidates spent a lot of time
joking, interrupting each other, swapping put-downs and complaining
that they were not getting enough attention. Bush flashed his quick
humor when he was asked _ based on his past comments about his
belief in Christ _ whether as president he would think to himself
``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office of, `Dear God
_ help me!''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Keyes deadpanned, ``So would we, Governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few minutes later, it was Bush and McCain needling each
other.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Bush's plan for a tax cut dissipated the federal
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it doesn't,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it does,'' McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``No it doesn't, yes it does,'' Bush mimicked.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Keyes and Russert engaged in a standoff as
Russert implored him to stop talking, while Keyes refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes ultimately sniped, ``The format of this debate is a little
strange. I begin to wonder when Mr. Russert will declare his
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, too, seemed to feel overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay here and take some time myself,'' he
insisted when one of his attempts to make a comment bucked up
against a time limit. ``I'm taking this microphone, I tell you
right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
