<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO ESTABLISH 2 MONUMENTS IN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 Resending to correct head.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Washington) - President Clinton, a Democrat who loves visiting
Republican-dominated Arizona, returns next week for a speech in
which he is expected to establish two national monuments here.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would say only that Clinton was scheduled to
arrive on Air Force One in Arizona on Monday night and would make
``an environmental announcement'' Tuesday at Grand Canyon National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said privately that Clinton likely will
use the magnificent backdrop to prevent uranium mining and urban
sprawl by creating the roughly 1 million-acre Grand Canyon
Parashant National Monument, bordering the Canyon's North Rim, and
the 71,000-acre Agua Fria National Monument, north of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt announced proposals for the new
Arizona monuments last month. But they are controversial, with
objections raised by Gov. Jane Hull and Republican members of
Arizona's congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona lawmakers have said the monuments amount to a land grab
that bypasses Congress. But Babbitt has said the action is needed
because Congress has failed to protect the areas. Clinton also is
expected to create two monuments in California. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
