<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: VERY DIFFERENT DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial for Friday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Campaign debates may be a familiar form of political theater,
but there is something rare and compelling _ even admirable _ about
the unscripted psychodrama of the encounters between Vice President
Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom have two candidates from one party put before the voters
such starkly contrasting personalities and such different visions
of what a president ought to be. The suspense of the exercise is
that neither the candidates nor commentators know whether the
voters will prefer an argumentative master of detail ( Gore) or a
self-contained generalist ( Bradley).
</P>
<P>
   Both men are capable of pandering to the usual Democratic
constituency groups on specific issues, but at the macro level,
each is saying take me or leave me. Gore presents himself as the
consummate legislative craftsman. Bradley radiates disdain for
political games and the culture that produced them. The vice
president is the more facile debater, snatching questions out of
the air while Bradley waits to be called upon. Gore is an
interrupter, Bradley a shrugger.
</P>
<P>
   Their growing antipathy reached its peak in the Wednesday
debate, and their subtexts were at their clearest. By putting Gore
in the ``Washington bunker,'' Bradley was depicting his opponent as
the captive heir to a corrupt administration. By asserting that ``a
president should be a fighter,'' Gore was casting Bradley as a
dreamer who lacked the stomach for fighting the Reagan and Gingrich
revolutions.
</P>
<P>
   In their next debate Saturday, Bradley will face a tactical
problem. Can he hit Gore harder without damaging his own
anti-politician image? Gore, for his part, seems irrevocably
committed to his flamethrower mode. Whatever happens next, these
candidates have shown that one-on-one debates really can give
voters a choice on issues and on leadership temperament as well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
