<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8910 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     01-06 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK'S EFFORT TO LISTEN TO PLAYERS RESTORED LOST TRUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It wasn't until the end of November that coach Ken
Hitchcock began to understand just how sick his Dallas Stars really
were. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The realization made him want to toss his own cookies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The thing that was frustrating for me was that we weren't
handling being winners very well,'' Hitchcock reflected after the
rejuvenated defending Stanley Cup champions hit the halfway point
of the season with a 3-1 victory over Nashville at Reunion Arena
Wednesday night. ``I'd never seen our team play that badly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were horrible and I was at a loss as to what to do. I knew
what our problems were, but for the life of me I couldn't figure
out where to start fixing them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was more than a simple Stanley Cup hangover, though that
was all part of it. This went to the core of what Hitchcock is
about as a coach and what the Stars are about as an organization. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was about work ethic and honor and the kind of franchise
and team the Stars would be. It was about a coach's will clashing
with the raw emotions of players still weary from last season's
march to the most challenging championship in sports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From \RMike\S Modano's injury on, not only did we get players
hurt all the time, we lost our focus. We had some players play
like, `What can we get away with?' We were at a real loggerheads
with our team regarding the joy of competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taking too many things for granted and I'd never
experienced that. There was very little emotion and passion to
compete. The wins and the losses felt the same.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The players had barely a month to recover after celebrating with
the Cup before they were back in Vail, Colo., with no sense of the
letdown ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that was the problem,'' said retired defenseman Craig
Ludwig, who watches most games from the press box these days as a
consultant to general manager Bob Gainey. ``I just think they
expected to pick up where they left off. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry is different. When you start plugging different
people in, there's an adjustment time. All this is compounded by
everybody in the league trying their damndest to beat the Stanley
Cup champions. This is the team everybody measures themselves
by.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That idea alone seemed to catch the Stars by surprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the assumption that we could just turn it off and
on, like a tap,'' Hitchcock said. `There was also the reality that,
`Man, why do these teams have to play us like this?' We were hacked
off because teams were playing us hard. We had the wrong attitude
toward competition.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Hitchcock simply did what he does best. He
started talking to his players, not as a team, but as individuals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talked to them as a group, they just flat weren't
listening,'' Hitchcock said of the Stars' struggles during the
early part of the season. ``I couldn't get their attention. The
group wasn't willing to do things. I felt like we were starting to
lose trust. I felt like I was getting nowhere with the group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What started the process back was when I began talking to
individuals and I started asking questions. I left a couple of
conversations and thought, `Jeez, there's a lot of feelings here
that we weren't aware of ... friends lost, physical energy, mental
energy, why do we have to play this hard so early, a lot of
questions by individuals.' There were a lot of things built up
inside people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter of the season was probably the most difficult
period Hitchcock had ever gone through as a coach, certainly his
most critical challenge as a head coach in the NHL. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were two extreme low points, the first near the end of
October in Toronto, where Hitchcock felt the Stars actually
embarrassed themselves in the city he considers the Mecca of
English-speaking hockey in Canada. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really hard to take for our team,'' Hitchcock said.
``We had nine players injured and we didn't have a competitive
team. I thought, halfway through the game, their guys eased up on
us. That's the first time in a long time in coaching where I felt
like I didn't have a good enough team to win a hockey game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A month later, just after Thanksgiving, things hadn't gotten
much better. The Stars blew a lead against Anaheim, and Hitchcock
began to wonder if the Stars had it in them to turn it around. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got beat to every puck everywhere in the second half
of the game,'' he said. ``We had a 2-0 lead in a very important
game and we just got beat everywhere. I've never seen our team play
like that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day there was a team meeting in Atlanta where everybody
_ coaches and players _ had their say. During the game that night,
the Stars followed a solid, promising first period with another
horrible effort in the second period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock and team captain Derian Hatcher both addressed the
team in no uncertain terms and the Stars rallied to not only win
that game, but began playing with a new determination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `I realized that I had been going about things the wrong way and
that I needed to start reeling in individual guys rather than
dealing with the group,'' Hitchcock said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tipoff was a meeting with struggling Joe Nieuwendyk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of stuff came up that we as coaches never thought
about,'' Hitchcock recalled. ``All this stuff from the past came
out, friends missing and teammates gone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win and you win big, you make friends for life. You
let those guys go, you break a bond. It comes back on paper easier
for coaches, but that emotional connection that players make
doesn't come back right away. Nobody's going to tell you that as a
group, but it started coming out when I began talking to
individuals.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars still aren't where they were last year and may never
be if they can't get players healthy. But at least they're all back
on the same page. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitch got us all to play one way, and the final result was
what happened five months ago,'' Ludwig said. `To win \Rthe Cup\S
again, they have to have people healthy and make sure the guys who
have had to play so much because of injuries aren't burned out when
the playoffs get here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, that's hope enough for Hitchcock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a great team,'' he said, ``but we're becoming a good
team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's a good start to the regular season's final 41 games. Then
the real test begins again. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
