r s BC-HKN-STARS-OPTIMISM-TE     01-06 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OPTIMISM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM RETURNS TO STARS TEAM THAT TEETERED ON DESPAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If optimism has a sound, Mike Keane flinging
one-liners around a bustling Dallas Stars locker room has to be
close.
</P>
<P>
   For space once dominated by edgy silence now has a feel of a
college fraternity, and a just-finished, injury-plagued, bumpy
first half of this season has a feel of a springboard to a second
half that Stars players can't wait to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I feel confident is our players are willing to
accept responsibility, to a man, for their performances. We stopped
looking at the coach, looking at the system, looking at injuries,
looking at all of these other outside things and we're finally
willing to look within again,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``There is a sincere belief in this group that if we ever do get
healthy we got ourselves a heck of a team because of what we've
gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   What they've been through almost destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what almost destroyed them might just propel them to
another Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two months were real tough. I don't think anybody
expected it to be that hard,'' Stars captain Mike Modano said.
``The walls were caving in on us, and everything seemed to be
coming in on us at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was talking, but they weren't listening. The coach
knew it. The players knew it. But nobody really knew how to solve
it.
</P>
<P>
   There was meeting after meeting after meeting. Even Stars
general manager Bob Gainey talked to his team leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point it seemed like, and critical is too hard of a
word, but it seemed like a necessary time to let the players know
that it wasn't just Ken delivering the message, but the message was
from our organization,'' Gainey said. ``Even though, we tried to
prepare for the aftermath of a long and successful season. There
are, at times, just the need for time to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a beginning necessitates an end.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 26, Stars players reached an end of sorts, the low
point, Hitchcock said. Dallas blew a two-goal lead in a loss to
Anaheim, sending them to a 10-11-3 mark. In 1998-99, loss No. 11
didn't occur until Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   So, a couple of days later, as Dallas prepared to play Atlanta,
players and coaches closed doors and unleashed a little honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meeting was to tell (Hitch) to back off a little bit, and
we'll come out of it ourselves,'' Stars forward Guy Carbonneau
said. ``I think everybody understands what (Hitch) is trying to do.
He's a really demanding coach, and we don't have a problem with
that. But I think we proved to him that we have a lot of experience
and leadership on this team, and sometimes, we need to overcome
those things by ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Two periods later, Stars players found themselves right back in
whatever nightmare it was they thought they had freed themselves
from.
</P>
<P>
   Only, instead of trailing Anaheim, they were trailing an
expansion team and only Hitchcock and defenseman Derian Hatcher
talked between periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said something like, `This isn't kosher. No one is happy
with what's going on here. If this is a turning point, let's go.
We've got the guys in here to get the job done. Let's do it,'''
Stars defenseman Brad Lukowich remembers.
</P>
<P>
   In a Disney-like plot twist, a turnaround began.
</P>
<P>
   It was for a period, at first, Dallas coming back to defeat
Atlanta. A streak followed, an 11-4-2 mark since what Hitchcock
calls their stripping down. They're tied for first in the Pacific
Division, seven points out of the lead in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happens is when you are not winning people become
outspoken and you don't want to hear some of the things at first,''
Hitchcock said. ``At the end of the day, you have to say `Why is
this guy ticked off? Not he's ticked off, he's an idiot, blah,
blah, blah. So you get past the emotion and get into the fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are what changed this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts were the Stars were looking for way to get away with
less-than-inspired play. They were looking for reasons not to play
at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 20 games we were reluctantly playing, almost,''
Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner said. ``We weren't mentally ready
to go all out again, and that's Hitch's style.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hitchcock: ``I felt in the first 20 games ... I felt a
fight between players and coaches in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   What it boiled down to was they were looking for excuses.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have to look far.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' injury list has read like the roster for most of this
season. Modano, Hatcher, Joe Nieuwendyk, Shawn Chambers, Darryl
Sydor, Jere Lehtinen, Brian Skrudland, Grant Marshall, and on and
on.
</P>
<P>
   The chemistry didn't work with the first group of players (i.e.
Pavel Patera, Warren Luhning, et al.) brought in to keep the Cup on
ice until the roster returned. They had to go get another group
(Brenden Morrow, Roman Lyashenko, et al.).
</P>
<P>
   They've worked better, or maybe the Stars were just ready to
turn it around. Whatever it was or is, it can still be felt
dangling in the Stars' locker room now.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any doubt that optimism has a sound, listen:
</P>
<P>
   ``We easily could've folded. We had excuses,'' Keane said.
``Maybe, some people said we were at the bottom of the barrel and
couldn't get any lower. I think we've responded.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
