u f BC-AUDIT-STOCKS-1000(2TA     01-06 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIT-STOCKS-1000(2TAKES)-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC CITES HUGE ACCOUNTING FIRM FOR VIOLATING CONFLICT RULES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: Clarifies second, 13th and 15th graphs.)   (jw) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most partners of PricewaterhouseCoopers, the world's largest
accounting firm, violated rules requiring that they not have
investments in companies audited by their firm, the Securities and
Exchange Commission said Thursday. The firm said that five partners
had been dismissed as a result of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A law firm, which studied the accounting firm after previous
problems led to SEC action in a few cases, compiled a report that
documented a system in which violations were routine, many partners
said they were unfamiliar with the details of longstanding rules
and little effort was made by the accounting firm to enforce them.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said that 31 of the 43 partners in the firm's top
leadership had committed at least one violation, as had six of the
11 partners responsible for enforcing the rules requiring that
senior employees of accounting firms have no stake in the companies
whose financial reports the firm is certifying as independent
auditors. Altogether, the investigation found 8,064 violations by
partners and employees of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report is a sobering reminder that accounting
professionals need to renew their commitment to the fundamental
principle of auditor independence,'' said Lynn E. Turner, the chief
accountant of the SEC and a former partner of Coopers &AMP; Lybrand,
one of the firms that merged in 1998 to form
PricewaterhouseCoopers. He said a new study would review the
performance of other major accounting firms, adding, ``I am
concerned about whether the new study will find any differences
between the firms.''
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers said it did not believe the integrity of
any audit had been compromised, although 140 cases were identified
in which employees or partners participated in audits of 52
companies despite having investments in the companies. It said a
new system had been installed to prevent future violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we found the violations were not inadvertent, or
reflected a total disregard of the rules, we've dealt with that in
a serious way,'' said Kenton Sicchitano, PricewaterhouseCoopers'
global managing partner for regulatory and independence matters. He
said that five partners, and a slightly larger number of other
employees under the level of partner, had been forced to leave, and
that other employees had faced lesser penalties. He declined to
give names.
</P>
<P>
   At the SEC's request, the Public Oversight Board, an agency
created by Congress to keep watch on auditors, will review the
other major accounting firms to see if they have also violated the
rules. ``This is a very serious problem,'' said Charles Bowsher,
the chairman of the board and a former comptroller general of the
United States. ``I think everybody in the profession will be
surprised by the magnitude of this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, the SEC's chief accountant, said he was both
``disappointed and incredulous'' when he learned of the results and
had thought when he was at Coopers that the rules barring
investments in audit clients were understood and obeyed. The report
said that noncompliance had been widespread at both Coopers and
Price Waterhouse before they merged, and that fewer than half of
the violations related to conflicts created by the 1998 merger,
which meant that partners of each old firm had to sell investments
in clients of the other firm. The report was prepared by Jess
Fardella, a partner in the New York law firm of Lankler, Siffert &AMP;
Wohl, at the SEC's request.
</P>
<P>
   Independent auditors' reports on corporate financial statements
are important to the structure of financial markets and are
required of companies that sell securities in this country. Since
the 1930s, SEC and accounting profession rules have barred auditors
from having investments in companies audited by their firms. But
those rules have always been left to the firms to administer, with
little oversight by the SEC or any other organization.
</P>
<P>
   An SEC spokesman said the investigation was continuing, but
declined to say whether any enforcement actions were likely.
</P>
<P>
   James Copeland, the chief executive of Deloitte &AMP; Touche,
another major accounting firm, said in a telephone interview
Thursday that the firm continually emphasized the need for
independence. ``We do believe that our policies and procedures are
effective,'' he said. ``But in an organization of 30,000 people, it
would probably be unrealistic to suggest you won't have any
instances of noncompliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of PricewaterhouseCoopers began in 1997, after
the SEC received a tip that independence rules had been violated in
the Tampa, Fla., office of Coopers. That led to an SEC censure of
the firm and a finding that three people in the Tampa office had
owned stock in four companies audited by that office.
</P>
<P>
   That was viewed as an aberration when the enforcement action was
announced early last year, but as part of the penalty, the SEC
required that PricewaterhouseCoopers pay for the review by
Fardella.
</P>
<P>
   The Fardella report did not name any PricewaterhouseCoopers
partners who had violated independence rules, nor did it identify
the companies whose audits were involved, because no disciplinary
charges have been brought. But the earlier Tampa case led to the
SEC's forcing some companies to change auditors. One of those
companies, the Pediatrix Medical Group, later saw its stock plummet
after the new auditing firm raised questions about the company's
accounting procedures, which were subsequently changed. The stock
has not recovered, although there were other issues than accounting
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Fardella asked PricewaterhouseCoopers partners to review their
investments over the last two years, and to report any that were
not in compliance with the rules. Nearly half the 2,698 partners,
1,301, found at least one violation, with an average of five
violations.
</P>
<P>
   The Fardella firm then chose 200 partners at random to study in
detail. It found that 77.5 percent of them ``failed to self-report
at least one independence violation,'' despite being told the SEC
was carefully watching the situation. His report estimated that
86.5 percent of all partners had committed at least one violation,
and said that reflected ``serious structural and cultural
problems'' at PricewaterhouseCoopers and its predecessor firms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brown, the chairman of the accounting department at the
Stern School of Business at New York University, said the results
of the study were surprising. ``The firm gave their partners such a
heads-up here and were saying we are going to be under such great
scrutiny, that you should take this very seriously,'' he said.
``For a set of partners to do that, it seems like the firm has not
put independence on the level that is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The independence rules are complicated, and apply to investments
held not only by partners and other employees of accounting firms,
but also by their immediate families. They bar all significant
investments in companies that the firm audits, or in mutual funds
whose investment advisers are audited by the firm. Some cases were
clearly inadvertent, such as a partner whose checking account was
in a bank audited by PricewaterhouseCoopers, and who failed to
quickly reduce the balance after it rose over the insured limit of
$100,000 as a result of a payment by the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Partners are allowed to own mutual funds that are not audited by
the firm, even if the fund owns shares in companies that the firm
audits. But some partners mistakenly assumed that exemption carried
over to unit investment trusts, a form of investment similar to
mutual funds. When Price Waterhouse merged with Coopers and Lybrand
in 1998, the partners had a month to divest investments that were
newly prohibited because they were on the list at the other firm.
Nearly half the violations related to delays in making such
dispositions.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that many of the partners and other employees
who broke the rules had tried to abide by them, and criticized the
firm's compliance system for not making compliance easier. But it
added that some partners had made little effort to comply.
</P>
<P>
   The new PricewaterhouseCoopers system involves a computerized
list of all securities in the country, with an indication of which
securities are barred on independence grounds. All employees will
be required to report all holdings and transactions, which will
then be monitored to assure compliance and to require sales if a
new audit client comes aboard with whom there is a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for two other major accounting firms, KPMG and Ernst &AMP;
Young, said their firms had strong policies in effect. ``We have
rigorous procedures and policies in place, which we take very
seriously and continually monitor and improve,'' said George
Ledwith, a spokesman for KPMG. Les Zuke, a spokesman for Ernst &AMP;
Young, said the firm had ``an effective system for monitoring the
independence of its professionals, a system that is now electronic
and continually updated for accuracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
