<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BOX-AYALA-DEFENSE-TEX     01-06 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULIE AYALA TO DEFEND WBA TITLE MARCH 4 IN LAS VEGAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ World Boxing Association bantamweight
champion Paulie Ayala is close to finalizing an agreement to fight
Johnny Bredahl of Denmark on March 4 in Las Vegas for his second
title defense.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains to be negotiated is the purse, according to
Shawn Ayala, Paulie's brother and vice president of Boxing
Management, Inc. BMI is seeking a purse near $400,000 for Ayala to
face the WBA's No. 4 contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it seems to me is that Top Rank (Ayala's promoter) is
throwing everyone at Paulie,'' Shawn Ayala said Thursday. ``They
sought the No. 2 and No. 3, but they were busy. Going down the list
is basically what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ayala-Bredahl bout is scheduled to be the main event of a
TVKO pay-per-view card that also features Nestor Garza vs. Danny
Romero in a 12-rounder for Garza's WBA super bantamweight title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it will be all worked out,'' said Paulie Ayala
(29-1, 12 knockouts). ``I never watched him (Bredahl), but I know
of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He challenged me, but right now everyone out there is trying
to challenge me. Everyone wants to beat the world champion. I'm not
taking this guy for granted. His record and ranking speak for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ayala, the 5-foot-9 Bredahl (45-1, 23 KOs), is a
left-hander. He is the European Boxing Union and International
Boxing Organization bantamweight champion but never has fought
outside of Denmark. His list of minor championship titles includes
WBO junior bantamweight and World Boxing Union bantamweight belts.
His only loss was against Wayne McCullough in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In his last bout, Bredahl stopped Paul Lloyd in the first round
on Oct. 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, 29, won the WBA title at 118 pounds with a unanimous
12-round decision against Johnny Tapia on June 23 in Las Vegas. He
defended the title against the WBA's No. 1 contender, Soahin
Srithai Condo, on Oct. 23 in Fort Worth. Ayala was named ``The Ring
Magazine'''s Fighter of the Year for 1999, and his bout against
Tapia was selected as Fight of the Year. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
