<HEADLINE>
ATTITUDE LIFTS TEXAS FRESHMAN WHEN KNEE WON'T
</HEADLINE>
 12 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assassinations and natural disasters aside, we all have those
moments in our lives that _ sometimes no matter how hard we try _
we never forget.
</P>
<P>
   For Texas freshman William Wyatt, that incident happened Dec.
11, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two minutes into the second half,'' Wyatt said with pinpoint
recall. ``We were playing the Mesquite Skeeters. I was on a fast
break and a dude cut in front of me. I jumped to my left, and I
felt something snap in my right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking, `No. This can't be happening to me.' I
knew what it was, but it was a denial thing at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven games into his junior season at South Grand Prairie, a
player who even at that stage of his development was regarded as
one of the top five players in the state, was threatened by serious
knee injury. He suffered a torn anterior cruciate ligament, an
injury he knew could have a far-reaching effect. An attempted
comeback that season after surgery failed. As a senior, he had to
be content with doing what he could, which was still better than
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hadn't gotten hurt, there's no telling what (the team)
could have done,'' South Grand Prairie coach Mike Rogers said.
``Last season, he kind of just drug his leg around and never was
near full strength. He was still good enough to make a difference,
but it would have been interesting to see what kind of player he
would be today if he had gotten a full junior and senior year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt, a 6-foot-7, 220-pound forward, might still accomplish
some things. After three operations _ the latest in September _
Wyatt has fought his way into the inside rotation on one of the Big
12's best teams. Wyatt played a season-high 13 minutes Thursday
night aghainst Baylor, bring his three-game total to 29 minutes. He
has scored six points, pulled down 10 rebounds and has two steals
as Rick Barnes has used him as a defensive tool in the inside
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt can't do the things he once could, and, even if he could,
his playing time would be limited this season because of the
Longhorns' depth. But he says that he can recapture full mobility
and expand on a wealth of talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I want to bring to this team this year is my defense
and intensity,'' Wyatt said. ``I know I can do little things to
help this team win. What I have to do is take things day by day and
not look at the years that might be ahead. If I don't do that,
there might not be a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this has been hard, because when I was young I had it all.
Now that I've had to work at it, it's made me appreciate things.
It's humbled me a little bit and made me want to work for
something. And I know I can get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Wyatt's future doesn't depend on the knee, on which
he continues to get daily treatment. Wyatt, whom Rogers predicts
will be the Texas governor some day, graduated in the top
percentile of his high school class and was courted by Stanford. He
is an impressive young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many kids are as focused,'' Texas strength and
conditioning coach Todd Wright said. ``His attitude alone will
carry him a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that attitude that first attracted Barnes and kept him
focused on Wyatt even after the injury. That attitude also helped
Barnes determine in the limited exposure of September's individual
workouts _ when clean-up surgery was deemed necessary _ that this
kid could help. Now.
JAYHAWKS' KENNY G. IS IN TUNE WITH OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Kansas coach Roy Williams said the fact that
Kenny Gregory was the MVP of the 1997 McDonald's Classic was
probably the worst thing that could have happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were already high in Lawrence as fans anticipated
the arrival of the athletic Ohio player of the year. They
skyrocketed after Gregory's showing in the McDonald's high school
all-star game, usually an up-and-down affair with only a semblance
of defense. The game suited what Gregory does best: run the open
court, dunk and sweep the offensive glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``People got even higher about him,'' Williams said. ``Even
though it was a great experience for him that day, it was probably
a bad thing to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory developed back problems his freshman year, keeping him
from living up to lofty initial expectations, and battled back and
knee problems last season, though he finished third in scoring
(11.3 points per game) on an injury-depleted roster.
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't look now, but the ninth-ranked Jayhawks are playing
right to the strength of the high-flying 6-foot-5 winger with a
41-inch vertical leap. He's leading a deep Kansas lineup in scoring
(14.7 points per game) and field-goal percentage (.618), and his
open-court antics are a featured part of the Jayhawks' running
game. Kenny G. and the Allen Fieldhouse crowds are loving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely having more fun than last season,'' Gregory
said. ``We're scoring more and getting the tempo up. With the depth
we have this year, that (style) helps both me and some of the other
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory doesn't have to force his jumper as he did sometimes
last season when Kansas was point-starved and most everyone was
being asked to do diverse things and play long minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My strengths are taking it to the basket and getting to the
offensive boards,'' Gregory said. ``I'm trying to play within my
game and do what I am capable of. But overall, the thing I'm
enjoying most is that we have a lot better team, we're winning a
lot more and I'm playing with a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   IN THE LANE
LONG DISTANCE. PLEASE!
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 through 1999, few teams could shoot 3s with the Texas
Tech Lady Raiders. Guards Rene Hanebutt and Julie Lake bombarded
the nets 984 times from beyond the arc and 396 of those shots found
net. They made Tech the Big 12's most dangerous 3-point shooting
team in 1997 and '99.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hanebutt &AMP; Lake Shooting Circus has moved on, and they
took Tech's 3-point game with them.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders made only 3 of 21 3-pointers against Iowa
State's zone in Sunday's 62-37 loss. Last year, Tech defeated the
Cyclones twice and made 18 of 38 in the process. This season, Tech
is only the seventh-best 3-point shooting team in the Big 12,
hitting 31.8 percent, which has dragged their overall shooting
percentage to a ninth-best 43.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, it's a concern,'' coach Marsha Sharp said. ``We've
tried to compensate by attacking the basket and rely on our
offensive rebounding, to use our athleticism to get to the basket
rather than rely on the perimeter game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders are an athletic team. They can run and play
defense. But lack of an outside threat could endanger the Lady
Raiders' hope for an 11th consecutive NCAA Tournament berth.
STICKING WITH CHENOWITH
</P>
<P>
   Kansas coach Roy Williams admitted he was considering a lineup
change last week as center Eric Chenowith continued to struggle.
Some fans have been clamoring for Williams to start impressive
freshman Drew Gooden, who is the team's leading rebounder.
Chenowith was booed during a four-point performance in eight
minutes against Saint Louis last week at Kansas City's Kemper
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Chenowith is averaging 9.8 points per game, down four points
from last season, and he has not played with much confidence. But
Tuesday night, Chenowith scored 14 points on 7-for-10 shooting
against Penn, and life for the moment looks good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told coach Williams in the locker room thanks for sticking
with me,'' Chenowith said. ``I'm sure a lot of coaches would have
changed the starting lineup. This was fun. It was the first time
I've smiled on the court in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenowith received a standing ovation during the Penn game and
received a vote of confidence from Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more impressed with Eric than I have ever been,'' Williams
said. ``The booing in the crowd at Kemper the other night ... yet
he's continued to try. I couldn't be happier for anybody.''
FREE THROWS
</P>
<P>
   The debut of Texas Tech transfer Moses Malone Jr. in Monday's
walk over Prairie View A&AMP;M was predictably uneventful. He continues
to slowly work back into playing shape while recovering from a
stress fracture in a foot. He did not score in seven minutes, had
two fouls and one turnover. But sophomore Andy Ellis is on a tear
heading into tomorrow's Big 12 opener at Oklahoma State, averaging
23.3 and 13.7 rebounds in his past three games. His 20 rebounds
against Prairie View were the fifth-best total nationally this
season. He hit a double-double (13 points, 10 rebounds) with 9:14
left in the first half on his way to a 25/20 game.
</P>
<P>
   Texas expects to hear this afternoon from the NCAA Clearinghouse
on the eligibility of guard Roosevelt Brown, a freshman from
Duncanville. Iowa State's Stacy Frese was the consensus preseason
pick for Big 12 women's player of the year, but Texas' Edwina Brown
has had the most impressive nonconference season. Brown is leading
the league in scoring (22.9 points per game), is fourth in assists
(5.9) and is 10th in rebounding (8.1). And those totals have not
been padded by competition against weak teams. In four games
against Top 25 competition (Tennessee, UCLA, Illinois and Rutgers),
Brown is averaging 22.7 points and 5.9 rebounds and is shooting 54
percent. Nebraska guard Cookie Belcher is now officially out for
the season _ according to coach Danny Nee _ unable to recover from
the surgery that re-attached two torn ligaments in his right
(shooting) hand. Add Tech forward Cliff Owens (ankle) and Kansas
State guard Josh Reid (Dec. 27 surgery to put a pin in a broken
bone in his foot) to the list of pivotal players out for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas sophomore guard Jeff Boschee was ranked No. 30 among the
top 50 sport figures of all-time in North Dakota by Sports
Illustrated.
By the numbers MAKING THEIR POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State pounded Langston, 125-65, Wednesday. Some
statistical highlights: 125 _ Cowboys' second-highest point total,
behind 127 against Santa Fe in 1977 28 _ career-high point total by
forward Brian Montonati 25 _ career-high point total by guard
Glendon Alexander with a career-high seven 3-pointers 18 _ career
high point total by point guard Doug (good-field, no-hit) Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't hurt you any,'' coach Eddie Sutton said on the
benefits of playing Langston. ``But I don't know how much good it
does you.'' nn
</P>
