<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY WAS SUPER DAY FOR DERBY HOPEFUL
</HEADLINE>
 RACING REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When anyone finds out you've been to the racetrack on a Sunday
in January, they've got to be wondering what you possibly could be
doing at such a place at that time of the year. You must be
slacking off.
</P>
<P>
   Live racing won't start at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie for
another three months. The Breeders' Cup finished in November. The
Kentucky Derby isn't until May.
</P>
<P>
   With as much football on television as there was on Sunday, what
could be accomplished with a trip to the racetrack?
</P>
<P>
   If no one knew what Arthur Hancock III does for a living, they'd
be asking him such a question. A breeder of racehorses, even
Hancock wasn't able to get out to the track on Sunday. But he
didn't sit at home and watch football. He was able to get an audio
race call from Santa Anita Park.
</P>
<P>
   With a cluster of football around him, Hancock, though, may have
heard the start of history. And what better time to be around
history than to catch it in its first moments.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old colt with a long, easy stride named Fusaichi
Pegasus won his first race on Sunday. Hancock didn't see a bit of
it, but the words he heard on the audio of the race from track
caller Trevor Denman's South African accent made him know it was an
impressive performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard him say that the colt was `exuding class' and then
that the colt couldn't have won it any easier,'' Hancock said. ``I
knew we had a good one then.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, who nearly broke his maiden in his career
debut against a talented horse named David Copperfield, won on
Sunday while covering 6 furlongs in 1 minute, 10 4-5 seconds. Older
horses covered the same distance in almost identical time later in
the day, but the winner didn't travel three-wide around the turn
like Fusaichi Pegasus. Plus, that horse's rider asked for more _
Kent Desormeaux barely moved a hand over Fusaichi Pegasus while the
colt galloped along on his own.
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of horse racing can take a horse and make him as
useful as a pail full of bent nails. But Hancock, who has bred
horses such as Gato Del Sol, Sunday Silence and Menifee, might have
brought us one this time around who's better than anyone in that
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has been years in the making. Though Hancock
bred him along with Stonerside Farm ( owned by Houston NFL
franchise owner Bob McNair), Fusaichi Pegasus actually is a part of
the influence put on the horse racing industry by Arkansas
lumberman John Ed Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus is out of a mare named Angel Fever, who is a
full sister to former Preakness winner Pine Bluff and a half sister
to Arkansas Derby winner Demons Begone, both bred and owned by
Anthony. He eventually sold Angel Fever after she was injured
shortly into her racing career. Hancock and McNair spent $525,000
for her, and she produced Fusaichi Pegasus when bred to Mr.
Prospector.
</P>
<P>
   The colt didn't pick up the name until after they sold him. And
that was more than a year ago, when a Japanese businessman, Susaos
Sekiguchi, bought him for $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now this thing should start sounding familiar. The last time the
Triple Crown chase saw a high-dollar horse this talented owned by a
Japanese businessman was in 1992 when A.P. Indy (he cost $2.9
million as a yearling) was running around. Neil Drysdale trained
A.P. Indy, and he's got Fusaichi Pegasus now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse has been awesome from the time he hit the ground,''
Hancock said. ``I called Bob \RMcNair\S the night this colt was
born and I told him that we had Superman here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in super hands with Neil. After I talked with him the
last time, I shot my mouth off and said this is the best horse I've
ever raised. If he's not, I won't make another prediction in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Hancock will go quiet after the Kentucky Derby. But this
much we know: The horse was worth a trip to the racetrack on a
Sunday in January.
DOGGING SAM HOUSTON
</P>
<P>
   Sam Houston Race Park handled about $25 million on wagers from
simulcasts of greyhound races last year, but state law doesn't
force Sam Houston to pay any of that money to the horsemen who race
in Houston. That's why the Texas Horsemen's Partnership is asking
the Texas Racing Commission to determine if any of the money can
put in horse owners' accounts or to halt the simulcasting if they
can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll ask the commission if the horsemen have the right to say
what simulcasts the tracks can bring in,'' said Tommy Azopardi,
executive director of the Texas Horsemen's Partnership. ``I think
they'll say we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Azopardi said it might not go that far. He said Sam Houston
senior vice president Bob Bork wants to offer a deal in order to
keep the greyhound simulcasts going.
CASNER BUYING FARM
</P>
<P>
   Prestonwood Farm, which stands the influential sire Kris S. and
has campaigned Belmont Stakes winner Victory Gallop and two-time
Breeders' Cup Mile champ Da Hoss, is close to being sold to a
partnership that includes Bill Casner of Southlake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to close on it by today,'' Casner said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it looks as though Art, Jack and J.R. Preston might sell
the Lexington, Ky., farm, they plan to continue racing. Casner, who
owns a part of Bet Me Best along with the Prestons, is joining with
telecommunications executive Ken Troutt to buy the farm. Casner and
Troutt spent $9.3 million on 18 horses at the Keeneland November
Sale.
</P>
<P>
   SURFSIDE'S UP
</P>
<P>
   Surfside, third in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies and recent
winner of the $400,000 Hollywood Starlet, is expected to race
Sunday in the $100,000 Santa Ysabel Stakes over 1 1/16 miles at
Santa Anita Park. Del Mar Futurity winner Forest Camp is expected
for tomorrow's $100,000 San Miguel Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Santa Anita this week, General Challenge worked 7
furlongs in 1 minute, 23 4-5 seconds this week compared with the
1:25 4-5 that was turned in by both Budroyale and Puerto Madero.
</P>
<P>
   SCARED OF EARLY GOER
</P>
<P>
   The folks in Louisiana want no part of Early Goer. The
undefeated colt was expected to race in today's $40,000 Erwin
Memorial Stakes at 6 furlongs for Louisiana-breds at Fair Grounds,
but the race was canceled when there weren't enough horses entered.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Hebert, trainer of Early Goer, hopes to take on
Louisiana-breds again in the $75,000 Crescent City Derby on Jan.
22. He'll probably find enough takers this time since it will be
Early Goer's first trip around two turns.
</P>
<P>
   BARN GREETS ASMUSSEN WITH LEADING NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Just as everyone was getting used to Scott Blasi being in the
winner's circle, Steve Asmussen is coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Asmussen ends his 45-day suspension Sunday when he returns as
trainer of record for horses owned by the Ackerley Brothers Stable
and a number of other clients racing at the Fair Grounds in New
Orleans. Blasi, a Kansas native who is Asmussen's top assistant,
handled the horses during Asmussen's absence.
</P>
<P>
   He did quite nicely with his opportunity. According to
statistics at Fair Grounds, Blasi is the leading trainer at the
current meet through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of the job Scott and everyone else has done,''
Asmussen said. ``They did a good job all of last year, not just the
past couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Asmussen, 36, was suspended by the board of stewards last year
at Fair Grounds after a horse from his barn tested for a substance
containing painkiller properties.
</P>
<P>
   He has kept up with Fair Grounds' races through a satellite dish
at his home near Laredo. He is kept busy by working at his family's
horse training facility in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets to New Orleans, he has some proven prospects ready
for big races at Fair Grounds. Undefeated Littleexpectations might
try two turns in the Lecomte Stakes on Jan. 29, and Gallery
Furniture Texan Juvenile winner Snuck In is expected for the Risen
Star Stakes on Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 30 to 60 days for Littleexpectations is going to tell
us a lot,'' Asmussen said. ``He's a little lighter colt that should
develop, and I don't expect he'll have the same distance
limitations'' as his stakes-winning sprinting sibling Little
Sister.
</P>
<P>
   BLASI TOPS FAIR GROUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Now that Steve Asmussen will be handling his trainer duties at
Fair Grounds, the leading trainer standings will soon change.
Asmussen's top assistant, Scott Blasi, goes back to his assistant
trainer duties in Asmussen's barn. Blasi had the lead in the Fair
Grounds trainer standings through Wednesday. Trainer Starts Wins
Pct. Purse money Scott Blasi 41 13 .317 $346,430 Michael Stidham 36
12 .333 $222,690 Tom Amoss 54 9 .167 $185,772 Al Stall Jr. 44 8
.182 $166,905 Michael Doyle 36 8 .222 $124,698 Sam David 38 7 .184
$128,780
</P>
</TEXT>
