<HEADER>
A9057 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RECS-$     01-06 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RECS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 COLLEGE PREP: DEAR ADMISSIONS COMMITTEE... 
</HEADLINE>
  (For publication Sunday, Jan. 9) 
(mk) 
 (Glenn C. Altschuler is both the dean of the School of Continuing
Education and Summer Sessions and the Thomas and Dorothy Litwin
Professor of American Studies at Cornell University.) 
By GLENN C. ALTSCHULER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, a colleague asked for my advice about his son's
application to Harvard. He suspected a teacher had written a
less-than-stellar letter of recommendation and wondered whether he
should call undergraduate admissions in Cambridge to try to
persuade a secretary to yank it from the boy's folder.
</P>
<P>
   Professors of politics may be more paranoid than parents in
other professions, and considerably more Machiavellian. But in the
importance he attached to the letter of recommendation, my
colleague was no different from thousands of high school students
and interested adults.
</P>
<P>
   He need not have worried. Most recommendations do not help, and
they virtually never harm, college applicants.
</P>
<P>
   William Hiss, the vice president for administrative services at
Bates College, advised students and teachers as dean of admissions
for 20 years. Hiss tells teachers to be ``cautious about making
red-flag comments'' about a student's personal and disciplinary
problems. One misstep, and litigation is likely, he says, citing
the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act, Americans With
Disabilities Act and state statutes on the confidentiality of
discipline records.
</P>
<P>
   On academic matters, too, the epistolary equivalent of grade
inflation has set in. As a member of Cornell University's
admissions committee for a decade, I would search applications in
vain for even subordinate clauses like ``While Susan did not
participate often in discussions.'' With such Boy Scout merit-badge
recommendations as ``Josh is courteous, kind, resourceful, thrifty
and brave,'' to quote one recent submission to Cornell, little
wonder most letters have no impact on the fate of an applicant.
</P>
<P>
   In an informal survey of several dozen high school teachers last
semester, almost all said they see their role as helping students
get into the college of their choice, not helping institutions
select the best-qualified candidates. They also write upbeat
letters for anyone who asks. (Popular teachers might evaluate three
dozen students a year; guidance counselors as many as 150.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I emphasize the best qualities I perceive,'' said one
advanced-placement history teacher at Norman Thomas High School in
Manhattan. ``I ignore the negative, even when I'm well aware of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The results are brief essays that differ little, if at all, from
one another. With so many recommendations opening with, ``The first
words that come to mind when I think of X are...,'' one wonders if
there's a software package out there facilitating the formulaic.
Gerry Cox, an admissions dean at Cornell, says he dismisses
missives with generic content when considering applicants. ``The
more they sound alike, the less difference they make,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some letters, however, do make a difference. While no
recommendation will complete a Hail Mary pass, in colleges and
universities with many more applicants than spaces in the freshman
class, a thoughtful, detailed letter can make a qualified student
stand out.
</P>
<P>
   But pressed for time and inspiration, teachers may need help in
this mission. Instructions on application forms are vague. Cornell,
which guarantees confidentiality by promising teachers it will
``destroy all subjective evaluations after the selection process is
over,'' asks only for candid comments on ``intellectual and
personal promise'' and ``qualities that make this candidate
unique.''
</P>
<P>
   To increase your chances of getting an effective recommendation,
you do not have to take your daughter's social studies teacher out
to dinner come application time, as a set of panicked parents at
Scarsdale (N.Y.)High School recently did. Here are a few dos and
don'ts for students and teachers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Waive your right to see letters written on your behalf. The
risk that the contents are damaging is slight, and admissions
committee members give greater credibility to confidential
communications.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not submit more than two or three letters, unless you are
certain they are all insightful gems. There is much truth in the
admissions adage, ``The thicker the folder, the thicker the
applicant.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Unless they know you, do not solicit letters from graduates of
the university to which you are applying, your parents' business or
law partners, members of Congress, governors, ex-presidents of the
United States or titans of telecommunications. A recommendation
letter from an eminent person who is not well acquainted with you
will be a perfunctory testimonial. Remember, too, that generous
donors have an impact, if at all, only on the applications of their
own children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers can help if they supervised you themselves. A few
years ago, a roofer wrote about a young man from a comfortably
middle-class family who had worked as a manual laborer one summer,
carrying shingles up the ladders to the more skilled roofers. To
the surprise of his boss, ``the kid'' worked without complaint
through stifling heat when several of the more experienced crew
groused, took long lunches and asked to leave early. I have seen
few letters address motivation more effectively. Cornell admitted
the young man.
</P>
<P>
   _ The most influential letters of recommendation are filled with
concrete details and a comparative assessment of the applicant.
Supply teachers with copies of essays you have written for their
classes, descriptions of science projects and other quotable
material. Perhaps you'll get a letter like this one, submitted with
an application to Brown University: ``Stefan used spirituals,
sermons and slave narratives in an essay about dissimulation,
double-entendre and psychological resistance among
African-Americans before the Civil War. Deftly crafting his own
interpretation of the slave personality, he was unafraid to
challenge the assumptions of the distinguished scholars Stanley
Elkins and Eugene Genovese. The result was one of the two finest
papers in the junior class.'' Brown accepted the student, even
though his high school grades were not outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   _ The same specificity can be used to describe activities
outside of class, as this recent recommendation did from a teacher
at the Commonwealth School in Boston: ``Noah was the organizing
spirit behind our weekly luncheon discussion group that brought
speakers to the school. The kind of student who read the whole
book, even when a chapter is assigned, Noah was the most incisive
and well-informed questioner in such public assemblies, whether the
speaker was a law professor or an ecology activist.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If teachers ask for your high school transcript and a list of
extracurricular activities, remind them, in a tone that is at once
deferential, diplomatic and direct, that either a guidance
counselor will make a general assessment, or members of the
admissions committee will have this information and can interpret
it for themselves. Ask the teachers instead to focus on particular
academic and personal skills drawn from observation in the
classroom and evaluation of exams, essays and lab assignments.
</P>
<P>
   _ With recommendations, as with every other component of a
college application, strategy and tactics are no substitute for
performance. Those who do their very best give their teachers the
material for an excellent evaluation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
