<HEADLINE>
WINNING HOMESTAND HELPS STARS REBOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Suddenly, the defending Stanley Cup champions
have the home fire stoked again.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars already have more home losses (nine) this
season than all of last season (eight), but they enter Friday
night's sixth and final game of the homestand with a 4-1 record. In
four games since a 3-1 loss to San Jose, the Stars have scored 15
goals and moved six games above .500 and into a three-way tie for
the Pacific Division lead with 48 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked up our game on the road a little bit and coming home
for six games we knew that it was going to be a critical part of
our schedule,'' defenseman Jamie Pushor said. ``It's definitely
important to get your points now. It's tough to get them in March
and April, so it's definitely a focus of ours.'' GAVEY SHRUGS OFF
GOAL
</P>
<P>
   Forward Aaron Gavey didn't get off to the start he would have
liked in his first game back from the Michigan K-Wings. In the
first period, his pass from behind the Stars' net bounced off Jamie
Pushor's skate, then Pushor's pass nicked off Gavey's skate and
onto the stick of Nashville's Scott Walker in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's shot hit the right post then went off the back of
goalie Manny Fernandez's leg and into the net to give Nashville a
1-0 lead. Gavey looked up as if to say, ``Give me a break.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of the game,'' Gavey said. ``The last thing
I'm going to do while I'm here is worry about things that happen,
I'm just going to play. I thought I played a pretty good game last
night and the team played well.'' INJURY UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Roman Lyashenko is expected to return to action
Friday against Vancouver. The Stars played without three centers
Wednesday: Lyashenko, Joe Nieuwendyk and Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland is likely to miss two months, but Nieuwendyk is close
to returning, Ken Hitchcock said Thursday. He took part on the
power play and the rush in practice Thursday, but with little
contact. After Friday's game, Nieuwendyk will have three practices
to prepare for the upcoming six-game, 13-day road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Grant Marshall also is expected to return Friday or
during the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's past the rehab stage; he's into full practice, and it's
now our evaluation when we think he's ready,'' coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``He's given the coaching staff the green light.''
</P>
<P>
   How defenseman Richard Matvichuk feels might determine if
Marshall sees ice time Friday. Matvichuk left Wednesday's game
after the first period with the flu and he did not practice
Thursday. Hitchcock expects him to play Friday, but said if
Matvichuk is not 100 percent, he would likely opt to play seven
defensemen as he did against Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see how this group on defense feels,'' Hitchcock
said. ``If Matty feels he can only give limited minutes, I don't
think it is smart for us to go back and play with six again. We're
better off playing with seven.'' CHARITABLE STARS
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars Foundation donated $10,000 to Scottish Rite
Hospital in Dallas on Thursday. The grant is for the hospital's
sled hockey program to purchase sleds and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Stars president Jim Lites made the presentation at the hospital
with members of the United States Paralympic Sled Hockey Team. The
U.S. team is to face the DFW Sled Hockey Foundation team in an
exhibition game after the Stars' game Friday at Reunion Arena. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
