<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9062 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURN     01-06 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NORTHAMPTON: its uncertainties. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adrienne McAlpine, 41, said she found dating a challenge, given
her living situation at Cutter House. ``What do you say to a guy?
How would you like to come over to . . . my dorm?' ''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled: ``I was in the bathroom brushing my teeth, and all
of a sudden, there was a man coming out of the stall. I thought,
`Wow, when I was their age, I would have been petrified if that
happened.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ms. Jordan and Ms. Marlowe lived on the fifth floor
of the Northrup House dormitory. Ms. Marlowe's room was 7 feet by 9
feet. There was no elevator. ``It's like military service,'' she
said. ``I'm proud I served, but I wasn't crazy enough to reup for
another term.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the time they're driving me crazy,'' Ms. Marlowe said,
referring to the trads. ``They have purple hair, their music is
loud. But the other half I think, `The country is in good hands.'
''
</P>
<P>
   As for the tattooing and piercing common among the trads, Mrs.
Land said she barely notices that anymore. ``It's a good learning
experience,'' she said. ``It's a lot like when we used to wear our
sweaters backward, and my father never could understand.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ms. Jordan and Ms. Marlowe are sharing a spacious
two-bedroom apartment just off campus. Mrs. Land and Mrs.
Martindell have apartments in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Land's sunny one-bedroom is filled with secondhand
furniture _ her husband's MIT chair, her son Stephen's desk, her
son David's chairs. Most Thursdays, she collects her books, closes
up the apartment and drives two hours home to Westport. There, she
resumes her responsibilities as a wife, doing her husband's laundry
and the grocery shopping and cooking. Since her husband stays in
Manhattan while she is at Smith, she prepares food he can take back
to the city in small containers, like chicken Parmesan, chicken
salad, applesauce and hash.
</P>
<P>
   She might go to a craft show with her daughter Ellie, or kayak
with Stephen. It can be hard to find time to study.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Land _ who has been president of a PTA and the Westport
Young Women's League, served on the board of a regional mental
health organization and worked with unmarried teen-age mothers in
Bridgeport, Conn. _ made the dean's list last year. She will
graduate this spring, three years after her granddaughter Elizabeth
Humphries finished.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Colvard, graduation is, thankfully, several years off.
``If I had my druthers, I'd spend the next 10 years here,'' she
said. ``All the trads are talking about what they're going to do
when they get out of here. I've been out of here. I've done out of
here. I want to be in here for a while.'' &QC; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   STUDY OPTIONS FOR WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   Many private women's colleges offer programs for students beyond
age 22 who want to complete a bachelor's degree or start anew, part
or full time. The women are integrated into the college community,
and can even live on campus. They attend classes with
traditional-age students and are held to the same academic
standards, although for admission, extra weight is given to life
and work experiences. The following programs have students in their
60s, 70s and even 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Scott College, Atlanta: Return to College Program.
Previous college course work is not required but strongly preferred
for admission to this program. Campus housing is not available for
nontraditional students. Current enrollment: 90. (800) 868-8602;
admission(at)agnesscott.edu; www.agnesscott.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Bryn Mawr College, Bryn Mawr, Pa.: Katharine E. McBride Scholars
Program. Bryn Mawr accepts women returning to college or entering
for the first time, with ``credentials of life experience, wisdom,
sharpened focus and a seasoned enthusiasm for learning,'' according
to its literature. Although the program expects its students to
enroll in the same rigorous course of study as other
undergraduates, poor school records from the past do not preclude
admission. Current enroll-ment: 56. (610) 526-5152;
admissions(at)brynmawr.edu; www.brynmawr.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, Mass.: Frances Perkins
Program. Students can complete requirements for bachelor of arts
degrees. Although admissions standards are similar to those of
other applicants to Mount Holyoke, and recent coursework is
evaluated, there is ``a recognition that previous academic records
do not always define the current potential of an applicant.'' Women
younger than 24 can apply if they are veterans or have dependents.
Current enrollment: 155. (413) 538-2077;
frances-perkins(at)mtholyoke.edu; www.mtholyoke.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph-Macon Woman's College, Lynchburg, Va.:
</P>
<P>
   Prime Time Program.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates must be at least 25 years old and have taken some
college courses or have ``exceptional accomplishments,'' said Susan
Timmons, the program director. Current enrollment: 67. (804)
947-8141;
</P>
<P>
   stimmons(at)rmwc.edu; www.rmwc.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Smith College, Northampton, Mass.: Ada Comstock Scholars
Program. This program is designed for women seeking to complete a
bachelor's degree ``at a realistic pace,'' according to college
literature. Women younger than 24 can apply if they are veterans or
have dependents. Current enrollment: 207. (413) 585-3090;
comtock(at)smith.edu; www.smith.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley College, Wellesley, Mass.: The Elizabeth Kaiser Davis
Degree Program. Most participants have been in the work force, and
although it is not required, some college experience is preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Women can earn a degree on ``whatever time schedule they have,''
said Shelagh Dunlap, the assistant dean of continuing education.
Current
</P>
<P>
   enrollment: 120. (781) 283-2270; wscor(at)wellesley.edu;
www.wellesley.edu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
