<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTY DEBATE COVERS TAXES, ETHICS, RELIGION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ George W. Bush and John McCain tangled over
campaign finance reform and taxes in a feisty, freewheeling GOP
presidential debate Thursday that covered ethics, gays in the
military, religion in politics and the fate of a Cuban boy.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes were particularly high for the leading GOP
presidential contenders with polls showing the two locked in a
tight battle in New Hampshire, which holds its primary election
Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was more aggressive than in previous encounters, pledging
``to cut taxes, so help me God,'' and stressing his experience as
Texas governor. While McCain vowed to continue his fight for
campaign finance reform, he also found himself trying to explain
his decision to help a large contributor get a decision on a permit
from a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although the focus was on the leading contenders, the other four
candidates, conservative activists Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes,
magazine publisher Steve Forbes and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, also
delivered their share of verbal punches during the hourlong debate
at the University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The barbed exchanges began early as Bush challenged McCain on
his proposal to eliminate unrestricted ``soft money'' to political
parties. He charged that such a move would hurt conservatives and
Republicans who depend on such funds to counter union support for
Democrats, even though McCain's proposal requires organizations
like unions to get permission from members before using their dues
for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's asking us to unilaterally disarm, which I will refuse to
do,'' Bush said. However, the Arizona senator said that eliminating
``soft money'' would also hurt organized labor's ability to help
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain also suggested that Bush did not support campaign
finance reform because he has raised more than $67 million for his
presidential effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy million dollars, and I don't think you have an idea of
how important campaign finance reform is to restore the confidence
of young Americans and their government,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you don't need to do is tell me what I have an idea about
or not,'' Bush responded.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush questioned McCain's key campaign program, the Arizona
senator later slammed the Texas governor's marquee proposal, his
$483 billion tax plan, saying it would sap so much of the federal
budget surplus that there would be no money left to solve the
looming financial problems of Social Security. McCain said he would
use two-thirds of the surplus to pay for the retirement program's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is wise or conservative to take the entire
surplus and put it into tax cuts,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush accused McCain of having a ``Washington mind-set'' and
said his plan would leave enough money to deal with Social
Security. Then, like a schoolyard taunt, McCain repeated that
Bush's proposal would eat up all of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``No it doesn't,'' Bush replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it does,'' retorted McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated his vow to cut taxes, going further than his
father's broken pledge of ``Read my lips. No new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only, `No new taxes' _ this is `Tax cuts, so help
me God,''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor immediately backtracked on that pledge when
moderator Tim Russert pressed Bush as to whether he would raise
taxes in a time of war to ``spend what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, if we go to war,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush differed with McCain on taxes and campaign finance,
he refrained from attacking McCain on recent reports that as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee he interceded on behalf
of a major contributor who was seeking federal approval for a
television license.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has long railed against the influence of special
interests on members of Congress, said he did not regret writing
letters to the Federal Communications Commission on behalf of
Paxson Communication. McCain received $20,000 in contributions from
Paxson executives and has used their corporate jets on the campaign
trail. He is reimbursing Paxson for first-class airfare.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain responded that by interceding on Paxson's behalf, he
was just doing a senator's job ``to make the bureaucrats work for
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do the same thing again at almost any time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, the Republican candidates also plowed through a
minefield of hot-button social issues. Bush was asked to explain
his answer in another debate that Jesus Christ was the political
philosopher with whom he most identified.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was asked whether non-Christians in the country
would feel excluded from his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I was asked what influenced my life, and I gave the answer
that way _ an honest, unvarnished answer,'' he said. ``Some may
accept the answer and some may not. But Tim, I really don't care.
It's me. It's what I'm all about. It's how I live my life.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bush was further pressed on whether he would ``take an
expression like `What would Jesus do' into the Oval Office, '' the
governor answered to laughter, ``I would take an expression in the
Oval Office, of ``Dear God, help me.''
</P>
<P>
   To that Bauer interjected, ``So would we, governor.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also plunged into the latest national
controversy, the decision by the Clinton administration to let the
father of 6-year-old Cuban Elian Gonzalez, rescued off the coast of
Florida, take him back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Only Keyes said the father should be allowed to take his son
back to Cuba if it could be proved that he was not coerced by
communist dictator Fidel Castro. But the others said the boy should
remain in this country, with Forbes suggesting that the Clinton
administration's decision was overtly political.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is Bill Clinton's human sacrifice to Fidel Castro,'' Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also sought to draw contrasts with the Democratic
contenders who in Wednesday's debate pledged to appoint military
leaders who would let gays serve openly in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   While Keyes said he would ban gays from the military, the other
Republican candidates said they supported the current ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy instituted during Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
