<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILM-CRITICS-AWARDS-1     01-06 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRITICS-AWARDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BIG YEAR FOR INDEPENDENT FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to change fourth to sixth in entry for `The Cider House
Rules,' and corrects spelling in same entry to Hallstrom.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which turn-of-the-year movie horse race do you follow? The one
at the box office? Or the stampede of critical 10-best lists that
nudge prestigious films toward Academy Award consideration?
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when ``Saving Private Ryan'' won many critics' polls
and did slam-dunk business, it looked as if Hollywood was gearing
up to steal back some of the critical thunder that has increasingly
accrued to independent films. But this year the tables have turned
again. On Sunday evening when the New York Film Critics Circle
distributes its annual awards at Windows on the World, mainstream
Hollywood will be given a mostly frigid shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it's the year of the independents. ``Topsy-Turvy,''
the British filmmaker Mike Leigh's movie about the making of
Gilbert and Sullivan's ``Mikado,'' won best film and best director.
Hilary Swank was voted best actress for ``Boys Don't Cry,'' the
harrowing true story of the rape and murder of a young woman posing
as a man, and the twisty comedy ``Being John Malkovich'' won three
awards: for best supporting actor (Malkovich), actress (Catherine
Keener) and best first feature (its director, Spike Jonze). Richard
Farnsworth, who won best actor for his performance in David Lynch's
Disney film ``The Straight Story,'' like Ms. Swank, is a nobody by
Hollywood standards.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the rosiest of projections, the cumulative box office of
``Topsy-Turvy,'' ``Boys Don't Cry'' and ``Being John Malkovich''
amount to only a small fraction of what is earned by ``The Green
Mile,'' the mystical tear-jerker that looms as the end-of-year
adult film with the sturdiest box office legs. It's not that
Hollywood failed to deliver some worthy movies into the marketplace
in time for the holiday season. ``American Beauty,'' ``The Straight
Story,'' ``The Insider,'' ``The Hurricane'' and ``Man on the
Moon,'' in particular, earned favorable reviews and Academy Award
buzz. It's that none of them had the all-around clout of ``Saving
Private Ryan'' or ``Titanic,'' to name two recent blockbusters that
came about as close as Hollywood movies can come to being all
things to all people.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a checklist of recommended movies, some independent
and others mainstream, with outstanding performances noted as well
as flaws. The list (which excludes worthy family fare like ``Toy
Story 2'' and ``Stuart Little'') is in descending order of this
critic's preference.
</P>
<P>
   `Topsy-Turvy'
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leigh's finely textured portrait of the 19th-century comic
operetta geniuses William S. Gilbert (Jim Broadbent) and Arthur
Sullivan (Allan Corduner) may be the ultimate backstage drama on
screen. Set at a critical moment (1884) when Sullivan considered
quitting the team to compose ``serious'' music, ``Topsy-Turvy''
contemplates the creative chemistry of a stiff-necked prude
(Gilbert) and a voluptuary (Sullivan) whose faltering collaboration
resumes after Gilbert's wife drags him to an exhibition of Japanese
culture. It results in ``The Mikado,'' which the movie shows being
constructed from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: First-rate acting across the board. Few, if any, films
have so searchingly examined the process of creating a theater
classic from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The fascinatingly detailed rehearsal scenes are a bit
longer than some might wish.
</P>
<P>
   `Boys Don't Cry'
</P>
<P>
   Set in Nebraska and based on true events, the harsh, realistic
drama (with the directorial debut of Kimberly Peirce) tells the
story of Brandon Teena (Hilary Swank), a young female drifter
posing as a man, who is raped and murdered by two of her friends
after they discover her deception. The independent film is a
brutally realistic evocation of macho sexual anxiety exploding into
violence.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Ms. Swank's cocky, boyish Brandon is convincing enough
to pass as a fresh-faced cowpoke. The actress burrows so deeply
into the character's skin that we feel the thrill (and danger) of
her charade. Chloe Sevigny as Brandon's loyal, sleepy-eyed
girlfriend, Lana, who loves Brandon whatever sex he may be, is
gently heart-rending.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The rape scene, one of the most graphic ever filmed, is
not for the squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   `All About My Mother'
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Almodovar has called his newest film a ``screwball
drama.'' And that's exactly what this gender-bending, triple-hankie
homage to ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' ``All About Eve'' and
classic women's pictures turns out to be. Cecilia Roth is a mother
in Madrid who revisits her past in Barcelona after losing her
17-year-old son in a car accident. The Almodovar philosophy is
eloquently (and amusingly) summed up by Agrado (Antonia San Juan),
a tough transsexual prostitute who declares, ``A woman is more
authentic the more she looks like what she has dreamed for
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: The story is intricately structured and continually
surprising, and Ms. Roth's radiant performance encapsulates the
director's radiant compassion.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Almodovar's inflamed, gender-bent erotic world is not a
place where everyone will feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   `American Beauty'
</P>
<P>
   As in last year's ``Happiness,'' the suburban American dream is
eviscerated, but this time in glossier, more predictable ways.
Kevin Spacey, once again the embodiment of sarcasm, is an
embittered dropout dad (with ``Lolita''-worthy daydreams) locked in
combat with his upwardly-mobile wife (Annette Bening), an avid
hawker of real estate. A right-wing gun nut lives next door, and
the children of both families are fiercely alienated. Beautifully
photographed, the movie (the flashy film debut of the theater
director Sam Mendes) is a shimmering nightmare evocation of the
spiritual emptiness lurking behind our boom economy.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Spacey and Ms. Bening strike cold but spectacular
sparks.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The satire, especially the fascist next door, is too
cut-and-dried.
</P>
<P>
   `The Talented Mr. Ripley'
</P>
<P>
   In this deluxe adaptation of Patricia Highsmith's novel, Anthony
Minghella creates a tempting, exquisitely shaded evocation of
American aristocrats abroad. Drenched in moody period jazz and set
mostly in Italy in the era of ``La Dolce Vita,'' the cool-handed
thriller stars Matt Damon as a wealth- and status-hungry chameleon
who covets the carefree expatriate life of Dickie Greenleaf (Jude
Law) and his girlfriend, Marge (Gwyneth Paltrow), enough to kill
Dickie and impersonate him.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Law's insouciant American golden boy is definitive, as
are Cate Blanchett playing a zany American textile heiress and
Philip Seymour Hoffman as a bluff, preppie bully.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Damon seems a little too innocent for the title role of
a master con man. The movie loses momentum in its final half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `The Straight Story'
</P>
<P>
   The director David Lynch, who delights in gouging phosphorescent
worms out of the shiny apple of American life, has made a wistfully
upbeat movie in which that apple is withered with age but
worm-free. The movie, based on a true story, follows the journey of
Alvin Straight (Richard Farnsworth) on his 1966 John Deere lawn
mower from Laurens, Iowa, to Mount Zion, Wis., to reconcile with
his ailing brother, Lyle.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Farnsworth, a supporting actor whose credits go back to
old-time cowboy movies, touchingly evokes the dignified sadness of
old age.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Not much really happens. The movie's real journey is
emotional and culminates in a scene in which Alvin and a fellow
World War II veteran weep together as they share their wartime
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   `The Insider'
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mann directed the true story of Jeffrey Wigand (Russell
Crowe), the tobacco-industry whistle-blower who is persuaded by
Lowell Bergman (Al Pacino), a producer for ``60 Minutes,'' to
reveal his damning evidence of corporate conspiracy. But when CBS,
caught in a corporate conflict of interest, balks, Wigand is left
twisting in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Russell Crowe gives one of the year's great screen
performances as Wigand, a reluctant, beleaguered whistle-blower
with a reservoir of anger beneath his thick skin. Christopher
Plummer, doing an uncanny impersonation of Mike Wallace, radiates
the lethal geniality of a coiled, twitching rattlesnake.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: In an effort to generate suspense, the movie overdoes
the creepy effects.
</P>
<P>
   `Titus'
</P>
<P>
   In the theater director Julie Taymor's shattering screen version
of Shakespeare's goriest play, the parallels between the slaughter
in ancient Rome and the killing fields of Rwanda and Cambodia are
sharply drawn. Anthony Hopkins' Titus suggests a transcendent
fusion of King Lear and Hannibal Lecter. And the movie, which
time-travels from ancient Rome to fascist Italy to a contemporary
video arcade, suggests an immersion in virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Hopkins' raving Titus is both ghoulishly funny and
tragic, and Ms. Taymor's best stage images, brought to the screen,
are indelible.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The performances don't mesh, with Hopkins, Alan Cumming
(as the decadent boy-child emperor) and Jessica Lange (the plotting
empress) all seeming to belong in different films.
</P>
<P>
   `Being John Malkovich'
</P>
<P>
   The year's most original comedy is a zany, urban ``Alice in
Wonderland'' and a coup for the first-time director Spike Jonze,
who comes from the world of music video. John Cusack is an
unemployed puppeteer who takes a job in a surreal office where he
discovers a portal into the mind of the actor John Malkovich
(wittily playing a version of himself). The story takes a
gender-bending twist when two women use his body to make love to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Among the dazzling comic conceits are a low-ceilinged
office in which everyone has to stoop to get around and a scene in
which Malkovich enters his own head and finds himself in a
restaurant where all the patrons resemble John Malkovich.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: For all its cleverness, the movie doesn't add up to
much metaphorically. It's really just a head trip about a head
trip.
</P>
<P>
   `Cradle Will Rock'
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins' cheery film about the 1937 production of Marc
Blitzstein's musical ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' which ran afoul of
the Federal Theater Project for its leftist politics, has the
temerity to imply that today's art world, devoted to abstraction,
was nurtured by Nelson Rockefeller and promoted by William Randolph
Hearst as a kind of conspiracy to keep artists out of politics.
Like almost everything else in the movie, the notion is a gross
oversimplification. But it is still gratifying to find a Hollywood
movie trumpeting political ideas. The movie's sketches of
Rockefeller, Hearst, Orson Welles, John Houseman, Diego Rivera and
other '30s luminaries are about as subtle as costume-ball
caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: The movie fizzes with a maniacal if unfocused energy.
Lively performances in the ensemble cast belong to Emily Watson,
Bill Murray, Joan Cusack, Vanessa Redgrave and Cherry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The social history is so simplified that the movie
sometimes has the naivete of a buoyant high school pageant.
</P>
<P>
   `The Cider House Rules'
</P>
<P>
   John Irving's sixth novel has been softened by the director
Lasse Hallstrom (``My Life as a Dog'') into the World War II-era
reverie about a dreamy young man (Tobey Maguire) who leaves the
Maine orphanage where he grew up in the care of his mentor, the
abortionist Dr. Larch (Michael Caine), to discover the world and
``be of use.'' The main subplot of a movie that suggests a
candy-coated 1940s echo of ``David Copperfield'' revolves around
the abortion of a migrant farm worker impregnated by her father.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Maguire's calm, moony-eyed Homer and Caine's likably
pragmatic Dr. Larch buoy the film's mood of a wistful grown-up
fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The movie's tenderness often verges on sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   `Magnolia'
</P>
<P>
   The director Paul Thomas Anderson tries to shoot the moon in
this Robert Altman-style mosaic of unhappy people converging on the
San Fernando Valley, which is visited by a plague of frogs falling
from the sky. Two of the stories deal with elderly men dying of
cancer who have wreaked terrible emotional damage on the lives of
their estranged children. The movie is a serious, anguished
reflection on male atonement.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Tom Cruise as the Tony Robbins of misogynistic sex in
another role in which his phony, too-bright smiles match his
character. Jason Robards, playing a cancer patient, rumbles
eloquently.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Though often bravura, the acting is hysterically
pitched. The frogs could go, along with several subsidiary
characters.
</P>
<P>
   `The End of the Affair'
</P>
<P>
   Neil Jordan's atmospheric adaptation of Graham Greene's
much-loved novel, starring Ralph Fiennes and Julianne Moore, should
erase all memories of the awful 1955 version featuring a mismatched
Deborah Kerr and Van Johnson. The movie is so true to its period
that wartime London feels almost like another planet in another
century.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Ms. Moore's luminosity and Fiennes' obsessive
introspection fuse beautifully. Jo Stafford's 1940s recording of
``Haunted Heart'' sends a romantic current through the film.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Michael Nyman's stodgy, overbearing score.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `Tumbleweeds'
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of this ``mother and daughter hit the road to start
a new life'' movie may be familiar. But the British actress Janet
McTeer (who rocked Broadway in a revival of ``A Doll's House'') as
the free-spirited Mary Jo Walker and Kimberly J. Brown as her
12-year-daughter, Ava, lend the relationship an extraordinary
emotional depth.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Ms. McTeer's portrayal of a hot-blooded Southern gal of
a certain age who loves too easily is so real it hardly seems like
acting. Few movies have captured more powerfully the intimacy of
the parent-child bond.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The movie is small, the story familiar, the visual
ambiance murky and the time frame indefinite.
</P>
<P>
   `Sweet and Lowdown'
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's good-natured ode to 1930s jazz stars Sean Penn as
Emmet Ray, a Django Reinhardt-like guitar virtuoso, and Samantha
Morton as the mute, adoring girlfriend whom he loves and abuses. If
this glowing little movie recalls ``Purple Rose of Cairo'' and
``Radio Days'' in its wistfulness, Penn, playing a heel you can't
help liking, gives it a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Penn's carefully stylized performance is surprisingly
low-key for an actor who has specialized in tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Uma Thurman's gawky turn as a society woman is
dramatically unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   `The Green Mile'
</P>
<P>
   This weepy Christian allegory, directed by Frank Darabont from a
Stephen King novel, pushes every emotional button at least twice.
Tom Hanks is Paul Edgecomb, a Louisiana prison guard working on
death row. Michael Clarke Duncan is John Coffey, the gentle black
giant and Jesus figure wrongly convicted of raping and murdering
two little girls. With its clear-cut heroes and villains, mushy
miracles, horror (a grisly electrocution), adorability (a cute pet
mouse) and a framing device and star (Hanks) both borrowed from
``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``The Green Mile'' rings commercial bells.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: A fine ensemble cast and the ability to summon tears
from the most resistant viewer.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: A running time of more than three hours and a queasy
feeling afterward that those tears were jerked by master
puppeteers.
</P>
<P>
   `The Hurricane'
</P>
<P>
   The heroic struggle for freedom and justice by Hurricane Carter,
jailed for nearly 20 years after being framed for a triple murder,
has been turned by the director Norman Jewison into a big
sentimental ballad of a movie. So many of the facts have been
altered to pump up the drama that the movie feels like fiction. But
Denzel Washington's portrayal of an imprisoned man wrestling with
the demons of despair and his own pent-up violence is volcanic.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Among the heroes Washington has portrayed, he has delved
the deepest into this one's soul.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: True to its cliched 60s liberal heart, the movie allows
no moral ambiguity. On one side we have Hurricane and his saintly
champions, on the other his evil racist persecutors.
</P>
<P>
   `Girl, Interrupted'
</P>
<P>
   Susanna Kaysen's memoir of her two-year stay in a fancy New
England mental hospital in 1967 after a suicide attempt has been
brought to the screen with a delicacy that crumbles only near the
end. Winona Ryder was born to play the whiny, self-pitying Susanna,
who is said to be a borderline personality. Angelina Jolie is Lisa,
a fellow patient and a daredevil sociopath who vies against the
institution for Susanna's soul.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Ms. Ryder's sensitive performance doesn't demand our
love. Ms. Jolie's blazingly scary Lisa proves once and for all that
she can really act.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The movie is a minuscule period piece, an Ivy League
``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' without metaphorical weight.
</P>
<P>
   `Liberty Heights'
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker Barry Levinson revisits his Baltimore hometown for
this nostalgic, semi-autobiographical reverie on anti-Semitism and
interracial dating in the mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: The period detail is perfect and the mood seductive.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The movie only skims the issues it addresses.
</P>
<P>
   `Any Given Sunday'
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone's football film is a brutal, rousing rah-rah cheer
for the sport's bone-crushing macho mystique. This crude
all-American success fable pits Jamie Foxx, playing a rebellious
young quarterback for the Miami Sharks, against his embattled
war-weary coach (Al Pacino) in a clash of values.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Terrific playing-field sequences. Foxx's subtle
portrayal of an athlete tempted by the perks of big-time celebrity
should make him a full-fledged star.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Cameron Diaz is over her head as a greedy team owner.
The story clatters toward a ridiculously upbeat ending.
</P>
<P>
   `Man on the Moon'
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey's uncanny impersonation of the comedian Andy Kaufman,
who disappeared into his comic alter egos, is a tour de force that
could earn Kaufman, who died in 1984, more recognition than he ever
received in his lifetime. But if the film, directed by Milos
Forman, effectively conveys Kaufman's love-hate relationship with
show business, it offers no clues about what made him tick.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: Carrey's remarkable re-creations of Kaufman's
appearances on ``Saturday Night Live'' and at Carnegie Hall and of
his loutish lounge-lizard alter-ego, Tony Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The movie reminds us that as profound as Kaufman's
concepts about the fourth wall may have been, the humor he
delivered was often hit-or-miss. There's hardly any background
story.
</P>
<P>
   `Angela's Ashes'
</P>
<P>
   As much as Alan Parker's overly long film adaptation prettifies
the impoverished Irish childhood described in Frank McCourt's
best-selling memoir, the movie's vision of the rain-soaked slums of
Limerick still casts a horrifying pall of gloom.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: The film captures the harshness and absurdity of
McCourt's Catholic education.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: Emily Watson's long-suffering mother is a one-note role
and Robert Carlyle's drunken father seems absurdly clean-cut. Three
actors playing Frank at different ages don't connect, and the
author's spunky humor is all but lost.
</P>
<P>
   `Sleepy Hollow'
</P>
<P>
   Tim Burton's take on Washington Irving's tale is a visual marvel
whose ominous Gothic figures seem to spring from the inky crevices
of storybook etchings. But the story has all the impact of an
overheated slasher film.
</P>
<P>
   PLUSES: ``Sleepy Hollow'' is a pictorial wonder, and Johnny Depp
as a jittery New York City policeman investigating the murders
gives one of his scientifically perfect performances.
</P>
<P>
   MINUSES: The story of a Headless Horseman haunting a Hudson
Valley town has no mythic resonance and isn't especially scary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
