<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR ASSURES VICTORY AS DEVILS DOWN BRUINS, 6-3
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The New Jersey Devils had goals from a penalty
shot, a power play and into an empty net Thursday night as they
ended their most successful trip of the season with a 6-3 victory
over the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   The victory extended the Devils' unbeaten streak to seven games
and gave them seven of a possible eight points on this four-game
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora secured the victory with his penalty shot with 5
minutes 20 seconds to play in the third period and the Devils
ahead, 4-3. It was the Devils' first penalty shot of the season and
was awarded after a Buffalo player closed his glove on the puck
during a scrum in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the six goals by the Devils, it was goaltender Martin
Brodeur who was their best player. A number of his 25 saves came at
critical times and kept the Devils in the game when the outcome was
up for grabs. Brodeur was so good at baffling the Sabres that at
times players were scratching their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Devils coach Robbie Ftorek's policy of sitting
players out at unexpected times is paying off. Randy McKay was
asked to sit out the overtime victory against Ottawa on Monday and
scored the winning goal in the next game, in Pittsburgh on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Pederson was perplexed by his benching against Pittsburgh
and responded Thursday night with his second goal of the season.
Ftorek gave Pederson extra inspiration by making him an alternate
captain for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Hamel, who was promoted by Buffalo earlier in the day,
delighted the crowd when he opened the scoring in his very first
shift in the league, 2:09 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took the lead on Pederson's goal and Claude Lemieux's
13th of the season, both coming before the game was 6:47 old.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo tied the score at 2-2 with 10:13 left in the first
period, when Brian Holzinger beat Brodeur with a back-hander. The
Sabres regained the lead 7:08 after the first intermission when the
rookie Maxim Afinogenov scored on a 4-on-4 situation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils tied the game again, with 1:55 left in the second
period, when Patrik Elias leaped on a rebound from Sykora's shot
for his 12th goal.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik's 12th goal of the season broke the 3-3 tie with
7:19 left in the third period, before Sykora scored on the penalty
shot and Scott Gomez scored into the net left vacant when Buffalo
inserted a skater for its goaltender.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
