A9077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-ISLES-FLYERS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS HOLD OFF ISLANDERS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If, as coach Butch Goring had implored them, the
New York Islanders' goals were to play with energy and emotion, to
be aggressive, to win faceoffs, and put pressure on their
opponents, then Thursday's game against the Philadelphia Flyers had
to be judged a success.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until you looked at the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of power-play goals helped the Flyers run their NH
L-leading undefeated streak at the First Union Center to 14 games
as the Islanders lost their fifth straight, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Before a sellout crowd of 19,703, the Islanders rallied from a
3-0 deficit, with Jorgen Jonsson cutting the lead to 3-2 with 7
minutes 2 seconds gone in the third period on his sixth goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Weekes, who was the last opposing goaltender to win here
in the Vancouver Canucks' 5-2 victory on Oct. 26, got the loss as
the Islanders dropped to 9-24-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, winners of four straight, are 23-11-6-1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers took the lead 6:25 into the game when Rod Brind'Amour
scored on a long wrist shot. Mark Recchi set up the play after he
had shaken off Jamie Rivers on the boards behind the net and angled
the puck through the crease to the waiting Brind'Amour, who had
gotten in front of Dave Scatchard in the left face-off circle. It
was Brind'Amour's third goal of the season
</P>
<P>
   A little more than two minutes later, the Flyers got their first
power-play try when Scatchard was sent to the penalty box for
tripping. Philadelphia, which went into the game with a
league-leading 40 power-play goals, did not waste this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Recchi, waiting just inside the blue line, took a hard shot on a
pass from Brind'Amour that was tipped in by Mikael Renberg from
just in front of the net at 9:55.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders got their first power-play chance when John
LeClair was called for high-sticking midway through the second
period, but could not get off any shots on Flyers goalie John
Vanbiesbrouck.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers went up, 3-0, on yet another power-play goal at 13:40
of the second period, this one from Daymond Langkow on the third
assist of the game from Recchi while Brad Isbister was in the box.
</P>
<P>
   Isbister was called for slashing and unsportsmanlike conduct
after tangling with Ulf Samuelsson along the boards, a call that
had an infuriated Goring.
</P>
<P>
   Isbister then took on Luke Richardson, with both drawing five
minutes for fighting at 13:58. Five seconds later, they were joined
by Steve Webb and Craig Berube, who fought at mid-ice, with Webb
drawing five minutes for fighting and Berube five minutes for
fighting and a 10-minute misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Connolly scored for the Islanders at 19:11, taking the feed
from Scatchard and wristing it past a diving Vanbiesbrouck from the
left side, about 12 feet out, for his sixth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Its is no coincidence the Islanders' current skid comes in the
absence of their captain, Kenny Jonsson. The defenseman, who is
suffering the lingering effects of a virus and has lost more than
10 pounds, missed his third straight game Thursday night although
he skated with the team in the morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
