A9079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-RUSSIA-REFORMS-B     01-06 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RUSSIA-REFORMS-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REFORMS RUSSIA NEEDS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial for Friday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Russia spent much of the past decade stumbling toward a new
political and economic system without coherent direction from the
Kremlin. Boris Yeltsin's early departure is a chance to halt this
costly drift. His successors must put in place the missing but
essential building blocks of a new society, including the rule of
law, a financial system free of corruption and a central government
able to collect taxes and provide competent and enlightened
administration throughout Russia's vast territory.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Putin, who now serves as acting president, has endorsed
these goals and has begun his tenure with a show of personal energy
and heightened governmental activism. But it is too soon to tell if
he will become the constructive democratic leader Russia needs. His
background in Soviet intelligence and close links to Yeltsin's
compromised entourage leave his true intentions in doubt. Putin
often speaks of his goal of creating a strong state. But it is not
clear whether he means that state to be authoritarian or
democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Russian governments have used their power to
stifle freedoms and carry out the orders of czars and Communist
tyrants. What is needed now is a government that is democratically
accountable, but strong enough to collect taxes, restore basic
services, control crime and create an environment conducive to
democratic politics and freely competitive markets.
</P>
<P>
   To make that possible, Putin and the Parliament must radically
simplify a tax system so complex and unfair that millions of
Russians feel justified in simply ignoring it. Once the tax code is
rationalized, Moscow must develop mechanisms to enforce it. As tax
revenues flow in, the new government will have to use them to
urgently repair a health care system and social conditions that
have fallen into deep crisis. In the past decade, life expectancy
for Russian males has plunged to a shockingly low 58 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin will also have to promote the creation of honest
police forces and independent courts to rein in a violent new
criminal class, which has exploited the breakdown of public
institutions to muscle in on legitimate businesses and terrorize
would-be entrepreneurs. Moscow must also carry out a rational
downsizing of Russia's military forces. Over the past decade, large
forces have been kept in place but subjected to brutal budget cuts
that have left many officers and soldiers irregularly paid,
miserably housed and deeply embittered.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the run-up to the March 26 presidential elections,
Putin should make clear that he expects independent and fair
political coverage in the government-controlled and pro-Kremlin
media. The distortions in coverage that marked December's
parliamentary election campaign ill served Russia's democratic
aspirations. More evenhanded coverage of the presidential race
would help enhance the legitimacy of the eventual winner, which now
appears likely to be Putin.
</P>
<P>
   In the five months since his emergence as a political leader,
Putin has emphasized military action in Chechnya at the expense of
these more fundamental and important issues. With that ugly
campaign now bogged down amid heightened Chechen resistance, there
is a serious risk of rising casualties among Russians as well as
Chechens. If Putin's goal is to build a strong Russian democracy,
the assault on Chechnya is the wrong way to begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-REPUBLICAN-CAMPA     01-06 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBLICAN-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A HOTTER REPUBLICAN CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   In a lively, almost raucous debate in New Hampshire Thursday
night, Gov. George W. Bush dropped his relaxed country-club
demeanor to focus on his sweeping tax-cut scheme, denigrate the tax
cut offered by Sen. John McCain and hammer the senator over his
advocacy of campaign reform. McCain had the better of the tax
argument and deftly defended the role of humor in politics. But he
was less impressive in explaining two letters he wrote as chairman
of the Senate Commerce Committee to the Federal Communications
Commission on behalf of a major campaign donor.
</P>
<P>
   The senator defends the letters as legitimate, and his debating
partners did not challenge his assertion. But the letters were a
mistake that he should acknowledge without equivocation. Until now,
McCain has been able to present himself as the underdog foe of
special interests. It turns out, however, that in November and
December he wrote letters to the FCC asking for swifter action on a
licensing deal being sought by Lowell Paxson, a major contributor
and supplier of corporate jets for McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain argues that his letters were appropriate because they did
not press the commission for a result favorable to Paxson, only for
prompt action on a long-delayed matter. But no one in Washington
would doubt what action McCain would favor. It is improper for any
chairman of a Senate committee with oversight functions over a
federal regulatory agency to intervene on behalf of one company,
irrespective of whether that company is a campaign donor. McCain
should have been more sensitive, given his often-expressed regret
over trying to help Charles Keating, a campaign contributor, in the
savings and loan scandals of more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush and some other Republicans tried to
suggest that the senator's action rendered his advocacy of campaign
finance reform invalid. This error does not detract from the
worthiness of McCain's cause. But it has damaged his campaign and
raises serious questions about his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   On the tax-cut issue, McCain's approach is more sound than that
of the Texas governor. Bush's tax scheme is costly and unfair. As
McCain noted, it drains money that might otherwise be available to
keep Social Security solvent. The country will benefit if the
Republican campaign now turns to fiscal responsibility and ethics
as two issues that most concern the voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GOVERNORS-ISLAND-N     01-06 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOVERNORS-ISLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST OF GOVERNORS ISLAND COULD PIT CITY AND STATE AGAINST
CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After more than four years of warring over the future
of Governors Island, New York city and state officials who finally
announced an agreement Thursday are now likely to find themselves
allies in a new battle over the disputed turf. Their potential foe?
Federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   At a joint news conference Thursday, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki provided details of the development
plan the city and the state agreed on. But the cost of reacquiring
the land, and possible opposition from members of Congress who
sense a few more dollars for the federal budget, remain at issue.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bullock, the chief of staff to Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., said the biggest hurdle in Congress will be
making up a projected budget shortfall if the island is transferred
for anything less than its fair market value, which Congress has
estimated at $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although real estate experts say that estimate is highly
inflated, it was included in the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, when
Congress designated Governors Island for sale in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That estimate was arrived at despite an offer President Clinton
made to Giuliani and Pataki in October 1995 to use his influence to
turn over the island to the city and state for $1 if they presented
a joint plan for its public use. The mayor and the governor did so
Thursday, but battles over the federal budget have made it less
likely that such favorable terms would still be available.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he still hoped to seize on the president's offer,
which had been conveyed through Moynihan. He said he was ``counting
on Sen. Moynihan over the course of the next year or two to be able
to get that property for us without having to pay a ton of money
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Moynihan Thursday, made available by the
senator's staff, Clinton said he still hoped to help convey
Governors Island to New York, but did not mention a price. ``We
look forward to working with you and New York officials on the
necessary details,'' the president said, adding that he was
``encouraged to learn that New York state and New York City have
agreed to a tentative plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle on Capitol Hill can be expected to begin next
month, said Rep. Jerrold L. Nadler, a Brooklyn Democrat. Nadler
said Thursday that he, Rep. Carolyn Maloney, a Manhattan Democrat,
and Moynihan would introduce bills in the House and Senate to have
Governors Island turned over to the city and state for $1.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler said the proposal, which some legislators in other
regions may see as a giveaway, would nonetheless win favor among
the Republican majority in the House, since both the mayor and
governor are Republicans. ``The stars are lined up this year,''
Nadler said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bullock said that the $500 million estimate that Congress
built into the Balanced Budget Act could still mean some thorny
political maneuvering. ``It is certainly going to require
legislation, and maybe more than one piece of it,'' he said. ``It
is not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is unlikely that Congress could fetch $500 million for
the island, which was a Coast Guard base until 1996, Bullock said,
``the impact on the budget is very real, since when you try to take
$500 million out, you reduce the federal surplus by just that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Correcting the congressional bookkeeping, he said, will require
joint action by the White House and the New York state
congressional delegation. First, he said, Clinton would be asked to
submit a federal budget for fiscal 2001 that adjusted the
anticipated revenues from the sale of Governors Island to a far
lower, more realistic amount.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bullock said, bills seeking to hand over the island for
$1, or for another amount below what it might fetch from private
developers, could be deliberated in the House and Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2345EST &QL; 
