<DOCNO> NYT20000106.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-POLITICIANS-N     01-06 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLITICIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CANDIDATE SIGHTINGS AROUND TOWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   With New York's 18 million residents, hundreds of whom are
certified politicians, one could argue that the state does not
really need any more. That view, however, would seem unnecessarily
provincial, given the fact that New York, unlike, say, Boston, does
not require longstanding attachments. To be a fully participating
New Yorker, one must simply move to the state and register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   So having Hillary Rodham Clinton unpacking at her Westchester
mansion, while her husband announces that he is going to vote in
New York, and an ex-governor of Massachusetts moving into a
Manhattan apartment in case he wants to take over a second
statehouse in Albany makes a certain amount of sense.
</P>
<P>
   That former Massachusetts governor, William Weld, is aiming for
the 2006 gubernatorial race as a Republican candidate-in-waiting in
case neither Gov. George Pataki nor Mayor Rudolph Giuliani wants to
run for the state government's top job. Weld's is a bold response
to a heretofore invisible demand. If elected, he would become the
first person since Sam Houston of Tennessee and Texas to serve as
governor of two states.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was spared a lonely-looking arrival in the suburbs
by President Clinton's decision to take a break from Middle East
peace talks to be with her. It must have been a strange first
evening, after so many years in the nation's four-star public
housing, to see the old familiar geegaws from their Arkansas days
and remember how to operate a backyard barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   So welcome, Clintons. Welcome, Welds. New York is a state that
embraces immigrants _ not only the tired and poor, but also the
politically restless and the electorally unattached. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-00 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
