<HEADLINE>
YEHUDA EBSTEIN, EXECUTIVE IN JEWISH GROUPS, DIES AT 75  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NICK RAVO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yehuda Ebstein, a former executive of several Jewish
nonprofit organizations, died on Dec. 27 at his home in Manhattan.
He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said a daughter, Aviva Ebstein Kroninger
of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ebstein was born in Oppeln, Germany, on Oct. 1, 1924, and
emigrated to Palestine in late 1938 with his family. He joined the
British Army at 15, at the outbreak of World War II, and earned the
rank of lieutenant colonel.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Ebstein returned to Palestine to fight for
Israeli independence and served in the Israeli Army, again rising
to the rank of lieutenant colonel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, he arrived in the United States and spent more than 30
years working for Jewish nonprofit groups like the Development
Corp. for Israel, which sold bonds for projects in Israel. He
worked there from 1952 to 1958.He then joined the American Friends
of Hebrew University and the World Jewish Congress, where he was
executive director of its American section.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Ebstein joined the National Committee for Labor Israel,
the U.S. affiliate of Histadrut, the national labor organization in
Israel. He was executive director for its New York region until
1984, when he became deputy executive vice president of the
committee. He was appointed executive vice president in 1990 and
retired two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his daughter, Ebstein is survived by his wife,
Shoshonna; another daughter, Gila Lewis of Greenwich, Conn.; a
sister, Ilse Dinari of Ramat Gan, Israel, and five granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
