<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY BEARING DOWN ON GORE, IOWA VOTER POLL INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ In a state once expected to start Al Gore's
easy stroll to the Democratic presidential nomination, challenger
Bill Bradley is bearing down intently on the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's Democratic establishment, firmly behind Gore, has watched
warily as Bradley's insurgent campaign narrowed the polling gap and
may have established an edge heading toward the state's Jan. 24
presidential nominating caucuses. A new statewide poll and
anecdotal reports from around the state point to deterioration in
Gore's once-solid lead.
</P>
<P>
   A big question is how well Bradley must do in Iowa to
fundamentally alter the political equation that still makes the
Democratic nomination Gore's to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Bradley) probably has to do something as shocking as
win in Iowa,'' said John Haskell, a political science professor at
Drake University in Des Moines. ``He has to do something
dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Bradley already leading Gore in polls in New Hampshire,
where the first presidential primary will be held Feb. 1, both
Democratic campaigns are looking to Iowa for an invigorating jolt _
but without building up expectations that cannot be met.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley walked from his rented jet into a Des Moines airport
hangar Thursday to the aging disco tune ``Ain't No Stopping Us
Now.'' But his national political director, Anita Dunn, was quick
to dampen any thought of an inevitable surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still just trying to build. We're not even thinking
about peaking yet,'' Dunn said. ``We're actively engaged in trying
to convert Bradley supporters into caucus-goers.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comment reflected the knowledge that Gore, with the backing
of most unions and Democratic officeholders, has a built-in
institutional advantage that can be of inestimable value in a
caucus fight, which is a quintessential organizational battle.
</P>
<P>
   Caucus analyst Jon Hall of the University of Northern Iowa in
Cedar Falls said, however, that the organizational fight is not
lopsidedly in the vice president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Gore and Bradley have done a relatively good job,'' Hall
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, a former professional basketball player and U.S.
senator from New Jersey for 18 years, was ready to play the
potential martyr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up against entrenched power, there's no doubt about
it,'' Bradley said during 4 1/2 minutes of remarks at the airport.
As to how he expected to do in Iowa, Bradley was willing to rest on
an intentionally inexact political cliche: ``Let's surprise people
with our result in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who hit the state Monday on his first campaign trip of the
new year, will continue to fight back, including Friday, when he
arrives with Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy set the high-water mark for a Democratic challenger in
Iowa, winning 31 percent in his ultimately ill-fated 1980 campaign
to wrest the nomination from President Carter, noted Bradley's Iowa
spokesman, Jim Farrell. Bradley strategists know they must do
substantially better to have any hope of denying Gore the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley face off Saturday in an Iowa debate, and both
candidates have promised to spend a majority of the days before the
caucuses in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bradley knew he must prove himself a plausible candidate
in the early contests, he has spent many more days in Iowa than
Gore during the campaign: 63 to 36, according to the count of
caucus historian Hugh Winebrenner of Drake University.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell said Bradley's low-key delivery is a plus in Iowa, where
``it helps to be dull. His style is pretty good for Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody like (President) Clinton who's polished is considered
probably a little dishonest,'' Haskell said, ``and Gore's trying so
hard, he probably is being viewed that way now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton remains popular with many die-hard Democrats,
the most avid caucus attendees, Gore's connection to the morally
tarnished administration appears to provide Bradley an opening.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Geri Huser of Altoona, one of the handful of Iowa
Democratic officeholders to back Bradley, sees an advantage to her
candidate's lack of current Washington connections _ both in the
caucuses and general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are individuals who will vote for Bradley who will not
vote for Gore'' if he is the Democratic nominee, Huser said. ``They
don't want to hear about White House problems for the next nine
months.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator arrived for his first Iowa visit of the new
year to a front-page headline in the Des Moines Register, the
state's leading newspaper, that said: ``Bradley turns up the
heat.'' The story detailed Bradley's growth from a long shot to a
serious contender, with a large field staff and a television
advertising budget that will match Gore's dollar for dollar.
Falling back on his basketball background, Bradley had told local
reporters: ``The full court press is on.''
</P>
<P>
   Also out Thursday was a new statewide poll of likely voters
showing Gore's lead over Bradley cut to 13 percentage points, down
from 24 points in a similar survey in November. In the poll, for a
group of midwestern television stations, Gore had dropped below 50
percent support and led Bradley 45 percent to 32 percent. The poll
had a 5.4 percentage-point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Tufty, who oversaw the poll of 300 likely Democratic
caucus attendees said the shift to Bradley was significant and put
him in the lead among men and younger voters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
