<HEADER>
A9090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT &LR;      01-06 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS AND STRIPES WINS, BUT OFF THE WATER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ When it comes to the America's Cup, a
day with no racing is rarely a day with no activity. Though there
was not enough wind on Thursday to allow the yachts to start in the
challenger semifinals, there were winners and losers off the water
as the international jury, which helps govern this often
contentious and often litigious regatta, set about considering
protests and requests.
</P>
<P>
   The loser was Le Defi Francais, and the winner, at least for the
moment, was Stars and Stripes, which leads the semifinals with a
3-0 record. The French were docked a further half-point by the jury
for their role in the collision that damaged Stars and Stripes from
behind during a race on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a forgettable round for the French, and the shark
that was seen patrolling the water near their boat on Thursday was
an appropriate symbol. They have gone from predator to prey. After
winning seven races in a row in the final preliminary round, the
French are now in last place with an 0-3 record. After the penalty,
the point total by Le Defi's name in the standing reads minus 0.5
with seven races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also granted Stars and Stripes' request for 24 more
hours to complete repairs on the crack in its scoop caused by the
collision. Dennis Conner's team had already been granted 24 hours
to make repairs. Barring further machinations or further problems
with the weather, Stars and Stripes will next race on Saturday
against America One. Its race against America True will be
postponed until the end of this round, in which all six
semifinalists are scheduled to face each other twice.
</P>
<P>
   The extra extension granted Conner did not sit well with Dawn
Riley, the skipper of America True, which had been scheduled to
race Stars and Stripes later Friday. ``We know that Dennis would
rather sail us in heavy air than light air,'' Riley said in
reference to the light wind conditions expected in the Hauraki Gulf
Friday. ``He has taken full advantage of all the latitude the jury
gave to him and delayed another day. If he wanted to fix this in
one day, he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Cahill, a spokeswoman for Stars and Stripes, said that
its builders had deemed that further work was necessary. But Stars
and Stripes has not seen the last of the jury, and at its next
appearance it could be the team on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Challenge, which lost to Stars and Stripes on the first
day of this round, has filed a protest of its own against the
Americans. The Japanese claim that Conner's team beat its boat
while using a rudder that was in breach of Article 19 of the
America's Cup protocol because it was not made in either the United
States or New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   One skipper who spoke on condition of anonymity said the rudder
was manufactured in Australia. But in a statement, Conner's team
said it was ``confident that all rules of nationality in the
appropriate documents for this America's Cup have been met.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury will consider the protest Friday night, but it is
unclear whether it will be able to make a ruling. The jury could
refer the issue to the arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
   Before this round began, America True had asked the panel for an
interpretation of Article 19, a request that the panel has still
not answered formally. ``When we heard the rumor about Stars and
Stripes' rudder, we asked for the clarification,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   What certainly piqued the Japanese syndicate's curiosity was
Stars and Stripes' decision to ask for a new measurement
certificate the morning after its victory over Nippon. America's
Cup yachts must conform to certain design parameters, and when a
challenger or a defender makes a change, it must ask for a
measurement. Stars and Stripes was within its rights to do so _
each challenger may make one change per round _ and was issued a
new certificate for its second race.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the questionable rudder was still on the boat,
Cahill declined comment. But Riley said, ``They only used the
rudder in the race against Nippon.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley added: ``I'm quite disappointed in the lack of realism of
the jury. They have to know what's going on here.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
