<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN WOMAN DENIES TIES TO SUSPECTED ALGERIAN TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ A Canadian woman who federal prosecutors say
has links to suspected Algerian terrorists denied any such ties on
Thursday as she and a companion were indicted on immigration and
passport violations.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Lucia Garofalo, 35, of Montreal, was arrested in
Vermont on Dec. 19 at a Canadian-American border crossing along
with Bouabide Chamchi, a 20-year-old Algerian.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors had argued last week that Ms. Garofalo
was indirectly tied to Ahmed Ressam, an Algerian charged last month
in Washington state with transporting bomb materials into the
United States from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But the indictments handed down by a federal grand jury here on
Thursday make no mention of terrorist involvement on the part of
either Ms. Garofalo or Chamchi.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garofalo's lawyer, Maryann E. Kampmann, said her client had
no connections to Ressam or to ``any terrorist organization
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   A single mother of three, Ms. Garofalo has been in solitary
confinement here for 18 days on the grounds that she poses a threat
to national security. Both she and Chamchi pleaded not guilty on
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
