<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING LITTLE HANDS THAT USE COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Md., Ill., Calif., Australia) (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)  
 (Pamela Mendels writes about education and technology for The Times
on the Web.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By PAMELA MENDELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QC;  Every half-hour, students in Kenneth A. Kwajewski's computer
class at West Middle School in Andover, Mass., take a break from
spreadsheets and word processing to do head rolls and arm
stretches. And every so often, Kwajewski turns on music and the
children do the chicken dance, flapping their arms like barnyard
dancers at a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching is a crucial element of technology training at West
Middle. Karen Jacobs, the president of the American Occupational
Therapy Association in Bethesda, Md., and mother of a West Middle
student, even stops by to demonstrate how to use a keyboard and
mouse and position themselves properly. Tips: if a chair is too
high, use a backpack as an elevating footrest; for lower-back
support, roll up a jacket for a cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this `Net' generation,'' Kwajewski said, ``it's important
children develop good habits so they don't develop injuries,
especially if they are going to interact with computers their whole
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Many health specialists agree, noting that the push to train
children on computers has not been accompanied by an equally
fervent drive to teach how to use them safely: to adopt practices
that might prevent crippling hand and arm injuries that can afflict
computer-using adults. But they also agree there is a paucity of
research examining what intensive computing means for little hands,
and few cases of keyboard-related injuries among young children.
</P>
<P>
   Steven J. Anderson, the chairman of the committee on sports
medicine and fitness at the American Academy of Pediatrics, based
in Elk Grove Village, Ill., said that he rarely sees patients under
age 25 suffering from computer-related repetitive stress injury.
For one thing, doctors say, children are not logged onto computers
as many hours as adults are. For another, they are less sedentary
than adults. That, combined with blessings like flexible joints and
tendons, could make them more resilient.
</P>
<P>
   But computer-related problems are not unheard of. Robert E.
Markison, a San Francisco hand surgeon, has treated tendinitis in
computer users as young as 11. Characteristics that might make a
child more susceptible to repetitive stress injury, he said,
include ``uneven circulation,'' suggested by cold hands, and a
strong tendon link between the ring and little fingers, exhibited
by difficulty moving one finger without moving the other.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Sarwark, a pediatric orthopedic surgeon at Children's
Memorial Hospital in Chicago, said that over the last five years he
has noticed an emergence of young patients with postural problems,
which he attributes partly to prolonged computer use.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the few studies on computer usage by youngsters,
researchers at Curtin University of Technology in Perth, Australia,
last year queried 314 students, age 10 to 17, who used laptops an
average of 17 hours a week. About 60 percent reported discomfort
associated with the equipment. ``My worry is that we know very
little about how children should use computers to maintain health
and maximize satisfaction in learning,'' said Leon Straker, a
co-author of the study and a senior lecturer in ergonomics, the
applied science of effective, safe design.
</P>
<P>
   For a study published earlier this year, Alan Hedge, a Cornell
University professor of ergonomics, examined computer work stations
at three elementary schools. In most cases, the study found
``striking misfits'' _ for example, keyboards and monitors placed
so high children had to crane their necks. In addition, he said,
children spend more and more hours at home computers doing research
for school projects, participating in chats and playing games at
stations often set up for Mom or Dad.
</P>
<P>
   But what concerns specialists most about the first generation
weaned on computers is the future. ``There's a push now to have
children use computers more at school and home,'' said David M.
Rempel, a medical doctor and director of the ergonomics program at
the University of California, San Francisco and Berkeley. ``If they
are on computers more and more hours per week _ 20, 30 hours _ then
we have to pay close attention to their work habits, position and
work-station design.''
</P>
</TEXT>
